<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA IMPROVING AT PERFECT TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The UCLA Bruins had plenty of explanations for
their masterful upset of No. 1 Stanford. Big men Jerome Moiso and
Dan Gadzuric dominated. Point guard Earl Watson was almost
flawless. JaRon Rush and Jason Kapono hit crucial jump shots. They
played with patience and poise in a raucous environment.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked why it took 28 games for a performance of this
caliber, the Bruins struggled for specifics.
</P>
<P>
   Nor could they explain how a team that wins in Maples Pavilion
could lose at Arizona State by 29 points two weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we got back from Arizona, we did a little
soul-searching,'' junior forward Rico Hines said. ``We didn't have
any team meetings, but everybody soul-searched. We've taken a
different approach to practice and a different approach to games.
We're preparing so much better. You can sense it as soon as you
walk in the gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``(In Arizona), when we got behind, we self-destructed. But the
last two games, when we've gotten down we've kept fighting and
gotten back in the games. Now, the sky's the limit for this team.
We've got JaRon back, and we're just starting to scratch the
surface of what we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not too late. UCLA (17-11, 8-8) is one victory from
attaining the 18 required for an NCAA Tournament berth. (That
should come Thursday against last-place Washington State in Pauley
Pavilion.)
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the Bruins are peaking at the perfect time. The
NCAA selection committee values strong finishes above all when it
picks the 64-team field; the Bruins have won four in a row and
beaten the No.1 team on its home floor.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors have contributed to the turnaround:
</P>
<P>
   --Watson's emergence.
</P>
<P>
   In the eight games since Ryan Bailey joined the starting lineup
and reduced Watson's ballhandling responsibilities, Watson has 47
assists, 20 turnovers and is playing as well as any point guard in
the conference. Even when Bailey doesn't play, Watson seems more at
ease with his role than he did earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has taken time for me to learn the point guard spot,'' said
Watson, who played off-guard in 1998-99 while Baron Davis ran the
team. ``I can honestly say I wasn't a point guard at the beginning
of the season. It's been on-the-job training.''
</P>
<P>
   --Frontline improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Gadzuric and Moiso have dominated at various points in their
careers, but never at the same time - until now.
</P>
<P>
   Gadzuric had 22 points and 16 rebounds at Cal while Moiso
provided solid support (nine and six). Saturday, with Gadzuric in
foul trouble, Moiso had 17 points and 12 rebounds and controlled
the game in the final minutes of regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fortunate to be able to make some big shots,'' Moiso
said. ``That's something I should do, but I don't do it
consistently.''
</P>
<P>
   --Improved ballhandling.
</P>
<P>
   There's no better gauge of UCLA's success (and failure) than
turnovers. The Bruins committed 45 in two games in Arizona and lost
by 44 points. But they committed just 27 in two games against the
Oregon schools and won both.
</P>
<P>
   In the first 12 minutes against Cal, they committed 10 turnovers
and fell behind 31-12. In the final 28 minutes, they committed only
seven turnovers and outscored the Bears by 40 points.
</P>
<P>
   They committed five turnovers in five minutes against Stanford
and fell behind 19-4. They committed just nine turnovers in the
final 35 minutes and outscored the Cardinal by 16 points.
</P>
<P>
   --Rush's return.
</P>
<P>
   It's not about the 19 points he scored against Stanford,
although the Bruins aren't complaining. But what they covet most is
Rush's energy, his tenacity, his rebounding, his versatility, his
defense and his five fouls.
</P>
<P>
   ``He takes the pressure off every other player,'' coach Steve
Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   With his performance Saturday, Rush also took enormous pressure
off the embattled coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   When it's time for their performance review with athletic
director Peter Dalis, the coaches can claim - with the Stanford
game as evidence - that Rush's suspension cost them four or five
victories this season.
</P>
<P>
   Rush beat the No. 1 team, catapulted UCLA into the tournament
and possibly secured the staff's future. That's a pretty good
afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
