<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7807 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-DORAL-HNS &LR;      03-06 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DORAL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It wasn't Jean Van de Velde at last year's British Open.
It wasn't Scott Hoch at the '95 Shell Houston Open. It wasn't even
Greg Norman at, oh, any tournament any year.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin Langham isn't the most famous pro golfer to suffer
fatal self-inflicted wounds, just the most recent.
</P>
<P>
   There's something about a pro golfer suffering from gag reflex
that brings out a certain amount of sympathy. But in Langham's
case, the blame for his losing the Doral-Ryder Open doesn't fall
completely on his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Almost. But not completely.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Furyk's sizzling back nine Sunday at Doral's Blue Monster
helped him beat Langham by eight shots over the final seven holes,
giving Furyk an unexpected two-shot win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really put myself in a hole,'' Furyk said. ``And I should
feel real fortunate that I won the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Furyk helped his own cause tremendously. He fired a dandy 30 on
the final nine, ending up with a 7-under-par 65, and his 23-under
265 total tied the tournament record set by Norman in 1993. Furyk's
fifth PGA Tour win was his first east of Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   For Langham, who shot 2-under 70, he will have to live down the
fact he lost a six-shot lead in the final seven holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know that,'' he said of his huge lead. ``As soon
as you start thinking about that, you are setting yourself up for
failure. I didn't do anything that was crazy or dumb.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not. The old line about South Florida _ it's not the
heat, it's the stupidity _ didn't necessarily apply to his demise.
But Langham did do plenty wrong. For the fourth consecutive day,
the pros tore into the tame Monster, which was defenseless in calm
conditions. But Langham shot 2-over 38 on the final nine, which
overshadowed a wonderful birdie-birdie-birdie start to his round.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were only a couple of guys who could have caught me with
a round of 65, and Jim was one of them,'' Langham said. ``I gave
him a little bit of light, and he took advantage of it. For one
reason or another, it wasn't my turn.''
</P>
<P>
   For 11 holes, it looked like it was very much Langham's turn. He
had played wonderful, bogey-free golf as his lead doubled from the
three-stroke cushion with which he started the day.
</P>
<P>
   But Furyk did all he could, then relied on some help from
Langham.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my caddie, let's go shoot a 30 on the back nine and
maybe we'll have a chance,'' Furyk said.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Langham had shot himself in the foot and just about
everywhere else coming into the 18th. Three bogeys in five holes
had done plenty to give Furyk the momentum, not to mention a
one-stroke lead after 71 holes.
</P>
<P>
   Furyk clinched the tournament when his approach on 18 nestled
eight feet from the hole. Langham tried his best to recover when
his 8-iron stopped 10 feet away. But his putt slipped by the edge,
and Furyk put an exclamation point on his back nine by making his
birdie for the two-shot final margin.
</P>
<P>
   Langham was cruising along without a care through the 11th hole,
on which he chipped in for birdie. He was 5-under for the day to
that point, 24-under for the tournament and six shots ahead of
Furyk. Nobody else had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Truth to tell, Furyk shouldn't have had one, either.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the blink of an eye, Langham's lead was down to a
single stroke as he lost at least one shot to Furyk on four
consecutive holes.
</P>
<P>
   Furyk birdied the par-5 12th, then Langham showed signs of
muscle tightening with back-to-back bogeys, including a missed
four-footer for par on the par-4 14th.
</P>
<P>
   Furyk birdied the 13th, then reached 21-under for the tournament
when he knocked a 7-iron within two feet at the par-3 15th. That
made it a one-shot deficit with three to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 13th definitely was a turning point,'' Furyk said. ``I
felt like a two-shot swing there might put some pressure on him.
Two holes earlier, it was a six-shot lead. Now, it's down to
three.''
</P>
<P>
   After a couple of routine pars on the 16th, Langham continued to
self-destruct. His drive dribbled into the left rough on the 17th,
then he hit a horrible approach about 20 yards right of the green,
leaving himself with an ugly chip. He left his first flop shot
short of the green, then chipped again to within a foot. But the
damage was done. And it was compounded when Furyk canned a 20-foot
birdie putt. The two-stroke swing put Furyk one shot up with only
the long, perilous 18th to play.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
