<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-HEAT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT LAKERS BEAT THE HEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At some point Sunday, Laker legs turned to mush,
jumpers lost their juice and the NBA's winningest team suddenly
lost all ability to do much of anything.
</P>
<P>
   Anything except win.
</P>
<P>
   Proving that even their worst days are better than most teams'
best, the Los Angeles Lakers misplaced their offense for three
quarters and still dominated the East's second-best team, dealing
the Miami Heat a 93-80 loss at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Lakers' most unaesthetic showing in weeks, as they
shot 39.5 percent from the field, and just 26.8 percent (15 of 56)
after the first quarter. And it didn't matter in the least.
</P>
<P>
   On perhaps momentum alone, they won their 15th in a row, and
only the Clippers stand in the way of matching the incredible
16-game streak they posted earlier this season. The Lakers are only
the third team in NBA history to have two streaks of at least 15
games in the same season.
</P>
<P>
   Not that any of this made the game more palatable to coach Phil
Jackson, who on Sunday saw more similarities to the Lakers'
late-January swoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to get sucked up into any optimistic feel that we
can play this way and continue,'' Jackson said. ``This is
reminiscent of something that happened about six weeks ago to us
(when the Lakers went 3-6)....
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to be a little sharper, a little tighter,
get some more practice time. We haven't had much. It's good that we
have a day off after we play the Clippers, but until that time,
we're going to have to maintain what we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is plenty, even on a bad day. Glen Rice snapped out of a
three-game funk to carry the Lakers with 23 points on 8-of-16
shooting and added a season-high 10 rebounds for his first
double-double of the season.
</P>
<P>
   That helped balance out a listless day from the Lakers' top
scorers. Shaquille O'Neal made just 5 of 17 shots from the field,
finishing with 17 points, 11 rebounds and seven assists. Kobe
Bryant had 15 points and seven rebounds but was 5 for 12.
</P>
<P>
   The role players did the rest - Ron Harper scoring 14 points,
Robert Horry pitching in 10 points and seven rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of weapons on this team,'' O'Neal said. ``As
long as me, Kobe and Glen can maintain what we've been doing and
guys step off the bench and contribute a lot, we're going to be a
hard team to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Or catch. In winning their ninth consecutive home game, the
Lakers extended their lead over idle Portland to two games.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a rough few games for O'Neal, whose shooting
percentage is on a steady decline, and Jackson observed, ``Shaq
looked very tired.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, outscored by Alonzo Mourning (21 points), thought
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never get tired,'' he said. ``I'm more beat up than tired.
I'm always beat up. A lot of chopping. But I don't get tired....
When they need me to hit those shots I'll hit them. Every time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers led by as many as 18 points, and the Heat never got
closer than 11 in the second half against a stiff defensive stand.
All the Lakers' offense came in the first quarter, when they rode
Rice's 13-point outburst to a 37-23 lead that never withered.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning and P.J. Brown both fell victim to foul trouble, and
the Heat got a mere 11 points from their aging backcourt of Tim
Hardaway and Dan Majerle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both teams ground to a rather enigmatic halt in the second
half,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   The victory capped a six-day span in which the Lakers - the
NBA's leaders at 49-11 - knocked off the other top team in the West
(Portland, 46-12) and the top two teams in the East (Indiana at
39-19, Miami at 37-22).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a huge statement,'' Rice said. ``In the last
couple of days we've played the one and two that's in the East and
pretty much were able to go out there and handle them. I just think
it's a sign of this team really growing and maturing and going out
and playing together.... We've always had the confidence that we
could pretty much beat any team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
