<SLUG> BC-BKC-USCNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE DID IT ALL GO WRONG FOR USC?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's almost hard to believe that as recently as
Feb. 3, USC was tied for first place in the Pacific-10 Conference
with a 6-1 record, and seemingly on pace for an NCAA Tournament
bid.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans were already without forward Sam Clancy (broken
right foot) and forward Jarvis Turner (broken left ankle), but
seemed to have enough left to win five of their final 11 games, the
number necessary to earn a tournament berth.
</P>
<P>
   So where did things go wrong? Forward Brian Scalabrine thinks
the problem began when USC upset then No. 2-ranked Arizona 80-72 on
Jan. 22 in their first game after the injuries to Clancy and
Turner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually thought we'd be worse (than we are) without Sam,''
Scalabrine said. ``But then we beat Arizona and you know what we
did? We fooled ourselves into thinking we were a better team.''
</P>
<P>
   USC went 3-7 without Clancy. The Trojans (14-14, 7-9) have lost
eight of their past nine games and may be reeling, but they still
believe they will earn a bid to the National Invitation Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll probably get the two Washington (schools) this week and
go to the NIT,'' Clancy said.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of frustration: It might just be the result of a prolonged
slump, but patience is beginning to wear for the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   After Jeff Trepagnier missed a layup against Cal, USC coach
Henry Bibby immediately motioned reserve Nate Hair to check into
the game. Trepagnier saw Hair head toward the scorer's table, and
threw his hands in the air while asking Bibby why he was coming
out.
</P>
<P>
   The two then had an animated discussion - all during the game -
over why Trepagnier was being removed. ``I just asked what I did
wrong, and he told me I had to make those shots,'' Trepagnier said.
</P>
<P>
   Trepagnier and Scalabrine also chastised teammates on the court
against Cal.
</P>
<P>
   Staying positive: With the season winding down, Bibby is trying
to remain upbeat instead of criticizing after losses.
</P>
<P>
   He praised the Trojans repeatedly following their 83-71 loss to
Cal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we played hard. Brian played on one leg. Sam is just
getting back,'' Bibby said. ``But they haven't thrown the towel in.
I'm proud of the guys. We're building things and we have a solid
foundation in this program.''
</P>
<P>
   Clancy update: Clancy reported feeling better after the Cal game
than he did in his return against Stanford on Thursday, after
missing six weeks with a broken foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little sore but not much,'' Clancy said. ``I got tired
a little bit but overall I felt good.''
</P>
<P>
   Clancy played 31 minutes, nearly twice as much as Bibby planned
to use him going into the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Two records: Point guard Brandon Granville already set a
single-season record for assists, and Saturday at Cal he set a
school-record for most turnovers (112) in a season. Granville is
only six turnovers ahead of Scalabrine.
</P>
<P>
   On the mark: Forward David Bluthenthal has made 25 consecutive
free throws. The school record is 37 by John Block in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Not welcome: Cal honored several former football coaches at
halftime Saturday, but when former Golden Bears and current San
Francisco 49ers coach Steve Mariucci was introduced, the crowd of
more than 12,000 booed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gee ... tough crowd,'' the Cal public-address announcer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
