<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-PEPPERDINE-SAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE FALLS TO SAN DIEGO
</HEADLINE>
 DIEGO-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ With about a minute left Sunday,
Pepperdine's Damaris Hinojosa sat on the bench, wrapped a towel
around her head and leaned forward.
</P>
<P>
   Hinojosa, the Waves super freshmen forward, couldn't bear to
watch the last few seconds tick away in a stunning 61-58 loss to
San Diego in the West Coast Conference tournament final,
Pepperdine's second consecutive setback in the WCC championship
game.
</P>
<P>
   On the other sideline, an eerily similar scene was unfolding.
San Diego coach Kathy Marpe sat down, hid her face in a towel and
began to cry.
</P>
<P>
   Such similar reactions, but for such different reasons. Hinojosa
was trying to put a disaster in perspective. For Marpe, it was a
wonderful dream come true.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine (21-9) had come to the WCC tournament fully expecting
to leave with the school's first NCAA Tournament bid. Instead, the
Waves played their worst game of the season at the most inopportune
time, falling apart in the second half and losing to a team it
easily handled twice this year.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Waves have to hope for an at-large berth into the NCAA
Tournament. More likely, they'll settle for the Women's NIT.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly what they were hoping for.
</P>
<P>
   Hinojosa was at Moorpark High last season when the Waves fell in
the WCC title game to St. Mary's. That loss hurt. Sunday's setback
was more painful because this was Pepperdine's year to break
through. The Waves were the WCC regular-season champions. They'd
won 11 consecutive games heading into Sunday, 19 of their last 22.
San Diego (17-12), the fourth seed, wasn't even supposed to be in
the final, let alone !ital!beat!off! Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   But it's San Diego who will go dancing later this month, not the
Waves.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to hand it to San Diego, they played with great
heart and tremendous hustle and they were determined not to lose,''
said Hinojosa, the WCC Freshmen of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Hinojosa finished with 11 points, but made just 3 of 12 shots.
Pepperdine's other star Rasheeda Clark - had only nine points on 4
of 14 shooting. Clark, the conference Player of the Year, did not
score in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego concluded a brilliant run here this weekend. The
Toreros beat Loyola Marymount, host Santa Clara and top-seeded
Pepperdine to earn their second trip to the NCAAs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an emotional win,'' Marpe said afterward, fighting back
tears. ``We weren't going to leave anything out there on the floor.
We've practiced so hard this year, because (winning the tournament)
was what our goal was.''
</P>
<P>
   The key was a devastating stretch midway through the second
half, when the Toreros broke open a close game by outscoring
Pepperdine 9-0, overcoming a 45-41 deficit to take a 50-45 lead.
They immediately tacked on a 10-2 run to go ahead 60-47 with two
minutes left, effectively ending Pepperdine's hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time all year we didn't answer a run with a
run,'' Hinojosa said.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Gray had 15 points and 12 rebounds to lead San Diego.
Maria Perez-Barris and Susie Erpelding added 14. The Toreros also
got 11 points from Kerri Nakamoto and eight from Melissa
Glazebrook, two role players who weren't factors in the previous
meetings between the teams.
</P>
<P>
   The future is still bright for the Waves, who return a majority
of their team, including stars Clark and Hinojosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we can do is try to get back to the final,'' Pepperdine
coach Mark Trakh said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
