<SLUG> BC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET THE P-I STIR YOUR SYNAPSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Welcome, disgruntled former readers of Seattle Times
sports. Good to have you with the Post-Intelligencer after your
years of wandering the world without the P-I as your beacon of
morning enlightenment.
</P>
<P>
   The P-I has prepared this little quiz of the current sports
scene to stimulate the synaptic responses dulled by years of
reading afternoon sports.
</P>
<P>
   You're welcome. Answers at the end.
</P>
<P>
   This winter, Ken Griffey Jr. was to the Mariners as:
</P>
<P>
   a) The Road Runner was to Wile E. Coyote.
</P>
<P>
   b) Eddie was to Beaver.
</P>
<P>
   c) Lucy was to Charlie Brown.
</P>
<P>
   d) All of the above.
</P>
<P>
   The Kingdome is being destroyed because:
</P>
<P>
   a) As the biggest SOB in the valley, Paul Allen gets his way.
Every time.
</P>
<P>
   b) His Experience Music Project can't win the Ugliest Building
in Creation Award with such formidable hometown competition.
</P>
<P>
   c) Allen can't stand the fact that the Sonics won more
championships in the building than he has won with his NBA team in
Portland's Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   d) All of the above.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks have flailed about almost helplessly in this
off-season's free agent market because:
</P>
<P>
   a) Former front office exec Randy Mueller and former coach
Dennis Erickson furiously spent all the Seahawks' money under the
salary cap in what was a futile bid to save their jobs in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   b) Word is out among free agents about what November and
December life will be like at Husky Stadium the next two years, and
decided it would be better to sign with the Chechnya Rebels.
</P>
<P>
   c) Without more quarterbacks coming from the traditional and
once-formidable Milton College/Central Washington pipeline, the
chance for a winning season seems remote.
</P>
<P>
   d) All of the above.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to watch good college basketball in this state:
</P>
<P>
   a) Move to Spokane.
</P>
<P>
   b) Walk over to the little school on the canal at Nickerson.
</P>
<P>
   c) Get cable or a satellite dish.
</P>
<P>
   d) All of the above.
</P>
<P>
   For the men's and women's basketball programs at the University
of Washington, this has been the worst combined season since:
</P>
<P>
   a) Clarence E. ``Hec'' Edmundson changed his nickname from the
politically incorrect ``Hell.''
</P>
<P>
   b) The movie ``One Million B.C.'' with Raquel Welch in that
sabertooth-tiger outfit.
</P>
<P>
   c) The Big Bang.
</P>
<P>
   d) All of the above.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a respectable won-loss record, the Sonics suddenly have
one of the NBA's worst home-court attendance marks because:
</P>
<P>
   a) Shawn Kemp's kids refuse to go.
</P>
<P>
   b) Even in this hot real estate market, it takes awhile to get
the actual proceeds from a home sale in order to buy a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   c) The period between the heydey of the '96 Finals and now is so
vast that there is no known unit of measure in our time-space
continuum to allow the sports fan to connect the events.
</P>
<P>
   d) All of the above.
</P>
<P>
   The fairest, most reasonable justification for the posture of
oppression that is annually adopted by Mariners ownership to
justify its latest pursuit of public subsidy is:
</P>
<P>
   a) Our wealth is just on paper.
</P>
<P>
   b) Do you have any idea how many shares of Microsoft we had to
sell to pay Bobby Ayala $1.8 million to pitch in Montreal last
year?
</P>
<P>
   c) Hey, you try to run a business that's answerable to Bud
Selig.
</P>
<P>
   d) None of the above. None exist.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' opening night next month at the new ballpark will:
</P>
<P>
   a) Be colder than a wink from Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   b) Provoke a virulent epidemic of wistfulness for the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   c) Cause a renewal, inspired by the events around the WTO, of
the latest Seattle cultural tradition: Dumpster fires.
</P>
<P>
   d) All of the above.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Borrell is:
</P>
<P>
   a) A new video game.
</P>
<P>
   b) A rappelling technique invented on the climbing rock at REI.
</P>
<P>
   c) An NCAA recruiting violation.
</P>
<P>
   d) A Sonics forward.
</P>
<P>
   Kazu Sasaki:
</P>
<P>
   a) Is, after eight years, a payoff for the Mariners being owned
by Nintendo.
</P>
<P>
   b) Maybe the coolest Japanese contribution to Seattle since
Uwajimaya.
</P>
<P>
   c) Will be first relief pitcher in years to come out of the
Seattle bullpen that won't provoke hysterical laughter and
high-fives in the opposing dugout.
</P>
<P>
   d) All of the above.
</P>
<P>
   In sports, the term ``fantasy'' refers generally to a variety of
gambling games involving the drafting of athletes whose seasonal
achievements earn points toward cash prizes for the fantasy general
manager. The term can also mean:
</P>
<P>
   a) Believing that Barry Henthorn is merely a benevolent
philanthropist helping oppressed youngsters survive, as Sports
Illustrated described in its latest issue, the ``urban killing
fields'' of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   b) Optimism that Alex Rodriguez will re-up with the Mariners
without having first won the World Series, Super Bowl, NBA Finals
and Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   c) An expression of hope by a Sonics fan about a potential
first-round playoff matchup against either the Lakers or Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   d) A column in the Times by Michael Fancher.
</P>
<P>
   Because of some confusion surrounding the joint operating
agreement between the Times and P-I, the best way to distinguish
the newspaper rivals is:
</P>
<P>
   a) If the paper isn't being delivered properly, it's the
responsibility of the Times.
</P>
<P>
   b) If your copy looks out of register or otherwise funky, it's
the responsibility of the Times.
</P>
<P>
   c) If it's a quality sports section, as it says on the big
globe: It's in the P-I.
</P>
<P>
   d) All of the above.
</P>
<P>
   For choosing any answer other than d) well, that's why we're
here _ to sharpen your sports knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
