r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     03-06 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS COMING TO THEIR OWN DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You don't have to have an elephant's memory to
recall the days when the Los Angeles Lakers were at their defensive
best after the game clock had expired. They'd ward off questions
about their lethargic rotation on defense, swat away concerns about
team chemistry and intercept any inquiry headed toward
introspection or accountability.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Lakers so closely guarded their egos last season, it
was chilling.
</P>
<P>
   This year their focus is on passing muster with Phil Jackson,
not passing the buck, and the results have been nothing short of
breathtaking. The chip the Lakers once carried on their collective
shoulder has become a veritable bowling ball they're throwing at
opponents lined up like pins.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers completed the NBA equivalent of a 7-10 split on
Sunday, knocking off the Miami Heat 93-80, two days after toppling
the Indiana Pacers. The Lakers, who are on a 15-win roll, never
trailed against the Eastern Conference's two top-ranked
heavyweights and won by a combined 28 points.
</P>
<P>
   More impressive than what the Lakers pulled off on this first
weekend of March was how they did it. They relied heavily on their
defense, which is sort of like Evander Holyfield, who was among the
Staples Center sellout crowd, out-finessing an opponent.
</P>
<P>
   It probably was of little solace to fire-breathing Heat coach
Pat Riley, but his players put forth a commendable effort on both
ends of the floor. The Heat outshot the Lakers, 41.7 percent to
39.5 percent and held them to 76 field-goal attempts, seven below
their season average.
</P>
<P>
   And yet ...
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice burned the Heat like a melted candle in the first
quarter, collecting 13 of his 23 points on 5-of-7 shooting to help
the Lakers to a 14-point lead after 12 minutes. All of the Lakers
were on fire; Ron Harper made 4 of 5 shots, Kobe was a perfect 3
for 3 and Shaquille O'Neal made 3 of 5.
</P>
<P>
   After converting 15 of their first 20 shots, the Lakers made
only 15 of their final 56 attempts. In the final three quarters
O'Neal had five assists against just two baskets, Bryant managed
only two field goals and Rice missed 6 of 9 shots.
</P>
<P>
   And yet ...
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' lead never fell below seven points in that span and
they never led by fewer than 11 over the final 24 minutes. Not
coincidentally, O'Neal had two blocked shots in that time and
Bryant had two steals. Miami's P.J. Brown logged as many personal
fouls (three) in the second half as he did points and Heat center
Alonzo Mourning was outscored in that span by Rice and Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, under Jackson, their first-year coach, have
developed brass knuckles to go along with their eye-candy offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of funny,'' Bryant mused. ``We used to rely on our
offense to win. Now we're relying on our defense. In the past we'd
get a big lead and relax on defense. Now we relax on offense and
our offense gets real sloppy and our defense is what carries us.''
</P>
<P>
   It's about time, Robert Horry said. On many a night last year
the reserve forward felt like he was the only one who cared what
happened when the Lakers didn't have the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, guys are starting to take pride in their defense,''
Horry said.
</P>
<P>
   The wonderful thing about defense is it's impervious to bad
bounces, capricious rims or uncooperative backboards. It requires
no Midas touch to dominate on the defensive end, no journeys to the
Zone such as the one the Lakers took the first 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   All it takes is desire.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, neither Del Harris nor his replacement, Kurt Rambis,
could coax a dependable defensive effort out of the Lakers last
year. The difference a coach can make was borne out with four
minutes left in the second quarter Sunday, when O'Neal took a
charge that saddled the 6-foot-10, 261-pound Mourning with his
third foul.
</P>
<P>
   When their two bodies collided, it was a small wonder it didn't
register on the Richter scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable that Shaq took a charge,'' said Harper,
shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   Just the other day, Harper had recounted a conversation he and
Jackson had when they both were with Chicago. The Bulls were
playing the Lakers and Jackson asked Harper to double down on
O'Neal in an effort to slow him. Harper's response? ``I said,
`You're crazy! I said I'm not taking a charge on him. I have two
kids. I need to see them.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal wasn't thinking Sunday of the child he has, just the
championship rings he is missing. NBA titles may not be won in
March, but messages can be delivered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just beat him to the spot because I knew where he was
going,'' O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year an abdominal injury that was slow to heal made it hard
for O'Neal to slide-step to where he needed to be. It says a lot
about O'Neal, and by extension, the Lakers, that his health no
longer is his only defense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
