<HEADER>
A7815 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BOX-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     03-06 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LOU Savarese was wearing his cell phone Sunday, knowing that at any
minute his lawyer would be calling to say he had received a signed
contract from Mike Tyson, America's antihero.
</P>
<P>
   Having pretty much worn out his welcome in the colonies, Tyson
took his last fight to jolly old England, where the Brits, a
contrarian nation, embraced him. His match with Savarese is
scheduled for April 8 in Milan, Italy, where Lou is expected to
enjoy the home-field advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing about Italians,'' he reminds you, ``they are pretty
animated. At fights, they get excited like soccer fans. If they get
behind me, that would be a big plus.''
</P>
<P>
   Although everyone who opposes Tyson can expect his popularity to
rise, Savarese offers a contrast even sharper than usual. Big Lou
is a whistle-while-you-work kind of guy _ friendly, open,
unguarded, sensible.
</P>
<P>
   In the other corner is Iron Mike, who, if there was a quiz show
that had a category called ``Bad Choices,'' he would be a
multimillionaire. Oh, we forget, he is, or was, a multimillionaire.
When Tyson stopped to smell the flowers, the flowers wilted.
</P>
<P>
   At 34, Lou is trying to make the biggest leap in boxing, from
journeyman to headliner. Tyson is merely trying to live down his
reputation as a calamity waiting to happen, a tornado looking for a
trailer park.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy had it all,'' sums up Lou. ``He made $200 million,
literally, but it didn't make him happy. When he was with Cus
D'Amato and Jimmy Jacobs, they did a great job of marketing him. I
remember they took the press back to his old neighborhood and
showed him feeding the pigeons.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had every physical attribute, strength and speed. He was
tough-minded. He had endorsements and was doing well. Then he
signed with Don King, and everything went downhill. He had some
terrible people around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the guy still commands so much attention. You saw it in
London _ they sold out the arena in two days, and they compared him
to the Beatles, the crowds he drew in the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   A true odd couple, the two won't need any introductions, but
they haven't exactly spent quality time chilling together. ``We run
in different circles,'' says Savarese, in what must qualify as a
major understatement. ``I run into him at fights; we say hello. I
followed his career because we're both from the same part of the
country. I went to a lot of his early fights in the Catskills.''
</P>
<P>
   Lou Savarese was part of a bold experiment that brought a wave
of young gladiators to Houston in the mid- to late 1980s. They were
recruited by Josephine Abercrombie, a lovely lady from a prominent
family who tried to bring to boxing a new system based on honesty,
trust and fair dealings.
</P>
<P>
   It was like trying to spray a dumpster with Air Wick. The
program didn't cause a sudden rush of wealthy idealists to the
sport, but Savarese was one of those who stayed. He has never had
it all, but he almost always had enough, while winning 39 fights
out of 42.
</P>
<P>
   He demolished Buster Douglas in one round, Tim Puller in two,
and scored a TKO over Buster Mathis Jr. in seven on national TV.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he spent most of his career waiting for the kind of
exposure he figures to get from his bout with Tyson, which will be
seen around the globe on Showtime. He lost a split decision in 1997
to George Foreman, who once employed him as a sparring partner.
Last summer he picked a bad night to have a letdown and lost to
Michael Grant in New York, but it was a nice payday, a million or
so, and Savarese has invested his money wisely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came from a real humble family in upstate New York,'' he
confides. ``I'm living a dream now. It sounds corny, but it's true.
It's a terrible business, but I love boxing. I love the characters,
the craziness, the fact that it attracts all walks of life. You go
to Vegas, it's a whole different scene from the crowds at Madison
Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from a long line of hard-nosed guys, from a real
blue-collar town where everybody has a great work ethic. A lot of
my friends work in construction. I had a card in the plumbers'
union. When I walked by a construction site in New York, I'd start
jogging.''
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time he thought his way out of the 9-to-5 world
would be through baseball. At 6-5 and 240 pounds, he was a high
school outfielder who could run and hit with power, and the Mets
gave him a tryout. A prospect in the same camp was a future Atlanta
Braves shortstop named Walt Weiss, whose glove kept the Astros from
winning a playoff series in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had put the same dedication into baseball that I did in
boxing,'' says Savarese, ``I might have made it. But at 18, the
last thing a kid is thinking about is dedication.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
