<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7816 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-BAYLOR-STUKES-HNS     03-06 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BAYLOR-STUKES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
WACO _ Some people might think what Tevis Stukes has done this
season to turn around his basketball career is proof he could
overcome the biggest obstacle of his life. It isn't even close.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Growing up in the projects in New Orleans taught Stukes some
hard lessons that were more important than basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got in with a bad crowd as a kid,'' Stukes said. ``I
couldn't continue to hang with those people. With the path I was
on, I was going to end up one of two places _ in jail or in a
grave.''
</P>
<P>
   Stukes, a 5-11 senior guard, will end his college career this
week as the leading scorer on a Baylor team from which he walked
away last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was through,'' Stukes said. ``I thought I was
gone. But most of my life, I've been in situations where I had to
make a choice. This time I made the right choice and took advantage
of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Stukes was a junior-college transfer who left the
team at midseason after a disagreement with former Baylor coach
Harry Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people looked at me last year like I was a bad person
who didn't want to listen to anybody,'' Stukes said. ``That wasn't
the case. Coach Miller had no problems with me on the court. He
would tell me I was one of the hardest-working players he had on
the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing but respect for coach Miller. But I was having
problems at home, and then coach Miller and I started having
difficulties. It was better for me and the team to just walk away.
It was hard times for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Stukes left the team, but he didn't leave Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really understood the whole story and all the aspects
of the disagreement Tevis had last season,'' said Baylor coach Dave
Bliss, who was hired to replace Miller last spring. ``But the one
thing we admired that Tevis did was keep his eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's highly unusual. A lot of times they drop out of school
and go back home in a situation like that. Then they have no
opportunity. In Tevis' case, his clock would have run out before he
had a chance to play again. But he had the presence to stay in
school, and that comes from within. That speaks to me a great deal
about the type of person he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Stukes admits he came close to leaving, but he decided to stay
after talking to his mother, Dorothy, and meeting with Baylor
athletic director Tom Stanton and associate AD Jim Trego.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked for my release papers from Mr. Stanton and Mr.
Trego,'' Stukes said. ``They told me they thought it was the wrong
thing for me to do, and I listened to them. I really didn't want to
leave. It was just the anger I had built up inside. I've had that
feeling before.''
</P>
<P>
   Stukes often had that feeling while growing up in the ghetto. He
admits that before he was a teen-ager he already was involved in
selling drugs to try to earn money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all you have around you at a young age is drugs, it's hard
to say no to that money,'' Stukes said. ``You want to make that
fast money, especially when you live in a single-parent home and
you are the youngest of four kids. I wanted a lot of things my mom
couldn't get for me, and that pushed me toward the streets. I fell
in that trap.''
</P>
<P>
   But basketball was the one good thing in Stukes' life. It was
clear early on that he had a gift for shooting. Coaches were
watching Stukes as a young teen-ager, along with forward Lester
Earl, both of whom were trying to overcome their environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lester and I have been playing basketball against each other
since we were 12 years old,'' Stukes said. ``Lester knows how rough
it was. There were times when we were supposed to play in
tournaments together but I couldn't go because I was in trouble.
The coach wouldn't take me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lester has seen the projects I grew up in. It was hard. Every
night somebody was dying, getting shot or going to jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Earl, a senior at Kansas, has gone through a troubled college
career that began with a payoff scandal at LSU. Stukes might never
have made it to college if not for a decision by his mother to move
to Lake Charles, La., before Stukes' senior year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big turning point in my life,'' Stukes said. ``It
couldn't have come at a better time. She wanted me to get out of
the environment I was in. If we had not moved to Lake Charles, I
probably wouldn't be here right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Stukes is today would have been hard to imagine one year
ago. He ranks among the top five in scoring in the Big 12
Conference, averaging 17.8 points a game, and he leads the league
in 3-point shots made with 94.
</P>
<P>
   ``God gave me a talent to shoot, and he wants me to use it,''
Stukes said. ``So I try to give it all I have every time I step on
the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Most fans would say the weakness of his game is that Stukes
takes too many bad shots, which shows in his .362 shooting
percentage. But Bliss said Stukes' shot selection is misleading.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times Tevis is forced to take a bad shot because we
don't have other people to protect him,'' Bliss said. ``That causes
him to take some shots he doesn't need to take and makes his
percentage look lower than it normally would be. But I appreciate
the fact that he knows how much he's needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Stukes has helped lead the Bears back to respectability with a
13-14 record going into the Big 12 tournament in Kansas City, Mo.
Baylor lost every conference game last season en route to a 6-24
mark. But the team won four league games this year and was
competitive in several others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Bliss has a tremendous coaching philosophy, and all his
assistants know what they're doing,'' Stukes said. ``Coach Bliss is
going to turn this program around, believe me. He will have Ferrell
Center rocking in a couple of years. I just wish I had another year
to play with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bliss is happy he had Stukes around for his first year with the
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cupboard here wasn't bare, but it certainly was thin,''
Bliss said. ``Tevis gave us something to work with. I marvel at how
he has improved through the course of the Big 12 season. He really
has picked up of late. The chance to coach him this year and watch
him improve has been very enjoyable.''
</P>
<P>
   Stukes knew that his second chance also would be his last chance
as a college player.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important to me to show people that I could take
advantage of my opportunity,'' Stukes said. ``Coach Bliss didn't
worry about what happened last year. He just wanted to know that I
still was interested in going to school here and playing basketball
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stukes said he wanted to show people more than his
basketball skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I showed everyone at this university that I wanted to
be here by staying in school and going to class,'' Stukes said. ``I
kept working out on my own and kept doing the things I needed to
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a lot of motivation because there were days when I
didn't want to get up and go to class, but I did it. I was
determined to show people I wasn't who they thought I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Stukes knows people saw him in an unfavorable light after what
happened last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``People judge unfairly, but I've been dealing with that all my
life,'' he said. ``They see how I wear my chains, my earrings, my
gold teeth and my tattoos, and they think I'm a thug.
</P>
<P>
   ``But people who know me know I'm one of the most respectful
guys around here. I respect my elders. I want people here to say
that Tevis is a respectful young man who looked up to people and
never disrespected anybody. I want everyone to see that I took the
right path.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
