A7846 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN     03-06 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER SLUMP, RICE HEATS UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Glen Rice didn't hide his frustration. He had
sputtered on offense for three consecutive games and set out to
stop the trend quickly Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long, as Rice made 5 of 7 shots for 13 points in
the first quarter against his former team, the Miami Heat. He
finished with 23 points, nearly matching his total for the prior
three games combined (27 points).
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of whether or not we're winning, I always get down
when I go out there and I don't play up to my potential,'' Rice
said.
</P>
<P>
   He's found his groove in the Los Angeles Lakers' triangle
offense at times, only to see it periodically slip away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does at times,'' he said, ``but I can't let that happen.
I've got to go out there and just play basketball. I can't worry
about anything but going out there and doing my job. I'm always
putting a lot of pressure on myself when I'm not going out there
and playing up to my capabilities and not hitting the shots that I
know I can hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you're thankful that you have guys like Shaq
(O'Neal), Kobe (Bryant), Robert (Horry) and those guys playing very
well, where the slack has been taken up. And I owe it to myself to
go out there and play the way I know I'm capable of playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said he saw the resurgence coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glen told me before the game, he said, `Yo, Kobe, I'm ready to
go, man.' So I knew he was going to come out and do his thing,''
Bryant said. ``He was just able to find his spots a little bit
better. I think he's just starting to get his rhythm back in this
offense a little bit. It's on him to be more aggressive, not to be
as passive as he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Foul mood: Miami's Tim Hardaway was impressed by the Lakers
after the Heat's 93-80 loss, but he said they had help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the referees are scared to call fouls against them,''
Hardaway said after the Heat was called for 29 fouls to the Lakers'
22. ``I think they're afraid of the Lakers and (coach) Phil
Jackson. As a team, we feel we don't get calls as an elite team. We
feel that the referees hate us and we have to overcome every game.
... I'm not saying they're not a good team, but give us a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal had a different take: ``I think the league, they owe me
those calls. I admit I got away with one or two. Shoot, I'm
supposed to. I'm at home. If I'm on the road, I expect not to get
those calls. ... Like I said, the league owes me those calls. I get
fouled every time down, period, no questions asked.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
