A7847 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-SANTAC     03-06 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-SANTACLARA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE BEATS SANTA CLARA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ Tezale Archie hit a pair of free throws
with 20 seconds remaining to seal Pepperdine's 58-55 win over host
Santa Clara in the semifinals of the West Coast Conference
tournament Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves, the WCC regular-season champions, move into tonight's
final against Gonzaga, an 80-70 winner over San Diego in the
earlier game. Pepperdine (24-7) split its two games against the
Bulldogs this year.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament champion gets an automatic bid to the NCAA
Tournament. Last season, Gonzaga won the WCC title and advanced to
the Elite Eight.
</P>
<P>
   Archie missed two free throws with six seconds left after Santa
Clara's Darrell Teat missed on a 3-pointer seconds before. But
Broncos guard Brian Vaka misfired on a last-second 3-pointer to
give the Waves the win.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Armstrong had 15 points for Pepperdine while Tommie
Prince added 13.
</P>
<P>
   Prince put the Waves ahead 56-55 with 43 seconds left on a pair
of free throws. On Santa Clara's next possession, Nick Sheppard
stepped in front of Teat to force a charging call, giving the ball
back to Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves led 47-41 with six minutes left, but Santa Clara
(19-12) chipped away, outscoring the Waves 13-5 over the next four
minutes to go ahead 54-52 on Nathan Fast's steal and breakaway dunk
with 2:16 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine survived a sloppy start to lead 28-24 at halftime.
The Broncos scored the first six points of the game and led 20-12
at one point.
</P>
<P>
   It could have been worse, but the Waves' defense, a strength all
year, kept things close.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine got it rolling over the last seven minutes, forcing
11 consecutive Santa Clara misses to spark an 11-0 run to go ahead
23-20.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong had seven points at the half to lead Pepperdine. Lewis
added six.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos, who shot 36.7 percent from the field, got 10 points
from Jaime Fields.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves won both meetings against Santa Clara during the
regular season, limiting the Broncos to 59.2 points per game on
just 39 percent shooting from the floor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 0150EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7848 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-DUCKS-PREDATORS-L     03-06 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-PREDATORS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS HOLD ON FOR VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Anaheim Mighty Ducks' offense generated
little more than hockey's version of a passed ball Sunday night,
but that was plenty as Guy Hebert pitched a shutout and Anaheim
defeated Nashville 1-0 in front of 13,601 at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert stopped all 33 shots he faced, and Johann Davidsson, a
forgotten man in Cincinnati most of the year, scored on a
harmless-looking wrist shot at 17:10 of the second period to help
the Ducks end a losing streak at two games.
</P>
<P>
   It was hardly artistic, but Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg dared
anybody to put an ugly face on a victory that moved the Ducks
(28-29-10-1) within two points of Calgary and San Jose in the
battle for the eighth and final Western Conference playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't like the game?'' he said when asked if the Ducks
were happy to just win and move on. ``We just came off a tough week
(1-2 on a three-game trip) and our team showed some character. It
found a way to win and that's all that mattered.''
</P>
<P>
   For the better part of two periods it didn't look as if either
team was going to find the back of the net. Both Hebert and
Nashville goalie Tomas Vokun were solid, if not spectacular.
Quality scoring chances were rare.
</P>
<P>
   But finally the Ducks broke through with a goal from an unlikely
source on an unlikely play.
</P>
<P>
   Davidsson, recalled from Cincinnati on Saturday, took advantage
of solid forechecking by Mike Leclerc and Ladislav Kohn and decided
to wrist a shot toward the Nashville net. The puck got through a
maze of players in front of Vokun, including Leclerc, and dipped
between the Nashville goalie's legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal was the result of good pressure,'' said Hartsburg.
``And in these types of games those are usually the type that
decide them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks had seen plenty of those goals go against them this
season, so they were thrilled to get one going their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed somebody to be lucky and I was the lucky guy,'' said
Davidsson, who has spent the majority of the year in the minors
after playing the entire 1998-99 season in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth goal of Davidsson's brief NHL career (69 games)
seemed to surprise the Swedish forward as much as anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said `Oh my God, I think it's going,''' he said with a big
smile. ``It's funny how things work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hebert also had a big smile after posting his fourth shutout of
the season and first since Dec. 17, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said `He (Vokun) is never seeing that one,''' said Hebert of
Davidsson's shot. ``There's no sympathy at all. I was thinking `All
right, that might be enough to win this game.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And it was, thanks to Hebert, who was especially sharp in the
early moments of the first and second periods. He stopped three
shots from close range at the 30-second mark of the second period,
but perhaps the biggest saves he made came in the opening 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim goalie stopped 14 Nashville shots, including three
in succession early in the game. After stopping Mark Mowers twice
from the base of the left circle, Hebert slid across the crease to
deny Tom Fitzgerald's bid from the right side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working hard on that, trying to beat the pass to
player,'' said Hebert, referring to his recent workouts with goalie
consultant Francois Allaire. ``That (the saves) set me into a good
rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   Hebert now wants to see the entire team get into a good rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to win more than our fair share of the last 15 to make
(the playoffs,'' he said. ``There's going to be a lot of scoreboard
watching over the next few weeks, but if we take care of business
we won't have to watch as much.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
