<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE HOPES PARRIS WILL RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When they needed a big basket, he was there. A big
rebound, he was there. A hustle play? Jeff Parris was there.
</P>
<P>
   Parris almost single-handedly kept the Cal State Northridge
men's basketball team from a potentially embarrassing loss Saturday
night against Sacramento State.
</P>
<P>
   He scored 23 points, grabbed 10 rebounds (including six
offensive) and had four steals as the Matadors closed out their
most successful season in Division I with an 81-57 win over the
Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   Parris keyed a late 20-0 run with offensive rebounds, slam dunks
and put-backs. He also was 9 of 13 from the free-throw line in the
game, well above his 55 percent season average.
</P>
<P>
   The CSUN coaches and players hope they haven't seen the last of
Parris at Matador Gym.
</P>
<P>
   Parris is a senior, but he's played only three seasons in
Northridge; he lost his freshman season as a non-academic
qualifier. Through academic achievement - Parris is going to
graduate in May with a degree in psychology - he's earned the right
to be granted an additional season of eligibility by the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't anticipate anything different than (Parris) coming
back,'' CSUN coach Bobby Braswell said. ``I know his parents want
him back (playing). He came in here and he got his degree in four
years. I'm very, very proud of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the game, Parris was included in a tribute to the
team's senior class, which included Andre Larry and Hewitt Rolle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to talk it over with my close friends and family
members and my coaches and see what I can do,'' he said. ``I had a
good career here. Just in case I didn't come back, I wanted to have
that senior night experience.''
</P>
<P>
   In case you missed it ...: Montana's 77-75 upset of Eastern
Washington on Saturday night meant both the Big Sky Conference
men's and women's tournaments will be held in Missoula.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday night, the Big Sky announced a rough sketch of
this week's tournament schedule. Four games will be played
Wednesday the two men's and women's quarterfinals. The fifth-seeded
Northridge men (18-9, 10-6) play fourth-seeded Weber State in the
final game of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The second-seeded Matadors women (17-9, 11-5) play one of the
quarterfinal winners Thursday in the women's semifinals. The men's
semifinals are Friday and both championship games are Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Flying high: Four CSUN track and field athletes - Brandi Prieto,
Annetta Wells, Clinte Motley and Billy Bush - competed Friday and
Saturday in the prestigious USA Indoor Nationals at the Georgia
Dome in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a CSUN assistant coach - Dominique Arnold - who had
the best meet. Arnold was nipped at the wire by South Carolina's
Terrence Trammell in the 60-meter hurdles final. Both men had the
same time: 7.57 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, a senior at Northridge, was fifth in the shot put with a
mark of 60 feet, 1 inches. He won the Big Sky indoor title with a
throw of 61-9, qualifying him provisionally for the NCAA indoor
championships this week in Fayetteville, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Prieto, a senior, was eighth in the women's triple jump with a
mark of 41 feet, 11 inches. She's a provisional NCAA indoor
qualifier in both the triple jump (42-7) and the 55-meter hurdles
(7.95).
</P>
<P>
   Wells, a junior, competed but didn't qualify for the 200 and 400
finals. She won both events - the 200 in 24:32 and the 400 in 54.67
- at the Big Sky indoor meet.
</P>
<P>
   Motley, a junior, competed in the triple jump but didn't make
the final. He was the conference champion with a mark of 52-9.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, Motley and Jennifer Capeheart, who won the Big Sky pole
vault with a mark of 11-11, are all provisional qualifiers for the
NCAA championships.
</P>
<P>
   Losing bodies: Three offensive linemen quit the football team in
February, including Joe Bergman, a sophomore who started the
Matadors' first two games before injuries ended his season.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman, a 6-foot-5, 290-pound guard from Bakersfield, had a
concussion and torn ACL last year. Another guard, sophomore Geoff
Watson (6-3, 285) also quit, as did Ernie Fierro (6-4, 300), one of
CSUN's top transfers last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
