<HEADLINE>
THIS ON-LINE LEAGUE ROCKS, OR RATHER, DOESN'T
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A punishment that Major League Baseball
commissioner Bud Selig failed to sock to Atlanta Braves pitcher
John Rocker - a one-month regular-season suspension was cut in half
by an arbitrator - has not only been upheld by an on-line fantasy
league but taken further.
</P>
<P>
   FantasySportsnet.com has suspended Rocker for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Company CEO Darrell C. Lerner, however, said they would review
Rocker's situation before the All-Star break, and ``if there have
been no further transgressions, and his ERA is below 3.00 and he's
accumulated 15 saves, he might be reinstated for selection by FSN
subscribers.''
</P>
<P>
   Way to take a stand.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, a statement released by the New York-based site
noted: ``The announcement was made in a blatantly transparent
attempt to gain publicity for the new Web venture.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider it done.
</P>
<P>
   --Although it deals mostly with selling trading cards and
autographed stuff, a site called RealLegends.com has added a spot
for new books and movies for sale.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not buying, you can at least see pretty much every
trading card produced since 1948.
</P>
<P>
   --With a Java chessboard to illustrate all the right moves, the
U.S. Chess Federation site (www.uschess.org) is offering members
coverage of the Linares 2000 Super Tournament, which is referred to
as the unofficial world championship. It runs through Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the participants are top-ranked chesser Garry Kasparov.
</P>
<P>
   --And not only does the Professional Racquetball Association
exist, it has a Web site (www.PRATour.com) starting this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
