<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7853 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-SKI     03-06 1998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKINNER STILL BELIEVES BC CAN REACH HEIGHTS? 
</HEADLINE>
 COLLEGE-SKINNER-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Two bookcases sit behind Al Skinner's desk in his
second-floor office at Boston College's Conte Forum.
</P>
<P>
   One has the usual assortment of pictures, basketballs, and
memorabilia. The other is virtually empty, unusual for a coach
finishing up his third season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got some old stuff (from his days at Rhode Island),''
Skinner says with a soft laugh. ``But I will be patient and wait.
And hopefully there will be enough new stuff to fill those shelves.
That's a little goal for myself: To fill it up with all BC stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearing what could be the final game of the 1999-2000 season _
the 13th-seeded Eagles will face fourth seed Connecticut Wednesday
in an opening-round Big East tournament game _ Skinner was talking
about the past, present, and future of BC basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the Eagles' 11-17 record this season, coupled with
the 15-16 and 6-21 marks of the two previous campaigns, Skinner, in
charge of rebuilding the Eagles program, was remarkably upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, we're ahead of schedule,'' said Skinner, who
never had had three consecutive losing seasons. ``I didn't think
this was going to happen until next year or the year after.''
</P>
<P>
   A strange statement from a coach whose team lost 14 of its last
16 games, although Saturday night's win over Villanova made Skinner
happy entering the contest against UConn.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner considers games as more than wins and losses. He
measures progress in effort, competitiveness, hustle. He has little
choice, of course.
</P>
<P>
   He is in a marathon, not a sprint, three years into a seven-year
contract. He believes it may take that long before the Eagles reach
the goal of being truly competitive in the Big East, and thus
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   To understand where Skinner and BC want to travel, you have to
understand where they have been.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Skinner, who grew up in New York, attended the University of
Massachusetts, played two seasons in the American Basketball
Association and three in the National Basketball Association before
starting a coaching career that included nine seasons and four
postseason appearances at Rhode Island, believes he is in the right
place at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   He may also be the perfect person to guide BC after the NCAA
Tournament-quality program that Jim O'Brien spent a decade building
was ruined when O'Brien left in a swirl of acrimony and discord
over admissions standards.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner's public demeanor suggests calmness. He is a players'
coach, with patience.
</P>
<P>
   His troops have noticed. ``It's like my dad told me,'' said
senior Michael Cotton, who has watched Skinner deal with the early
stages of rebuilding. ``The best ability is dependability. That's
him. He lets you play, lets you be yourself. It's never too high,
never too low.''
</P>
<P>
   That belies what churns inside, however. ``Al plays in these
pickup games at lunchtime,'' says associate head coach Tim O'Shea
with a laugh and a shake of his head. ``And he's got that killer
instinct. It's like he still playing for a paycheck. When it comes
down to crunch time, it doesn't matter who he's playing _ teachers,
the postman, his mother _ he'll go after you.''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner doesn't deny his competitiveness. He says it is part of
his upbringing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came out of New York,'' he says. ``I wasn't even close to
being one of the best players. All I knew was that I wanted to
compete and if I wasn't good enough, I had to work at it. So that's
what I did on a daily basis. I worked to get myself better. If I'm
not good enough right now, it's up to me to take that energy and
work and get myself better. That's what I try and relate to my
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet a man must know his limitations and Skinner understands that
the dawn-to-midnight schedule some coaches of losing programs might
follow during the season is not his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't take it home,'' he says. ``That's the one thing I
don't do. If I need to do work, I do it here. Once I arrive home,
that's for my family. It would be unfair for them for me to bring
my woes home.
</P>
<P>
   ``And for me it has to be on a daily basis. I go home and have
some quality time with my family. If I don't, I'm not living the
quality of life I want.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to work at my best every day. My biggest goal is how I
can work at that every day. It's a known fact that you need a
certain amount of rest. You need certain peace of mind. Some guys
get too overworked and they can't give their best. If you're tired
and stressed out, you can't think clearly and the mental part of
this game is probably the most important.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coming from Rhode Island, where Skinner built a team that came
within a heartbeat of reaching the Final Four in the season after
he left, to Boston College, was a mental challenge of the first
order.
</P>
<P>
   How not only to rebuild a program, but the reputation of a
school that had been battered by not only changes in coaching, but
of a betting scandal in football, muted references to racism in the
academic process, and total chaos in the athletic department until
athletic director Gene DeFilippo came in. He figuratively opened
some windows that allowed fresh air to flow through the department
and let people feel good about their jobs and themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has always been a difficult job,'' said Skinner. ``The
academic requirements and reputation of this school will always
make it that way. The pool of student athletes to draw from is much
smaller than what I could draw from at Rhode Island.''
</P>
<P>
   There is more. ``Let's face it,'' he said. ``The city of Boston
has had its share of problems as far as minority students are
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember my first year here. I spoke to a couple of key
people on the West Coast. All they could remember was the Boston of
the '60s and '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm dealing with guys my age whose sons are playing. They
said, `Al, you're a good guy. But Boston?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner acknowledges the changes in attitude, which have
resulted in people like former Celtics great Bill Russell coming
back and embracing the city again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize the evolution the city has made,'' he said. ``But
that still lingers. Those are the things you deal with. It's not
just BC. But the city of Boston has to take some responsibility for
what exists.''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner remembers a year ago going hard after a player who lived
in Alabama. ``We brought him in here and he loved the place,'' said
Skinner. ``But his dad says, `I can't see my son in Boston.' What
are you going to do about those things? You get a kid to say yes,
and his dad says what he said. Those are the realities you deal
with.''
</P>
<P>
   It is that type of thinking that Skinner says has kept BC behind
Big East schools such as Rutgers and Seton Hall, who also made
coaching changes three years ago but are much farther along in the
rebuilding process than the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner says he is looking for the right attitude as much as
ability. ``As long as I know I'm working hard at it and my players
are working hard at it, I have to take some satisfaction. All I ask
is that they give 100 percent. I don't believe in that 110 percent.
That's non-existent. I believe in the work ethic, as corny as that
is. I have certain beliefs that drive me. I'm not saying I don't
get sidetracked. But eventually I come back and keep my eye on the
prize. That is who I am. I ask this of my players. You have to play
with passion, with desire. That's the only way I know how to
play.'''
</P>
<P>
   His players playing or practicing without passion raises
Skinner's temperature gauge to a dangerous level. ``If he's going
to lose it,'' says O'Shea, who has been with Skinner for 12
seasons, ``someone is going down. People are scared. He has trouble
with people who don't play aggressively.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Skinner and his staff face the same hurdles that O'Brien and his
staff faced. He is required to compete at the Big East level, but
also bring in players who can also be successful students.
</P>
<P>
   It is a delicate balance. ``The last thing I want to do is bring
in someone and have him not succeed,'' Skinner said. ``I think
that's very unfair. I have a sense of responsibility for that. The
people I bring in have to have a certain amount of academic
success. It doesn't always mean graduate. But it does mean having
some achievement. I don't want people playing for me that don't
have a commitment to that.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, it's a hollow feeling for me because I don't
enjoy it because I feel like I have taken advantage of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner says the foundation is in place. Guard Troy Bell, a
leading contender for Big East Freshman of the Year, and forward
Uka Agbai could be the starting point.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago players of that caliber wouldn't even listen to
Skinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are getting into homes now and people are allowing us to
sit down and talk to them and let us tell them how they can help
make us better,'' he said. ``I don't think we could have done that
two years ago or a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we're making progress. Unfortunately it may not show up
on the scoreboard. But I know the hurdles we had to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to reach a certain level where at least I have a
chance to see if I can do what I'm paid to do and to do it well. I
have in the past. But that's the past. We're looking ahead to the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, Skinner will have a couple of more years to
fix what is broken.
</P>
<P>
   When he came from Rhode Island he knew what he faced and how
long it would take to make it right. He asked for the seven-year
contract. ``I don't think anyone has accused me of being stupid,''
Skinner said. ``I know it's going to take some time. I also know
how to build a program.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DeFilippo says he is more than willing to give Skinner the time
because he has liked what he has seen thus far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a coach,'' DeFilippo says. ``I know what it takes to
win, to build a program. At the end of five years, we'll know
better and he'll know better which direction this program is going.
I think Al is doing the right things. He's a wonderful person, a
great role model, and a heck of bench coach. I have all the
confidence in the world that he is going to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner has survived this season with what appears to be a
minimum of wear. Aside from the losing, he says things are just
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few brushfires have broken out _ the latest being the
persistent rumor that Bell was unhappy and wanted to head back home
to Minnesota. Bell and Skinner say those rumors are without
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says no,'' said Skinner. ``But more important, his attitude
says no. He wasn't playing (before a recent season-ending knee
injury) like he wanted to get out of here. And he said he didn't. I
don't know many young people who can be that dishonest. When they
get to the professional level, yeah, they can be. But at this level
they haven't learned that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner says small steps need to come before big steps, but
there is no doubt in his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in BC, I believe in the city,'' said Skinner. ``I
know where I want to go; I know what I want to accomplish. I have
my eye on the prize.''
</P>
<P>
   The prize is to make BC competitive in the Big East and
nationally. The prize is to restore respect to the program.
</P>
<P>
   But there is more than that for Al Skinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long run,'' he says, ``relationships are the most
important thing. That's what it's all about for me in this
business. I still want to compete at the highest level. It
motivates me and drives me. But it's still about the relationships
I develop here with my players. In order for me to develop those, a
young person has to have some kind of success here. I have to
create an environment that's going to do that, both athletically
and academically. And that's what I'm trying to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
