</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITINO ADMITS HE COULD ENVISION LEAVING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Rick Pitino said he wasted no gray matter wondering
what kind of reaction he'd get Sunday at the FleetCenter. It was
his first home game since his memorable postgame rant five days
ago, but he said he didn't even think about how the crowd would
respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, no,'' he said when asked if he thought about what
might happen in the building. Nothing much did. There was very
little cheering or booing when his name was announced before the
Celtics' 97-91 victory over the Orlando Magic in a festive
FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   There was hardly any ``negativity'' whatsoever all game, just
some scattered boos when the Celtics missed their first 14 shots.
Then again, this was a matinee with a PG crowd more suited for
``Toy Story 2'' or ``My Dog Skip.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino expressed satisfaction with the crowd. ``Very few teams
are going to beat us with this type of atmosphere,'' he said. His
comments last Wednesday, he said, were directed at ``very few
people, probably less than 100 people. Because the people that
didn't like what I said, the guilty conscience needs no accuser.
They are negative people. People who are positive people, cheering
the hell out of the Celtics, that's great.''
</P>
<P>
   He then addressed comments attributed to him in Sunday's New
York Daily News. In the article, Pitino said he would leave at the
end of next season if things did not improve and gladly step aside
for Larry Bird if that's what he thought was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can go one more year and be realistic and say, `I'm
not getting it done,' and go out and hire somebody else,'' Pitino
said in the story. ``At that point, I might have to.'' He also
said, ``At the end of next season, I can say, `I gave it my best
shot' and move on and get somebody else to coach this team. Or, I
can decide to break this team up and rebuild, which I don't see
myself doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about those remarks Sunday, Pitino said he did not put any
time limit on his stay in Boston. But he did say that he would
remove himself from the equation if he saw things were not
improving.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I was basically saying was, that if I'm not getting the
job done in my mind, then I'm not holding up (owner) Paul Gaston,''
Pitino said. ``That's not what I'm going to do. That's not the way
I am. Paul Gaston has been great to Rick Pitino. He gave him one of
the greatest jobs in all of coaching. But if I wasn't getting it
done, I would go to Paul and say, `Let's come to a mutual
agreement. You've given me the break. You need to make a decision.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want him coming to me,'' Pitino went on. ``I want to
make it easy. He's very happy with me. So is the organization. He's
not happy with the amount of wins we have. I'm sure he's ticked off
about that. But he knows how hard we're working and he also
believes we're not that far away. I believe that as well. But I
don't want to see this town negative. I don't want that. I've got
too much confidence in my ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino said he sometimes feels he should ``have a little more
Lou Holtz in me.'' Holtz, of course, doesn't think his team can win
anything (and this past season, at South Carolina, he was right).
Pitino is the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've never lost and I've never been that way,'' he said,
referring to the gloom-and-doom Holtz. ``So I'm the eternal
optimist. But this is a tough job. It's a bitch. It's much, much
tougher than I ever anticipated, much tougher, because youth is
very difficult in the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   He also was quoted in the News as saying, ``If I could,
tomorrow, bring in Larry Bird to be the coach here, I would step
aside in a second. Because I think this town loves Larry Bird.
Because I think this town would benefit. It would be very upbeat
and very positive.'' He also said the same would go for Bill
Russell in an executive role. But, he added, ``I don't think any of
those people will outwork me or outcoach me.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino said he was talking about hypotheticals when he brought
up Bird's name. (Bird never would take the job anyway.) He said it
was merely an example of what he would do to see the Celtics
succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm saying is, I'm for the Celtics winning,'' Pitino
said. ``And if I wasn't getting the job done, I'd bring in anybody,
it wouldn't matter who, if I felt that person could get the job
done. That's my only message. When it's all said and done, I'll
bring in anyone. The whole point was just about the Celtics
winning. It was, if somewhere down the road, if they want a Celtics
legend, I'll do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino said if it doesn't work out here, he will try and get
another pro coaching job. ``I came to this level to win a
championship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And how long did he think he could stick around as an executive
after hiring his successor, if it came to that?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll cross that bridge when I come to it,'' he said. ``But I
could (stay) for a year, maybe. But coaching is in my blood. That's
what I do. Right now, I don't even want to think about that. I want
to do what is best for the Boston Celtics. But I also have a
responsibility to do the best thing for the organization and if I
don't see improvement from the basketball team, I would not hold up
anybody. That is not my nature.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 0211EST &QL; 
