<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7855 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-LEWIS-BOS &LR;      03-06 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS: COUNT ME IN 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-LEWIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ If you insist on measuring Darren Lewis by
the numbers, he suggests with just a trace of exasperation that you
take a look at this one.
</P>
<P>
   For the last seven seasons, beginning with a Giants team that
won 103 games in 1993, Lewis has played on teams that either went
to the playoffs or were in postseason contention well into
September.
</P>
<P>
   That includes the Red Sox, of course, who have won the wild card
in each of Lewis's two seasons as the starting center fielder.
</P>
<P>
   That's no coincidence, in Lewis's view. ``It's no secret that
the strongest part of my game is something that doesn't show up in
the box score,'' he said. ``There is no stat for my strengths. I
know I can say I helped this team win. Look at the last two
years.''
</P>
<P>
   But even though he signed Lewis to a three-year deal immediately
after the 1998 season, Lewis's first with the club, Red Sox general
manager Dan Duquette has tried to upgrade the center field position
in each of the last two winters. He came very close to signing free
agent Bernie Williams last winter, and this winter landed Carl
Everett, whose offensive skills have him heralded as the best
center fielder the Sox have had since Fred Lynn.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Lewis played center and hit leadoff when the Sox lost,
11-6, to the Minnesota Twins at Hammond Stadium. But when the
season opens next month in Seattle, Everett will be the starting
center fielder, barring injury. Lewis will be on the bench as an
outfield reserve, unless he is in another uniform.
</P>
<P>
   One might tend to take that personally, and Lewis is no
exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it's natural to feel that way,'' he said. ``I leave
my heart and soul on the field. But it all comes down to what
continues to motivate me as a player, to prove them _ whoever
`they' are _ wrong. I'll try to fight my way back, make myself an
everyday player again.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's definitely something special on this team. If
there wasn't something special, I'd be begging to get out of here.
But the grass isn't always greener somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Paint by the numbers, and Everett is a Monet, Lewis a coloring
book. Everett hit .325 last season, 85 percentage points higher
than Lewis's .240. He hit 25 home runs to Lewis's two, scored 86
runs to Lewis's 63, drove in 108 runs to Lewis's 40. Everett's is a
bat the Sox will feature in the No. 3 hole. Lewis's bat was one the
Red Sox often tried to hide.
</P>
<P>
   But Lewis insists the numbers don't give the texture and
shadings any good portrait requires. They don't show the Gold
Glove-caliber defense, the willingness to give up an at-bat to move
a runner over, his ability to drop a bunt, his refusal to sit out
when hurt, the dedication and professionalism in a clubhouse that
sorely needed both when he arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any team that would choose Lewis over Everett, who is
four years younger, comes close to being Lewis's equal afield, and
has a better arm? Of course not.
</P>
<P>
   But is there a place for a player who brings what Lewis offers
to a team? Manager Jimy Williams says absolutely. ``Darren Lewis
belongs on this team,'' he says. ``He's a winner. Those guys are
not easy to find.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than two months, Lewis was bothered by a sore left
wrist he injured while sliding into second base in Toronto. But he
said little about the injury, even as his average plummeted. He hit
just .215 after the All-Star break, .180 after Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wrist got me in some bad habits,'' Lewis said. ``I was
swinging the bat long, trying to protect it. But I'm the type of
person not to use an injury as an excuse. Just go play ball. I'm
not the type to go on the DL with a nagging injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did the numbers slip? Sure, they did. But I've got to play.
There's too many things I can do to help the team win. Some players
don't get a hit, they can't help the team win. I can go without a
hit and still help.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lewis is not certain whether he can accept being a Sox
extra after being a cast member for the last two years, especially
when it's hard for him to shake the feeling that his contribution
has been denigrated by the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize that people have different views and different
philosophies,'' he said. ``Those things are out of my control. My
game is the same as it has been the last eight years. If you look
at my numbers, they're very similar every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Has their philosophy changed? It looks that way. Have my goals
changed? No, they haven't. I still do the same things I've done
every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis acknowledges that the best teams have good veteran players
on the bench, too. He cites the Yankees and Chad Curtis as an
example. Curtis didn't play much, but he still played a vital role
as a reserve and hit two home runs in Game 3 of the World Series
against the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Lewis would like very much to remain part of the
mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to be in one spot,'' he said. ``People know Darren
Lewis plays for the Boston Red Sox and that I make a difference on
this team. I'm happy with that at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Would there be a point, if the playing time doesn't come, where
he would be unhappy?
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I going to ask them to trade me?'' he said. ``Not at this
point. There may come a point where I have to think about myself
just like they think of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy where I'm at. I enjoy my teammates, I enjoy the city
of Boston. I'm on a team that has a chance to win. Am I going to
have some at-bats? Maybe, maybe not. When you look at the team on
paper right now, Darren Lewis is the fourth outfielder, but that's
not the way I approach it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody can get hurt, somebody may not be producing, and
they'll still have a guy who has worth to the ballclub. I've proved
that year in and year out.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the numbers say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 0213EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
