u s BC-BBA-RYANCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-06 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KELLY HAS SEEN TWO SIDES OF TWINS 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ God bless Tom Kelly. Ask him a question and
you're not going to get a diplomatic,
on-the-one-hand-but-on-the-other-hand response.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this (Brad) Radke thing going to be a distraction?'' the
Twins manager asks. ``How can it not be? They usually are. Every
new city, someone's going to ask him about it. Someone's going to
ask me about it. It's a better story than asking about this
ballclub. He's going to be a target.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, in case you're coming in late, 27-year-old Brad Radke is
Minnesota's best pitcher. He has entered the final year of his
contract, and so is now prime trade bait. He would, in theory,
enhance the title chances of many a contending club, the Red Sox
included. He is far and away the juiciest news topic on a
low-payroll team where even someone who regularly tapes ``Baseball
Tonight'' in order to watch it the next morning would find it a
major chore just to name five players on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kelly has been to the baseball mountaintop _ twice. He
managed the Twins to the World Series championship in both 1987 and
1991, before growing payroll imbalances systematically eliminated
the Milwaukees, the Pittsburghs, and the Minnesotas from any
practical hope of contention. The Twins had enough residual roster
strength to win 90 games and finish second in 1992, but the crash
came in a major way the following season (71-91), and in the last
seven years his teams have won 147 fewer games than they've lost.
That state of affairs will not change in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   So here sits Kelly, legs crossed, leaning on a bat,
acknowledging that, once again, what he's up to and what the likes
of Joe Torre, Johnny Oates, and even Jimy Williams are up to in the
upcoming season are two entirely different things.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little different here than it was a couple of years
ago,'' he says. ``We have made a commitment to play the younger
fellas. Our payroll is $17 million, give or take, and it's not
going to change. We're looking at a few older guys to give us a
little stability. We've got (pitcher) Bobby Ayala, but I don't know
if he'll make the team. We've got (third baseman/DH) Butch Huskey,
who's had success with a few teams (and who hit a home run against
the Red Sox Saturday). We're taking a look at (pitcher) Sean
Bergman. But mostly what we're trying to do is get it across to the
young guys that they've got to be more consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   As he speaks, there is a Minneapolis newspaper column in
circulation alleging that he has a difference of opinion with
general manager Terry Ryan over the quality of the youngsters in
question. This is one time when the truth may be a bit hard to come
by, since Kelly is publicly committed to staying the course in
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Kelly professes to be excited about such young
players as first baseman David Ortiz, third baseman Corey Koskie,
and catcher Matt LeCroy.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids need to get stronger mentally,'' he explains.
``They have to understand that this is a seven-day game. They play
well for two or three days a week, but that's not enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Twins are off the radar screen for the average fan, but for
the aficionados Kelly holds an ongoing fascination because, as much
as any manager in the game, he is the clear public face of his
organization. Since 1986, you think ``Twins,'' you think ``Tom
Kelly,'' first in the early glory days when an unsmiling,
media-unfriendly Kelly scared away most inquisitors, and now in his
more avuncular phase, when he welcomes familiar media faces who
have come to commiserate over his now unchangeable role as
caretaker of a team that absolutely, positively cannot win.
</P>
<P>
   He does not ask for sympathy because he has brought this on
himself by reupping when there were chances to leave. But he likes
his life, both in the Twin Cities and down here (he owns some
greyhounds), and with the two rings he certainly doesn't have to
prove anything to anybody.
</P>
<P>
   He's still having fun. He tries to pitch batting practice every
day, for example. ``Keeps me away from the media,'' he says with a
laugh. ``And it gives me a little more personal approach, plus a
little exercise.'' He still loves the day-to-day swirl, and he
really does enjoy the idea of seeing kids improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I'm in for here,'' he says. ``I'm here because the
owner said, `Tom, we'd like you to stay. This is our program.' If I
had any doubts about it, I wouldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Those World Series victories now seem like stories being told
around someone else's campfire. ``I don't think much about it,'' he
says, ``unless someone asks me. I'm more caught up in the
day-to-day, the process we're in now. With this team, I'm still
learning guys' names.''
</P>
<P>
   The championship rings are home in a drawer. ``I'm not a jewelry
guy,'' he says with a shrug. ``The only ring I wear is a wedding
ring. I had the same Timex watch I bought for something like 19
bucks for 19 years until it finally wore out this winter. Every
once in a while I bring out a ring for some occasion, and then I
wind up showing it to someone and I walk away and forget about it.
Finally, I said, `I can't keep doing this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He may not be especially reflective, but he is not stupid,
that's for sure. He has no worries. Say he decides he's given
enough to the Minnesota Twins when his contract runs out at the end
of this year. He won't turn 50 until August. He's got two
championships on his resume. He's known to be a good soldier.
Imagine what a manager like that would be worth on the open market.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of people to feel sorry for in this game, but
Tom Kelly isn't one of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 0215EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
