<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7857 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-BURNS-BOS &LR;      03-06 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BURNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLISON BACK BELEAGUERED COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Mass. _ With the departure of Ray Bourque imminent,
the question remains: What, if anything, will that mean for the
future of Bruins coach Pat Burns?
</P>
<P>
   Burns, in the third year of a four-year contract, was endorsed
by president/general manager Harry Sinden as being safe through the
season. But what then? Will Burns be forced to pay for the bizarre
circumstances that have brought down this club brick-by-brick? Will
he be held responsible for the key injuries, the lack of depth, the
meltdowns of Joe Murphy and Marty McSorley, the lack of centers?
</P>
<P>
   Forward Jason Allison, whose loss was the single biggest
disaster of the year in a season full of them, said it would be
devastating if Burns were to be fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if anyone would be shocked after what they hear
but definitely disappointed and upset,'' said Allison. ``I'd almost
feel badly that we kind of did it. I just hope it doesn't come to
that. I don't think he deserves that for what he did the last two
years here.''
</P>
<P>
   As a coach, Burns is not a warm and fuzzy personality, although
he's certainly nicer than former Patriots coach Bill Parcells and
more down to earth than Celtics coach Rick Pitino. He can be
irascible, short, and irritable with his players and Allison said
that's all the more reason he should stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Figure this out,'' said Allison. ``He's one of the tougher
coaches in the league, he's very strict and a pretty
defensive-minded guy. He can have tight reins sometimes and he's
not always going to pat you on the back, he'll let you have it. But
you ask around the room and every guy wants him back. That should
say something. If you have a guy everyone wants back because he's
soft and easy, you understand that, but obviously he's done more
than a good job here or they wouldn't all go to bat for him and
want him back because it cannot be fun sometimes when he's not in a
good mood. You don't see that (kind of support) very often.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Bruins didn't make the playoffs, in '97,
players were carping publicly and privately about management,
then-coach Steve Kasper, and everything else. Kasper didn't have
much to work with either, but he paid with his job anyway. It's
likely Burns will, too. Allison said if that's the case, it's
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's earned all the respect of the players in here,'' said
Allison. ``He's not an easy guy sometimes and everyone still wants
him back and thinks he deserves to be back so there should be not
even a thought of firing him. You can't honestly blame him for this
year. I'm sure he feels very frustrated like `What else can I do?'
He's been really hard on us, he's lightened up, he's tried
different systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we got to a certain point in the year when everything was
going bad, you saw there was no way things were going to turn
around and it snowballs. What do you want him to do? He can only
coach what he gets. The players have to play well and we have to
have the right group of players here and the right talent. I sure
hope he doesn't get punished for this. It was one thing after
another all year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were overwhelmed, 3-0, Saturday in a game against the
Philadelphia Flyers, Bourque's likely destination. Goalie Rob
Tallas said he saw the footage of Burns's very brief news
conference and said he sensed just how upset his coach is about the
team's inability to compete against the league's best teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to be frustrated and rightfully so,'' said Tallas.
``Coaches dream of teams like the Red Wings where I don't think
there's a whole lot of coaching involved on that team. It's just
setting it up and watching the players perform and do things with
ease and with so much talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our team, we need to be coached and coached right through
a game. That's tough on him. He's been doing that all year. There
haven't been nights where Pat could just take off and let our
talent win games. A lot of people don't see that. Detroit can just
go out and play. It's been a very difficult season for him. Pat
took us from a bunch of talented young guys with something to prove
two years ago and made superstars out of some of them.
Unfortunately, they're hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallas said as much as he and his teammates have felt the
frustration Burns was feeling personally, the players all said he
hasn't ever taken it out on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a coach, he could easily come in here and explode and start
screaming at us and start passing on what management passes to him
but Pat doesn't do that,'' said Tallas. ``He's like a little bit of
a sponge; he absorbs most of it. He is a fiery coach, he does bring
some of it to us but I don't think he brings the management stuff
to us, he just brings our play to us and what we did wrong. He's
been real good at taking most of the heat for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Burns said he will try to keep his team focused Monday night
against Ottawa despite the circus atmosphere that has surrounded
the club all year. ``They're obviously a team that is not as big as
the team (Saturday),'' said Burns, referring to the mammoth Flyers
. . . Tallas will be in net Monday night . . . Anson Carter, out
for the season because of impending wrist surgery, will have his
ailing right shoulder looked at in the next day or so and expects
to undergo a test that will determine the damage since the rotator
cuff isn't getting any better and Carter said he has no strength in
the arm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
