<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-MAGIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENCOURAGING SIGNS FOR CELTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As the Celtics gathered around coach Rick Pitino before
the start of the fourth period, every face in the group smiled.
</P>
<P>
   There were hugs and high-fives. Pitino shouted instructions over
a boisterous crowd eagerly anticipating the first Boston win in a
week and a half. A man behind one baseline held up a neon green
sign that read, ``I still believe in Rick Pitino and these young
Celtics.'' A group of fans behind the Boston bench stood to applaud
the home team and their effort against the Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, in his first game back at the FleetCenter since comments
that faulted Bostonians for their impatience and poor attitude
concerning the Celtics, Pitino got the encouragement he asked for.
The sellout crowd of 18,624 cheered the Celtics, heckled the Magic,
and booed the referees. Orlando timeouts were filled with noise.
Each time the Magic took the ball down the floor, chants of
``De-fense, de-fense'' were heard. And with positive backing from
fans Pitino accused of negativity less than a week ago, Boston
snapped its four-game losing streak and defeated Orlando, 97-91.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very, very pleased with the crowd,'' said Pitino, who
received only a faint smattering of boos when he was introduced
during pregame ceremonies. ``We had a sellout today, a great crowd.
They helped us win this game. They forced us to play great defense,
and we are thankful for that crowd. It was wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the Celtics were looking to win over fans in the first
quarter, they certainly weren't in any hurry. Shooting poorly at
the start of the game, Boston quickly fell behind. A 17-foot jump
shot by Paul Pierce with 5:16 left in the opening stanza marked the
Celtics' first field goal of the afternoon. But Orlando failed to
capitalize as Boston stuggled, shooting 25 percent from the floor
(6 for 24) in the first.
</P>
<P>
   The visitors opened up a 7-point lead on two occasions late in
the opening quarter, but they couldn't put any more distance
between them and the Celtics. Instead, the Celtics collected
themselves, kept up their defensive pressure, and staged a
comeback. A 7-0 run fueled by 3 points and a steal from Pierce tied
the game at 11 with 3:45 remaining in the quarter. Orlando took a
timeout and regained the lead, though Boston trailed by just 1
point as the teams entered the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get down on ourselves because we were playing tough
defense,'' said Kenny Anderson, who had 14 points, 5 assists, and 4
steals. ``You just have to keep playing and keep your head in it.''
</P>
<P>
   After a Danny Fortson free throw tied the game at 29, the
Celtics took the lead for good when Adrian Griffin hit a 16-foot
jumper with 5:53 left in the first half. A combination of
aggressive defense and improved shooting helped the Celtics stay
ahead of the Magic, who are the fifth-highest-scoring team in the
league. Boston attacked Orlando's half-court trap, collected an
impressive 16 steals, and forced 26 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you turn the ball over 26 times, you're not going to win
a game,'' said Orlando coach Doc Rivers. ``I thought it was an
extremely winnable game, but not because of their record.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston entered haltime ahead, 45-40, after it doubled its field
goal accuracy to 50 percent. Antoine Walker found his range,
scoring 11 of his 18 points in the second quarter, while Fortson
dropped all 6 of his points before halftime after making his third
consecutive start.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics' lead reached a game-high 15 when Anderson hit a
3-pointer with 29.9 seconds left in the third. Orlando spent the
quarter trying to keep Boston's lead below double digits, but
leaving Eric Williams (8 points) wide open at the 3-point arc and
letting Griffin (15 points, 11 rebounds) drive to the basket didn't
help the visitors in their push for the playoffs. The Magic, their
two-game win streak snapped, remain in ninth place in the Eastern
Conference behind Milwaukee and Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Celtics struggled to make shots early in the fourth
and the Magic surged to close within 5 in the final minute, the
home team didn't let its hard work and the crowd's enthusiasm go to
waste.
</P>
<P>
   As they continue their four-game homestand, the players let it
be known they appreciated the support. They were not in their usual
rush to leave the floor or the locker room. Pierce, who led the
team with 19 points before fouling out in the fourth, stayed behind
to sign autographs. Postgame, it was not the same dispirited team
that showed up after recent disappointing losses to Dallas and
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big victory for us to get off that skid and get back
on the positive side,'' said Walker. ``Hopefully, the fans
appreciate our effort because we're going to continue to work very
hard. It was a real lively crowd that was real into it. It's huge
(to have a supportive crowd), especially when you've been
struggling like we have, being up and down. It's a lift emotionally
and it keeps guys into it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
