<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAGLES GET BALL ROLLING 
</HEADLINE>
 COLLEGE-GEORGETOWN_BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORRS, Conn. _ The Boston College women's basketball team
wasn't happy with its No. 4 seed in the Big East tournament, but
after the first two games, the Eagles could be forgiven if they're
wondering when the competition starts.
</P>
<P>
   BC led virtually the entire way and defeated Georgetown, 74-52,
in the quarterfinals before a crowd of 10,027 at Gampel Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   As for the competition, well, that starts Monday night when the
No. 19 Eagles face the top-ranked University of Connecticut, which
trounced St. John's, 85-41.
</P>
<P>
   Georgetown (17-12, 9-7) opened the game with a 3-pointer by
junior guard Dani Illic, and BC started the game 0 for 4 from the
field. But a layup by forward Alissa Murphy, followed by another
from Kim Mackie, put the Eagles up, 4-3, and marked the beginning
of a 10-2 run.
</P>
<P>
   It would be the first of many runs for BC (25-7, 12-4) as it
opened a 20-point lead at 30-10 with 3:27 to go in the half before
settling for a 32-18 halftime advantage.
</P>
<P>
   BC shot a less-than-stellar 36 percent, as it made 11 of 31
shots. But Georgetown shot even worse, 32 percent (7 for 22), and
committed 15 turnovers in the half.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as if the Hoyas might close the gap in the second
half, thanks mainly to junior guard Katie Smrcka-Duffy, who
exploded for 15 of her game-high 20 points. But Georgetown couldn't
come any closer than 11 (47-36) with 8:10 to play.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the three stars of the game went to work as Cal
Bouchard hit two free throws and a 3-pointer, Murphy sank a layup
and a free throw, and Becky Gottstein had two layups to give the
Eagles a 14-point lead with 5:29 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to loosen things up, and played better the second
half,'' said Georgetown coach Pat Knapp. ``Our kids played hard,
but we didn't get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgetown's biggest threat is Smrcka-Duffy, who leads the
conference with an average of 18.6 points per game. The trouble is,
she's the Hoyas' only threat, and the only Georgetown player to
average double figures. Forward Nok Duany had 13 points, but only
three other Hoyas scored.
</P>
<P>
   BC, meanwhile, had plenty of ammunition. Murphy scored a
team-high 19 points, Bouchard had 18, including four 3-pointers,
and Gottstein added 18 points and seven rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The win was especially gratifying for Gottstein. She was on
crutches during last year's quarterfinal loss to Georgetown after
she sprained her ankle in the first-round win. Plus, Gottstein
returned to the lineup Saturday after being sidelined for six weeks
with a stress fracture in her ankle.
</P>
<P>
   BC coach Cathy Inglese took Gottstein's heroics in stride,
though.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I expect it? No,'' Inglese said. ``Am I surprised? No. She
finds a way to get it done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 0220EST &QL; 
