<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MAINE-DELAWARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO BEDARD, NO CHANCE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, Del. _ The player at the end of the Maine bench hurt the
Black Bears most Sunday in the America East tournament semifinals
against Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Maine point guard Andy Bedard, a transfer from Boston College,
had no points, no shots, no assists. He was sitting out, having
broken his left wrist against Hartford Saturday. So Maine, which
had defeated Delaware twice during the regular season, was not the
same team.
</P>
<P>
   Delaware, before a packed house of 5,086 at the Bob Carpenter
Center, went on to wreck Maine, 68-46.
</P>
<P>
   Delaware visits top seed Hofstra Saturday in the league final.
</P>
<P>
   Maine connected on just 27.6 percent (8 of 29) of its tries in
the first half while Delaware, with eight wins in a row, hit 18 of
32 for 56.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, there were horrible moments for the Black Bears,
who had come in as the tournament's No. 2 seed (Delaware was No.
3).
</P>
<P>
   Maine committed turnovers its first two times down the court,
prompting coach John Giannini to signal two timeouts in the first
3:24.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a much different basketball team with Andy Bedard,''
said Delaware coach Mike Brey, his team 24-6 overall and 15-4 in
the league. ``He's a great player and to lose him and have to
regroup without a practice is very difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a huge loss, he's a great player,'' Brey added. ``He's
one of the reasons why they didn't shoot as well. Bedard delivers
the ball to those guys when they're wide open and at the right
place; he's amazing the way he controls the game. He's a heck of a
player and he's also beaten us a lot _ that's why I respect him.''
</P>
<P>
   Delaware, with 21 points and 10 rebounds from Mike Pegues, was
ahead, 14-10, before going on a tear, with senior forward Madou
Diouf hitting 6 of 7 on his way to 13 points. Delaware got 9 of the
last 12 points for a 40-22 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Kestutis Marciulionis added 14 points for Delaware. Nate Fox
paced Maine with 16 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``About everything bad that could happen did happen,'' said
Giannini, his team ending its season at 24-7, 15-3. ``I was very
confident even without a great player like Andy, but without having
any time to really prepare, it made it difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what's made it even more difficult was playing on the road
against an outstanding team in a wild arena. We did not execute
very well in the first half because we couldn't even hear our
calls. I thought we missed layups and free throws that we normally
make. It definitely snowballed against us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 0222EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
