u s BC-RUN-ECACCHAMPIONSHIPS     03-06 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-ECAC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANHATTAN'S POMPEY SETS SIGHTS HIGHER 
</HEADLINE>
 CHAMPIONSHIPS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL HARBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Aliann Pompey doesn't usually enter the 500-meter run.
But she did Sunday at the ECAC Division 1 Indoor Track Championship
at the Reggie Lewis Center. One thing is for sure: It was a nice
change of pace.
</P>
<P>
   Pompey not only won the 500-meter ECAC championship, she also
ran the fastest 500-meter race by a collegian.
</P>
<P>
   The Ghana-born New Yorker blistered the oval in 1 minute 9.23
seconds, breaking the NCAA mark of 1:09.38 set by Cathy Tattray of
Tennessee in 1984. This is just a prelude. The Manhattan College
graduate student has her sights set higher.
</P>
<P>
   She will travel to Fayetteville, Ark., this week to compete in
the NCAA Division 1 Championships, but she won't run in the 500.
Why? There is no 500-meter event in the NCAAs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually run the 400. My coach wanted me to run the 500 to
prepare for next week's NCAAs,'' said Pompey. She should do well in
the 400. She is seeded second in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   If the 500-meter run did anything, it certainly boosted Pompey's
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we came up for the ECACs, I had my heart set on
breaking the 500 record,'' said Pompey, who has set many school and
meet records during her career at Manhattan. This is her first NCAA
record. Although she is a graduate student, she is considered a
fifth-year senior because she was a medical redshirt last season.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, she didn't even post the best time in Saturday's
preliminary heats. ``I wasn't trying to run fast on Saturday,''
said Pompey. ``I was just trying to qualify for the championship
race.'' She won her qualifying heat in 1:11.48. Sunday, her closest
competitor was Chantee Earl of Pitt, who finished two seconds
behind her.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a runner who is competing out of her regular event
and coming back from a knee injury that sidelined her for an entire
season.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 14, 1998, Pompey cut in front of a runner, got bumped,
and fell. ``I ran for the next couple of weeks, but the pain in my
knee wouldn't go away. So I had an MRI and they saw that I broke
it,'' said Pompey.
</P>
<P>
   She had a stress fracture of the tibia. ``She's a terrific
runner,'' said Manhattan coach Joe Ryan. ``Not many runners can
come back from an injury like that. Not many will stay in shape
during a long rehabilitation like she went through. She deserves a
lot of credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Pompey bolted out of the blocks and never looked back.
It's something she has consistently done since she returned to the
track. She hasn't lost a race all year.
</P>
<P>
   Pompey, 21, is already committed to compete in the Sydney
Olympics for Ghana in the 400 and the 4 x 400 relay team. ``That's
one meet I'm really looking forward to running.''
</P>
<P>
   Some athletes didn't compete in the ECAC Championships,
including Harvard high jumper Dora Gyorffy. Villanova's top
distance runners _ Carrie Tollefson, Kristen Nicolini, and Ann
McGranaham _ qualified Saturday for Sunday's mile championship. But
when the finals began, they withdrew. This meet comes at a
precarious period in the schedule. With the NCAA Championship
looming just days away, some sat out to rest up for the big event.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't detract from this meet,'' said Cornell track
coach Lou Duesing. ``There are still plenty of talented competitors
looking for a chance to qualify for the NCAAs.''
</P>
<P>
   Another oddity at this championship was the absence of George
Mason. The school has won this meet for the last six years. But
veteran track coach Norm Gordon was dismissed after last season.
</P>
<P>
   The team championship went to Georgetown with 87 points. West
Virginia (78), Seton Hall (69), and Connecticut (41) followed. The
best performance by a Boston school was Northeastern, which
finished 12th with 19 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
