r e BC-TV-PRIMARIES-KANSAS-K     03-06 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PRIMARIES-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTING FOR CANDIDATES BASED ON THEIR LATE-NIGHT APPEARANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON BARNHART  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star   During the 1960 presidential race,
New York Times political reporter James Reston wrote that the
campaign had come down to two basic tests: ``Who can stand up to
Nikita Khrushchev. And who can sit down with Jack Paar.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Times have changed. Nikita is gone, and television _ which was
just starting to assert itself in presidential politics 40 years
ago _ is now a main source of election coverage for three out of
four Americans.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe the only thing that matters today is how well you do
with ``Paar'' _ or rather, with Jay Leno and David Letterman,
Paar's latter-night descendants.
</P>
<P>
   Think I'm kidding? Try this little test on your co-workers. Ask
them which Republican candidate was accused of writing negative
campaign brochures about his opponent in Michigan. Then ask them
which one was half an hour late to an interview with Leno last
week. (Answer to both: John McCain.)
</P>
<P>
   You'll immediately smoke out the political junkies in your
office with the first question. It's been a hot topic for weeks
among the Beltway insiders who show up on CNN, Fox News,
``NewsHour'' and other TV bull sessions.
</P>
<P>
   But to many of us who are going to vote today _ 16 states are
holding ``Super Tuesday'' primaries _ how the candidates performed
on late-night TV may be as important as how they fared on the news
and in televised debates.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that more than 11 million viewers last week caught
either McCain's tardy turn with Leno or George W. Bush's comically
inept satellite interview with David Letterman. That's about four
times the combined viewership for the two prime-time presidential
debates CNN aired last week.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just how many are watching, but who. Younger
viewers may flock to Leno and Letterman, but they tend to avoid
cable and network news. That's why candidates _ especially
underdogs looking for new blood _ try to get themselves booked on
late-night shows.
</P>
<P>
   It's what prompted candidate Bill Clinton in 1992 to blow his
own horn, literally, on ``The Arsenio Hall Show,'' and give Black
Entertainment Television's popular ``BET Tonight'' an interview the
day before the tough 1998 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Candidate Bob Dole picked up that cue, making regular
appearances on any late-night show that would have him, including
``Late Night with Conan O'Brien'' and ``Saturday Night Live.''
(After his 1996 defeat, he did a sketch with Dole impersonator Norm
Macdonald.)
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley has made the circuit several times since the '96
election. He's paneled with Dave, Conan and Charlie Rose. Al Gore
hasn't been as prolific _ he made hay for years off his 1993 visit
to Letterman's show _ but early last month, as Bradley was mounting
a late surge, Gore finally darkened Leno's doorstep. (In the
``Tonight Show'' tradition, Leno flattered him with jokes, e.g.,
``Earlier today, computer hackers actually shut down Al Gore for
two hours.'')
</P>
<P>
   With the GOP race heating up, and public interest in the
candidates growing, bookers for the late-night shows got into the
fray. Letterman, issuing a typical caustic challenge, dared Bush to
come on his show and ``settle once and for all whether (he) is a
colossal boob or not.''
</P>
<P>
   In reality, the ``Late Show'' staff was trying to get Bush on
the show before the ``Tonight Show'' did. Suddenly the Texas
governor was being courted by both shows, like an A-list movie star
with a blockbuster to plug.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, in their eagerness to get their man the maximum
exposure, Bush's handlers agreed to something they'd later regret.
Since Bush couldn't get to New York, Letterman interviewed him last
Wednesday via satellite from St. Louis (Bush was scheduled on the
``Tonight Show'' in California last night).
</P>
<P>
   Right away, Bush dug himself a hole, breaking one of the
Letterman show's cardinal rules, ``Thou shalt not be funny with
Dave.'' The host asked how he managed to look so youthful and
rested after all that campaigning. Bush grinned and said, ``Fake
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The studio audience tittered nervously, sensing what would come
next.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that pretty much how you plan to run the country?''
Letterman shot back, as the crowd roared its approval.
</P>
<P>
   Bush then tactlessly tried a couple of heart jokes, which were
further mangled because of the satellite delay. Finally, he tried
holding up a ``DWEEBS FOR BUSH'' T-shirt his staff had given to
him, even though Letterman hadn't called him a ``dweeb.'' Nobody
laughed.
</P>
<P>
   The segment went so badly that after the commercial, Bush's
advisers were on the phone with Letterman's producer, no doubt
pleading for mercy. But the show went on.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's televised pratfall, seen by 5 million viewers, appeared
not to hurt his poll numbers or his chances for wrapping up the GOP
nomination today.
</P>
<P>
   In part, that's because McCain didn't help his cause with Leno,
during which the senator delivered one of his trademark odd moments
of spontaneity. He emptied his pockets on Leno's desk, revealing
half a dozen different lucky trinkets, including a compass, a Hopi
tribal feather and a flattened penny (``so (my) campaign won't be
run over,'' he joked).
</P>
<P>
   McCain, surely sensing the drop in cabin pressure, added,
``Nothing wrong with being a little superstitious, is there?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no,'' said Leno. ``It's just a little (cough)
frightening.''  &LR; brk:``I'd say pick Leno''
</P>
<P>
   Why do candidates do this? Why do they risk tangling with
entertainers who can make them look like, well, colossal boobs?
</P>
<P>
   Again, the answer is youth. In January, the Pew Research Center
for People and the Press discovered that 80 percent of all voters
under 30 were getting their information about political candidates,
at least some of the time, from ``non-traditional sources'': MTV,
``Saturday Night Live'' and, yes, Jay and Dave. Nearly half of
young voters even said they ``occasionally learned something about
the campaign'' from late-night TV.
</P>
<P>
   At least one commentator thinks that's not such a bad thing. Bob
Somerby, a Washington political satirist, stand-up comedian and
frequent guest on Fox TV, has been chronicling the foibles of the
Washington press corps in his widely-read Internet column The Daily
Howler (dailyhowler.com).
</P>
<P>
   Somerby believes that journalists who cover the presidential
race are more concerned with their own celebrity than with breaking
real news. So they rarely if ever stray from the pack and often get
fixated on issues that voters couldn't care less about _ ``negative
campaigning,'' for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's stupid,'' Somerby says. ``This idea that if you're
running for president you're not supposed to say anything critical
of your opponent _ what are we, in the second grade now? But that's
the theory of this whole campaign as it's been run by the press
corps.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to pick one source of information,'' said Somerby,
``I'd say pick Leno.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 0932EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
