<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 09:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7945 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-MOVIE-REARWINDOW-KANS     03-06 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-REARWINDOW-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTORING HITCHCOCK MASTERPIECE A PAINSTAKING PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the film preservation business, Robert Harris is known as a
purist's purist. His goal in restoring a vintage film is nothing
less than re-creating with absolute authenticity the experience of
a movie's earliest audiences.
</P>
<P>
   How much of a purist?
</P>
<P>
   Well, in restoring Alfred Hitchcock's classic 1954 thriller
``Rear Window,'' Harris was greatly disturbed to find that the
colors in the original film had badly deteriorated. To make sure
the film's palette was perfectly reproduced, he tracked down
Georgine Darcy, who had played ``Miss Torso,'' the exhibitionist
dancer who kicked up her heels in the apartment across the court
from that of leading man James Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Darcy had kept the pink shorts she wore in ``Rear Window,''
storing them where they wouldn't fade. Harris was allowed to borrow
them so that he could use them as a reference to ensure that the
colors in the restored film matched those of the original clothing.
</P>
<P>
   And Harris doesn't rest once the restoration work is completed.
He even polices the theaters showing his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been having trouble with theaters trying to save 12
cents by cutting the amperage to the projector lamp,'' Harris said
in a recent phone interview from his Bedford Hills, N.Y.,
laboratory. ``Some theaters just don't have enough light.''
</P>
<P>
   For ``Rear Window'' Harris faced a monumental task: While the
film had been shot in the three-strip Technicolor process _ the
best way to preserve a color film _ it had been stored in poor
conditions and had badly deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   With Technicolor, a beam splitter in the camera separates the
blue, red and green light waves of the color spectrum. Each is
recorded on a separate piece of black-and-white film. Black and
white doesn't fade over time, as color film does.
</P>
<P>
   To make a pristine new print, each of the three black-and-white
films are dyed the appropriate color _ red, blue or green _ and
then combined to create a full-color print.
</P>
<P>
   This three-strip process is time-consuming and expensive. By the
early '70s, Technicolor had been replaced with Eastman Color, a
single-negative color film like the film used in household cameras
to make color prints. But Eastman Color film fades with time;
three-strip Technicolor, because it's based on black-and-white
elements, should always produce true color.
</P>
<P>
   That's the theory anyway. In the case of ``Rear Window,'' the
original Technicolor elements were either missing or in bad shape,
forcing Harris to work backward. He took an old Eastman Color
negative used to make exhibition prints and then used a beam
splitter to break each frame down into separate blue, red and green
negatives.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first time Technicolor's expensive three-dye process
had been employed since 1974's ``The Godfather Part II,'' the last
feature film to be shot in that process.
</P>
<P>
   But then even the best Eastman Color negative Harris could find
showed signs of fading, meaning every shot had to be adjusted to
bring back the film's original intense hues.
</P>
<P>
   So how was an acknowledged masterpiece like ``Rear Window''
allowed to deteriorate so badly?
</P>
<P>
   ``The rights to Hitchcock's films reverted to him in '67, and he
was ill-advised,'' Harris said. ``He was told to keep certain
elements and junk everything else, and that was really bad advice,
because it limited what we had to work with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as bad, these elements were stored not at the studio but
in a large commercial storage facility where the temperature was 55
at night and 110 during the day. That is precisely how you
shouldn't store film.''
</P>
<P>
   The original soundtrack to the film has been lost; the restored
``Rear Window'' uses the best sound elements from numerous 35mm
exhibition prints, which have been cleaned up digitally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Using digital sound techniques, you can eliminate hiss and
pops,'' Harris said. ``But theater sound systems used when `Rear
Window' came out in '54 had been in place since the '30s. These old
systems weren't terribly reliable in producing perfect sound, but
they were adequate for that time. The trouble is that when you play
these old soundtracks on a modern theater system, you can detect
every little change in ambiance. It magnifies the old recordings'
inherent flaws.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris and his partner, Jim Katz, take a lot of time on their
projects. In the last 14 years they've worked on only four other
restorations: ``Lawrence of Arabia,'' ``My Fair Lady,''
``Spartacus'' and ``Vertigo.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes their work involves sleuthing. For ``Lawrence'' and
``Spartacus,'' Harris tracked down scenes trimmed before those
epics went into general release.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, who cut his teeth assisting in Kevin Brownlow's epic
restoration of Abel Gance's silent film ``Napoleon,'' seethes when
he considers that few movie studios take film preservation
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been lucky to work a lot with Universal, which is
probably the most restoration-conscious studio. After we'd done as
much to `Rear Window' as we could on our budget, they came up with
another $70,000 to make sure it was as good as it could be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, then you've got Disney, which had a very good
preservation department but shut it down because of
belt-tightening. God forbid they should cut into Michael Eisner's
salary to save their movies for posterity.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Harris' big gripes is that many films are restored only
to the point where they look reasonably good for video release.
</P>
<P>
   ``Video hides a multitude of sins,'' Harris said. He described
this kind of thinking as, `` `We're not going to worry about it
now, and in 25 years it will be somebody else's problem.'
Meanwhile, you don't have a version of the film good enough to
project in a theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, it doesn't take that much money to save a
film.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently Harris is working to restore ``Williamsburg, the Story
of a Patriot,'' the short subject that has been playing
continuously for nearly 40 years at the visitors' center in
Colonial Williamsburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years they've made print after print of the negative,
which is now completely faded. We're trying to find enough money to
get the project going. I mean, 50 million people have seen this.
The problem is they need $1.8 million to do the job, and they've
raised only about $800,000.''
</P>
<P>
   So when does Harris think he'll be able to start work on the
project?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I've already started,'' he said. ``I've been at it 12 or
14 months, working pro bono so far.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
