A7946 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-MOVIE-DOUGLAS-KANSAS-     03-06 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-DOUGLAS-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL DOUGLAS ACTS UP A GENTLE STORM IN `WONDER BOYS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star   Michael Douglas was in the middle of
costume fittings for ``Wonder Boys'' when it struck him that he
might be going out on a limb.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I was trying on the pink chenille woman's bathrobe I'd be
wearing for half the movie,'' he recalled in a recent phone
conversation, ``and it suddenly occurred to me, `Oh man, should I
be doing this?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah. For his work in ``Wonder Boys'' Douglas, 55, has
received some of the best reviews of his career. He portrays a
disheveled college professor and struggling novelist whose life
comes unwound over one crazy weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, ``Wonder Boys'' is a change of pace for the dynamic
Douglas, who in recent years has specialized in playing powerful
alpha males.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, this is one of the most vulnerable roles I've been
offered in a long while,'' said Douglas, an Oscar winner for his
ruthless tycoon in ``Wall Street.'' ``The last two screen images of
me audiences got was in `A Perfect Murder' and `The Game,' and
those were both pretty dominant characters. But at this point in my
career I figured it was time to do something different.''
</P>
<P>
   But how did a successful, powerful guy like Michael Douglas _ a
guy who, after all, can win the heart of a beauty like actress
Catherine Zeta-Jones _ get into the head of Grady Tripp, a loser
who once wrote a best-selling novel but now devotes himself to
chasing women and avoiding responsibility?
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's one similarity between me and Grady it's that I
know what it's like to peak early,'' Douglas said. ``I was only 30
when I won the Oscar for producing `One Flew Over the Cuckoo's
Nest.' And I remember thinking at the time: `Well, it's all
downhill from here.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Because as an actor I was a late bloomer. Through most of
college I never got around to declaring, and I finally reluctantly
got into acting because both my parents are actors and I figured
theater would be an easy major.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, later I got into it with a vengeance, did
off-Broadway shows and films and television. But I was never what
you'd call a gifted actor. I really had to fight to define my
craft.''
</P>
<P>
   What people forget, Douglas said, is that when he accepted a
role on the long-running TV series ``The Streets of San Francisco''
he was, in effect, declaring himself a TV actor. Today performers
can have both television and movie careers, but in the early '70s
the two worlds rarely met.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't easy to make the transition from TV back to feature
films,'' Douglas said. ``What I did after `Cuckoo's Nest' was to
produce films like `The China Syndrome' and `Romancing the Stone,'
and cast myself in them. But I also produced `Starman' and had
planned on starring in it. The reason Jeff Bridges ended up in that
role is that I wasn't approved by the studio making the movie. I
wasn't bankable enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really get much acknowledgement until `Wall Street'
in '86.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas said he had plenty of reasons to do ``Wonder Boys.'' For
one thing, it was directed by Curtis Hanson, who was coming off the
success of ``L.A. Confidential.'' For another, he was crazy about
the supporting cast, which included Tobey Maguire
(``Pleasantville,'' ``Ride With the Devil,'' ``The Cider House
Rules'') as one of Grady's problem students, Oscar-winner Frances
McDormand as his love interest and Robert Downey Jr. as Grady's
flamboyant book editor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I was blessed with such a good script and such a good
director who has his own ideas of comic timing. One of the things I
love about this picture is that the laughter comes from the pauses
between dialogue. To get those laughs, to sit in a theater and hear
how they affect an audience, is a real joy.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas said he's taking things easy these days, preparing for
his wedding to Zeta-Jones (his second, pending a divorce; her
first) and the birth of their child. And he spends lots of time
with his famous father, Kirk Douglas, who still is recovering from
the stroke he suffered two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad and I talk a lot. As fellow actors we can share and
commiserate a lot. He's very compassionate, always ready to share
his advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, during those years my career was in flux he was
giving lots of unsolicited advice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
