<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERTUESDAY-SCENARIOS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDICAPPING SUPER TUESDAY: HOW TO TELL WHO WON 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
(bl) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When the primaries or caucuses came one at a time
_ like Iowa, New Hampshire, South Carolina and Michigan _ it was
easy to tell whether Gov. George W. Bush or Sen. John McCain was up
or down. And even when there were three contests last Tuesday,
figuring out who was up was easy because one candidate, Bush, swept
Virginia, Washington state and North Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be so simple this Tuesday, with 13 Republican
contests. Tuesday is the biggest and most important single day of
the primary season. And, perhaps, the most confusing. Consider the
possibilities:
</P>
<P>
   Bush Triumph
</P>
<P>
   If Bush is the top Republican vote-getter in California, he will
capture all of that state's delegates _ the largest trove of any
state. He is well ahead in the polls there. If he also wins New
York, where he and McCain are neck and neck in the polls, Bush
would have won the two biggest prizes. If Bush wins Ohio, the third
big prize, he would be unstoppable in his march to the nomination.
The bonus would be if Bush also won Georgia and other states where
he leads in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   California Dreaming
</P>
<P>
   The dream scenario in Austin: Bush wins the states above but
also beats McCain in California's ``beauty contest'' _ surpassing
him in the popular vote among Republicans, independents and
Democrats. Only Republican votes count toward delegates, but if
McCain does not prevail with those other voters, he would be hard
pressed to make the case that he would be the most broadly
appealing nominee in the general election. McCain's advisers have
given up hope of winning the delegates in California. But they
argue that if McCain wins the popular vote _ especially finishing
ahead of Al Gore and Bill Bradley _ that would at least assure him
bragging rights for another week.
</P>
<P>
   McCain Triumph
</P>
<P>
   The one safe bet among McCain's advisers is that he will sweep
New England, where voters tend to be more moderate _ and more
disposed to an insurgent. His camp's best hope is that he could
claim victory by winning Massachusetts, Maine, Rhode Island and
Vermont plus New York and the beauty contest in California. If
McCain could rack up those victories, and also win in Ohio, the
senator would make it a real race. In Ohio, Democrats and
independents can vote in the Republican primary, but Democrats have
their own primary and many may not cross over to McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Mixed Verdict _ or the Big Muddle
</P>
<P>
   If Bush wins, say, the delegates in California, but McCain
triumphs in New York, they could each claim an important victory.
Then the candidate who captures Ohio could declare himself as
having the edge. But what if Bush wins California and New York, but
McCain triumphs in Ohio, Missouri and New England? Given McCain's
victory in Michigan, he could then claim that he was the only
vote-getter in the Midwest, a critical battleground in the general
election.
</P>
<P>
   Far-Fetched _ But You Never Know
</P>
<P>
   Pundits and pollsters have been confounded at every turn. So no
possibility can be dismissed. Take Georgia, the only Southern state
up for grabs. It is assumed to be another conservative fire wall
for Bush, as was South Carolina. But the race is open to all
voters. What if McCain's independent appeal stirs moderates? Bush
could always prevail in Connecticut, where he was born and where
his grandfather was a U.S. senator. But polls show that many voters
in that fairly moderate state find McCain most appealing.
</P>
<P>
   The Other Race
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bradley are also on ballots in 16 states Tuesday.
Bradley insists that March 7 is his ``takeoff'' day. But polls show
him way down everywhere _ barely ahead of Alan Keyes in the popular
vote in California. The one state where Bradley may be a bit of a
factor is his childhood state of Missouri. The primary is open to
all registered voters, though Bush is well ahead in the polls. For
all the talk of taking off, what Bradley really is hoping for is a
miracle _ somewhere, anywhere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 0941EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
