<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EISENHOWER-MARY-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IKE'S GRANDDAUGHTER IS NEW CEO OF KC-BASED ORGANIZATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURA R. HOCKADAY  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Mary Eisenhower
remembers first hearing about People to People International around
the dinner table at her grandfather's farm near Gettysburg, Pa.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Granddad believed that people are born good and that if we
used the goodness in people to establish world relationships, we
could have a lasting peace,'' Eisenhower said. ``He learned that
philosophy from growing up in Abilene, Kan. He felt that people
didn't have problems, governments did. If there were a way to jump
over the governments and get straight to the people, we could
become friends, and friends would not want to fight each other.''
</P>
<P>
   As the new chief executive officer of the Kansas City-based
People to People, Eisenhower carries on the mission of her
grandfather Dwight D. Eisenhower, who founded the international
organization in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Eisenhower travels around the globe, chartering chapters,
speaking at worldwide conferences and developing ties between the
United States and other countries. She also oversees student and
professional exchange programs that allow U.S. citizens to live and
learn abroad, often while staying with host families. Other
programs bring people to the United States for three-week visits in
American homes.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenhower speaks modestly about her close ties with the World
War II five-star general who was the 34th president of the United
States (1952-1960) and was known and loved the world over as
``Ike.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1955, Mary Eisenhower was christened in the Blue Room of
the White House and attended family Christmas dinners in the State
Dining Room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned to use a finger bowl at age 3,'' she said, laughing.
``In 1954, Granddad bought the farm near Gettysburg, Pa., and
retired there with my grandmother after leaving the White House. It
was only an hour-and-15-minute drive from Washington, so he could
get there easily, but when he'd say he was coming home from the
office, I never really thought about it being the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family and I lived next door to the farm, so we were there
all the time. I can remember Winston Churchill, Charles de Gaulle
and Nikita Khrushchev visiting at different times. Churchill was
drafted into changing the diapers for my sister's doll, and I
remember asking De Gaulle why his glasses were so thick.''
</P>
<P>
   Bridges of friendship
</P>
<P>
   Many years later at a People to People conference in California,
Mary Eisenhower met Sergei Khrushchev, son of the late Soviet
leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sergei and I were both speaking at the conference, when I
looked across the room and saw him,'' Eisenhower said. ``He looked
like his father, whom I'd met when I was very little. I was
introduced to Sergei, and he made a few jokes. I thought, `This is
a nice man.' At the time (1996) he was still a Russian citizen, but
he and his wife have since become U.S. citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Eisenhower's ability to communicate and make friends easily
is an asset for People to People, said Bill Jarvis, international
board president.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are drawn to her,'' Jarvis said. ``She is sincere,
down-to-earth, and she is a great speaker. I heard her at the
conference in Newport Beach, Calif., in 1996. She wants to carry on
the legacy her grandfather started and to keep his dream alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis, assistant treasurer of Hallmark Cards Inc., helps
continue another legacy _ the invaluable partnership between People
to People and Hallmark. In the beginning, the State Department
operated People to People. Wanting to transform it from a
government to a private, nonprofit organization, Ike called on an
old friend, Joyce C. Hall, founder of Hallmark Cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather asked Joyce Hall if he would give the seed
money to enable People to People to go private,'' Mary Eisenhower
said. ``Joyce Hall said, `Yes, but I don't do anything outside of
Kansas City.' .MDBR/.MDNM/''
</P>
<P>
   So the headquarters moved to Kansas City in 1961, and the Hall
family has been a major benefactor ever since. Offices are housed
in a red brick mansion at 501 E. Armour Blvd. The living room,
filled with mementos from around the world, is known as the Joyce
C. Hall Room.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenhower arrived in Kansas City a year ago to work with People
to People. She had lived in Huntsville, Ala., where she owned and
operated an engineering firm with her former husband. They are now
divorced. Her son, Merrill Atwater, who turns 19 this month, is a
senior at Valley Forge Military Academy near Philadelphia. He plans
to attend Missouri Western State College in St. Joseph in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   International childhood
</P>
<P>
   Long before becoming involved with People to People, Mary
Eisenhower often met others from around the world. Her father, John
Eisenhower, who followed Ike to West Point and into the Army,
served from 1969 to 1971 as the U.S. Ambassador to Belgium.
Following the death of her husband in 1969, Mamie Eisenhower
visited her son and his family in Brussels for six months. It was a
joy for her granddaughter, Mary.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandmother, whom I called Mimi, was my best friend,''
Eisenhower said. ``I could talk to her about anything. She had big
blue eyes, and they always had a sparkle. She was very feminine but
had a great belly laugh. She and Granddad both did. She said she
always wore bangs to cover up her high Carlson forehead (inherited
from a Swedish ancestor).''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Eisenhower accompanied her grandmother on the funeral train
in 1969 that bore Ike's body from Washington to his final resting
place at the Eisenhower Center in Abilene, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trip took five days,'' she said. ``There were droves of
people lined up on both sides of the track along the way. I
remember them holding signs that said: `I liked Ike.' I'll never
forget that.
</P>
<P>
   ``About two days into the trip, my grandmother said to me,
`Let's go back to see Granddad.' An honor guard was guarding the
casket. Mimi said a prayer, then got up and put her hand on the
shoulder of one of the guards and said, `Thank you for watching
over him.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later, Mary Eisenhower was attending her grandmother's
funeral in Abilene. Mamie had had a stroke in September 1979 and
died Nov. 1, two weeks before her 83rd birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had taken the cream- and gold-colored brocade gown with
her to the hospital that she'd worn to the golden wedding
anniversary party my parents had had for her and Granddad in
1966,'' Mary said. ``She wanted to be buried in it.''
</P>
<P>
   New spark
</P>
<P>
   Mary Eisenhower, with her charisma and skills, will inject new
life into People to People, believes board chairman Bill Dawson, a
native Kansas Citian who now lives in Long Beach, Calif. He and
fellow board members are counting on Eisenhower to revitalize the
organization, which has operated behind the headlines for many
years. She leaves in a week for South Africa, where she will
charter new chapters in Cape Town and Johannesburg, adding to the
more than 160 chapters in 38 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Of People to People's several exchange programs, the largest is
the Student Ambassador Program for middle and high school students.
Nearly 20,000 American youths are expected to travel to Europe and
Australia this summer for three weeks of study that includes brief
home stays with host families.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenhower, whose job is full of travel, has established a solid
base in Kansas City and relishes free time in her apartment on the
Country Club Plaza. It is a base, also, for any family member who
may visit. All live in the East. Her father and mother, who
divorced in 1984, have each remarried but maintain close family
ties. Older sisters Anne Eisenhower Flottl and Susan Eisenhower
Sagdeev live in New York and Pennsylvania, respectively. And
brother David and his wife, Julie Nixon Eisenhower, married 31
years and the parents of three children, are in the Philadelphia
area. David Eisenhower teaches at the Annenberg School of
Communications, University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   The Eisenhower Center in Abilene, now easily accessible by car
for Mary, is a favorite destination for the youngest grandchild of
Ike and Mamie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go there to get my batteries recharged,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
