A0392 &Cx1f; var-z
u v BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      03-06 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
(Repeating) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, March 5, moved Saturday and are repeated Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in the `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   CATHOLICS-POLITICS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The GOP slugfest over
whether John McCain is baiting Catholics by painting George W. Bush
as anti-Catholic has freed a genie from a bottle corked 40 years
ago by John F. Kennedy. Democrats are rejoicing, for it was only
six years ago that the Gingrich-led House revolution showed that a
Catholic majority of voters had shifted for the first time in
decades from Democrats to Republicans on the House ballot. Before
that, Catholics split their ticket, as in voting for Ronald Reagan
but then returning to their old lunch-pail Democratic roots. By
Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   With sidebars, BOBJONES-REVIEW and MCCAIN-RELIGION-REVIEW.
</P>
<P>
   DARK-MATTER-REVIEW (Undated) _ Modern astronomy was supposed to
banish Aristotelian and mystical notions about the composition of
the universe, proving that everything above consists of no-nonsense
matter, that we live in a material world. But as was clear from
Dark Matter 2000, a conference held in February, the quest is only
progressing because of science's willingness to stretch the very
meaning of the word ``matter.'' This once-simple stuff is coming to
seem as ethereal as anyone could have imagined. By George Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-DIVIDE-REVIEW (Undated) _ The latest buzzphrase among
politicians and computer executives is the digital divide, the gulf
between those who have access to computers and the Internet and
those who do not. People in the latter category, the thinking goes,
are being shut out of the most important mode of gathering and
exchanging information in the new century. In fact, there is a
growing recognition among those dealing closely with the issue that
the term digital divide, while clever and provocative, has become a
catchall phrase for politicians with conspicuous agendas and that
the divide is a complex phenomenon that no amount of measurement
can fully explain. By Katie Hafner.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-POLITICS-REVIEW (Undated) _ In 1996, immigrant bashing was
in: Bob Dole, Pete Wilson and Pat Buchanan took positions that
could be seen as anti-immigrant. But what a difference four years
makes. In the 2000 campaign, nary a nasty word has been uttered
about immigrants. GOP strategists say Hispanic Americans will be to
this year's campaign what soccer moms were to the 1996 campaign.
Democratic and Republican strategists agree that Hispanics may
provide swing votes in California, New York, Texas and Florida _
which together account for half the electoral votes needed to win
the presidency. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SUPERTUESDAY-SCENARIOS-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ With the primary
and caucus schedule so far, it's been easy to keep track of whether
Gov. George W. Bush or Sen. John McCain is up or down. It may not
be so simple this Tuesday, with 13 contests. It is the biggest, and
most important single day of the primary season. And, perhaps, the
most confusing. Consider the possible scenarios. By Richard L.
Berke.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH-HEELS-REVIEW (Undated) _ What's behind the comeback of high
heels? Professional women may have discovered that sex appeal is
power because it is a way to get people to do what you want. And
high heels are the prime symbol of erotic femininity, because they
inspire simultaneous fantasies of vulnerability (who can run in
them?) and of the heel as weapon. They are a gal's version of a guy
thing: the female power tool. By Elin Schoen Brockman.
</P>
<P>
   L.A.-POLICE-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Scandals often require not
just scandalous facts but a trigger, a nettlesome event, to
activate public outrage. In Los Angles, for example, a police
corruption scandal in which officers brutalized, framed and shot
innocent people has suddenly erupted, after quietly simmering for
five months. At least one of the triggers, in this case, may have
been a proposed bond offering. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   LAPD-NYPD-ABUSES-REVIEW (Undated) _ A scathing report detailing
corruption and abuse in an elite-anti-crime unit of the Los Angeles
Police Department came just a week after four officers in a similar
squad in New York were acquitted in the death of an unarmed man
they shot 19 times. But where the New York officers may have been
reckless, the Los Angeles officers were almost certainly
premeditated criminals. Although there is no indication that the
New York unit has engaged in such lawlessness, critics say such
squads are risky ventures that frequently lead to problems. By Jane
Fritsch.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-SLUR-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ The brush fire over John
McCain's use of the word ``gooks'' flared and faded quickly.
Asian-Americans may have wondered: Would McCain have gotten more
bad publicity from a slur against blacks or Hispanics? Some
excerpts, primarily from Internet e-mail forums directed at Asian
Americans, capture this and other sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   BRIT-CORPORAL-PUNISH-REVIEW (London) _ Britain has outlawed
corporal punishment in schools, and the debate has now shifted to
the home, with the Labor government trying to rewrite the law to
set out exactly what constitutes acceptable hitting. The current
law, which dates back to Victorian times, was recently thrown into
limbo when the European Court of Human Rights ruled that it had
failed to protect a young British boy from ``inhuman or degrading
punishment'' by his stepfather. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   CHILE-U.S.-REVIEW (Undated) _ U.S. agencies that worked with
Chile during the Pinochet era have been reviewing their files and
slowly revealing the degree of U.S. knowledge about the system that
killed democracy for a generation of Chileans. The full extent of
U.S. involvement with the Pinochet regime remains shrouded in
secrecy, but some facts have been coming into sharper focus. By
Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
