<SLUG> BC-CANDIDATES-INVEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING STOCK OF THE CANDIDATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It used to be you were what you ate. But in today's
market-driven _ and diet-conscious _ culture, we are as interested
in how people invest as in what they ingest.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the 2000 presidential hopefuls, personal
investments can be telling, not only about the wealth of those men
eager to trade in their homes for public housing in Washington. But
they also offer insights into the personalities of the contenders,
their lineages, their outlooks, their interests _ and their
willingness to take risks. As much as you might learn from leafing
through George W. Bush's position papers, for example, you can
learn far more by plowing through his personal financial disclosure
report. There, as on the stump, the governor of Texas emerges as a
chip off the old establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Just how blue a chip can be summarized easily: Procter &AMP; Gamble.
Warner Lambert. Wells Fargo. Disney. The more contemporary entries,
all in a trust established for the governor by his mother, Barbara,
are themselves popular conventional stocks like Lucent, MCI
WorldCom, and Microsoft, about as mainstream as you can get in the
high-tech world.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkled throughout the mix, along with Kmart and ITT, are
standard money-market accounts, bond and stock funds. But there's
more than blue eyes and blue chips to Bush. His portfolio includes
at least $7 million in Treasury notes, and perhaps much more than
that, as federal law requires that only a range of values, not
specific numbers, be listed.
</P>
<P>
   The portfolio also includes an intriguing assortment of oil,
gas, mining, and farming interests, which is about as close as a
member of the Bush family ever comes to living off the land.
Generally, the blue chips are in Mom's trust, the natural-resources
investments in her eldest son's own name.
</P>
<P>
   The big contrast with Bush the investor isn't in Senator John
McCain, his rival for the Republican nomination, but in Bill
Bradley, the bank president's son and former New Jersey senator who
is challenging Vice President Al Gore for the Democratic
nomination. Bradley's investments, though heavily weighted toward T
notes, BankAmerica stock, and conventional mutual funds and money
markets, are by far the most new-age of the candidates'. The man
who raised so much money on Wall Street has a portfolio stocked
with emerging software, e-commerce, and computer-related stocks
including Homegrocer.com, E-mail Shopper Inc., and Ecom2ecom Inc. _
edgy entries that would be out of place in the Bush safe-deposit
box.
</P>
<P>
   McCain may be a gambler on the stump but he's no risk-taker in
the market. Scion though he is of a prominent military family, he
owns no stocks. Indeed, most of the family wealth comes from his
wife, Cindy, whose family runs the second-biggest Anheuser-Busch
distributor in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain children's investments are predominantly in
traditional, widely diversified, large-cap mutual funds, a standard
politician's gambit to avert just the sort of press inquiries that
we so eagerly make. The McCain children also have investments in
equity index funds, municipal money markets, and Arizona municipal
bonds. ``It's a set of very conventional investments,'' says Robert
Delgado, who oversees the family's investments.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also has a foundation account, dedicated to children's
charities and Native American philanthropies and underwritten in
part by proceeds from his best-selling book, ``Faith of My
Fathers,'' inside the $275 million Arizona Community Foundation. He
reaps no benefit from the growth of those investments.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Gore. He has income from the lease of a pasture he
owns in Tennessee, some mineral royalties, a bunch of Treasury
strips, a few savings accounts, and not much else.
</P>
<P>
   No bonds, no stock, except for less than $15,000 in Occidental
Petroleum in his father's estate. He's been on the government
payroll since 1977 and has an income of around $300,000, including
his federal salary ($175,400).
</P>
<P>
   But things may be improving for the vice president. He was able
to afford only $353 in charitable contributions in 1997. In 1998,
the most recent year for which tax returns have been completed,
Gore gave away $15,000. Onward and upward!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
