<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 09:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0396 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-L.A.-POLICE-REVIEW-NY     03-06 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-L.A.-POLICE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT BECOMES A SCANDAL MOST 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating  (The Week in Review)  
(bl) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Real scandals often require not just scandalous
facts, but a trigger, a nettlesome event, to activate public
outrage. In Los Angeles, for example, a police corruption scandal
in which officers brutalized, framed and, in at least two cases,
shot innocent people has suddenly erupted after quietly simmering
for five months.
</P>
<P>
   At least one of the triggers, in this case, may have been a
proposed bond offering.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan is nothing if not fiscally responsible,
and so he broke his near silence on the police scandal three weeks
ago, not in response to more disclosures of abuse, but to announce
that he had a plan to cover its costs. Legal experts have warned
that civil suits by the victims could cost the city more than $200
million.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor suggested that the city take the money it expects as
its share of the national tobacco settlement _ more than $300
million over the next 25 years _ and use it to finance an offering
of bonds. This would net the city a little more than $90 million
right away. The problem was that the mayor had already proposed
that the windfall be used mostly to help the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's plan, which he offered at a press conference, was
intended to insure that the country's second-largest city would not
go bankrupt in a sea of lawsuits for monetary damages. But rather
than reassure people the announcement has catalyzed public outrage
against the Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   In short order, the police officers union defied the
department's chief and demanded an independent investigation of the
widespread abuses, the FBI and the U.S. attorney announced separate
criminal investigations, and the City Council narrowly voted down a
motion to begin its own investigation of the Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost issue began to really cause serious alarm among a lot
of people,'' said Joel Wachs, the city council member and mayoral
candidate who made the motion. ``Absolutely, that was the
catalyst.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramona Ripston, the executive director of the American Civil
Liberties Union office here, had been advocating such an outside
investigation since September, and had little support until now.
The bonds, she said, sobered up people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor was more concerned with the money aspects of this
than the moral or ethical aspects, but suddenly when the city
realized this was going to cost so much, people finally began to
focus,'' Ripston said. ``We had no real supporters outside our
little group'' until recently.
</P>
<P>
   Advocacy groups for the disabled were outraged that financing
promised them would be taken away, but the mayor has since assured
them he will get the money from elsewhere. This only means, of
course, that someone else will have to suffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody is going to lose their money and it doesn't seem
fair,'' said John Whitbread of the Westside Center for Independent
Living. ``Everybody's nervous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 0948EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
