<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 09:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7962 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN08-CO     03-06 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Further holes in the Cuba embargo
 &HT;    (For release March 8, 2000.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Coincidentally (I presume), two stories in major
newspapers last Sunday disclosed how our four-decades-old economic
boycott of Cuba _ including the Helms-Burton Act _ is little more
than a mere annoyance en route to doing business with Fidel Castro.
Also, among the hard-line Cuban exiles parading angrily in Miami's
streets and banning entertainers and others who have performed for
Fidel, there are those clandestinely investing in Cuba, trying to
get a foot in the door for that day when Castro falls.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be business as usual, but it's approaching that
condition.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times, in a Sunday Business section piece, revealed
how foreign companies, notably in Canada, not only are doing
business with Cuba but how they evade crashing into the clauses of
Helms-Burton. Those edicts provide that any executive, from any
country, who does business on confiscated property in Cuba that was
owned by Americans pre-Castro, not be allowed to enter the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The Times article disclosed that tons of American money is
pouring into Cuba through a sieve that allows Americans to invest
in foreign companies doing business with Cuba, so long as they do
not own a controlling interest in the company, or that the company
does not gain more than half its revenues in doing business on the
island.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day as the New York Times article, the Miami Herald
ran a front-page piece revealing that some Cuban-Americans, despite
the embargo and despite what was supposed to be overwhelming
contempt for the Castro regime, are doing business with him _ also
in anticipation of his mortality, which they seem to think will
turn Cuba into a democracy on the morning after the burial.
</P>
<P>
   The Herald article disclosed that business meetings have been
held in the arch anti-Castro Little Havana section of Miami between
Castro's diplomats and Cuban-Americans. Some in the
exile-controlled Cuban-American community are doing straight-up
business with their adversaries in Havana. This is in addition to
those already making personal visits to relatives on the island and
bringing food, medicine and money.
</P>
<P>
   The article reported that ``Cuban Americans have boasted of
selling hotel supplies, food, clothes and computers in Havana.
Others are said to be brokering oil deals for Havana and trying to
establish ice cream and shoe factories in Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   What does this all say about the embargo? About Helms-Burton?
</P>
<P>
   It says that the embargo is little more than water plunging
through the openings in a colander. After 40 years, Americans (and
Cuban-Americans) can deal with Fidel Castro no matter what laws we
impose.
</P>
<P>
   For the past few decades, I have been of the opinion that the
stated embargo was the best thing that ever happened to Castro. He
has been able to blame all his failures on the embargo. Even when
companies in Spain, Canada and elsewhere began investing in Cuba,
putting up hotels and factories, Castro was able to fall back on
the embargo to implicate it for the overall deprivation on the
communist island.
</P>
<P>
   Since everyone seems to know a way around the embargo, including
Cuban-Americans, no less, there doesn't seem to be any real need to
continue it; or is it just to please a few dedicated anti-Castro
Miamians, their ages catching up with them just as is the
73-year-old Castro's?
</P>
<P>
   The embargo is a political position with declining economic
impact. Castro has weathered the storm. Investment in Cuba is a
reality. We may not like it _ I don't _ but it's real; particulars
staring up at us from the pages of our Sunday newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 0949EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
