</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
(bl) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Keeping Up With the Joneses
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not hate Catholics, as charged,'' wrote Bob Jones III,
president of Bob Jones University.
</P>
<P>
   It was Sunday every day last week on the Republican campaign
trail. Sen. John McCain made a speech Monday calling the
televangelist Pat Robertson and the Rev. Jerry Falwell ``agents of
intolerance,'' while Gov. George W. Bush told everyone that he was
not anti-Catholic, but that his opponent was playing dirty
politics.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Bush clobbered his opponent in the Virginia and
Washington primaries, amid some evidence that McCain's attacks on
the religious right had energized support for his opponent, and
possibly annoyed the Catholics he was playing to. Bush also took
the North Dakota caucus.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles the Republican candidates, tuning up for the big
Super Tuesday primary there, featured Bush debating the televised
head of McCain, whose body was in St. Louis. The two men vigorously
blamed each other for lowering the tone of their contest, while
claiming that they preferred to deal with issues of substance.
</P>
<P>
   The 13 Republican primaries on March 7, including California,
New York and Ohio, are widely expected to decide the GOP nominee.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, legendary for its own brand of ferocious politics,
the candidates squared off about campaign advertising. Bush
released ads charging McCain with opposing money for breast cancer
research, and appeared with breast cancer survivors to denounce him
at a panel discussion in Long Island, with an uneasy New York City
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani in tow. McCain called the ads a distortion
of his record, and the radio host Don Imus denounced them.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared as if it was McCain who had his back against the
wall, since he has been unable to make serious inroads against
Bush's core Republican support, especially in California.
Independents and Democrats will not win him the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats had a debate in Los Angeles, too. The encounter
between Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley was so
amicable it lent credence to the impression in political circles
that the race was pretty much all over, even the shouting.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PETER MARKS
</P>
<P>
   A Sticky Icon Turns 50
</P>
<P>
   It was some year, 1950: the first Club Med opened, Minute Rice
was introduced, Smokey the Bear and the slogan ``only you can
prevent forest fires'' were born and a newfangled copying machine
was perfected by a little company in upstate New York that soon
changed its name to Xerox.
</P>
<P>
   But there was another entry on the hit parade of popular-culture
icons from 1950: Silly Putty.
</P>
<P>
   The goofy substance celebrated its 50th anniversary last week by
being stretched, pounded and squished, the same as always. At the
factory in Easton, Pa., executives were talking about how people
had found uses the inventor (who never knew what to do with Silly
Putty anyway) never dreamed of: plugging leaks, stabilizing wobbly
furniture, cleaning computer keyboards, quitting smoking. Yes, some
stop-smoking programs tell smokers they need to knead Silly Putty
when they get the urge to light up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It crosses generations, and you don't outgrow it,'' said
Tracey Muldoon Moran, a spokeswoman for Silly Putty. Of course,
there are those who wish they had, like the burglar who broke into
the company's Canadian office and stole a computer. It didn't take
a Joe Friday to catch the thief _ his fingerprints were all over
the Silly Putty he had played with before he made his getaway.
</P>
<P>
   The not-so-silly history of Silly Putty is that it was invented
by accident in a synthetic-rubber laboratory during World War II.
It languished until 1950, when a New Haven, Conn., toy store bought
the first batch. It quickly sold out. Soon baby boomers were
lifting backwards copies of comic-strip figures out of newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed since the '50s. Now, Muldoon Moran said,
``We get phone calls from folks saying, `My putty isn't working.'''
We tell them, `Your putty is working, it's the printing process
that's changed.'''
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES BARRON
</P>
<P>
   Eichmann's House: The Bureaucracy of Murder
</P>
<P>
   Last week Israel released the memoirs of Adolf Eichmann, whom it
executed for war crimes in 1962. The document, written in an
Israeli jail, was kept sealed for fear it would be used to distort
the history of the Holocaust. It was unsealed at the request of
lawyers for Deborah Lipstadt, an American professor being sued for
libel by David Irving, whom she has described in a book as ``a
dangerous spokesman for Holocaust denial.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the 1,100 handwritten pages, Eichmann, the architect of
Hitler's Final Solution, charted the Nazi hierarchy. Eichmann's
Jewish Office of the Gestapo _ B-4 _ is at the bottom, consistent
with his claim to have been a minor cog in the genocidal machine.
``I was one of the many horses pulling the wagon and couldn't
escape left or right because of the will of the driver,'' he wrote.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The chart is literally accurate, and deeply misleading. Aaron
Breitbart, a senior researcher at the Simon Wiesenthal Center in
Los Angeles, notes that, from 1942 on, Eichmann had formal
authority for eliminating the Jews, to which Hitler had given the
highest priority, and he reported directly to the No. 2 officer in
the SS (which ran the concentration camps). ``The SS had much more
political power than the Army,'' Breitbart said, ``and Eichmann had
much more power than any general.''
</P>
<P>
   Eichmann even felt he could defy Heinrich Himmler, the SS
leader, Breitbart said. In 1944, with the end of the war in sight,
Himmler ordered Eichmann to stop gassing Jews. Eichmann ignored
him.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PETER EDIDIN
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: By PETER EDIDIN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gore Fund-Raiser Convicted In 1996 Donation Scheme
</P>
<P>
   A federal jury convicted Maria Hsia, a longtime political
fund-raiser for Vice President Al Gore, on charges that she
masterminded a 1996 scheme to conceal illegal donations to the
Democratic Party, especially to the vice president. Some donations
came from Gore's much-criticized visit to a Buddhist temple in
California.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict made Hsia, a previously obscure immigration
counselor from Los Angeles, the major catch in the Justice
Department's investigation of campaign finance abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans quickly denounced the department for going after
``small-fry'' like Hsia and not prosecuting any senior Democratic
officials.
</P>
<P>
   _ By NEIL A. LEWIS
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan Asks U.S. for Arms
</P>
<P>
   China says it wants to talk, even as it builds up missile forces
just in case those renegade Taiwanese make trouble. The United
States just wants to cool things down. The Taiwanese, for their
part, have put the Clinton administration in a bind by asking to
purchase some sophisticated defensive weapons, including four $1.5
billion ships equipped with advanced radar and antimissile systems.
</P>
<P>
   China has warned of severe consequences if Taiwan gets the
destroyers, but Taiwan says a refusal would be tantamount to
selling out a democratic ally.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ERIK ECKHOLM
</P>
<P>
   Admission by Tobacco Maker
</P>
<P>
   A top executive of Philip Morris Cos., the nation's biggest
cigarette maker, said that nicotine was an addictive drug and that
the Food and Drug Administration should regulate tobacco. Philip
Morris said it still opposed FDA regulation of nicotine as a drug
but its comments mark a major turnabout and come as legal and
financial threats continue to surround the industry.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARRY MEIER
</P>
<P>
   Ending Social Security Curbs
</P>
<P>
   The House unanimously passed legislation that would allow people
to draw their full Social Security benefit even if they decide to
go on working past the age of 65. The bill would repeal a
Depression-era policy that cuts benefits for people 65 through 69
years old by $1 for every $3 earned above an annual limit,
currently $17,000. The Senate will take up the bill soon, and
President Clinton said he would sign it.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats, however, said the change would mostly benefit
affluent people while doing nothing to shore up the retirement
system's precarious long-term finances.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD W. STEVENSON
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry Out for One Year
</P>
<P>
   Four boxes of fan mail were stacked in front of Darryl
Strawberry's locker at the New York Yankees' spring training
complex in Tampa, Fla., obscuring the uniform he won't need this
season, or perhaps ever again. Strawberry, who turns 38 this week,
was suspended for one year by Bud Selig, the baseball commissioner,
for using cocaine. It was Strawberry's third suspension from
baseball, and for the third time he checked into a drug rehab
center.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BUSTER OLNEY
</P>
<P>
   Haider Steps Down in Austria
</P>
<P>
   Responding to pressure from abroad and home, Joerg Haider
abruptly resigned as leader of Austria's anti-immigrant Freedom
Party, which he transformed from a marginal fringe group to a
powerful national force in the last 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   Haider, 50, stepped down three weeks after his party joined a
government coalition, prompting punitive measures by the European
Union. European governments dismissed the resignation as a tactical
maneuver and said they would continue their diplomatic isolation of
Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Testing for Pregnant Women
</P>
<P>
   When the crack epidemic was in full swing during the 1980s, the
plight of ``crack babies'' led to a vigorous debate over what to do
about pregnant women who use illegal drugs. South Carolina came up
with a singular answer: test their urine when they come to public
hospitals for prenatal care or delivery, and report positive finds
to the police. Several dozen women were arrested, some taken from
hospital beds in handcuffs or leg shackles.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in a case brought by 10 of the women, the Supreme
Court agreed to decide whether the urine tests were
unconstitutional searches or whether they were justified by the
health needs of fetuses and babies.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LINDA GREENHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   Taking Aim at Tax Shelters
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department issued new rules to make it harder for
large corporations to evade income taxes. Treasury Secretary
Lawrence H. Summers said the official estimate that illegal
shelters cost $10 billion annually ``is just the tip of the
iceberg.'' But the next day tax lawyers at a Federal Bar
Association meeting in Washington pointed out loopholes in the new
rules that may create more business for the accounting, law and
investment firms that design abusive shelters for corporations.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   3 Killed in Rampage
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Taylor, a black man whose apartment, police said,
contained anti-white writings, shot five white men in a Pittsburgh
suburb, killing three. His rampage began when he set fire to his
home and ended at two fast-food restaurants. Taylor, who has a
history of mental illness, repeatedly pointed his gun at the police
officers who cornered him, but they did not fire. He was charged
with a hate crime, as well as murder.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   6-Year-Old Kills Classmate
</P>
<P>
   A 6-year-old boy brought a loaded .32-caliber gun to an
elementary school near Flint, Mich., and shot Kayla Renee Rolland,
a 6-year-old classmate in the first grade.
</P>
<P>
   The local prosecutor decided not to file charges against the
boy, saying he was too young to have formed criminal intent.
Instead, involuntary manslaughter charges were brought against a
19-year-old family friend who lived with the boy in a drug-ridden
flophouse.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID BARBOZA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
