<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-GAYS-SWING-SUPER-TUESDAY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAYS, STAND UP AND BE COUNTED THIS SUPER TUESDAY  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By CHUCK COLBERT  
 &HT;    Gay Democrats and Republicans _ in nearly a dozen states from
Massachusetts to Ohio, Georgia to Missouri and New York to
California _ head to the polls on Super Tuesday to make their
voices heard. These voices _ if loud and strong enough _ could make
a real difference in the upcoming presidential election.
 &HT;    ``In a close race, gay voters can be an important swing vote,''
says Sean Cahill, of the National Gay and Lesbian Task Force Policy
Institute. Cahill is the author of a recently released publication,
``What's at Stake,'' a primer for the 2000 presidential elections.
 &HT;    Issues of concern to gay voters have been featured prominently
in both parties' presidential debates. Democrats Bill Bradely and
Vice President Al Gore favor lifting the ban on openly gay members
of the armed forces. Republican hopefuls Gov. George W. Bush and
Sen. John McCain disagree and support the current ``don't ask,
don't tell'' policy ban.
 &HT;    The last two presidential elections demonstrated the growing
political clout of gay voters. At the national level 5 percent of
registered voters in the 1996 presidential election identified
themselves as gay, lesbian or bisexual, according to Voters New
Service exit polls.
 &HT;    In states such as New York and California the gay vote may be as
high as 10 percent.
 &HT;    According to exit polling data and the National Gay and Lesbian
Task Force, the gay vote was a key part of President Clinton's
electoral coalition in 1992 and 1996. Clinton received 72 percent
of the gay vote in 1992 and 66 percent 1996.
 &HT;    Gay voting trends can also be seen in the Republican Party.
 &HT;    ``More and more gay voters are backing Republicans,'' writes
Cahill. ``While only one-quarter of gay, lesbian or bisexual voters
(GLB) backed Republican Congressional candidates in 1992, by 1998
one third of GLB voters backed Republican House candidates.''
 &HT;    Heading into Super Tuesday, increasing numbers of gay voters _
particularly the gay Log Cabin Republicans _ are mobilized by the
insurgent candidacy of McCain. In a recent campaign speech in
Virginia Beach, Va., he called religious right leaders Pat
Robertson and Jerry Falwell ``agents of intolerance. ''
 &HT;    Buoyed by his surprise victories in the New Hampshire and
Michigan primaries, McCain _ Vietnam War hero and self-described
``proud Reagan Republican '' _ appears poised to draw previously
disaffected Independents and even Democrats back into the voting
booth. Some of those voters will no doubt be gay.
 &HT;    There is no question McCain is the best choice for gay
Republicans. Despite the efforts of Log Cabin Republicans, the
G.O.P. has consistently positioned itself against any form of gay
civil-rights legislation.
 &HT;    Nonetheless, McCain met with the gay Log Cabin Republicans last
year and accepted more than $40,000 in campaign contributions.
 &HT;    ``I am unabashed, unembarrassed and proud to work with you,'' he
told Log Cabin. ``There is no room for discrimination in the party
of Lincoln,'' McCain says.
 &HT;    Bush balked at the idea of meeting with gay Republican
leadership. Last fall on ``Meet the Press,'' Bush told Tim Russert
he would ``probably not'' meet with Log Cabin ``because it creates
a huge political scene.''
 &HT;    There's little comfort on McCain's ``Straight Talk Express'' for
gays. Like Bush, he opposes federal hate crimes legislation, gay
and lesbian adoptions, same-sex marriage and domestic partnerships
as well as federal legislation banning employment discrimination
based on sexual orientation. In 1996 McCain voted against the
Employment Non-Discrimination Act, or ENDA, a national employment
discrimination ban, which lost by a vote of 49-50.
 &HT;    Democrats offer a shining path of support for gay civil-rights.
Bradley and Gore are aggressively courting the gay community. When
it comes to gay voters' key issues _ hate violence,
anti-discrimination measures, parenting, adoption and foster care,
equality for same-sex relationships, health care and military
service _ the democratic contenders voice strong support for
equality and fairness.
 &HT;    ``If gay Americans can serve openly in the White House, in
Congress, in the courts, in the Treasury Department _ why can't
they serve openly in the military?'' Bradley says. ``It doesn't
make sense.''
 &HT;    ``I would try to bring about the kind of change in policy, on
the 'don't ask; don't tell' policy that President Harry Truman
brought about after World War II in integrating the military,''
Gore says.
 &HT;    Gay voters have countless good reasons to get to the polls and
vote on Tuesday.
 &HT;    ``The American public overwhelmingly supports our equal and fair
treatment,'' writes Cahill of the Task Force. ``This support has
increased markedly over the course of the 1990s.''
 &HT;    Let's keep that support on track and on the upswing by voting on
March 7. Swing this Super Tuesday.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Chuck Colbert serves on the board of the National Lesbian and
Gay Journalists Association.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Chuck Colbert 
