<HEADER>
A7990 &Cx1f; tdt-z
c a BYline &LR;      03-06 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 BYline 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Alex Pham
</P>
<P>
   Globe Staff
</P>
<P>
   &UR; gfcapsline &LR;  &UR; ufcdrop,5 &LR;  W  &UR; rr &LR;  OODSIDE, Calif. _ In Silicon Val-
ley, where failure is worn like a badge of courage, Ann Meceda is a
shining exam- ple of success.
</P>
<P>
   At 28, she is already on her third start-up, having been chief
executive of one, executive vice president of new media for
another, and now executive vice president of business development
at a third Internet venture.
</P>
<P>
   Showing no signs of fatigue, Meceda agreed to sit down for
dinner recently to discuss what it feels like to be part of a new
generation of hard-charging, risk-defying, and
nomadic &UR;  &LR; entrepreneurs flooding the Valley with wave after wave of
Internet start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do like the concept of starting with nothing and cre- ating
something out of it,'' said Meceda, looking relaxed and composed in
her gray sweater and indigo jeans as she nibbled on a chicken
sandwich at Buck's, an eclectic diner that over the years has
become the de facto breakfast hangout for Silicon Valley venture
capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   The rugged journey for Meceda began in 1997, six months before
she was to graduate from the Haas School of Business at the
University of California at Berkeley. Meceda and a group of fellow
classmates launched a start- up called Private Communications Corp.
as a project for a class on entrepreneurship. PCC was built around
the con- cept of an ``anonymous, disposable telephone number'' that
could be used by online dating services to let people extend their
online chats over the phone without having to disclose their real
phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   In May, just weeks before graduating, Meceda be- came the
company's CEO, knowing that the business could just as easily burst
into flames as catch on like wild-H fire. Her decision to forgo a
job in Paris with a global entertainment company to head a risky
start-up became  &UR; -------------------- &LR;  the subject of a 1998
Harvard Business School case study.
</P>
<P>
   Ten months after she took the job, PCC ran out of money, despite
having raised $324,000 in capital, and Me-H ceda moved on. She
jumped to another start-up, HLH Entertainment, a music production
company in San Fran- cisco, as chief financial officer and then
executive vice president of new media. Folks at HLH didn't bat an
eye- lash over her experience at a failed start-up.
</P>
<P>
   The high-tech &UR;  &LR;  start-up business is like baseball, ac- cording
to Randy Komisar, a veteran Silicon Valley entrepreneur who helped
found Claris Corp. among other companies. One can ``fail 70 percent
of the time and still be considered a success,'' Komisar wrote in
his upcoming book, ``The Monk and the Riddle,'' which is being pub-
lished in May by the Harvard Business School Press.
 &UR; -------------------- &LR;  ``The Valley recognizes that failure is an
unavoidable part of the search for success.''
</P>
<P>
   Meceda, the daughter of two entrepreneurs, seems unfazed by past
adversity or the possibility of sudden failure in the future. She
is now involved in an Internet start-up that is currently in
``stealth mode,'' a Silicon Valley tactic that calls for absolute
secrecy about &UR;  &LR;  the company's business plan in order to prevent
copycats during the crucial ramp-up phase. The wraps come off in
April. By then, &UR;  &LR;  her company would have created a comfortable head
start over its rivals, Meceda says. Until then, she &UR;  &LR;  is not even
allowed to reveal her company's name. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Asked whether she is a millionaire yet, Meceda laughed
and &UR;  &LR; said no. After a moment's thought, however, she changed her
answer. ``Maybe,'' said Meceda, who explained that her equity in
HLH might be worth $1 &UR;  &LR;  million, depending on how well the company
did in its last round of financing. ``I'm just not sure,'' she said
with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Meceda noted that some of her &UR;  &LR;  peers &UR;  &LR;  talk about ``being
done,'' accumulating enough wealth to be able to pursue other
interests. ``It's about achieving a sense of financial freedom, to
have a choice as op- posed to having money for money's sake,'' she
explained.
</P>
<P>
   But Meceda doesn't look forward to ``being done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really have an endpoint,'' Meceda said. ``As long as
people keep coming up with ideas, I've got a job.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufauthor &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Alex Pham is a Globe reporter covering Silicon Val- ley. She can
be reached by e-mail at pham(AT)globe.com.
</P>
