<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN0307-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bill brings back bird brawl
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Not everyone shares my enthusiasm for the
Florida Legislature. But I look on the first Tuesday after the
first Monday of March as something of a holiday. It kicks off a
two-month period when the state's editorial writers and columnists
may open their newspapers each morning confident that outrages and
comedy will leap from the pages. You just need to write it down
fast enough. This session should be no exception.
</P>
<P>
   Perusing the list of pre-filed bills _ legislation already in
the works before the session starts _ one finds all the perennials.
</P>
<P>
   Bills to gut the growth management law? Check. Bills to allow
more secrecy at all levels of government? Check.
</P>
<P>
   Bills to create tax breaks to select little niches of commercial
endeavor. Check, check and the check is in the mail. Bills that are
entirely symbolic but guaranteed to start an argument? Check.
</P>
<P>
   I was particularly happy to find the return of some legislation
in that last category _ a bill to give Florida a better state bird.
</P>
<P>
   I have long been a student of my state's weird array of official
symbols. State statutes describe the official state soil as myakka
fine sand (and a fine sand it is). Our official state reptile may
be bought in rubber replica at any better souvenir store. We have
an official beverage, official butterfly, official state fish
(freshwater and saltwater), official flower, official wild flower,
official gem, official shell, official stone, official tree,
official water mammals (freshwater and saltwater) and an official
state band (The St. Johns River City Band and not Jimmy Buffett's
Coral Reefer Band.)
</P>
<P>
   The official state song, ``Suwannee River,'' is an
embarrassment. I don't know how many Floridians can sing with any
conviction that they are ``still longing for de old plantation,''
but I suspect not enough to staff a good-sized Civil War
reenactment.
</P>
<P>
   Florida doesn't have a very strong identity. Even more than most
Americans, we are still deciding who we are. This makes the quest
for new symbols poignant, strange and sometimes surprisingly
heated.
</P>
<P>
   That happened last year when changing the official state bird
was debated hotly. The state bird is the mockingbird, a common,
noisy, aggressive creature found everywhere in the continental
United States. It's a
</P>
<P>
   bland state symbol that implies we don't have anything more
interesting on the wing around here.
</P>
<P>
   The suggested replacement was the scrub jay, a bird found only
in Florida but sadly in short supply. But the bird's threatened
status got the attention of development interests who saw state
bird status as a propaganda tool for environmentalists. They
imagined headlines like ``Strip mall slated in state bird's
habitat.''
</P>
<P>
   The development issue, however, stayed in background. Instead,
opponents went negative on the jay.
</P>
<P>
   ``They eat the eggs of other birds,'' huffed Marion Hammer, the
veteran NRA lobbyist enlisted to fight the scrub jay menace.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's criminal conduct, that's robbery and murder.''
</P>
<P>
   She described the bird as ``lazy,'' displaying ``a welfare
mentality.'' She almost called it a liberal.
</P>
<P>
   With legislators deadlocked on which was the nicer bird, the
bill died.
</P>
<P>
   The scrub jay bill is back for another try. This time, it says
right in the legislation ``that the designation of the Florida
scrub jay is the official state bird is strictly symbolic and does
not require any additional protections or acquisition of habitat.''
</P>
<P>
   There it is in black and white: Just because it's the state bird
doesn't mean we have to stop killing it. With this spelled out in
the act, there should be no reason to oppose the little scrub jay.
Personally, I'd feel better with a limpkin or great white heron,
but a scrub jay works fine for me. It's a truly native bird, and
one that, like much of natural Florida, is every year steadily
disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   The legislators should assent and move to more pressing
concerns. Like finding a hotter official state band or proudly
designating Key lime as the official state pie.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
