<HEADER>
A8020 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN07-COX     03-06 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weight-loss gurus' wallets grow fatter as you grow more confused
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Losing weight is simple, yet Americans spend $50
billion a year on weight-loss programs.
</P>
<P>
   Every year Americans get fatter.
</P>
<P>
   Film director Oliver Stone should make a movie about this giant
conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Recently the government sponsored a food fight among the diet
industry's heavyweights. That's suspicious right there.
</P>
<P>
   The entrepreneur behind the Atkins Diet, Dr. Robert Atkins,
squared off with Dr. Dean Ornish, the author of ``Eat More, Weigh
Less'' and four other best-selling diet books.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Barry Sears was on hand to defend his lucrative high-protein
Zone diet.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of those billions that fat Americans shell out every
year fill the pockets of these three men.
</P>
<P>
   Also on hand at the Agriculture Department's ``great nutrition
debate'' were other fat cats in the nutrition and diet promotion
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said the department sponsored
the debate because ``there is so much confusing, conflicting
information out there.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding. Americans love to buy diet books. They buy tons of
them. The only books Americans buy more than diet books are
cookbooks. Book stores can't stock enough diet cookbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Book publishers must be one of the secret ingredients in this
sure-fire recipe for wealth.
</P>
<P>
   The creators of some of the more lucrative diets sell their own
diet food to accompany their diet regimens.
</P>
<P>
   Expensive brand-name nutritional supplements come in pills,
candy bars, powders and drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, best-selling diets have emphasized hamburgers,
acupuncture, grapefruit, crystal therapy, steaks, hypnosis, high
carbohydrates, low carbohydrates, fasting, meditation, papaya juice
and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   High protein diets are hot right now.
</P>
<P>
   Most nutritionists, doctors and researchers who are not peddling
diet books or diet products are unimpressed with all the diet fads.
</P>
<P>
   So am I, although I have no diet, nutrition or weight-loss
credentials.
</P>
<P>
   I've never been on a diet, but I have gained and lost a lot of
weight in my lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   The way I see it, unless someone has a medical problem, gaining
and losing weight are simple enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Healthy people gain weight by taking in more fuel than they
burn.
</P>
<P>
   Cars and people both need fuel.
</P>
<P>
   If you add too much fuel to a car, it overflows on the ground
and pollutes the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, if you add too much fuel to your body, it does
not spill out on the ground. Instead, the extra fuel pollutes your
body.
</P>
<P>
   Fat people have these big, expandable fuel tanks they haul
around with them.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the fuel people funnel into their bodies is far from
premium grade. People would never dream of putting the sort of junk
fuel in their cars that they put in their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Premium gasoline may be too expensive for some motorists.
Premium-grade food, however, is generally less expensive than the
outsized portions of low-grade food that Americans gulp down daily.
</P>
<P>
   America would not be in the midst of an obesity epidemic if
people who supersized their fuel intake supersized their energy
output.
</P>
<P>
   Overeating followed by junk snacks and drinks while watching
television makes people fat. An evening of pushing remote control
buttons won't burn a french fry's worth of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Losing weight is just as simple as gaining weight.
</P>
<P>
   Stop overeating, take in only premium-grade food, and burn off
all that extra fuel you poured into your body.
</P>
<P>
   Losing weight is simple, but it sure isn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
