<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0307-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Polls are out...weather and naked ladies are in''
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ What with ``Super Tuesday'' and all, I'd have
thought politics would be the argument of choice this morning among
my retired buddies at the cafe. Not so. They're talking about water
tables, vacations, and women. Mostly women.
</P>
<P>
   Cal says if we don't start getting some rain and quick, farmers
are in for a rough season. ``No rain in sight,'' he quotes the AM
radio show he listens to every morning. ``They promised Tuesday,
but weathermen are like wives. They'll promise you anything just
so's you'll listen to them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that ought to be a lesson to you,'' I suggest. ``Maybe
you should start paying attention.'' Cal says that wouldn't be a
smart thing to do because if he started listening to Hazel after
all of these years she'd probably think he was up to something.
</P>
<P>
   ``More'n likely, no good,'' Amos chimes in with the obligatory
snicker. The boys are at it again. They've been goading and jabbing
one another with wisecracks like these for a lot longer than the 17
years I've known them. They'll admit to at least 70.
</P>
<P>
   It's always fun embroiling these two in a political discussion.
One usually winds up red in the face while the other pounds his
palm on the table so hard it jiggles the coffee mugs. But this
morning, nobody's going for the bait.
</P>
<P>
   Cal, a lifetime Republican, says he's as sick of pols and polls
as he is of that lousy bran cereal his wife feeds him every
morning. ``She says it's good for me. I ask her who wants to live
forever if he has to eat fodder for breakfast.'' Every once in a
while, he'll sneak in a short stack at the cafe, swearing all of us
to secrecy should we run into Hazel in the market or at church on
Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   About this time Benny huffs in straight from his brisk two-mile
morning walk. We slide our chairs around to make room for him as he
mops his brow. ``Boy,'' he exclaims between deep breaths, ``I sure
do feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Amos asks him why he looks so bad if he's feeling so good.
Benny, who recently had some bypass work done, tells Amos he's just
jealous because he couldn't make a couple of miles if he had all
day.
</P>
<P>
   Amos, who has a zipper in his chest just like Benny's, denies
this. ``I get all the exercise I need just going from my chair to
the icebox.'' He giggles, clapping a hand over his mouth which
means he forgot to put in his bridge this morning, and tells us
Lucy has been threatening to have their boys move the refrigerator
to the barn so he'd have to work harder for his ice cream. ``All
</P>
<P>
   she buys me is that no-fat stuff. Tain't really ice cream, is
it?'' He answers himself with a sad shake of his head and a
drawn-out ``Naa-aw.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So who're we voting for this year?'' I ask, trying again.
Benny says he doesn't care any more as long as Nixon doesn't get
it. Amos looks at him kind of funny and asks him if he hadn't heard
Nixon is dead. Benny says he was being sarcastic, but Cal says it
wouldn't surprise him any if a dead guy got elected.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one wants to talk politics which is not normal for
this usually fractious bunch. This is the fifth presidential
election year I've spent over coffee cups with these guys and their
sudden reticence on things political is puzzling.
</P>
<P>
   Amos wants to talk about his plane ride to Arizona, and Cal is
lengthily describing a picture of some movie star he saw in last
week's Time. ``She didn't have on enough of a dress to blow your
nose in. Honest, she was as good as nekkid.'' Benny wants to know
if he saved the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   My mind wanders off while the guys are chewing on that one, and
I can't help thinking that if this corner of northwest Ohio is any
indicator, the entire democratic process is in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Pols and polls are out...weather and naked ladies are in.
</P>
<P>
   Around here folks, it's back to basics.
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
