<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Search the world for long-lost friends
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Now that it seems almost everyone in the world is
online, with an e-mail account and a Web page, one task is easier
than ever _ finding a friend from years ago.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find directories and search engines made for just that
task. With any luck, you can track down that high school
sweetheart, college roommate or the fellow who borrowed that book
and never returned it.
</P>
<P>
   A good starting point for your search is Switchboard.com, a
search engine that helps you find an e-mail address, as well as
telephone numbers and even street addresses. So head to
www.switchboard.com/ and select the link called People Search. Once
there, you enter as much information as you have. The only
essential item is a last name. So you could _ foolishly for sure _
search the nation for all the Smiths. You can already see that it
will help if the person you are searching for has a fairly unusual
last name. But if you can narrow the search by supplying the city
and the first name, your search should be easy.
</P>
<P>
   Most Internet people-finders work the same way. But there's a
good reason to bookmark every search engine of this type you can
find. Since there isn't a master list of all Internet users, each
search engine will have a different group of names and addresses.
</P>
<P>
   So go next to Bigfoot.com, another longtime people-finder
located at www.bigfoot.com/. One really handy search feature here _
besides the one described above _ is the ability to find out a
person's name and address by entering an e-mail address. This
feature only works with those who have created a profile on
Bigfoot, so don't be disappointed if your search doesn't return any
information.
</P>
<P>
   One must in your list of people-finders is PeopleSearch.com. It
truly is different from the other sites. For one thing, this site
at www.peoplesearch.com/ uses multiple search engines to find a
person. That search is free; simply look for the link labeled Free
People Search. For another, just in case you have tried all the
other search techniques and still can't find the person, there's
even more help available. You'll pay for that help, starting at
$39, but there are times _ when a person has changed his or her
name because of marriage or just because the world is crawling with
people with that same name _ that you may need the help.
</P>
<P>
   Web pages are an excellent way to locate a person. And even if
your friend doesn't have a Web page of his own, there's a good
chance that another Web page may mention them. Businesses, schools
and social organizations often maintain directories that, at the
least, contain e-mail addresses and names of members. So use a
search engine _ AltaVista (www.altavista.com) is my choice for
searches like this because it does a good job of searching the body
of the page _ and simply enter your friend's name. Let's suppose
the name is Martha Smith. Enter it this way in AltaVista: ``Martha
Smith'' (include the quote marks). That is how you tell the search
engine to return only pages that contain those two names in that
exact order. If you don't do that you'll find every Martha, every
Smith, a daunting task.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, check the newsgroups. This is a subset of the Net where
people post messages according to topic areas. To find out if your
friend has left a message there (it will contain an e-mail address)
use this page _ which contains a variety of newsgroup search
engines _ at www.lycos.com/computers/internet/newsgroups.html.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
