<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH0307-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Help with your taxes
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Internal Revenue Service: The friendly IRS Web site opens with
the newsy Digital Daily. When we checked in, it was reminding
America that ``more than 1.6 million taxpayers who failed to file
tax returns for 1996 risk losing about $2 billion in refunds if
they don't get their late returns to the IRS'' this year. We
thought that sort of procrastination was illegal or something. The
site offers forms that can be filled in on-screen and then printed
for mailing. www.irs.ustreas.gov/
</P>
<P>
   Waste Basket: Just for fun, look here to read about what the
government does with our hard-earned money. The site is by a
watchdog group called Taxpayers for Common Sense, which monitors
proposals for federal land giveaways, boondoggles, corporate
handouts and budget gimmicks.
</P>
<P>
   www.taxpayer.net/TCS/wastebasket/wbindex.html
</P>
<P>
   H&AMP;R Block: When we looked, H&AMP;R Block, the granddaddy of tax
help, told us it was having ``difficulty handling everyone trying
to use our online tax program'' and was not accepting new users for
the $9.95 service. As it turned out, the site was also dealing with
a glitch that let some visitors view other people's financial data.
Yikes! The company promised to be back up soon, though, and as an
alternative was offering its downloadable software free, along with
a coupon for $10 off at an H&AMP;R Block office.
</P>
<P>
   www.hrblock.com/taxcenter/doingmytaxes/onlinetax.html
</P>
<P>
   HD Vest Online: It's free to fill out your 1040 on this site and
zap it to the IRS. The catch? Goodbye, privacy. After you're done,
the service uses your financial information to target you with
advertising and offers. And ``if you choose to withhold the
requested information, you will not be eligible to take advantage
of certain hdvest.com services such as the free tax-calculation
program or other services.'' So there. www.hdvestonline.com/
</P>
<P>
   TurboTax: Intuit-owned TurboTax for the Web offers online
preparation of the shorter 1040EZ form for free and other forms for
$9.95 each. There's an exception, though. Returns with adjusted
gross incomes under $20,000 will also be done free, Intuit says. As
is true with most such sites, you need not do all the work in one
sitting. The site remembers who you are and lets you pick up the
process where you left off.
www.turbotax.com/turbotaxweb99/welcome.html?SRC &QC; sectaxcust
</P>
<P>
   123: This site confused us by proclaiming ``Online Tax Prep for
Free'' on the opening screen, then introducing the fees: $5 for
printing returns, $9.95 for an e-filing. Where does the ``free''
part come in? Oh, that's for free access to the site, ``including
FREE return calculation.'' We are still scratching our head.
www.123taxprep.com/
</P>
<P>
   Report Suspect Tax Fraud: When you are done with the return and
hankering for revenge, why not turn in that neighbor with the
Jaguar and no visible means of support?
</P>
<P>
   www.ustreas.gov/irs/ci/taxfraudhotline.htm
</P>
<P>
   BUYING A COMPUTER
</P>
<P>
   Dave's Guides _ Buying a Computer: Advice doesn't get any
simpler or easier to read than this. After all, the information on
buying a computer is just one segment of teaching materials for an
online home computing course. Learn how to shop for a home PC,
notebook (laptop), used computer or upgraded tools.
www.css.msu.edu/PC-Guide/
</P>
<P>
   Peabody Institute: Much more than a shopping guide, this site
cuts through the clutter to give you the facts on buying a new
personal computer. Check out product comparisons, technical
terminology, how to find a bargain and key features to look for.
Don't fret about the fact that your wonderful new system will be
outdated in two years. www.peabodylibrary.org/purchase.html
</P>
<P>
   FairNet _ Computer Buying Tips: This utilitarian site helps
buyers decide what home computer features will best meet their
needs and budget. Apple or a PC? Desktop or laptop? To upgrade or
not to upgrade? Get the skinny here. The site is sponsored by the
Fairbanks, Alaska, Community Network.
</P>
<P>
   www.fairnet.org/fnvol/training/buytips.html
</P>
<P>
   Consumer World: This site is like the Consumer Reports of
Consumer Reports, with links to Web pages on a wide variety of
products. You'll have to root around for the computer-buying
resources, but the hunt is worthwhile. Get a handle on which
computer is right for you, what things cost, sources of new and
used computers, negotiating the best deal and how to save money on
software.
</P>
<P>
   consumerworld.org/pages/buyadv.htm
</P>
<P>
   Computer Buying Tips for Beginners: Should you buy a desktop or
a laptop? Should you consider mail order? What software fits what
you want to do? Browse here for info on the most basic decisions
you'll need to make before stepping into cyberspace.
help.unc.edu/documentation/html/dgg02.html
</P>
<P>
   Dave Barry in Cyberspace: Confused by computers? So is
syndicated columnist Dave Barry. ``I'm not going to bombard you
with a bunch of technical gobbledygook,'' Barry promises. ``I'm
going to present you with simple, practical, well-organized,
easy-to-understand information, a lot of which I will make up as I
go along.'' Tag along and get with the program.
</P>
<P>
   www.randomhouse.com/features/davebarry/word.html
</P>
<P>
   PC Today.Com: For the more experienced computer consumer, here
is a directory of computer systems and peripherals, including
motherboards, monitors and printers available from hundreds of
vendors. Compare products, link to manufacturers, publications and
trade associations.
</P>
<P>
   www.pctoday.com/default.asp?guid &QC; m6gncne0
</P>
<P>
   PC World.Com _ Buyer's Guide for Home PCs: PC World magazine put
25 of the snazziest new computer systems through ``a battery of
hands-on and real-world performance tests.'' They whittled the list
down to the 15 best machines on the market for various uses. Read
related stories on getting the best PC deals online, the best PC
prices under $1,000, etc.
</P>
<P>
   www.pcworld.com/top400/article/0,1361,13526,00.html
</P>
<P>
   Business Week Computer Buying Guide: When you get to this page,
check out the left-hand column (Computer Buying Guide) for product
reviews, a helpful beginner's guide and the Technology &AMP; You
column, which examines the fast-moving world of high tech as it
affects us all in the workplace, on the road and at home.
www.maven.businessweek.com/
</P>
<P>
   Computer Buying Guide.Com: This site is easy to navigate and
promises to educate you on computer basics in 10 minutes flat.
Answer all the quiz questions, and site creators show you your
``dream system.'' Whether you can afford it or not is another
matter. www.computerbuyingguide.com/
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS AND TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   Natives: It's still not too late to find a job at a ski resort.
This site offers information for ski workers and details about jobs
in resorts around the world. www.natives.co.uk/
</P>
<P>
   Golf Investors: Ah, yes, another fantasy stock league. This
time, it's golf that's putting the blue chip in the chip shots,
with golfers on the PGA Tour traded like stocks in real time.
</P>
<P>
   212.20.149.29/home/index.html
</P>
<P>
   House Law: Nothing fancy here. Just a monthly reporting service
covering legal developments in the housing, mortgage, finance and
home-equity lending industries. www.houselaw.net
</P>
<P>
   Senior Job Bank: The Senior Job Bank's motto: Ability is
ageless. This site is a nonprofit referral service to help older
people find full-time, part-time or temporary work in a wide range
of fields.
</P>
<P>
   www.seniorjobbank.com
</P>
<P>
   Move Again: It's the curse of success in the military: repeated
relocation. This site aims to make moving around a little less
painful, with abundant information about housing, businesses and
schools adjacent to military bases. www.moveagain.com/
</P>
<P>
   TV News Music: You're in the TV news biz and you need a
compelling theme song for the 6 o'clock news. Check out this
collection of rare and current TV news theme songs from local
stations around the United States. It's infotainment at it's most
infotaining. www.geocities.com/Pipeline/7612/
</P>
<P>
   Broker 4 Domains: Web addresses are like stocks and bonds, and
Broker4Domains helps you buy, sell or lease domain names. And just
like a Taurus or BMW, you can consider leasing options as an
inexpensive way to get the domain you want at a price you can
afford. www.broker4domains.com/
</P>
<P>
   Favorites: You spend hours bookmarking your favorite sites at
home but it's a pain to transfer them to your laptop or office
computer. This site lets you store bookmarks online and access them
from anywhere you have Web access.
www.bravuranet.com/favoritesanywhere/
</P>
<P>
   HotBar.Com: We were skeptical. After all, how much fun can it be
to add a new design, called a ``skin'' to your Web browser's tool
bar? Take our word -- it's way fun. Choose an image from among the
5,000 offered. It takes all of 15 seconds to download the new skin.
www.hotbar.com
</P>
<P>
   Auction Octupus: This site touts itself as the most powerful
online auction meta-search tool available on the Web. You have to
register to take full advantage of the many services here, but if
you're in a buying mood, they can show you where to pick up antique
dolls to sports memorabilia without really ``shopping.''
www.auctionoctopus.com/
</P>
<P>
   The Digital Fridge: Are there refrigerators in cyberspace, and
if so, are there magnets for all your pictures and drawings? The
Digital Fridge lets you post digital pictures and video clips for
friends and family to see. Create your private fridge and upload
your private stash of images. You choose who gets to peek inside;
only viewers with your private code can see these images. Lucky
them.
</P>
<P>
   www.thedigitalfridge.com
</P>
<P>
   Shields Up: The Internet is full of baddies who like to fiddle
with your computer's innards for fun and profit. The risk increases
with always-on cable and DSL connections, which make individual
home PCs easier to find and visit repeatedly. First, though, you
have to find out how vulnerable you are. Shields Up, a free
diagnostic tool, offers two tests of your computer's potential
exposure. (Most of this stuff is geared towards Windows, but Mac
owners can still benefit from a visit.) www.grc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
