<HEADER>
A8025 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-SAVVY0307-COX     03-06 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-SAVVY0307-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Resources aid in LAN-making Home network within reach
 &HT;    By Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Here's background on why we're taking up this space. We're
problem solvers. We investigate, figure things out, learn _
sometimes the hard way _ teach and bring new technology to the
newsroom.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: We don't know it all, but we can point you to a sea of
information and help navigate. We'll teach you to fish by tapping
the Internet, reference books, your instincts and common sense to
get the most out of technology.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: You've asked lots of questions about networking two, maybe
three, home computers and sharing files and a printer. The
technology's there. Why not make sharing easier than playing pass
the floppy or Zip? Turn Dad's printer into the ``family'' printer?
Share an Internet connection? That's why we're devoting this column
to the topic.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: You'll be creating your own LAN, or Local Area Network.
Impressive. If you've never heard of a LAN or need to know basic
network-speak, cruise to the Miramar Systems Inc. Networking 101
link (www.miramarsys.com
</P>
<P>
   /home/net101.htm).
</P>
<P>
   Sue: You must decide the size of your network and how much you
can spend. Some options include Ethernet, phone wire and wireless
networking. There's even a nifty power outlet deal. A quick
tutorial on Ethernet: It's a tried-and-true method of data
communication that requires a chunky cable, fatter than a phone
wire, connected from each computer Network Interface Card into a
hub (where you park devices on a LAN so they can chat). You'll have
to jump through some internal network hoops to share an Internet
connection. A place to start is the NETGEAR site (netgear
</P>
<P>
   .baynetworks.com/).
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: There's the obvious, which is using your phone line. To
find out about AnyPoint from Intel, surf to www.intel.com/anypoint.
A slick wireless option is the Airport for the Macintosh
(www.apple.com/airport/). We love Macs. Wireless is where we're all
headed. No more tangles.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Breathe, Jacki. Bear in mind that wireless is costlier. A
reliable and fast wireless PC solution would be Proxim (www.proxim
.com/). Or, hey, you may like the idea of plugging into a power
outlet to create a network. No NIC installs or hubs. For
quick-and-easy, go to Intelogis (www .intelogis.com). You can share
a printer, files and an Internet connection within minutes, all at
around $200.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: For a good list of home network kits, try ZDNet
(www.zdnet.com/products/stories/reviews/0,4161,2226069,00.html).
Kits have it all. Hardware and software, for as little as $90. And,
yep, you can shell out more, too. Prices vary depending on how
cutting-edge the network option, the ``plug-and-playishness'' of
the kit, who installs NICs, the type of cabling and the hub size.
The possibilities are all over the map.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
