<SLUG> BC-CAR-JUMPSTART0307-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Battery charger is a do-it-yourself jump
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Few things are more frustrating than a car that
won't start because of a weak battery.
</P>
<P>
   But a Philadelphia company is marketing a device that allows you
to jump-start your car from inside the car. You don't have to flag
down a stranger and wrestle with jumper cables. You don't have to
wait for the auto club to show up. You don't even have to open your
hood.
</P>
<P>
   StartMeUp is an emergency battery charger that weighs only six
ounces and easily fits in a glove compartment where it stays usable
for three years.
</P>
<P>
   If you attempt to start your car and get only the clicking noise
associated with a drained battery, you plug StartMeUp into the
cigarette lighter receptacle. After five minutes of charging, the
car will start, according to Future Labs, the Philadelphia company
that developed StartMeUp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It provides motorists with peace of mind knowing they will
never be stranded with a drained battery again,'' said Kyle Burns,
president and CEO of Future Labs. ``You wouldn't think of driving a
car without a spare tire. By the same token, people should have a
device that allows them to jump-start their car from safely inside
the vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   StartMeUp is a one-use product. After a unit starts a car, it is
thrown away. Future Labs says the product is environmentally
friendly.
</P>
<P>
   The product will not work if the battery is completely depleted.
If you hear a clicking when the ignition key is turned, that means
there's some life left in the battery, and StartMeUp should work,
Future Labs says. It won't work if the battery is defective or if
the starter is malfunctioning.
</P>
<P>
   StartMeUp is supposed to work on cars, minivans and light
trucks, both domestic and foreign. It doesn't work on diesel
engines, though a diesel model is being developed.
</P>
<P>
   A Future Labs press release indicated StartMeUp should be
available through automotive and discount stores nationwide for
about $19.95. If you can't find it in stores, you can order it
online at www.startmeup.com or by calling (888) 782-7863 (STARTME).
Phone and online orders carry shipping and handling fees.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
