<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MEDIA0307-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home theater moves to spotlight as layouts become more
affordable
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Home theater gets more affordable and more popular
each year. While there are still the few who pop $100,000 and up
for a Hollywood-style home theater, complete with leather seats and
screen sizes that rival your neighborhood multiplex, there are
reasonably good systems for $1,500 or less. One of the really hot
trends is flat plasma screen monitors. If you want to check out the
devices many see as the future of home theater, pick up the March
issue of Audio Video Interiors (you can also find it on the Web at
www.audiovideointeriors.com). In the same issue, you'll get the top
10 tech support tips that may help you solve problems without
making a call.
</P>
<P>
   Are you a Web auction junkie? Do you buy and sell on one of the
services such as eBay? If you do, you may spend more time than you
need to log on to the Web site to see how the item you care about
is doing. If you'd like to save some time, check out the March
issue of Popular Mechanics. You'll find an article that tells you
how to check your online accounts and place bids using a cell
phone. If you don't have access to the magazine, you can read the
article at www
</P>
<P>
   .popularmechanics.com/elect/9911EFCOWFAP.html.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   If you have a Macintosh, you probably value it because of the
ease of use and the fact it's designed for people who usually have
more interest in the work that it can do than in learning about the
innards of the machine and its software. But there are times when
things go wrong. That's when it helps to have a program such as
Norton Utilities Version 4.0 for the Macintosh. It's a Mac-friendly
program that helps you rescue damaged files on your hard disk,
speed up disk performance and even permanently delete especially
sensitive files. You can find the program on CD almost anyplace
that software is sold for about $40.
</P>
<P>
   Another Mac program worth checking out for the teenage females
in your family is called Seventeen Style Studio. It only comes in a
Mac version and lets kids and teens check out new hairstyles and
experiment with the way different types of makeup treatments would
look. You simply use your own photograph, then manipulate that
image with the tools that come with the software. This program
comes from MacSoft and sells for about $45.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   As the weather becomes more like spring, many people begin to
think of shaping up and exercising. Whether you are interested in
limbering up for golf, speeding up for soccer or just looking
better when it comes time to hit the beach, there's a site designed
to help. It's called GetFit.com and can be found at
www.getfit.com/zones/home/index.jsp. Besides the exercise tips,
there are recipes designed to help in a quest to slim down.
</P>
<P>
   While eBay gets most of the ink, there are some other nifty
auction sites on the Web. One worth checking _ since it comes from
a name that most people trust _ is the auction site on Yahoo.
You'll find it at auctions.yahoo.com/.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
