<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    You won't mind zombies taking revengeBy Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News ServiceFOR THE CONSOLE:
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's gross, it's gratuitously violent and the story's stupid,
but there's something about Sega's Zombie's Revenge ($50,
www.dreamcast.com) that's totally addictive. In the game, you are
one of three characters hacking, shooting or punching your way
through hundreds of zombies. The game is based on the arcade hit
and plays pretty close to the standup model. This makes for
lightning-fast game play _ if you blink or lose concentration, you
die. There is also the cool part of the game where you can pick up
almost anything and use it as a weapon. Zombie's Revenge is a
``must'' for the shooter game addict or anyone else who enjoyed
Sega's ``Dynamite Cop.''
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP:
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two years, Austin's Aspyr Media Inc. has made a
good business of creating Macintosh versions of popular PC games.
Following its success porting games such as the ``Tomb Raider''
series, Aspyr has scored a home run with its port of Sid Meier's
Alpha Centauri ($50 for Mac, www.aspyr. com).
</P>
<P>
   In case you missed it last year on the PC, the game is an
involved, addictive, turn-based simulation tracking the future of
seven political and cultural factions starting new civilizations on
an undeveloped planet. Taking control of one of these factions, you
rebuild an alien landscape, engage in domestic relations and
balance your power between battle and scientific or cultural
advancement. To say this game is deep doesn't begin to describe
Alpha Centauri's complexity. It's a must-have for any
empire-building gamer, and now Mac fans have a chance to own it,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
