A8037 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0307-COX     03-06 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0307-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our family has decided to collect the commemorative state
quarters. I thought I heard there will be five a year released over
the next 10 years, with five released in January1999 and another
five in January 2000. What is the schedule and which states are
presently in circulation? _ Angela Ozymy
</P>
<P>
   A: The coins, produced at the Philadelphia and Denver mints,
will be issued over a 10 year period (1999-2008), five per year.
(None will be issued for the District of Columbia.) The coins are
issued in the same order that the states joined the union.
Presently in circulation are quarters commemorating Delaware,
Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Georgia, Connecticut and Massachusetts.
Look for Maryland, South Carolina, New Hampshire and Virginia to be
issued this year (at about 10-week intervals). Expect the Lone Star
state quarter in 2004. For details, contact the U.S. Mint customer
care center at (202) 283-2646.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you use the poppy seeds from a poppy flower in baking?
They look like the kind you buy at the store. _ Linda G.
</P>
<P>
   A: All poppies are not created equal. According to the Central
Texas Poison Center at (800) POISON1, using poppy seeds from a
poppy flower for baking is dangerous because there are different
types of genus Papaver plants available in the store.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does baseball commissioner Bud Selig have an e-mail address
where we can send him our opinions on rulings? I am sick and tired
of the repeaters like Darryl Strawberry getting only a one-year
suspension while Pete Rose is suspended for life. I would like to
give Selig my thoughts on the subject whether or not he wants to
hear them. _ Bob Olson
</P>
<P>
   A: None that I could find. Send your missive of opinions to
Allan H. Selig, Office of the Commissioner of Baseball, 245 Park
Ave., New York, N.Y. 10167. It is harder to toss a letter than to
hit the delete button. Q: I don't know if you can help with this or
not, but my 15-year-old daughter put tattoos on. Do you know of a
doctor who can take them off? Is there a way to bleach them off? We
are up in the air about this. _ J.L.K.
</P>
<P>
   A: Bleach won't cut it. A laser procedure will. The process also
works on those pesky brown age spots. Some colors are more
difficult to lighten (e.g. greens and oranges). Some of the tattoo
is vaporized; some pulverized, and pigment particles are swallowed
by blood cells. Dermabrasion also works on some stubborn tattoos.
Other, possibilities? Photoderm, which requires local anesthesia
and might leave scarring, or infrared coagulator treatment, which
also requires a local anesthetic and takes longer to heal.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you give me information on the chapel in which JFK Jr.
was married? Also, are there similar ones in the Hill Country? _
Jenny P.
</P>
<P>
   A: The chapel is on Cumberland Island, Ga., a national seashore.
Built in the 1930s, the small Baptist church was a town gathering
center for an African-American community (this section of the
island was one of the first places blacks were allowed to own
property). The church only holds about 20 people, has no
electricity and, for most, requires an 11-mile walk (closer access
to the settlement is under study). Guests of the island's Greyfield
Inn, where the Kennedy reception was held, (904) 261-6408, have
vehicular access to the island's roads, alleviating the walk. To
apply for a special permit, call the The National Park Service at
(912) 882-4335.
</P>
<P>
   The Hill Country is soooo much closer. Sharon Buford, (830)
997-2835, of the Gillespie County Historical Society suggests an
1855 Methodist Church Sanctuary for weddings and receptions. To
view it, visit www.ktc.net/gchs. The native limestone church sports
lovely stained glass and electricity. Maximum capacity is 220.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I need a special hammer, a straight peen, to play
``nagelschlagen.'' I've exhausted the knowledge at Home Depot,
confounded Sears, frustrated The Hardware Store and surprised the
guys at Breed &AMP; Co. It's nothing more than a cross peen hammer with
the cross ``straight'' (parallel to the handle). _ Wayne Sanders
</P>
<P>
   A: Wayne, Wayne, Wayne, you should have come to me sooner. A
straight peen hammer is a blacksmith's tool. Order one from Koka
Metalsmiths by calling (507) 643-7946 or e-mail
kokairon(at)clear.lakes.com. Prices begin at $39. Koka also sells
silversmith hammers and Japanese-style hammers. Don't see many of
either in these parts.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, readers, the peen is the wedge- or ball-shaped end
of a hammerhead. ``Nagelschlagen'' is a German game played in
barrooms and at Oktoberfest and fairs involving a large tree stump
and nails.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there any way a private citizen can refuse to be counted
in the upcoming census? _ P.S.
</P>
<P>
   A: You could be fined, says spokeswoman Leslie Lawson. Census is
required by law. The census works with individuals to get everyone
counted through follow-ups and interviews with neighbors, and
participation has no negative repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   By law, the census cannot share your information with anyone,
including other federal agencies. The cost of not participating?
Loss of federal grant money for education, health care, parks,
roads, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard that a man died in Hawaii after being in a food
storage warehouse full of dried mouse and rat droppings. He died of
massive organ failure after inhaling this rodent dust. Is there a
virus like the hantavirus that lives in these droppings? Should we
all rinse off can tops and wipe off cardboard food packaging just
in case? Everything you buy has been in one of these warehouses. _
D.M.
</P>
<P>
   A: Pure rumor, says Norman Sato of the Hawaii Health Department.
``We have had no reports of that kind of death.'' The folks at the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention add that the hantavirus
has many types, one of which results in death by massive organ
failure.
</P>
<P>
   The Sin Nombre virus is the primary hantavirus in the United
States, and is carried by the deer mouse. The CDC recommends basic
precautions to prevent exposure: Eliminate rodent harbors, control
the rodent population (traps, etc.), clean up rodent-infested areas
and avoid rodents when outdoors. Of course, when cleaning rodent
droppings, do not stir up or breathe the dust. Good kitchen hygiene
includes wiping can lids and frequent hand washing.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin, TX 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
