<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8038 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FUTUREMAN-0307-COX     03-06 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUTUREMAN-0307-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The future's bright for Future Man
 &HT;    By Noah Bierman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Now seems the ideal time to be a futurist.
</P>
<P>
   The millennium came with nary a bug. Technology stocks buoy the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   So why does the human being known as FM-2030 (Future Man) sound
frustrated today, even as the clear sun reflects into his
stark-white Biscayne Bay condominium?
</P>
<P>
   ``My body is at the repair shop, so unfortunately I had to
borrow this body, just so I could interact with you,'' says FM, the
name he uses in casual conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Huh?
</P>
<P>
   Relax. It's future humor.
</P>
<P>
   To FM, his body is a 4 million-year-old anachronism, a primate's
body meant for swinging on trees, an inefficient and altogether too
fragile thing attached to a small, modern organ called the brain
which can ``look out billions of light years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I am, ready to gallop across the solar system,'' he says,
though his sick pancreas, ``a stupid, dumb, wretched organ,''
barely allows him to walk across the room.
</P>
<P>
   FM-2030 will not stay frustrated long. He's too busy
anticipating the day when scientists thaw his frozen body later
this century and transform him into a ``post-biological'' organism.
</P>
<P>
   Ideas like this _ the same ones he's been transmitting in
classes at Florida International University and his books _ still
excite him, after nearly four decades of provocative predictions.
</P>
<P>
   He teaches a class on the future, a subject he is so obsessed
with that he has taken on the persona of a futureman, a person
living decades from now. He speaks like a futureman, acts like a
futureman, thinks like a futureman and keeps it going 24 hours a
day. Every day.
</P>
<P>
   This makes for some interesting dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Wednesday, this gentle man who rolls his R's when he
calls people ``dear,'' pounds on the lectern.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are turning reality upside down, and we are saying that
death need not be final,'' he tells his class.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a loose black jacket with rolled sleeves over a black
shirt, he's about to show a short film on cryogenics to 28, largely
well-educated, adult students. Cryogenics, freezing the body until
science finds a way to cure what ails it, is but one subject FM
addressed in five weekly three-hour sessions at Miami Beach's
Wolfsonian Museum that ended last week. The inevitable end of
marriage, family, capitalism, socialism, poverty, religion and
automobile travel all took time to explain to a group of students
still very much living in the present.
</P>
<P>
   THE FUTURE REQUIRES IMAGINATION
</P>
<P>
   Describing the future, a space FM inhabits and romances,
requires imagination, he says. One has to stretch his mind, for
example, to comprehend the ``Santa Claus Machine,'' which FM says
will work like the copy machine, only it will reproduce the
molecular structure of three-dimensional objects. This, combined
with free energy from the sun, will provide limitless resources and
eliminate competition.
</P>
<P>
   Without competition, capitalism and socialism, we will die of
irrelevance. This is, of course, the short version. But it's a good
example of his thought process: technology, already in its
formative stages, will radically change human nature once it
becomes a commonplace part of the culture.
</P>
<P>
   And because the rate of change will continue to increase,
current logic will not apply to future realities.
</P>
<P>
   Or, to put it in even simpler terms, the whole world will
change.
</P>
<P>
   FM's students say they're initially stunned by their prof's
ideas. But as the class goes on and they begin to analyze his
logic, they begin to appreciate the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's right on in many ways,'' said Nancy Lipoff, 61, who took
the class with her husband and several friends. ``On the other
hand, for people who believe in religion and believe in tradition
and believe in preserving things for our children and
grandchildren, he doesn't fit into that mold at all.''
</P>
<P>
   No, molds do not interest FM. Though he lived in 12 or 13
countries by the time he was 17, he says has no nationality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I belong to the whole planet, and I embrace the whole
planet.''
</P>
<P>
   His ancestral origins? ``For that, you'll have to talk to my
ancestors.''
</P>
<P>
   Official records _ which list him as FM, Twenty Thirty _
indicate he's 69 years old, but he won't confirm.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto, his former employment at the United Nations, mentioned in
the forward of a book he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   What about the rumors that his family of international diplomats
includes former heads of state? ``I have no family,'' says FM,
explaining that networks of close friends, companions and lovers
replace traditional modes in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Without the need to produce babies inside the body, children
will have multiple mothers and fathers from multiple gene pools, he
once wrote. Children from these ``mosaic births'' will be raised by
groups which might or might not be temporary.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S IN A NAME?
</P>
<P>
   He knows you won't necessarily agree with him. Then again, no
one would have believed him 100 years ago if he insisted he didn't
belong to a tribe, he says. So please, ``allow me to define myself
the way I see myself.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what he began doing in the mid-1960s, when his name was
FM Esfandiary and he began teaching about the future at the New
School for Social Research in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Names convey ancestry, ethnicity, the past, nationality and
religion, he says, reading from his 1989 book ``Are You
Transhuman?''
</P>
<P>
   FM wanted to evoke the future with his name. And like the world,
it will evolve. ``I will change (the name) again right before
2030,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Understanding the future is essential or one risks riding on
Interstate 95 in a horse and carriage, to use one of his favorite
analogies.
</P>
<P>
   During class, one student who is particularly skeptical of FM's
vision insists his own name is FM-2020 ``because I'm 10 years
behind you.''
</P>
<P>
   FM laughs. ``I switch on the future in total context, and that's
too much future for most people,'' he says later.
</P>
<P>
   BETTING ON A BRIGHT FUTURE
</P>
<P>
   Still, FM is confident, even if his timing is premature. If he's
wrong, it's a shame for humanity, he says.
</P>
<P>
   But FM is betting his money on a bright future. He's arranged to
pay $100,000 to the Alcor Life Extension Foundation of Scottsdale,
Ariz., to preserve his body in liquid nitrogen when his body no
longer works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why risk being in the last generation to die before anti-aging
solves the life span problem?'' reads the company's pamphlet.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that occurs 30, 50 or 100 years after his death, FM
plans to relish his golden years for centuries, if not millennia _
even if he has no money when he wakes up.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like me don't give a damn. I'll be so glad that I'm
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
