<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8042 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TECH-TOOLS0307     03-06 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS0307 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    National park digital guides cover nuances from every angle
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It would be hard to find two more utterly different
places than Yellowstone National Park and the Okefenokee Swamp: one
majestic, the other dark and brooding.
</P>
<P>
   They are, however, the most magical places I have ever seen, and
I haven't seen nearly enough of them.
</P>
<P>
   Maptech, whose reproductions of Geological Survey maps of North
Georgia we discussed some time ago, has produced a series of
National Park Digital Guides for all 54 national parks. I've been
tracing on one of them the places we saw at Yellowstone.
</P>
<P>
   I'm parked now overlooking the Hayden Valley, not far from the
Lake Hotel, in the hour before dawn. Our son, an outdoor
photographer, was working in the park, and he brought us to that
spot at just that time. I cannot remember the last time I saw land
illuminated by starlight; it may have been 50 years ago, when
coyotes yapped and sang around our house just as they do now in the
valley.
</P>
<P>
   The park maps have all the advantages of Maptech's standard
topographical maps _ you can measure distances as the crow flies or
along a path, and when you have laid out your distance line you can
switch to a profile view that shows how much uphill and downhill
you'll have to contend with. You can zoom in and out, mark up a map
with a trail you want to hike and print it out.
</P>
<P>
   The maps also have a lot of text; there are guides to services
in the park you're looking at, plus discussions of the flora and
fauna, history, climate and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   The Okefenokee is included on the CD-ROM in Maptech's terrain
Navigator series that also covers the Georgia coastal area. All the
same goodies are here, even the profile views, although there isn't
much profile to the Okefenokee.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to find Billy's Island, the turnaround point in our
epic motorboat adventure. The problem with outboard motors like
those they rent in the swamp is that they steer exactly opposite
the way one steers a car. It takes a while to remember which way to
twist the throttle to run it up or shut it down.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect there's an alligator that hangs out not far from
Billy's Island who still has nightmares about our encounter; I can
only hope we didn't stunt his growth. He was only about 3 feet long
when we met; he was minding his own business, sunning himself on a
partially submerged log.
</P>
<P>
   A close-up photo was in order. With the captain at the helm and
his lady in the bow, the idea was to run up the motor briefly, then
shut it off entirely and glide soundlessly as close to the 'gator
as we could. I maneuvered the boat around to line up with the log,
the memsahib positioned herself up front, and I put the motor in
gear. Unfortunately, instead of shutting it down, I twisted the
wrong way and put the pedal to the water, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   The poor 'gator awoke to the sight of a motorboat roaring toward
him at breakneck speed, a woman's legs flailing in the air over the
gunnels. Fortunately, the memsahib stayed with the boat, and the
'gator was long gone when we replaced him on top of the log.
</P>
<P>
   The map of the swamp wouldn't help my seamanship, but it would
certainly make venturing beyond Billy's Island a lot nicer. In the
meantime, it's great fun just to scroll around the swamp and
imagine that water like a black mirror, with the birds overhead,
the reptiles watching you pass in the heavy silence. We'll do it in
kayaks next time. A motorboat is almost an insult to the place.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
