<HEADER>
A8043 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TECHNOBUDDY0307-COX     03-06 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY0307-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pentium chips fast, but Celeron might be better buy
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When is the best time to buy a computer? It's when you
need one.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the questions I get by phone and e-mail, that's the most
common. And there are dozens of cliched _ and unsatisfying _
answers to the question. My favorite is to wait until the computer
you own won't perform some vital task _ either won't run a program
that you need, or runs it so slowly that it's unsatisfying.
</P>
<P>
   But the real truth with computers is that most people buy a
computer when they get the craving, very much like buying a car.
The old one still runs, still gets you to work, but _ with obvious
exceptions _ most of us do not wait until the wheels fall off the
old car. It's the same with computers.
</P>
<P>
   We are coming into some confusing times when it comes to buying
a computer.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing to know is that new chips are coming from Intel.
There'll soon be even faster Pentium III chips, and also _ probably
next month _ Intel will bring out a new version of its popular
lower-priced junior brand chip, the Celeron. The Pentium III chips
will be fast _ with the state of the art at 866 megahertz and
increased to 933 megahertz later in the year. And they'll be
relatively expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The Celeron chips won't be as fast _ with a top speed of 600
megahertz _ and not just because of the clock speed (that's the 600
megahertz part).
</P>
<P>
   I hate to throw numbers around _ someone could get hurt _ but we
need them to tell this story. One of the factors in how fast your
computer runs is a thing called bus speed. That's the speed the
chip is able to use when transferring data. Think of the bus as the
pipeline that connects the chip and the computer. The faster that
pipeline _ the speed also is measured in megahertz _ the better the
computer is at wringing all the speed out of the chip.
</P>
<P>
   Celeron chips use the old bus speed of 66 megahertz. The new
Pentium III chips work at bus speeds of 100 to 133 megahertz. That
means that a 600-megahertz Pentium III chip will run much faster
than a 600-megahertz Celeron chip, maybe 30 percent faster.
</P>
<P>
   All that being true, I'm guessing that you know what the next
shoe to drop is. You are thinking that the Pentium III is the best
buy. And _ if you're in true need of blazing speed, if you spend a
lot of time with graphics, if you are designing a nuclear submarine
in the basement _ that's right. It's also right if money is no
object. Go ahead and pop for the Pentium III.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're like me and tend to use a home computer to log on
to the Net, play a few games (they are power-hungry, but the
600-megahertz Celeron will run them just fine, especially if you
get a high-end video card to go with it) and to write letters _
then a Celeron is worth looking at.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some people in the industry think that Intel actually
did too good of a job in designing the Celeron (and the new one is
even better because of a new chip technique that is important but
almost impossible to explain in the space I have left). The Celeron
runs so fast and sells for so little that some folks think that
Intel is losing a lot of Pentium III sales to that computer.
</P>
<P>
   What sort of price differential can you expect between the
Celeron and the Pentium III? I'm guessing that the new chips will
be about $300 apart (the spread will vary based on the speed of
each chip, but that's close).
</P>
<P>
   And since the Pentium III tends to go into higher-end machines,
the actual price difference when you consider the end price of the
PC may be higher.
</P>
<P>
   So, if you have PC lust now that it's turning spring, at least
consider looking at the new Celeron chip in March.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Celeron chip PC over one with Pentium III
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
