   CAR-JUMPSTART _ A Philadelphia company is marketing a device
that allows you to jump-start your car from inside the car.
StartMeUp is an emergency battery charger that weighs only six
ounces and is small enough to store in a glove compartment where it
stays usable for three years. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News). 11.
WITH PHOTO. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: THIS IS JAMES CUMMINGS' GADGETS COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   MISSROSE _ When Robert Horne died of lung cancer nearly two
years ago, he bereaved two women. He was faithful to both to the
very end of his life. One woman was his wife, Missy Horne, who
treasures his memory still. She's in her 60s. ``I don't lie about
my age, but I don't advertise it either,'' she said. The other is
Rose Sachs, 87, one of Palm Beach's best-known socialites, whose
40-year relationship with ``my Robert'' bears an uncanny
resemblance to the 1989 movie Driving Miss Daisy, in which a black
man and a wealthy white woman gradually come to discover a shared
humanity. ``It's true,'' said Missy Horne. ``Whenever they pulled
up in the Rolls-Royce at the Palm Beach Airport, all the porters
would shout, ``Here comes Robert! Driving Miss Daisy!''' ``That's
right,'' giggled Rose Sachs. ``They called me 'Miss Daisy.' I would
ride up in the front seat with Robert, because we had so much to
talk about. There were people who thought that was improper, but I
didn't care. I loved Robert.'' (Browning, Palm Beach Post). 57.
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   FUTUREMAN _ Now seems the ideal time to be a futurist. The
millennium came with nary a bug. Technology stocks buoy the
economy. So why does the human being known as FM-2030 (Future Man)
sound frustrated today, even as the clear sun reflects into his
stark-white Biscayne Bay condominium? (Bierman, Palm Beach Post).
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMERQ&AMP;A _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Consumer Q&AMP;A. (Greig, Austin
American-Statesman) (l, a) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   HOSPITALS-INFECTIONS _ ATLANTA _ Melanie Dodd's patient needed a
dressing changed. It sounded like an uncomplicated task, but it
included more steps than a space shuttle launch: Wash and dry
hands. Pull on latex gloves. Loosen the edges of the dressing.
Change the gloves. Put on mask. Change dressing... At a time when
hospitals are seeing a growing number of drug-resistant illnesses
and ``secondary infections'' - where patients contract diseases
AFTER they enter a hospital - it's been said that hospitals today
are a terrible place for sick people to be. With CDC holding a
major conference in Atlanta this week on preventing hospital
infections, we detail how consumers can protect themselves from
hospital-borne diseases and profile nurses and docs in the
frontlines of the defense. (McKenna. Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
30. WITH PHOTOS and tip list and chart of new figures on hospital
infection rates.
</P>
<P>
   CARDIOLOGIST _ ATLANTA _ Dr. Elisabeth Ofili, chief cardiologist
at Morehouse School of Medicine, is the first woman to be elected
president of the Association of Black Cardiologists, an
organization formed 25 years ago. She plans to lead the
organization's goal of starting an international resource center in
Atlanta on cardiovascular disease among blacks worldwide. Ofili,
44, was born in Nigeria, where she attended medical school before
moving to the United States and completing her medical residency.
(Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 6. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-DISPARITY-BLACKS _ A lack of health insurance and low
income-status are reasons often given for the disparity between
blacks and whites when it comes to health care access and disease
death rates. But even when economics and insurance are equal,
treatment is often still unequal, concludes a Morehouse School of
Medicine report released last week. (Guthrie, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-INTERNET _ A newly launched website hopes to make spring
and fall a little easier for allergy sufferers. Using your zip
code, Pollen.com majm generates a free local forecast of probable
pollen counts for the next four days. (McKenna. Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 5.
</P>
<P>
   ANEURYSM-STENT _ The aneurysm in Bob Kincaid's abdomen was
growing. The ballooning piece of his blood vessel was big enough to
pop. When aneurysms rupture in the aorta, a main artery, the odds
of survival aren't good. But Kincaid, a 77-year-old man with heart
trouble, turned to a new procedure that fixes aneurysms without
surgery and its risks. Kincaid's aneurysm was repaired from the
inside, using and aortic stent. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News). WITH
PHOTOS and ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   BRAINBOY _ PALM CITY _ When Shawn Nigam was 6-months-old, he
couldn't sit up by himself but could say words like ``ball'' and
``car.'' At 10-months, he learned the alphabet and five months
later, he could write letters. By age 2, Shawn was reading and
writing approximately 65 words.Now, the precocious 3-year-old with
a 150 IQ -- making him one of the smartest kids his age in the U.S.
-- has a penchant for the solar system, computers and new
languages. (Davies, Palm Beach Post). 34.
</P>
