<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN0307-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When I am Queen, the viewers will love my network shuffle
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Remember when NBC's Thursday lineup was
``Must-See TV?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's not must-see anymore. Instead of ``Seinfeld'' and
``Mad About You,'' the Peacock has ``Jesse'' and ``Stark Raving
Mad'' wedged in there with ``Friends,'' ``Frasier'' and ``ER.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC no longer has a must-see night, although Wednesday came
close for a while, when ``Freaks &AMP; Geeks'' briefly joined ``West
Wing'' and ``Law &AMP; Order.'' And Fox comes close on Sundays,
although ``Futurama'' ruins the good comedy flow and the last few
``X-Files'' have been disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   If I were Queen of All Prime-Time Scheduling (a job I richly
deserve on so many levels), every network would have at least one
must-see night. Every network except UPN, which is riddled with bad
sitcoms and wrestling. My solution would require moving a couple of
shows from one network to another and changing one hourlong
comedy-drama into a half-hour comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Sound drastic? Sure, but I'm Queen of All Prime-Time Scheduling,
at least for today.
</P>
<P>
   FOX'S MUST-SEE SUNDAY SCHEDULE:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``King of the Hill''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Freaks &AMP; Geeks''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Simpsons''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Malcolm in the Middle''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The X-Files''
</P>
<P>
   Fox gets this one because we're already used to seeing the
network's best shows here. We'll start with two hours of sitcoms
and wind up with ``The X-Files'' _ but we're going to make Chris
Carter promise not to write any more episodes riffing on ``Cops''
or virtual reality games. What's NBC's ``Freaks &AMP; Geeks'' doing
there?
</P>
<P>
   Since the network is clearly planning to cancel this fine teen
comedy-drama, we'll tighten it to a half-hour and sell it to Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody wins, especially viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ABC'S MUST-SEE MONDAY SCHEDULE:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Practice''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``NYPD Blue''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Once &AMP; Again
</P>
<P>
   This assumes ``Monday Night Football'' season is over, of
course. The alphabet network has three of the best dramas on TV, so
why not line 'em up? This way we get a tidal wave of emotions,
starting with shock, moving through heartache and winding up with
heartfelt.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's Must-See Tuesday Schedule:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Ally McBeal''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Get Real''
</P>
<P>
   (Only two hours because that's all Fox programs during
prime-time on weeknights.)
</P>
<P>
   The network famous for sleazy reality shows and edgy comedies
also has a couple of first-rate dramas. One is wildly fanciful, and
the other is so real it makes your teeth ache. If you are among the
millions who have not sampled the new family drama ``Get Real,''
get with it. The realistic portrayal of the married couple's
passion and communication woes can be excruciating to watch, but
isn't that what realistic drama is about? Jon Tenney and Debrah
Farentino reek of honesty in their ups and downs.
</P>
<P>
   NBC'S MUST-SEE WEDNESDAY SCHEDULE
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Third Watch''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The West Wing''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Law &AMP; Order''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to NBC's fine dramas, an argument can be made that we're
in a Golden Age for the genre. The network's top producers have
long proven capable with cops and lawyers. This year Aaron Sorkin
has proved that political drama can be riveting.
</P>
<P>
   NBC'S MUST-SEE THURSDAY SCHEDULE:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Friends''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Frasier''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Will &AMP; Grace''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Sports Night''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``ER''
</P>
<P>
   Let's restore this night to its former luster. All it takes is a
little juggling and a multimillion-dollar deal with creator Aaron
Sorkin's production company. That's how NBC would acquire ``Sports
Night,'' a truly first-rate comedy that ABC seems ready to let go.
It was off the schedule during the February sweeps and will end its
season prematurely on April 4. It would fit snugly with NBC's smart
sitcoms on this night.
</P>
<P>
   CBS'S BETTER-THAN-A-POKE-IN-THE-EYE FRIDAY SCHEDULE:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``60 Minutes''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Everybody Loves Raymond''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Cosby''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Judging Amy''
</P>
<P>
   Improved ratings notwithstanding, CBS doesn't have a lot of good
stuff on the air this season. The network _ and all of television
for that matter _ would collapse if ``60 Minutes'' disappeared, so
we'll start with that, add a couple of easy-to-take (but hardly
thigh-slapping) comedies and wind up with the best of the Big Eye's
rather tepid new dramas.
</P>
<P>
   WB'S MUST-SEE SATURDAY SCHEDULE:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Felicity''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Buffy, the Vampire Slayer''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Angel''
</P>
<P>
   Grown-ups can take the night off. Go see a movie, leave the
rowdy teens at home where they're relatively safe and turn on a
trio of fun programs that are geared just to them. All have hot
guys and gals, rock music and quirky stories.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
