<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's Georgia's turn to vote in the primaries
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Today is ``Super Tuesday'' for Georgia and 15 other
states. It's the biggest day of the year for primaries and
caucuses, which give voters a chance to help pick their parties'
candidates for president.
</P>
<P>
   Voters will choose delegates, who will go to the national
conventions to nominate the parties' candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The race is tightest among Republicans. Texas Governor George W.
Bush has 170 delegates so far. Arizona Senator John McCain has 105
delegates. It takes 1,034 delegates to lock in the nomination. A
total of 613 Republican delegates will be awarded on today.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is expected to win Georgia, which has 54 delegates. Bush
hopes to do so well today that McCain drops out of the race. But
McCain has lots of support in New England and in New York, Ohio and
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   FLOODS TRAP THOUSANDS IN AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   Rescuers from many nations are trying to save thousands of
people stranded atop roofs and trees by flooding in Mozambique. The
country, which is one of the poorest in the world, is on the
southeastern coast of Africa. Two weeks of heavy rain in early
February left Mozambique with its worst flooding in 50 years. Then
Cyclone Eline hit on Feb. 22. (A cyclone is the same thing as a
hurricane.) It dumped huge amounts of rain, ripped roofs off houses
and cut off power and water supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The government estimates that about 1 million people are without
homes. Aid officials say that thousands may be dead. They say that
about half the children rescued have been separated from their
parents _ or that their parents are dead.
</P>
<P>
   Now, officials are concerned about Cyclone Gloria, another storm
heading toward Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
   ROCKER BACK ON THE FIELD WITH THE BRAVES
</P>
<P>
   Braves relief pitcher John Rocker joined his team in Florida
last week for spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker read an apology to reporters for saying mean things about
gays, minorities and foreigners during a magazine interview.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the interview, the baseball commissioner had banned
him from spring training and the first month of the season. But
Rocker appealed the ruling. An ``arbitrator'' _ a type of judge _
heard arguments from both sides, and decided to reduce the
punishment. The arbitrator ruled that Rocker should sit out the
first 14 days of the regular season. In addition, he cut Rocker's
original $20,000 fine to $500. The arbitrator did not explain the
reasons behind his ruling.
</P>
<P>
   At the team's training camp, Rocker tried to make up with his
teammates, many of whom were angry about his comments in the
interview.
</P>
<P>
   At a closed clubhouse meeting, Rocker was described as near
tears as he apologized and pleaded with his Atlanta teammates.
``Please, guys, let me play,'' he asked them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
