<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 1101EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 11:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8055 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-SPRING-BREAK-HNS &LR;      03-06 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRING-BREAK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SPRING BREAK NO VACATION FOR PARENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BARBARA HIGDON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Spring Break and graduation trips looming just ahead,
travel companies have the student market in their sights.
</P>
<P>
   Spring Break accounts for about 30 percent of that business
annually, said Elliot Veith, manager of marketing communications
for Council Travel, the international travel agency. More than 1.5
million undergraduates will take a Spring Break trip this year.
</P>
<P>
   Students with fat wallets book package trips to exotic resorts _
and that's not just college kids. Spring Break traditions have
trickled down to high school, and a trip to Disney World with Mom
and Dad just can't compare. More often, Junior and Sissy want to
hit the beaches alone.
</P>
<P>
   Where are the boys and the girls going for Spring Break?
</P>
<P>
   Florida is still first. Council Travel's figures indicate Panama
City Beach is the biggest draw, with Daytona Beach third. Cancun
ranks No. 2, followed by South Padre in Texas and Colorado's
various ski resorts at Nos. 4 and 5 in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Bikini-clad girls wave from glossy cover photos on USA Student
Travel's flier for Cancun Grad Week 2000. One relatively low price
includes air fare, seven nights' hotel accommodations and free
admission to hot dance clubs and more.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet lists many more tour companies willing to book
spring trips to Mexico. Many solicit student representatives to
distribute fliers at high schools and help pay their own way by
booking other travelers. High school kids are free to book any of
the trips _ there is no age discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   USA Student Travel's note to parents suggests that allowing kids
to travel can be one of the most rewarding aspects of being a
parent. ``Seeing your child light up as they glimpse new countries
and cultures for the first time, feeling their excitement as they
meet new friends, watching them make connections between classroom
learning and `real life''' is what student travel is all about.
</P>
<P>
   While the company's educational trips to Space Camp, Washington,
D.C., or Europe may fulfill those parental expectations, Cancun
offers more ``real life'' than some teens can handle.
</P>
<P>
   Parents may look on the whole rite with bemused indulgence _
some born of actual experience. After all, there's not much new
under the sun, is there? What's the harm in letting hard-working
kids have some fun?
</P>
<P>
   USA Student Travel's brochure clearly states the risks. It
indicates the drinking age in Mexico, for example, is 18 and
cautions there is a lack of enforcement. Company literature states
that it does not condone the use of alcohol, and that these are not
school-sponsored activities. Students younger than 18 must have a
parent's signature on the application form; however, neither that
nor the child's age is verified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though the drinking age may be lower, there is a legal age for
drinking in Mexico,'' said Jeff Trexler, sales manager for USA
Student Travel. ``Most of what is illegal in the U.S. is illegal in
Mexico. You can't go on vacation and suspend adherence to the
laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents must know their children, Trexler said. ``If they
haven't observed responsible behavior in their kids in the 18 years
they've been at home, they shouldn't expect it in a foreign
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Bullock, a licensed professional counselor whose practice
deals with families and children in San Antonio, suggested that a
child's behavior though the years will probably indicate behavior
in a Spring Break setting.
</P>
<P>
   It depends on the parent-child relationship, Bullock said. It
depends on the amount of trust and whether you have the kind of
relationship where your child will call you if there is a problem.
``If they've always pushed limits at home, and we think they're not
going to do it when we're not there, we're crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Even for parents who trust their children, there's concern about
the other dangers in an atmosphere devoid of control or
supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Trexler stipulated that USA Student Travel is merely ``a regular
travel agency. We book air, hotel and transfers.'' They do not
chaperone, though staff members try to be available to help in
emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of minor injuries requiring medical attention compounded
by language problems are frequent. Public nudity, drug use, theft
and drunkenness are common. If you want an idea of what the beach
scene is like at Spring Break, read Student Advantage's ``Spring
Break Revealed'' message board (www.studentadvantage.com) that
lists more than 100 student reviews of Cancun.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Weiss accompanied her daughter's group on a graduation
trip to Cancun in 1999 and was on the scene when a San Antonio girl
died in a fall from a hotel balcony.
</P>
<P>
   What was Cancun like?
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot imagine,'' Weiss said. ``The excess is too much for
words. I thought there would be one adult for every six kids, but
on our airplane of 339 kids, there were four 4 adults.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When the kids got off the plane in Cancun, there were little
bars set up everywhere. By the time they got on our bus, kids were
drinking Corona beer.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the bars,'' Weiss said, ``The waitresses would walk around
with a whistle. When they whistled, the kids could buy two shots of
tequila for 50 cents. They'd pour it down the kids' throats.''
</P>
<P>
   Cancun doesn't corner the market on accidents. Falls, drownings
and other injuries occur at other destinations, including South
Padre in Texas. An 18-year-old Oklahoma woman became the first
Texas Spring Break fatality of 1998 when she was struck in an
alcohol-related hit-and-run on the beach at South Padre. In 1995, a
17-year-old from Austin died after falling six stories from an
island hotel balcony.
</P>
<P>
   Although Florida remains the top destination for Spring Break,
travel there is down by 20 percent in part because places such as
Fort Lauderdale _ the setting of the 1960 Spring Break film ``Where
the Boys Are'' _ banned Spring Breakers years ago. Still, about
500,000 Spring Breakers descend on Florida Panhandle beaches.
</P>
<P>
   What should parents consider before allowing kids to go on a
Spring Break trip?
</P>
<P>
   Investigate the tour companies carefully, determine the air
carrier, read the fine print, and ask plenty of questions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Barbara Higdon is a frequent contributor to San Antonio
Express-News.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
