<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Monday, March 6, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Tuesday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NY-PRIMARY (New York) _ A neck-and-neck race among Republicans
and a last-ditch effort by a Democrat have turned New York's
presidential primary into the most suspenseful of the 16 Super
Tuesday contests. By LARA JAKES.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-PRIMARY (San Francisco) _ Two major changes in California
law transformed Tuesday's primary and prompted the presidential
candidates to briefly focus their attention here, even if their
natural instinct was to ignore this unfathomable state and its
unmapped new-economy politics. For the first time, Californians get
to vote early in the presidential primary, and they get to vote for
all candidates regardless of party. By ROBERT SALLADAY and ZACHARY
COILE.
</P>
<P>
   VETS-McCAIN (San Francisco) _Veterans from an Army battalion
that spent more time in Vietnam than almost any other during the
war have nothing but respect for John McCain, the former Navy flier
who spent six years in a North Vietnamese prison. But they're not
sure he should be president. By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PEDOPHILIA (Colonie, N.Y.) _ Detective Lt. Thomas
Breslin gingerly taps a keyboard as he converses in an Internet
chat room with an older man from Long Island. Breslin's undercover
screen name isn't enticing _ it's actually very plain _ and when
asked, the detective tells the man that he is a 14-year-old female
just home from school. Within seconds, the man has downloaded a
naked photograph of himself to Breslin's computer and types a
message to the fictitious teenager: ``So you like older guys? ...
You'd be my secret.'' Welcome to the new era of pedophilia, where
predators no longer risk staking out playgrounds or video arcades.
By BRENDAN LYONS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TATTOO-REMOVAL (San Francisco) _ Generations of parents have
warned their children about tattoos. It's painful to put them on.
There's the risk of infection. And, once on, it's too late for
regrets because a tattoo can never come off. That's when it's time
to visit someone like Dr. David Laub, a board-certified
dermatologist and cosmetic surgeon, who can remove a tattoo. By
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The treasures of the newest
Bay Area recreation lands, waters and wetlands are known to few,
yet are surveyed without hardly a thought from afar by thousands
each day. This area covers 13,000 acres, highlighted by 10,000
acres of wetlands and an intricate web of waterways that can be
accessed by canoe, kayak or power boat, along with dirt roads on
levees that can be used as trails that are ideal for biking, hiking
and birdwatching. There are also several of the better shoreline
fishing spots in the region. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPRING-BREAK (Undated) _ Students with fat wallets book package
trips to exotic resorts _ and that's not just college kids. Spring
Break traditions have trickled down to high school, and a trip to
Disney World with Mom and Dad just can't compare. More often,
Junior and Sissy want to hit the beaches alone. And Florida remains
a popular destination. By BARBARA HIGDON.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA (Havana, Cuba) _ Two words of advice on traveling to Cuba:
Go. Now. Go before Burger Kings mar the Malecon or someone slaps up
a Gap at the Plaza de la Revolucion. Go while Russian-built Ladas
still whisk past the plaza's mammoth image of Che Guevara. Catch a
fading glimpse of the Western Hemisphere's last Communist state for
better and for worse. Yes, some things are better. And many things
are worse. By KATE GURNETT.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ One month a Republican, and I
can't wait to get back to the party of Hillary and Bill and Al and
the other Bill, the one who used to have an outside shot. That's
how painful this presidential primary has been. How backward is the
Republican Party? The GOP has taken us into a new millennium with a
primary based on religious war - and between different groups of
Christians, of all things. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The only ballot-measure petition
I'll ever sign is one that proposes a moratorium on ballot
measures. Each California election gets worse. The list of complex,
confusing propositions grows more unwieldy. Millions of dollars are
wasted as big industries like tobacco or insurance put self-serving
propositions on the ballot and ragtag citizens groups fight them.
By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
</TEXT>
