by e-mail. Please specify that you want the art when you order the
article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``e'' entertainment news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By KEVIN WEST  
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Under the bright Southern California sky, a black Mercedes wired
with three phone lines speeds down the Ventura Freeway into the San
Fernando Valley. Its destination is a small '70s-era tract house in
Woodland Hills, where Gwyneth Paltrow is just waking up from a nap
to film a scene in her next Miramax movie, ``Bounce,'' costarring
Ben Affleck and directed by Don Roos (``The Opposite of Sex'').
</P>
<P>
   In the back seat of the limo, Miramax co-president of production
Meryl Poster clutches her cell phone, which is quiet for a moment.
Her first stop of the day, she explains, will be an easy one,
because the Oscar-decorated stars of ``Bounce'' are surprisingly
low-maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a happy set,'' she says. ``They're consummate
professionals. I don't need to be holding their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   All the same, whenever talent like Gwyneth and Ben are involved,
it's prudent for the studio brass to ``show support,'' as Poster
says. So for the duration of the nine-week shoot, she has relocated
with her family from New York's Upper East Side to a snug house in
Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   In the previous year, she had also traveled to Massachusetts for
``The Cider House Rules,'' on which she served as executive
producer. Then she headed to Italy for ``The Talented Mr. Ripley.''
</P>
<P>
   If Harvey Weinstein is the demanding father in the Miramax
family, then Poster is the understanding mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meryl is Harvey's relationship person,'' Paltrow says.
``Without Meryl, Harvey wouldn't get anywhere, bossing everybody
around. Meryl is there to smooth it over.''
</P>
<P>
   Poster diplomatically adds that Weinstein ``has great
relationships with actors. I have great relationships with
agents.''
</P>
<P>
   But Paltrow clearly counts on Poster for peace of mind. The
first word out of her mouth when she emerges from her dressing room
is ``Meryl?'' And between takes, Gwyneth gravitates toward the
older woman _ whispering in her ear, hugging her and using her as a
leaning post for stretching exercises.
</P>
<P>
   During crew lunch, the two recall that they first crossed paths
at an audition around 1991, then quickly became pals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw her on `Mrs. Parker and the Vicious Circle,''' Poster
recalls. ``I thought there was something in her.''
</P>
<P>
   Poster used to invite the actress to premieres, and they
attended the Toronto Film Festival together.
</P>
<P>
   ``She protected me from Robert Downey Jr.,'' remembers Paltrow
with a laugh. ``I do come from a pretty nice family.''
</P>
<P>
   The decisive moment for Paltrow _ and for Miramax _ soon
followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harvey said, `If you do ``The Pallbearer,'' then I'll give you
``Emma,'' ' '' Paltrow recalls. ``As usual, Harvey got his way.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Paltrow has stuck with the studio far longer than
she has stuck with her boyfriends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live in New York _ I don't have personal relationships with
any other studios,'' she says. ``Things just grew and grew, and I
was here.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said of Poster's rise. She arrived at Miramax
from the William Morris Agency at the moment when the scrappy
independent film company had its first major hit, ``Sex, Lies, and
Videotape.'' It was a bumpy landing for Poster, who started as
executive assistant to Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first week I was there, I quit,'' she recalls. ``I hated
it. The pressure was so intense.''
</P>
<P>
   But Poster succeeded in making herself indispensable to
Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company grew so fast that as his assistant I was going to
lunch with Daniel Day Lewis,'' she remembers.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later, she is still Weinstein's shadow. ``My wife
calls her my day wife,'' Weinstein says.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the movies on which she was executive producer _
``Cop Land,'' ``The Pallbearer,'' ``Wide Awake'' and ``Marvin's
Room,'' in addition to ``The Cider House Rules'' _ have been
lackluster at the box office, Poster has proven herself a keen
scout for unknown talent. Most recently, she signed Jason Biggs to
a two-movie deal before ``American Pie'' made him a youthful
commodity.
</P>
<P>
   And while Poster may have mastered the cozy den-mother schtick
with her young stars, Weinstein stresses that she's a formidable
presence in the office, where it really counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meryl is a firecracker,'' he says. ``She kicks ass. Every day,
she starts with me and works her way up.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Kevin West is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 1152EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8069 &Cx1f; ttf-z
r l BC-HOLLYWOOD-DEN-MOTHER-     03-06 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-DEN-MOTHER-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERYL POSTER: MOTHER SUPERIOR  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine,
contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE showing Meryl Poster is available FREE OF CHARGE
to purchasers of this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY
by e-mail. Please specify that you want the art when you order the
article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``e'' entertainment news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
