</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-FASHION-STAKES-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSCAR PREVIEW: THE FASHION STAKES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from Women's Wear
Daily, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``e'' entertainment news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By MERLE GINSBERG  
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   It's that time again. On Feb. 15, the Oscar nominations were
announced. Suddenly, five women underwent more stylistic scrutiny
than any supermodel or society girl ever has.
</P>
<P>
   Designers in New York, Milan, Paris and Los Angeles dropped what
they were doing to take note of these ladies, who are suddenly
Fashion's Most Desirable _ at least until March 27.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? One of these candidates could emerge as the next
Gwyneth Paltrow, a celebrity who gets as much attention for her
talent as she does for her sense of style. After all, it's not a
bad runway to show off the new trends for evening: only about a
billion people will be watching.
</P>
<P>
   No designer worth his or her sequins could ever hope for better
product placement _ a dress on an Oscar nominee is better than
having a commercial on the Superbowl.
</P>
<P>
   But will the first Oscar ceremony of the new millennium be any
different than the usual frenzied parade of ballgowns?
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the worst things,'' Tom Ford notes, ``is seeing a dress
wear an actress rather an actress wear a dress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger,'' says noted New York celebrity hairdresser John
Sahag, ``is that in looking glamourous, many actresses end up
looking old fashioned.''
</P>
<P>
   I decided to take a poll of fashion experts _ the designers,
hair stylists, makeup artists, clothing stylists, retailers and top
fashion editors _ to see what advice they can offer this new Top
Five.
</P>
<P>
   Some liked the challenge of glamming up the more serious
actresses, like Janet McTeer, Meryl Streep and Annette Bening.
``I'd love to see them in classic looks, sort of modernized Grace
Kelly,'' offers Jeanine Lobell, creator of Stila Cosmetics and a
veteran of Oscar makeup. ``If women like that do too much and get
too trendy, it's hard to pull off.''
</P>
<P>
   Most everyone agrees with Barneys New York creative director
Simon Doonan, who says: ``The general consensus is, it's time for
something new!'' That means no more ballgowns, beaded sweater sets,
evening separates, too-tight clothes, and death to the pastel
pashmina. But what else do Oscar fashionistas have up their silken
sleeves?
</P>
<P>
   Here, some pointers from the pros.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANNETTE BENING, for ``American Beauty'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She's always had the body and the swagger to wear anything, but
Annette Bening is loyal to one man: Giorgio Armani. She usually
wears a black column dress or black evening tuxedo. This year, she
has another requirement: on March 26, she'll be nine months
pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   DONNA KARAN: ``I want to dress Annette Bening. I like the red
evening column with a draped neckline that was a knockout on our
fall runway. I can seriously see Annette Bening in this, in either
the red or the black. I love dressing her. I think she has stature
_ divine! She is an American beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   VALENTINO: ``Even though I have not seen all the movies and I'm
not familiar with all the actresses, I believe Annette Bening has
an amazing and perfect American style.''
</P>
<P>
   AMY SPINDLER, New York Times Magazine: ``Annette Bening pretty
much always wears Armani. She's like the first lady of Hollywood
and she should dress like a first lady.
</P>
<P>
   PAMELA DENNIS: ``I love Annette, but I heard she's not going
because of the pregnancy. She's a classic beauty. Between her,
Julianne Moore and Hilary Swank, you can't do better than those
three. Not only do I respect them as artists, they also have
amazing bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   VERA WANG: ``In all fairness to Annette Bening, she's been
pregnant for eight months and she still managed to look elegant at
the Golden Globes. But I don't think for her it's a year she'll be
making a major fashion statement.''
</P>
<P>
   PHILIP BLOCH, stylist: ``Annette likes Escada. I'd suggest
something cashmere. Maybe Randolph Duke. They're pretty, they're
comfy, they're sexy. I did one for Cindy Crawford when she was
pregnant. Thank God we're not in the days of having to hide it any
more.''
</P>
<P>
   CAROL SHAW, makeup artist, did Bening's makeup for the recent
Vanity Fair cover: ``I think she's just naturally luminescent. I
would do her either very understated or with a shiny red lip. Very
Old Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   SALLY HERSHBERGER, hairstylist: ``She always looks great, but
I'd like to freshen up Annette Bening's look a little. I'd brighten
up her color and smooth her short hair into an Audrey Hepburn-type
of style.''
</P>
<P>
   MARK GARRISON, hairstylist: ``I'd like to see her with
chin-length hair, with lots of layers. She needs slightly more
volume and movement in her hair. She's very, very sexy, but with
hair that's too extreme _ too short, too full. I'd also like to see
more of an amber-copper mix with her color. I'd also give her long
bangs.''
</P>
<P>
   HAL RUBENSTEIN, InStyle: ``Annette Bening dresses older than she
is. She wears Armani and Escada, and it's not the designs, her
choices are a little matronly. She doesn't have a typical face. Her
hair is too big. This is a woman who is more unique looking. She's
very sexy yet she doesn't dress sexy at all. I wish she would. She
has a great capacity for seduction.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JULIANNE MOORE, for ``The End of the Affair'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Julianne Moore always manages to set off those amazing red locks
with of-the-moment looks _ by Prada, Dolce &AMP; Gabbana, Ralph Lauren
_ without ever looking too fashiony or contrived. She walks the
line between fashionable and subtle without ever falling on her
heels.
</P>
<P>
   TOM FORD: ``Julianne Moore has the greatest style. I'd love to
dress her.''
</P>
<P>
   VALENTINO: ``Julianne Moore is sexy and glamorous and she's the
one I'm most curious about.''
</P>
<P>
   TOMMY HILFIGER: ``I think Julianne Moore looks very good in
casual. I'd like to see her in our leather jeans and a cashmere
turtleneck.''
</P>
<P>
   VICTOR ALFARO: ``I'd put Julianne Moore in a simple dress in a
vivid color, perhaps violet to play off her red hair. She's so
alluring and sexy.''
</P>
<P>
   HEIDI WEISEL: ``I have a beautiful brown cashmere dress in the
collection that would look great with Julianne Moore's red hair and
white skin. She should wear something fitted and sexy.''
</P>
<P>
   MARK GARRISON, hairstylist: ``For me, Julianne Moore is the
ultimate. You don't see many redheads on the screen. I would keep
her hair long, at about collarbone length, but I'd give it a bit of
angle between the cheekbone and jaws, with some long wispy layers
for movement. Her color is awesome _ I wouldn't change a thing
there.''
</P>
<P>
   BRAD JOHNS: ``Julianne Moore is an example of the perfect
redhead. She should always stay with the reds, but I would play
with red seasonally on her _ for a winter show like the Academy
Awards, I'd make her a rich auburn, and in the summer, I'd do a
gorgeous strawberry shade.''
</P>
<P>
   JAMES PURCELL: ``We need to get her to look more like a
glamorous actress than a Gucci ad. I would put Moore in something
neither over-the-top nor overly beaded, but simple and elegant with
a more dramatic hairstyle.''
</P>
<P>
   HAL RUBENSTEIN, InStyle: ``Of all the actresses nominated for
Best Actress, Julianne Moore likes clothes the most. She wears
Prada and Ralph and looks that are very simple. However, when Moore
wore a Ralph Lauren gown, the back was cut too close to the sides.
But she's very savvy not to wear looks that are too billowy or too
full. She always looks fuller than she is.''
</P>
<P>
   ANDRE LEON TALLEY, Vogue: ``Julianne Moore could go vintage. She
could look great in a Henry James dress. I would suggest she go to
Galliano. She should have major impact on the red carpet. She's
just so beautiful. She should do a Victorian Henry James look.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JANET MCTEER, for ``Tumbleweeds'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-1-inch British actress and Tony Award winner (for ``A
Doll's House'' on Broadway in 1997) is an enigma to designers but
says that what she'll wear to the Oscars is at the bottom of her
priority list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure somebody will come up with something nice for me to
wear,'' she said recently. ``I wore all British things to the
Golden Globes. Or I could be the first woman to wear pants to the
Oscars. But you don't often get to wear a really fancy frock in
your life, do you? So bring on the fancy frocks. I do hope all the
designers come calling. Stand in line, matey!''
</P>
<P>
   VERA WANG: ``Somebody I'd like to see make an effort is Janet
McTeer, because she's so sensual and so sexy in that film, and
she's someone who could look even better at the Academy Awards. She
has an incredibly sensual body. At the Golden Globes, she looked
like she wanted to escape it. I'm thinking something minimal but
beautifully cut, sophisticated and sensual.''
</P>
<P>
   HAL RUBENSTEIN, InStyle: ``Janet McTeer is a British actress who
blew everybody off the map when she did `A Doll's House.' She's a
very full-shaped lady, and tall, and designers should be aware of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   BRAD JOHNS: ``Janet McTeer needs to do something dramatic for
the Oscars, because a lot of us don't know her well. If she does
something really different, it'll make everyone wake up and say `Oh
my God, that's her?' I'd cut her hair _ which is too long, by the
way _ very short, and I'd bleach it beige. Then I'd do a beige gown
and taupe lips. Then, I guarantee, everyone would be talking about
her after the show because she'd look so fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   ANDRE LEON TALLEY, Vogue: ``Janet McTeer is a very handsome
woman. She wore a twin set with a skirt with a bit of a dramatic
train to the Golden Globes. For an English woman, she looked
fantastic. She shouldn't try to upstage herself if she did well at
the Golden Globes. She looked very handsome.''
</P>
<P>
   JOHN BARRETT, hairstylist: ``Janet has a stunning face. I styled
her for the Golden Globes, and I brought out her face, using her
hair as an accessory. I also added a little red to her hair. I'd
like to see her do something similar for the Academy Awards.''
</P>
<P>
   JESSICA PASTER, stylist: ``The woman has so much presence. I'd
love to see her in something by Oscar de la Renta _ she's so
statuesque.''
</P>
<P>
   PHILLIP BLOCH, stylist: ``Someone like Janet McTeer, she's
waiting to be discovered. With her I would go with a beautiful
Badgley Mischka or Randolph Duke. She doesn't have to be
unpredictable. I love the fact that she's not a young starlet or an
older actress. I don't see her in something sexy, sexy. Maybe
Valentino or Armani. They're going through the Valentino archives.
I'm waiting for the sketches. Maybe something from the '40s. Or
there are some really great things from Chanel Couture. I could see
her in something fresh and spring-like.''
</P>
<P>
   ART LUNA, hairstylist: ``English women have these weird hairdos.
She would look so great with a short haircut. She has a
great-looking neck, that beautiful length that so many women don't
have. I'd do even a low ponytail with hair extensions at the nape,
emphasize the face and neck. That English look is such stoic
beauty. The more you add, the worse it looks.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MERYL STREEP, for ``Music of the Heart'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is Streep's 12th Academy Awards nomination, which makes her
the most nominated female ever, tying with Katherine Hepburn.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Meryl may have every bit as much talent as Hepburn _ but
if only she had half as much style. Maybe after 11 times at the
Oscars she'll finally get it right. As Tom Ford reiterated, ``Meryl
Streep may be brilliant, but fashionwise, she needs a little
help.''
</P>
<P>
   DONNA KARAN: ``I love Meryl,'' said the designer, scanning the
racks in her showroom for an example of the look she would
prescribe. She pulled out a turtleneck dress and declared it right,
with a few alterations: ``Just simple and beautiful, down to the
floor.''
</P>
<P>
   VALENTINO: ``Meryl Streep is above and beyond fashion and her
style matches her personality: warm, elegant and superior.''
</P>
<P>
   ANDRE LEON TALLEY, Vogue: ``Meryl Streep should go with
something very classic. She should do the Park Avenue Matron look
and wear a marvelous twin set, maybe an embroidered and embellished
sweater and full skirt, preferably Oscar de la Renta.''
</P>
<P>
   AMY SPINDLER, New York Times Magazine: ``Meryl Streep should
wear Michael Kors. It plays up to her sexiness. She's been playing
it down and needs to play it up. Or, she should wear Celine. Her
hair should be over one eye. Kors knows how to give the ladies of a
certain age some confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   ART LUNA, hairstylist: ``I'd like Meryl Streep to cut her hair
off a bit, something off the shoulders, short around her face. Not
anything fancy, not extremely trendy. Something along the way of
very chic, above the shoulder. Then the weight line would be at the
right length.''
</P>
<P>
   PHILIP BLOCH, stylist: ``Meryl Streep's been looking heavier. I
hope she'll be a little more glamorous at the Oscars. You don't
want her to look like the mother of the bride. I'd love to try
something a little corsety: emphasize the cleavage, suck in the
waist, push up the breasts. I rarely do black, but in this case I
might.''
</P>
<P>
   PAMELA DENNIS: ``I always wanted to dress Meryl Streep because I
respect her so much as an actress. She hasn't come off as sexy
lately, but I think she can be classy and sexy at the same time.''
For Streep, Dennis suggested a beaded white robe with pants.
</P>
<P>
   RANDOLPH DUKE: ``I'd liven up her look with a tailored jacket
and a wonderful skirt. I've spent time on the red carpet and I've
seen photographers and journalists clamoring for a quote from
Portia de Rossi, when Meryl Streep comes in and no one pays
attention to the greatest actress of our time. That's incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   HEIDI WEISEL: ``Meryl Streep is a great actress, but I think she
could use a little help in the fashion department. I'd love to make
her look glamorous and beautiful in a black strapless gown with an
A-line skirt.''
</P>
<P>
   MARK GARRISON, hairstylist: ``Of all the nominees, she's the one
that I'd most like to make over. First, I'd give her shorter hair _
something about chin length, keeping the ends soft and sexy,
something with a little volume so it's not just stuck to her head.
I'd keep her as a blonde, but give her some brighter highlights for
some depth.''
</P>
<P>
   BRAD JOHNS: ``Meryl Streep is the USA's perfect blonde. She can
wear any color blonde. If I were coloring her, I'd do a dark blonde
base with lighter tones in front and a little darker in back _ sort
of a surfer-girl shade. Her hair is too long right now.''
</P>
<P>
   VICTOR ALFARO: ``I suggest a look that's clean and simple and
something she's comfortable with, even if it's not fabulous. She
should look like herself. At this point, it doesn't matter what she
wears.''
</P>
<P>
   HAL RUBENSTEIN, InStyle: ``Meryl Streep is the one who needs the
most help. I don't think she cares enough. Maybe she should wear
Oscar de la Renta. He doesn't sacrifice a woman's elegance while
trying to make them look modern.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HILARY SWANK, for ``Boys Don't Cry'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She's this year's Oscar It Girl, with all the dream elements a
designer's looking for: tall, thin, hip, stylish, great looking,
has talent _ and a good bet to win.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Karl Lagerfeld, Donatella Versace and Tom Ford have put
her on the ``Must Dress'' list. As InStyle's Hal Rubenstein puts
it: ``Hilary Swank will be drowning in dresses.''
</P>
<P>
   ANDRE LEON TALLEY, Vogue: ``Hilary Swank has the greatest style.
She set the tone at the Golden Globes in a black Versace, and it
was a major coup for her and for Versace. She should stick with the
tried-and-true formula.''
</P>
<P>
   SIMON DOONAN, Barneys New York: ``It would be great if Hilary
Swank wore Comme des Garcons, or better yet, vintage Comme des
Garcons! My advice for the Oscars is vintage, vintage, vintage.
Hilary Swank could wear something vintage like a Dior `New Look'
dress.''
</P>
<P>
   VALENTINO: ``Hilary Swank is changing her look so as not to be
framed with the character of her movie. I know her well _ she
attended my couture show in Paris and I'm happy to help her
again.''
</P>
<P>
   RANDOLPH DUKE: ``I would pick Hilary Swank (to dress), because
she'll get the most attention _ and this is no secret _ it's all
about who will get the most attention.''
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTINA PERRIN: ``I think Hilary Swank has the most fantastic
body and that beautiful short, cropped hair. She should wear
something very sleek and dark red.''
</P>
<P>
   CAROLINA HERRERA: ``I would like to see Hilary Swank in
something different beside a slinky embroidered dress. A red
strapless dress would be beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   VICTOR ALFARO: ``Although Hilary Swank glammed it up in Versace
Couture at the Golden Globes, I think she should wear a satin
tuxedo for a feminine/masculine play. I don't really want to see
her in a ballgown or a long dress.''
</P>
<P>
   JESSICA PASTER, veteran Oscar and Hollywood stylist: ``I have
the thrill of dressing Hilary for the Oscars this year! I think
she's our young Mia Farrow, with a sensuality about her that's the
girl next door with a little edge. I am thinking about color this
time. The Golden Globes was Hilary's first time out. I predict
she's gonna have a little more fun at the Academy Awards. We're not
married to one designer.''
</P>
<P>
   JEANINE LOBELL, Stila Cosmetics and veteran Oscar makeup artist:
``I'd like to work on Hilary Swank. I just like the way she looks
and I think that she doesn't need a lot of makeup. She's the kind
of person you'd put one thing on _ a little eye or a little lip _
she's not someone you'd like to paint everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   JOHN SAHAG, hairstylist: ``Hilary Swank's hair looks like it's
growing out from the film. I definitely think that now that she
finished her movie she could go back to being feminine: grow the
sides, fringe, and back out, and go for something messier and more
tousled. I think that would be a nice contrast for the public to
see.''
</P>
<P>
   MARK GARRISON, hairstylist: ``Hilary should consciously play
against the androgyny we've seen of her to show her versatility.
I'd take her hair a little longer. I'd also give her soft bangs
that she could brush to the side, and layer her hair a bit on top
for volume. I'd also like to see her with some caramel highlights;
they'd give her hair a little sparkle and make it a little more
electric.''
</P>
<P>
   BRAD JOHNS, celebrity colorist, Avon Centre: ``Because she
played a boy in `Boys Don't Cry,' I'd tell her to arrive at the
Oscars totally femmed out _ big red lips, honey-colored hair,
something really high gloss, high glam. I'd dress her in a gorgeous
Badgley Mischka dress and get Kevyn Aucoin or Laura Mercier to do
really glamorous makeup on her.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Merle Ginsberg is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 1214EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8096 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-NARCOLEPSY-STUDY-ART-     03-06 1393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NARCOLEPSY-STUDY-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET SLEEPING DOGS ARISE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    TWO COLOR SLIDES are available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By JACK McCLINTOCK  
 c.2000 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   When Emmanuel Mignot opened the door, a dachshund bounded into
the basement room at Stanford University's Sleep Research Center.
</P>
<P>
   Across the room, a dozen men and women exchanged nervous
glances. Now they watched as Mignot's associate, Seiji Nishino,
reached for his research tool: a can of dog food.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allez Beau teckel!'' said Mignot, a native of Paris, as he
knelt to rub the dog's belly.
</P>
<P>
   Beau seemed an excitable but ordinary dog. His regular food was
dry pellets. But today, Beau would get canned dog food _ a special
treat.
</P>
<P>
   Nishino spooned the wet food onto the floor, and Mignot cooed,
``C'est de la bonne viande.'' Beau perked up, trotted happily to
the food, sniffed, rolled his eyes in pleasurable anticipation _
and dropped to the concrete, limp as an empty sock.
</P>
<P>
   The visitors, members of a narcolepsy support group from
California's East Bay area, awwwwwww-ed in sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most dramatic symptoms of narcolepsy, the disorder in
which sleep instantly overwhelms a person during the day, is
collapse triggered by excitement or strong emotions. So what
happened to Beau, a narcoleptic dog, did not surprise the people in
the room.
</P>
<P>
   As a lab researcher with a Ph.D. in molecular pharmacology,
Mignot believes he has finally discovered the key to understanding
narcolepsy. Last August, Mignot announced that he and others
experimenting with a colony of narcoleptic dogs had identified the
gene that causes narcolepsy.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, a few weeks later molecular geneticist Masashi
Yanagisawa and his colleagues at the Howard Hughes Medical
Institute and the University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center
announced they had found a closely associated gene in mice.
</P>
<P>
   Both groups of scientists believe their discoveries could soon
lead to an effective treatment for the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Narcoleptics are not the only ones for whom the new findings
offer cause for hope. Ultimately millions of Americans, including
everyone who has insomnia or is overweight, could benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Sleeping and eating are linked both behaviorally and
evolutionarily. When Yanagisawa found the sleep gene in mice, he
was studying a gene for eating. They turned out to be the same.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the identification of the gene could also lead to
the creation of drugs to suppress appetite and fight obesity. Drug
companies are already working on it.
</P>
<P>
   In the faulty gene Mignot and Yanagisawa uncovered, a
straightforward biogenetic mechanism has gone awry. A normal cell
has chemical receptors on its surface that link up with specific
molecules generated by the body and control the timing of such
functions as eating and sleeping. If the receptor genes don't work
(as in narcoleptic dogs), or if the chemical isn't produced (as in
the mice), things go wrong. The challenge is to discover how the
mechanism breaks down in narcoleptic humans and then to develop
drugs that correct it.
</P>
<P>
   Narcolepsy is characterized by extreme daytime sleepiness,
involuntary sleep attacks, paralysis, hallucinations and, in severe
cases, episodes of cataplexy in which a person _ usually in the
grip of strong emotion _ suddenly loses muscle tone and goes limp.
That's what happened to Beau when he sniffed that dog food.
</P>
<P>
   Narcolepsy usually shows itself during adolescence or in the
early 20s, ``a really tough time,'' Mignot notes. ``At an age when
narcoleptics want to conform, they get so excited they fall down.''
</P>
<P>
   In one study of 500 narcoleptics, 85 percent said the disorder
had reduced their job performance, 33 percent said their
medications reduced their sex drive, 15 percent were permanently
disabled and many reported impaired memory and concentration.
</P>
<P>
   In its worst form, the malady can destroy a person's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without medication, I can hardly do anything,'' says Mali
Einen, 38. She discovered she was narcoleptic at age 24 when her
baby daughter, Kelsey, said something funny during a Christmas
celebration. At that moment, Mali suddenly collapsed ``like a
puppet with its strings cut, right into the Christmas tree,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Einen's life has changed. She was a single mom with
a successful career as a hedge-fund money manager. But as her
narcolepsy grew worse, she had increasing difficulty coping with it
at work and at home. Once, passed out and dreaming that someone had
broken into the house, she woke up, dialed 9-1-1 and screamed, then
had to explain what had happened to the police.
</P>
<P>
   She hasn't worked or dated in years, and only medication keeps
her alert enough to get through the day. She and Kelsey, now 16,
live alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been lonely,'' she says resignedly. ``Life is lonely.''
</P>
<P>
   What we call narcolepsy was first noted by French physician
Jean-Baptiste Edouard Gelineau in the 1880s. Normal people remain
wakeful during the day, then pass through three stages at night:
wakefulness, non-REM sleep and REM sleep _ in that order. REM
sleep, named for the rapid eye movements that accompany it, is the
dreaming stage of sleep. In narcoleptics, however, REM sleep
arrives out of order. Usually triggered by emotion, it abruptly
follows the wakeful stage, and the person slumps into a waking
dream.
</P>
<P>
   So far, even the best available drugs treat only symptoms.
Amphetamines and other stimulants keep the narcoleptic awake;
antidepressants fight off cataplexy.
</P>
<P>
   Einen took Ritalin for a year, then found she was building a
tolerance to it. So she switched to Dexadrine, an addictive
stimulant she has relied on for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   At night, Einen now takes an experimental drug, gamma
hydroxybutyrate, which she says knocks her into a deep, restorative
sleep, but only for two or three hours. Then she has to get up and
take another dose. ``I still need naps,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Mignot's research has shown that dogs inherit narcolepsy much
like human beings do; some siblings get it and some don't. For a
decade, Mignot and his colleagues have scrutinized the dogs' DNA,
comparing it with that of normal littermates until, in 1998, they
narrowed the defect down to a single chromosome.
</P>
<P>
   All the complex set of symptoms that add up to narcolepsy
results from tiny changes in that single gene, a receptor in the
dogs' brains intended to receive molecular signals from chemicals
called hypocretins, also known as orexins.
</P>
<P>
   Think of brain cells as rooms with locks called receptors on
their surfaces and a hypocretin as a key that is also a stimulant.
In a normal animal, the hypocretin hooks up with the lock, opens it
and stimulates it to increase electrical activity _ to be alert.
Without the receptor gene, however, the key won't open the lock and
can't stimulate the brain cell. That's what's wrong in the dogs.
</P>
<P>
   In Yanagisawa's mice, the receptor is present but the hypocretin
isn't. In other words, the lock has no key. But the effect is the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Will it be the same in humans? And can we use the information to
help narcoleptics? Mignot thinks so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to find drugs that can replace or block or mimic the
effect of the molecule like hypocretin,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Einen remains positive, grabbing 40 winks
whenever she must during the day. She's easy to spot, she says:
``I'm the weirdo in the Burger King parking lot with the doors
locked and the seat pushed back, taking a nap.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Jack McClintock is a contributing editor to Discover magazine.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 1227EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
