<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8102 &Cx1f; sci-z
r l BC-RUNNING-SHOES-ART-NYT     03-06 1353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUNNING-SHOES-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOEING THE ATHLETE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    FOUR COLOR SLIDES are available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By KAREN WRIGHT  
 c.2000 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   When he's not dashing down the fast lane at a track meet or
practice, 22-year-old sprinter Rahim Sajan runs for the sake of
science.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Calgary's Human Performance Laboratory, he
stands patiently, one hairy and muscular leg extended, while small
silver balls are taped to strategic sites near his hip, knee and
ankle joints.
</P>
<P>
   Today Sajan will be testing three different pairs of prototype
running shoes fitted with three different soles. As he runs the
length of a 30-meter track, the reflective balls will help video
cameras capture the movement of his joints.
</P>
<P>
   A steel platform embedded in the track's floor will measure the
force exerted when his feet touch down. Then he'll be wired for
treadmill testing, with electrodes like little metal buttons
recording the electrical signals going to his leg muscles as he
runs.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the research is to determine which sole aids his
performance most while protecting him from injury. So far, the
results are leaving common assumptions about running shoes in the
dust.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out, for example, that the impact generated during
running is not nearly as damaging as was once thought. A good
running shoe should support the natural alignment of the feet and
legs, rather than correct it. And the lesson for picking the best
shoe for you boils down to this: If it feels good, wear it. That
advice is simple, the biomechanics supporting it is not.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the Calgary team is physicist-turned-biomechanist
Benno Nigg. A longtime member of the International Olympic
Committee Medical Commission, Nigg set out to build better running
shoes back when they were still called sneakers. His earlier ideas
helped establish the prevailing belief that the main functions of
running shoes should be to properly align the legs and feet and to
cushion the impact of a heel-toe stride.
</P>
<P>
   But Nigg has since come to question these prescriptions. His
doubts began when he set out to prove that the jarring impact of
running on hard surfaces is a major cause of injury. In fact, he
and others doing similar studies found no relation between the
magnitude of impact forces and the injury rate in runners.
</P>
<P>
   Fast runners, for example, land with two or three times the
force of slower runners, yet in Nigg's studies they were injured no
more frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Running on hard surfaces doesn't result in more injuries than
running on soft surfaces. And if the impact from running was
stressful to joints, degenerative joint diseases such as
osteoarthritis would presumably be more common in runners than in
nonrunners. They aren't.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Nigg's studies show that joints are taxed most not
at the moment of initial impact but by the stress on the foot as
the runner's weight rolls from the heel toward the toes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The forces during midstance and takeoff are about three to
five times higher than the forces during landing,'' Nigg says. Thus
he concludes that impact has been unfairly blamed. ``There may be
certain cases where impact produces an injury, but it's not an
epidemic, which the sports-medicine world and the fitness world and
the shoe producers thought was the case. And we thought it too.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet runners do get hurt; two-thirds of serious runners can
expect to sustain an injury in any given year. And no one would
dispute that cushioned shoes feel better than brogans for a jog
around the park.
</P>
<P>
   So what makes one shoe better than another? Nigg believes the
answer lies in the muscle activation that not only keeps a runner's
posture stable but also counters vibrations of the soft tissue in
the body when a runner's heel strikes the ground. Studies like the
one in which Sajan takes part have shown that muscles tense up in
order to reduce these soft-tissue vibrations.
</P>
<P>
   Studies that correlate muscle activation with both comfort and
oxygen consumption show that the more work the muscles have to do
to minimize soft-tissue vibrations, the less comfortable and more
exhausting running will be.
</P>
<P>
   But Nigg also found that higher impact doesn't necessarily
create more work for the muscles. That's because soft-tissue
vibrations occur at different frequencies in different people, just
as guitar strings of different lengths and diameters resonate at
different frequencies when plucked in the same manner.
</P>
<P>
   In people, the preferred frequencies depend largely on body
weight and muscle tone. So the problem for runners is not so much
the initial force of the impact as its effects on soft tissue.
Running in a particular pair of shoes can amplify the natural
vibrations, and the runner's muscles must work harder to counteract
them.
</P>
<P>
   The cushioning in running shoes can help or hinder how the
body's muscles respond _ or, in Nigg's words, ``tune'' _ by
shifting impact frequencies away from or toward the frequency at
which an individual's soft tissue naturally wants to resonate.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why different people like different shoes,'' Nigg says.
``You can tune yourself to a certain shoe. Or you can choose a shoe
that you don't have to tune too much.''
</P>
<P>
   With the right shoe, the difference in performance, he says,
``is up to 5 percent _ that's eight minutes in a marathon.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on his findings, Nigg proposes that injuries result when
too much muscle energy is taken up with the task of countering
vibrations rather than with running.
</P>
<P>
   Proper alignment is important, too, but Nigg's ideas about
what's proper have changed since the 1970s. Thirty years ago, he
pioneered the dual-density midsole, a layer of cushioning that is
harder on the inner part of the arch and softer on the outer part,
which helps correct the excessive inward rolling of the foot,
called overpronation, that plagues as many as half of all runners.
Dual-density midsoles have become a standard feature of
high-performance shoes.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of a single model of ideal movement _ the concept
that put a dual-density midsole in every shoe _ Nigg's research
suggests that each body has its own preferred pattern of motion,
which is revealed when a person is running barefoot.
</P>
<P>
   Muscles will fight to maintain that template of barefoot
movement if shoes counteract it, Nigg says. But shoes that promote
barefoot alignment will greatly lessen the load on muscles,
improving comfort and performance.
</P>
<P>
   Working from these conclusions, Nigg and his colleagues have
assailed another standard feature of running shoes: the toe spring,
or raised forefront. Toe springs were thought to help the foot rock
forward during a stride, but they may actually impede takeoff by
immobilizing the joints at the ball of the foot.
</P>
<P>
   Nigg's main goal now is to persuade companies to group their
shoe models according to parameters such as degree of cushioning,
dynamic alignment and shape, so that consumers who have found a
model that works for them can easily spot other new or existing
models with the same properties.
</P>
<P>
   Although his colleagues are skeptical, Nigg says, the grouping
system has been well received by shoe manufacturers and could show
up on shelves within five years. Stay tuned. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Karen Wright is a contributing editor to Discover magazine.)
</P>
</TEXT>
