here as well, the freestyle-skiing competitions of aerials and
moguls. For more information, contact Deer Valley Resort, P.O. Box
1525, Park City, Utah 84060; (800) 558-3337; www.deervalley.com.
 &HT;    Close to Park City is the Utah Winter Sports Park, a 387-acre
facility that will host the bobsleigh, luge, skeleton, ski jumping
and Nordic combined. The skeleton competition is aptly named, since
competitors board a narrow sled that is really just the frame of a
stripped-down bobsled. Riders go headfirst down the icy bobsleigh
track at close to 80 mph.
 &HT;    The 1,335-meter bobsleigh/luge track has five start areas and is
one of only 12 competition-certified ``refrigeration tracks'' in
the world.
 &HT;    In addition to watching American hopefuls practice on the
bobsleigh and luge, a singular highlight is watching others try out
skeleton, which has only twice before been an Olympic sport.
 &HT;    Better yet, amateur bobsleigh enthusiasts can take a ride on the
track. Two guests at a time can ride in a four-man bobsled,
accompanied by a driver and a brakeman. The cost is $125 per person
and reservations are required. Rides on a training device called a
Rocket are $27 per person.
 &HT;    Nordic ski jumping at the Utah Winter Sports Park is available
to the public, but the jumps are not the official Olympic jumps.
Instead, participants use the K-10 meter, K-20 meter and K-40 meter
ski jumps. These jumps are designed so that the jumper is never
more than two feet off the snow.
 &HT;    The Winter Sports Park claims that this is the only public
jumping facility in North America, if not the world. The cost is
$30 for adults, $20 for youths ages 13 to 17, and $15 for those
under age 12. The price includes instruction and a helmet. For more
information, contact the Utah Winter Sports Park, P.O. Box 980337,
Park City, Utah 84098; (435) 658-4200;
http://www.slc2002.org/sports/uwsp_frame.html.
 &HT;    Northwest of Park City, near the city of Ogden, the Snowbasin
Ski Area is the site of six Olympic events, including the men's and
women's downhill, combined downhill and super G races.
 &HT;    The men's downhill course was designed by Olympic Gold medalist
Bernard Russi. It has a vertical drop of 2,770 feet that is
expected to generate race speeds of more than 90 miles per hour.
 &HT;    Amateur skiers can enjoy the vertigo-inducing course at much
slower speeds, of course. And they can enjoy Snowbasin, one of the
great hidden secrets of Utah skiing.
 &HT;    While a new base area for the Olympic Games is being built, this
ski area still has an old-fashioned mom-and-pop feel to it. It's a
large, challenging and uncrowded mountain beloved by Ogden locals,
and the views that stretch into neighboring Nevada and Wyoming are
a bonus. For more information, contact Snowbasin, P.O. Box 460,
Huntsville, Utah 84317; (801) 399-1135; www.snowbasin.com).
 &HT;    For more information about wintertime fun in this part of the
country, contact Ski Utah, 150 West 500 South, Salt Lake City, Utah
84101; (800) 754-8824; www.skiutah.com.
 &HT;    For updates on the Olympic Games, contact the Salt Lake City
Organizing Committee, 257 East 200 South, Salt Lake City, Utah
84111; (801) 212-2002; www.slc2002.org.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Everett Potter is a New York City-based free-lance travel
writer.) 
 ---- 
 c.2000 Everett Potter 
