<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: A good crop of character
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Deniece L. Barker
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   I grew up in Sudan, a small West Texas town where tumbleweeds
still tumble and antelopes still roam today.
</P>
<P>
   It's a town where farmers crawl into their weather-beaten pickup
trucks and putter snail-like into town down the narrow, two-lane
blacktop, their brake lights flickering on and off as they
carefully survey the crops that line both sides of the road.
</P>
<P>
   When the farmer sees an oncoming vehicle, he lifts a dry, crusty
forefinger off the steering wheel, then places it back down again _
his way of saying howdy to both friends and strangers alike.
</P>
<P>
   My grandpa was one of those farmers, and like the others, he too
was bound to the rich, dry ground through a type of marriage
whispered between him and God _ a marriage of pure determination,
wit and perseverance pitted against the forces of nature.
</P>
<P>
   It was a hard, grueling role, but one that my grandpa embraced
proudly and one that he proclaimed not only for himself but for his
entire family.
</P>
<P>
   Like any child, I was unaware of his struggles to make a good
crop year after year. But as I grew older, I began to see traces of
those struggles in his sun-baked face and the wrinkles buried deep
into his tired old skin.
</P>
<P>
   I could see them in the calluses that came from a lifetime of
wrapping his hands around a hoe handle as he walked up and down
each row, whacking down weeds that grew too close to the
vulnerable, undeveloped cotton.
</P>
<P>
   I saw them in his posture, a crooked spine from years of bending
and picking up irrigation pipes, then placing them back down again
just two rows over, day after back-breaking day.
</P>
<P>
   And when the storms blew in with hail the size of golf balls,
dropping like boulders from the blackened sky, I could see the
despair that would well up in his eyes, his precious crop a mangled
mess of leaves, stalks and cotton bolls floating on the soaked
ground.
</P>
<P>
   But there was tenacity in his walk as he sloshed through the
muddy rubble, surveying the destruction, and he didn't give up.
</P>
<P>
   No, my grandpa simply nursed what was left _ and for his
efforts, God rewarded him with a small but adequate crop.
</P>
<P>
   Only now at middle age do I realize the depth of those struggles
and fully appreciate the legacy my grandpa left me.
</P>
<P>
   Embedded deep inside, I embrace pride, strength, courage and,
above all, tenacity, which I'll cherish forever.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Deniece Barker lives in Longview, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915. A photo of the writer is optional. If your
article is used, you will receive $25.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
