<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8140 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      03-06 1300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSFER $100,000 TO BALANCE THIS PORTFOLIO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Q. My wife and I believe our pensions and Social Security will
provide adequate living expenses in retirement. The listed holdings
are only a security blanket. Should we reduce the mortgage debt
with funds from the above? Is our portfolio balanced? Should we
reduce some holdings, or add a bond fund? When we reach the age of
mandatory IRA withdrawals, which funds should we start with? Should
we invest discretionary money in additional funds or more secure
CDs?
</P>
<P>
   T.L., Escondido, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; A. You don't identify which Hotchkis and Wiley funds you hold,
but even so, you have a little less than 86 percent of your IRA
portfolio in three large-cap domestic funds: Fidelity's Magellan
and Contrafund, and the Janus fund. I'd cut that to about 50
percent, which would mean transferring $100,000 to other funds.
</P>
<P>
   Staying within your current fund families, I suggest you allot
that $100,000 evenly among three funds that will improve your
portfolio balance: Fidelity Mid-Cap Stock, Fidelity Select Health
Care, and Janus Venture (a small-cap fund).
</P>
<P>
   Since you will not be calling on the IRA money in the
foreseeable future, I see no particular need to add bonds. But if
your view of a security blanket is a portfolio that's going to
provide a smoother ride, reacting less to sour markets, then you
might consider substituting Fidelity Puritan for Janus Venture.
That would do less to diversify the portfolio, but it would give
you a little more exposure to bonds than the two high-yield funds
you now hold. It would also reduce the risk in my initial
suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   Even though you are comfortable financially, I suggest you keep
the CD account as an emergency backup, perhaps moving $5,000 to a
fund such as Fidelity Cash Reserves. Its check-writing privilege
will provide liquidity, without any penalties.
</P>
<P>
   As for where to invest any excess funds, that's where I would
bring the mortgage into play _ prepaying against the mortgage as
surplus funds become available.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a retired lawyer. My wife and I own winter and summer
homes valued at approximately $600,000. Our goal is to earn about
$35,000 to supplement Social Security. Lately, the two American
funds, for which we paid $100,000, have dropped about 12 percent,
and I am concerned that higher interest rates will further deplete
these accounts. How can we achieve our goal without great risk?
</P>
<P>
   C.S., Dover, N.H. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I calculate the annual yield from your portfolio at $29,037 _
not counting the unspecified IRA and the nearly negligible
dividends from your common stock. Whatever the current IRA holding,
you could move it to a GNMA fund in which you could expect it to
contribute another $3,900, based on an assumed 6.5 percent yield.
You also could swap your position in American Balanced fund, which
yields 3.67 percent, for additional shares in Income Fund of
America, which has a 5.4 percent yield, thereby adding $808 to your
income stream. That would take you to $33,745.
</P>
<P>
   To make up the final $1,255, you could follow one of two
strategies:
</P>
<P>
   Convert about $20,000 of your common stock holdings to the
fixed-income side. Another strategy _ one I usually don't endorse _
is to simply sell $1,255 worth of common stock each year. My
typical reluctance involves people who are counting on capital
gains from the stock market to supply a large part of their income.
In your case, the amount is fairly small, and since this is the one
segment of your portfolio which should bring you significant
long-term gains, I'd rather that you sell only enough to make up
that $1,255 each year, rather than sell a larger chunk to add to
the fixed-income side.
</P>
<P>
   I presumed that your money market holding is a mutual fund
account rather than a bank's; therefore, I estimated a 5 percent
yield. If that's not the case, I would quickly make it the case.
Typically, mutual fund money market accounts pay about double the
yield of average bank money market accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Next, don't be discouraged about the two American funds. Both
hold conservative value-oriented portfolios, and value is one
market segment which has been pounded lately. (And of course bonds,
which make up most of the rest of their portfolios, is another
market segment that's been unpopular lately.) But both funds have
solid long-term records. I wouldn't sell either because of recent
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you have a disproportionate amount of your assets in
real estate. You certainly could get yourself into a much sounder
long-term situation if you sold one of your residences. Selling
real estate would not only provide some growth capital, it would
also lower your tax burden, thus reducing the amount you will need
to live on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: I contribute 12 percent of my salary to my company's 401(k).
How much can I expect to have at 65, and how can I improve my
investment allocations to maximize my retirement portfolio?
</P>
<P>
   T.F., Woburn, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I'm a little confused about the $59,271 in the income fund,
and am hoping that it's a typo _ and that the money is actually
invested in Fidelity Equity-Income fund. If it is indeed in an
income fund, I would move it immediately. You're simply too young
to have the lion's share of your retirement savings in a
fixed-income holding.
</P>
<P>
   If I were selecting a portfolio from among those available in
your plan, I would put 20 percent in Fidelity Growth Company, 40
percent in Fidelity US Equity Index, and 20 percent each in
Fidelity Low-Priced Stock and Templeton Foreign. If you developed
such a portfolio, contributing $860 a month for 16 years and
realized average annual portfolio growth of 10 percent, you would
end up with $715,260 in the 401(k).
</P>
<P>
   In addition, if your IRA remained in a money market account, you
might expect it to grow to a further $29,761 after 16 years. On the
other hand, if you followed my strong advice that you move the
money to stock mutual funds, it would amount to $62,647, based on a
projection of 10 percent annual returns.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion would be to use this money to make a couple of
sector plays, dividing it evenly between Fidelity Select Health
Care and Fidelity Select Computers. Both of these funds have fairly
high risk levels, but both operate in sectors that provide a lot of
opportunity, and if you stick with them for 16 years, the odds
appear good that the 10 percent growth projection will prove
conservative.
</P>
<P>
   But if you think even that's too risky, you still should get out
of the money market account. If you're looking for a conservative
home for the IRA, but one that will still give you a fair prospect
for some growth, you might look at Fidelity Puritan fund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Money Musings: I have been watching somewhat bemusedly a
takeover fight involving Dexter Corp., of Windsor Locks, Conn., in
which my daughters have small interests. Dexter, which has been so
sound asleep for a decade or so that I wince when I remember that
it was I who bought the stock, is being wooed by International
Specialty Products of Wayne, N.J. Dexter makes much of the fact
that ISP has not specified how it proposes to finance its $45 per
share cash tender offer. I cannot fathom why Dexter stockholders
should care, provided ISP's checks don't bounce. The battle seems
to demonstrate the argument that stock markets are efficient _ when
managements don't produce for a long time, stockholders get the
small consolation of a buyout. The current management, after all,
will get the more substantial consolation of their golden
parachutes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
