<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8153 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-FAMILY-BOS &LR;      03-06 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FAMILY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FAMILY' AN ADOPTION HORROR STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
A MEMBER OF THE FAMILY 
By Susan Merrell 
HarperCollins, 350 pp., $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Had the title not been taken already (by So-Cal punk heroes
Social Distortion), Susan Merrell could have called her first novel
``Mommy's Little Monster.'' The child at the center of ``A Member
of the Family'' is, in more sympathetic terms, a profoundly
disturbed, emotionally scarred little boy at war with everyone
around him.
</P>
<P>
   But really, Michael Latham is a monster, pure and simple. What
else to call a child who beats the stuffing out of his classmates,
bloodies his teacher's face with a handful of rocks, spits at his
therapist, clamps down on his mother's finger with the ferocity of
a pit bull, smears feces everywhere, and regularly brutalizes his
sister?
</P>
<P>
   That this terrible tyke is so relentlessly incorrigible makes
``A Member of the Family'' mesmerizing _ and, at times, almost
unreadable. Though well written, it is the nightmarish, often
unpleasant story of a family's deterioration caused by an
uncontrollable child. Yet the occasional desire to walk away from
the book _ and Michael _ mirrors the dilemma faced by Chris and
Deborah Latham, who struggle with the decision of what to do with
their adopted son.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Michael is adopted, which gives this novel an especially
painful twist _ should an adopted child who proves too difficult to
handle be returned like a malfunctioning appliance? Born amid the
horrors of the collapsing Romania, Michael was 18 months old when
he was rescued from an orphanage by the Lathams. But the stain of
his early life remains.
</P>
<P>
   Before Michael, Chris and Deborah enjoyed the sort of ideal life
and marriage just ripe to be shaken to its core. They live in a big
old house in Sag Harbor, on Long Island, with their daughter,
Caroline. They are eager to share the bounty of their lives when
they accept a child, born Mihai, into their home.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as a toddler, Michael seemed ``as mercurial as an
ancient god.'' He was remote and aloof, rarely responding to warmth
and love with the welcoming ease of his sister. As the novel
begins, Michael's already 5, and his moods have grown more extreme.
Still, Deborah refuses to acknowledge the depth of his troubles.
She takes issue with anyone, including Chris, who believes Michael
is out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't give up on him. I won't,'' Deborah says, when
Michael's teacher complains of the boy's ``utter disregard'' for
those around him. ``I don't care how difficult you make it. He's my
son.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael may be her son, but he's also a cross between Damien of
``The Omen'' and Saddam Hussein. His parents try brain scans and
homeopathic therapies, but nothing seems to make a difference.
Michael isn't just unruly; he's a pint-size terrorist holding his
family hostage. If Deborah refuses to see it, her husband and
daughter are abundantly aware of the effects. Chris has withdrawn
emotionally, and Caroline yearns for the days before Michael came
to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so much better without him. You think I can't remember,
but I can,'' the 7-year-old tells her mother. ``I remember how nice
it was, before. Can't he go back?'' But Deborah isn't having any of
it. Certainly, there's something to be said about the
indefatigability of a mother's love, but at times Deborah just
seems clueless. Each day Michael inflicts some fresh hell on his
family, but Deborah insists he's getting better, that this phase
will pass as if it were nothing more serious than a spell of
bed-wetting. But as Merrell writes, ``Like a virus he was
infiltrating every cell of the organism that was their family. And
it was killing them.''
</P>
<P>
   When Merrell concerns herself with the breakdown of the Latham
family, the book is absorbing, and reminiscent of Doris Lessing's
``The Fifth Child.'' But _ perhaps because she's writing her first
novel _ Merrell doesn't trust herself enough to stay with that
story alone. Her novel bogs down with excursions into the bitter
marriage of Martin and Alice Dunn, an older couple who years before
took in a foster child, Des, who may have contributed to the death
of their son, Jack. There's the revelation of a secret from Chris's
life, also involving Jack's death, which isn't as shattering or
interesting as Merrell wants it to be.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, several cases, most prominently the lawsuit filed by
the adoptive parents of convicted child killer Jeremy Strohmeyer,
have focused on the culpability of adoption agencies in placing
children predisposed to violence or mental problems. With this
backdrop, ``A Member of the Family'' arrives with a harrowing,
ripped-from-the-headlines immediacy.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the effect is intended or not, this story may do for
adoptions what ``Psycho'' did for showers. ``Good wombs hath borne
bad sons,'' William Shakespeare wrote in ``The Tempest.'' As this
novel makes frighteningly clear, so have good adoption agencies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 1330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
