<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8155 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-STAGE-GRAY-BOS &LR;      03-06 1742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-GRAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWIMMING TO SPALDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since ``Swimming to Cambodia'' in 1985, Spalding Gray's
monologues have been one of the highlights of the theater season.
Three of them were turned into feature films, and Gray has even
appeared in a commercial for Virgin Atlantic. Friday night he
begins a three-performance run at the Emerson Majestic Theatre of
his new monologue, ``Morning, Noon and Night,'' about life with a
wife and three children in Sag Harbor, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard, then, to remember that it wasn't so long ago he was
on the periphery of the country's cultural consciousness. I first
met Gray in 1985 when I was covering television and he was
performing before the Television Critics Association at a press
event for PBS's new avant-garde show, ``Alive From Off-Center.'' If
Spalding Gray were to write a monologue about meeting Spalding Gray
it might go something like this:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As I walked through the Arizona Biltmore, the hotel that Frank
Lloyd Wright built in Phoenix, cocktail hour was beckoning. After
that, dinner and a performance by a guy named Spalding Gray, whom I
had heard about but never seen. It looked to be a night of eating,
drinking, and maybe even being made merry on a company expense
account.
</P>
<P>
   Cocktails were served beside the elegant swimming pool and as I
headed to the bar I bumped into the publicist for ``Alive From
Off-Center,'' the show on which Gray was appearing, along with
David Byrne, Laurie Anderson, and others. ``Hey, Ed, you want to
meet Spalding?'' ``Sure,'' I lied, thinking this meant I might have
to do some work.
</P>
<P>
   What did I know about Spalding Gray? A friend had tried to get
me to see him the last time he was in Cambridge, and when I asked
what he was like, my friend said, ``He's very funny. He's kind of
like Garrison Keillor with an edge.'' ``Prairie Home Companion''
was never high on my dance card, so I passed.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing I noticed was Gray's flannel shirt, and when the
publicist introduced us I expected a hippie-ish, hail-fellow folkie
like Jay O'Callahan so I put on my phony smile and enthusiastically
shook his hand, ``Hi, Spalding.'' ``Hello,'' he mumbled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any chance we'll see you back in Cambridge, Spalding?'' ``I
was just there.'' ``I know. I was out of the country. I really
wanted to see you.'' He acknowledged the lies with a nod of utter
uninterest. The ``interview'' was not going well, which was
something of a relief because now I could drink in peace, and I
bumbled my way toward a graceless exit.
</P>
<P>
   After dinner the television critics were ushered into a room
where Gray was going to perform part of ``Swimming to Cambodia.''
This was well before the movie had come out and so, like me, almost
all of my colleagues had no idea who Spalding Gray was or what they
were in for.
</P>
<P>
   Gray entered solemnly, sat down behind a desk, took a sip of
water, and started talking about taking a break from work beside a
swimming pool at a modern hotel. How bizarre _ only the one he was
talking about was in Thailand while he was shooting ``The Killing
Fields.'' More striking than the coincidence, though, was the way
he came alive. This was no Garrison Keillor with an edge. This was
Jack Kerouac with an edge. This guy who seemed nervous and
shut-down started unbuttoning the sleeves of his flannel shirt and
unleashing a torrent of near-paralyzing insecurities turned into
Zen insights, neuroses turned into perfect moments, chance
encounters turned into swirling metaphors for war and peace. As the
monologue skipped across time, he was also making hilarious fun of
people he had met, from John Malkovich to a guy sitting next to him
on the train. Uh-oh. What if his thing was standing by pools at
cocktail hour waiting for people to make fools of themselves?
</P>
<P>
   I started playing back the none-too-reliable tape in my head of
what I might have said to him. ``And then this guy I had never met
named Ed Siegel came up to me with this sycophantic grin: `Hey,
Spald, when are we going to see you in Cambridge again?' even
though he had obviously never seen me in Cambridge or anywhere else
in his life? Who did he think I was? Garrison Keillor?'' I started
worrying about whether my socks matched, if I had spilled a drink
on myself, if I had put on deodorant after the shower, whatever
else I might have done to add fuel to his monologue. I broke out in
a cold sweat as I envisioned every pair of critics' eyes turned to
me, laughing at my socks, my hair. Laughing at me! The paranoia was
uncontrollable as I imagined: ``Don't TV critics take showers?''
Gales of laughter. ``How about that comb-over?'' More laughter.
</P>
<P>
   After a while, I realized he was working from a script and had
much bigger fish to fry anyway. Now that the jokes were at other
people's expense I could sit back and enjoy Gray to my heart's
content.
</P>
<P>
   When the performance was over, many of the critics headed to the
PBS hospitality suite. (I don't mean to give the impression that
journalists are always looking for free drinks.) The others I
talked to weren't as smitten with Gray (``It went on so long . . .
) and after despairing of finding another fan (``What was he trying
to say?'') I looked on the couch and there was Gray, staring
blankly at the TV in the middle of the room. Thinking that his
abruptness at cocktail hour was just a case of preperformance
jitters, I cruised over to my new soulmate and sat beside him.
Since I wasn't reviewing the performance, I figured I could be
frank, even if it did come out like more fakery. ``That was
terrific.'' ``Thanks.'' ``I haven't seen `Swimming From Cambodia'
before. What are you going to do on `Alive From Off-Center'? He
looked alarmed. ``I'm not doing `Swimming From Cambodia' on `Alive
From Off-Center.' '' ``Yes, no, I know.'' ``I'm doing something
else.'' ``Right. I know.''
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't going any better than the last time, so I figured he
must be one of those artists who's only on when he's onstage and
headed back to my room. I did, however, become a huge fan of his,
and when he came back to Cambridge and Boston in future years I
went to see each of his monologues. Honest.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 years after meeting Gray I had switched beats, from
television to theater. The publicist from the Trinity Repertory
Company was on the phone, saying that Spalding Gray was coming to
Providence for workshop performances and was available for
interviews. Normally I shy away from interviewing people I'm
reviewing, but as this wasn't open to review I figured I had no
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Watching him perform ``Skiing to New England,'' which would
eventually become ``It's a Slippery Slope,'' I again marveled at
his ability to turn an everyday experience like learning to ski
into a combination of Buddhist beatnik metaphors: ``To be in
control you have to be out of control.'' When I remembered I was
going to have to interview him the next day, the sweats came back
as my mind started racing. ``Aren't you that television critic from
Phoenix who asked all those idiot questions? What are you doing
here?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was supposed to be a 10 a.m. interview at the glittering
Westin breakfast buffet, but I was too nervous to eat and talk at
the same time, so I got there early and had breakfast before the
interview. At 10:20 he hadn't shown so I asked the hotel operator
to connect me to his room. ``Helloooo,'' said a very tired, very
unhappy voice an octave or two lower than the voice I was
expecting. ``Spalding Gray?'' ``Yeahhh.'' ``This is Ed Siegel. I
think I have an appointment with you.'' ``What time is it?'' he
moaned. ``10:20.'' ``Ohhh, I haven't slept this long in ages.''
``Would you like to cancel?'' I asked hopefully. ``No, give me a
few minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   I was envisioning the monologue he'd be making: ``Television
critics are people who are paid to watch television, if you can
imagine that. At television critics conventions they're paid to
watch television, eat, drink, and chase celebrities. This idiot
television critic from The Boston Globe, fresh from interviewing
Boy George and Mr. T together after a press conference about `The A
Team.' . . . Ten years later I'm sound asleep in this luxurious
hotel and the phone rings and it's this same guy waking me up to
come down for an interview. . . . '' Maybe he had even done
research about prior humiliations: ``And then, while everybody else
was making out on the bus, he was too shy to ask Ruby Greenberg for
a kiss. . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   A grizzled Gray stepped off the elevator, carrying a bottle of
Poland Spring. I was dreading the interview as he got his
breakfast. We sat down, I asked him the first question, and he
proceeded to give me one of the most affable, candid, and genuinely
introspective interviews I've ever had, answering everything in
detail, and in good humor, questions about the breakup of his
marriage (part of his previous monologue), whether people dread
speaking to him for fear of winding up in his monologues (a bit of
projection, perhaps), whether he does things because they'd make
good material for monologues.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later I wondered whether I should ask the final
question, and since part of the message of the previous night's
monologue was to go for it, I decided I might as well. ``You know,
we've actually met once before when I was a television critic. Do
you remember doing `Swimming to Cambodia' for PBS?'' ``Oh yeah.''
``I can't get over how different you are. You seemed completely on
edge, and ever since I've thought of you as someone who's really
shy and who opens up only when he's onstage.''
</P>
<P>
   He seemed amused at what was obviously a completely erroneous
exercise in pop psychology and said, ``I remember it was cocktail
hour and I was angry because everyone else was drinking and I don't
drink before a performance.'' (In ``Gray's Anatomy'' he says, ``If
you don't drink, your day is just one big (he lets out a long yell)
_ Bed!''). ``I had also been up for something like 48 straight
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   I drove back to Boston wanting to call all the TV critics and
say, ``See, I wasn't such a loser'' _ and then remembered the
monologue was in my imagination. I was content that I seemed to
have good material for a feature _ and even more content that
Spalding Gray had better material for monologues than an evening
spent with critics, one in particular.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
