u e BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS &LR;      03-06 0438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``When Mountains Walked'' by Kate Wheeler (Houghton Mifflin,
$23). A remarkable first novel about a young American woman's
discovery of herself in Peru. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A Heartbreaking Work of Staggering Genius'' by Dave Eggers
(Simon &AMP; Schuster, $23). This memoir-of-sorts, about a young man
raising his younger brother, is hip, funny, wildly intelligent, and
full of narrative energy. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Bridget Jones: The Edge of Reason'' by Helen Fielding (Viking,
$24.95). She's back, still keeping a diary recording her obsessions
(calories, cigarettes, and romance), still engaging our unlikely
sympathy. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Simple Stories'' by Ingo Schulze (Knopf, $25). A novel in 29
interlocking stories about life in a small East German town,
astringently written and brilliantly crafted. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Missing World'' by Margot Livesey (Knopf, $23). A
psychological suspense story handled with acumen, a riveting sense
of timing, and a dazzlingly intelligent structure. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Enduring Roots'' by Gayle Brandow Samuels (Rutgers, $25).
These ``encounters with trees'' turn into meditations on the facts,
folklore, and myth connected with America's trees. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A Vast Conspiracy: The Real Story of the Sex Scandal That
Nearly Brought Down a President'' by Jeffrey Toobin (Random House,
$25.95). A serious yet entertaining chronicle of the late
unpleasantness. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``So I Am Glad'' by A. L. Kennedy (Knopf, $23). The shade of
Cyrano de Bergerac enters the life of a cool Scottish maid. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Gloaming'' by Alice Elliot Dark (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
$23). Stories that suggest a whole universe in a single incident. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Fasting, Feasting'' by Anita Desai (Mariner/Houghton Mifflin,
$13). A novel of youth, at home in India and in the United States. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Of No Country I Know: Selected Poems and Translations'' by
David Ferry (University of Chicago Press, $14). In his own work and
interpretations of classics, the poet's powers have deepened. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortune's Rocks'' by Anita Shreve (Little, Brown, $24.95). A
page-turner about a girl who has a tragic affair with an older
man. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Anne Morrow Lindbergh'' by Susan Hertog (Nan A.
Talese/Doubleday, $30). In search of a living moral example, the
biographer finds a woman who married the century's dominant public
hero but who craved privacy and silence. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Flu'' by Gina Kolata (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $25). A
masterly recounting of medical history, and a good mystery story
about the pandemic of 1918-19.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
