<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8159 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TRAUSCH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-06 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAUSCH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPLITSVILLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ It's not love, but it's close, and the scene usually
plays out like this: The new client, looking eager, grateful, and a
little guilty, clutches the portfolio and asks, ``But what do I
tell my other accountant?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer from the newfound CPA is practiced, firm, and kind:
``It's time for you to move on. You need someone with greater
capability _ someone who understands that you've grown.''
</P>
<P>
   The client knows how true that is, and prepares to write The
Letter _ typically the way that such breaks are made. But after all
those years and tax forms with good old Number One, the decision
still hurts. A relationship with an accountant or a financial
planner is, after all, a marriage of sorts. And divorce can be as
traumatic as it is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons given on both sides of the desk can sound painfully
familiar: ``We weren't communicating.'' ``She'd been burned before
and didn't trust me.'' ``Lack of commitment.'' ``He was fine when I
was starting out, but now, well. . .''
</P>
<P>
   Accountant Jeff Levine of Alkon &AMP; Levine PC has seen heartbreak.
He has a client who is paying to have his taxes done twice _ once
by Levine and again by the accountant the client wants to let go
but just can't. The client's old Number One may be inadequate, but
he has also fallen ill. And how can you give a guy the ax at a time
like that?
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Kahn tells another tale of heart over mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the last five years I was with my accountant that I had
to break it off,'' she says. Kahn, president of New Dimensions in
Technology, an executive-recruiting firm, had a 15-year accounting
relationship with her New York money man, but had grown weary of
the commuter partnership and wanted somebody local. Eventually, she
found a Massachusetts CPA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It broke our friendship,'' she says of her old Number One.
``We don't speak.''
</P>
<P>
   John Buono, who works in the training department of the NStar
utility company, left his acountant for Turbotax. ``He was so busy
he didn't even notice,'' Buono says.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, cruel indifference! And after one has bared all the numbers
and expressed those innermost desires for early retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no semblance of a relationship,'' says Dave Porter,
managing partner of Baystate Financial Services, remembering his
breakup with an accountant. ``No communication.''
</P>
<P>
   Porter, who is a financial planner, says focus group data have
shown him that people consider accountants, whose traditional
purview is taxes and overseeing the books, their ``most trusted
adviser, the guy in the white hat.'' The relationship often spans a
client's lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks financial planners, whose profession has developed in
the last 25 years and who generally take a broader look at a
person's goals, are more likely to experience strain with clients,
especially in this roaring economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectation level is incredible,'' Porter says. ``A client
will say, `My neighbor got a 30 percent return. How come I only got
25 percent?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes those demands can drive the money professional _
accountant or planner _ to call it quits with a client, although
that's rare. ``It happens if there is continuing tension,'' says
accountant Jim Welch, the managing principal of Needel, Welch &AMP;
Stone PC. ``When the staff keeps getting abrupt, demanding phone
calls, then it's time to break it off.''
</P>
<P>
   People change, notes Tom McFarland, president of The Darrow Co.
and chairman of the Financial Planning Association of
Massachusetts. ``Something dramatic may have happened in their
lives and they're just not the same person who first walked in the
door.'' That's when it's time for the financial adviser to say,
ever so tactfully, ``Maybe you should think about calling around
and getting somebody else.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the fiscal equivalent of ``Maybe we should date other
people,'' and that's never easy to say or accept. ``Even with a bad
relationship, it's tough,'' says Levine, the Newton accountant.
``When a client leaves, it feels like a little piece of my heart is
leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   Who says accountants are dull? Who says the ledger is cold? This
is finance, ladies and gentlemen, and it's very, very personal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Susan Trausch is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached
by e-mail at trausch(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
