<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S AN `OSCAR' REALLY WORTH?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for March 26 Academy Awards!)   (RESENDING from March 1 for those needing)  
  
 (This 425-word ``separate-buy'' story is from the February issue of
``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``e''
entertainment news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``f'' financial
news files.)  
  
 By THOMAS O'NEIL  
 c.2000 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUESTION: What's an Oscar really worth?
</P>
<P>
   ANSWER: It depends on how you look at it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 400: &LR;  &QL;  That's the sum that R.S. Owens and Co., the
Chicago-based
manufacturer, spends to create each of the 13.5-inch-tall,
8.5-pound statuettes. An Oscar is made of brittania and is coated
with layers of copper, nickel, silver, and, finally, 24-karat gold
electroplate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; $50 MILLION: &LR;  &QL;  The industry trade publication Variety estimates
that's
how much the major studios will spend promoting their Oscar
hopefuls this year. Expenses for these blitzes now include ads in
Variety and The Hollywood Reporter, parties and private screenings,
plus thousands of videotapes and DVDs dispatched to the 5,500
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1955-56, the producers of ``Marty'' actually spent more
money on the film's Oscar campaign ($400,000) than they did to make
the movie ($350,000). The tactic worked: ``Marty'' won the
best-picture award.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; $64 MILLION: &LR;  &QL;  How much last year's winner for best picture,
``Shakespeare in Love,'' garnered in additional revenue following
the Oscar nominations. The amount represented a 177 percent
increase beyond the $36 million it took in prior to the
nominations.
</P>
<P>
   $20 MILLION PER FILM: That's what Tom Hanks now commands after
having won two best-actor awards (``Philadelphia'' in 1995 and
``Forrest Gump'' in 1996.) Other members of the $20 Million Club
include Jim Carrey, Harrison Ford, John Travolta, Brad Pitt,
Leonardo DiCaprio, and Julia Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   $24 MILLION: The 1998 best-picture champ, ``Titanic,'' earned
that amount in additional box-office revenue for each _ yes, each _
of its record 11 Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   _ $2 MILLION: Not all winners have been able to cash in on their
Oscar gold in a big way. Mel Gibson's ``Braveheart'' won best
picture in 1995, but the movie's box-office revenue increased only
from $68 million to $70 million as a result.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Perhaps because the film earned most of its money when it
was released in May and then re-released in December to create
Oscar buzz. By the time the Academy Awards rolled around in March
1996, most interested moviegoers had already seen the film.
</P>
<P>
   $1.54 MILLION: The most ever paid at auction (on June 12, 1999)
for an Oscar. This was the price for the statuette awarded to
``Gone With the Wind'' for best picture in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   $0: Since 1950, Oscars have been awarded for display purposes
only. Winners must sign an agreement conferring actual ownership to
the Academy of Motion Pictures Arts &AMP; Sciences. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this 425-word ``WORTH'' magazine article, it must
be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
