<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8188 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS &LR;      03-06 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH AFFAIR WITH OYSTERS DEALT A BLOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The fishmonger sat glumly outside a cafe here in
Montmartre, pointing to the oysters he can't give away these days.
``Even you Americans aren't buying them,'' he said ruefully.
</P>
<P>
   Worse still, the French aren't buying them. This is like
Italians cutting back on pasta or Germans giving up sausage.
</P>
<P>
   Per capita, nobody in the world eats more oysters than the
French. They slurp down nearly 2 billion oysters a year. In France,
oyster farming is a $250 million a year industry that employs more
than 8,000 growers.
</P>
<P>
   But that industry is under threat like never before because of
an oil spill and the severe storms that struck around Christmas.
The winter storms ruined at least 20 percent of the oyster beds
along the Atlantic coast, according to France's National Oyster
Growers Association. To make matters worse, the tanker Erika broke
up and spilled 3 million gallons of crude into the waters off the
Atlantic coast.
</P>
<P>
   Goulven Brest, president of the growers' association, said the
government has to do more to bail out his members. In some
villages, like Fouras, halfway down the coast, all of the oyster
beds were destroyed. Growers there will not be able to harvest
another crop until 2003. ``Unless the government intervenes, a huge
number of growers will go out of business,'' Brest said.
</P>
<P>
   On land, French farmers are famous, or infamous, for their
propensity to strike or dump crops to demand more subsidies. They
have blamed their problems on globalization and have trashed or
picketed McDonald's restaurants, seeing the American fast-food
chain as a villain undermining their traditional food chain.
</P>
<P>
   But the long-term threat to the oyster industry is largely the
fault of Mother Nature, while the suddenness of the crisis is
mostly self-inflicted. The French, worried about the possibility of
contamination from the oil spill, have simply stopped eating
oysters in large numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The French agency in charge of food safety has repeatedly
assured the public that the oysters currently on the market are
safe to eat because they were harvested from the sea and put in
purified water beds months before the storms and spill. Like many
Europeans, the French apparently have little faith in, or aren't
listening to, their government when it comes to food safety.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Dupon, a fishmonger who sells shellfish to restaurants in
the north of Paris, said demand at restaurants has dropped
precipitously, in some cases as much as 70 percent. Supermarkets
are selling half as many oysters as usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the tourists; it's the French who aren't buying,''
Dupon said.
</P>
<P>
   If the oysters on sale here now are safe _ and the ones sold at
Le Sancerre in Montmartre certainly tasted good _ that does not
bode well for the industry, because the real problem will come in
two or three years with a dramatic shortage of French oysters.
While the shortfall could easily be made up by imports, the French
traditionally are leery of knockoffs of staples such as wine and
pate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had Irish oysters and English oysters,'' Dupon said.
``I don't want to be chauvinistic, but they are not as good as
French.''
</P>
<P>
   While wholesalers like Dupon face a more immediate problem posed
by consumer confidence, the oyster growers face a more long-term
threat.
</P>
<P>
   Brest says his association's members need more help than the $50
million in subsidies the government has pledged so far. Last month,
in a tepid imitation of their landlubber counterparts, hundreds of
angry oyster growers marched on the Department of Agriculture here,
demanding a bailout. Like oysters, such demonstrations seem likely
to become a staple of French life for the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   Fishmongers like Dupon, meanwhile, have to persuade their
customers that the oysters on sale are safe and tasty. That means
having to ingest them in front of doubting customers. Dupon said he
had to eat two dozen one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love oysters,'' he said, patting his stomach, ``but even for
me, that is too much.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kevin Cullen, the Boston Globe's European bureau chief, is based
in London.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
