<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN'S CANDIDACY SHOULD START LOOKING FOR A PARKING PLACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   That sputtering you hear is the ``Straight Talk Express''
running out of gas.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called phenomenon that is John McCain's campaign for the
Republican presidential nomination will soon be over _ if not this
Tuesday, then the following Tuesday. These next two rounds of
primaries should make it clear, even to the most ardent
Bush-haters, that Texas Gov. George W. Bush will be the Republican
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, McCain has been running on fumes since Bush
crushed him in the South Carolina primary. He won Michigan a few
days later, but that was a phony victory in a primary where less
than half the voters were Republicans _ and where many Democrats
who marked their ballots for McCain were just trying to embarrass
Republican Gov. John Engler.
</P>
<P>
   Motives of non-Republican voters aside, McCain's success in
Michigan was completely meaningless because he lost overwhelmingly
to Bush among Republican voters. And here's a news flash: A
candidate can't win the Republican presidential nomination without
Republican votes.
</P>
<P>
   It's such a simple premise, you can't help but wonder what
McCain was thinking about when he decided to base his campaign on
the pursuit of Democrats and independents. Maybe the answer is that
it wasn't really a decision; maybe he realized early on that
non-Republicans were his core audience and he simply went with the
flow.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. It didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't worked up till now, anyway, and there's no reason to
expect the strategy to suddenly catch fire as McCain takes on Bush
in real Republican primaries that will be dominated by real
Republican voters.
</P>
<P>
   There may be a few states _ Massachusetts, to name one _ in
which McCain's anti-Republican rhetoric will be helpful to the
senator from Arizona. That verbal nuclear warhead he fired at the
party's Christian conservatives last week may have been
well-received in some quarters.
</P>
<P>
   But for hard-core Republicans _ including those who aren't big
fans of Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell _ McCain's blast at the
religious right was another manifestation of his stated desire to
conduct a ``hostile takeover'' of the Grand Old Party.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans figure they encounter more than enough hostility
from their enemies in this country. They don't need a
standard-bearer who's even money to nod in agreement when his
Democratic opponent starts trashing the GOP in the general election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   There are other questions about McCain, of course. Questions of
hypocrisy regarding a candidate who rails against campaign finance
abuses even as he accepts contributions from lobbyists who stand to
benefit from his activities as chairman of a powerful Senate
committee. Questions about duplicity when a candidate who claims to
be a straight talker lies about campaign tactics. Questions about
the temperament of a candidate who is magnanimous when he wins but
throws a veritable tantrum when he loses.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans who are tempted to vote for McCain might want to
consider such questions. But they don't really need to; all they
need to do is consider the issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bush calls himself a ``reformer with results,'' and that's what
he is. He ran for governor on a platform of reform _ education
reform, tort reform, reform of the juvenile justice system, among
others _ and he worked with legislators of both parties to enact
those campaign promises into law. He can achieve similar results as
president _ and Republican voters know it.
</P>
<P>
   Come fall, independents and even some Democrats will finally get
the message as well. Bush is what McCain claims to be: a
forward-looking conservative who can appeal to a broad
cross-section of voters. He did it in Texas. He can do it as a
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain surge was an intriguing piece of fiction conjured up
by a fawning media and assorted opinionizers who have no use for
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   It made a good story in a campaign that originally figured to be
lacking in suspense. But the story is about to end.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
