<HEADER>
A8182 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-OSCAR-NIGHT-MOVIE-QUI     03-06 1553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-NIGHT-MOVIE-QUIZ-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A QUIZ FOR THE ALSO-RANS: ON OSCAR NIGHT, WHAT COUNTS ISN'T HOW YOU
PLAY THE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Denzel Washington in a scene from ``The
Hurricane.'') 
 By S. BURELISON  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    ``It's an honor just to be nominated.''
 &HT;    You'll hear that phrase a lot this Oscar season, as the
Academy's nominees put on their best faces and pretend they don't
care much whose name is read on March 26.
 &HT;    But four-time nominee _ and four-time loser _ Barbara Stanwyck
confessed that each loss was painful.
 &HT;    ``Anyone who says they're not is lying,'' she said.
 &HT;    Losers should take solace, however, in the knowledge that even
Oscar can make mistakes. Also-rans such as Alfred Hitchcock,
Richard Burton, Cary Grant and Stanwyck herself left behind films
that have withstood the test of time, which is far tougher than
winning any award.
 &HT;    ``It's so much fun being nominated _ everyone is a winner,''
two-time nominee Liv Ullman said. ``And then, afterward, there are
four losers.''
 &HT;    In honor of those 80 percent, try your hand at these questions
about Academy Award losers. 
 -0- 
 THE LOSING QUESTIONS  
 &HT;    1. Two actresses made history in 1998 when both were nominated
for playing the same character in the same film _ and both lost.
Who were the ladies, and what was the movie?
 &HT;    2. James Dean didn't live to experience his two nominations,
both of which he lost. For which films was he tapped?
 &HT;    3. Portraying lawyers is a good way for actors to get nominated,
but the Academy often has objected to their winning. In which films
were screen attorneys James Stewart, Spencer Tracy, Paul Newman and
Susan Sarandon reversed on appeal?
 &HT;    4. Frankly, my dear, 1939 was a great year for Best Picture
winner ``Gone With the Wind.'' Four of its performers were
nominated, with only two winning. Name the other two.
 &HT;    5. Denzel Washington's nomination for portraying boxer Rubin
``Hurricane'' Carter doesn't guarantee a win _ just ask John
Garfield, Kirk Douglas, James Earl Jones and Sylvester Stallone.
Name the movies in which they were nominated for roles as boxers,
only to be KOed by the voters.
 &HT;    6. For which film did Marjorie Main, best known as Ma Kettle,
get an Oscar nomination?
 &HT;    7. Versatility is no guarantee: What actress was nominated as a
nun in 1985 and as a floozy in 1994, but lost both years?
 &HT;    8. What a drag _ two talented actors dressed as women for their
nominated performances, but lost. Can you name the gentlemen and
their cross-dressing comedies?
 &HT;    9. Actress Shelley Winters won two Oscars out of four
nominations. In both of her losing roles, she ends up all wet. What
are the films?
 &HT;    10. John Travolta has received two Best Actor nominations in his
career, losing both. What were the films?
 &HT;    11. The votes just weren't there for Raymond Massey, Alexander
Knox and Anthony Hopkins when they portrayed American presidents
onscreen. Name the real-life commanders-in-chief they played.
 &HT;    12. ``I am big _ it's the awards that got small,'' Norma Desmond
might have said. Who was Norma, and what Best Actress nominee lost
for playing her?
 &HT;    13. Oscar perennials Meryl Streep and Tom Hanks both lost for
their first nominations. Name the films.
 &HT;    14. What leading man called his nominated performance in ``None
But the Lonely Heart'' ``a successful bit of acting,'' even if he
didn't win the statue?
 &HT;    15. What two actors, playing husband-and-wife entertainers, got
matching 1994 Oscar nominations _ and went home equally
empty-handed?
 &HT;    16. After six nominations and no gold, Al Pacino was nominated
twice in 1993. Name the films.
 &HT;    17. Who didn't get the Academy's sympathy vote for dying young
in ``Steel Magnolias'' (1989)?
 &HT;    18. Name the four actors nominated, but not voted Oscars, for
their portrayals of real-life figures Lou Gehrig, Howard Hughes,
Patsy Cline and South African activist Steve Biko.
 &HT;    19. Best Supporting Actress nominee Angelina Jolie is a rising
star, just as was her father, Jon Voight, when he was first
nominated. What film got him the nod?
 &HT;    20. Here's the toughie: There have been only two films in which
the entire cast was Oscar-nominated _ and lost. What were they? 
 -0- 
 THE WINNING ANSWERS  
 &HT;    1. In ``Titanic'' (1998), Kate Winslet was nominated for Best
Actress as young Rose, while Gloria Stuart earned a
supporting-actress nod as the elderly Rose in the film's framing
sequence.
 &HT;    2. James Dean died in 1955, only months before being nominated
as Best Actor for ``East of Eden'' (1955) and shortly after
finishing ``Giant'' (1956), for which he received his second
posthumous nomination.
 &HT;    3. James Stewart was nominated for ``Anatomy of a Murder''
(1959), Spencer Tracy for ``Inherit the Wind'' (1960), Paul Newman
for ``The Verdict'' (1982) and Susan Sarandon for ``The Client''
(1994).
 &HT;    4. Clark Gable lost out on a ``Gone with the Wind'' Oscar, as
did supporting-actress nominee Olivia de Havilland to co-star
Hattie McDaniel. Thomas Mitchell, who played Scarlett's father, won
Best Supporting Actor, but not for ``GWTW'' _ he had also played
the drunken doctor in ``Stagecoach'' (1939).
 &HT;    5. Out for the count were nominees John Garfield for the classic
``Body and Soul'' (1947), Kirk Douglas for ``Champion'' (1949),
James Earl Jones for ``The Great White Hope'' (1970) and Sylvester
Stallone for ``Rocky'' (1976).
 &HT;    6. Ma Kettle first appeared as a supporting character in ``The
Egg and I'' (1947), for which Marjorie Main was Oscar-nominated.
Main played her for seven more years in the popular ``Ma and Pa
Kettle'' series.
 &HT;    7. Meg Tilly was nominated for Best Supporting Actress for
``Agnes of God'' (1985) and ``Bullets over Broadway'' (1994), and
lost both times.
 &HT;    8. Jack Lemmon was nominated for ``Some Like It Hot'' (1959) and
Dustin Hoffman for ``Tootsie'' (1982), but both went home
empty-handed.
 &HT;    9. Winters is drowned by her boyfriend in ``A Place in the Sun''
(1951) and succumbs to a heart attack while trying to escape a
sinking ship in ``The Poseidon Adventure'' (1972).
 &HT;    10. John Travolta's first nomination was for ``Saturday Night
Fever'' (1977). His second came 17 years later, for a very
different role in ``Pulp Fiction'' (1994).
 &HT;    11. Raymond Massey was ``Abe Lincoln in Illinois'' (1940),
Alexander Knox was ``Wilson'' (1944) and Anthony Hopkins was
``Nixon'' in 1996.
 &HT;    12. Norma Desmond is the faded silent-screen star in ``Sunset
Boulevard'' (1950), portrayed by Gloria Swanson, whose loss to
``Born Yesterday's'' Judy Holliday was considered an upset.
 &HT;    13. Meryl Streep said she was happy she didn't win for ``The
Deer Hunter'' (1978), because she had perspiration stains on her
dress. Hanks may or may not have sweated over his loss for ``Big''
(1988).
 &HT;    14. Cary Grant, remembered best for his comedies, was nominated
only for two serious roles, in ``Penny Serenade'' (1941) and ``None
But the Lonely Heart'' (1944).
 &HT;    15. Laurence Fishburne and Angela Bassett, as Ike and Tina
Turner, were both nominated for ``What's Love Got to Do With It''
(1994).
 &HT;    16. After six losses, Al Pacino was nominated for his supporting
role in ``Glengarry Glen Ross'' (1992) and his leading role in
``Scent of a Woman'' (1992). He won the latter ... finally.
 &HT;    17. Julia Roberts was the only member of the high-powered
``Steel Magnolias'' cast to get a nomination.
 &HT;    18. Gary Cooper played Lou Gehrig in ``Pride of the Yankees''
(1942), Jason Robards played a disheveled Howard Hughes in ``Melvin
and Howard'' (1980), Jessica Lange starred as Patsy Cline in
``Sweet Dreams'' (1985) and Steve Biko was portrayed by Denzel
Washington in ``Cry Freedom'' (1987).
 &HT;    19. Jon Voight was nominated, along with co-star Dustin Hoffman,
for ``Midnight Cowboy'' (1969), the first X-rated movie to win as
Best Picture.
 &HT;    20. The casts weren't too large, obviously: Michael Caine and
Laurence Olivier were both nominated for ``Sleuth'' (1972), and
James Whitmore was nominated for his one-man show, ``Give 'Em Hell,
Harry!'' (1975). Both had originated as stage productions.
 c.2000 S. Burelison  
<TEXT>
