<HEADER>
A8183 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-DEVON-SAWA-IN-FINAL-D     03-06 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEVON-SAWA-IN-FINAL-DESTINATION-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVON SAWA, THE LAST BIG THING 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Devon Sawa in a scene from ``Final
Destination.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Back in 1997, Devon Sawa was the Next Big Thing.
 &HT;    Talented and handsome, Sawa turned up everywhere as the hype
machine kicked into overdrive for the family adventure film ``Wild
America.'' Teens drooled over Sawa, while magazines and television
shows dutifully gave him the up-and-coming treatment.
 &HT;    Nobody went wild for ``Wild America,'' however, and instead of
emerging as a rival to teen-dream co-star Jonathan Taylor Thomas,
the 17-year-old Sawa found himself dangerously close to the
Hollywood scrap heap.
 &HT;    Sawa then retrenched and sought good, if lower-profile, work in
such independent features as ``A Cool Dry Place'' (1998) and ``SLC
Punk!'' (1999). He also appeared in ``Idle Hands'' (1999), a
disastrous teen horror/comedy that had the ill fortune to be
released in the wake of the Columbine High School massacre.
 &HT;    Friendly and refreshingly realistic, Sawa has no problem dealing
with his flash-in-the-pan moment.
 &HT;    ``I wasn't taken very seriously back then,'' he says by
telephone from his Los Angeles home. ``I knew that, and I took a
little break. Then I tried to enter the world of young actor
instead of young heartthrob or whatever they wanted to call me. It
was a very tedious and long transition.
 &HT;    ``Going in, all I wanted was longevity,'' he says. ``I didn't
want to cash in at such a young age. I wanted to have a good career
and be respected as an actor.''
 &HT;    He pauses.
 &HT;    ``There's no right way of doing anything in this business, and
no way to predict what will happen,'' he says. ``When I didn't want
to be the flavor of the month, it was unfortunately at a time when
the scripts that came with a lot more money and much bigger budgets
were just crap.''
 &HT;    Movies like ``SLC Punk!'' thus attracted Sawa's interest.
 &HT;    ``That was two minutes of screen time, but it was challenging
and something cool to do,'' Sawa says of the comedy/drama about a
punk rocker (Matthew Lillard) and his buddies in Salt Lake City.
``I guess it was me rebelling against the teen-idol world _ I
wanted to stay away from that.''
 &HT;    Sawa, now 21 and a little wiser, returns to the screen on March
17 as the star of ``Final Destination.'' Co-written and directed by
James Wong, a noted ``X-Files'' scribe and director, ``Final
Destination'' is a $25 million supernatural thriller, a far cry
from his recent fare.
 &HT;    ``The film is about a guy who has a premonition of an airplane
going down, and he has the premonition before the plane actually
takes off,'' Sawa says. ``He gets kicked off the plane because he
freaks out.
 &HT;    ``So you see him in the terminal, and in the background the
plane goes down exactly as he predicted it would,'' the actor
continues. ``Now Death is after him and six friends who were on the
plane.
 &HT;    ``You could sense Death, but it's never really a character,'' he
adds. ``Death was played by the special-effects team.''
 &HT;    The toughest days on set, Sawa says, didn't involve special
effects, explosions or manifestations of the Grim Reaper. Mother
Nature was actually a bigger challenge.
 &HT;    ``We shot a lot at night in Vancouver, British Columbia,'' says
the actor, himself a Vancouver native. ``Some of it was in the
middle of winter. We had wind, rain and 14-hour days, and we had to
make it look like it was springtime in Paris.
 &HT;    ``Plus, we had these light clothes on,'' he says, laughing. ``It
was tough at times, but we got through it.
 &HT;    ``I feel good with this one,'' Sawa adds. ``Even if it doesn't
produce what they're predicting at the box office, I felt like I
made an amazing movie. I'm very proud of it _ it's very creepy.
 &HT;    ``Hopefully people will enjoy it, and that's the most important
thing.''
 &HT;    Sawa will next be seen in ``Guilty,'' a psychological thriller
that he describes as a big-budget indie feature. The film,
currently being shopped around to potential distributors, co-stars
Gabrielle Anwar, Angela Featherstone and Bill Pullman.
 &HT;    ``Bill and I worked together for a week on `Casper' (1996),''
Sawa says. ``I was 15, and he seemed like the most amazing,
together guy. I wanted to work with him again because I thought I
could learn from him, and I did.''
 &HT;    The subject matter is pretty grim, the actor says. His character
leaves home in search of his long-lost father, and along the way
falls in with an attractive girl (Featherstone). But once he
actually meets his father (Pullman), he discovers that the girl may
have been raped by his father.
 &HT;    ``It's about how everybody deals with these different twists and
turns,'' Sawa says enigmatically.
 &HT;    The actor has nothing else on his plate at the moment. Having
recently ended a long relationship, he's ``single and on the prowl
in this crazy town,'' as he puts it. When not out prowling, Sawa
can usually be found in front of a television set indulging his
latest habit, watching wrestling.
 &HT;    Still, he says, his great passion remains acting.
 &HT;    ``I started when I was 10 years old,'' Sawa says. ``I don't know
anything else. I love it.
 &HT;    ``Out of the 14 hours a day you work, the actual two minutes you
get on screen that day are worth it,'' he says. ``To become someone
else, to see the special effects and stunts, is amazing. To see it
all cut together is really worth it. But I love those two
minutes.''
 &HT;    He pauses, groping for words.
 &HT;    ``There's something about when the camera starts rolling and you
start acting,'' he says tentatively. ``You don't feel that there
are 100 people around you. You just feel like you're in a scene,
and when the director yells `Cut,' all of a sudden you are back in
the real world.
 &HT;    ``It's like a drug, really,'' Sawa says. ``You just went away
for two minutes and stepped into a whole new world.
 &HT;    ``It's the coolest thing ever.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Final Destination,'' consult
the official Website at www.deathiscoming.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
