<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8193 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX     03-06 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIMARY SABOTEURS MAY BLOW THEIR OWN POLITICAL FINGERS OFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It isn't particularly noble to disdain political party
affiliation, stay away from both primaries and refuse to attend
precinct conventions. Basically, that's a cop-out. It limits your
choices to two candidates whom other people have selected for you.
</P>
<P>
   But for members of one party to invade the other's primary for
the purpose of mischievously affecting its outcome is not only
vaguely dishonorable. It's foolish. Such a practice frequently
backfires. Its perpetrators often find that they've outsmarted
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush suggests that Michigan Democratic Party
loyalists voted promiscuously in the Republican primary there last
month. Bush says he won a majority of the strictly Republican vote,
as exit polls would indicate. He feels that Michigan Democrats
conspiratorially infiltrated the GOP primary to vote for Sen. John
McCain, believing he'd be easier to defeat in November than Bush.
</P>
<P>
   If so, they may have done themselves no favor. Current polls
show the reverse to be true: McCain would be harder to beat. But
polls can be notoriously fickle, and those taken this early in a
presidential year are far from reliable indicators of what voters
will do in November. In four of the last five presidential races,
the one whom opinion polls favored in the springtime did not
triumph in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Remember? In 1988, Michael Dukakis outpolled George Bush as late
as August. President Bush looked strong in the spring of 1992, the
year he lost to Bill Clinton. Voters can be almost as changeable _
and unpredictable _ as Texas weather.
</P>
<P>
   As vice presidential adviser Jack Quinn put it Feb. 27, polls
taken amid the ups and downs of state primaries amount only to
``snapshots of people on a roller coaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Political contacts in Michigan say that independents, not
Democrats, were the ones who sank Bush. But an unknown number of
Democratic activists did infiltrate Republican voting boxes to vote
for McCain, expressly to embarrass Michigan Gov. John Engler, with
whom they've been feuding politically. Engler had staked his
influence and a big chunk of his reputation on handing Bush a
victory there, and the McCain win was egg on Engler's face.
</P>
<P>
   To this lifelong Democrat, that seems a surpassingly poor reason
to inflict oneself on another party's primary. The only thing it
achieves is the dilution of one's own influence in one's own party.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, a citizen may vote in either primary but cannot
legally vote in both. A Democrat opting to create mischief in a
Republican primary, for example, would deny himself any voice or
vote in his own party's selection process _ for congressman,
sheriff, state and local officials.
</P>
<P>
   The law of unintended consequences very often attends the
maneuverings of those who play games with the time-honored
two-party process. Southern Democrats supporting George Wallace's
maverick bid for the presidency in 1968 were just enough to elect
Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably, Ross Perot's Reform Party clipped enough votes off
Bush in 1992 to elect Clinton. The Green Party in New Mexico
siphons enough votes away from the Democrats to elect Republican
administrations. This in spite of the fact that the Greens appear
philosophically closer to Democrats than to those whom their
defections unwittingly benefit.
</P>
<P>
   One colossal political blunder of Texas Democrats playing games
burns in my memory. It was 1961. Lyndon B. Johnson, having been
elected vice president, vacated his Senate seat. A special election
was called, with a short-fused four-month campaign. Anybody with a
$50 filing fee could become a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Still in my 30s and with three terms in the House, I announced
for the Senate seat, convinced of my electability. Seventy other
candidates followed my example _ the largest field of contenders in
Texas history. Undaunted by the size of our state and my own
financial limitations, I felt I could win by prodigious personal
effort. I'd just get up earlier, go to bed later, travel more
miles, shake more hands and make more speeches than any of the 70
other contenders, I said.
</P>
<P>
   To make a long story short, I ran third _ barely nosed out for
second place by Bill Blakely of Dallas, who had been appointed
interim senator by Gov. Price Daniel. A little-known professor
named John Tower of Wichita Falls, the lone Republican in the race,
ran first by garnering all the Republican votes. The Democratic
vote had been split 70 ways.
</P>
<P>
   Blakely, merely by consolidating the Democratic voters, would
have been a shoo-in. But a group of disgruntled Texas Democrats
decided that they'd short-circuit the system.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these were self-styled liberals. They had little in
common with Blakely, but far less with Tower. Nevertheless, they
went to the polls in the runoff and voted for Tower.
</P>
<P>
   Their reasoning was that Blakely would ensconce himself in the
hierarchy of Washington seniority and be hard to defeat. Tower, on
the other hand, with nobody really for him but the Republicans
(then a distinct minority in Texas politics) would be dead meat at
the next election. They could get rid of him much more easily than
Blakely, they figured, and so these Democrats paraded smugly into
the polls and pulled the lever for Tower.
</P>
<P>
   They outwitted themselves. A full generation later, Tower was
still in the Senate and meanwhile had spearheaded the effort that
built the Texas Republican Party into the formidable force that it
is today. Poor Bill Blakely by then had been dead for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Those fellow Democrats of mine were, as the British say, too
clever by half.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 1340EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
