<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8184 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-JULIA-ROBERTS-IN-ERIN     03-06 1459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JULIA-ROBERTS-IN-ERIN-BROCKOVICH-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE IMPORTANCE OF BEING ERIN: JULIA ROBERTS TAKES A TURN TO THE
DRAMATIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Julia Roberts in a scene from ``Erin
Brockovich.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    When ``Erin Brockovich'' opens on March 17, you'll see a Julia
Roberts you've never seen before.
 &HT;    Or so she promises, as she leafs through a stack of publicity
photos during an interview at New York's Regency Hotel.
 &HT;    ``Frankly,'' she says with a shake of her long mane of curly,
red hair, ``it's more cleavage than God ever thought to give me.''
 &HT;    The real-life Brockovich, a housewife turned environmental
crusader, loved suck-it-all-in clothes that left little to the
imagination. Not at all Roberts' style _ on this cold winter day,
she looks ready for a bridal shower in a dainty mauve sweater,
matching long skirt and 20 beaded, matching bracelets.
 &HT;    ``I would come to the set to shoot this movie in my T-shirt,
sweatpants and flip-flops,'' the actress says, ``and then I would
be transformed into Erin gear. When I would walk back onto the set
in the highest heels and tightest little numbers, the crew guys
would yell, `What happened to you?!'''
 &HT;    Not that Roberts minded. She wanted to do something different
with ``Erin Brockovich,'' a taut drama that is a sharp contrast to
her recent string of hit romantic comedies, including ``My Best
Friend's Wedding'' (1998), ``Notting Hill'' (1999) and ``Runaway
Bride'' (1999), which between them raked in $395 million at the box
office.
 &HT;    Directed by Steven Soderbergh, the film casts her as a single
mother of three, undereducated and without much of a job history,
who winds up working for a fussy, set-in-his-ways attorney (Albert
Finney). And then she stumbles across records of a cluster of
cancer cases in a nearby small town, and starts raising hell.
 &HT;    ``I did this movie because I loved this woman,'' Roberts says.
``She has such spirit. You take a situation like this, where you
have a court-environment movie about files, water and people
getting sick _ Erin could have been a very quiet person going,
`Well, this doesn't seem right.' That would be so boring.''
 &HT;    Not to worry, because in real life and onscreen alike, Erin
Brockovich is no shrinking violet.
 &HT;    ``It was so much fun to go, `What the f--k is this about? This
doesn't make any sense,''' Roberts says, grinning. ``There was an
energy about this woman that was so appealing as an actor.''
 &HT;    On the other hand, she admits that it wasn't as much fun when
the role started seeping into her real-world life.
 &HT;    ``I carried her around all the time,'' the actress says. ``For
instance, on the set, if I needed some caffeine, I would suddenly
say, `What is the matter with you people _ do we have to wait for
another damn millennium to get coffee? What the f--k is going on?'
 &HT;    ``Normally, I'm like, `I'm sorry, is the coffee still coming?
Why don't I get it? Don't worry about me.'''
 &HT;    Some critics are already viewing ``Erin Brockovich'' as Roberts'
shot at an Oscar, a test of whether she has the acting chops to
move beyond romantic comedy. But she denies seeing things in so
serious a light.
 &HT;    ``I just do movies that are good,'' she says cheerfully. ``If
they were all good romantic comedies, that's all I'd do.''
 &HT;    Not so long ago, Roberts lacked such equanimity. She hated being
pigeonholed as a romantic-comedy star, and seemed resentful of her
own fame. In recent years, however, she has apparently become more
comfortable with ... well, with being Julia Roberts.
 &HT;    Her two most recent films even seemed to spoof her public image:
``Notting Hill,'' which cast her as a tabloid-plagued movie star,
and ``Runaway Bride,'' which played off of her much-publicized,
highly changeable love life.
 &HT;    ``I've come to terms that this is my chosen profession and I
really love it,'' she says. ``The good outweighs the bad.
 &HT;    ``I can deal with the scrutiny now,'' she adds, ``because I know
the comments of a total stranger don't amount to a hill of beans.
This is just a person who isn't willing to say it to my face.
 &HT;    ``Would I be a dental hygienist so nobody would say bad things
about me? I don't think so.''
 &HT;    At the very least, she makes a better living this way _ at $20
million per film, she's the highest-paid actress in the history of
Hollywood.
 &HT;    ``Getting paid $20 million doesn't make me a better actor,'' she
cautions. ``It doesn't make me work harder or less hard. I'm as on
time to work now as when I got paid scale plus 10 percent.
 &HT;    ``Nothing changes because of what you get paid,'' Roberts adds,
``except what you get paid _ and the fact that everybody wants to
talk about what you get paid. Which, where I come from, is an
inappropriate question to ask somebody.
 &HT;    ``No offense,'' she adds brightly.
 &HT;    The 32-year-old actress comes from Smyrna, Ga., where she grew
up as the child of two acting teachers. All three of their children
became actors, taking Roberts as a common stage name: Lisa and Eric
preceded their sister to New York, but while Eric remains a film
and television regular, it's Julia who really broke the bank,
beginning with ``Mystic Pizza'' (1988).
 &HT;    Two years later, she became an international star playing a
hooker with a heart of gold in ``Pretty Woman'' (1990), and the
rest is film history.
 &HT;    Well, actually, some of it is tabloid history. There was the
engagement to actor Kiefer Sutherland, which she broke off three
days before the wedding. There was the short-lived marriage to
singer Lyle Lovett. There were reported romances with actors Liam
Neeson, Dylan McDermott, Daniel Day-Lewis and Matthew Perry.
 &HT;    Roberts' greater calm these days has a lot to do with her
two-year-old relationship with ``Law and Order'' star Benjamin
Bratt.
 &HT;    ``I feel like I radiate when he's nearby,'' she admits. ``The
confidence I have gives me a feeling of empowerment that floors
me.''
 &HT;    So is the runaway bride about ready to stop running?
 &HT;    ``Let's just say I am very happy right now,'' she says
teasingly. ``You'll be the first to know if we get married.''
 &HT;    One plus, she adds, is that Bratt doesn't mind that his
girlfriend is more famous than he is, a fact with which Roberts has
long since come to terms.
 &HT;    ``I believe two people are connected at the heart, and it
doesn't matter what you do or who you are or where you live,'' she
says. ``There are no boundaries or barriers if two people are
destined to be together.''
 &HT;    Besides, she knows as well as anyone that fame can be evanescent
in Hollywood, where for years magazines and television shows have
been touting each newly arrived beauty as ``the next Julia
Roberts.''
 &HT;    ``Honey, who needs the next when you have me right here?'' she
says with a laugh.
 &HT;    ``I don't have concerns about not being famous anymore,'' she
adds, more seriously. ``I never have. Someday the audience might
get sick of me.''
 &HT;    Occasionally she is reminded that, even now, her $20 million
smile doesn't shine on everyone _ a fact which, she says, is oddly
reassuring.
 &HT;    ``Last year I was at a dinner party,'' she recalls. ``A woman
asked me what I did for a living. I said, `I'm an actress.' At that
point someone abruptly said to her, `You don't know who Julia
Roberts is?' And everyone attacked this poor woman.
 &HT;    ``Frankly, I was really impressed,'' Roberts says. ``I thought,
`This woman has a life.'''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
