<HEADLINE>
BRUNEI'S GOLDEN GLITTER FADES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANDAR SERI BEGAWAN, Brunei _ Since the 1970s, this oil-rich
kingdom on the northwest coast of Borneo has been awash in cash,
enough for the world's richest ruler to build the world's largest
palace, with plenty left over for free health care, free education,
even free vacations for his loyal subjects.
</P>
<P>
   But after nearly 30 years of a petroleum-lubricated
free-for-all, the party is over for Brunei, its spendthrift
royalty, and its coddled citizenry.
</P>
<P>
   In the most dramatic sign that the time has come to pay the
piper, Sultan Hassanal Bolkiah's government filed suit late last
month against his playboy younger brother, Prince Jefri Bolkiah.
The state is demanding that the prince pay back what sources peg at
more than $10 billion in public funds that he allegedly frittered
away, buying himself luxury hotels and expensive jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   The prince was saved by sovereign immunity from an embarrassing
court battle two years ago when a former Miss USA accused him and
the sultan of drugging her and keeping her as a palace sex slave.
The prince also managed to fend off or settle other lawsuits in
Britain and the United States involving alleged debts. So when the
state of Brunei filed suit, it shocked a nation where the royal
clan rules with unquestioned authority, and most citizens believed
them above the law.
</P>
<P>
   In another surprise, an economic analysis commissioned by the
sultan recently concluded that Brunei's abundant state spending is
``unsustainable'' and warned of ``fundamental economic problems
which threaten to undermine the prosperity and . . . social
stability'' of this tranquil backwater of 330,000 people. With oil
predicted to run out in 25 years and the population growing twice
as fast as the economy, the report said Brunei must diversify its
economy, trim its public sector, and promote a work ethic _ or face
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit and doomsday report were a double alarm bell for the
pampered princes and populace, ``but nobody's listening,'' said one
Western diplomat. If Bruneians continue to expect a high standard
of living for free, a society that has long been well-fed and
docile could ignite before the oil runs dry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since oil came, the royals spend their money like hell _
they give tips of $10,000, run up hotel bills of $1 million _ and
our Cabinet ministers are paid more than the prime minister of
Malaysia,'' said a 33-year-old employee of Brunei Shell Oil Corp.
``Jefri's a scapegoat; they're all spending our money.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has distinguished between the royals' money and the
public's money, and now tens of billions are lost. We've all been
very selfish and blind, but I blame the sultan, because he didn't
set the rules in the first place,'' said the man, who spoke on
condition of anonymity because of fear of imprisonment for
criticizing the royal family. But at the same time, he added, ``I
have a secure job, a good life, a good salary. Why should I
complain?''
</P>
<P>
   Oil accounts for between 75 and 90 percent of government
revenue, and has made possible universal welfare without an income
tax, earning Brunei the nickname ``the Shellfare state.'' Even a
granite-and-marble-paved amusement park with Corinthian-columned
archways _ a sort-of Caesar's Palace meets Romper Room _ is free to
all comers. (Built by Jefri Bolkiah, it is also the top evening
entertainment in a country that officially bans discos and liquor).
</P>
<P>
   True to its name, Brunei Darussalam, or ``Brunei, abode of
peace,'' has long been a somnolent backwater. The last sultan
squelched a revolt in 1962 and imposed a state of emergency, which
technically remains in effect. The last parliamentary elections
were in 1968; in 1982, even the appointed legislature was
abolished. There is one opposition party with just 100 members.
Most people are too comfortable to demand change.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half of Brunei's populace is employed by the government
and enjoy high wages, short work hours, interest-free loans for
houses and cars, subsidies for private school and overseas
universities, and free trips to London and Mecca after several
years of service. No wonder, then, that many would rather wait for
a government post than accept a job in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   But cracks in this so-called Muslim paradise began to show two
years ago, when Amedeo Development Corp., Jefri Bolkiah's private
conglomerate, went belly up. At the same time, $35 billion was
rumored missing from the national reserves, which the prince
controlled, spurring the sultan to fire his brother as finance
minister and head of the state investment.
</P>
<P>
   The prince denies any wrongdoing and has vowed to fight the
lawsuit. His friends darkly hint that if the case goes to court,
records of lavish and questionable spending may prove equally
embarrassing for the sultan and his other brothers.
</P>
<P>
   The prince reportedly owns countless custom-made cars and
planes, a yacht named after a female body part, a $5 million set of
10 gem-encrusted watches, the official jeweler to the Queen of
England, and the Bel-Air Hotel in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   With his company in bankruptcy, however, local construction was
halted, foreign workers were sent home, and restaurants shut for
lack of customers. Monster projects that the prince began _
including a fortress-like Finance Ministry and an $800 million,
gold-leafed hotel with eight swimming pools _ remain unfinished
today.
</P>
<P>
   Previously depressed oil prices fed a budget deficit of $1
billion since 1994. The Asian financial crisis of 1997 that hit
Brunei's trade partners did not help either.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the sultan, crowned the world's richest man by
Fortune magazine in 1987 with a net worth estimated at times as
high as $40 billion, lost the title to Microsoft Chairman Bill
Gates. Brunei's per capita gross domestic product _ once the
highest in Southeast Asia _ slipped 40 percent in a decade, falling
behind Singapore and Hong Kong, to $14,800 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Officials fret about the unemployment rate _ now at 4.9 percent
_ and complain that locals refuse to take jobs available in
restaurants, construction and household help.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, the weaknesses in Brunei's economy go far deeper
than the collapse of the prince's firm, Amedeo. Foreign investors
say Brunei is strikingly lacking in entrepreneurial spirit, perhaps
because people have been coddled and taught not to question
authority. Brunei's wealth has created a literate population, but
it has also fostered an entitlement mentality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have cousins and friends who won't take a job. They say,
`No, I want $2,000 a month; I'd rather wait.' So they just eat and
sleep at their parents' home,'' said Anis, 26, one of the few
Bruneians who work alongside Filipinos and Indonesians at a major
shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, a shantytown of ramshackle stilt-homes built on the
water sits in the shadows of an opulent mosque featuring imported
marble, stained glass, chandeliers and an escalator on one bank of
the Brunei River, and the sultan's 1,788-room palace on the other.
But a boat ride reveals that what looks like a squalid slum from
the shore is actually a middle-class community, and many residents
boast of luxury cars on the mainland. The floors in their homes are
covered in linoleum, and toilets are a hole in the planks emptying
into the river. But the shacks house big-screen TVs, washing
machines, refrigerators and opulent furniture.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a very big gap in incomes from the richest to the
rest of us, but no one is hungry,'' said Osman Bakar, 30, who
ferries commuters across the river. ``It's been a paradise here,
but it's changing. Everything used to be free. Now, children have
to pay a few dollars for books and we pay $1 to the doctor.'' There
is even talk of making people contribute to health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Finance Minister Selamat Munap said that ``the collapse
of Amedeo was . . . a very good wake-up call for us . . . that we
have to be prudent in our financial affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Munap said the state is also asking itself, ``How do you
encourage a culture of production, as opposed to a culture of
consumerism? . . . When entitlements are cut, (people) will work
harder.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the government has frozen state hiring and is pushing
for privatization. But the most important shift will have to be in
attitudes, some say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people here expect the government to do things for them,
rather than asking what they can do for the country,'' said a
30-year-old information technology manager. ``People of the younger
generation who are exposed to the Internet and to the outside world
are beginning to change that. It may change slowly, but it's got to
change or Brunei can't survive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
