<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8195 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX     03-06 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIMARY SABOTEURS MAY BLOW THEIR OWN POLITICAL FINGERS OFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It isn't particularly noble to disdain political party
affiliation, stay away from both primaries and refuse to attend
precinct conventions. Basically, that's a cop-out. It limits your
choices to two candidates whom other people have selected for you.
</P>
<P>
   But for members of one party to invade the other's primary for
the purpose of mischievously affecting its outcome is not only
vaguely dishonorable. It's foolish. Such a practice frequently
backfires. Its perpetrators often find that they've outsmarted
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush suggests that Michigan Democratic Party
loyalists voted promiscuously in the Republican primary there last
month. Bush says he won a majority of the strictly Republican vote,
as exit polls would indicate. He feels that Michigan Democrats
conspiratorially infiltrated the GOP primary to vote for Sen. John
McCain, believing he'd be easier to defeat in November than Bush.
</P>
<P>
   If so, they may have done themselves no favor. Current polls
show the reverse to be true: McCain would be harder to beat. But
polls can be notoriously fickle, and those taken this early in a
presidential year are far from reliable indicators of what voters
will do in November. In four of the last five presidential races,
the one whom opinion polls favored in the springtime did not
triumph in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Remember? In 1988, Michael Dukakis outpolled George Bush as late
as August. President Bush looked strong in the spring of 1992, the
year he lost to Bill Clinton. Voters can be almost as changeable _
and unpredictable _ as Texas weather.
</P>
<P>
   As vice presidential adviser Jack Quinn put it Feb. 27, polls
taken amid the ups and downs of state primaries amount only to
``snapshots of people on a roller coaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Political contacts in Michigan say that independents, not
Democrats, were the ones who sank Bush. But an unknown number of
Democratic activists did infiltrate Republican voting boxes to vote
for McCain, expressly to embarrass Michigan Gov. John Engler, with
whom they've been feuding politically. Engler had staked his
influence and a big chunk of his reputation on handing Bush a
victory there, and the McCain win was egg on Engler's face.
</P>
<P>
   To this lifelong Democrat, that seems a surpassingly poor reason
to inflict oneself on another party's primary. The only thing it
achieves is the dilution of one's own influence in one's own party.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, a citizen may vote in either primary but cannot
legally vote in both. A Democrat opting to create mischief in a
Republican primary, for example, would deny himself any voice or
vote in his own party's selection process _ for congressman,
sheriff, state and local officials.
</P>
<P>
   The law of unintended consequences very often attends the
maneuverings of those who play games with the time-honored
two-party process. Southern Democrats supporting George Wallace's
maverick bid for the presidency in 1968 were just enough to elect
Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably, Ross Perot's Reform Party clipped enough votes off
Bush in 1992 to elect Clinton. The Green Party in New Mexico
siphons enough votes away from the Democrats to elect Republican
administrations. This in spite of the fact that the Greens appear
philosophically closer to Democrats than to those whom their
defections unwittingly benefit.
</P>
<P>
   One colossal political blunder of Texas Democrats playing games
burns in my memory. It was 1961. Lyndon B. Johnson, having been
elected vice president, vacated his Senate seat. A special election
was called, with a short-fused four-month campaign. Anybody with a
$50 filing fee could become a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Still in my 30s and with three terms in the House, I announced
for the Senate seat, convinced of my electability. Seventy other
candidates followed my example _ the largest field of contenders in
Texas history. Undaunted by the size of our state and my own
financial limitations, I felt I could win by prodigious personal
effort. I'd just get up earlier, go to bed later, travel more
miles, shake more hands and make more speeches than any of the 70
other contenders, I said.
</P>
<P>
   To make a long story short, I ran third _ barely nosed out for
second place by Bill Blakely of Dallas, who had been appointed
interim senator by Gov. Price Daniel. A little-known professor
named John Tower of Wichita Falls, the lone Republican in the race,
ran first by garnering all the Republican votes. The Democratic
vote had been split 70 ways.
</P>
<P>
   Blakely, merely by consolidating the Democratic voters, would
have been a shoo-in. But a group of disgruntled Texas Democrats
decided that they'd short-circuit the system.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these were self-styled liberals. They had little in
common with Blakely, but far less with Tower. Nevertheless, they
went to the polls in the runoff and voted for Tower.
</P>
<P>
   Their reasoning was that Blakely would ensconce himself in the
hierarchy of Washington seniority and be hard to defeat. Tower, on
the other hand, with nobody really for him but the Republicans
(then a distinct minority in Texas politics) would be dead meat at
the next election. They could get rid of him much more easily than
Blakely, they figured, and so these Democrats paraded smugly into
the polls and pulled the lever for Tower.
</P>
<P>
   They outwitted themselves. A full generation later, Tower was
still in the Senate and meanwhile had spearheaded the effort that
built the Texas Republican Party into the formidable force that it
is today. Poor Bill Blakely by then had been dead for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Those fellow Democrats of mine were, as the British say, too
clever by half.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 1340EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8196 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-0307-     03-06 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-0307-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ALLEGATIONS OF RUSSIAN RIGHTS ABUSES CONTINUE
 &HT;    (750&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHOLKOVSKOYE, Russia _ Stillness in this small muddy town on
Chechnya's eastern border stretches from morning to late afternoon,
punctured only by cattle ambling down the street and men smoking
and stamping their tired feet in the winter chill.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government calls Sholkovskoye a model village in
their campaign to win the hearts and minds of Chechen civilians,
and bring normal life back to this breakaway republic devastated
during six months of war between Islamic separatists and the
Russian army.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no shooting. Relations between the authorities and the
population are excellent,'' boasts Col. Sergei Mikhailov, Russia's
deputy commander in the region, as he sits in the sandbagged town
hall building under a portrait of acting Russian President Vladimir
Putin.
</P>
<P>
   But his words contrast those of civilians here, who say Russian
soldiers have brought only a mirage of stability, an uneasy peace
threatened by hostility between those who survived and those who
waged the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've created the appearance of normal life, but it's not
real,'' said Alimkhan Magomedov, an unemployed ethnic Chechen. ``We
have absolutely no rights _ they still treat all of us as if we're
bandits.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia's leadership announced the capture last week of the
village of Shatoi _ described as the last rebel stronghold _ and
vowed to wrap up their offensive quickly. But the rebels, who have
pledged to wage a guerrilla-type war against the Russians, said
they would continue to offer stiff resistance against the troops.
</P>
<P>
   In the days following the Russian announcement, federal forces
suffered two major setbacks in fierce battles both on the southern
front and in the Chechen capital Grozny, which the army had boasted
was completely subdued and safe.
</P>
<P>
   In a weekend interview with the British Broadcasting Corp.,
Putin repeated the military line that Russian forces have
effectively crushed rebel resistance. In addition, he stressed that
the primary task of the Russian forces would be to build peace in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Plans have been laid to decrease the Russian military presence
from the current 100,000 troops to about one-third that number, and
to slowly replace the Russian military commandant system governing
liberated villages like Sholkovskoye with new civilian
administrations and local militia forces.
</P>
<P>
   But neither Putin nor the Russian government has explained how
Russia will pay for the rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   In the three years between the first Chechen War and the second,
the Russian government transferred more than $2 billion to the
civilian Chechen government. The money was earmarked for rebuilding
infrastructure like electric and phone lines destroyed during the
first war, but most of it was embezzled Chechen officials.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Deputy Prime Minister Nickolai Koshman has said that
reconstructing Chechnya will cost Russia some 10 billion rubles
(US$400 million), but would not elaborate on what that figure
includes. Estimates for rebuilding the Grozny, where more than
600,000 people lived until the Russian air force flattened it in
devastating air attacks, run close to (US$1 billion) alone.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 Russian federal budget only allocates 515 million
rubles (US$18 million) for Chechnya, an amount that compounds
cynicism among the civilian population in the war-torn region that
life will improve under Russian rule.
</P>
<P>
   This region on Chechnya's _ east bordering Dagestan _ is the
most pro-Russian part of Chechnya. It was one of the first areas to
be occupied by Russian forces after locals ran the Chechen rebels
out of the town of Sholkovskoye last October, and was spared the
destruction visited on cities like Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   Electricity and gas are working in the town, but food and work
are scarce. Along Sholkovskoye's two-lane unpaved main street the
only economic activity comes from kiosks selling Snickers, soda and
chewing gum. Other household items are nowhere to be seen on store
shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some residents like pensioner Marina Kudelina, an ethnic
Russian, are satisfied with life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is better since (the Russian army) came and the bandits
left. We get our pensions and we sleep soundly in our beds,'' the
72-year-old said.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone has pleasant things to say about the military.
</P>
<P>
   Luba Zagayeva is one of thousands of people who fled fighting in
Grozny and have taken shelter with relatives in the region
surrounding Sholkovskoye. Zagayeva said she lost all her identity
papers in the rush to flee the relentless air raids on her home.
Without the documents, she can't receive any food aid or travel to
another town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got nothing left there, and nothing to feed my children
here,'' Zagayeva said, standing in the town square hoping to catch
the attention of military officials entering and exiting the city
hall building.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   For the four months she has lived in Sholkovskoye with her
children, the commandant's office refused to replace her family's
documents, making life harrowing for her husband and older son. The
lack of identity papers is grounds for arrest by the Ministry of
Interior soldiers that patrol the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's constant harassment. They take our men on the pretense
that they have fought for the rebels. It's no good to tell them
they have never lifted a weapon. We either pay to get them out of
jail, or they take them away and we never see them again,''
Zagayeva said.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Mikhailov denied that his men make unwarranted arrests
among the Chechen civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chechens like to work in armed forces. We must remain vigilant
and keep discipline or else peace will break down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the four months the Russian military has controlled the town,
50 criminal cases have been opened against townsfolk, with charges
ranging from robbery to drug possession to loitering. The
defendants must be transferred to the Russian town of Krasnodar,
because Sholkovskoye has no working court system.
</P>
<P>
   Mikhailov said the best long-term solution for peace in Chechnya
would be to replace the Russian troops with a local police force
that will defend the rule of law. He has already appointed a
Chechen chief of police for Sholkovskoye. So far, 180 people have
completed applications to join the local militia. No one's been
hired yet, because there's no money to pay them.
</P>
<P>
   For some Chechens, who have witnessed war for most of their
lives, the answer is much more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were independent, it was all a big mess and we
starved,'' says Abdul Magomedov, an 18-year-old chewing sunflower
seeds in Sholkovskoye's main square. ``Now (the Russians) think
they can give us bread and we'll all be happy again. But they're
wrong. We still want our own government, our own president. We
still want freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
