<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGER-RICKY-MARTIN-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROSSOVER KING: THE UNLIKELY TRIUMPH OF RICKY MARTIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of singer Ricky Martin.) 
 By KEVIN DICKSON  
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 Not to be released in Canada before March 19, 2000. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   How does a soap-opera bartender turn into the world's top male
singer?
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Ricky Martin. Only five years ago, he was best known as
``General Hospital's'' Miguel Morez, a Fabio-haired martini-maker
who left women the world over shaken and stirred, and was prone to
breaking into song at the drop of an olive.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, soap fans still remember Miguel fondly, even if
nowadays the recollection makes Martin wince _ especially when fans
bring it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was going through my mind in those days?'' he says with a
laugh, shaking his head. ``It always happens, it always happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Puerto Rico 29 years ago, Martin blazed a unique road to
stardom, with stops along the way as a child star with the
prototypical boy band Menudo, a stint on ``General Hospital,'' a
run on Broadway in ``Les Miserables'' and, finally, his emergence
as a top Spanish-language recording artist.
</P>
<P>
   And there matters stood until Martin stepped onstage to sing
``The Cup of Life'' at the 1998 Grammy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the stage midway through a lifeless ceremony, Martin and
his zero-to-60 hips galvanized millions of viewers, speaking the
language of sex so fluently that most viewers didn't even realize
he wasn't singing in English.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, ``La Vida Loca'' skyrocketed to the top of
the charts worldwide _ it was the kind of song that, once you heard
it, stayed in your head all day _ and Ricky Martin went from Latin
star to bigger-than-life, worldwide presence.
</P>
<P>
   In person, Martin is forthright and garrulous, his natural
enthusiasm charging whatever topic he's discussing. Take, for
example, his love for rock music, a love that would have led him in
a very different direction if it weren't for his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really influenced by rock music because of my
brothers,'' Martin recalls. ``Then one day my mom said, ``Enough
with rock _ I cannot stand it anymore! Do you know about Latin
sounds?'
</P>
<P>
   ``She grabbed us by the ear and took us to a Celia Cruz and Tito
Puente concert and said, `This is music that you have to learn to
appreciate, because this is you, it's where you come from, your
sound.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't too happy at the concert,'' he admits, ``but later
on, today, I say, `Mom, thank you so much,' because it's just the
fact that I can not just talk about this music but I can perform
it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Martin adds, his first musical passion was, believe it
or not, disco. Blame it on ``Saturday Night Fever'' (1977).
</P>
<P>
   ``I was, like, 7,'' he recalls with a laugh, ``but I thought I
was John Travolta. I was combing my hair back and walking with a
little limp like him, and I wanted to wear polyester. My mom was
like, ``This is Puerto Rico, it's really hot, you're not wearing
it.' I was really wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's rapid rise has left him at risk from backlash.
Celebrity is a potent drug that some stars, such as Madonna, can
acclimate themselves to, while others, such as Kurt Cobain, are
unable to handle.
</P>
<P>
   Martin has publicly credited his spiritual beliefs and yoga for
helping him to deal with praise and criticism alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm grateful for whatever people are saying,'' he says with a
shrug. ``Being grateful to critics, both good and bad, and being
willing to say, `Hi, nice to meet you, my name is ... ' to
anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   A small circle of longtime friends also help him maintain his
poise, the singer adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``They keep me balanced,'' Martin says. ``My friends are people
that I've known since I was 10, 12 years old. I grew up with them,
they know me pretty well. They're really honest about me and my
music, because it's the way I express myself.''
</P>
<P>
   For someone whose career has been based in large part on his sex
appeal, Martin is surprisingly uncomfortable being identified as a
sex symbol.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I have to deal with, unfortunately,'' he says
with a grimace. ``I'm not going to waste all my energy thinking
about whether people think I'm a sex symbol or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sexuality and sensuality are two different things,'' he adds.
``Sensuality is something that you're born with. Sexuality is
something that I keep for my room, and it's not coming out of
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, when it comes to sex, Ricky Martin says he's
pretty much an old-fashioned guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself kind of conservative when it comes to sex,''
he says, ``and I respect others when it comes to that. I don't
judge when it comes to sex _ and I'm talking about myself, I'm
talking about straight, gay, lesbian, it doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is too short not to be happy,'' he says. ``You've got to
be happy. If you're happy making love to a dog, go for it!''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses, then laughs at his joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, don't do that,'' he says. ``Don't do that!''
</P>
<P>
   As Martin winds up a tour that has taken his ``Vida Loca''
around the world several times, he's preparing to head back into
the studio to record his followup album while keeping one eye on
the future. Ten years down the road, he says, he still wants to be
singing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being on stage is not something I want to let go of,'' he
says. ``It's just amazing, this feeling of control. I'd also like
to do something behind the camera _ I've learned a lot from a lot
of directors I've worked with over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``And maybe I'll stop for a couple of years and study
cinematography,'' he says. ``Then maybe I can start directing my
own videos. That's something I'd love to try, because it's another
perspective. Seeing myself from an outside point of view is very
healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin has a firm idea as to how he'd like to be remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone that taught someone about Latin cultures, someone that
worked a lot,'' he says very seriously. ``And, at the same time,
someone that always was grounded.''
</P>
<P>
   As he gets up to leave, Martin turns with one more comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the thing that has worked for me is to be stubborn,''
he says thoughtfully. ``If you want something without hurting
others, go for it. Maybe it's not tomorrow, maybe it's not the day
after tomorrow, maybe it's in five years, but eventually it will be
yours.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at the same time, start getting ready for whenever you
have it in your hands _ you can manage it, you can control it,'' he
concludes. ``Be surrounded by great people, creative people, people
that are honest _ and be yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Kevin Dickson is a Los Angeles-based correspondent for TV
Guide Canada.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on Ricky Martin, consult his
official Website at www.rickymartin.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
