<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8200 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-ISLAM-SHIFT-BOS &LR;      03-06 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISLAM-SHIFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATION OF ISLAM SOFTENING ITS MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Nation of Islam, for decades renounced by many Muslims for
unorthodox and racially divisive beliefs, increasingly is embracing
traditional Islam, say close observers of the Nation of Islam,
including some gathered at a conference on Islam at Harvard this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Nation of Islam leader Louis Farrakhan in a speech last Sunday
appeared to have abandoned two tenets of the Nation of Islam that
are anathema to orthodox Muslims: that Nation of Islam founder
Wallace Fard Muhammad was an incarnation of Allah, and that Fard's
successor, Elijah Muhammad, was a prophet.
</P>
<P>
   Farrakhan, who had a brush with death while battling prostate
cancer last year, had already taken several steps toward a
rapprochement between the Nation of Islam and orthodox Islam. Last
year he urged Nation of Islam members to begin observing Ramadan,
an Islamic holy month, at the same time as orthodox Muslims, as
well as during a second period of time prescribed by Elijah
Muhammad. Farrakhan has also indicated that he wants to take
thousands of Nation of Islam members on a pilgrimage, or hajj, to
Mecca.
</P>
<P>
   Making such a pilgrimage is considered desirable for observant
Muslims, and although Farrakhan has done so before, he has never
led a large group of Nation of Islam members.
</P>
<P>
   Following a conciliatory speech by Farrakhan in Chicago last
weekend, African-American Muslim leaders and religion scholars say
they detect an important shift underway.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have just witnessed is a total theological
transformation of the Nation of Islam, which for 70 years has given
blacks a great sense of dignity and self-worth but also has
perpetuated a skewed and distorted version of Islam,'' said Arthur
Magida, a Farrakhan biographer. ``And if Farrakhan really embraces
a color-blind Islam now, then he will have made a clean break with
the full tradition, which has always pitted black against white.''
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance with orthodox Muslim leaders on Feb. 25 and in
a speech two days later, Farrakhan eschewed the inflammatory
rhetoric for which he is known, and suggested that he is ready to
erase the main theological differences that have divided the Nation
of Islam from orthodox Islam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Has Farrakhan changed?'' he asked. ``Yeah, I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there remain stumbling blocks to unity with
orthodox Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are indications that Farrakhan is trying to
diversify the Nation of Islam _ he is hoping Asian-Americans,
Hispanics and even whites will join a Million Families March he is
planning as a follow up to the Million Man March of 1995 _ he has
not formally renounced the Nation of Islam teaching that whites are
a devil race. Farrakhan has in the past drawn criticism for racist
and anti-Semitic oratory.
</P>
<P>
   And the Nation of Islam's newspaper, the Final Call, continues
to publish a list of beliefs that contradict Islamic teachings that
Allah takes no human form and Mohammed was the final prophet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of suspicions right now, partly because
Farrakhan has said things in the past, but his actions were
different,'' said Lawrence H. Mamiya, an expert on the Nation of
Islam who teaches Africana studies and religion at Vassar College.
</P>
<P>
   But Mamiya calls last weekend's events historic, and says the
Nation of Islam will continue to play an important role in the
spiritual life of some black Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farrakhan will continue to emphasize the need for a special
message to black people, which has been the forte of the Nation of
Islam in the past,'' he said. ``The Nation of Islam is still
playing a very important role in black communities, especially
among the underclass and those in prison, and their whole effort to
reform the lives of poor black people is still going on.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, leaders of the Nation of Islam and the largest
group of Sunni Muslims in the United States both said they regard
the changes as significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've known each other since we were young men, and I'm
convinced I'm hearing a new Farrakhan, a different man,'' said Imam
Warith Deen Mohammed, a son of Elijah Muhammad who renounced his
father's teachings and now leads a group of Sunni Muslims called
the Muslim American Society, which claims 2 million followers.
``This means we can now accept him as a great leader, perhaps the
most popular leader in the African-American Muslim community.''
</P>
<P>
   Warith Deen Mohammed said he has been working ``to help them (in
the Nation of Islam) free themselves from the false concepts of
reality that would burden them forever'' and that, even today, ``we
know they have certain fundamental attachments to the past that for
us represent a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Nation of Islam historically played an important
role for ``the African-American culturally deprived masses,'' but
that the role is less important today, when the black community is
more educated and more integrated by the mass media into mainstream
American thought.
</P>
<P>
   Warith Deen Mohammed said he expects that as a result of
Farrakhan's evolving views, it is possible that a more radical
splinter group will break away from the Nation of Islam. However,
he said, ``it's going to be a small number of African-Americans,
because of misery and hurt and blinded by their own inability to be
successful, who will be the desperate ones asking for people to
denounce the country and denounce Christianity, and their numbers
are going to keep diminishing. The world is too open now and too
filled with knowledge for there to be big masses attracted to those
old teachings. I don't see a big role for anybody to hold on to
those ideas I was given when I was a boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Minister Don Muhammad, the Nation of Islam's top official in
Boston, said he sees no theological division between the Nation of
Islam and orthodox Islam.
</P>
<P>
   ``The adherent to the faith today would be doing Allah a
disservice if he attempted to align himself with one group or
another,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Minister Don Muhammad did not describe the
Nation of Islam's founders in prophetic terms, instead saying ``All
Muslims believe in Allah and the prophet Mohammed, but the
honorable Elijah Muhammad can never be denied for the great work he
did. The prophet Mohammed never had to deal with drugs and AIDS and
the kinds of things that plague the black community today.'' He
described Elijah Muhammad as ``a direct messenger to black
people.''
</P>
<P>
   But Don Muhammad said the Nation of Islam still has an important
role to play as a distinct organization, if not a distinct
religion. He said black Americans ``are in a serious, pitiful
condition as it relates to other civilized people on earth; we've
got problems other ethnic groups do not have, and we cannot go any
further without addressing them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Nation can help black Americans tackle those issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are black people in this country who really need at this
time Mr. (Elijah) Muhammad's teaching about doing for themselves,
staying with their families and taking care of their children,'' he
said. ``These aspects have nothing to do with religion itself, but
it is part of the Nation of Islam's work, and these are aspects the
Nation of Islam must address.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
