u a BC-LORD-AMHERST-ART-BOS &LR;      03-06 1482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LORD-AMHERST-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (Eds.: Jefferey is cq)  
 LORD JEFF: HERO, VILLAIN, AND COLLEGE TOWN'S NAMESAKE  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMHERST, Mass. _ Lord Jeffrey Amherst dispatched the French and
Indians with such finesse some 240 years ago that in his honor, a
prominent college, a glacier, a mountain, and more than 20 towns,
including this one, proudly took his name.
</P>
<P>
   But history of late is being less kind to Lord Jeff. A small but
vocal group of citizens is questioning the propriety of naming
places after a guy, it turns out, who ordered killing Native
Americans by deliberately issuing them blankets infected with small
pox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where political correctness ends, but I know
where it starts,'' said Jack Dunphy, who is leading a charge
against Lord Jeff. ``This guy committed an egregious deed. Amherst
should not bear his name.''
</P>
<P>
   If Dunphy and associates have their way, Amherst someday might
be renamed for one of the early tribal chiefs of the area, perhaps
Chuckwalop, Umpanchala, or Quonquont. And Lord Jeff would be
relegated to a historical marker somewhere explaining how he was a
father of germ warfare.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the latest example of how politically adjusted
perspective is trying _ literally _ to change the map.
</P>
<P>
   The US Board on Geographic Names receives about 450 requests a
year to name or rename places nationwide. About half the inquiries
that come to the Reston, Va., headquarters target previously
unnamed features _ a hill or ridge, for example.
</P>
<P>
   However, the other half address names that may have once been
acceptable, but for reasons of historical fact or political
correctness are now considered inappropriate by some, according to
Roger Payne, the board's executive secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is never easy. The response is almost always emotional when
change is the issue,'' said Payne.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, changing the name of the western Massachusetts
college town is a long shot _ not to mention the glacier and
mountain peak in Alaska named by Amherst graduates at the turn of
the last century. In fact, some 85 places nationwide offically
carry the Amherst name, apparently most, if not all, honoring Lord
Jeffrey or the college bearing his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not named after Lord Jeff,'' said Douglas Wilson, a
spokesman for the prestigious college. ``We're named after the town
that took his name. But it would be fair to say we have adopted
him.'' The college team mascots are the Lord Jeffs and Lady Jeffs.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some people around Amherst appear inclined to distance
themselves from their namesake. Michael Maderia, innkeeper of the
quaint 74-year-old Lord Jeffery Inn, said his establishment has
been fingered occasionally by critical students as the original
home of Lord Amherst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lord Jeff never came close to this area,'' Maderia emphasized.
He said life might be a little easier sometimes if his inn had
another name. ``But for this, you would have to start by renaming
the town, then the college _ which owns the inn,'' Maderia said.
</P>
<P>
   A pamplet distributed by the Amherst History Museum confirms
that the lord never came closer to Amherst than northwestern New
York State. As for the business of genocide, the pamphlet sidesteps
the matter. After quoting sermons of the Colonial era extolling
Lord Jeff as a Christian hero who loved the enemies he subdued, it
adds: ``While current residents might have mixed emotions about the
name of Amherst, those living within the region during the mid-18th
century may have been proud to adopt the name.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's heroes, today's criminals: Finding them is not hard,
notes William Fowler, director of the Massachusetts Historical
Society. He and other historians offer a few examples:
</P>
<P>
   --King Charles I of England (Charles River) was such a
tyrannical ruler that he was decapitated in 1649.
</P>
<P>
   --Chief Justice William Stoughton (Stoughton, Stoughton
Junction) presided over Salem Witch Trials.
</P>
<P>
   --Ephraim Williams (Williamstown, Williams College) and son
Elijah worked a land scam to cheat Indians out of hundreds of acres
in western Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   --Nicholas Brown (Brown University) hailed from a family that
made big bucks in textiles _ while dabbling in the slave trade.
</P>
<P>
   --George Washington (2,170 features nationwide) had inherited 10
slaves by the time he was 11 years old. When he died, he owned 316
slaves.
</P>
<P>
   The New Orleans school system is midway through renaming 25
schools honoring former slave holders, including the George
Washington Elementary School.
</P>
<P>
   The state historian in Connecticut hopes such revisionism does
not migrate north. ``Except for names that have become clearly
derogatory, where do you ever draw the line between a passing fad
and historical significance?'' asks Christopher Collier. ``Perhaps
the best solution is to teach history, not bury it. Because once
you start the process of changing names, it's hard to stem it.''
</P>
<P>
   The name squaw is attached to more than two dozen features in
Maine. But the word is considered today to be a pejorative term for
an Indian woman, and many Native American leaders have pushed to
eliminate it. The Maine Legislature is expected to vote next month
to remove the word from the map, following the lead of Minnesota
and Montana.
</P>
<P>
   In Rhode Island and Providence Plantations (most people are
unaware of the state's full name), legislation introduced last
month aims to strike the slavery-evoking ``plantation'' reference.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three decades, federal officials have allowed 28
places using the term Negro to drop the ethnic label, critics
frequently noting that there were no ``Caucasian Ponds'' or ``White
Man Rivers,'' so why should Negro be acceptable?
</P>
<P>
   Buzzards Bay, however, still has a Negro Ledge, and Plymouth a
Negro Pond. Frances Picket lives on a road that dead ends at Negro
Pond. Sometimes, history cleans itself up along the way.
``Somewhere along the way we all just started calling it Black
Pond,'' said Picket. ``I had no idea it has another name.''
</P>
<P>
   Precedence for changing the name of an entire town is spotty at
best. New England historians say the burgeoning tourist trade a
century ago encouraged some locals to buff up their image, which is
why Herring Gut on the Maine coast became Port Clyde, Ray's Pond in
southern Vermont became Lake Rayponda, and Sodom in northern
Vermont became Adamant.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, some seemingly ignored history in western
Massachusetts lit a fire under Jack Dunphy of Greenfield. A local
newspaper series offered one account after another of Indian
attacks on settlers. But there was no mention of the 1675 attack by
Colonel William Turner (Turners Falls) and Samuel Holyoke (Holyoke)
on an unarmed Indian village. Approximately 300 men, women, and
children were killed, many shot in their wigwams.
</P>
<P>
   And there was no mention of Lord Jeffrey's plague-infected
blankets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will Do well,'' Amherst wrote a commander in the field,
``to try to Inoculate the Indians, by means of Blankets, as well as
to Try Every other Methode, that can Serve to Extirpate this
Execrable Race.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter d'Errico, a law professor at the University of
Massachusetts, Amherst, has done extensive research on this and
other dispatches attributed to Amherst. He has little doubt that
Lord Jeffrey used small pox to kill, a tactic that historians
believe was well-known to the British military strategists _ and
their Colonial forefathers such as John Winthrop Massachusetts'
first governor. ``For the natives, they are all dead of small
Poxe,'' Winthrop wrote, ``so as the Lord hathe cleared our title to
what we possess.''
</P>
<P>
   Does d'Errico support renaming Amherst? ``A place name is
important. It is remembrance, it is owning up to history,'' he
said. ``So after a real discussion, a real debate, I probably would
support a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunphy said he and a few people got together on Martin Luther
King Day, called themselves People Speak Truth, and started
planning. Now several dozen strong, the group intends to take its
case of ``historical amnesia'' to local schools and colleges.
Eventually, they hope to start a petition drive that puts the
matter before Town Meeting members. To some longtime residents, it
will recall a period in the protest-packed late 1960s when Lord
Jeffrey was a target of criticism that never went very far. To
date, Town Hall has received just one letter on the subject. It was
critical of Lord Jeffrey.
</P>
<P>
   Are Amherst's 35,225 residents destined to live in Chuckwalop?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a stretch,'' said Fowler of the Massachusetts
Historical Society. ``And face it, had it not been for Lord Jeff,
we would all be speaking French.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
