<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8212 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCHOOL-CHOICE-ART-BOS     03-06 1395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-CHOICE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 VERMONT SCHOOL CHOICE HAILED, SCRUTINIZED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DORSET, Vt. _ By the time she sits for the 8 a.m. ``Morning
Meeting'' at the Long Trail School, Amanda Ameden, 13, has been
traveling for 45 minutes, on two separate buses, over winding Green
Mountain passes. A worthwhile sacrifice, says her mother, Teresa
Ameden. Amanda gets to attend the school of her choice. And her
local school board pays a hefty chunk of the private tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Along with some 10,000 students from small Vermont towns, Amanda
takes part in the state's 185-year-old school choice program _
little known outside the state, largely beloved within, and, until
recently, noncontroversial.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the politically driven, experimental voucher systems that
have sparked debate in cities such as Milwaukee, Vermont's
school-choice program was born of necessity. In a sparse, rural
state, many towns are too small to maintain schools of their own.
This way, they can meet their constitutional obligation to provide
an education to every child.
</P>
<P>
   But at a time when school vouchers are increasingly mentioned in
presidential debates, Vermont's program now stands as something of
a test case for the complex issue of parental freedom. And it
suggests one way education might be conducted under a President
McCain or a President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   About 90 school boards, from resort towns at the foot of ski
mountains to farm communities in the valleys, take part in the
Vermont program, sending their education money to schools outside
their borders. Parochial schools are off-limits, based on a state
Supreme Court decision, but parents can choose public or private
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Or they can pick unconventional private schools such as Long
Trail, where teachers go by their first names, two dogs and a cat
roam the halls, and students end the day with chores: emptying the
trash, shaking out rugs, washing dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Many parents and their children hold their voucher system dear.
Families have been known to move to school-choice towns; one
cluster of ski mountain towns continually refuses to pool its
students into a public high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Choice,'' Teresa Ameden declares, ``is a wonderful thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But some parents and private-school leaders are sensing a
growing threat to the tradition. They point to a unanimous vote the
state Board of Education took about a year ago, suggesting that the
state should stop sending public money to private schools.
</P>
<P>
   The vote _ a recommendation that carried no force of law _ was
rescinded the next month amid protest by private-school leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Now, state education officials downplay its significance.
</P>
<P>
   Board members raised the idea with little thought or research,
said Bill Reedy, legal counsel for the state education department,
who called it ``a quick and not a long-lasting aberration.''
</P>
<P>
   But some voucher advocates saw it as a sign of future threats.
When board members voted, ``I don't think they were on drugs or
sleep-deprived,'' said Mary Barrosse Schwartz, whose daughter
attends Long Trail School. ``To me, that says where they were
coming from.''
</P>
<P>
   She and other activists also worry that a pending bill in the
Legislature, which would create some regional districts for
public-school choice, might eventually be used to replace the
current voucher system.
</P>
<P>
   And Long Trail headmaster Dave Wilson, president of the Vermont
Independent Schools Association, said he hears ``rumblings all the
time'' about limiting private-school choice. ``There's a feeling
the state is creeping more towards invading our independence,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that scrutiny is growing should hardly be a shock;
across the country, vouchers are hot-button stuff. But they are
also edging further into the mainstream political debate.
</P>
<P>
   Several states, including Massachusetts, have experimented with
small choice programs, limited to public schools. But sending
public money to private schools has still been considered a radical
step, used only in rural states such as Vermont and Maine, which
has a similar voucher program.
</P>
<P>
   Reedy said he often gets calls from policy makers in other
states, who ask what they can learn from private vouchers in
Vermont. Not much, he tells them. In most other places, proponents
see the voucher system as a way to spur improvements in failing
public schools, while opponents warn that choice could bleed public
schools of students and money.
</P>
<P>
   In Vermont, vouchers aren't a remedy; they're available only to
students with no local public schools. And Vermont lacks the racial
diversity of other states, so its vouchers don't raise the
segregation worries that have stirred debate elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wilson calls his state ``a laboratory for school
choice.'' And for his students, he said, the experiment has proved
positive.
</P>
<P>
   Long Trail opened in September 1975 with four teachers, 14
students, and a $100-per-month lease at the Dorset Sportsmen's
Club. It was a large, open room, divided by partitions that were
taken down every Friday afternoon. On weekends, the building was
used for dances.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years later, the school has 120 students and a
large, rustic building looking out on the Taconic Mountains.
Students have three hours of homework every night, but they also
take part in a host of activities, from cooking to dancing to
tabletennis.
</P>
<P>
   Long Trail has a familial atmosphere, and some students say
that's precisely why they chose the school.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Sarah Kapusta, 17, said teachers seem to care about
students.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Kara Watson, 16, said students repect one another's
differences.
</P>
<P>
   But other students want things that Long Trail doesn't offer.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Tyler Pabst, 15, said he plans to switch schools next
year so he can play on sports teams at a larger school.
</P>
<P>
   That's a benefit of choice, parents say; schools develop their
own personalities, and students and parents can select the schools
that best fit their needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids could be matched with institutions, instead of trying to
make every institution provide everything,'' said Lois Fish, whose
son and daughter graduated from Long Trail.
</P>
<P>
   But Reedy questions how many of Vermont's voucher students can
truly take advantage of their choices. Some small private schools
don't have space for every student who wants to attend.
</P>
<P>
   And often, private school tuition costs more than the vouchers
provide. In some cases, school districts make up the difference
through taxes or private donations. Some schools offer
scholarships; Long Trail offers them to about half of its students.
But in some cases, parents have to make up what can be a costly
gap.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation can also be a barrier, said Lorna Jimerson, a
former Vermont school board member who did her doctoral
dissertation on school choice in Minnesota. While some Vermont
schools and towns pay for buses, parents often need to provide
transportation. So if a family wants to take advantage of vouchers,
she said, it'd better have a car with good snow tires.
</P>
<P>
   There's also some evidence that Vermont's voucher system divides
students by social class, Jimerson said.
</P>
<P>
   One recent study showed that students in one school-choice
community, from an island on Lake Champlain, segregated themslves
at will. Some students, it seemed, felt more comfortable around
people with similar backgrounds and picked their schools along
those lines.
</P>
<P>
   But that was a small, rare study, said Bill Mathis,
superintendent of the Rutland Northeast Supervisory Union, a public
school district.
</P>
<P>
   Though there are strong emotions on both sides of the
school-choice debate, even in Vermont, there is very little data on
how the system is actually working.
</P>
<P>
   So as yet, Mathis said, there's no objective way to know whether
other states should see Vermont as a model.
</P>
<P>
   He'd love to see ``good, honest-to-goodness, quality research on
the effects of the existing system,'' he said, to ``see whether
it's a subsidy for rich parents that really isn't available for
not-so-rich parents. School-choice schemes are put out there as a
panacea. Let's go have a look.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
