u a BC-CALIF-PROP22-BOS &LR;      03-06 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-PROP22-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA WEIGHS SAME-SEX MARRIAGE BAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The door-to-door campaign that Shannon Keating has
been waging after work and on weekends is both overtly political
and painfully personal.
</P>
<P>
   Like scores of gays and lesbians across California, Keating is
asking neighbors and strangers to look closely at her life,
detailed in a three-page letter that she usually stuffs in their
mailboxes, but prefers to put in their hands. In it, she and her
partner of 16 years write of raising a son and daughter together in
Redondo Beach, PTA meetings, and Little League games. They wonder
what kind of threat their family could pose to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to introduce myself and say, `Here's my family,
and I'm who you're afraid of,' '' said Keating, an executive with
20th Television, a division of Fox TV. ``It's real personal. I
don't think they understand who they'd be voting against: me.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurring Keating to activism in her off hours is one of the most
hotly contested measures on Tuesday's ballot, one that proponents
say would uphold the sanctity of marriage and opponents call thinly
disguised bigotry. The measure known as Proposition 22 asks voters
to validate only marriages between one man and one woman. Passage
would bar the state of California from recognizing any other kind.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, state code already allows only a man and a woman to
marry. But it does not prevent California from recognizing unions
formalized in other states _ a loophole that supporters of the
``California Protection of Marriage Initiative'' say must be
closed. Although same-sex marriages are prohibited in all 50
states, they warn that a recent Vermont Supreme Court ruling over
domestic partnership rights, under consideration by that state's
Legislature, could lead the way to weddings featuring two men or
two women.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to define what a family is or what love is,
but we believe that the ideal for marriage is a man and a woman,''
said Robert Glazier, a spokesman for the Yes on 22 campaign. ``We
understand single-family homes, blended homes, extended familes,
but we believe that is the best way for children to be raised. It
sends a strong message.''
</P>
<P>
   The message, however, depends on the messenger.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say Prop 22, which is leading in the polls, would
change little, except to strengthen existing law. They note that 30
other states have passed definition-of-marriage laws, two of them
through ballot intitiatives such as California's.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Godfrey, a controller for a home remodeling contractor and
Yes on 22 advocate, says he is the one being discriminated against.
According to him, 17 of the signs he placed in front of his house
on a busy Fresno street were stolen, two were vandalized, and a
window was broken. He calls the response to his stance ``borderline
hate.'' Other Prop 22 supporters have reported similar incidents
around the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the idea of two men or women marrying because I'm
a Christian and in the eyes of God it's not correct, it's not
morally correct,'' said Godfrey, who has never before felt
compelled to get politically involved. ``But I do not discriminate
against gays. I have been taught to love them.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents scoff at those arguments, saying that Prop 22 would
legalize discrimination against them and possibly force them to
relinquish gains already made. They say the law could be used to
roll back gays' civil rights, overturn domestic partnership
benefits, and prevent hospital visitations where only immediate
family members are allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 issue that people have to understand is that they
don't have to support gay marriage to be against the Knight
Initiative,'' said No on 22 campaign manager Mike Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   The opponents charge that antigay sentiment is at the root of
the measure, sponsored by a conservative Republican state Senator
William (Pete) Knight, who has tried without success to pass laws
against same-sex marriage and whose son is gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very cynical, trying to twist any fears people may
have about gay people into some triumph for them,'' said state
Assemblywoman Sheila Kuehl, who is a lesbian. ``The right wing,
frankly, doesn't care which community they're bashing in which
year. If people are worried about illegal immigration, boom, bring
on immigration as an issue. Now it's gay rights. It's really about
fund-raising and wedge-issue politics. It's ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   The divisions, in fact, have broken down along lines that are
sometimes predictable and sometimes not so predictable.
</P>
<P>
   The Roman Catholic, Southern Baptist and Mormon churches, for
instance, are pushing hard for passage, while several Jewish and
Protestant leaders have come out in opposition. The California
Republican Party has endorsed the measure. Most Democrats running
for office in California oppose it, as does actress and AIDS
activist Sharon Stone, who whipped off her fox coat at a recent
fund-raiser and auctioned if off for $16,000 to fight the iniative.
Talk radio's Laura Schlessinger, known as Dr. Laura, favors
passage.
</P>
<P>
   Less expected, a small group called Gays for 22 recently
declared its support for Prop 22, saying they favor state's rights
and see no harm in the initiative. A group of moderate Republicans
that includes Ward Connerly, who led the drive to abolish
affirmative action, oppose the measure as unncessary government
intrusion into people's private lives.
</P>
<P>
   David Knight, an Air Force Academy graduate and Gulf War fighter
pilot who has been all but estranged from his father since
announcing he was gay, has also spoken out against Prop 22 from his
home in Baltimore. The senator said foes of the measure ``should be
ashamed for exploiting a private family matter for political
gain.'' But the elder Knight has kept mostly quiet in the weeks
leading up to the election.
</P>
<P>
   A Field Poll conducted the last week of February showed the Yes
on 22 campaign leading 53 percent to 40 percent, virtually
unchanged since the previous poll. Other surveys, such as a
nationwide Harris poll earlier this year, have found little support
for legalizing same-sex marriages.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Spiegel and his partner of 15 years, who had a religious
wedding ceremony that is not legally recognized, are raising a
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a simple issue, even if it seems that way,'' said
Spiegel, a real estate attorney in San Francisco. ``We've got to
make people understand that, and the only way we're going to change
their hearts and minds is if they can meet us and learn our stories
and see that they're not so different from their own.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
