<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-CAKES-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRETS OF SUCCESS:   
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim.  By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Fabrice Marcon was born and raised in France and
started cooking when he was 14, coming to the United States after
serving as a sous chef under Paul Bocuse. The guy knows how to
cook, which shows at the charming Hyde Street Bistro, which he
bought in 1997. Here he brings his talents to the table to create
simple, straightforward French-California food.
<TEXT>
<P>
   His Potato Roquefort Cakes are a great example of his cooking
philosophy. He mixes creamy mashed potatoes with crumbly Roquefort
cheese, forms them into patties and sautees them to crisp the
outside. He then puts them on a bed of greens studded with juicy
ripe pears, setting up a sweet-tangy contrast. To bring it all
together, he drizzles a little hazelnut oil over the salad, adding
a nutty nuance and creating a clever twist to the classic nuts,
cheese and fruit combination.
</P>
<P>
   The small, one-room restaurant is unpretentious yet charming,
with an alcove off to one side for larger parties. It's a perfect
neighborhood spot for rustic yet sophisticated country fare.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Hyde Street Bistro, 1521 Hyde St. (at Pacific), San &LR; 
 &LR; Francisco; (415) 441-7778. Dinner nightly. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Firm blue cheese. &LR;  If the cheese is too soft, the potato cake
will fall apart when frying. You want the cheese to be firm and
crumbly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Ripe pears. &LR;  The soft texture and sweetness of pears sets up
a pleasing contrast to the pungent, hot cheese in the cakes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Hazelnut oil. &LR;  Drizzling the oil over the top completes a
classic triad of flavors: fruit, cheese and nuts.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; POTATO ROQUEFORT CAKES
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 large russet potatoes, scrubbed
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces firm Roquefort cheese, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   11/2 ripe Anjou pears, stemmed, cored and diced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound mixed salad greens
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped fresh tarragon
</P>
<P>
   Vinaigrette (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Hazelnut oil
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Pierce the potatoes in several places, then bake in a preheated
375 degrees oven until they can be easily pierced with the tip of a
sharp knife, about 1 hour. Remove from the oven and set aside until
they are cool enough to handle.
</P>
<P>
   Cut them in half and scoop the soft flesh into a bowl. Mash with
a fork. Add the cheese and 1 tablespoon of the olive oil; stir to
combine. Taste, then season with pepper and salt, if needed. Form
the mixture into 4 equal patties, about 1/4 to 1/2 inch thick.
Cover and refrigerate about 2 hours, until chilled.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the remaining 1 tablespoon oil in a skillet over medium
heat. Add the potato cakes and fry until brown on both sides, about
5 to 7 minutes, turning once. Transfer the cakes to a baking sheet.
Bake until heated through, about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the pears with the salad greens and chopped tarragon. Toss
with the vinaigrette and divide among serving plates. Top each with
a Roquefort cake and drizzle with a little hazelnut oil.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 520 calories, &LR;   &LR; 16 g protein, 38 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 36 g fat (13 g saturated), 52 mg cholesterol, 1,087
mg sodium, &LR;   &LR; 3 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
VINAIGRETTE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 shallot, minced
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Whisk together the mustard, vinegar and minced shallot in a
small bowl. Slowly whisk in the oil. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 1/3 cup.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER TABLESPOON: &LR;   &LR; 60 calories, &LR;   &LR; 0 protein, 0 carbohydrate, 7
g &LR;   &LR; fat (1 g saturated), 0 cholesterol, 33 mg sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
