<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTE-SAUCE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 TASTER'S CHOICE: Spicy Pasta Sauces Can Empty Your Wallet   By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  The booming market for pasta sauce shows no sign
of slowing, and the latest trend appears to be ``authentic''
varieties based on Italian recipes.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year the panel tasted jarred  &LR; puttanesca &LR;  sauces, which
combine chopped tomatoes, capers, olives, garlic, anchovies and
spices. Today's panel tried another Italian classic:  &LR; arrabbiata &LR; ,
a spicy tomato sauce with chile peppers.
</P>
<P>
   Most of today's sauces were significantly more expensive than
regular jarred sauces, ranging from $5.89 for just over nine ounces
to a wallet-emptying $10.99 for 32 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists couldn't agree on a favorite, and weren't particularly
impressed with the category as a whole. The biggest complaint was
that the spice in many of the sauces was too harsh.
</P>
<P>
   First place went to  &UR; Rao's Homemade &LR;  (24 ounces, $10.99 at
Andronico's), the most expensive brand sampled. Panelists liked the
tomato flavor, but thought it wasn't spicy enough to be considered
an arrabbiata. Several disliked the texture, which they described
as gelatinous and floury. Three would buy it, one might buy it, and
one would not.
</P>
<P>
   Imported  &UR; Rustichella D'Abruzzo &LR;  (9.53 ounces, $5.89 at Whole
Foods) came in second. Two panelists liked the flavor, but others
found it acidic and metallic, and objected to an overly smooth
texture. One would buy it, two might buy it, and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   Third place was a tie between  &UR; Coppola Mammarella &LR;  (26 ounces,
$5.99 at Andronico's) and  &UR; Don Pomodoro &LR;  (25.4 ounces, $5.99 at
Andronico's).
</P>
<P>
   One panelist thought the Coppola sauce looked the most homemade,
but two others thought it looked and tasted watery. Many thought
garlic overpowered other flavors. Two might buy it; three would
not.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were divided on Don Pomodoro, the other imported
brand. One thought it was too spicy and harsh, but two others liked
the spice. Still another thought it was too mild, tasting more like
stewed tomatoes. Two might buy it; three would not.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth place went to  &UR; Coco Pazzo &LR;  (24 ounces, $7.49 at Rainbow
Grocery). Three panelists thought the sauce was so overseasoned
with dried herbs that it tasted bitter; one described it as
``oregano sauce with some tomato.'' One might buy it; four would
not.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Donna Katzl,
chef-owner, Cafe For All Seasons, San Francisco; Roland Passot,
chef-owner of La Folie in San Francisco and Left Bank in Larkspur
and Menlo Park; Kim Severson, Chronicle staff writer; and Kirk
Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San Francisco. All products are
tasted blind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
