<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-EYES-DVD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EYES WIDE SHUT' OPENS ON DVD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stanley Kubrick's ``Eyes Wide Shut'' arrives on VHS and DVD on
Tuesday, marking the anniversary of the director's death on March
7, 1999. When the film was released, last August, it was greeted
with a host of negative reviews. Its theatrical run was over in two
weeks and, while it subsequently grossed a respectable $155 million
worldwide, it didn't live up to its prerelease hype.
</P>
<P>
   The DVD version is a remarkable way to appreciate a much
misunderstood masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   The DVD includes the 159-minute film and 42 minutes of brief
interviews with stars Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman and, for some
inexplicable reason, Steven Spielberg, conducted after the film's
release. It's also the American version, with the ``offending'' few
seconds of a couple doing the NC-17 obscured. (To protect
</P>
<P>
   EYES, Page N14 &QL; 
our Puritanical sensibilites, a pair of partygoers were digitally
readjusted.) Some may be disappointed that the DVD doesn't include
the uncensored, mature European version.
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick masterfully weaves story, performance, language,
lighting, color, editing, framing, music, and camera movement into
a complex symphony about the infinite capacity of human beings to
hide their secrets, deceive themselves, and ritualize away their
own humanity.
</P>
<P>
   When the film was released, most critics were dismissive. They
evaluated ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' Kubrick's first film since 1987's
``Full Metal Jacket,'' as if it were just another Friday movie
opening. Many of them didn't even respect it enough to hate it.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Siegel, in a sharp, smart celebration of the film in the
October issue of Harper's, lined up a sampling of critics' quotes:
</P>
<P>
   --``This two hour and 39 minute gloss on Arthur Schnitzler's
fantasmagoric novella feels like a rough draft at best.'' J.
Hoberman in The Village Voice.
</P>
<P>
   --``Ridiculously though intellectually overhyped for the very
marginal entertainment, edification and titillation it provides
over its somewhat turgid 159 minute running time.'' Andrew Sarris
in The New York Observer.
</P>
<P>
   --``In `Eyes Wide Shut' nothing works.'' Louis Menand in The New
York Review of Books.
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick, who died six months before the film's release, may have
foreshadowed the critical and commercial American reaction to his
final film when he named it ``Eyes Wide Shut.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A simple story &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The story is simple _ at least on the surface. Dr. Bill (Cruise)
and Alice (Kidman) are a well-to-do married New York couple. They
have, as the saying goes, everything going for them. Beauty.
Wealth. A healthy child. They go to an elegant Christmas party
where an elderly Hungarian flirts with Alice and two models flirt
with him. Downstairs, in the ballroom, the zombielike guests look
very much like the resurrected ghosts at the Overlook in ``The
Shining'' (1980). Upstairs, tucked away in a bathroom, a hooker is
passed out from an overdose. She's revived by Dr. Bill. But the
incident remains a secret between the doctor and his host, the
oleaginous Mr. Ziegler (Sydney Pollack).
</P>
<P>
   Later, when Dr. Bill and Alice are home in bed smoking
marijuana, she reveals a secret to him about a previous dalliance
she had with a sailor. This admission ignites a series of events
that involve Bill going on a dreamlike trip through a faux
Manhattan, much like the Nighttown sequence in James Joyce's
``Ulysses.''
</P>
<P>
   The story is set at Christmastime, and Kubrick opens virtually
every sequence with tired, lifeless Christmas trees _ reinforcing
the mood with Christmas cards and garish lights. Where's the peace?
Where's the good will? Gifts are no longer an expression of
generosity but a conditioned response to a tradition repeated so
many times it's lost its meaning.
</P>
<P>
   When the film came out in August there was a bellowing hue and
cry that Kubrick had promised a sexy film with Cruise and Kidman.
Frontal nudity. Hot stuff. Porno for the intelligentsia. First of
all, he promised no such thing. Even the film's most virulent
detractors would admit that if Stanley Kubrick wanted to make an
erotic film, he could have easily constructed the lustiest film
ever made.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a sexy film, but a film about sex. And Kubrick has some
very tantalizing notions on the subject. The only sexy scenes are
the black-and-white sequences featuring Alice and the naval officer
and, most important, imagined by her husband.
</P>
<P>
   In one of Kubrick's most brilliant touches _ the much-maligned
orgy sequence _ he manages to make gorgeous naked women dull. With
a faux Gregorian chant on the soundtrack and a central figure
dressed in red conducting the proceedings in a cathedral-like
rotunda, Kubrick suggests that even sex has become hammered into a
quasireligion. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A critical debate &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Using sex, Kubrick shows us how that spontaneous event is
crushed by repetitive ritual.
</P>
<P>
   One of the critical debates involves whether the film is a total
or partial dream. Kubrick doesn't provide any obvious clues such as
out-of-focus cinematography or hazy imagery. But his New York City
is a quasi-Manhattan. There are identifiable landmarks such as
yellow cabs and newsstands, but the odd lighting and set designs
suggest a twilight zone somewhere between sleep and awareness. This
is the state where Kubrick seems most comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick has an undeserved reputation as a prefab director, that
is, a cold, calculating film scientist who forces the actors to go
through his minutely detailed, preconceived choreographed motions.
Nothing could be further from the truth. Casting Cruise and Kidman
was not for the obvious marketing appeal, but because Kubrick was
curious to find out what would happen when he put a celebrated,
married, acting couple through a film that centered on a
nightmarish marital crisis. He was genuinely curious about what
might transpire.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most difficult sequences, when Dr. Bill is
confronted by a gang of homophobic toughs, it's clear that Kubrick
is using the unsubstantiated rumors of Cruise's bisexuality to
inspire both the actor and character to new heights of
interpretation. Kubrick was using Cruise and Kidman as conduits to
the people he was really after _ the audience. He might have
thought that if he got the two stars to raise the bar, the viewers
would follow.
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick, according to Cruise in the DVD interview, told him,
``We've got to earn every scene with this character.'' And he did.
Kidman did as well. Courageous, tough, and sensitive, Kidman's
Alice, lost in wonderland, has moments when she sees through all
the conditioned behavior. And Kidman left the film with a profound
respect for its maker.
</P>
<P>
   As she relates on the DVD interview, ``Stanley lived films . . .
he loved films . . . he had a belief in the purity of filmmaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nicholson, who gave a stunning performance in ``The
Shining'' _ another film that wasn't given its artistic due until
years after its original release _ endorses Kubrick's working
methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stanley invites you to participate in his films,'' he says.
``You're never allowed a shortcut. You can't go through the
motions. Not only was he a great filmmaker, he was also a great
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   A great audience is what ``Eyes Wide Shut'' deserves.
</P>
<P>
   One virtue of ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' especially on DVD, is that,
like all of Kubrick's other films, it improves with each viewing.
</P>
<P>
   In the final analysis, there are clues to be left and plots to
be served and characters to be drawn, but what remains is an enigma
as puzzling as the apes confronting the monolith in ``2001: A Space
Odyssey'' (1968).
</P>
<P>
   In a piece of irony that would probably be too much for the
subtle Kubrick, the critical pounding delivered by critics to his
last film is a confirmation of his theme _ that we've become so
conditioned by the manipulative cliches of movies that when one
arrives that doesn't fit the mold, people don't know what to think.
Watch ``Eyes Wide Shut'' with both eyes wide open.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 1349EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
