</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics. 
 
 WINE POTPOURRI: Clouds Hover Over Vintage '99  By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Preliminary California wine-grape crush numbers
are in for vintage '99 and the news is mixed. On the upside, the
California Agricultural Statistics Service reports that some 2.6
million tons of wine grapes were crushed in 1999, up 3 percent from
1998's crush of 2.5 million wine-grape tons.
<P>
   The downside is that tonnage for Chardonnay, America's most
popular white wine, is off. Fact is, reports wine business
consultants Motto, Kryla &AMP; Fisher, 1999 Chardonnay tonnage
statistically was even with that of 1998, but did not reach the
same tonnage harvested in 1997. Eric Sims, of MK&AMP;F, says that
458,000 tons of Chardonnay were crushed in 1999, compared to
428,000 tons in '98 and 491,000 tons in '97.
</P>
<P>
   ``What that means,'' explains Sims, ``is that the demand for all
California wine, including Chardonnay, is greater than the
California wine supply.'' He adds that a fixed supply can mean only
one thing; ``Consumers can expect higher prices for California
wine.''
</P>
<P>
   Sims points out that coastal Chardonnay brands (Robert Mondavi
Coastal, Beaulieu Vineyard Coastal) will be hardest hit by the
lower '99 crush, the result of a cool summer, since the outp
</P>
<P>
   A`'or
Chardonnay in the Central Coast region that extends from Monterey
to Santa Barbara fell in '99. This is especially bothersome since
the region has experienced heavy grapevine plantings in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   The sunny side of the 1999 California wine-grape picture, says
Sims, is consumers can expect some very good '99 wines at low
prices from the Central Valley. ``Central Valley wine-grape areas
like Lodi experienced excellent growing weather in '99, so I think
we'll see some outstanding wines, like Lodi Zinfandels, at very
good prices.'' Sims predicts that '99 Central Valley wines will be
of higher quality at lower prices than coastal wines.
</P>
<P>
   Red-wine drinkers, especially with a taste for Cabernet
Sauvignon above $10, also may be looking at higher prices. The
Agriculture Department report shows that the 1999 crop for Cabernet
Sauvignon in Napa, Sonoma and Monterey were all off _ a clear
indication, says Sims, that prices are likely to go up for premium
Cabernet Sauvignon. The Cabernet crop for 1999 was down 12 percent
in Napa County, 13 percent in Sonoma County and a whopping 26
percent in Monterey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Meanwhile in Australia &LR;
</P>
<P>
   While California deals with a problematic 1999 wine-grape
vintage, Australia reports a record crush in 2000 of 1.2 million
tons, up from the 1.12 million tons posted in 1999. An official of
the Winemakers' Federation of Australia states, however, that the
record 2000 crush is about 8 percent less than earlier
expectations. Blame late-season cold weather for the loss.
</P>
<P>
   Couple the healthy growth from the 2000 vintage in Australia
with the country's soaring wine exports and you have a new
competition to the already over-heated and over-priced U.S. wine
market. In less then 10 years, Australia doubled the area under
wine grapes and boosted wine production over the last 15 years from
10 million liters in 1985-'86 to approximately 200 million liters
in 1989-'99.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bragging Rights &LR;
</P>
<P>
   What winery, in the Northern or Southern Hemisphere, can
rightfully lay claim to the first wine released from grapes
harvested in the year 2000?
</P>
<P>
   Greenwood Ridge Vineyards, in Mendocino's Anderson Valley, will
release Year of the Dragon, a ``very, very, very late-harvest white
Riesling'' on March 15, saying the wine is the ``first enological
baby of the millennium.'' Late-harvest wines usually are picked
after the other grapes are in, sometimes as late as December, but
rarely into January of the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwood Ridge 2000 Year of the Dragon Late Harvest Riesling,
will sell for $20 and be available throughout the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wine Basics &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Merlot is fast becoming one of America's most popular red wines,
but it isn't without controversy. Once a blending grape in Bordeaux
that stood in the shadow of Cabernet Sauvignon, Merlot is more
widely planted there now than Cabernet. The shift is mainly due to
changing worldwide tastes for softer consumer-friendly red wines.
</P>
<P>
   Merlot from the best Pomerol chateau, such as Petrus, will age
for 30 years, producing an elegant wine with great depth. But
so-called New World Merlots, especially from California, are softer
and rounder.
</P>
<P>
   Merlot is grown in all of California's main wine regions and
does well in Eastern Washington, Southern Oregon and New York's
Long Island. Popular Merlots also are available from Chile and
Northern Italy. New Zealand Merlots and Merlot-Cabernet blends from
Hawkes Bay are the latest finds from the Southern Hemisphere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
