 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: The Chronicle regularly features ``Best Way'', a
column in which the Food staff tries to establish the most reliable
way to cook many of our favorite foods. 
 
 BEST WAY: How to Dress a Salad   By Margarita Camacho  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  The task of dressing a salad seems simple enough,
but the two basic methods of produce very different results.
<TEXT>
<P>
   To find out which way is best, The Chronicle Food department
began with two straightforward salads. Each was composed of 21/2
ounces of mixed baby greens, 1/2 thinly sliced cucumber, 1/2
julienned carrot and 11/2 medium tomatoes, cut into wedges. We then
made a basic vinaigrette using 1 part red wine vinegar to 2 parts
olive oil, and seasoned it to taste with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   For the first salad, we mixed all the vegetables and greens
together, then added 21/2 tablespoons of the dressing. We tossed
it, seasoned it with two large pinches of salt and pepper, and
tossed again.
</P>
<P>
   For the second salad, we dressed each component individually. We
tossed the greens with 1 tablespoon vinaigrette and seasoned them
with a pinch of salt and pepper. We then tossed the carrot,
cucumber and tomatoes separately in their own bowls with 1 teaspoon
vinaigrette per bowl and very small pinches of salt and pepper.
Finally, we combined all the ingredients in one large bowl.
</P>
<P>
   We did not expect much difference between the two salads, but we
were wrong. With the first method, the salad looked good and tasted
fine, but was nothing special. But with the second method, where
the components were first dressed individually, the salad not only
looked better overall but each ingredient appeared brighter and
more appealing on its own.
</P>
<P>
   The second salad also had better flavor. The greens tasted
bright, the carrots were light, the cucumbers were refreshing and
the tomatoes seemed more tomato-y.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a difference in the wilt factor. After letting
the salads sit for a few hours, the first one was limp and looked
tired. The second one wilted a bit, but retained its bright
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEST WAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Treat each component separately. Toss half the dressing with the
greens and use the remaining dressing on individual ingredients.
Finally, toss everything together. The taste and appearance are
worth the trouble.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 1350EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
