<HEADER>
A8223 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-STAGE-HIRSCH-BOS &LR;      03-06 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-HIRSCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILLING IN THE CANVAS OF `ART' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN DEZELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Art'' is a play about three men, a painting, and lofty ideas
that blow a 15-year friendship apart.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly the standard stuff of contemporary stage comedy, it is
less so because the characters are middle-aged professional
Parisians; the painting is abstract; and the insults lobbed _ one
character calls another an ``enemy of modernism'' _ are not
fighting words, at least in most American vocabularies.
</P>
<P>
   But Paris-born playwright Yasmina Reza's ``Art,'' which won the
1998 Tony Award for best play and the Laurence Olivier Award for
best comedy in 1997, was a hit on Broadway and in London's West
End. It's been staged in more than two dozen countries in the past
three years. The touring production, starring Judd Hirsch, has been
playing to critical accolades and full houses in cities all over
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch plays Marc, an aeronautical engineer appalled that his
close friend Serge (Cotter Smith), a successful dermatologist, has
paid $40,000 for a monochrome painting.
</P>
<P>
   It's all white, sputters Marc. All right, it's got three
off-white lines in it. Whatever: It's still execrable, a bad joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marc believes that he's developed a certain taste in this
world which is worthwhile,'' Hirsch said recently over lunch in
Boston. ``He believes that he's not quite like everybody else. And
he's come to understand that there's a value in that. He's someone
who tests his identity by sort of exposing hypocrisy or exposing
anything that is less than honest.''
</P>
<P>
   As Marc sees it, Serge's pricey monotone canvas embodies the
essence of silly intellectual pretense. Worse, the work seems to be
an emblem of Serge's newfound identity _ his embrace of an
intellectual life and social set that doesn't involve his onetime
mentor, Marc.
</P>
<P>
   Serge gets upset, irritated, then angry with his friend's
response. He defends the painting on aesthetic grounds, pointing
out that the purchase is a good investment. That is yet another
signal, to Marc, that civilization as he likes to think of it has
come to an end. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A third opinion &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marc turns to their mutual friend, Yvan (Jack Willis), to
arbitrate. But Yvan considers himself ``a lightweight, I have no
opinions.'' Preoccupied with a new job and a marriage he probably
shouldn't be getting into, he tries to placate Marc and Serge _ and
ends up alienating both.
</P>
<P>
   On a night the three have plans to go out to dinner and a movie,
their differences over the painting devolve into a three-way
argument. Accusations are hurled, grievances unfurled. Serge and
Marc come close to blows and Yvan ends up mistakenly getting hit.
</P>
<P>
   Marc, Serge, and Yvan wonder what they have ever had in common,
and realize that their relationship has instinctively relied on
leaving vital things unsaid. Honesty is a form of betrayal among
these three. They're awed by the seeming impossibility of
maintaining close friendships over time _ but more so by the
prospect of not doing so.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a relationship you would ordinarily run into,''
said Hirsch.
</P>
<P>
   ``American men do have friendships, but they're not friendships
like this. There's nothing about sports in this whole damned thing.
There's nothing about competition in any other way. There's nothing
about going out in a boisterous way _ like to a sports bar.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled having ``relationships like this _ arguments like
this'' when he was a teenager and as an undergraduate at City
College in New York. ``When I was 19, 18, 20, my friends and I
would go to the movies, we would go to concerts, we'd sit home and
listen to symphonies. We'd go to the museum. And we had tremendous
arguments. When you're that age, the last thing you learned is the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very into sports, don't kid yourself. We were such
fanatics about baseball, basketball; the New York Knicks or the
Yankees, whoever was on. We had tremendous arguments about that.
But that didn't stop us from being about Nietzsche or Schopenhauer.
They were just about as important as baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   A native New Yorker, Hirsch, 64, took a ``funny route'' from the
Bronx to Broadway, where he made his debut in ``Barefoot in the
Park'' in 1966. He took engineering courses at City College,
transferred to Cooper Union to study architecture, did a brief
stint in the Army, then went back to City. ``I put all the courses
together, got my degree in physics, and immediately walked into
acting school!'' He shrugged, and added: ``Ha!'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Heady times &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He sometimes wishes he had become a scientist or architect. He
designed a country house in upstate New York where he lives with
his wife and young daughter during the summer and on weekends
they're not in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   But the late '50s and early '60s were heady times in New York
theater. ``At that time the off-Broadway scene was very active. New
playwrights were being born every five minutes. Styles were being
developed, companies were being formed, that would last anywhere
from 1 to 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so taken with what I saw off-Broadway _ I even saw
Eugene Ionesco plays _ where do you see Eugene Ionesco plays? I saw
these productions that you knew you had to do _ Eugene O'Neill's
``The Iceman Cometh.'' Four and three quarter hours at the old
Circle in the Square in New York. Jason Robards was in it. Anne
Meara was the girl at the bar, I think. Peter Falk was the
bartender. I didn't know who these people were at that time, and I
don't think they knew who they were either. I saw Edward Albee's
``The Zoo Story.'' That made me want to be an actor more than
anything I've ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were dynamic, thoughtful plays _ they were not about
great themes. They were personal. Language plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Plays like ``Art.''
</P>
<P>
   A two-time Emmy winner for ``Taxi,'' Hirsch is better known for
his TV work and films such as ``Ordinary People'' and ``Running on
Empty'' than stage acting. But his theater career has been
impressive. He won Tony Awards for ``I'm Not Rappaport'' and
``Conversations With My Father,'' both by Herb Gardner.
</P>
<P>
   He was willing to take on an increasingly rare role _ a star who
tours in a Broadway play _ because he finds ``Art'' unusually rich
and challenging.
</P>
<P>
   Reza provides the sketchiest of details about each of the
characters, he said. There's tremendous leeway for actors to
``investigate, to make up stuff.'' Marc, for example, talks about
Paula, who shares his life. ``It's up to the actor to decide
whether to play him married.'' Hirsch doesn't; others do.
</P>
<P>
   Each company that performs the show reads it very differently.
Brian Cox portrayed Marc as a curmudgeonly character on Broadway.
Others play him as a man who seldom questions the veracity of his
own opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says he's a maverick. He likes to think he does things that
are unexpected,'' said Hirsch. But the actor sees Marc as more of a
self-doubter. He wonders: ``Does he feel a little on the stale
side?'' His character is less an intellectual snob than someone who
thinks other people are trying to put one over on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a guy who looks at a painting like this and says `Get me
the guy who did this!' ''
</P>
<P>
   A nimble 90-minute ensemblepiece that's both thought-provoking
and funny, the play is ``full of ideas and conflict and drama,''
Hirsch said. It's also open to interpretation _ ``as blank as the
painting in a lot of ways.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
