<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8225 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-DJS-BOS &LR;      03-06 1772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-DJS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY'RE THE NEW POP STARS, THEY'RE THE SCRATCH MASTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A thundering bass beat slams off the walls of the BBC
2000 club. Looking up from his turntables, the manic DJ Skribble
takes the crowd higher by shouting into the microphone: ``Make some
noise! Are you ready to blow the roof off this place?'' The answer
is immediate, as the youthful, audience starts shaking harder on
the dance floor and in every nook and cranny of the sold-out club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throw your hands up!'' adds Skribble, a nonstop energy source
who flashes a big smile under his New York Yankees cap, knowing
that the crowd is now his.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, in this 1,500-capacity Saugus club north of Boston,
Skribble, a nationally known DJ who hosts ``MTV Jams,'' is besieged
by fans and autograph hounds. ``I come here every time he plays.
He's totally out of control. He really makes you want to move,''
says Scott Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him on MTV's NewYear's show. I just love him,'' says
Tammy Crane says of Skribble's house music and hip-hop fusion,
which he enhances by creating drum loops and on-the-spot remixes.
</P>
<P>
   Skribble, 26, a former bad boy who says he used to ``deface
public property and bomb trains'' during his youth in New York,
greets each smitten fan. ``I'm on the road every week _ next week
is Las Vegas, then Orlando, but hearing people say you did a good
job is worth more to me than any money I could get,'' he states.
</P>
<P>
   That's saying something, because these days, DJs are making
eye-opening incomes _ as much as or more than some rock stars, if
you factor in club appearances, chart-hit remixes for the likes of
Madonna, Celine Dion, and Whitney Houston; and fees for DJ
compilation albums, which can earn them $25,000 per album.
</P>
<P>
   In the nation's hottest dance clubs _ including Boston's Avalon
and BBC 2000 in Saugus, and others in New York, Miami, Chicago,
London, and other dance meccas _ the top-name DJs now command
nightly paychecks of up to $15,000. That's a far cry from the $25
to $50 club fees they often took home during the disco era in the
'70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line: They are like rock stars now,'' says Tom
Calderone, vice president of MTV. ``They get picked up in
limousines, they get treated like kings.'' (Only occasionally are
DJs treated like queens. Jackie Christie and DJ Rap are two women
who tour at this level, but it's a world dominated by men.)
</P>
<P>
   When top DJs come to town, the clubs pay for their air fare,
hotels, and meals, according to Steve Adelman, executive director
of the Lyons Group clubs on Lansdowne Street, Boston's dance
epicenter, with Avalon, Axis, and the Karma Club.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the money the DJs make in clubs is mainly profit, except
for paying to upgrade their record collections and purchase the
special-effects units and remixers they might bring to the rooms.
(The clubs supply the turntables.) But the DJs don't have to divide
the money among musicians and roadies, hence their higher profit
margins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have 12 to 15 out-of-town DJs coming every month. It
has become quite an operation,'' says Adelman, who gets
particularly excited about the Friday ``Avaland'' series at Avalon.
It's a Studio 54-style night of DJ music and theatrics that often
includes scantily clad dancers hired to shimmy on platforms or
special chairs above the crowd. ``Anything to boost the energy,''
adds co-owner John Lyons, who notes that the DJs often feed off the
extra stimulation.
</P>
<P>
   The energy couldn't have been any higher than on a recent Friday
when New York-based Jonathan Peters, considered one of the top 10
DJs in the world, manned the club's turntables. His star rose last
year after he remixed Whitney Houston's ``My Love Is Your Love,''
which went to No. 4 on the Billboard charts. Peters has his own
label (Deeper Records) and two studios in New York, where he's also
remixed songs by Paula Cole, Jon Secada, and Montell Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a music producer, but I'm also all about the party,'' says
Peters, who thrilled the 2,000-strong capacity crowd at Avalon by
spinning trance music, house music (with a deep bass throb), and
what he calls ``cutting-edge Top 40,'' meaning songs that are
destined for Top 40 radio, but only after being played in the clubs
first. His Whitney Houston remix, for instance, was played at his
weekly Saturday gigs at the Sound Factory in New York a full six
months before it was released to radio. (A song that went a similar
route was Cher's ``Believe,'' which Peters didn't work on, but
which just won a Grammy for best dance recording.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Vocal House'' tune &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A 16-year veteran who can recall times when club owners paid him
nothing after a slow night, Peters is part of a growing breed of
DJs who bring their own music to clubs (in the form of remixes and
original songs), which further builds their mystique as stars. At
Avalon, Peters played an original ``vocal house'' tune, which
merged the deep groove of house with a gently soulful R &AMP; B vocal
layered on top by a young studio singer named Karessa Jones. Titled
``Corrupt,'' it sounded like another hit in the making.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything changed after I worked with Whitney,'' says Peters.
``I've got major labels coming to me from all over now to remix
records. I can work around the clock if I want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Each Saturday, Peters does work around the clock at the Sound
Factory, where he starts his shift at 11 p.m. and doesn't finish
until 2 p.m. the next day. He touches on many styles of dance music
and will have 3,000 people partying in the club at 10 in the
morning. That's quite different from the parochial club times in
Boston, where he'll spin at Avalon from 11 p.m. to just 2 a.m., the
city-ordained closing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't condense 15 hours into 3 hours,'' says Peters.
``What you do is just try to make it a best-of for 3 hours. It's
hard, but it's still great to see people having a good time. Hey,
it's a blessing to be able to do this. Even when I made $100 a
night, I still loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many DJs who have paid their dues, Peters launched his
career despite the protests of his parents. ``My family 15 years
ago would say, `You want to be a DJ? What are you doing?' But now
that I've had a level of success with my remixes and touring, they
don't say that anymore.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All the world's a club &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real global scene now,'' adds John Digweed, a popular
British DJ who recently played at Axis. ``I go to South Africa and
to Russia now. There are so many countries to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, DJs are even more popular in Europe, where most name
DJs are booked six months in advance. Digweed, and his
oft-recording partner, Sasha, have more work than they can handle
there, but are also becoming increasingly popular in the States.
</P>
<P>
   ``On this last tour of America, I played to 25,000 people in two
weeks,'' says Digweed, whose specialty is fusing trance and house
music, which he did while accompanied by a spectacular light show
at Axis. ``It really has reached a point where DJs are looked upon
as the pop stars of the dance scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many of the 20-something fans at Axis chanted ``Digweed!
Digweed!'' as he finished his trippy set. ``It's a pretty big buzz
when you hear that,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a lot more respect these days,'' notes DJ Boris, a
transplanted Russian now based in New York. ``You are the act when
it comes to a club today. Just two years ago, you were still a
second-class citizen in many places. You seemed irrelevant to the
club.''
</P>
<P>
   That all changed with the remix phenomenon _ and the recent
emergence into the mainstream of Fatboy Slim (who spun at the Karma
Club before his dance-pop hits ``Rockafella Skank'' and ``Praise
You'' broke last year), the English techno group the Chemical
Brothers, and Moby, who came from the DJ culture and has also had
pop hits.
</P>
<P>
   More DJs are likewise part of touring bands. Where once drum
solos were obligatory parts of live shows, there's now the sight of
rock star Beck letting his DJ crank up a turntable solo. It's the
same with hip-hop queen Lauryn Hill, who holds a musical ``battle''
during her show by pitting her DJ's solo, improvised turntable
scratchings, against vocals from her singers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the record, on the road &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ``rave'' culture of the late '80s and early '90s _ in which
all-night dance parties were held at various official and
unofficial sites _ also spurred the popularity of DJs. Two British
brothers, Steve and Jon Levy, who produced some of the early raves
in Los Angeles, now run Moonshine Music, which they tout as the
first DJ compilation record label, having begun in 1993. Their
roster includes DJs Micro, Carl Cox, Keiko, Cirrus, and Christopher
Lawrence. They will often sell between 100,000 and 200,000 copies
of each record _ not exactly Alanis Morissette numbers, but the
sales are growing with each release.
</P>
<P>
   Moonshine is also assembling its fourth annual tour, which will
feature many of its DJs going to clubs around the country in
September. And, for the first time, the Moonshine tour has a
sponsor _ Listen.com, a heavyweight Internet firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very happy to get such a major sponsor because it helps
legitimize what we do,'' says Steve Levy. ``It shows that the
corporate world wants to come into what is still a street-level
thing.'' In May Moonshine will launch a new Web site, djmixed.com,
a search engine for electronic music that will also feature a
DJ-mix radio station.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the top-name DJs still come from the music-industry
centers of New York and London. One DJ hoping to buck this trend is
Boston's Chris DeSimone, 28, who spins every Thursday and Saturday
at the new Club Play in suburban Malden. ``The goal for me is to
produce remixes. When you become a producer, you get much bigger,''
says DeSimone, a go-getter who is making national contacts thanks
to just starting a once-a-month gig at the House of Blues in Los
Angeles. Last Sunday, DeSimone played there for an audience that
included actor Ben Affleck and singer Paula Cole. They had come to
see the latest hot-shot DJ from the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Today's all-star DJs are making money beyond their wildest
dreams, but many also know that, like rock stars, it can all vanish
in a hurry given the intense competition and fickle public tastes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to remember that it's a gift to be doing this,''
concludes DJ Skribble. ``I've gotten to travel the world and things
have blossomed since I got on MTV, but I know that any second it
could be taken away from me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
