<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8260 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-LOUIE-BOS &LR;      03-06 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-LOUIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SORROW BEHIND THE HUMOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE BARBARIANS ARE COMING 
By David Wong Louie. Putnam. 
372 pp. $23.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good Lord, this man is funny. But as with the best comic
writers, the humor in David Wong Louie's fiction is an elegant
vessel for the rest of life: for its pure tragedies, half-baked
sorrows, and ordinary messes. His highly regarded 1991 story
collection, ``Pangs of Love,'' showcased his talent for the bleakly
absurd, casting the shadows of the multigenerational immigrant
experience onto the fictional milieu of alienation and flight.
``The Barbarians Are Coming'' is his first novel, and it uses those
thematic conceits with even greater virtuosity. By placing the
emotional nexus of his story between a Chinese-born father and his
only son, Louie has taken the love-hate tendrils of any
parent-child bond _ the shame, tenderness, and too-late silences _
and made them ache with longing and specificity.
</P>
<P>
   If every immigrant experience has to bear its particular burden,
in the Chinese-American family, it's the matter of honor _ which
can translate as redemption to one generation and a prison sentence
to the next. For Sterling Lung, the sense of duty that his parents,
Genius and Zsa Zsa, always hounded him about is merely another
obstacle to be cleared on his way out the door: away from creepy
Chinese medicinal herbs, arranged marriages to old-country brides,
the familiar smell (work and bleach) of his father's laundry in New
Jersey. Cruel irony, then, that Sterling finds himself flirting
with a parody of the yellow-peril fool that he and his parents most
feared. A Swarthmore graduate who eschews the medical career of his
parents' dreams for a stint at the Culinary Institute of America,
Sterling builds a life mainly characterized by its non-Chinese
qualities: a rich Jewish bride _ Bliss! _ whom he doesn't really
love, a job cooking fabulous French food for a bunch of
unappreciative WASP women in tony Connecticut. And before you can
say ``spicy three-flavor chicken,'' Sterling has his own cable-TV
cooking show _ where he's supposed to talk fast, chop faster, and
make jokes about his heritage, all under the umbrella of ``The
Peeking Duck.''
</P>
<P>
   The barbarians of Louie's title refer both to the Americans his
parents must endure and the potential dangers they believe their
children face: ``In their eyes I was a scoundrel,'' thinks Sterling
in his chef's apron, ``a dumb-as-dirt ingrate. This was their
reward for their sacrifice, leaving home for America, for lean
lives among the barbarians, so I might enjoy penicillin and daily
beef and be spared Mao and dreary collectivism.'' The knife
Sterling wields in the kitchen is barely a match for that of his
creator, whose sendups of the Richfield Ladies' Club and Sterling's
in-laws are as fiercely accurate as they are hilarious. When the
ladies get tipsy one night after a special meal, they begin to
guess the height of their little chef _ and decide, amid their
drunken gaiety, that the winner will get to take him home. And when
he still can't be corralled to cook won-ton cliches for them, they
replace him _ with an authentic Chinese guy they found washing
dishes at a place called the First Wok.
</P>
<P>
   Too often, comic novels can rely on humor as a facile shortcut,
thereby diminishing their emotional arc, but Louie's satire
achieves the opposite effect. If ``The Barbarians Are Coming''
weren't so funny, it would kill you. This perception dawns on you
slowly: Lulled into the easy framework of Bliss (a self-centered
dental student who's getting back at Daddy with her Chinese
boyfriend) and the Richfield Ladies, you don't see the freight
train of realism coming. With their all-consuming laundry and lousy
English and browbeating ways of communicating, Genius and Zsa Zsa
are depicted with a certain comic detachment; then their real
stories begin to unfold, and the intimate sorrows of their
histories are more stunning for the element of surprise they carry.
</P>
<P>
   Louie manages this feat by narrative sleights of hand. Opening
in 1978, when Sterling is 26, the novel begins in the present
tense, with Sterling as first-person narrator. As the story grows
more complex _ as Sterling marries Bliss, has two sons, moves away
from his parents _ the tenses and narrative perspectives change,
traveling back to Genius's immigration during World War II. And
most of the things that we (and Sterling) took for granted _ the
Americanized names of Genius and Zsa Zsa, for instance _ turn out
not to be so funny after all.
</P>
<P>
   So this is humor in the Swiftian sense: piercing and satirical
and delivering something far larger than comedy for its own sake _
heading, unerringly, toward that ``long, quiet, furious sorrow''
that both Genius and Zsa Zsa had to repress in order for each of
them to make it in America. If there is a weakness to Louie's
novel, it is more sophisticated than what normally befalls first
novels: His subplots are often too interesting for what turns out
to be their relatively inconsequential status. This is a matter of
priority: Next to, say, the multidimensional revelation of Genius
cursing out the window of an automobile, how much can we invest in
a couple of slapstick moments at the ladies' club?
</P>
<P>
   But every palpable image in ``The Barbarians Are Coming'' has a
reason for being here, from the cheap reproduction of
Michelangelo's David on the Richfield grounds to the gorgeous buck
on Bliss's father's estate _ a deer whose noble presence is
threateningly male, silent, and unafraid. The care taken in this
novel is mostly out of sight; it's obscured by Sterling's ongoing
saga and by the riveting farce-drama that constitutes the sometimes
mendacious prism of parental love. But careful it is,
excruciatingly so, and that quality is what paves the way for the
novel's final 100 pages _ toward this thudding realization that
Sterling finally allows himself to feel: ``At what age, into what
depth of despair must one sink before one realizes life's simplest
truth _ that it ends, and because it ends, one should live out
one's days with as much dignity as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, nobody gets to learn that lesson until you've done
plenty of the opposite: wasted time, suffered foolishly, hurt the
people who love you, missed a hundred chances to make it right.
Sterling and his extended family have bountiful opportunity to
screw up, and a few moments, at least, to undo some of the damage.
Through it all comes the memory of Genius, on a boat out of China,
hearing the call of the ocean's waves: Do honor Do honor Do honor.
That litany both haunts and defines David Wong Louie's story, which
turns out to be as generously, utterly, American as it is
eloquently precise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gail Caldwell is book critic for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
