   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CAMPAIGN (Los Angeles) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush,
savoring polls that show him leading in most of the 13 Super
Tuesday GOP contests, campaigns in California and appears on NBC's
``Tonight Show.'' By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN-CAMPAIGN (Los Angeles) _ John McCain, hoping that the
apparent demise of Bill Bradley's campaign will inspire independent
voters to support him, appeals to Californians to give him victory
in the popular vote in the state where George W. Bush is expected
to win the 162 delegates to the GOP convention. By STEWART M.
POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Goodbye, Bill Bradley. We barely
knew ye. Your quixotic adventure is over. You never won a primary
and Tuesday (today) elections across the country will reaffirm the
polls that show you badly trailing Vice President Al Gore in every
primary state voting that day. Bradley himself virtually conceded
defeat in a Sunday television appearance, claiming that he had not
given up hope but sounding as though he actually had. By MARIANNE
MEANS.
</P>
