<HEADER>
A8262 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS &LR;      03-06 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !! ``Agnes Browne'' Anjelica Huston directed and stars in this
comic melodrama about an Irish widow and mother of seven kids.
Agnes's struggles suggest ``Angela's Ashes'' Lite. You know the
Brownes are never going to come up against anything they can't
overcome in this upbeat film, whose idea of a fairytale finish is a
Tom Jones concert. (R)
</P>
<P>
   !! 1/2 ``Beautiful People'' This optimistic, open-hearted film
throws desperate Bosnian refugees at a cross-section of Londoners
who become better people for helping them. Overloaded and
overextended, the film can flesh out only a few of its plot strands
in more than caricatured fashion _ but its commitment and energy
carry it past its shortcomings. (R)
</P>
<P>
   !! ``The Closer You Get'' Sweet but slight, this story about a
bunch of Irish bumpkins trying to rev up their sex lives in a
Donegal backwater is little ado about nothing. Its problem is not
so much with what's there (though a lot of it seems cluelessly
anachronistic) as with the fact that there's not enough of it.
(PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   (FR) !!! ``Drowning Mona'' A crude, vigorous, and funny comedy
of lowlifes who all become suspects when Bette Midler's bad-news
harridan drives off a cliff in her Yugo. The inventiveness and
flavor fall away at the end, but until then Casey Affleck, Danny
DeVito, Neve Campbell, and Jamie Lee Curtis deliver the gamy goods,
and the wacko gleam in undertaker Will Ferrell's eye is priceless.
(PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   !!! ``My Dog Skip'' Quiet, poignant, and character-driven, this
is a coming-of-age story set in the Mississippi Delta of the 1940s.
Taken from a memoir by Willie Morris, the movie sets an 8-year-old
boy and his Jack Russell terrier against the background of a tense
but loving family and a sleepy Southern town just emerging from the
Depression and beginning to engage with World War II. (PG) (Bruce
McCabe)
</P>
<P>
   ! 1/2 ``The Next Best Thing'' Madonna and Rupert Everett just
don't strike any sparks in this film about a yoga instructor whose
gay best friend becomes the father of her child during a
martini-filled night of Fred and Ginger routines. She seems
ill-at-ease, as well she might, given the script's way of
unerringly making wrong choices as it turns her character
unsympathetic and underlines the fact that Everett has been trained
to speak lines and Madonna hasn't. (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   ! 1/2 ``Three Strikes'' Rap impresario D. J. Pooh directs his
first feature, an urban comedy whose funny moments are few and far
between. Brian Hooks plays the twice-convicted bumbler trying to
avoid the triple jeopardy of the title as he navigates an
all-too-familiar world of stereotypes _ homeboys, sex-starved
women, and trigger-happy cops. (R) (Paul Robicheau)
</P>
<P>
   !!! ``What Planet Are You From?'' This Mike Nichols comedy takes
the Mars-Venus stuff to new distances, if not new heights. Garry
Shandling is the alien dispatched to Earth to impregnate a woman to
keep his species going; Annette Bening is the needy recovering
alcoholic. What could have been a trenchant satire of man-woman
relations thins out into an ongoing penis joke as Shandling's alien
stands around looking as if his face is going to melt. Bening saves
the film with superb readings. (R)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
