<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, March 7:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS (Los Angeles) _ A combined lede: Gov. George W. Bush and
Sen. John McCain in California on last day of campaigning before
Super Tuesday. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   With photos of Bush and McCain, NYT4.
</P>
<P>
   DEMS (New York) _ A combined lede: Former Sen. Bill Bradley and
Vice President Al Gore in New York. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   With photos of Gore and Bradley, NYT5.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-NY (New York) _ A look at how the New York Republican
establishment got so tied up with George W. Bush. By Adam
Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-OHIO (DAteline to kum) _ A look at the Republican race in
the one big open-primary state on Super Tuesday, Ohio. By David E.
Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA-VOTERS (Covington, Ga.) _ If previous elections were a
blur of policy headlines and angry demands, this year's is more
like an interesting novel that local voters suddenly have the time
and the wherewithal to read. There is a plot, and they are in it.
There's not much doubt who will win Tuesday's primaries in Georgia;
both Bush and Gore are enormously popular here, and none of the
four major candidates has even bothered to campaign here on a
regular basis. But neither inevitability nor prosperity seems to
have dimmed Newton County's interest in this election. No one here
has seen a single political ad or shaken a candidate's hand, yet
voters are planning to show up at the polls, and they won't be
making a decision in last-minute frustration. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes along the campaign
trail.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-TANKERS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rules
unanimously that states cannot set their own, tougher standards for
oil tanker safety, saying this is a duty of federal regulators,
except for rules relating to some unique point of local geography.
By Linda Greenhouse. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-TRIALS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rules in favor of
prosecutors in a case challenging trial practices. At issue was a
prosecutor who attacked the credibility of a defendant who had been
present in court throughout his trial. Because he had heard all the
proceedings, the prosecutor said, his testimony was tailored and
therefore suspect. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ELDERLY-DRUGS (Washington) _ The Congressional Budget Office and
other researchers, in new reports, measure prescription drug use by
the elderly; evaluate President Clinton's proposal for Medicare
drug benefits. By Robert Pear. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   PLAYER-SENTENCED (Houston) _ A high school basketball player
gets a 5-year sentence for throwing a punch during a game. By Ross
E. Milloy. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   LOUIMA-TRIAL (New York) _ Three police officers are convicted of
conspiracy in the 1997 precinct house torture of Abner Louima, a
Haitian immigrant. The charges, following the conviction of another
officer for actually torturing Louima, stem from an attempt to
conceal the role played by one of the defendants in this trial.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PAROLE (Jerusalem) _ A Jewish settler sentenced to life
in prison for murdering a Palestinian is being paroled after
serving seven years. Critics say this continues pattern of early
release of Jews convicted of killing Arabs. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-MEDIA (Johannesburg) _ As part of President Mbeki's
campaign against the press, the South African Human Rights
Commission holds hearing on racism in the media. By Rachel Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TAIWAN (Beijing) _ In one of the most strident statements
yet on Taiwan, the Chinese military said Monday that it would
``spare no effort in a blood-soaked battle'' to protect China's
territorial integrity and said that China would not be tricked into
negotiations with Taiwan leaders who secretly oppose rejoining the
motherland. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.N. (United Nations) _ The head of the U.N.
administration in Kosovo, Bernard Kouchner, reports to the Security
Council. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-INVEST (Onjungri, North Korea) _ A few miles north of the
demilitarized zone that has divided the Korean peninsula for half a
century, Hyundai, South Korea's largest corporation, has spent more
than $1 billion to install deepwater docks, build a spa with a
glass atrium, pave roads and string electric cables. It has plans
for a 1,000-room seaside hotel, 45-hole golf course and ski slope
in a desolate North Korean village. The reason, Hyundai says, is
corporate good will, which as the maxim goes, makes good business
sense. But not everyone agreed that Hyundai should invest so
heavily in a country where the risks far outweigh the potential for
return. ``I admire what Hyundai is doing in North Korea but the
bottom line is that these projects are highly risky and offer
little hope for significant financial return,'' said a Seoul fund
manager whose portfolio has substantial Hyundai stock. By Calvin
Sims.
</P>
<P>
   MGM-MIRAGE (Los Angeles) _ Mirage Resorts agreed to be acquired
by MGM Grand for a sweetened offer of $4.4 billion in cash and
stock. The deal will combine some of the most striking assets in
the gambling industry, including Mirage's $1.6 billion Bellagio
resort and MGM's 5,005-room MGM Grand hotel-casino, the largest
hotel in America. It may also bring together two of the casino
industry's most powerful figures, Mirage's chairman, Steve Wynn,
and MGM's majority stockholder, Kirk Kerkorian. The statement
announcing the deal does not say what role, if any, Wynn would play
in the new company. By By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   QWEST-USWEST (Undated) _ Looking at how Qwest Communications
made a mess of its deal with U S West. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   NINE-WEST-SETTLE (Undted) _ Nine West settles a class-action
lawsuit that accused the company of conspiring with stores to fix
prices. Under the settlement the company will pay $34 million to
women's groups across the country. By Melody Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ The Nasdaq composite marched closer to
5,000, while the other market indicators slip in mid-afternoon.
Treasury prices were slightly lower. Crude oil was at $31.70 a
barrel. European stock markets were modestly higher: London was up
1.55 percent and Frankfurt was up 0.12 percent. The Nikkei closed
down 0.66 percent; Hang Seng, up 2.74 percent. By Kenneth N.
Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   GENZYME-BIOMATRIX (Undated) _ Genzyme, one of the few profitable
biotechnology companies, says it will acquire Biomatrix Inc., the
maker of an injected arthritis treatment, for about $700 million in
cash and stock. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   TV-CINAR () _ Cinar, the Canadian children's programmer whose
programs include ``Arthur'' and which has beeen under a tax fraud
investigation, says founding couple Ronald Weinberg and Micheline
Charest have resigned. Cinar also discloses that about $122 million
of its funds have been used without board approval. By Timothy
Pritchard.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Thomas L. Friedman's ``Foreign Affairs'' and Gail Collins'
``Public Interests.''
</P>
