<HEADER>
A8308 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-OSCARS-TECH-CEREMONY-     03-06 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-TECH-CEREMONY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIE ACADEMY PUTS FOCUS ON SCI-TECH OSCARS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even before the glitz and glamour of Oscar night (still a few
weeks away, folks), a round of plaques and commendations bearing
the motion picture academy's seal gets handed out to a group of
folks most of us have never heard of.
</P>
<P>
   These are the awards for scientific and technical achievement
(or Sci-Techs), which the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and
Sciences bestowed Saturday night on the developers of camera
lenses, film projectors and filters.
</P>
<P>
   Will you recognize the winners' names? Probably not. But their
equipment has greatly helped the makers of such recent movies as
``The Thin Red Line'' ``Mighty Joe Young,'' ``Saving Private Ryan''
and ``Eyes Wide Shut.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't be anything without the actors,'' admitted camera
designer Fritz Gabriel Bauer, who picked up his third Sci-Tech
award during the black-tie affair at the Regent Beverly Wilshire
Hotel. ``But they wouldn't be anything without us, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, who developed one of the world's smallest and lightest
sound cameras _ the Moviecam Superlight _ was one of 12 Sci-Tech
recipients. The Gordon E. Sawyer award, Sci-Tech's lifetime
achievement award, went to former Eastman Kodak pioneer Roderick T.
Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   The task of explaining the winners' achievements _ with the aid
of video clips _ fell to actress Salma Hayek, who admitted that she
was a slightly unusual choice to host a tech awards presentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I have an engineering background,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hayek labored at times while reading off reams of complicated
names and technical terminology from a TelPrompTer, but the star of
``Wild Wild West'' and ``Fools Rush In'' proved to be a good sport,
willing to laugh at herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I make a mistake,'' she told the audience, ``I want
you to pretend you're me and that you're up here doing this in
Spanish.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodland Hills-based Panavision Inc. was recognized for its
contribution to developing the Millennium Camera System viewfinder.
Panavision engineer Takuo Miyagishima also received a John A.
Bonner Medal of Commendation.
</P>
<P>
   FPC Inc.'s Barry M. Stultz and Milton Jan Friedman received a
special award of commendation for their creation of an
environmentally responsible program to recycle and destroy film. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 1431EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
