<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8319 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-CALIF-PRIMARY-HNS &LR;      03-06 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-PRIMARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CALIFORNIANS ARE BUMMED OUT THAT THE CANDIDATES KISSED OFF THE
STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT SALLADAY and ZACHARY COILE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO_ Two major changes in California law transformed
Tuesday's primary and prompted the presidential candidates to
briefly focus their attention here, even if their natural instinct
was to ignore this unfathomable state and its unmapped new-economy
politics.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Californians get to vote early in the
presidential primary, and they get to vote for any candidate
regardless of party. Both of these changes seemed a perfect fit for
the Golden State: Virtually ignored on the national primary stage
every four years, the state and its increasingly independent
electorate would have a voice for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's real money being spent on real TV ads. There are real
live bodies campaigning in California _ that's something we haven't
seen in long, long time,`` said Tony Quinn, a Republican political
analyst.
</P>
<P>
   But with the exception of a few rallies with mariachi bands and
Vietnamese dragon dances, the political discussion in California
has focused almost entirely on issues raised in earlier primaries
from smaller states that hardly represent the country's diversity.
Candidates have come through California on an assembly line,
dragging with them the confederate flag and the leadership of Bob
Jones University.
</P>
<P>
   In two separate statewide votes _ Proposition 198 in 1996 and
Prop. 3 in 1998 _ Californians said they wanted a truly open
primary, which would allow them to pick any candidate from any
party. But the rules were changed in the Legislature, because what
voters wanted conflicted with the rules of the establishment
parties.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a two-tier voting system where anyone can vote for
any candidate _ the so-called ``beauty contest'' _ but only votes
of registered Republicans and Democrats will count in selecting
delegates. This system favors Bush and Gore because they long ago
wrapped up the establishment of their parties.
</P>
<P>
   The state could find itself in the strange position of having
one candidate _ McCain _ win the popular vote, but lose all 162 GOP
delegates to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President pro tem John L. Burton, D-San Francisco, the
most powerful Democrat in the Legislature, and Assembly Speaker
Antonio Villaraigosa, D-Los Angeles, who has endorsed Gore, helped
the Republican and Democratic front-runners get their advantage.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the national parties that rejected outsider's picking
their presidential candidates. This system has bothered McCain, who
notes Republicans make up only 35 percent of the electorate in
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think they would want to actually win an election for a
change,`` he said recently.
</P>
<P>
   The fastest growing voting bloc in the state is voters who
decline to state their party. The new primary system shuts out this
entire population of voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly is a feeling of disconnect: The voters are
going in one direction, and the party regulars want to maintain
control,`` said Ann Crigler, director of USC's Jesse Unruh School
of Government. ``It seems to me there is this great effort by the
parties to control their power. But it's a little too late for that
. . . . The public is feeling frustrated, and they don't know what
to do, and this builds further on the lack of trust people have
with elected officials.``
</P>
<P>
   And Californians got little chance to hear the candidates' views
on state issues such as offshore oil drilling or former Gov. Pete
Wilson's controversial initiative to stiffen sentences for young
criminals. Instead the discussion focused on national issues and
national campaign tactics, fueled by the establishment national
media.
</P>
<P>
   And while the candidates did spend time in California before the
New Hampshire primary, they rushed through the state in the days
leading to Tuesday because the early primary has compacted the
whole election.
</P>
<P>
   Add to this one of the most confusing ballots in state history.
While the initiative system supposedly gives power back to the
people, it's really special interest groups and lawmakers who have
twisted Tuesday's election into a knot of new electoral rules and
old problems voters may have thought they took care of in previous
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Want to annoy the insurance industry? Then vote ``yes'' on the
two initiatives they put on the ballot. That's right, they want you
to vote against them, to repeal current law. Remember Indian
gaming? It's back on the ballot _ twice. Most Indian tribes want
you to vote for the first measure on the ballot, and reject the
older second measure, even though they appear on face value to be
virtually identical.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the way Californians vote and how they monitor
politicians keep getting changed. Once again Tuesday, there is a
campaign finance reform measure on the ballot, even as the last
campaign finance measure, Proposition 208, is being debated in
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people think you need a Ph.D. to cast a ballot in
California,'' said Kim Alexander, president of the nonpartisan
California Voter Foundation, which produces an online voter guide.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the California primary really mattered was in
1972, when George McGovern beat Hubert Humphrey and went on to win
the Democratic nomination. That extended fight lasted through the
California primary and into the convention.
</P>
<P>
   The last time a Republican primary in California mattered was in
1964 when Barry Goldwater beat Nelson Rockefeller, signaling the
shift of GOP power from the East Coast establishment to the Sun
Belt states.
</P>
<P>
   Even if this year's candidates have spent little time on state
issues, voters don't seem to mind much. Recent polls show that
three-quarters of California voters say they are paying close
attention to the presidential races.
</P>
<P>
   If Secretary of State Bill Jones is right, 52 percent of state
voters will cast ballots, which would be the largest turnout in 16
years in California.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen states will vote in primaries or caucuses Tuesday, what
some have called the country's first national primary. In a system
where each state vies to be the earliest, candidates are forced to
veer right in the South, move left in the North and in the West -
all in the same week. It's called the ``windshield wiper effect.''
</P>
<P>
   This windshield wiper system favors establishment candidates
like Gore because when things start moving quickly, ground-level
operations and special interest support provide invaluable help in
making phone calls, putting literature on doors, fanning out
high-powered endorsers all over the state to build media attention.
The result also is that candidates don't have time to focus on the
issues of each state or each region of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this any way to elect a president?'' asked Mark Petracca, a
political scientist at UC-Irvine. ``(What) people need to
understand is that it's not just that we in California want the
attention. They key difference is what are we going to talk about?
What difference does it make to Californians whether or not South
Carolina flies the confederate flag?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
