<HEADER>
A8324 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-TUESDAY-REVIEWS-LA     03-06 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TUESDAY-REVIEWS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPN, FOX MANAGE TO KILL EVEN MORE BRAIN CELLS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Tonight is TUESDAY, March 7 in this story. Fact box below) 
Our rating: 1 star for ``Secret Agent Man,'' 2 stars for ``Family
Guy'' 
 
 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fox and UPN, understanding just how cynically apolitical the TV
viewing populace really is, has prepared some
lowest-common-denominator counterprogramming for us while the
networks report on Super Tuesday. The best that can be said of this
fare: Even something as tediously trivial as the future of our
country looks good by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   First up: ``Secret Agent Man,'' UPN's long-delayed action series
whose relationship with the `60s Patrick McGoohan series begins and
ends with the theme song (the title sequence is replete with
Bondian flourishes in the music and silhouettes of cavorting
babes). Whatever UPN has been doing since it took it off the fall
schedule _ allowing it to age on the shelf, or copiously
rejiggering it _ hasn't had much of an effect on the quality, or
lack of same.
</P>
<P>
   Like the already-canceled ``The Strip,'' ``Secret Agent Man''
boasts semi-coherent storytelling, witless wit and the one thing
that's supposed to atone for its multitude of sins _ ample
pulchritudinous bosoms and bottoms.
</P>
<P>
   Our hero is Monk (Costas Mandylor, which, if you think about it,
is actually a better name for a hero in an idiotic action series
than Monk), who, like most secret-agent men, has a spiffy suit, a
little black book the size of the Manhattan Yellow Pages and a
propensity for fighting in slo-mo with the occasional inexplicable
freeze-frame. He works for some vague organization that has a lot
of cool, giant, high-tech computer screens on the walls and sultry
employees who coolly cascade through the background in short black
cocktail dresses.
</P>
<P>
   In tonight's pilot, he meets up with an on-the-lam exotic
foreign spy with whom he apparently has a history, and there's this
group that wants her back and has this sci-fi-looking gizmo that
makes electricity go crazy and they'll do bad things if Monk
doesn't sacrifice this exotic foreign spy, as we noted, with whom
he apparently has a history. His vague organization, not wanting
electricity to go crazy anymore, decides to sell out Monk, even if
he is their absolute best agent, and so Monk's partner Holiday
(Dina Meyer) and buddy Davis (Dondre T. Whitfield) are torn between
their semi-fierce loyalty to Monk and the prospect of having to
find new jobs where they won't likely get to wear spiffy suits and
black cocktail dresses.
</P>
<P>
   See, even if this is the first episode of this series, these
interconnected relationships are supposed to resonate with us so
deeply that we'll care about this exotic spy, his vague
organization's selling him out and his partner's semi-fierce
loyalty. But not even the actors bother trying to sell us the
premise !ital!or the tongue-in-cheekiness _ and not one of them
exudes the sort of cool, intelligent charisma that one expects from
a spy (although the bad guy with the electrical gizmo, played by
Jesus Garcia, is fun and should be given an expanded role in the
series). Bottom line: It's as bad as everything else on UPN. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
`FAMILY GUY'
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Over on Fox comes the re-relaunch of ``Family Guy,''
Wunderkind animator Seth McFarlane's deadpan, low-brow but
high-concept series. The problem with the show isn't that it's not
funny enough _ though it often isn't _ but that its funniest bits
are the throwaway parodies, with virtually no attention spent on
making the story or characters interesting.
</P>
<P>
   So, tonight, there are pretty wicked little riffs on ``Mr.
Rogers' Neighborhood'' and ``The Jetsons,'' but the actual story _
Brian the family dog has some bizarre pseudo-Oedipal crush on the
lady of the house, while evil, Peter Lorre-esque infant Stewie
stews about menacingly in the background _ is a snoozer. And the
characters, Xeroxes of Xeroxes of an army of semi-eccentrics from
countless other shows, don't exactly inspire or invite repeat
viewings. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: ``Secret Agent Man.'' &QL; 
What: Action-adventure series. &QL; 
Who: Costas Mandylor, Dina Meyer, Dondre T. Whitfield. &QL; 
Where: UPN. &QL; 
When: 8 tonight. &QL; 
Our rating: 1 star &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The show: ``Family Guy.'' &QL; 
What: Animated series about a family that may be dysfunctional, but
can do gross-out gags with the best of `em. &QL; 
Where: Fox. &QL; 
When: 8:30 tonight. &QL; 
Our rating: 2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
