<HEADER>
A8326 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-GYPSIES-HAIDERISM-ECO     03-06 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GYPSIES-HAIDERISM-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SAD GYPSIES OF SLOVAKIA  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 675-word article is from the current (week
beginning 4 March 2000) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRATISLAVA _ Mikulas Dzurkinda, the Slovak prime minister,
winces when asked what he thinks of Joerg Haider.
</P>
<P>
   ``A very hard question,'' he says after a long pause. ``I'm
certain Austria will stay democratic. But,'' he adds, ``demagogues
are frightening. Imagine the trouble they could cause if they got
hold of our Gypsy question.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. If the politics of hate were to make a comeback in lands
to the east of the present EU, Gypsies could be prime targets.
</P>
<P>
   When Haider's supporters deride Slovakia, they invariably have
Gypsies in mind. If Slovakia joined the Union, say some Haiderites,
incoming Slovakian Gypsies would become a problem for Austria.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, several thousand of them have sought
asylum in the EU, particularly in Finland and Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Though Romania has the largest number of Gypsies (also known as
Roma) in Europe, Slovakia has the highest proportion: some say they
are nearly a tenth of Slovakia's population of 5 million.
</P>
<P>
   And the average of 4.2 children per Gypsy family, compared with
1.5 for other Slovaks, means that by the last quarter of this
century there might be as many Gypsies as ethnic Slovaks.
</P>
<P>
   The plight of Slovakia's Gypsies has long been grim. But since
communism ended, it has become even grimmer.
</P>
<P>
   Four out of five have no job. Life expectancy is falling,
illiteracy rising, crime rife. Tuberculosis is again common in
Gypsy villages. Large families, sometimes 14-strong, often cram
into squalid shacks that used to house three or four people.
</P>
<P>
   Gypsy children are particularly vulnerable. Few get much
education. One study reckons that only 3 percent of them finish
secondary school.
</P>
<P>
   In primary school, they start off with social and linguistic
disadvantages that are hard to redress. Some speak little Slovak,
are ill-fed and do not know how to use soap or cutlery.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them, including bright ones, are summarily dumped in
special schools for the mentally handicapped.
</P>
<P>
   An extra foundation year at the start of primary school, known
as ``zero grade,'' has been tried successfully in some places, so
the government hopes to offer it to Gypsy children across the
country, starting this autumn. But persuading their parents to keep
them at school after 14 is harder.
</P>
<P>
   Slovakia's president, Rudolf Schuster, thinks that special
boarding schools might be set up. ``It's often impossible for Gypsy
children to learn at home,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office in 1998, the ruling coalition government,
which replaced a more nationalistic one that included a virulently
anti-Gypsy (and anti-Hungarian) party, has tried to tackle the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that the EU will not let Slovakia into its club
until it is satisfied that the country's Gypsies are being given a
fair deal. So Slovakia has held international conferences on the
matter, has listened hard, and doled out cash for schemes approved
by Gypsies themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But the Gypsies do not always help their own cause. Slovakia's
have at least 13 political parties, which spend as much time
fighting each other as trying to improve their people's lot.
</P>
<P>
   And, abject as most Gypsies are, for many of them theft is,
sadly, a way of life.
</P>
<P>
   Dzurinda recounts, with evident sympathy, how poor Slovak
farmers often accost him with tales of how crops and animals, even
pet dogs, have been stolen by Gypsies. ``They have tears in their
eyes. They want to know who will pay for their chickens.''
</P>
<P>
   All the same, most Slovaks still seem loath to give their Gypsy
citizens a chance. Michal Vasecka, who studies Gypsies at a Slovak
think-tank, tells how people, in reply to his questionnaires, often
add their own suggestions: ``Send them to the gas chambers!'' or
``Back to India!'' or ``Kill them!'' and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even the better-disposed sort of Slovak politicians, such as
Dzurinda and Schuster, flatly deny that their countrymen are
prejudiced against the Gypsies at all. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 1441EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
