<P>
   &UR; DR. WEIL'S WISDOM: SIZING UP FAD DIETS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DR-WEIL-HEALTH-LIFEBEAT _ Three new studies on Americans and
weight gain were released last fall, and the news wasn't good. The
verdict: Not only is obesity on the rise _ from 12 percent of the
population in 1991 to almost 18 percent in 1998, according to the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention _ but more than half of
the adults in this country are now considered at least moderately
overweight. All this, despite the fact that total fat consumption
in the United States has decreased over the past decade. What's
going on here? And what to do about it? By Dr. Andrew Weil, written
with Joseph V. Amodio. (1,500 words and 3 sidebars, all in one
file.)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Color photo of Dr. Andrew Weil is available in JPEG
format by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STURDY YELLOWWARE HAS SERVED AMERICANS WELL FOR 200 YEARS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES-YELLOWWARE-LIFEBEAT _ When shipments of English
yellowware crossed the Atlantic early in the 19th century,
Americans eagerly made room in their cupboards. More durable than
redware and less cumbersome than stoneware, the newfangled goods
were handsome to behold and inexpensive to buy. Today, yellowware
remains functional, but it's also fun to collect. By Debra Muller
Price. (550 words.)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Two color photos of yellowware bowls are available in
JPEG format by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HONEY, I'M HOME ... FOR TWO DAYS ANYWAY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVELING-PARENT-LIFEBEAT _ Not very long ago, my 5-year-old
daughter, Willa, held a birthday party for her doll Lucy. Willa
played Lucy's mom, while I played Lucy's grandmother, and my
3-year-old son, Devin, was her uncle. Someone, however, was
missing. ``My husband is away on a trip,'' Willa explained, as she
blew out Lucy's candles. ``He travels a lot for work.'' This hit
suspiciously close to home. My husband, Austin, travels for his job
_ a lot. By Laura Hilgers. (1,300 words, optional add.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOR DOGS WHO CAN'T PLAY SOLITAIRE, INTERACTIVE PLAYTIME &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DOG-DAYCARE-LIFEBEAT _ Dogs are social beings. They need
company. Well-socialized pets _ dogs that respect and interact
comfortably with people as well as other dogs _ are happy and
responsive. But because today's families tend to spend less and
less time at home, their gregarious canine companions sometimes
miss out on the socializing they crave. In order to develop into
friendly companions, young animals need extended interactive
playtime. Thus the ultimate in surrogate pet parenthood _ day-care
facilities for dogs _ is quickly becoming a solution. By Toni
Gardner. (925 words)
</P>
