r l BC-DR-WEIL-HEALTH-LIFEBE     03-06 2231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DR-WEIL-HEALTH-LIFEBEAT-ART-1,500&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DR. WEIL'S WISDOM: SIZING UP FAD DIETS
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text.  (ART ADV: A photo of Dr.
Andrew Weil is available in JPEG format by calling William Gonzalez
at 212-499-3355.)  (th)  Dr. Andrew Weil, a pioneer in the field of
integrative medicine, recently authored ``Eating Well for Optimum
Health.'' Joseph V. Amodio writes for ``Country Living's Healthy
Living.''
 &HT;    
 By DR. ANDREW WEIL, written with JOSEPH V. AMODIO 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
<P>
   Three new studies on Americans and weight gain were released
last fall, and the news wasn't good. The verdict: Not only is
obesity (the state of being more than 30 percent above one's ideal
body weight) on the rise _ from 12 percent of the population in
1991 to almost 18 percent in 1998, according to the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention _ but more than half of the adults
in this country are now considered at least moderately overweight.
All this, despite the fact that total fat consumption in the United
States has decreased over the past decade. What's going on here?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there's no great mystery. While we grasp the
importance of limiting fat intake, we still eat too much and move
around too little. It's that simple. We're gobbling up low-fat or
no-fat cookies, chips and cakes as if they're full of air, not
calories.
</P>
<P>
   One more truth about Americans: We're addicted to the quick fix,
some magical diet that will help us shed those excess pounds
without pain. Perhaps that's why bookstores are bursting with
guides to seductive programs like high-protein, low-carb diets that
let you eat bacon and burgers by the plateful while shunning pasta
and potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   While some diets are downright ridiculous (the chocolate lovers'
diet springs to mind) and can be unhealthy in the long run, there
is a kernel of truth behind many of the best-selling diet books and
weight-loss supplements. And let's face it, some of us find a
structured program helpful in kicking off a weight-loss effort and
staying on track.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at the theories behind some of the most popular
plans and pills and what you can learn from them, as well as some
healthy long-term solutions to weight management.
</P>
<P>
   A LOOK AT THE BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   Protein Powerhouses
</P>
<P>
   Theory: Programs outlined in books such as ``Dr. Atkins' New
Diet Revolution,'' ``The Carhohydrate Addict's Diet'' and ``Sugar
Busters!'' are all based on the same underlying principle _ when
you eat lots of carbohydrates, insulin production in the body
spikes, which in turn promotes fat storage, harms cardiovascular
function, and in some cases, can even lead to adult-onset diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Where they fall short: Dieters are allowed to load up on foods
like bacon, steak and cream, which are high in saturated fat and
should be consumed only in moderation. The high levels of protein
in these diets can also stress the liver, kidneys and immune
system, and increase calcium loss from bones. High-fat,
high-protein foods also tend to crowd out all the protective
nutrients in fruits and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Golden nugget: For carbohydrate-sensitive people _ maybe 25
percent of the population _ restricting certain carbohydrate-rich
foods, such as potatoes, bread and other products made from flour
and sugar, is sensible advice. But eating those foods will not
disturb insulin production if you are not in that group.
</P>
<P>
   If you are tempted to try these plans, keep total fat
consumption to no more than 30 percent of calories and saturated
fat intake at 5 percent (go easy on the meat, butter, cream and
cheese). Instead of avoiding carbohydrates altogether, include some
healthy ones like starchy vegetables, fruits, whole-wheat pasta and
chewy, multigrain breads.
</P>
<P>
   Percentage Players
</P>
<P>
   Theory: According to high-protein diets like the one laid out in
``The Zone,'' by Dr. Barry Sears, when you eat the ``right''
combination of foods _ in the Zone's case, 40 percent of calories
from carbohydrates, 30 percent from protein, 30 percent from fat _
your body will reach a metabolic state that works at peak
performance, keeping you thin.
</P>
<P>
   Where they fall short: Sears' basic plan provides 900 calories a
day, which means starving yourself. I would lose weight if I ate
900 calories of pure fat a day and nothing else. In addition, very
low-calorie diets promote loss of lean muscle mass as well as body
fat. The Zone philosophy only applies strictly to that minority of
the population that is carbohydrate-sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   And looking at food as a drug to manipulate your hormonal
chemistry, as Sears advises, does not seem to me to be a healthy
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Golden nugget: I think Sears is right when he calls attention to
the glycemic index _ a measure of how quickly particular
carbohydrates are converted to blood sugar. High-glycemic foods
like rice cakes, bread and potatoes are probably chief culprits in
obesity for many of us. And Sears' discussion of good fats and bad
fats is accurate.
</P>
<P>
   A better way to apply this philosophy is to keep fat intake to
30 percent of calories or below, carbohydrates in the 50 percent to
60 percent range, and protein to 10 percent to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fat Fighters
</P>
<P>
   Theory: Dietary fat is the real villain when it comes to weight
gain and overall health, says Dr. Dean Ornish, whose ``Eat More,
Weigh Less'' whole-foods, plant-based diet gets no more than 10
percent of its daily calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Where they fall short: The palatability of food falls off
sharply as fat calories drop below 20 percent. Unless people are
facing medical crises, it is unlikely that they will be able to
follow a 10-percent-fat, vegetarian diet without the help of a
professional chef. These diets also greatly increase the risk of
deficiency of essential fatty acids, particularly the valuable
omega 3s that are present in fatty fish and egg yolks.
</P>
<P>
   Golden nugget: Ornish's emphasis on a plant-based diet with
plenty of fruits, vegetables, grains, beans and soy products has a
scientific basis. Initially devised as a way to help reverse the
symptoms of coronary heart disease, it has received the backing of
the medical community as an effective cholesterol-lowering and
weight-loss plan, albeit one that's not easy to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Body Shape Adherents
</P>
<P>
   Theory: The foods you eat (and your exercise choices) should be
based not on personal preference but on your genetically determined
build, according to dietary guides like ``The Body Code'' by Dr.
Jay Cooper and ``Dr. Abravanel's Body Type Diet and Lifetime
Nutrition Plan,'' an update of the 1984 text by Dr. Elliot D.
Abravanel.
</P>
<P>
   Where they fall short: Some of the recommendations go against
conventional wisdom. For instance, on Cooper's plan, the Warrior
types are prescribed little or no strength-training (because it
supposedly bulks you up), whereas experts acknowledge that some
level of weight training is important for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Nurturers should ideally exercise in the morning, says
Cooper, a recommendation that is both odd and unrealistic; one's
exercise schedule should be based on personal preference rather
than genetic makeup.
</P>
<P>
   Golden nugget: This plan _ loosely based on the principles of
Ayurveda _ acknowledges that no single diet works for everyone. And
each of the guidelines for the four body types is really quite
nourishing, based on a whole-foods diet with some healthy fats and
lean meats.
</P>
<P>
   Dieting Done Right
</P>
<P>
   So how does one diet safely and effectively? Ignore the fads
that sound too good to be true (they usually are), and instead pay
attention to these two tried-and-true tenets _ eat less and
exercise more. Here's how to do it:
</P>
<P>
   MAKE CALORIES COUNT. Determine your caloric requirements
(usually 2,000 to 3,000 calories a day, depending on gender, body
size and level of activity). Keep fat intake to 30 percent (or
less) of total calories (with no more than 5 percent from saturated
fat). Eat 50 percent to 60 percent of calories as carbohydrates,
mostly whole foods like grains rather than floury, sugary fare.
Keep protein in the 10 percent to 20 percent range, emphasizing
fish and soy products. Eat plenty of fresh vegetables and fruits,
and avoid alcohol, which promotes the storage of excess calories as
fat.
</P>
<P>
   Get moving. Exercise is an essential component to any
weight-loss plan. Start off with a 10-minute walk, five days a
week, and increase the time by 5 minutes each week, till you are
walking 45 minutes at a stretch. Add one to two days of resistance
training each week to increase lean muscle mass (which will help
you burn more calories at rest).
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. Be aware of the motional aspects of weight
control. Rather than feeding their bodies, compulsive eaters are
often attempting to feed their souls, filling an emptiness inside.
Eating may also be a way of coping with anxiety. I urge you to try
stress-reduction exercises (like yoga or meditation), which also
encourage mindful eating.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, consider whether you really need to lose as much as you
think. If your weight is not threatening your health, then try to
accept your body as less than perfect but beautiful just the same.
</P>
<P>
   THE SKINNY ON SUPPLEMENTS
</P>
<P>
   Even after the drug cocktail Fen-Phen was linked to heart-valve
defects and taken off the market, some people just won't give up
their search for the ``Magic bullet.'' Below are a few of the more
popular options:
</P>
<P>
   CONJUGATED LINOLEIC ACID
</P>
<P>
   Claims: CLA, a fatty acid, supposedly prevents fat from being
deposited in cells by speeding fat metabolism. According to two
small studies, subjects who consumed varying amounts of CLA noted a
reduction in body fat and an increase in lean tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Reality: To get the desired effects, you must exercise and
change your diet, which makes CLA no better than standard
weight-loss techniques. Plus, long-term side effects are unknown.
</P>
<P>
   PYRUVATE
</P>
<P>
   Claims: Proponents say that this naturally occurring enzyme _ a
key player in the metabolic process that transforms nutrients into
energy _ can help with weight loss, increase stamina and decrease
cholesterol without side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Reality: Supplemental pyruvate does not cross easily from the
bloodstream (where it goes after digestion) into cells (to be used
in the transformation process), so even taking a large amount will
have little effect on fat-burning.
</P>
<P>
   CHROMIUM PICOLINATE
</P>
<P>
   Claims: Chromium, a trace mineral found in foods like whole
grains, cheese, nuts and spinach, is said to increase muscle mass
and reduce body fat by enhancing insulin sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   Reality: While chromium is used by the body for insulin
metabolism and does play a role in energy production, unless you're
deficient in the mineral _ and most people aren't _ supplemental
chromium won't do anything for you.
</P>
<P>
   SIZE MATTERS
</P>
<P>
   The problem for many dieters isn't what they eat, but how much.
These days, everything from bagels to beefsteak is served
oversized. Want to keep closer tabs on portion sizes? Just hold out
your hand:
</P>
<P>
   1) Your palm is roughly the size of 3 ounces (one serving) of
fish, meat or poultry.
</P>
<P>
   2) Your cupped hand can hold about 2 ounces (about two servings)
of nuts.
</P>
<P>
   3) Your thumb tip represents a teaspoon (remember that as you
swipe your finger in the peanut butter jar). Three thumb tips equal
a tablespoon.
</P>
<P>
   4) Your thumb, measured from second joint to end, represents
about one tablespoon of liquid (one serving of oil or dressing) or
an ounce Of cheese.
</P>
<P>
   5) Your fist equals one cup (one serving of cereal, pasta or
rice).
</P>
<P>
   FAKE FATS
</P>
<P>
   Olestra is a fatlike substance that cannot be absorbed by the
intestinal tract, and so is eliminated from the body. It is
currently used as an ingredient in fat-free potato and corn chips
and may soon be approved for use in other foods. Products made with
this fake fat need to be fortified with the fat-soluble vitamins
(A, D, E and K) because it carries away some of these nutrients.
</P>
<P>
   Olestra can also wreak havoc on the intestines of certain
individuals. The real problem I see with it is that it encourages
greater consumption of low-quality, carbohydrate-rich foods that
promote obesity in many people and fail to provide the protective
elements found in higher-quality snack choices like fruits and
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
