<HEADER>
A8358 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-ANTIQUES-YELLOWWARE-L     03-06 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-YELLOWWARE-LIFEBEAT-ART-550-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STURDY YELLOWWARE HAS SERVED AMERICANS WELL FOR 200 YEARS
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text.  (ART ADV: Two color photos
of yellowware bowls are available in JPEG format by calling William
Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.)  (th)  Debra Muller Price writes for
``Country Living.''
 By DEBRA MULLER PRICE 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When shipments of English yellowware crossed the Atlantic early
in the 19th century, Americans eagerly made room in their
cupboards. More durable than redware and less cumbersome than
stoneware, the newfangled goods were handsome to behold and
inexpensive to buy.
</P>
<P>
   Potters in England developed yellowware late in the 18th
century. Working with buff-colored clay that gives the ware its
name, they made useful forms and fired them at high temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-19th century, a thriving American industry was under
way. Potteries in Ohio, New England, the mid-Atlantic and the South
churned out pudding molds, canisters and colanders _ but the deep,
easy-to-handle mixing bowls became the enduring favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Made well into the 1930s and beyond, these simple vessels have
been used by cooks to serve up countless batches of biscuits,
cookies and bread dough.
</P>
<P>
   Today's collectors value them for the warm color they bring to a
room. Yellowware really enhances a setting, said John Gallo, an
Otego, N.Y., antiques dealer. ``It makes a cupboard come to life.''
</P>
<P>
   Dating a piece of yellowware becomes easier if you brush up on a
few key characteristics. The first bowls were thrown by hand on a
potter's wheel, but the majority of yellowware from the late 19th
and early 20th centuries was produced with the use of molds.
</P>
<P>
   Molds gave birth to a variety of embossed and impressed designs
with floral, geometric and scenic motifs. The lip on a bowl also
hints at the age: Pieces from the 19th century often feature rolled
lips, while 20th-century examples tend to have a less-rounded lip
or a wide collared rim.
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR 1
</P>
<P>
   NESTING INSTINCTS
</P>
<P>
   Seasoned collectors focus their energies on finding graduated
sizes of the same pattern for nesting. Not only do they enjoy the
thrill of the hunt, but sets of bowls also bring more money than
individual ones.
</P>
<P>
   Though bowls are commonly seen in nests of five, many were
actually produced in eight to 12 different sizes, ranging from
about 4 inches in diameter up to 17 inches or more. The most
valuable pieces generally fall at either end of the spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR 2
</P>
<P>
   BUYER'S GUIDE ANTIQUES
</P>
<P>
   Period yellowware bowls with slip bands or embossed decoration
range from about $25 to $200 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   DEALERS
</P>
<P>
   America Antiques and Emporium, 26 S. 3rd St., Newark, Ohio
43055; (740) 345-0588.
</P>
<P>
   East Meets West Antiques, 160 N. La Brea Ave., Los Angeles,
Calif. 90036; (323) 931-0500.
</P>
<P>
   Feather Tree Antiques, Lancaster, Mass. 01523; (978) 365-6456.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn and John Gallo Antiques, P.O. Box 13, Otego, N.Y. 13825;
(607) 988-9963.
</P>
<P>
   REPRODUCTIONS
</P>
<P>
   East Knoll North Pottery, P.O. Box 163, Becket, Mass.
01223-0163; (413) 623-5633.
</P>
<P>
   Fioriware, 26 N. 3rd St., Zanesville, Ohio 43701; (740)
454-7400.
</P>
<P>
   Mason Cash, 1901 Rte. 130, North Brunswick, N.J. 08902; (732)
940-8300.
</P>
<P>
   LEARN MORE
</P>
<P>
   ``Kitchen Ceramics,'' by Suzanne Slesin (Abbeville Press; 1997;
$35).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
