<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8360 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-IRISH-TREATS-LIFEBEAT     03-06 1312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-TREATS-LIFEBEAT-ART-1,100-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR DAMP DAYS, 3 PERFECT PARTNERS FOR A SOUL-WARMING CUP OF TEA
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text.  (ART ADV: Two color photos
of soda bread and chocolate bread pudding are available in JPEG
format by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.)  (th) 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The music of tea splashing into a porcelain cup has been known
to soothe an Irish soul long before the amber liquid even touches
the lips. But as a new generation of innovative Irish chefs have
come into their own, teatime sweets just may upstage the
ritualistic afternoon cuppa.
</P>
<P>
   By making good use of the Emerald Isle's culinary history and
rich dairy products, baked goods once meant merely to sustain have
gained recognition as combinations of farm-fresh ingredients and
unpretentious country charm. Starting off with three classic
recipes, we've transformed each one into a delicious and comforting
sweet.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, traditional quick-leavened soda bread suffers from a
dry texture, owing to the low gluten content in Irish flour. Using
sugar, butter, eggs and a generous amount of buttermilk results in
a tender, cakelike loaf with a fine, moist crumb.
</P>
<P>
   Bread pudding is anything but humble when enhanced with
semisweet chocolate and baked in a rich custard; an ample drizzling
of whiskey sauce adds a spirited finish.
</P>
<P>
   Making sweet use of potatoes, ``pratie apple'' is apple pie with
a light mashed-potato crust, and the filling is infused with a
mixture of butter and brown sugar as it bakes. These easy-to-make
treats don't stray too far from their heritage _ part of what will
delight you when teatime rolls around.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE SODA BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Sweet chewy currants provide the perfect counterpoint to
fragrant caraway seeds. Baking this soda bread in a cast-iron
skillet instead of on a baking sheet gives it its shape and ensures
even cooking.
</P>
<P>
   MAKES 8 SERVINGS
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   3 cups unsifted all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups currants or raisins
</P>
<P>
   1 3/4 cups buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon plus 1 teaspoon caraway seeds
</P>
<P>
   1) Heat oven to 350 degrees. Grease a 10-inch cast-iron skillet
with 1 tablespoon butter. Line the bottom of skillet with waxed
paper and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2) In a large bowl, combine flour, sugar, baking powder, salt
and baking soda. Stir in the currants.
</P>
<P>
   3) In a small microwave-safe dish or small saucepan, melt 2
tablespoons butter. In a medium bowl, mix together the buttermilk,
eggs and the melted butter. Stir buttermilk mixture into flour
mixture just until combined. Fold in caraway seeds. Pour batter
into prepared skillet and dot top with the remaining 2 tablespoons
butter.
</P>
<P>
   4) Bake until a cake tester inserted in center comes out clean _
about 1 hour. Let cool 10 minutes before serving. Nutrition
information per serving-protein: 9 grams; fat: 10 grams;
carbohydrate: 75 grams; fiber: 3 grams; sodium: 762 milligrams;
cholesterol: 73 milligrams; calories: 415.
</P>
<P>
   CHOCOLATE BREAD PUDDING
</P>
<P>
   Serve this dessert warm with our Irish Whiskey Sauce (recipe
follows).
</P>
<P>
   MAKES 8 SERVINGS
</P>
<P>
   3 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1 cup half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 8-ounce package semisweet chocolate
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup Irish whiskey
</P>
<P>
   4 large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 1-pound loaf challah or French bread, cut into 2-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   Shaved chocolate and confectioners' sugar (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1) Heat oven to 350 degrees. Grease a 2-quart baking dish and
set aside. In a 6-quart saucepan, combine milk and half-and-half.
Bring to a simmer over medium-low heat, stirring occasionally. Add
granulated sugar and chocolate; stir until melted. Bring mixture to
boil; cook 1 minute. Remove from heat and stir in whiskey.
</P>
<P>
   2) Beat yolks in a small bowl. Slowly whisk in 1/4 cup of milk
mixture. Whisk egg mixture into remaining milk mixture until well
combined and thickened. Stir in butter, vanilla and salt. Fold in
bread; spoon pudding into dish. Let soak 1 hour at room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   3) Bake until knife inserted in the center comes out clean-
about 50 minutes. To serve, spoon into bowls; garnish with shaved
chocolate and sprinkle with confectioners' sugar, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Nutrition information per serving-protein: 14 grams; fat: 28
grams; carbohydrate: 59 grams; fiber: 5 grams; sodium: 370
milligrams; cholesterol: 131 milligrams; calories: 529.
</P>
<P>
   IRISH WHISKEY SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Try pouring this over pound cake or brownies as well.
</P>
<P>
   MAKES 1 1/2 CUPS
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Irish whiskey
</P>
<P>
   In a 1-quart saucepan, melt butter over medium heat. Add flour
and cook, whisking until well combined. Remove from heat and stir
in milk, sugar and whiskey. Bring to a boil, whisking constantly,
until thickened _ 5 to 7 minutes. Serve immediately. Nutrition
information per tablespoon-protein: 0.4 grams; fat: 1 gram;
carbohydrate: 3 grams; fiber: 0; sodium: 13 milligrams;
cholesterol: 4 milligrams; calories: 26.
</P>
<P>
   PRATIE APPLE
</P>
<P>
   MAKES 10 SERVINGS
</P>
<P>
   4 large (about 3 pounds) baking potatoes, peeled and cut into
1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 cup unsifted all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   6 (about 3 pounds) Granny Smith apples, peeled, cored and thinly
sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup firmly packed light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1) Place potatoes in a 3-quart pan. Cover with water; add salt.
Bring to a boil; cook until fork-tender _ 12 to 15 minutes. Drain
and mash. Stir in 2 tablespoons butter, granulated sugar and
ginger. Cool 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2) Heat oven to 425 degrees. Stir flour into potato mixture,
forming a soft dough. Turn out onto floured surface; form into a
round. Divide in half. Place one half between 2 sheets of plastic
wrap and roll into an 11-inch circle, about 1/4-inch thick. Remove
top sheet of plastic; invert into an 8-inch deep-dish pie plate.
Add apples. Roll out remaining half of dough and cover pie. Crimp
edges of dough together; make 4 slits in top. Bake until lightly
browned _ about 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3) Melt remaining 2 tablespoons butter with brown sugar. Remove
pie from oven. Cut a 2-inch circle in center of pastry. Remove
circle; pour in brown-sugar mixture. Replace circle and return pie
to oven. Bake 20 minutes more. Cool 30 minutes and serve. Nutrition
information per serving-protein: 4 grams; fat: 5 grams;
carbohydrate: 73 grams; fiber: 6 grams; sodium: 158 milligrams;
cholesterol: 12 milligrams; calories: 343.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
