<HEADER>
A8361 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-TRAVELING-PARENT-LIFE     03-06 1497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVELING-PARENT-LIFEBEAT-1,300&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONEY, I'M HOME ... FOR TWO DAYS ANYWAY
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text.  (th)  Laura Hilgers, a
``Child'' contributing editor, lives in San Anselmo, Calif.
 By LAURA HILGERS 
 c.2000 Child magazine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not very long ago, my 5-year-old daughter, Willa, held a
birthday party for her doll Lucy. Willa played Lucy's mom, while I
played Lucy's grandmother, and my 3-year-old son, Devin, was her
uncle.
</P>
<P>
   Someone, however, was missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband is away on a trip,'' Willa explained, as she blew
out Lucy's candles. ``He travels a lot for work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I take a lot of trips, too,'' Willa said. Then, as if to
expose my fantasies, she added, ``When I'm away, my husband watches
the kids. And he cooks, too!''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Willa's ``spouse,'' my husband, Austin, does not cook,
unless you count burnt grilled-cheese sandwiches. He does, though,
travel for his job _ a lot. As a writer for Sports illustrated,
Austin travels 30 to 40 weeks a year, three to five days at a time,
to cover football or hockey or to take on hardship assignments like
interviewing half-naked swimsuit models.
</P>
<P>
   He receives an assignment from his editor on Monday, departs
Wednesday or Thursday, early, and returns around dinnertime on
Monday. He misses every other Thanksgiving with us, and most
Easters. And without fail, he's gone for New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Austin was traveling this much when I started dating him, but
before we had children, I liked his absences. I'd kiss him goodbye,
tell him how horribly I'd miss him, and then spend the next five
days seeing movies, going out with friends and staying in bed all
Saturday morning, reading.
</P>
<P>
   These days, when I kiss him goodbye and tell him how horribly
I'll miss him, I mean it. When he walks out the door for a five-day
stint, I pretty much want to sit down and cry.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no time: Willa is yelling for more butter on her
waffle. Devin has dragged a chair to Austin's dresser and shoved
off the change jar. Willa won't dress for school and whines so
loudly that Devin whacks her with a dump truck. I separate them and
look at the clock: It's not 8 a.m. yet. Only 105 hours to go!
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, we have no monopoly on domestic chaos. But what's
tough for us _ and much, much tougher for truly single parents _ is
that there's not much relief. Austin is usually gone on weekends,
which means that we are alone on Saturdays and Sundays, when
there's no preschool, no daytime baby sitter and not many friends
hanging around. (They're spending time with their own families.)
</P>
<P>
   And, because both Willa and Devin are so young, we can't ever do
things like go to restaurants (Devin never sits longer than 90
seconds) or to the movies (``much too scary,'' says Willa) or even
to the zoo (just another opportunity to run away, in Devin's book).
Often our weekends alone are about as relaxing as a visit to the
mall on the day before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, I wondered why other mothers seemed so much
calmer, so much more organized than I was, until I realized its
just harder when you're on your own. You can't get anything done
except watch the lads.
</P>
<P>
   This might be fine if I were one of those Zen, go-with-the-flow
moms, but I'm not. I like order. I like solitude. So, slowly, I'm
learning how to get through the single-mom marathons, my sanity
nearly intact.
</P>
<P>
   First, in order to always get a break Willa, Devin and I stick
to a fairly regimented schedule. On Friday night, we have ``movie
night,'' the one night each week the kids get to watch videos. On
Saturday morning, we go to the gym, and I check them into childcare
while I work out. On Sunday morning, we divide up at church: Devin,
to childcare; Willa, to Sunday school; and me, to a pew for an hour
of solitude. I'm still trying to figure out whether I go to worship
or simply to be alone.
</P>
<P>
   I also accept, or hire, as much help as possible. We have a baby
sitter who comes three-and-a-half days a week, during which time I
try to work, although that time is too often eaten up by bill
paying or grocery shopping. I hire a college student to come every
other Saturday night, so I can go out, sometimes by myself. I
always accept invitations to people's houses, if anyone's crazy
enough to invite us. And I beg Austin's sister, Gibby, to help me
Sunday afternoons, by which time I'm convinced I'm suffering from
chronic fatigue syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Now our weekends are chock-full of activities, many of them
enjoyable. But the fact remains, we're still without Daddy.
Recently, I told Willa that Austin was going to be gone for two
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two whole days?!'' she said. ``That's OK,'' I replied, ``Mommy
will still be here.'' ``Yeah,'' she said, ``but with Daddy we do
more funner things.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true. Austin is Mr. Fun, which is why I married him. The
kids quickly sniffed him out as a fun-loving, slow to-discipline
sucker, an image only reinforced by the way he deals with his
absences. He showers Willa and Devin with presents (courtesy of
airport gift shops) and lets them watch TV, eat sweets and stay up
well past their bedtimes. Then he departs, leaving me with fired,
sugar-hyped, materialistic kids. I've tried lecturing him, but it's
slow going. (Remember, he's Mr. Fun.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the excruciating pleasure deprivation, however, Willa
and Devin don't seem to truly suffer when Austin's gone. I think
this is because I've tried to create consistency for them. I work
at home because I believe that with Austin gone, they need me
around more.
</P>
<P>
   And I constantly remind them that Austin's absence is temporary.
Even when Willa was tiny, I would tell her and, later, Devin,
``Daddy leaves, but he always comes back.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the kids are old enough, Austin tries to call them each
night. Devin says, ``I got a green lollipop.'' Willa laments, ``My
new Barbie dress got torn.'' They're funny conversations, but
comforting: Daddy is still there.
</P>
<P>
   As for Austin, he misses us, but he's usually ensconced in a
nice hotel room (with room service!), and he's quick to admit that
I have the tougher job. Even if he doesn't mean it, he has to say
it.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen how hard it is to raise kids on your own without words
of gratitude. After my parents' divorce, my mother raised four
teen-agers alone, a feat that still astounds me and points up how
lucky I am to have a spouse who supports us financially and
emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, someday Austin may say the same of me. I recently had
a psychic reading done, and for what it's worth, the psychic told
me that in 10 or 15 years, I'd be the one traveling all the time.
On the craziest days alone with the kids, I savor that thought. I
just hope Austin learns how to cook.
</P>
<P>
   HOW BEST TO SURVIVE THE FREQUENT ABSENCES OF ONE PARENT
</P>
<P>
   1) Stay in touch with the family. Kids need to know that a
traveling mom or dad is still part of their lives. If you travel a
lot, send your child a postcard from the airport before leaving (so
that it will reach home quickly). Jot down a schedule of some of
your child's day-to-day activities, such as a spelling test on
Monday or swimming lessons on Thursday, so you can discuss
important events when you call home.
</P>
<P>
   2) Take it easy with the gifts. Too many, too frequently, lead
to high expectations. Then if you do show up without presents, your
children may be disappointed. They should be happy to see you _
without toys and candy.
</P>
<P>
   3) Be smart about what you can accomplish if you're on your own.
You're one person; you can't do it all, but you can do your best.
</P>
<P>
   4) Try to understand how the absences affect your spouse. The
on-the-road parent needs to recognize how tough it is for everyone
at home and, more important, to verbalize it. Likewise, if you're
the one at home, it may seem like your spouse is on vacation, but
it's important to acknowledge that most business trips are tough,
too.
</P>
<P>
   SOURCE: Jane Annunziata, a clinical psychologist in McLean, Va.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
