<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSHGORE-EDITORIAL-RESEND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO IT'S BUSH VS. GORE. YAWN...  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Editorial...TIMELY FOR TODAY, `SUPER TUESDAY' _ MARCH 7!)   (UPDATED, RESENT from March 1)  
  
 (This 575-word ``separate-buy'' commentary is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 By THE EDITORIAL BOARD OF THE INDEPENDENT  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The string of victories for George W. Bush in the Republican
primaries last Tuesday has left John McCain, his challenger,
apparently sprawled on the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, the electoral fat lady has not yet sung. Not until
today's (Tuesday's) Super Tuesday _ a bumper crop that includes
California, New York, Massachusetts and nine other states _ do we
reach the generally agreed point of no return.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has confounded expectations before. The scale of his
victory in New Hampshire stunned Bush's supporters. He was written
off after his defeat in South Carolina _ and returned from the
political dead in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the fact that Bush won not just Virginia and North
Dakota but also the state of Washington suggests that the era of
McCain excitement may be drawing to a close.
</P>
<P>
   The race in Washington was expected to be close; in reality,
Bush achieved victory by a triumphant 20 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   All of which means that U.S. politics is returning to a sense of
steady-as-she-goes. The potential shake-up elements have fallen by
the wayside.
</P>
<P>
   Oddball candidates such as the billionaires Steve Forbes and
Donald Trump are gone. On the Democratic side, the outsider Bill
Bradley _ whose remarkable successes made the vice president, Al
Gore, feel uncomfortable in recent months _ now seems out for the
count.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley made an all-out bid in Washington state; he was defeated
there by a crushing margin of more than two to one.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that the outsider is doomed to remain on the outside.
Even Bradley's spokesman admitted to being ``a little
disappointed'' _ political-speak for ``The end is nigh.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss of the darkish horses is a pity. It is always fun to
feel that drastic upsets may be on the way. More important, though,
the substantive reasons why Bradley and McCain both seem to have
ended in the out pile must be regretted.
</P>
<P>
   Partly, it was (of course) a question of money. George W., son
of George, and Gore, the White House darling, have much larger war
chests to draw on than the outsiders could dream of.
</P>
<P>
   But it was more than that. Many voters liked the
tell-it-as-it-is breath of fresh air that McCain, a former prisoner
of war in Vietnam, brought to the campaign _ but too many remained
wary of what he stood for.
</P>
<P>
   Crucially, he put an electoral foot wrong when he attacked the
powerful Christian coalition, describing them as ``agents of
intolerance.'' As the description was fair, it is regrettable that
too many Republican voters seem unenthusiastic about such home
truths.
</P>
<P>
   Many important issues, including foreign policy and the death
penalty, have scarcely figured in the campaign so far. Now, the
tragic shooting of a six-year-old child by another six-year-old in
Michigan serves as a reminder of the madness of American gun law _
a laxity that Bush, as governor of Texas, has supported.
</P>
<P>
   It may be hoped that Bush will be partly wrong-footed by the
shooting, though it is too much to hope that further evidence of
gun lunacy will lead to an outbreak of sanity.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, it seems that America may be coming back to the
number it first thought of _ Gore, who only a few months ago seemed
irrevocably tarred by the scandals of Bill Clinton's White House,
but who is now seen as Mr. Dull, Dependable and Clean.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be exciting. But countries have faced worse problems
than that. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 575-word editorial from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper
in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
