<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8376 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-CUBA-2TAKES-HNS &LR;      03-06 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CUBA: COMMUNIST STATE OPENS ITS HEART TO CAPITALIST VISITORS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KATE GURNETT  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ Two words of advice on traveling to Cuba: Go. Now.
</P>
<P>
   Go before Burger Kings mar the Malecon or someone slaps up a Gap
at the Plaza de la Revolucion. Go while Russian-built Ladas still
whisk past the plaza's mammoth image of Che Guevara. Catch a fading
glimpse of the Western Hemisphere's last Communist state _ for
better and for worse. Yes, some things are better. And many things
are worse.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba is complex, a country for the curious and the thoughtful.
It is no place for the dispassionate. They have Cancun.
</P>
<P>
   This magical, sad communist land boasts blocks of majestic
colonial structures now converted into crumbling solarios, the same
buildings chopped into tiny rooms to house families. Hustlers
(jineteras) sit shamelessly on sloppy laps of German tourists.
</P>
<P>
   But people keep their sense of humor. They have a joke about
camellos, the overcrowded hump-backed city buses. Borrowing the
current warning against movies, Cubans use the phrase to warn bus
riders: Sex, violence and adult language.
</P>
<P>
   These days, with dozens of delegations and U.S. college
exchanges arriving monthly, Havana's resemblance to a live history
lab is heightened. Every day an essay question. Compare and
contrast a six-hour Fidel Castro anti-Yanqui speech with the old
Cuban man on his stoop in a Cleveland Cavs cap.
</P>
<P>
   Complexities of Cuban life emerge at breakfast at the
marble-floored luxury Melia Cohiba hotel. A well-vested violin,
accordion and bass trio plays ``Unforgettable'' for Italian and
Spanish tourists who circle a buffet table larger than most Cuban
living rooms. The food could feed the average Habanero for a month.
</P>
<P>
   Compare and contrast Cuba's socialist past with its new
capitalist cloak.
</P>
<P>
   Waves splash over the Malecon, Havana's famed nine-mile seaside
walkway, as two colleagues and I leave the hotel. A bici-taxi
(bicycle pulling two canopied seats) driver offers a ride. We
stroll the tree-lined streets of Vedado, home to embassies and
government officials. Trees abound here; Fidel Castro loves trees.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately a young Cuban hustler named Armaro walks up,
offering a tour, a good restaurant, a club. Thousands of Cubans
grab their share of dollars this way. Castro allowed dollars into
the country in 1993. Today they all but dominate, placing this
socialist land in the position of a Santiago pet pig. Part of the
family, but about to be eaten.
</P>
<P>
   ``The embargo gives us time to get ready for the time when the
big flush of American investments comes,'' Havana's urban
development Director Mario Coyula had told us earlier. ``Because
everything can be lost over time.''
</P>
<P>
   Already in Varadero, where 50 international tourist hotels reign
over the island's best beaches 90 minutes east of Havana and where
Cubans, essentially, are not allowed, Cuba already has its Cancun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shouldn't you be careful?'' I ask Armaro in quiet Spanish as
we approach a corner policeman in green fatigues, beret and a
pernicious stare. The police are known to harass unofficial tour
guides.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't bother me,'' Armaro boasts. ``I'm not black.''
</P>
<P>
   Compare the revolutionary integration of Afro-Cubans to past and
present racism.
</P>
<P>
   Armaro's uncle lives in Miami and owns a restaurant. He sends
his seven relatives $50 each at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a cheap uncle,'' I joke. ``Tell him to send more.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughs and points at an elementary school with no windows.
The bell rings. After the Soviet Union collapsed, he said, ending
$5.5 billion in annual Cuban subsidies, the bells broke and there
was no money to fix them. Teachers were a comical sight, he
remembered, as they stood in front of classrooms, hollering
``Change classes!''
</P>
<P>
   Abandoned by the Russians, Cuba is for the first time in history
truly independent. No longer a Spanish colony, no longer dominated
by the United States, no longer a Soviet welfare client. Seemingly
without regret, it moves forward, carefully picking its economic
partners.
</P>
<P>
   And Cubans love to discuss where they went wrong, openly and
honestly, even at high levels of government. (Compare that to your
average U.S. politician.)
</P>
<P>
   We leave Armaro and head for the dollar supermarket _ there is
nothing for sale in the peso market. We need rum and chicken, two
rarities we plan to share at dinner with some newfound Cuban
friends. They have no rum. They have no chicken. They have no
cooking oil.
</P>
<P>
   But still they invited us to dinner after we met their son
Miguel on the street. He bought us a glass of white rum and asked,
apropos of nothing, ``Do you want to meet my parents?''
</P>
<P>
   This is NOT uncommon. Cubans love people.
</P>
<P>
   Their flat was up a dark staircase, crowded with dusty brown
books, a fig tree and wall posters of Che Guevara and swimsuit
models, reflecting the two generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Che is my heart,'' Miguel's mother said. American poster babes
are her son's.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel's father, a professor, poured the first bit of brown
Havana Club rum from the new bottle into the fig tree, an offering
to a Santeria god belonging to the pantheon of the Afro-Caribbean
religion practiced by many Cubans. He told us how the revolution
changed his life. Before Castro, his Jamaican heritage brought
discrimination, he said. After, he found good jobs and social
acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Cubans, he asked us not to print his name. The press
is government-run and people do not speak freely. I chose a
pseudonym for his son.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE . . . MORE)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HAVANA: x x x for his son. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the older generation still believes strongly in the
revolution and the guerrillas who tossed out the corrupt dictator
Fulgencio Batista. They appreciate the free health care, the free
university educations. But dollars entice their children, who know
nothing of Batista and were raised on scarcity and tired communist
slogans. Miguel's mother lives in fear that he will take a boat to
Miami, as his best friend did a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some older professionals are disgruntled, too. Castro ``comes
between a man and his wife,'' said one man who wants to play the
forbidden American radio in bed at night. His wife, afraid the
neighbors will hear, won't let him. So he retires to the living
room. Contrast social progress with lack of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, American culture pervades. Rare is the cabdriver who
doesn't blast American hits of the 1980s, from Michael McDonald to
Air Supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the music of my teen-age time,'' said Cesar Font, 36, a
Havana cabbie. ``Billy Joel was very famous in Cuba. He did come
here in 1979 ... Christopher Cross. Kool and the Gang. In my casa I
have 80 minutes live (of Kool and the Gang).''
</P>
<P>
   The songs helped Font learn English. In the land of salsa, he
prefers Willie Nelson and Dolly Parton.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just music. They love the people. And despite the flap
over 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez, they bear us no grudge. Marching
100,000 strong during our visit, their demand that Elian return was
sincere, even if they were bused in by the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans are surprised they don't find a hostile
population,'' Coyula said. ``We never talk much officially, but we
have American culture in everything, in films and in music. More
people are coming here; they're really sympathetic with the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   The thrill for many Americans who visit Cuba in greater numbers
each year is that access has been denied.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Prohibition,'' said Wayne Smith, chief of the U.S.
Interests Section from 1979 to 1982. ``The forbidden fruit.''
</P>
<P>
   Many who come sympathize with the revolution. Like Al Lewis, the
Green Party candidate for New York governor best known for his
portrayal of ``Grandpa'' on the hit '60s television series ``The
Munsters.''
</P>
<P>
   Leftists love Cuba. After all, this is the country that granted
asylum to some Black Panthers. Joanne Chesimard, former head of
Black Liberation Army who escaped from prison in 1979, won
political exile and is still here.
</P>
<P>
   We met three other Green Party members in Santiago de Cuba on
the island's eastern end at a modest bed-and-breakfast run by Zaida
Moraleza, a retired doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago is poorer than Havana. Here young boys playing street
ball use a splintered piece of wood and a bottle cap. People from
this part of the country are so impoverished that if they move to
Havana, Habaneros dub them ``Palestinians.''
</P>
<P>
   But life here is good, according to Moraleza's daughter, also
named Zaida Moraleza, who helps her mother run the
bed-and-breakfast. She wishes the economy was robust enough for
Cubans to travel to Europe and Central America. ``Then they would
see that we live comfortably here. Now they can't compare.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicine may be plentiful in the United States, Moraleza said,
but it isn't cheap. A cousin in Texas who had a kidney transplant
died because he couldn't afford the $200 a week for medicines, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, more and more Americans visit the island, joining the
Canadians and Europeans who have been coming here for a decade.
More than 1.7 million tourists came in 1999, up from 500,000 in
1993. Two million are expected in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moraleza complained about foreign tourists coming here to have
sex with 14-year-old prostitutes. ``It's horrible,'' she said. Cuba
does not yet compare to Acapulco or Bangkok, where such abuse of
children is rampant. But prostitutes openly greet foreign tourists,
often in their hotel lobbies. The government does make arrests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have harassed the prostitutes,'' said Julio Espinoza, the
National Assembly's International Relations Committee coordinator
general. ``But it persists. Is the solution to bring all of them to
jail? It would be very easy. But our objective has to be persuasion
and to offer them jobs. And that is combined with harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course the ultimate question: Will history absolve Fidel
Castro?
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that so many Americans have is that this is just a
total failure,'' Wayne Smith said. ``But they did produce the most
egalitarian society I think this hemisphere has seen. There is no
freedom of expression, no freedom of the press, but it is
egalitarian. They did provide free health care to everyone, free
education.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he hopes the United States will ease the embargo,
prompting Cuba to move toward democracy. ``There's no place quite
like it in the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And whether or not history repeats itself, the best time to
visit Cuba is now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 1519EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
