<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8383 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-INTERNET-PEDOPHILIA-H     03-06 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-PEDOPHILIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POLICE WATCH THE INTERNET FOR HIGH-TECH PEDOPHILES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRENDAN LYONS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLONIE, N.Y. _ In a cramped, windowless room at Colonie Police
Headquarters, Detective Lt. Thomas Breslin gingerly taps a keyboard
as he converses in an Internet chat room with an older man from
Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Breslin's undercover screen name isn't enticing _ it's actually
very plain _ and when asked, the detective tells the man that he is
a 14-year-old female just home from school.
</P>
<P>
   Within seconds, the man has downloaded a naked photograph of
himself to Breslin's computer and types a message to the fictitious
teenager: ``So you like older guys? ... You'd be my secret.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the new era of pedophilia, where predators no longer
risk staking out playgrounds or video arcades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them just want to talk dirty,'' Breslin says as his
computer screen suddenly fills up with messages from other people
in the chat room hoping to strike up a conversation with the teen.
</P>
<P>
   The Colonie department is one of the few local forces that use
the Internet to nab suspects beyond its borders. During the past
three years, police have lured about half a dozen people from as
far away as Virginia and Connecticut who were seeking sex with
minors.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics say such police tactics border on entrapment and
infringe on privacy rights, and that departments should focus on
crimes in their own back yard. But advocates of the approach say
pedophiles and other criminals have saturated the Internet, where
police jurisdictional boundaries disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always controversy about police sting operations and
allegations of entrapment, but the thing that you have to remember
is these subjects are predisposed to do this type of criminal
activity,'' said Richard Bernes, who retired as head of the FBI's
high-tech crimes squad in 1997. ``All the police departments are
doing is allowing themselves to become the victim.''
</P>
<P>
   Breslin and two other middle-aged Colonie detectives spend their
``spare time'' browsing chat rooms posing as teenagers. And they
are no slouches
</P>
<P>
   when it comes to knowing their teenage lingo. They know the
names of the popular teenage band members and use hip language like
``phat'' when describing something as cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've also had numerous cases with child pornography
distribution from out of state, with suspects trading it
electronically over the Internet,'' Breslin said.
</P>
<P>
   Colonie decided to police the Internet after the department
received numerous complaints from local residents or businesses
about computer-related crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't say to people we don't do computer stuff here,''
Breslin said. ``We finally got to the point where we had to go
further with our training or get out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The three detectives who do the work in Colonie _ Breslin and
detectives Steve Tanski and Mike Tully _ usually spend no more than
a half-hour each day browsing questionable chat rooms, the
lieutenant said. They go online when they have time to kill in
between their normal police duties, unless actively working a
strong case.
</P>
<P>
   Breslin couldn't say how much it costs the department.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Thomas Spina, who has prosecuted many of
Colonie's cases, said he has turned away cases on occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very strict guidelines they have to follow to avoid
any type of entrapment,'' Spina said. ``We have to be the
receivers. If they've been too suggestive, I won't pursue the
case.''
</P>
<P>
   In several of the cases that Spina successfully prosecuted, he
said, the accused had a history of child molestation or dealing in
child pornography. ``They were predisposed to this type of
activity, so there is no entrapment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
