<HEADER>
A8386 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-06 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NO MORE PROPOSITIONS, PLEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The only ballot measure petition I will ever
sign is one that proposes a moratorium on ballot measures.
</P>
<P>
   Each California election gets worse. The list of complex,
confusing propositions grows more unwieldy. Millions of dollars are
wasted as big industries like tobacco or insurance put self-serving
propositions on the ballot and ragtag citizens groups fight them.
</P>
<P>
   We are stuck with this beast _ 20 of them statewide. Here are
some that deserve a ``no'' vote in Tuesday's election:
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 21 _ It should be enough to know that this is a
left-over from former Gov. Pete Wilson's silly attempt to be
president.
</P>
<P>
   Filled with dangerous, sweeping generalizations _ any juvenile
gang member convicted of murder would qualify for the death penalty
_ its sledgehammer centerpiece is mandated sentencing, which disses
the experience of the state's 227 juvenile court justices.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 21 also would ensure that thousands of kid felons go
straight to adult prison. And it would cost us close to $430
million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 22 _ California law already says a legal marriage is
between a man and a woman. Bankrolled big-time by the Mormon and
Catholic churches, 22 is the work of state Sen. William ``Pete''
Knight. He wants to slam the door forever on gays and lesbians who
are working toward some kind of official recognition of their
domestic unions.
</P>
<P>
   Such a stance is not only unkind, it denies two major realities:
</P>
<P>
   _ Thousands of California gays and their children already live
in stable, healthy, community-enhancing families; they deserve the
same rights and benefits as heterosexual couples enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Despite all the high-minded talk about the ``sanctity'' of
male-female marriage, it is hardly a perfect haven of family bliss.
Spouses and children in heterosexual families are battered and
abused every day, and about half of all guy-gal marriages end in
divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't society need all the loving, committed domestic unions
it can find?
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 28 _ One fact should suffice as reason enough to
reject this colossal time-waster: The man who got it on the ballot
is president of a mega-chain of stores called ``Cigarettes
Cheaper!''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, California voters did the right thing and imposed a
50-cents-per-pack tax on cigarettes. The money, about $670 million
a year, is largely controlled by local commissions for use in their
own areas to promote child development and education programs and
to fight smoking by children.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Cigarettes Cheaper wants to repeal the tax for several
altruistic reasons, he says. Among them: The folks in charge of
spending the money are taking too much time deciding which programs
will make the best use of the dough.
</P>
<P>
   One more thing. You alleged liberals and fed-up Democrats who
like John McCain's straight-shooter style and find him
``refreshing''? Do me a favor. Sit down and look at his voting
record.
</P>
<P>
   All the charm and honesty in the world can't wipe out the fact
that McCain is rabidly anti-choice, anti-gun control, anti-gay
rights, anti-environmental protection and about as hawkish in
foreign policy as Gen. Jack C. Ripper in ``Dr. Strangelove.''
</P>
<P>
   Wake up! This guy could make Reagan look like F.D.R.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
