<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0265 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8387 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-VETS-MCCAIN-HNS &LR;      03-06 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETS-MCCAIN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     VETS SAY THEY ADMIRE McCAIN  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Veterans from an Army battalion that spent more
time in Vietnam than almost any other during the war have nothing
but respect for John McCain, the former Navy flier who spent six
years in a North Vietnamese prison.
</P>
<P>
   But they're not sure he should be president.
</P>
<P>
   McCain ``seems to be able to say the right things to people who
are fed up with the establishment, and he undeniably has the aura
of a hero. But I still have some concerns,'' said Tim Swett of
Bethesda, Md., the first commander of the 5th Battalion of the 7th
Cavalry, 1st Cavalry Division.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator's campaign for the GOP nomination against
Texas Gov. George W. Bush has emphasized his biography,
particularly the story of his capture and survival as a POW, as it
targeted veterans for support.
</P>
<P>
   But Joe Dzikas, 54, of West Haven, Conn., a sergeant in
headquarters company in 1966-67, cautioned against putting too much
emphasis on McCain's status as a veteran. ``Personally, I hope they
don't vote with that veteran thing in mind,'' he said. ``A guy can
be a veteran and still be a bum. Vietnam was a long time ago . . .
don't sit back on your laurels, don't think something you did 30
years ago makes you a better person.''
</P>
<P>
   American voters have agreed with Dzikas in the last two
elections, choosing Bill Clinton, who had no battle experience,
over highly decorated World War II veterans George Bush and Bob
Dole. The election also seemed to mark a generational change of
leadership for Americans from those steeled by World War II to
those who came of age during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Although McCain, too, is part of the Vietnam generation, he fits
the mold of the decorated war veteran-turned-politician.
</P>
<P>
   How much that personal history counts with voters will be seen
in large part on Tuesday, when 613 Republican delegates are
contested in 16 primaries and caucuses across the country including
California. In an attempt to gauge the importance of McCain's
veteran credentials, The Examiner spoke with vets In some of those
states who served in the 5th of the 7th _ a battalion that was in
Vietnam from 1966-71, longer than almost any other infantry unit.
</P>
<P>
   Contemporaries of the senator, most of them pushing 60, the
veterans offered views on McCain that ranged from enthusiastic to
lukewarm, with M.D. ``Papa Doc'' Maxwell of St. Joseph, Mo., a 5th
of the 7th medic in 1966-67, arguing the hardest for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You give me a choice between (Democratic Vice President Al)
Gore, Bush and McCain, and I'll take McCain _ all you got to do is
look in his eyes,'' he said. ``I'd rather have McCain because he
looks at somebody straight across the table. He looks you straight
in the face and says, `This is what I'm going to do.'''
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell, 59, awarded five Purple Hearts during his Vietnam tour,
said, ``Tell you what, if vets get off their dead butts and do
something for once, McCain would win this presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time this country stood up to the world and said, `Hey,
we've had enough,'''he said. ``We're not going to send our kids to
Kosovo, we're not going to send kids to die when they don't even
know what's going on. I think McCain feels the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Nunez, 55, of Orange, Calif., ``I'll probably vote McCain,
but I don't think he'll win. The guy gives direct answers, and I
like honesty. I was talking with some other vets and we'd like to
see Bush make him secretary of State or vice president, but I don't
think their egos would let them do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nunez rued what he thinks is a missed opportunity for McCain in
California's primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think McCain has really pushed for California at all.
I've heard very little down here,'' said Nunez. ``I wish the
candidates would stop beating each other up and just stick to the
issues. I'm going to have grandkids here in June and I want to hear
what they have to say about education and Social Security, things
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerhard Brostrom, who served in the same squad of Charlie
Company in 1967 with Nunez, said, ``As much as I respect McCain, it
doesn't affect my affinity for the Democrats, particularly Gore,
who I think also had an honorable wartime record (in Vietnam).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a firm believer in the political process, so I hope McCain
stays in the race, even if he loses Tuesday,`` said Brostrom. ``I'd
like to see a horse race in the Republican Party. I like what
McCain can inject into the campaign.'' Brostrom, who spent his
Vietnam tour living out of helicopters and jungle holes, said,
``McCain seems to have real candor and honesty, even filtered
through the press.``
</P>
<P>
   Wes Westmoreland, 62, who works for Thomas Steel in Warren,
Ohio, said 180 of the 500 men at the mill are veterans who are
following McCain closely. ``People are saying his chances are less
than 50 percent,'' said Westmoreland, a sergeant major with the 5th
of the 7th who did three tours of Vietnam. ``But they've been wrong
before, and I hope they're wrong this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Vietnamese gave him an opportunity to leave prison but he
stayed with the rest of the guys and went through a hell of an
ordeal. I have a lot of respect for him.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Edvins Beitiks of the San Francisco Examiner was a squad leader
with A Co., 5th of the 7th, in 1967-68.)
</P>
</TEXT>
