<HEADER>
A8396 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-06 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STRIKING IT RICH IN THE BAY AREA'S OUTDOOR JACKPOT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The treasures of the newest recreation area in
the San Francisco Bay Area are known to few, yet are surveyed
without hardly a thought from afar by thousands each day.
</P>
<P>
   This area covers 13,000 acres, highlighted by 10,000 acres of
wetlands and an intricate web of waterways that can be accessed by
canoe, kayak or power boat, along with dirt roads on levees that
can be used as trails that are ideal for biking, hiking and
birdwatching. There are also several of the better shoreline
fishing spots in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Where? While relatively few have learned of these places, it is
likely that millions of Bay Area residents have driven right by it
on Highway 37 between San Rafael and Vallejo: It is the Napa-Sonoma
Marshes Wildlife Area, the centerpiece of the Department of
California Fish and Game's new multiple-use wildlife ethic.
</P>
<P>
   My recent visit showed that it isn't fishing and hunting that is
attracting most of the people who love this place. Rather, it's
hiking, biking and birdwatching drawing people who love nature and
open spaces in a peaceful setting with the chance of something
special.
</P>
<P>
   The Napa-Sonoma Marsh is shaped like a giant square and roughly
bordered by Highway 37 to the south, Highway 12 to the east,
Highway 121 to the west and Highway 12/121 to the north. There are
five access points, two well-signed parking areas off Highway 37
and another three near cut-off roads from Highway 12/121, as well
as two public boat ramps. A map is advised, available from the
Department of Fish and Game at the address at the end of this
story.
</P>
<P>
   The network of rivers, sloughs, creeks, tidal-influenced
brackish water lakes and ponds _ often bordered by levees for
hiking or biking access _ makes this among the most unique
recreation sites in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful white egrets are commonly seen poking about for food,
along with dozens of waterfowl species, including all the major
duck and geese species, with hawk sightings also common. At a pond
west of the Buchli Station Road access, there is a rookery of 15 to
20 black-crowned night heron, those lovable fellows who look like
cartoon characters by the way their head seems to sit on neck-less
bodies. In addition, fishing for striped bass is often good in
spring and fall at a spot called Salt Pond No. 1, as well as at the
neighboring San Pablo Bay National Wildlife Refuge near the mouth
of Sonoma Creek.
</P>
<P>
   The best jump-off point for hikers and bikers is the Buchli
parking lot, with access to a series of connected roads and routes
set on levees. To reach the Buchli parking lot: From Highway 121/12
(the road that connects Sonoma and Napa), drive to Duhig Road, turn
south, and drive to Las Amigas Road. Turn left (east) on Las Amigas
and drive to Buchli Station Road. Turn right (south) and drive to
the parking lot at the end of the road just over the railroad
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   On our visit, the weather was unsettled, with dark, billowing
cumulus clouds towering over Mount Tamalpais and the surrounding
foothills and occasional surprise rainbows brightening the
landscape. A refreshing 10-knot breeze was being sent out of the
south. It added texture to a habitat known for its understated
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   In a canoe, it can seem as if you are a million miles away from
San Francisco, paddling about, exploring vast wetland communities.
A complex web of navigable waterways includes Sonoma Creek, Napa
Slough, several unnamed brackish-water ponds, and fingers of the
Napa River. You can even get lost! Imagine that: Getting lost in
the Bay Area?
</P>
<P>
   It's possible here, that is, without a navigation chart.
</P>
<P>
   While this is accessible by power boat, DFG senior biologist Jim
Swanson, who commonly surveys the area with a Boston Whaler, also
advises careful use of a tide book to stay clear of being grounded
by low tides.
</P>
<P>
   One of Swanson's challenges is to convert old salt ponds here to
viable wetland habitat. It may seem a formidable task, but
Swanson's first try has been a success after only a year of work,
with a former salt pond already filled with plants, clams and
invertebrates, and in turn, all the wildlife that depends on them.
It has become a model for salt ponds in other regions.
</P>
<P>
   This wildlife area has come together piece by piece over the
past 15 years with purchases paid for by the State Wildlife
Conservation Board. A key missing piece of the land puzzle was
found in 1994, when the state was able to buy salt ponds located
roughly in the center of the complex. Much of the money that has
made this refuge possible has come from penalties paid by Shell Oil
as damages for an oil spill in the mid-1980s near Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of the best things the DFG has done in the Bay Area in
the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   For a map/brochure, write to the Department of Fish and Game,
P.O. Box 47, Yountville, CA 94599, or phone 707-944-5500. It can
also be picked up in person at the DFG regional office at 7329
Silverado Trail in Napa.
</P>
</TEXT>
