<HEADER>
A8416 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN04-COX     03-06 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Christian right can't intimidate this GOP candidate
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Sen. John McCain tells the big money boys that
their campaign donations are corrupting government.
</P>
<P>
   Then he tells Iowa corn farmers that ethanol subsidies are a
waste of taxpayers' money.
</P>
<P>
   Next he takes a whip to the ``union bosses'' of the Christian
right in South Carolina and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is not your father's Republican. He's not typical of any
political species.
</P>
<P>
   No one would be surprised if McCain refused to kiss a baby and
say it's a stupid practice. Besides, the woman's baby was ugly.
</P>
<P>
   In the temple of the Christian right, McCain lambastes Pat
Robertson, the founder of the Christian Coalition, and Jerry
Falwell, the founder of the Moral Majority.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said that it was time for the Republican Party to stop
bowing to these ``union bosses who have subordinated the interests
of working families to their own ambitions.'' He denounced
Robertson and Falwell as ``agents of intolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The politics of division and slander are not our values,''
McCain told a Virginia Beach crowd a short distance from the
Christian Coalition headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Like his father before him, Gov. George W. Bush wants the votes
that Robertson and Falwell can deliver.
</P>
<P>
   Bush cannot argue that division and slander are Republican
values. He also cannot easily dispute that Robertson and Falwell
have built their extremely lucrative preaching careers based on
division and slander. Better to change the subject.
</P>
<P>
   After two long terms with Bill Clinton as president, Americans
want the next occupant of the White House to be guided by higher
values than ``what the definition of `is' is.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, most of the candidates in this presidential race have
attempted to convince the voters that they are tight with Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to name his favorite philosopher in one debate, Bush
quickly said Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   If the candidates think that parading their religion
demonstrates values higher than Clinton's, they have not considered
that Clinton does the same.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan's handlers first hit upon the idea of inviting the
fundamentalist Christian leaders into the Republican tent.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for political support from the televangelists, the
Republicans promised to champion favorite pulpit issues utilized by
the preachers.
</P>
<P>
   This was a match made in heaven for the Gipper, the Moral
Majority and the Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   When it was his time to run, former President Bush honored the
deal struck with the Christian right.
</P>
<P>
   Bush the Father, like Reagan, went to South Carolina to speak at
Bob Jones University, an institution renowned for its religious and
racial intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Bush the Boy did the same. That's when McCain first lashed out
against the practice of courting religious bigots in exchange for
their political support.
</P>
<P>
   Bush carried South Carolina and steadfastly defended his
appearance at Bob Jones University until McCain whipped him in
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Then Bush admitted that he should have separated himself from
some of the bigoted beliefs associated with the fundamentalist
university.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't enough for McCain, who has been targeted with a
morally despicable telephone campaign by Christian right
fundamentalists.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was careful to not condemn all conservative Christians,
only those ``self-appointed leaders'' who preach intolerance and
bigotry and have become a ``corrupting influence on religion and
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a problem-solver,'' Bush said in response to McCain's
attack of his powerful supporters. ``It sounds like he's a
finger-pointer.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, finger-pointing might be the right medicine for
the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
