<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8418 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-TATTOO-REMOVAL-HNS &LR;      03-06 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TATTOO-REMOVAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IN TATTOO BUSINESS, IT'S NO PAIN, NO GAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANK BLACKMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Generations of parents have warned their
children about tattoos.
</P>
<P>
   It's painful to put them on. There's the risk of infection. And,
once on, it's too late for regrets because a tattoo can never come
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't no lie, it hurts,'' Golden State Warriors forward
Donyell Marshall said. ``The first time I got mine, I almost passed
out in the chair.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyle Tuttle is the proprietor of a tattoo shop. He has been in
this line of work for 50 years and has seen more than his fair
share of clients squirm, moan and whimper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's neither excruciating nor entertaining,'' Tuttle said.
``It's something in between. Tattoos have a good brisk sting to
them. But if didn't sting, even wimps would get them.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuttle wanted to dispel one myth, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can truthfully say I've never once seen an infected tattoo
caused by the tattoo artist,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Intricate, time-consuming needle work gets expensive. A large
tattoo might take three or four hours to put on. The going rate in
San Francisco is $125 per hour. A top artist will charge $200 per
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Business always has been good.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always been a segment of society that gets tattoos,''
Tuttle said.
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, it was returning GIs who made up the bulk of
the tattoo customers. The golden age of body art began with the
women's movement in the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It opened up half the human race to tattooing,'' Tuttle said.
``That was a big shot in the arm. The next shot in the arm was the
cross-over into the black community. It started through black
athletes. Everybody needs role models.''
</P>
<P>
   In time, some people become disenchanted with their tattoos. A
relationship that was supposed to last a lifetime ends. Or a large
tattoo that inspired oohs and aahs in high school produces frowns
in the workplace a decade later.
</P>
<P>
   That is when it is time to visit someone like Dr. David Laub. He
is a board-certified dermatologist and cosmetic surgeon with an
office in Mill Valley. He can undo what Tuttle did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, technology has improved,'' Laub said. ``Years
ago, the only way to remove a tattoo was to excise it off or use a
dermabrader to take it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``With lasers, we can choose the proper wave length for each
color. So we can not only remove black but blue and red, too. Black
is the easiest, green is the most difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Until laser surgery became commonplace, it was only possible to
remove small tattoos, and they either had to be removed with a
scalpel (excised) or scraped off (dermabrasion).
</P>
<P>
   ``With the advent of lasers you can do the procedure over
several months,'' Laub said. ``The tattoo will start lightening in
color. Depending on the tattoo, it will go away 100 percent or 80
to 90 percent. That depends on the color.''
</P>
<P>
   This procedure, in addition to being time-consuming, is
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   A small tattoo could require anywhere from five to 10 20-minute
sessions to remove, costing up to $300 for each visit. For a large
tattoo, each session will last 45 minutes, and the cost will be
proportionately higher.
</P>
<P>
   So before visiting a tattoo artist, it might be a good idea to
consider the consequences of changing your mind later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spoken in high schools about this,'' Laub said. ``When I
talk to students, I always tell them they should start with a small
one. It should be one color, preferably black. The reason for that
is that it's much easier to take off one color and a smaller one is
easier to take off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the trend is toward larger and larger tattoos
that are pretty ornate. And the larger they are, and the more
colors they have, the harder they are to take off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
