<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PRIMARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW YORK'S PRIMARY IS MOST SUSPENSEFUL OF SUPER TUESDAY RACES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LARA JAKES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A neck-and-neck race among Republicans and a
last-ditch effort by a Democrat have turned New York's presidential
primary into the most suspenseful of the 16 Super Tuesday contests.
</P>
<P>
   Frantic get-out-the-vote efforts by Democrats Bill Bradley and
Al Gore and Republicans George W. Bush and John McCain culminate
Tuesday in the biggest primary day of the 2000 presidential race.
One-third of the delegates who will nominate presidential
candidates will be selected on a single day.
</P>
<P>
   And New York _ second only to California in the number of
delegates at stake _ has emerged, for the first time in years, as a
crucial primary state.
</P>
<P>
   But while polls and political analysts have called Vice
President Gore and Bush, the Texas governor, the all-but-certain
winners in California, New York is still up for grabs, at least
among the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show GOP voters nearly evenly divided between Bush and
McCain, the Arizona senator who was 20 points behind in New York
just six weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shootout,'' said Jay Severin, a New York-based GOP
consultant. ``New York will be the life-saver for McCain if he can
pull it out. It would be beating Bush where Bush was supposed to be
the prohibitive favorite. If he wins New York, it's an indication
that he, not Bush, can win the nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   Severin adds, ``California is the sizzle, but New York is the
steak.''
</P>
<P>
   An Albany Times Union-Buffalo News poll released Sunday shows
Bush and McCain running neck-and-neck among enrolled Republicans
who say they are likely to vote Tuesday. The poll, conducted Feb.
29 to March 3 by Zogby International, shows McCain at 43 percent
and Bush at 40 percent _ within a 3.3 percent margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   Among Democrats, the poll had Gore leading Bradley, the former
New Jersey senator, by a decisive 58 percent to 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A large voter turnout should be an advantage for Bush and Gore,
both of whom have their respective parties' organizations to get
voters to the polls, said Buffalo-based GOP analyst Jack Cookfair.
New York primaries, however, even when they are contested, have
traditionally yielded low turnout _ 26 percent among Democrats in
1992, and 36 percent among Republicans in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is going for broke in New York, which many observers say
he must win to remain competitive. By the time polls close Tuesday,
the former New York Knicks basketball star will have spent five of
the previous six days in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also is spending significant time in the Empire State. But
his visits to Florida last week and to his home state of Tennessee
on primary night signal that he already is looking ahead to the six
primaries in ``Southern Super Tuesday'' on March 14.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and Gore have each unleashed multimillion-dollar ad
campaigns in New York over the last 10 days with at least two
television spots each running in all of the state's urban media
markets. Both are blanketing Democrat-rich New York City and
courting suburban swing voters with visits and get-out-the-vote
telephone calls targeted to reach up to 500,000 Democratic
households.
</P>
<P>
   Although young voters account for a meager estimated voter
turnout of 8 percent, Bradley is appealing to them to boost his
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``They respond to Bill's message of change and hope and
integrity,'' said Bradley's national deputy campaign manager,
Jacques Andre DeGraff. ``A list of 600 endorsements doesn't move
somebody who's 22 years old,'' he added, taking a jab at the
state's pro-Gore Democratic establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Gore meanwhile, is reaching out to traditional Democratic voting
blocs _ labor unions, minorities and women _ and sticking to
traditional Democratic themes: the environment, health care and
education. He also is looking past the primary process to zone in
on the GOP opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, the Republican candidates _ they have both supported
draining money away from public schools at a time when more is
needed,'' the vice president said last week at P.S. 163 on
Manhattan's Upper West Side. ``They seem to think that just because
New York schools begin with `P.S.' that education is an
afterthought.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and McCain seem too busy duking it out with each other to
notice. McCain has touted himself as the candidate with the best
chance of defeating Gore but has had his hands full in the face of
TV and radio attacks on his Senate voting record on the environment
and breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Bush budgeted $1.5 million for TV and radio spots in New York to
pump up his record in Texas _ and deflate McCain's in the Senate.
Bush also started airing a radio spot Saturday attacking McCain's
education record, in a move analysts said was aimed at women
voters.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a Texas-based group calling itself ``Republicans
for Clean Air'' shelled out another $1.5 million in the state on
Bush's behalf. Their ad, which the Bush campaign says was done
without its knowledge, paints a harsh picture of McCain while
lauding the Texas governor's environmental record. The Sierra Club
described the ad as full of ``half-truths.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has had problems in his own ranks, most notably the past
week's rift between Gov. George Pataki and New York City Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, who have often clashed over the years. Though
both have endorsed Bush, Giuliani has refused to join in attacks on
McCain, whom he calls a personal friend. That prompted Pataki aide
Zenia Mucha to accuse the mayor of being disloyal to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The rift, which drew attention away from the candidate and
toward the local politicians, surely doesn't help Bush in the
waning days of a campaign where a solidified Republican
establishment was supposed to provide Bush's political muscle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
