<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8443 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT &LR;      03-06 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN'S SAFETY OFTEN NEGLECTED IN CARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By JANE E. BRODY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With all the concern most parents express about the safety of
their children, it is surprising _ no, shocking _ that so many
parents are so casual about a proven safety measure that could make
a life-or-death difference: the consistent use of proper child
restraints in motor vehicles, especially for children who are too
old for infant and child safety seats and too young for adult seat
belts.
</P>
<P>
   In New York state, parents cannot take a newborn home from the
hospital in a car without a proper car safety seat. All states have
laws requiring children under 4 to be restrained while riding in a
car, and 25 states require that children up to 16 be restrained at
all times.
</P>
<P>
   And, after a series of deaths caused by air bags, parents have
been advised to place all children 12 and under in the rear seat,
where the risk of death in an accident is 35 percent lower than it
is among front-seat occupants.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite all the laws and warnings, motor vehicle accidents
remain the single largest cause of death among children 15 and
younger.
</P>
<P>
   Analyses of fatal accidents have shown that there are many a
slip between the law and the proper use of restraint systems,
especially once children outgrow their child safety seats.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, there are many gaps in the laws for children aged 4
through 8. In 19 states, children in this age group can ride
unrestrained in the back seat of a motor vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   And no state requires the use of booster seats for children who
have outgrown their car seats, even though booster seats, which
raise youngsters high enough so that the adult lap-and-shoulder
belt can be used safely, is the only proper way to protect children
in this age group.
</P>
<P>
   ``After age 3, child safety seats are pretty much out of the
picture,'' said Dr. James Nichols, director of research and traffic
records at the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.
``Children are either not restrained at all or they are put _
improperly _ in adult seat belts.''
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, many youngsters are allowed to ride in
the front seat, where the impact from an air bag can kill them if a
crash doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   The safety agency has just begun a $7.5 million nationwide
campaign, ``Don't Skip a Step,'' to alert parents to the urgency of
using booster seats for children weighing 40 to 80 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Although there has been a decline in crash-related deaths among
infants thanks to greatly increased use of infant safety seats
(which should always be placed in the back seat facing the rear of
the vehicle), fatalities among children ages 4 to 8 have remained
stable since the mid-'90s.
</P>
<P>
   In a new study of fatal crashes conducted by the National Center
for Injury Prevention and Control, from 1994 through 1998, there
was little change in the death rate, the use of restraints or the
seating position among children in the 4 to 8 age group who were
killed in crashes.
</P>
<P>
   The study, by Steve Trockman and Dr. Ann Dellinger of the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta, found that
the death rate, adjusted for age, remained about 2.6 per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Of those killed, only 35.2 percent were using some kind of
restraint in 1994, a figure that climbed minimally to 38.1 percent
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The proportion of children killed while sitting in the back seat
was 50.1 percent in 1994 and 53.7 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   During the study period, 14,411 children ages 4 through 8 were
involved in vehicle crashes in which one or more fatal injuries
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Of these, 2,549 _ 17.7 percent _ died. In other words, each year
motor vehicle accidents took the lives of about 500 children in
this age group, at least half of whom would have survived had they
been properly restrained when the crash occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration cites even
more frightening data.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the latest year for which statistics are available,
only 4 percent of 5-year-olds who were involved in fatal crashes
were in any form of child restraint, and of those children who died
in the crashes, fewer than 2 percent were in appropriate safety
seats at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Of 609 5-year-olds involved in fatal crashes that year, 211 had
no restraint at all and 262 were using some sort of seat belt,
which is an inappropriate restraint for their size and can result
in serious injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our observational studies, seldom do we find more than 6 or
7 percent of 5-to-8-year-olds in a booster seat,'' Nichols said.
``It's always less than 10 percent of the children who are in a
seat that is appropriate for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet when parents are surveyed, Nichols said, most feel that they
already know all that they should know about keeping their children
safe in motor vehicles. ``Almost no one wants to know anything more
about child safety seats, and specifically about booster seats,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The American Academy of Pediatrics recommends the following
guidelines. From birth and until children weigh at least 20 pounds
and reach 1 year of age, they should ride in an infant car safety
seat facing the rear of a vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   This reduces the risk of spinal injury in case of a crash and
avoids the risk of injury from an inflating air bag.
</P>
<P>
   Infants who reach 20 pounds before age 1 should still ride
facing the rear in either a convertible safety seat or in an infant
seat approved for the higher weights.
</P>
<P>
   Children older than 1 who weigh 20 to 40 pounds can ride in a
child safety seat facing forward, as long as it is still in the
back seat.
</P>
<P>
   Once a child is too big for a child safety seat but still too
small to use an adult safety belt, a belt-positioning booster seat
should be used. This allows the shoulder harness of the vehicle's
safety belt to cross the child's chest and the lap belt to fit
across the upper thighs.
</P>
<P>
   If a shoulder strap rides too high on the child, he could be
strangled during an accident. And if the lap belt crosses the
abdomen, serious internal injury could result upon impact.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols notes that many booster seats come with their own
harnesses, which should be used to restrain the children until they
are big enough for shoulder-and-lap belts to be positioned
properly. Of course, the booster seat itself must be secured by a
lap belt in the rear of the car.
</P>
<P>
   The pediatric academy strongly advises against the use of add-on
devices (not those that are built into the vehicle) that try to
reposition the shoulder portion of the safety belt so that it fits
correctly on passengers who are short.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to get children always to use proper vehicle
restraints is for their parents to buckle up themselves and for
parents to insist that the children be properly restrained before
turning on the engine. And though many youngsters may clamor to sit
in the front, the academy insists that the back seat is ``the
safest place for children of any age to ride.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
