r l BC-LENT-CONFESSION-TEX     03-06 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LENT-CONFESSION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARDI GRAS ALSO A DAY FOR CONFESSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAIME JORDAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Episcopalian priests have a slogan when it
comes to confessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``All can, some should, none must,'' said Father Mark Cannaday,
rector at St. Alban's Episcopal Church in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Next week marks the beginning of a season of confession for many
faithful. Lent begins on Ash Wednesday and continues until Easter,
on April 23. Christians observe this time with fasting, abstaining
from various foods or activities, and confession.
</P>
<P>
   Mardi Gras, or Fat Tuesday, marks the day before Lent. Although
now associated with revelry and bawdy high jinks, this has not
always been the case. The archaic name for Mardi Gras, Shrovetide
or Shrove Tuesday, reflects a more spiritual focus. ``Shrive'' is a
verb meaning to hear a confession and grant absolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Catholics, this is an experience of emptying out our sins
so we can be filled with grace,'' said Father Jim Gigliotti of St.
Maria Goretti Catholic Church in Arlington. ``For the Catholic,
that opens up the door that is called the faith formation.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Episcopalians, for whom confession is a sacrament of the
church but not a requirement, the catechism states that Roman
Catholics must go to confession at least once a year. According to
the Second Vatican Council, a person should not miss more than
three months and preferably should go at least monthly, Gigliotti
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, guilt drives people to confession, Cannaday said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, it's a secret that people can't share anywhere
else,'' Cannaday said. ``They can't tell it to their wife or
husband or children or best friend. Or maybe they've told it to
someone and they say, `Why don't you go make a confession?' Their
ashamedness brings them into confession. Sometimes they're in the
midst of their sin, trying to find a way out.''
</P>
<P>
   Churches conduct confessions in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   Father Tom Hightower of St. Peter and St. Paul Episcopal Church
in Arlington does his by appointment. He takes the parishioner into
the church, locks the door and has the person kneel before the
altar. Hightower sits on a chair with his back to the confessor so
they're not face-to-face.
</P>
<P>
   Other churches have confessional booths, often portrayed in
movies, in which a priest sits in one compartment and the confessor
in another, with a divider in between to allow for anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cannaday admits he sometimes recognizes voices in the
booth, it's easier to put a person's identity out of his mind when
he doesn't see a face.
</P>
<P>
   The priest's job in that booth is tougher than one might think,
Gigliotti said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they just take my breath away,'' Gigliotti said.
``Believe me, they do tell you what is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   But hearing the gory details isn't always the toughest part.
Sometimes the most difficult part of the job is convincing a person
that his or her horrendous sin is forgivable, and reminding people
of the compassionate and merciful God, Gigliotti said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to fight the God of the imagination and you have to
give them the God of the Scriptures, and you only have so many
minutes to do this because there's a line out there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In many Episcopalian churches, confession is built into the
services.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Henderson, a Fort Worth lawyer and Episcopalian who
divides his time between San Juan Apostle and Trinity Episcopal in
Fort Worth, said that confession with a priest has never been part
of his routine.
</P>
<P>
   However, he has come to welcome the general confession built
into the worship service. Members repeat general phrases of
forgiveness ``then everybody crosses themselves and they feel a lot
better afterward,'' he said. ``I will say (that) when we have the
service where they skip the confession, it is almost as though
something is missing when we go up for Communion.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're performing it right, relief is exactly what one should
feel after confession, Hightower said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my experience that if someone comes to confession, they
walk away relieved,'' he said. ``What I basically teach about
confession is that we are all sinners, so we all need to confess,
either directly to God or in the presence of a priest.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Albrecht, director of the Pastoral Counseling and
Information Center in Dallas, said many of the modern-day
counseling principles have roots in the Catholic tradition of
confession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it really interesting as you read history at the
decline of the Catholic Church in Europe and the rise of Freudian
psychotherapy,'' he said. ``I think there is a parallel between
confession and psychotherapy. Therapy has been the modern role of
what used to be the confessional booth. I really do believe that
where the confessional rite is properly used, it's very, very
helpful to people.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
