<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8457 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-COLON-CANCER07-COX     03-06 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLON-CANCER07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COURIC URGES LAWMAKERS TO HELP PROMOTE COLON CANCER SCREENING
 &HT;    By ANGEL WILSON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Katie Couric, co-host of NBC's ``Today'' show, told
a Senate committee Monday that the entertainment industry is
mobilizing to raise national awareness of colon cancer, and urged
lawmakers to help.
</P>
<P>
   Couric, whose husband, Jay Monahan, was diagnosed with colon
cancer in 1997 and died nine months later at age 42, has become the
main spokesperson for the National Colon Cancer Research Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance was formed a week ago by Couric; Lilly Tartikoff,
widow of former NBC entertainment chief Brandon Tartikoff, who died
of lymphatic cancer at age 48, and the Entertainment Industry
Foundation. The goal of the NCCRA is to provide research and raise
public awareness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have put together public service announcements from Dennis
Franz of 'NYPD Blue,' Judge Judy, baseball player Eric Davis and
Sean Ferrer, Audrey Hepburn's son,'' Couric told the Senate Special
Committee on Aging. ``Those ads have already begun airing on
television stations nationwide.''
</P>
<P>
   Hepburn also died of colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   To demonstrate the importance of early colon cancer screening,
Couric said she would show her own screening Tuesday morning on the
``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   The more people learn there is nothing embarrassing about
screening tests such as sigmoidoscopies and colonoscopies, Couric
said, the more likely they are to take them.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that Medicare, along with many HMOs, provide for these
screenings, and said such simple measures could save lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every person screened is a potential life saved,'' Couric
said. ``Nobody needs to die of embarrassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Other witnesses, including colon cancer victim Shirley Heiligman
of New York City, and Dr. Bernard Levin of the University of Texas
Anderson Cancer Center, urged Congress to provide more money for
the battle against colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad irony is that cancer of the colon is probably the most
treatable and survivable of all cancers, if it is detected early
through proper screenings,'' Levin told committee members. ``We
must find ways to heighten public awareness about this disease and
to remove any barriers that may exist for the access to regular
screening procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   Colon cancer is currently the second leading cancer killer,
surpassed only by lung cancer. About 130,000 people are diagnosed
with colon cancer annually, and 56,000 of them die. While colon
cancer is usually associated with older white males, women are
diagnosed at a slightly higher rate than men. Blacks are at an even
higher risk, and around 13,000 people under the age of 50 are
diagnosed every year.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Center for Disease Control, 60 percent of
people who should be screened never have been. When detected
through early screening, the survival rate is over 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Angel Wilson's e-mail address is angelw(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
