<HEADER>
A8461 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-CHAUCER-NYT &LR;      03-06 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CHAUCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CHAUCER TALE, A CLUE TO AN ASTRONOMIC REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By JAMES GLANZ    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the sweet showers of April soon to arrive, piercing the
drought of March as birds make melody, scientists are longing to
make pilgrimages into the works of Geoffrey Chaucer, who wrote on
technical subjects as well as penning ``The Canterbury Tales.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Chaucer, a courtier, diplomat and customs official who
was born around 1340, wrote a treatise on the astrolabe, an
instrument used for navigating by the stars, the passages that have
caught the attention of scientists are in ``The Canterbury Tales.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, a physics professor at Southwest Texas State
University in San Marcos, has suggested that a squire's success in
``removing all the rocks from the coast of Brittany'' at the behest
of his beloved Dorigen in ``The Franklin's Tale'' is more than the
product of Chaucer's imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Though the tide rises and falls on the coast, it has never in
memory been ``so great that by at least five fathoms it oversprings
the highest rock in Brittany,'' an occurrence that the squire,
Aurelius, asks a magician to bring about.
</P>
<P>
   The professor, Dr. Donald W. Olson, has calculated that one of
the most uncommon of astronomical alignments, favoring extremely
high tides, actually occurred around Chaucer's year of birth and
could have covered the rocks.
</P>
<P>
   In an article in the April issue of Sky &AMP; Telescope, Olson and
two colleagues at Southwest Texas State _ Dr. Edgar S. Laird, an
English professor, and Thomas E. Lytle, a physics graduate student
_ argue that several clues in the tale show that Chaucer was
probably referring to an event that took place on Dec. 19, 1340.
</P>
<P>
   ``A very rare celestial alignment occurred in the 14th
century,'' Olson said. ``We think he's actually describing a real
event in `The Franklin's Tale.'''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Sigmund Eisner, an emeritus professor of English at the
University of Arizona, said that the conjecture was plausible.
``Every year or two I find some other spot in the works of Chaucer
where he uses his knowledge of astronomy,'' Eisner said. ``Don
Olson's article confirms one more.''
</P>
<P>
   Tides are caused by the gravitational pull of the Moon and the
Sun. The highest tides occur at new and full moon, when the Earth,
Moon and Sun are approximately aligned. But several effects can
cause even higher tides. When the Moon is at perigee, its closest
approach to Earth, the gravitational pull is greater and the tides
are higher. Similarly, Earth's being at perihelion in its orbit
around the Sun enhances tides.
</P>
<P>
   Another circumstance that can affect tides is an alignment of
the Sun, Moon and Earth that is more perfect than usual, and which
leads to a solar or lunar eclipse. But these factors, Earth and
Moon at perigee during an eclipse, happen at most once or twice a
century, and sometimes more than a thousand years can pass without
such a coincidence. But one took place on that day in late December
1340.
</P>
<P>
   The astronomical considerations are significant, since in the
tale, the clerk whom Aurelius pays to work ``magic'' on the tides
actually does some heavy celestial calculations to predict when the
highest of high tides will occur. ``Ful subtilly he kalkuled all
this,'' Chaucer wrote, referring to the subtle calculations, while
giving details on the astronomical tables, equations and celestial
positions that were called for.
</P>
<P>
   Among those details was that the Sun had entered Capricorn,
which occurred around Dec. 13 in Chaucer's day, Olson said. There
was also a reference to Christmas, further fixing the month, and
indications that the clerk was actually computing some of the
special alignments that would be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the high tide appears in the tale, and the characters
display nobility in extricating themselves from an uncomfortable
situation that astronomical forces have made possible. Dorigen
confesses her rash promise to her husband, a knight who travels a
lot; Aurelius releases her from the deal; and the clerk waives his
hefty fee.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the weakest link in Olson's reasoning is the supposition
that Chaucer knew about the rare event, since it occurred around
the year of his birth. But he argues that someone with Chaucer's
obsession with astronomy would have calculated his horoscope,
revealing the special conditions then. And as controller of the
customs office and a member of various royal committees, Chaucer
oversaw repair and construction of wharves, walls and ditches along
the Thames, making it likely that he would have familiarized
himself with the local history of the tides.
</P>
<P>
   Olson said he became interested in such arcane literary problems
through people he met at academic gatherings he attended with his
wife, Dr. Marilynn Olson, who is a professor of English at
Southwest Texas State. Aside from the light his study has thrown on
Chaucer's thinking, he said that his motivation was simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a lowly physicist; I don't do literary references very
well,'' he said, adding that the project ``gives me an excuse to
read the Tales in great detail.''
</P>
</TEXT>
