<HEADER>
A8464 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-DAVIDCROSBY-TEX     03-06 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIDCROSBY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE IS GOOD FOR A GROWN-UP DAVID CROSBY AND FRIENDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ask a simple question, get a simple answer: When David Crosby is
questioned about the difference between the Crosby, Stills, Nash &AMP;
Young of old and the CSNY of now, he doesn't even hesitate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all had to grow up some, and we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is both a funny thing to hear from a 58-year-old man in a
band where the youngest member (Neil Young) is 54 _ and extremely
telling.
</P>
<P>
   Crosby, Stills, Nash &AMP; Young were the biggest band in the world
for the few years they were together in the '70s, a
supergroup/summit meeting of four musicians who had already made
their bones as rock stars and knew they would be successful the
minute they opened their mouths to sing.
</P>
<P>
   Graham Nash had been in the Hollies. Crosby had been a Byrd.
Stills and Young had been in Buffalo Springfield, and Young had
already released his landmark ``Everybody Knows This Is Nowhere''
LP. And, of course, Crosby, Stills and Nash had already released an
eponymous record that included soft-rock staples such as ``Suite:
Judy Blue Eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, the battles between the four were
legendary. Outsize egos, tons of money and a desire among all four
to do solo recordings _ all split up CSNY after precisely one
studio LP, ``Deja Vu,'' and a self-indulgent double-live set,
``Four-Way Street.''
</P>
<P>
   CSNY burned hot and flamed out quickly, and though CSN regrouped
several times (and joined with Young for 1988's ``American Dream''
after Crosby kicked a long dependency on crack cocaine) a
full-fledged CD-and-tour CSNY reunion looked highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   But it happened, says Crosby, largely because all four are now
old and wise enough to appreciate each other. Released last Oct.
26, ``Looking Forward'' includes two Crosby songs, four by Young
(which, no surprise here, are the strongest), two by Nash, three by
Stills _ and one, the closing ``Sanibel,'' by Nash's friend Denny
Sarokin.
</P>
<P>
   Crosby's two songs, ``Stand and Be Counted'' and ``Dream for
Him,'' are all about making a difference and trying to make the
world a better place.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the same things that I've always said,'' he says.
``That love is the most important thing. No question. We're saying
family is a deep running thread in all of us now. But some of the
things that moved us then moved us now _ having the courage to
stand on your convictions, loyalty, love _ are the same things I've
always been about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking Forward'' began with songs Young was writing for
himself, and soon evolved into all four singing together at the
microphone, just like 'way back when.
</P>
<P>
   ``We built the record together,'' says Crosby. ``It was a very
organic process. We had a blast in the studio. We laughed our way
through the whole thing. Frankly, I think it was such a good
experience we'll do it again. There was a lot of give-and-take, a
lot of honesty, a lot of respect, and a lot of hilarity.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there was not a lot of interest elsewhere.
Despite significant promotion by Reprise Records tying the CD into
the group's first tour in 25 years, ``Looking Forward'' was gored
by critics (including me) and quickly slunk off the charts.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the current hoopla surrounding the band's pricey U.S.
arena tour (more on this later), ``Looking Forward'' is not even in
the ``Billboard'' Top 200 album chart, and hasn't been for weeks.
Crosby's opinion that the CD would rebound _ he did this interview
more than a month ago _ has not proved to be true.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the biggest buzz surrounding CSNY doesn't have
anything to do with the CD or the tour _ rather, it's Crosby's
sperm that's been making headlines.
</P>
<P>
   A recent ``Rolling Stone'' cover story revealed that the Cros is
the biological father of two boys being raised by Melissa Etheridge
and Julie Cypher.
</P>
<P>
   This revelation seems especially poignant because back in 1996,
just before he received a new liver, Crosby was reunited with a
son, James Raymond, whom he had never known about. The two play
together in CPR, a band that also includes Jeff Pevar. Crosby also
has a 4-year-old son, Django.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are Melissa and Julie's children,'' he says. ``That's
their family and their job to raise them and they're doing an
excellent job. I feel immensely blessed to have James in my life _
I'm greatly blessed with children.''
</P>
<P>
   He also says he has been pleasantly surprised by the public's
reaction to the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, I've been amazed at how positive it's been,'' he
says. ``I thought all the Neanderthals on the right would have
raised a flag of protest. But when I was on ``Larry King,'' all the
calls were positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to the prices for CSNY tickets has been a different
story. Even in an era of wildly escalating prices, the top ticket
price ($201) seemed a little _ or, perhaps, a lot _ ridiculous,
especially given the paucity of good new material on ``Looking
Forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after months of carping (much of it, again, from the press)
Crosby still defends the ticket prices. He notes, first of all,
that this is a one-time-only event _ the four, he says, will
``never'' tour again. Second, the show is more than three hours
long, and fans on various band Web sites have been raving.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are just focusing on the most expensive tickets,'' he
notes. ``There are a lot more $30 tickets. I've been on the Net a
lot and the universal answer was, `I went and it was money well
spent.' People who walked out of the shows will never forget them.
That's what I'm hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he's asked, don't the high prices mean that a lot of
working-class people won't be able to go?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a valid argument,'' he says. ``All they have to do
is buy a less-expensive ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   And so far, they have: Of the 10 shows reported so far in
``Billboard'' magazine, seven have sold out, each with a gross of
more than $1 million per night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about it,'' says Crosby; one can almost see
him smile through his big walrus mustache. ``I'm not worried about
a damn thing.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
