<HEADER>
A8466 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-CIRCUS-CLASSES-AR     03-06 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CIRCUS-CLASSES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DARING TO BE A DAREDEVIL, IN CIRCUS CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By ALISON HENDRIE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I never dreamed of running off to join the circus. A
childhood trip to the Big Top was thrilling but when the spotlight
hit the daring young men and women on the flying trapeze, I hardly
imagined myself hurtling through space in a sequined skirt. I like
my feet firmly planted on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   How, then, do I manage to be among the first in line when the
circus class comes to town? Certainly, boredom with the same old
step aerobics and stair-climber is a compelling motive. Mostly,
though, I wanted to impress my kids with some cool moves. And over
the last few months, sports clubs, ever seeking newer and more
unusual offerings, have begun to offer classes in circus skills.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Saturday, visions of high wires and elephants
dancing in my head, I arrived at Crunch Fitness here and shed my
shoes to the irresistible sounds of calliope circus music. Like
most of my classmates, I am no performer but consider myself fit.
The next hour, however, is as much about mental strength as
muscles. Fear is a palpable part of acrobatics as the nervous
laughter among the group attests. We are here not only to build
strength and flexibility, we are told, but to face our fears and
learn to trust our bodies and our acrobatic partners not to let us
down _ literally.
</P>
<P>
   Short, sturdy or slight, there is a place for everyone in circus
sports, an instructor assures us. All shapes and sizes are needed
for tumbling, flying, juggling or simply holding up the human
pyramid. The only requirement is confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Following the requisite warm-up, we head right into the very
backbone of circus acrobatics: the handstand. It's not easy.
Putting our weight on our hands, we slowly walk our feet up the
wall until we are upside down, holding for 30 seconds, which, from
this angle, is a very long time. I'm thankful when we move on to
backbends. Pushing off from the wrist through the forearm and up to
the shoulders, a row of arched backs grudgingly raises along the
floor to a chorus of grunts. This move, an instructor confides,
takes many months to master.
</P>
<P>
   Because so much of circus acrobatics is done upside down, we are
told that our arms must become like legs. The wrists take the brunt
of the workout initially, but the entire upper body musculature is
at work, controlling each movement and distributing the weight
evenly. Eventually, the acrobat learns to shift the center of
gravity through the torso, lightening the load on the hands until
they can carry the bulk like feet.
</P>
<P>
   Acrobats use these basics to create what an instructor, Tanya
Gagne, calls a ``dance-movement vocabulary with acrobatics.''
Pairing off, we begin a bizarre pas de deux as one partner lifts
the other into the air using only leg strength and balance. The
goal is to rest atop your partner's feet, arms spread-eagle and
toes pointed. From this, we contort into the shoulder stand,
placing our weight and our trust into the hands of the partner
below. I'm doubtful and scared, but with a rush of adrenaline I am
airborne, upside down and held only by my shoulders and perhaps a
spotter's hand. But I have done it, and upon landing, we high-five
each other, with bravado, disbelief and pride.
</P>
<P>
   The trapeze, quintessential circus prop, poses a greater
challenge. The simple act of hoisting one's own body weight is
surprisingly difficult and my hands slip as I grip the thin metal
bar. With help, I finally hang by my knees and even perform a
reverse arch before collapsing from fatigue and sore palms. As we
await another turn and respectfully watch a classmate flawlessly
execute the more aerial feats, we juggle. Or try. The comic relief
eases the strain and draws us closer, like a real circus family.
</P>
<P>
   Which is the point. Circus acrobatics is a confrontational,
in-your-face art form in which the physical closeness and
dependence not only create, but demand a bond. Already, I feel
closer to my 19-year-old partner, an NYU student. A giant,
12-person pyramid is our grand finale and we leave with confident
smiles, no longer the audience, but the center ring.
</P>
<P>
   And while I probably will not be doing back flips at my
daughter's next birthday party, I may just entertain the troops
with a little juggling.
</P>
<P>
   Not, however, upside down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
