<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8468 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-PLASTINATING-BODI     03-06 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PLASTINATING-BODIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW STUDENT AID: PLASTIC BODY PARTS, MADE FROM THE REAL THINGS
</HEADLINE>
  
(Attn: Germany, Mich.) (The Science Times)  
(DW) 
 By MARY ROACH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANN ARBOR, Mich. _ When a person dies in Detroit and no one
claims the body, an interesting thing may happen to it. The cadaver
may wind up being donated to the University of Michigan Medical
School's plastination laboratory and turned into an eternity-ready
version of itself.
</P>
<P>
   Plastination is the process of taking organic tissue _ a
rosebud, say, or a human head _ and replacing the water in it with
a liquid silicone polymer. The polymer hardens after the
application of a catalyst, permanently preserving the deceased
entity.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, plastination has been carried out on a relatively
small scale on cadaver parts and organs, which are then sold to
universities and medical schools for use in anatomy classes. But
last month, for the first time in North America, an entire human
body was plastinated.
</P>
<P>
   The project took place at the plastination laboratory at the
University of Michigan, opened in 1989 and run by Dr. Roy Glover,
an associate professor of anatomy.
</P>
<P>
   Plastination was invented in 1981 by Dr. Gunter von Hagens, a
German chemist. When his patent expired, Dow Corning modified the
process, making it cheaper and faster.
</P>
<P>
   Glover said he could plastinate a human heart in 24 hours, but a
week is needed with the von Hagens' method. Von Hagens plastinates
in sub-freezing conditions to keep the catalyst from hardening
prematurely; Dow Corning figured out a way to add the catalyst
after the body is impregnated with the polymer, so the entire
process can be done at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   As teaching aids, plastinated organs offer advantages over
models and organs preserved in formaldehyde, the traditional
method.
</P>
<P>
   Formaldehyde is unpleasant and toxic _ so much so that federal
authorities regulate its use in laboratories _ and organs
deteriorate quickly when taken out of the liquid. Plastinated
organs are nontoxic, durable, dry to the touch, and have no smell.
They can be written on and, if the client wishes, custom-dissected
to highlight specific structures.
</P>
<P>
   For the communication disorders program at Calvin College in
Grand Rapids, Mich., Glover created a plastinated bisected head and
neck, which affords a cutaway view of the human vocal apparatus.
While plastic models of this structure exist, they often distort
sizes and positions of parts for the sake of clarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students are amazed to see the real thing,'' said Dr. Judith
Vander Woude, an assistant professor at the college. ``It's been
absolutely wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Michigan Medical School, plastinated organs
are being used in tandem with ``virtual anatomy'' computer
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can actually hold the specimen in your hand and study the
computer program at the same time,'' Glover said. ``It's a powerful
learning tool.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their advantages, whole plastinated cadavers are
unlikely to replace whole embalmed cadavers in medical school gross
anatomy labs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plastinated parts are useful in gross anatomy for
demonstrating specifics,'' said Dr. Arlen Severson, head of the
department of anatomy and cell biology at the University of
Minnesota Duluth School of Medicine. ``But the plastic makes the
body too stiff.'' This makes it impossible for medical students to
do dissections.
</P>
<P>
   Also standing in the way is the cost of large-scale plastination
_ Glover's lab charges $13,000 to process a whole corpse _ and the
shortage of facilities and qualified plastinators. Worldwide, there
are 50 to 80.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, all the people that can do it are teaching
professors,'' said Dan Corcoran, president of Corcoran
Laboratories, a Bay City, Mich., company that supplies plastination
chemicals and equipment. ``They don't have time.''
</P>
<P>
   Corcoran estimated that of the 157,000 medical schools in the
world, perhaps 100 to 200 are using plastinated body parts.
</P>
<P>
   The intact corpses in Glover's lab today are not destined for
medical schools. They will become the main attraction at a
traveling anatomical museum, being developed by Glover and
Corcoran, with help from Dow Corning. Beginning this summer, the
exhibit will be available to tour natural history museums and
universities across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Glover showed a visitor the fourth whole human body
his lab plastinated as the process was under way. It was on its
back in a stainless steel tank of acetone, which filled the lab
with a powerful smell of nail-polish remover each time Glover
lifted the lid. The acetone drives water from the body's tissue,
readying it for impregnation with the silicone polymer. The man in
the acetone was in his 60s when he died. He had a mustache and a
tattoo, both of which will survive the plastination process. (Skin
plastinates as well as any other organ.)
</P>
<P>
   Each of the museum's bodies will be used to highlight a
different biological system or set of systems: digestive, nervous,
cardiovascular-respiratory, reproductive and musculoskeletal.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies will look pretty much as they did on the day of
death, with minor cosmetic enhancements. Muscle and skin
discolorations may be touched up with dye, and veins injected with
a colored version of the polymer. On some of the bodies, Glover
plans to remove the chest wall and reattach it with a hinge, so it
will swing open like a refrigerator door, revealing the organs
within. Both male and female corpses are being prepared, and no
changes will be made in the name of modesty. From the acetone bath,
bodies are transferred to the whole-body plastination chamber, a
cylindrical stainless steel tank filled with liquid polymer. A
vacuum attached to the tank lowers the internal pressure, turning
the acetone to a gas and drawing it from the body. As the acetone
is drawn out of the tissue, the silicone polymer is drawn in to
take its place.
</P>
<P>
   Glover handed his visitor a flashlight to see the view through a
porthole on the top of the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   When the acetone gas stops bubbling _ usually after about two
weeks _ the body is removed from the chamber. All that remains is
to pose the body, set the polymer with the catalyst, and mount the
finished specimen on a display stand. Glover uses a plant mister to
apply the catalyst, which starts a chain reaction that works its
way through the entire body, hardening it to a firm but sliceable
consistency.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies being plastinated for the anatomical museum are
unclaimed dead, people with no known next of kin. Glover did not
use bodies of people who had elected to donate their remains to
science because the families often wanted the deceased's ashes
(which come primarily from bone), and in this case he would be
unable to oblige.
</P>
<P>
   Donated bodies are, however, used for plastinating organs and
body parts. Potential donors are given a form allowing them to
authorize or forbid the university's various scientific uses of
human remains, including plastination. (The checklist uses the term
``permanent preservation.'')
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The commercial potential of plastination could be sizable. It
could be used in lieu of taxidermy for natural history museum
specimens.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   If care is taken to wipe down the fur with acetone after
plastination, it remains soft and pliable. It also stays in place
longer than on taxidermy specimens, because the plastination
process locks it into the epidermis. The only thing standing in the
way of commercial plastination of museum specimens is, again, lack
of facilities and people to perform the procedure. ``We could
probably do an elephant or a whale if we had a big enough tank,''
Corcoran said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Corcoran suspects that one day soon, some enterprising mortuary
scientist will build a factory-scale plastination facility for
human bodies.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   (Think what plastination could have done for Lenin.) The way
Corcoran sees it, the demand is already there.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a gentleman who does mummification somewhere,'' he
said. ``He does one a week, at $60,000 a body. And he's got a
backlog. There's enough eccentric people in the world that someone
would do quite well with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Possibly, it could be Corcoran himself. ``If the museum doesn't
take off, maybe I'll build some tanks and do that.'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Glover isn't interested in the noneducational aspects of
plastination. He politely refused a request from a woman who wanted
her dead Yorkshire terrier plastinated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do those kinds of personal things,'' he said. He
makes exceptions for science students, though. On the white board
in his office is a note to himself: ``Maria Lopez _ brain for
daughter _ science fair.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
