<HEADER>
A8473 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-FIRES-COMPUTERS-A     03-06 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FIRES-COMPUTERS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COMPUTER TO OUTSMART A RAGING FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Md.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent as NYT3 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.)  
 (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By MARK DERR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fire began when a cigarette ignited the couch. Within
minutes flames leaped to the drapes and the fire raged until,
deprived by closed windows and doors of the oxygen needed to
flourish, it subsided.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the smoldering fire continued to raise the temperature in
the room, bringing furniture, papers and candles close to their
ignition points. Arriving some time later, firefighters burst
through the door, and oxygen-rich air poured in with them.
</P>
<P>
   The room appeared to erupt into flames _ a phenomenon called
``flashover'' _ as the smoldering fire revived and, in rapid
succession, papers, candles and other furnishings ignited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you have flashover, you generally lose the structure and
lives,'' said Dr. Kevin McGrattan, a mathematician with the
Building and Fire Research Laboratory at the National Institute of
Standards and Technology in Gaithersburg, Md.
</P>
<P>
   This fire was hypothetical, created on a computer program that
McGrattan and his colleagues, Dr. Ronald Rehm and Dr. Howard Baum,
designed to simulate the behavior of fire in a building in precise
three-dimensional detail, and to evaluate systems for detecting and
extinguishing the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Fire Dynamic Simulator, the program is to be posted
soon for distribution on the Web site of National Institute of
Standards and Technology (fire.nist.gov). The program is the most
sophisticated and powerful of its kind, said Dr. Richard G. Gann,
senior research scientist at the lab.
</P>
<P>
   As part of continuing official investigations, researchers at
the laboratory have already used the computer model to reconstruct
fatal fires that occurred in Washington and Brooklyn in 1998. The
researchers have also used the program to predict the performance
of ceiling sprinklers in fires and to explain why a sprinkler next
to one already active fails to open in proper sequence, a
phenomenon known as sprinkler skip.
</P>
<P>
   Structural fires cost the American economy about $128 billion
annually in property damage, maintaining fire departments and
insurance. On average each year, 4,000 civilians die and 40,000 are
injured in fires, primarily in their homes; among firefighters, 80
to 90 die and 80,000 to 90,000 are injured. Nearly 75 percent of
fire fatalities occur in flashovers, Gann said.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, fire codes and designs aimed at preventing such
losses were based on the accumulated wisdom of firefighters, basic
mathematical calculations and laboratory tests of materials, Gann
said. But in the 1980s, researchers at the laboratory began
developing a computer program that would model the behavior of fire
in an enclosed space, using data on the type, amount and ignition
temperatures of whatever flammable materials were present. The
model drew on abundant data from tests of ignition temperatures and
burning times of new materials.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with another model anticipating the behavior of people
in the presence of fire, this so-called ``zone'' model gave
specialists a powerful tool for determining the layout of
evacuation routes, as well as the placement and timing of fire
alarms and sprinklers in buildings, railroad cars and planes.
</P>
<P>
   First released for use on a desktop computer in 1983, it is also
widely used by fire investigators, said Richard W. Bukowski, a
senior engineer at the fire research laboratory, who helped create
the ``zone'' model.
</P>
<P>
   But the model provides only a one-dimensional view of a room,
showing the vertical distribution of hot and cooler air, not its
horizontal movements. Unable to model the flow of air, it cannot
anticipate the behavior of fire in more complicated spaces, like
rooms with exposed beams or odd shapes. Although it can make rough
calculations about the changing intensity and size of the fire over
time, the program cannot determine its location in a room.
</P>
<P>
   The Fire Dynamic Simulator solves those problems by dividing a
room into cubes six inches on each side, McGrattan said. Using the
staggeringly complex equations of computational fluid dynamics, it
then maps in three dimensions the fire and the flow of heated air
through the room.
</P>
<P>
   Heat causes materials, like wood, candle wax or fabrics, to
release gases, which then fuel the fire in the presence of oxygen.
(Thus, water puts out a fire by cooling, not drowning, it, while
depriving a fire of oxygen smothers it.) The dynamic model takes
days to run through its calculations, making it less user friendly,
if more precise, than its predecessor _ but it has already proved
its worth.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, McGrattan ran the program before the test burning of
an actual building at the Underwriters Laboratory. The experiment
was designed to examine the workings of roof vents, sprinklers and
draft curtains, which hang from the ceiling of large buildings,
like warehouses, and are designed to funnel smoke from a fire
inside the building toward the vents.
</P>
<P>
   The computer model predicted that the draft curtains and, to a
lesser degree the roof vents, would actually interfere with the
working of sprinklers by delaying their opening and by blocking the
full distribution of water from them. Draft curtains and roof vents
are frequently required in existing fire codes, which are developed
locally, and sometimes by insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   But a model unified national fire code now under development for
large buildings would drop the demand for draft curtains, McGrattan
said.
</P>
<P>
   The model has also explained a number of flukes in the behavior
of fire alarms and sprinklers. For example, in fire tests in a
basement with exposed ceiling beams, the sprinkler farthest from
the fire consistently ignited before those directly over the
flames.
</P>
<P>
   A computer simulation revealed that the beams were acting as a
conduit and were channeling heat from the fire to the distant
sprinkler so fast that the sensor on the nearest sprinkler never
became warm enough to activate it.
</P>
<P>
   The model showed that in sprinkler skip, water from one
sprinkler cools the heat sensor on its neighbor so that the second
sprinkler is not activated, thus increasing the possibility that
the fire will spread. Adjusting the sensitivity or placement of the
sprinklers solves the problem.
</P>
<P>
   A similar computer model developed in the late 1990s
demonstrated that under specific sea and wind conditions, burning
the oil spilled from a tanker caused less environmental damage,
despite the smoke and air pollution, than removing it after it has
washed ashore. Experiments confirmed the model, and since then
spilled oil has been burned at sea off Alaska in 1998 and after an
oil tanker, the New Carissa, foundered off Coos Bay, Ore., in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Simulations now play an equally crucial role in developing,
designing and testing new kinds of fire codes, based not on
requirements for number and placement of exits, sprinklers,
extinguishers and the like but rather on fire safety goals.
</P>
<P>
   These performance-based codes set specific goals for fire
safety, including the amount of time needed to warn and evacuate
the building's occupants, and the efficiency of the smoke detection
and sprinkler systems, but leave up to the design team the how to
meet those goals.
</P>
<P>
   Bukowski estimated that these codes, being developed in Japan,
Australia, New Zealand and parts of Europe, can cut the cost of
fire protection in a new building _ now set at 15 percent or 20
percent of the construction cost _ by a third, while improving
safety. The fire research laboratory is working on a model
performance-based code of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Fire Dynamic Simulator cannot yet predict when
flashover will occur because of the sheer complexity of calculating
the interactions of hot and cold air, radiant temperatures and the
ignition points of multiple materials over a long period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fire modeling is like predicting the weather,'' McGrattan
said. ``We're pretty good in the short term, but not in the longer
term. We can predict the first couple of minutes of a fire
successfully, but after that, things become more dicey.''
Nonetheless, he said he expected in the next five years to be able
to ``confidently predict for any given room what the flash point
will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the progress made in bringing their models to fire
engineers, the researchers admit that firefighters are reluctant to
embrace the technology, preferring in most cases to rely on their
experience and traditional methods. Still McGrattan expects
computer simulations to be widely used in training, because they
can provide a clearer view of fire than video cameras or eyes
blinded by smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at the Building and Fire Research Laboratory also
hope within four years to have built a control panel that has
embedded in it a ``zone'' model for tracking the progress of a fire
in a building in real time. Sensors monitoring temperature,
occupancy, smoke alarms, sprinklers, ventilation and other systems,
would relay information back to the program, which would also have
an inventory of material in the building.
</P>
<P>
   Constantly updating its data, the computer would determine the
location and intensity of a fire, as well as movement, and feed
that information directly to firefighters, in all likelihood saving
lives and reducing injuries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
