<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 `SMELLS AND BELLS' OF LENT CAN'T BE FOUND ON THE WEB
 (Commentary)   &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    A recent survey found that those who are online enjoy less human
contact than those who are not. Does this electronic trend toward
isolation threaten religious life that traditionally has been
centered on congregations?
 &HT;    Journalist Mary Alice Williams, on the PBS program ``Religion
and Ethics Newsweekly,'' recently observed that ``With tens of
thousands of religious Web sites and a home page for every
organized faith group and then some, people can get a dose of
religion without ever getting out of their jammies.
 &HT;    ``Some prophesy the Web will reduce us to a virtual community of
believers practicing a kind of `McFaith' _ fast, convenient, but
hardly nourishing.''
 &HT;    Web-McFaith stands in stark contrast to the upcoming church
season: Lent. Beginning with Ash Wednesday on March 8, Christians
will make their annual liturgical pilgrimage toward Good Friday and
Easter.
 &HT;    Every year, the spiritual practices of those 40 days impinge on
my hectic spring schedule _ they are neither fast nor convenient.
 &HT;    But they are nourishing. With varying degrees of success or
commitment over the last two decades, I have tried to take Lent
seriously. Most years I find Lenten spirituality difficult; some
years easy. But nearly every year, I have come to understand
myself, God, liturgy, scriptures, and my church community in
greater spiritual depth through Lent.
 &HT;    I know many Christians who eagerly await Lent. Some actually
converted or returned to faith as a result of Lenten observance.
Their faith stories are often quite similar: Lent introduced them
to ``real church,'' a serious, rigorous and intentional spiritual
community.
 &HT;    What observers have failed to notice is that as our society
speeds up (the Internet being only the latest technological
manifestation of such) religious faith and practice must slow down.
 &HT;    Admittedly, there are nearly 30,000 religion Web sites with
nearly 25 million regular visitors. I'm one. But where do I go for
``serious'' spirituality? Not to the Web. I go to church.
 &HT;    It seems almost deviant to say so, but traditional church
appears to be making a comeback among computer savvy baby-boomers
and Generation Xers. In contrast to the disembodied spirituality of
cyberspace, people seem eager for sensual religious experience _
kneeling, incense, bread and wine, fasting, communal prayer,
congregational singing. The more ``smells and bells'' the better.
Thus, the Internet actually creates a need for human connection to
the divine. The stuff of traditional religion _ from liturgies to
pie suppers _ cannot (yet) be experienced over the Web. It exists
only in musty old buildings whose wood is scented with decades of
candle smoke; through whose windows colored light plays across the
carpet.
 &HT;    Something mystical and mysterious happens inside those
buildings_ something beyond our greatest technological
achievements. Those old buildings are sacred space, places where
the human and divine have touched for generations.
 &HT;    And I mean really touched.
 &HT;    Last year, the Benedictine monks of St. John's Abbey in
Collegeville, Minn., unveiled the first page of a new hand-written
Bible they have commissioned. It is the first hand-written Bible to
be produced in the West since the introduction of the printing
press and will not be completed until 2004.
 &HT;    The St. John's Bible is not intended to glorify a fading past,
but rather it is meant to be a ``21st-century Bible for the 21st
century.'' The monks want to ``link human imagination and the human
hand with the word of God'' thus making the ``word of God live on a
page.''
 &HT;    The primary artist, English calligrapher Donald Jackson, says
the quill pen is ``part of yourself; made of the same stuff as
fingernail.'' Like all artists' tools, it is ``an extension of
one's own fingers.'' And in the touching of finger to page, the
word of God creates a ``visual harmonic'' which strikes a
``universal chord.''
 &HT;    Human touch _ whether a hand-written Bible, Bach played on the
organ, or bread baked for the Eucharist_ is the only real access we
have to the divine. Because spirituality is itself disembodied, it
needs human bodies to be known.
 &HT;    The Internet, itself disembodied, cannot ultimately serve this
purpose. It does not come through the touch of a keyboard. We human
beings need material stuff to know that which is Spirit; we need
one another to touch the Divine.
 &HT;    Like the St. John's Bible, like Lent, spirituality cannot be
fast. Wisdom, insight, knowing oneself and God, serving and caring
for one another, marriage, friendship, parenthoodall take time.
 &HT;    The Internet may be a clever tool to assist our quests, but it
is not the artist's tool, it is not the community found in the
fellowship hall, and it is not the joy found through the rigor of
lifelong Lenten discipline.
 &HT;    You do not need high-speed access to find it; you only need go
down the street.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.2000 Diana Butler Bass
