<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8483 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      03-06 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; NUTRITION: Prenatal Hunger Tied to Adult Diabetes &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Hunger in the womb may contribute to adult-onset diabetes,
according to a group of Chinese and British researchers
investigating the rise in insulin resistance that has been found to
accompany improving diets in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   In research published last monthin the Annals of Internal
Medicine, epidemiologists culled obstetrical records from the
Peking Union Medical College Hospital between 1948 and 1954, a
period of chronic deprivation in China. They were able to trace and
test 627 grown children of women whose records were available.
</P>
<P>
   What they found was a strong correlation between undernourished
mothers and children who as adults, if their diets improved,
developed insulin resistance syndrome, a condition that is usually
a precursor to diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fetal adaptations to undernutrition may permanently change
metabolism,'' the article said. That can be a problem, the
researchers speculated, when diets improve, as indicated by the
fact the children, unlike their mothers, were not stunted as
adults.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of difficulty in metabolizing fat and rising
caloric intake could play a significant role in the increasing
rates of diabetes in countries attaining prosperity, they said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PATTERNS: When Strokes Discriminate by Race &LR;
</P>
<P>
   More African-American men who suffer strokes die from them than
do their white counterparts. Researchers have long suspected that
the reason could simply be that their strokes are more severe. A
new study from nine Veterans Administration hospitals found that
the strokes blacks suffer are indeed worse, but not by enough to
explain the difference in death rates.
</P>
<P>
   The study, in the journal Stroke, examined the records of 984
patients (30 percent of whom were black, scoring their initial
symptoms on a scale on which lower numbers indicated greater
severity. The average score for the black patients was 7.96; for
whites, 8.32. Patients arrived at hospitals about the same time
after the strokes.
</P>
<P>
   The lead author, Dr. Ronnie D. Horner of Duke, said that while
the difference was significant, it was not enough to account for
the differing outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEHAVIOR: Of Sex, Smarts and the Teen-age Mind &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between intelligence and sex among teen-agers
is more complicated than it seems, according to a new study from
the University of North Carolina-Chapel Hill.
</P>
<P>
   A number of earlier studies had determined that adolescents who
measured higher on intelligence tests were less likely than their
peers to engage in sexual intercourse. That led some researchers to
speculate that their generally higher levels of aspiration led to
greater caution.
</P>
<P>
   But the Carolina study, published last week in the Journal of
Adolescent Health, included two findings that did not fit that
picture. (The study combined data from a national survey of 12,000
adolescents and a more detailed look at the behavior of 300 North
Carolina teen-agers). One was that among students older than 15,
those at the very low end of the test's scale were as likely as
those at the upper reaches to abstain. The other was that
intelligent students were not just avoiding intercourse: they were
less likely to be kissing, petting or even holding hands.
</P>
<P>
   The study's lead author, Dr. Carolyn Halpern of the university's
Department of Maternal and Child Health, wrote that the data
indicate that teen-agers at the opposite ends of the spectrum
probably had different reasons for making the same decision. Girls
of lower intelligence might be shielded from opportunities for sex
more vigilantly, for instance, she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Halpern suggested that the data showing that
smarter teen-agers are postponing holding hands and kissing cast
doubt on the idea that their sex lives are governed by fears of the
possible consequences of intercourse. That would imply a kind of
``extremely farsighted concern that is hard to take seriously,''
she said. Finding effective techniques to promote abstinence may
require more research into how teen-agers are actually making up
their minds.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADOLESCENCE: Unleashing the Power of a Screaming Doll &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Some research produces new ideas. And some research tries to
figure out whether those ideas actually work, like a study released
yesterday on an approach to discouraging teen-age pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   The new idea is the Baby Think It Over Doll, a 7-pound surrogate
that bursts out wailing at intervals ranging from 15 minutes to 4
hours, 24 hours a day, and can be quieted only by a key attached to
the user's wrist. The hope is that a few days of this more onerous
version of Tamagotchi, combined with sex education, will
deromanticize young dreams of maternal bliss.
</P>
<P>
   But when Judith Krawlewski, a nurse, and Dr. Catherine
Stevens-Simon, a pediatrician at the University Health Sciences
Center in Colorado, signed up sixth- and eighth-grade girls from a
neighborhood with a high teen-age pregnancy rate to spend three
days and two nights with the dolls, the findings were
disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   In an article in the journal Pediatrics, they reported that the
experience did not change the intentions of those girls who hoped
to become mothers before the age of 20; in fact, it swayed 3 of the
109 girls in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   The doll did expose unrealistic thinking on the part of those
girls: they were the ones who found taking care of it harder than
they expected. But they were also more likely to think that their
child would somehow be easier.
</P>
<P>
   Given the propensity of adolescents to believe that nothing bad
can happen to them, the authors wrote, ``Pregnancy prevention
programs that only try to discourage parenthood are apt to be
ineffective.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Lambert, a spokeswoman for Baby Think It Over Inc. of Eau
Claire, Wis., called the study an unfair because researchers did
not follow the curriculum that accompanies the ``baby simulators.''
``It's an entire program, not just the baby,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HAZARDS: An Illness Strikes at Big Tobacco Farms &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The shift from small family-owned tobacco farms to larger
operations dependent on migrant labor is causing an increase in
green tobacco sickness, a form of nicotine poison caused by contact
with wet plants, according to a study in last month's issue of the
American Journal of Industrial Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   In the article, Dr. Sara A. Quandt, an epidemiologist at Wake
Forest University School of Medicine, said that 41 percent of the
farm workers she surveyed _ most migrant Mexican workers _ reported
having green tobacco sickness at least once a summer. The disease
is characterized by headaches, nausea, vomiting and dizziness.
</P>
<P>
   Only 9 percent of the workers sought medical care, she said,
because they feared losing their jobs if they missed a day in the
field or worked too slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Quandt said the principal cause of the increase appeared to be
greater exposure levels for migrant workers than for the family
members or hired hands who used to tend smaller amounts of crops on
smaller farms. Another factor is a shift toward planting rows of
tobacco plants more closely together to increase yield.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
