<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8486 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     03-06 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRY POTTER'S MAGIC BEWITCHES CHILDHOOD'S IMAGINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.2000 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the past year, J.K. Rowling's series of Harry Potter books
has topped the New York Times best seller list _ 18.5 million
copies in print in America. The books have been published in 29
countries; and in the United States, the books have been challenged
or banned in at least 26 schools, so far.
</P>
<P>
   Children across America have turned off their TV sets and turned
the pages of ``Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone,'' ``Harry
Potter and the Chamber of Secrets'' and ``Harry Potter and the
Prisoner of Azkaban.'' And as they wait impatiently for the
promised fourth book in the series, they turn to other children's
fantasy literature _ C.S. Lewis's ``Chronicles of Narnia'' and
Lloyd Alexander's ``Chronicles of Prydain.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Eager's ``Half Magic,'' Madeleine L'Engle's ``Wrinkle in
Time'' and J.R.R. Tolkein's classic trilogy, ``Lord of the Rings,''
are also enjoying a resurgence of sales. Children are reading again
_ with a passion.
</P>
<P>
   They have spread the word about the fledgling wizard Harry
Potter.
</P>
<P>
   So why are members of the religious right, the organization
called Family Friendly Libraries and other conservative groups
pushing to have the books removed from school reading lists and
school libraries?
</P>
<P>
   In one word, ``magic.'' Their protests against the Harry Potter
books are sparked by their objections to sorcery, the magic arts,
wizards, warlocks and witches. They don't like 11-year-old Potter
using magic to solve his problems. They have forgotten what it is
like to be a child.
</P>
<P>
   All children believe in magic. It's a way to explain the world.
It's a way to have some power over the world around them. It's a
way to overcome the fears children have. Fantasies and fairy tales
and stories about magical powers are important to the development
of a healthy psychological state.
</P>
<P>
   What child doesn't have an uncle who pulls quarters out of the
air or out of an ear to the delight of his nieces and nephews?
</P>
<P>
   What child hasn't talked to and for his or her dolls or stuffed
animals or toy soldiers? What child hasn't fantasized about being a
knight, a king or queen, or a superhero? What child has not thought
of incantations that would make some improbable or even impossible
event happen _ in an attempt to control the world around them?
</P>
<P>
   A rich fantasy life invigorates the imagination. Fantasy and
fairy tales acknowledge the fears and conflicts children have. And
they can provide answers or resolutions to a child's inner
problems.
</P>
<P>
   What child hasn't felt like ``The Ugly Duckling'' or felt
unfairly burdened by chores set by a parent as in ``Cinderella''?
The inherent lessons of these stories are not lost on children.
</P>
<P>
   In the first Harry Potter book, Muggles are defined as
``nonmagic folk.'' In reality, Muggles are those whose imaginations
have been so suppressed they cannot see the joy in pretending nor
the complex reasons for children's fantasies. Those who want the
Harry Potter books banned are threatened by an active imagination.
They are the real Muggles.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a deeper reality involved here. Tens of thousands
of years ago, early humans created a magical universe to explain
the planets, stars and natural phenomenon like lightning, eclipses,
floods and volcanoes.
</P>
<P>
   Humankind sought connections between events by creating a
magical universe. Much like we do, early humans sought answers to
the problems the world threw at them. Their approach was through
magic.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Lascaux cave paintings have been interpreted as
hunting magic _ the portrayal of a desired event would bring it
into reality.
</P>
<P>
   The arrow struck the reindeer or bison in a painting, thus it
would come to pass.
</P>
<P>
   In the magical universe, when two things look alike _ the magic
of similarities _ they share some interior properties that can be
used to bring health or illness. A leaf from the liverwort plant
looks like a liver and thereby was thought to be an effective cure
for liver ailments. Like conceives like: A cave painting if
rendered carefully brought about the portrayed event.
</P>
<P>
   Those immersed in the magical universe know that if two things
in the world have once touched one another, they are always in
contact. In voodoo, for instance, a single hair or fingernail
paring taken from a person can be used to cast a spell on that
person _ for the hair or nail clipping is always in touch with the
person from whom it was taken.
</P>
<P>
   Anthropologists have never found a culture that didn't create
its own magical universe. Magical connections are inherent in our
thought patterns.
</P>
<P>
   The magical universe inhabits the twilight of our psyches.
</P>
<P>
   The magical universe was gradually shoved out of its position of
prominence by the rise of the religious universe. Later, the
scientific universe eventually came to the fore.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these three universes seeks different ways of explaining
the world around us. They ask different questions and arrive at
answers by very different approaches.
</P>
<P>
   When lightning strikes a tree on a plain and kills the herder
sitting beneath it, a person imbedded in the magical universe would
explain that someone put a spell on the herder so that he was
killed by lightning.
</P>
<P>
   A religious person could interpret the event as a sign that
divine retribution will fall upon those who commit a sacrilege or a
violation of holy covenants.
</P>
<P>
   A scientist, however, would explain that the tree as the tallest
conductor of electricity in the locale _ because of the sap or
because it was wet with rain _ would draw lightning to it. The
herder sitting beneath the tree should have known better and was
killed because of his ignorance of natural phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   While it may no longer be a dominant perspective, the magical
universe still prowls in our minds, our thought processes, our way
of thinking.
</P>
<P>
   We all have some belief in magical connections and intuitions
that defy religion and science.
</P>
<P>
   The Harry Potter books acknowledge the thirst children have for
magic and fantasy. Children already fantasize about their lives.
These books give them the security that other children fantasize,
too. And that makes their own fantasies less fearful.
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy and imagination are crucial to our growth as human
beings. We gradually outgrow our childhood fantasies, but the
pathways they constructed to enrich our imaginations and to tap our
deepest fears are invaluable in helping us reach our fullest
potential as adults.
</P>
<P>
   And in the Harry Potter books, magic is the spell that subdues
childhood's fears, summons new life for the imagination and
conjures up a world of excitement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 1722EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
