<P>
   These sports stories for release Tuesday, March 7, 2000, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES _ Javy Lopez has worked hard throughout the offseason
to recover from a knee injury that forced him to miss the end of
last season. But his return to the lineup at catcher will send his
best friend - fellow catcher Eddie Perez - back to the bench.
Although Lopez feels bad that his presence cuts into Perez's
playing time, he's anxious to return to the Braves' lineup.
(CRogers, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   BASKETBALL/NCAA
</P>
<P>
   BKC-CREMINS-NEXT _ ATLANTA _ Who will be the next men's
basketball coach at Georgia Tech? Some of the names that have been
mentioned include Tommy Amaker at Seton Hall, Dayton coach Oliver
Purnell and Skip Prosser of Xavier. (Clemons, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-SEC-KENTUCKY _ ATLANTA _ Despite a SEC co-championship, it
has not been a smooth season for Kentucky. But this is March and
the Wildcats have never lost at the Georgia Dome. Of course, that
means even more pressure for coach Tubby Smith in the SEC
Tournament. Despite an NCAA title, Smith is still proving himself
to Kentucky fans and rumors of him jumping to the NBA are common in
the Blue Grass State. (Bunn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 22.
</P>
<P>
   BASKETBALL/NBA
</P>
<P>
   BKN-SHAQ _ When you're the slamming, rapping genie of the NBA,
the Shaq Daddy, the only Notorious B.I.G. still living large, the
league becomes your traveling party. And as with most parties,
there is a guest list, those welcome to your bash. (Skolnick, Palm
beach Post). 46. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL/NFLLEWIS-VICTIMS _ ATLANTA _ Expect the victims in the
murder case against Baltimore Ravens' All-Pro linebacker Ray Lewis
to be ``put on trial'' as the defense attorneys do everything they
can to present them as the bad guys, the aggressors. It'll be the
crux of a self-defense strategy. This has worked well in some cases
. . . but it can backfire. (Torpy, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
35.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL/NCAA
</P>
<P>
   FBC-APPLEWHITE _ He stands on the sidelines sometimes lost in
the crowd. He's Major Applewhite, the Texas quarterback who is
recovering from knee surgery. However, the pairin from the knee
surgery likely doesn't compare with the pain of watching heralded
sophmore Chris Simms work with the first team unit during spring
practice. The two were sharing playing time in the Cotton Bowl
against Arkansas when Applewhite went down with the knee injury.
Time and the maturity of Simms will tell if Applewhite returns to
his old form and position. Developing. (Wangrin, Austin
American-Statesman). 15-20,
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS
</P>
<P>
   BASS-OKEECHOBEE _ After a quarter-century of watching Lake
Okeechobee on television, Bruce Shupp finally got to visit the
fabled bass-fishing haven in January. His verdict: ``That's pretty
ugly-looking water,'' said Shupp, national conservation director of
the Bass Anglers Sportsman Society, the nation's largest bass
fishing organization. He was astounded by the water's pollution-fed
murk, and the loss of the fish-nurturing grasses along much of the
lake's shore. (King, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
