<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8496 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      03-06 0406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, March 7, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL FORECAST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Record warmth will envelop the Plains Tuesday as breezes from
the south transport very mild air to the north. Some places will be
as much as 25 degrees above normal Tuesday afternoon. The mild
weather will spread to the East Coast where readings in the 70s
will be common in the Middle Atlantic States as high pressure
promotes abundant sunshine. Many spots in the Southeast will have
readings over 80 degrees which are more typical of the summer
rather than early March.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast will also turn unseasonably mild, although some
clouds will stream to the southeast over New England. Meanwhile, a
cold front crossing northern Maine will bring cloudy skies and
isolated showers and flurries to the higher elevations of Maine and
New Hampshire. Noticeably cooler air will press to the south behind
this front.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms will develop in the southern Plains
ahead of a cold front moving out of the southern Rockies. In the
wake of the front, showers will also reach western Texas. Cold air
in the mountains will combine with moisture being forced up the
sloping terrain to bring patches of snow to the highlands of
northern Arizona along with the Wasatch and San Juan mountains.
Farther to the north, skies will be partly cloudy across the
Dakotas as high clouds stream to the east.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, showers will brush the Northwest coast as moisture
arrives from the Pacific. Winds will increase with gusty breezes
buffeting the shore. To the south, Southern California will turn
sunny once again.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOCUS: News Maker &LR;
</P>
<P>
   There is an adage in weather forecasting that a storm which
makes news in the West will do so again before it reaches the East.
This past weekend's storm in California brought nearly two inches
of rain to Los Angeles and heavy snow around Flagstaff, Arizona.
Tuesday, the disturbance will approach the western Plains where
warm, humid air is streaming north from the Gulf. The unusual
intensity of the disturbance when combined with unseasonable warmth
in the Plains and Mississippi Valley should produce a noteworthy
outbreak of strong thunderstorms late Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 1737EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
