<HEADER>
A8511 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-WAL-MART-UNION-TEX     03-06 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAL-MART-UNION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD WORKERS UNION CRITICIZES WAL-MART
</HEADLINE>
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: Story is being filed in ``a'' national and
``f'' financial categories.) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wal-Mart's plan to transfer meat-cutters to other departments at
180 supercenters, including the East Texas store where butchers
voted for a union, is aimed at stifling gains by labor, a union
organizer says.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I believe they are shooting themselves in their own
feet,'' said Brad Edwards, a Fort Worth-area-based official of the
1.4-million-member United Food &AMP; Commercial Workers.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said that the union has been deluged with calls and
Internet inquiries from angry Wal-Mart employees since the
Arkansas-based retailer announced the decision at a hearing last
week in the East Texas town of Palestine, where 18 seafood workers
and meat-cutters have petitioned for a union vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife hasn't had a good night's sleep since the
announcement,'' said Richard Rogers, whose wife is a seafood worker
at the Wal-Mart in Palestine. ``She is very, very concerned about
the plight of her co-workers and their skills.''
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 17, seven of 10 Wal-Mart meat-cutters in nearby
Jacksonville voted for union representation. It was the first
successful union vote at a U.S. Wal-Mart and was considered a major
organized labor victory. For decades, the nation's largest retailer
had prevented inroads by unions through its ``open door'' labor
relations policy and stock purchase plans.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said that meat-cutters and mechanics at six Texas
Wal-Marts will similarly petition for a union vote in coming
months. United Food &AMP; Commercial Workers won the right to organize
unions among ``appropriate'' units of skilled workers within a
store last year.
</P>
<P>
   As for the move to change meat-cutters' duties, he said, ``We
feel it is just some kind of scheme to railroad the workers who are
trying to organize.''
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart spokeswoman Jessica Moser said that the shift from
in-store preparation to prepackaged ``case-ready'' meat reflects a
retail trend and was not aimed at quieting union organizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working on this for several months,'' Moser said
from company headquarters in Bentonville, Ark. ``It had nothing to
do with the union.''
</P>
<P>
   Moser said that meat-cutters will keep their pay scale and be
able to discuss new job preferences. Wal-Mart meat departments in
Texas, Arkansas, Oklahoma, Missouri, Louisiana and Kansas would be
affected, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The move stems from a pilot project in northeast Arkansas, where
customers preferred prepackaged meat and poultry, the spokeswoman
said. The move will bring no savings in labor costs and no layoffs,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said that meat-cutters, who earn $10-$12 an hour, are
upset because they will be transferred to departments where they
will compete for work hours with co-workers earning less than $7 an
hour. In some stores, ``full time'' may mean less than 30 hours a
week, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wal-Mart may have had plans to do this,'' Edwards said of the
transfers. ``But they're doing this much, much quicker because of
the response the union has gotten over the last month or two.''
</P>
<P>
   The organizer said the transfers would likely be piecemeal and
would not affect what unions are formed inside stores.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 1758EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8512 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f BC-WAL-MART-UNION-TEX     03-06 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
