   The move stems from a pilot project in northeast Arkansas, where
customers preferred prepackaged meat and poultry, the spokeswoman
said. The move will bring no savings in labor costs and no layoffs,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said that meat-cutters, who earn $10-$12 an hour, are
upset because they will be transferred to departments where they
will compete for work hours with co-workers earning less than $7 an
hour. In some stores, ``full time'' may mean less than 30 hours a
week, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wal-Mart may have had plans to do this,'' Edwards said of the
transfers. ``But they're doing this much, much quicker because of
the response the union has gotten over the last month or two.''
</P>
<P>
   The organizer said the transfers would likely be piecemeal and
would not affect what unions are formed inside stores.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
