<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBRIGHT-CZECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVEL URGES ALBRIGHT TO SEEK CZECH PRESIDENCY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HODONIN, Czech Republic _ On a day devoted to the commemoration
of Czechoslovakia's first democratic president, its second, Vaclav
Havel, pressed Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on Monday to
consider succeeding him.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, born in Czechoslovakia and fluent in the language, has
said that she is not interested in the post, elected by parliament,
which Havel holds until 2003.
</P>
<P>
   But Havel, organizing a question about her candidacy from Czech
television as she stood next to him, urged her to consider the job,
in what was seen as a commentary on the current state of Czech
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally would consider it excellent because, into this
rather stale provincial environment, this would bring an
international spirit,'' Havel said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright did not respond, but her aides referred journalists to
statements last week in which she said her loyalties were with her
adopted country, the United States, and that she was flattered, but
did not want the job.
</P>
<P>
   Havel, a playwright and dissident, became president of the
post-Soviet Czechoslovakia almost by acclimation in 1989, and he
has been instrumental in bringing the Czech Republic _ formed in
the division of Czechoslovakia in 1993 _ into NATO and other key
Western institutions.
</P>
<P>
   But with the gloomy elegance for which he is known, Havel has
criticized the current crop of Czech politicians, in particular
former Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus, as unwilling to take on global
or even regional responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Czech population is still ambivalent about NATO
membership and about NATO's war last year in Kosovo, both projects
Havel pushed hard.
</P>
<P>
   Havel thus used Albright's presence here and the reverence for
Tomas Masaryk, the scholar-statesman who presided over the country
from 1918 to 1935 and was married to an American, to urge Czechs to
look to a wider world.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech here at a monument to Masaryk on the 150th
anniversary of his birth, Havel praised the earlier president's
tolerance and humanity, his devotion to freedom and democracy, and
his willingness to defend them, by force if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back at Masaryk's legacy,'' he said, ``we inevitably
feel compelled to put to ourselves the unpleasant question whether,
and how vigorously, we are at present capable of defending the
freedoms we enjoy.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Albright praised Havel for his own exercise of
international responsibility, most recently in canceling a
$30-million contract between Russia and a Czech company to provide
air-conditioning equipment for a nuclear reactor in Iran that
Washington fears is being used for weapons production.
</P>
<P>
   She said that halting the proliferation of nuclear weapons is a
priority for NATO, and in a speech at Masaryk University in Brno,
said: ``As with any goal worth achieving, it is not without cost.''
To protect sensitive technology, American companies also have had
to forego contracts, she said.
</P>
<P>
   After her speech, two self-described anarchists, both 22, threw
eggs at Albright. Her bodyguards were hit directly, and Albright
received a small spatter.
</P>
<P>
   Before the speech, she met with Roma, or Gypsy, activists and
students, who described the persistent discrimination that faced
them in Czech society and the region. Albright urged them to fight
for their rights and to educate their fellow citizens to reduce
prejudice.
</P>
</TEXT>
