<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8521 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER07-COX     03-06 1466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Republicans in California
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A feisty John McCain labeled George W. Bush ``so Clinton-esque
it's scary.'' Both Bush and McCain were making a final push Monday
in California, where 162 delegates to the GOP nominating convention
are the biggest prize of Super Tuesday voting. Bush has the inside
track on those delegates, but McCain is hoping for a symbolic
victory in the nonbinding popular vote. A confident Bush began the
healing process Monday by dismissing the rift between him and
McCain as a minor fracture in the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS IN NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore and Bill Bradley were both in the Big Apple on Monday,
ahead of today's big primary day. Gore was courting Jewish
activists, while Bradley, trying to revive his sagging campaign in
the Super Tuesday contests, greeted commuters in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   EMPHASIS ON FEMALE VOTE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's plan to finish off John McCain has included in
recent days an appeal to women voters that he believes will carry
over to his November showdown with Al Gore. The Washington Times
noted that Bush has placed a renewed emphasis on education, an
issue that rates highly with women, and that Elizabeth Dole has
been especially prominent on the campaign trail for Bush in the
past five days.
</P>
<P>
   SUPER LEAD IN `SUPERDELEGATES'
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has pledges of support from more than 400
``superdelegates,'' the Democratic Party leaders and elected
officials who will help choose a nominee at this summer's national
convention, according to The Associated Press. The support gives
Gore a big jump toward the 2,170 delegates needed to seal the
nomination. Gore has won 42 delegates in presidential contests so
far and is sure to pick up more in Tuesday's primaries. His
delegate count dwarfs that of rival Bill Bradley, who has won no
delegates in contests and just 27 superdelegates in the AP's
survey. On Tuesday, 1,315 Democratic delegates are at stake in
contests in 15 states and American Samoa.
</P>
<P>
   COULD MCCAIN PULL OUT WASHINGTON IN OVERTIME?
</P>
<P>
   Long after the media reported a win for George W. Bush in
Washington state's Feb. 29 primary, the laborious counting of
hundreds of thousands of absentee ballots is showing that Bush
might not be the winner there after all. The online magazine Salon
reports that as of Saturday, Bush led John McCain by fewer than
7,000 votes _ 351,881 to 344,933 _ with roughly 20 percent of the
ballots still to be counted.'' Salon notes that more than half of
the 188,000 absentee ballots that remain come from King County
(Seattle), where McCain led 32 percent to 26 percent. If that
pattern holds in the ballots yet to be counted, McCain could easily
overtake Bush.
</P>
<P>
   OH YEAH, THAT'S RIGHT, HE USED TO PLAY BALL
</P>
<P>
   In an ad broadcast in New York only, Bill Bradley's campaign has
teamed up two quintessential New Yorkers, former Mayor Ed Koch and
film director Spike Lee, who's a renowned Knicks fan. The two men
try to top each other with assertions about what a great guy
Bradley is. Lee punctuates the point by taking a faux jump shot
that seems to remind any voter who may have forgotten that among
Bradley's achievements is his pro basketball career with the New
York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING AHEAD TO THE END GAMES
</P>
<P>
   While the two underdogs are expressing confidence as they make
the TV talk show rounds, their aides are bracing for the worst by
quietly making plans for dignified exits. Bill Bradley's advisers
acknowledge he has little chance of loosening Al Gore's grip on
Super Tuesday states. John McCain's team was holding out hope for
an election night surprise. McCain, asked what was in store if he
fared poorly, replied, ``A happy life.''
</P>
<P>
   SHAKING THE MONEY TREE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush or his surrogates will return to the fund-raising
circuit this month to replenish coffers drained by heavy spending.
Bush finance chairman Don Evans said the plan all along had been to
raise more money, but acknowledged it was made more necessary
because of the unexpectedly strong challenge mounted by John
McCain. The campaign has scheduled five fund-raisers for March and
April, and is considering five to seven more, with a goal of
raising $5 million to $10 million, Evans said. The events already
scheduled will be in New York, New Jersey, Michigan, Illinois and
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   BARKING UP THE MONEY TREE
</P>
<P>
   Turning his sights on the Republicans, Al Gore criticized George
W. Bush on campaign finance issues, saying he was flooding the
campaign with ``soft money,'' and suggested at a senior citizens
forum in Cranston, R.I., that if Bush wins the Republican
nomination, he might not have won it fairly. Gore raised those
themes for the first time Sunday in Rhode Island, and repeated them
Sunday night in New York in an appearance with Hillary Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING PRETTY CLOSE TO FINALITY
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, so insistent that he takes nothing for granted, slipped
and called Super Tuesday ``this final, er, semi-final uh, uh
contest.'' The stumble lays bare what he has tried to convey in
code _ looking ahead to November, he's now reaching out to Bill
Bradley. Gore road-tested an evolving, new stump speech aimed at
more moderate voters than those he had targeted against Bradley.
Aides said Gore hoped to debut the speech in Nashville, Tenn.,
tonight as results come in from 15 states, where polls give Gore
commanding leads.
</P>
<P>
   NO FINALITY YET FOR KEYES
</P>
<P>
   Last place in the GOP race for the presidential nomination has
not dissuaded Alan Keyes from taking his fight all the way to the
party convention in Philadelphia. Speaking to about 150 people at
St. Louis University, Keyes said he is keeping his campaign going
with the help of small donors. Keyes: ``They're energized at the
thought that I'm not going to stop.'' Even though Keyes supporters
are few in number, they ``open their wallets enough for him to
continue,'' according to the St. Louis Post-Dispatch.
</P>
<P>
   LOYALTY TO A FRIEND REMEMBERED
</P>
<P>
   The mayor of Tempe, Ariz., is impressed with John McCain's
loyalty. Neil Giuliano, facing a threat that his homosexuality
would be exposed by Christian conservatives at a city council
meeting, did what he thought was nobody's business: He held a news
conference and declared, ``I happen to be gay.'' The reaction of
Arizona's senior senator, McCain, was swift and angry. ``John was
the first to tell the religious right, `This doesn't make a damned
bit of difference,' '' Giuliano said, remembering how McCain went
out of his way to call him a good mayor and a great friend.
``Politically in Arizona, McCain should have done just the
opposite. Instead, he came right to my defense. He's a loyal
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   TIED IN KNOTS OVER MARRIAGE
</P>
<P>
   When Californians choose between Al Gore, Bill Bradley and John
McCain and George W. Bush today, they also will decide whether the
state will validate gay marriages. Of the 20 propositions on the
ballot _ dealing with a slew of social and economic issues _
Proposition 22 is generating the most heat. It declares that only
marriages between men and women are legally valid. ``It's been a
more quiet campaign, but we certainly have a lot of action over
Proposition 22,'' said Stanley Moore, a political science professor
at Pepperdine University.
</P>
<P>
   SO LONG AS THEY DON'T THROW IRISH CONFETTI
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton celebrated St. Patrick's Day several days
early _ and got an early idea of how rough-and-tumble New York
politics can become. Clinton went from Riverside Church in
Manhattan, where she was repeatedly applauded for calling for
better police-community relations, to a St. Patrick's Day parade in
Queens, where she was alternately heckled and admired. Most of the
onlookers clapped and cheered, with some of them holding signs
saying ``Irish-Americans for Hillary.'' But anti-Hillary shouts
could be heard, like ``Go back to Arkansas, carpetbagger!''
</P>
<P>
   COUNT MINNESOTA OUT
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks after Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura abandoned the
Reform Party over a dispute about the party's presidential
candidate, the party's Minnesota branch split from the national
organization, cementing the internal divisions that left the party
in shambles. ``If we don't leave the national party, we will have
no honor, and we will doom ourselves to failure,'' said state party
chairman Dean Barkeley during a meeting in St. Paul.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
