<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8525 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-LOUIMA-TRIAL-ART-2TAK     03-06 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUIMA-TRIAL-ART-2TAKES(655)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 OFFICERS CONVICTED OF CONSPIRACY IN POLICE TORTURE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By EDWARD WONG and ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two New York City policemen and one former officer
were convicted Monday of covering up the brutal assault on Abner
Louima, a Haitian immigrant, in an emotional verdict that the
defendants' lawyers and families vowed through tears to fight.
</P>
<P>
   The three defendants _ Charles Schwarz, Thomas Wiese and Thomas
Bruder _ each were found guilty in federal District Court in
Brooklyn of obstructing justice by conspiring to manufacture a
story for authorities that Schwarz was not involved in the attack
on Louima in the bathroom of a Brooklyn station house in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The horrible details of the assault, in which a police officer
beat and sodomized Louima with a broken broomstick, had been fully
aired at a trial last year. Monday's verdicts spoke to the systemic
problem of whether police officers and officials of the policeman's
union lied to protect their brethren rather than the citizens they
were sworn to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Such concerns also were raised in the recent testimony of four
New York police officers who were charged in the shooting death of
Amadou Diallo, a 21-year-old Guinean immigrant, in the Bronx last
February. The officers were acquitted last month of all charges,
which included second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   In the Louima case, Schwarz was convicted in June of violating
the victim's civil rights by pinning him down on the bathroom floor
while another officer, Justin Volpe, sodomized him. Volpe pleaded
guilty to attacking Louima and is serving 30 years in prison.
Schwarz, who has been in custody, faces a possible life sentence
for that conviction.
</P>
<P>
   In the second trial that ended Monday, jurors were not directly
asked to consider whether Schwarz was, in fact, involved in the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the government argued in the monthlong trial that
Schwarz pinned Louima to the floor while he was tortured, and then
lied about his role with the help of Bruder and Wiese. The defense,
which said it would appeal Monday's verdict, claimed there had been
no plot to exculpate Schwarz because he was innocent from the
start. The three officers seemed stunned to the point of hysteria
Monday each time the jury forewoman pronounced the word ``guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruder, the first to be convicted, grabbed his neck, squinting
in disbelief, before laying his head on the shoulder of his lawyer,
Stuart London, and bursting into tears.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz sat back in shock when his verdict was read, then
glanced angrily around the courtroom, from his lawyers to his
family to the jury.
</P>
<P>
   After Wiese heard his verdict, he and Bruder met in a tearful
embrace, gripping each other's heads. Moments later, outside the
courtroom, Wiese's mother collapsed to the floor and Wiese dropped
to his knees to cradle her in his arms. ``Get a nurse!'' someone
shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Bruder paced the hallway amid a crowd of family and friends,
crying openly and calling out: ``You tell the truth and this is
what happens!''
</P>
<P>
   Andra Schwarz, Schwarz's wife, who has been working to appeal
her husband's earlier conviction, promised to fight Monday's
verdict as well. ``The prosecutors were not seeking the truth,''
she said, in a voice stony with fatigue and disbelief. ``They just
want a conviction. I'm fed up. We're not going to let them get away
with this.''
</P>
<P>
   As he was led out of the courtroom, Schwarz cursed and yelled,
``Why did they do this!'' His lawyer, Ronald Fischetti, said the
ex-officer was ``absolutely devastated.'' He added that he had
asked the authorities to place Schwarz on a 24-hour suicide watch.
</P>
<P>
   The three defendants face up to 5 years in prison for Monday's
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Louima was not in the courtroom when the verdict was read, but a
lawyer, Sanford Rubenstein, representing the Louima family, issued
a statement: ``I hope that as a result of today's verdict, a
message will be sent to police officers all over the country that
they will be held accountable if and when they obstruct justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Diallo trial, in which the white defendants killed a
black man, both of the Louima trials have raised questions of
racial bias within the police department. Volpe and the three
defendants in the Louima case are white, while Louima is black.
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyers in the Louima case suggested that the Diallo
case influenced Monday's verdicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to ignore the post-Diallo anti-jury sentiment,''
London, Bruder's attorney, said. He added that there were cases in
which juries had made mistakes, and that this was one.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   From the start, the government faced a daunting task in proving
there was a conspiracy to lie because conspiracies are, by nature,
crimes of secrecy. Although the prosecution introduced reams of
telephone records showing that the defendants spoke with each other
in a blizzard of calls in the days after the assault _ sometimes
only minutes apart _ there were no tapes of the conversations and
no ironclad way to know what was being discussed.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of hard evidence, the jury was left with a case
of inferences: Were the defendants joining forces on the phone to
concoct stories, as the government claimed? Or were the three
officers, who had subdued Louima on the street, calling each other
for moral support, discussing his hospitalization and the chance
that they might face repercussions for having injured their
prisoner during the arrest, as the defense maintained?
</P>
<P>
   The lack of concrete evidence also left the jury with the
difficult job of determining the credibility of a parade of
witnesses, many of whom have now testified so many times _ at two
grand juries, two trials and before a host of investigative
agencies _ that it was easy for lawyers on both sides to trip them
up with their own words.
</P>
<P>
   Louima, the first witness to appear, was grilled by the defense
about crucial instances where his account of the attack changed
over time. In his first interview with the police, Louima said his
pants and underwear were pulled down only after he was taken into
the bathroom. Later, however, he said he was led through the
station house with his buttocks and genitals exposed.
</P>
<P>
   But in addition to contradicting testimony there also were
several instances where witnesses told their versions of the events
of Aug. 9, 1997, for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   In a display of raw emotion, Volpe, subpoenaed from prison to
testify, gave his first detailed account of the night of Aug. 9,
1997. He described how he thought he had been punched by Louima on
the street and then, in a tense stand-off in the stationhouse
bathroom, had demanded an apology several times before throwing the
prisoner to the ground and sodomizing him.
</P>
<P>
   After the attack, Louima spent two months in the hospital
recovering from internal injuries that included a ruptured bladder
and colon.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz, too, took the witness stand for the first time in more
than 2-and-a-half years of court proceedings and offered an alibi
that had never been heard before. He said he was outside the
station house as the attack occurred, conducting a routine search
of his patrol car for evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bruder and Wiese did not take the stand, their stories
were revealed through the testimony of the government investigators
who interviewed them. According to former Deputy Inspector James
Burns, Wiese said he walked into the bathroom moments after the
attack and discovered Volpe brandishing a feces-stained stick with
Louima sobbing at his feet. Bruder told investigators that he saw
Volpe escorting Louima into the bathroom while Wiese was standing
outside the bathroom door playing with the station house mutt,
Midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Bruder and Wiese, each free on $100,000 bail, still face
departmental charges. And all three defendants are named along with
the city, the Police Department and the Patrolmen's Benevolent
Association in a $155 million civil lawsuit filed by Louima.
</P>
<P>
   After Monday's conviction, Wiese also might have to answer for
charges raised by Volpe on the stand that he was present in the
bathroom throughout the attack on Louima but did nothing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
