<SLUG> BC-CARDIOLOGIST07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First female to lead black cardiologists
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Overjoyed is how Dr. Elisabeth Ofili reacted when
elected the first woman president of the Association of Black
Cardiologists, a 700-member international organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I jumped up and down. Then, I said, `What have I done?'''
laughed Ofili, 44, chief cardiologist at Morehouse School of
Medicine, who already juggles her marriage, four children, academic
and medical careers, and faith and volunteer activities. She will
be officially named president this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The ABC, based in Atlanta, was formed in 1974 to draw attention
to the statistics on stroke and heart disease among blacks and to
promote prevention efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Ofili was born in Nigeria, to a father who was a U.S.
Information Service librarian and a mother who worked as a nurse
and raised seven children. Ofili received her medical degree in
Nigeria and a master's of public health in the United States, then
completed medical residencies in internal medicine and cardiology.
</P>
<P>
   She will oversee the ABC's goal of starting an international
resource center for cardiovascular disease in Atlanta. She also
wants to keep getting out the basic message on heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surveys show African-Americans have less knowledge in terms of
risk factors,'' Ofili said. ``And they're not as aware of their own
numbers, such as their cholesterol levels.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For more information about the Association of Black
Cardiologists, call 678-302-4222 or go to www.abcardio.org.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Guthrie writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
