A8529 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HEALTH-DISPARITY07-CO     03-06 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-DISPARITY07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Medical panel: More focus on equal treatment
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lack of health insurance and low income-status are oft-heard
explanations for the disparity between blacks and whites when it
comes to health care access and disease death rates.
</P>
<P>
   But even when economics and insurance are equal, treatment is
often still unequal, concludes a Morehouse School of
Medicine/Kasier Family Foundation report.
</P>
<P>
   Morehouse convened a gathering of Georgia's leading medical
researchers, doctors, public health leaders and managed-care
executives Friday to respond to the findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to understand the `why' is the next step,'' said Dr.
Lawrence Sanders, director of clinical medicine at Morehouse.
``We've got to connect this research to the people who live in the
communities who best know how to deliver the services they need.
The national goal is to end this disparity by the year 2010. But I
personally think it will take until the end of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Mayberry, author of the report and director of the
Morehouse Medical Treatment Effectiveness Center, noted some
improvements, such as in the likelihood of young black women
getting screening for breast and ovarian cancer. ``But older women
are still not being reached,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the report's findings:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The largest disparity continues to be in the most vital of
organs _ the heart _ which helps explain why African-Americans are
twice as likely to die of cardiovascular disease than whites.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Blacks are 13 percent to 40 percent less likely to receive
coronary angioplasty than whites and 32 percent to 70 percent less
likely to have bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Race was the biggest predictor of treatment of AIDS or HIV
patients. Blacks are 41 percent to 73 percent less likely than
whites to receive expensive and effective drug therapies.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Diabetes care was seen as most equitable; however, it has not
been as scrutinized as other health conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the review of hundreds of research studies conducted
nationwide since 1985, the Morehouse report is the most
comprehensive, up-to-date picture of health disparity in America,
said Dr. John Eisenberg, head of the Agency for Healthcare Research
and Quality. The watch-dog federal agency is leading President
Clinton's attack on the 98,000 annual deaths caused by doctor
errors.
</P>
<P>
   After three hours of hearing from the expert panel, Eisenberg
wrapped up the discussion, saying ``If this were a disease, we'd be
at the stage of describing what the problem is. We'd be asking,
`Why does this occur? What are the mechanics, causes?' ... Let's
find the remedies. Let's put them in place and let's disseminate
the knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kathleen Toomey, director of Georgia Division of Public
Health, cautioned that many times applying the most obvious
solution won't work. ``In public health, we often think all we need
to do is change health access, and we will improve their health
status. It's the `If we build a clinic, they will come,' theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we've learned they may or may not come and we may or may
not improve their health status at all,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For a free copy of the report, call 1-800-656-4533 or visit
Kaiser's Web site, www.kff.org.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
