<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-INTERNET07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Get allergy alert at Pollen.com
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trees are blooming. Bushes are budding. For a certain percentage
of the population, the signs of spring provoke a pressing question:
``Is it safe to go out of the house?''
</P>
<P>
   A newly launched Web site hopes to make spring and fall a little
easier for allergy sufferers. Using your ZIP code, Pollen.com
generates a free local forecast of probable pollen counts for the
next four days. It classifies the days in the forecast as low,
medium or high risk, and lists the plants most likely to be
releasing pollen for the length of the forecast. (Last week, for
instance, it ranked Decatur's Courthouse Square as medium-to-high
risk, with maple, alder and cedar tree pollen causing the most
trouble.) If you register _ which is not required to obtain a
four-day forecast _ Pollen.com will also send you e-mail alerts
warning when certain types of pollen are expected to reach
troublesome levels locally.
</P>
<P>
   The site is the creation of a Pennsylvania company called
Surveillance Data Inc., a private research concern whose
subsidiaries specialize in environmental modeling and manufacture
pollen-counting equipment. The company claims that its proprietary
computer models put the site's usefulness ahead of similar ones
such as the very informative National Allergy Bureau
(www.aaaai.org/nab/default.stm), which reports pollen counts but
does not predict them. Relatively new, Pollen.com has an
uncomplicated design, offers several links to allergy information
sites and is refreshingly free of advertising.
</P>
<P>
   M.A.J. McKenna writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 1816EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
