<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8531 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HOSPITAL-INFECTIONS07     03-06 1368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-INFECTIONS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Locally and globally, hospital infections a big global concern
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Melanie Dodd's patient needed a dressing changed.
</P>
<P>
   It sounded like an uncomplicated task: Remove an adhesive-edged
bandage from an elderly man's upper chest, where it covered a
catheter sewn into a blood vessel, and put on a new one.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't quite that simple. Moving around the private room, the
27-year-old nurse ran through a precise checklist: 15 steps to
clean the skin and change the dressing, including donning a sterile
mask, washing hands twice and wearing three pairs of gloves.
</P>
<P>
   From the doorway, Maureen Forier _ nurse-manager of Emory
University Hospital's 6G Intensive Care Unit and Dodd's supervisor
_ shook her head. She has been a nurse for 23 years; Dodd, for
five.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago, you would walk into a patient's room, say hello and
shake hands,'' Forier said. ``Now we're trained to go to the sink
first. We think about the potential for infection in everything we
do.''
</P>
<P>
   In the years between Forier's first nursing experiences and
Dodd's, health care has faced an uncomfortable truth: Infections
that are acquired during a hospital stay make some patients sicker
than they were before they entered the hospital and can endanger
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 2 million Americans each year _ one in 20 of all those
admitted to hospitals _ contract such infections, according to the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. The infections kill
almost 90,000 patients and cost an additional $5 billion each year
to treat.
</P>
<P>
   This week the CDC has organized an international scientific
meeting in Atlanta _ the first in a decade _ to examine the problem
of infections acquired by patients (called ``nosocomial,'' from the
Greek word for hospital). Experts attending the conference say the
news is mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This truly has international attention,'' said Dr. John
McGowan, a former CDC scientist now teaching at Emory's Rollins
School of Public Health. ``People around the world realize that
this is an issue they need to address, even if they have relatively
limited resources.''
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, researchers arriving for the conference were
met by good news: The CDC announced Thursday that 300 U.S.
hospitals participating in a 10-year pilot program had reduced
rates of certain infections by at least one-third.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the attendees faced abundant bad news. More
than 600 scientific papers were submitted in advance, many of them
detailing the advance of the so-called ``superbugs'' _ disease
organisms that have developed resistance to many of the drugs used
against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antimicrobial resistance is a huge problem, and it is only
getting worse,'' said Dr. James Steinberg, who tracks the results
of infection control programs at Crawford Long Hospital.
``Globally, it is one of the major challenges we face.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the infections contracted in health-care settings are
not caused by drug-resistant pathogens, though their proportion is
growing. Nosocomial infections don't have to be caused by superbugs
to be troublesome: They can arise from a flu virus coughed out by a
visitor and inhaled by a patient, or a bacteria that lives
harmlessly on intact skin but slips into a surgical wound. Managed
care's emphasis on moving mildly ill patients to outpatient care
has left hospitals handling a generally sicker population than in
the past, and improved technology has increased treatment options
for the very sick. The result has been a patient population for
whom any additional infection can have dire consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our patients are more ill, we generally have more patients and
less time, and our environment is characterized by more procedures
and more invasive devices,'' summed up Dr. Julie Gerberding,
director of CDC's Hospital Infections Program. ``Our patients are
more at risk. And so preventing infections is more challenging.''
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that danger has led, in many health-care
institutions, to an array of preventive steps. In the Emory system,
placards listing standard infection precautions _ procedures for
handling needles and linens, and requirements for wearing gloves,
gowns, eye-shields and masks _ are displayed at every nurses'
station. All personnel, down to the parking valets, are offered
vaccinations and protective devices. Each patient's room includes
protective containers for contaminated materials and needles, and
is stocked with disinfectants and boxes of gloves.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a staff nurse, we never used to wear gloves, even
to do all kinds of nasty things,'' said Betsy Hackman, who is now
director of infection control for Crawford Long and Emory
University hospitals. ``It wouldn't have occurred to us. But also,
they wouldn't have been available.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the emphasis on prevention, combating nosocomial
infections is an ongoing battle: CDC research has found that,
though up to 30 percent of potential infections could be prevented,
only 6 percent to 9 percent actually are. Some additional studies
of hand-washing by health care workers, the most basic act of
infection control, put their willingness to wash hands as often and
as long as required at less than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In part, researchers say, it's a question of perceived risk. The
gloves, masks and eye protection required by ``universal
precautions'' _ the AIDS-inspired recommendation, dating back to
the 1980s, that all body fluids be treated as potentially hazardous
_ were adopted relatively quickly by doctors, nurses and other
health care personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point of universal precautions was protecting the health
worker,'' said Dr. Henry Blumberg, hospital epidemiologist for
Grady Memorial Hospital. ``Washing hands is for the benefit of your
patients, so that you don't transmit any organism from one to
another. In that situation, a health care worker is unlikely to get
sick.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some experts say, the same industry conditions that put
patients at greater risk of nosocomial infections _ sicker patients
and tighter schedules _ also make it more difficult for health care
workers to avoid transmitting the bugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patient safety and patient protection are part of our culture
_ but if the patient is in the middle of a crisis, you don't
necessarily deem it appropriate to run away and wash your hands,''
said the CDC's Gerberding. ``It's a question of competing
priorities, and it causes trouble across the board.''
</P>
<P>
   Local hospitals such as those in the Emory system coach their
personnel in the necessity of infection control, usually through
formal trainings at least once a year. They also try to educate
their patients; Crawford Long, for instance, gives brochures to
newly admitted patients that explain why nurses and technicians may
be wearing gowns, goggles or masks.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, the infection-control measures protect the
individual patients who are vulnerable to hospital-acquired
infections for the days, weeks or months they spend in the
institutions. Behind that goal, though, there is a second one. No
one in health care wants to be responsible for encouraging the
spread of drug-resistant organisms, which thrive in hospitals and
among the sickest patients, and which threaten to return medicine
to the days before antibiotics. The most formidable drug-resistant
bug yet recognized _ Staphylococcus aureus that has become
partially resistant to the last-ditch antibiotic vancomycin _ has
surfaced four times in the United States in the past three years,
each time in a patient already under treatment in a health care
institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I know what's coming, if we don't get Staph aureus
under control, and I don't like it,'' said Hackman, Emory's
director of infection control. ``It would change my life as I know
it if we had to deal with that.''
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The CDC will be holding a conference this week on preventing
hospital infections: www.cdc.gov/ncidod/hip
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Learn more about staph infections in the health encyclopedia:
www.accessatlanta.com/living
</P>
<P>
   /health/
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
