<HEADER>
A8532 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-INFECTIONS-SIDE07-COX     03-06 0240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFECTIONS-SIDE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Protect yourself
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What can patients or family members do to protect themselves
against infections acquired in medical settings? Dr. Julie
Gerberding, director of the Hospital Infections Program at the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, recommends these steps:
</P>
<P>
   IN THE HOSPITAL
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ask the nurse or physician if they have washed their hands.
``It's not an easy thing to do, but it is possible to be your own
advocate.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ask whether intravenous lines, catheters or tubes are still
necessary. ``These devices are essential to taking care of a
patient, but sometimes they can be used longer than needed. Asking
`Do I still need this IV?' can save lives.''
</P>
<P>
   IN DAILY LIFE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't demand antibiotics when they won't be useful _ for
example, to treat a virus. ``The physician is not recommending
against antibiotics because they are trying to save money or get
you out of the office faster, but because they have a genuine
concern about antibiotic resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make sure children and adults have all their recommended
vaccinations. ``Flu shots and pneumococcal vaccine for adults can
prevent problems and complications that would require antibiotics
to treat.''
</P>
<P>
   _M.A.J. McKenna writes for the Atlanta Journal- Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
