<P>
   CAMPAIGN-TUESDAY (Los Angeles) _ With a final, furious round of
campaigning, the four main presidential candidates head toward a
coast-to-coast vote. By Michael Kranish and Jill Zuckman. 1500
words.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-REALITY (Undated) _ The McCain rocket that soared with
his startling triumph in New Hampshire may be pulled back to Earth
by the weight of Republican Party orthodoxy. By Walter V. Robinson.
1300 words.
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY-GORE (New York) _ Al Gore met political disaster here 12
years ago. Now he's back confident, and favored to defeat local
hero Bill Bradley. By John A. Farrell. 1300 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COURT-NAVY-YARD (Portsmouth, N.H.) _ New Hampshire turns to the
U.S. Supreme Court to try to settle the state's long-simmering
dispute with Maine over which state owns the Portsmouth Naval
Shipyard. By Lois Shea. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   WHALE-SUIT (Boston) _ The Conservation Law Foundation sues the
federal government for not doing enough to protect the Northern
right whale. By Scott Allen. 850 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN-ECONOMY (Boston) _ Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan says if
the high-flying stock market loses some of its zip, that will help
slow the economy to a more sustainable pace. He puts investors on
notice that the central bank could help that process along with
more interest rate increases. By Kimberly Blanton. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   FASTEST-CHIP (Undated) _ Advanced Micro Devices beats Intel to
the punch and announces a microprocessor that runs at 1 gigahertz a
second -- the fastest Intel-compatible chip ever. By Hiawatha Bray.
600 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-RYAN-COLUMN (Port Charlotte, Fla.) _ Yeah, yeah, yeah, Pedro
pitched and he wasn't anything special. The whole thing was pretty
un-Pedrolike, not that it really mattered. By Bob Ryan. 840 words.
</P>
