<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8535 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-NEWSTAND07-COX     03-06 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grisham sells _ in a monthly, too
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   His legal thrillers still sell in the millions, but John Grisham
is getting more enthusiastic responses to his serialized novel ``A
Painted House.'' The second installment of the six-part novel about
young Luke Chandler's adventurous summer in 1950s Arkansas appears
this month in The Oxford American ($5.95). As the story resumes,
the boy is questioned about a brutal fight among three of the
town's bullies and one of his father's migrant workers _ a fight
that resulted in a death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is one of John's best works,'' says Oxford
American editor Marc Smirnoff. ``People are going ga-ga over it,
and Stephen King called to say how much he liked it.'' Smirnoff
attributes the positive reaction to the fact that the semi-autobio-
</P>
<P>
   graphical novel is one of the most personal things Grisham has
written. ``Even though there aren't any lawyers in it, it reads
like a thriller.''
</P>
<P>
   The public response has translated into some big numbers for the
magazine, which, incidentally, is financed by Grisham. Sales have
soared from 50,000 to nearly 230,000 copies, Smirnoff says, and
readers who missed the first installment can order back issues by
e-mail: oxam(at)watervalley
</P>
<P>
   .net. The series eventually will become a book, Smirnoff says,
but no publication date has been set.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Star treatment: Newsweek ($3.50) gushes over Julia Roberts in
an eight-page spread on the $20 million woman. Roberts talks about
her new movie, ``Erin Brockovich''; her new love, actor Benjamin
Bratt; and admits that she has been estranged from her brother,
Eric Roberts, for years. In a sidebar, Donna Foote writes about the
real Erin Brockovich, a legal investigator who helped win a $333
million lawsuit against Pacific Gas and Electric for chromium VI
contamination.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On the pill: When John Rock and his colleagues developed the
birth control pill, they included a placebo or ``off'' week
allowing women to menstruate at the rate the researchers considered
normal. What Rock didn't take into account, says New Yorker ($3)
writer Malcolm Gladwell, was the possibility that Western women
were menstruating at much higher rates than women historically.
Those rates have resulted in a higher incidence of breast cancer,
Gladwell writes, and have led one researcher to advocate a new
birth control nasal spray that would reduce both the number of
periods and the risk of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Katie's crusade: In more health news, Time ($3.50) features
``Today'' show host Katie Couric in a cover story on colon cancer.
Couric, whose husband died of the disease two weeks after his 42nd
birthday, is hosting a five-day series this week on the morning TV
show to draw attention to the cancer and suggest ways of preventing
it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Split decision: The music and youth culture magazine Spin
($3.99) marks its 15th anniversary this month with four covers from
the past. Newsstand buyers can choose among the 1985 Madonna, the
1987 Beastie Boys, the 1993 Nirvana and the 1997 cover of the
Notorious B.I.G. The issue also looks back at a decade and a half
of musical history, from metalheads to B-boys.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: Atlanta is the ninth most wired city, according
to Yahoo! ($3.50). San Francisco remains at the top for the third
straight year, followed by Washington; San Jose, Calif.; Austin,
Texas; Seattle; San Diego; Boston and Dallas. ... Of all the roles
Madonna has played, that of mother would seem to be the biggest
stretch. Not so, the star of ``The Next Best Thing'' tells People
($2.99). ``I'm going to be the mother I never had,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
