<HEADER>
A8540 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BRAIN-BOY07-COX     03-06 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAIN-BOY07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH/SCIENCE: Boy, 3, takes on solar system, sentences and
all-around smarts
 &HT;    By Dani Davies
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM CITY, Fla. _ When Shawn Nigam was 6-months-old, he couldn't
sit up by himself but could say words like ``ball'' and ``car.'' At
10-months, he learned the alphabet and five months later, he could
write letters.
</P>
<P>
   By age 2, Shawn was reading and writing approximately 65 words.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the precocious 3-year-old with a 150 IQ _ making him one of
the smartest kids his age in the United States _ has a penchant for
the solar system, computers and new languages.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn's parents, Ravi and Himani Nigam, say they are at a loss
about how to teach him all he wants to know, such as Spanish,
French, Japanese. They speak English and each speaks a different
Indian language, both of which Shawn is learning.
</P>
<P>
   Socially and emotionally, he isn't ready for kindergarten. He is
an active, energetic, affectionate 3-year-old whose mother, like
any other mother of a 3-year-old, often says, ``Shawn, please stop
that.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, his parents appease him with Spanish audio tapes and
computer programs and have set up once-a-week lessons with two
tutors _ one for Spanish, one for English language skills.
</P>
<P>
   On the advice of school officials, his parents had Shawn's IQ
measured in January. At 3 years, 7 months, he landed in the 99th
percentile of children his age with a score of 150.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means that only one percent of the population in the
country in his age group would score higher,'' said Patricia Gage,
the child psychologist who tested Shawn. ``That is considered very
superior. One hundred-sixty is the highest you can get.''
</P>
<P>
   The handsome, bespectacled boy appeared on television twice in
February _ once on the CBS Early Show with Bryant Gumbel and once
on a local news program _ displaying his knowledge of the solar
system, world geography and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   The Nigams hoped the media attention would attract experts to
advise them of the best educational path for Shawn. For now, he
attends preschool in the mornings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always felt that children should play and enjoy
childhood,'' Ravi Nigam said. ``Even now, I don't push him. He
forces us.''
</P>
<P>
   His Spanish tutor, Gladys Velez, has had about six lessons with
Shawn. She uses colorful props, pictures and games to conquer his
3-year-old's attention span.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at his kitchen table, Velez holds up flash cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Como te llamas?'' Shawn reads from a card.
</P>
<P>
   Velez eyes him quizzically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me llamos Shawn,'' he answers.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he glides his feet in blue socks with red cars on them
across the shining kitchen tile as he wiggles and sings Spanish
songs, naming facial features and body parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Una rodilla, dos rodillas,'' the two sing together, first
touching one knee, then both as Shawn puts his smiling face
nose-to-nose with Velez.
</P>
<P>
   In 14 years of teaching elementary Spanish, she hasn't ever met
a student like him. She uses words like ``special'' and ``unusual''
to describe him and shakes her head when she remembers their first
lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in shock, to be honest with you,'' Velez said. ``I say
the word only once with him and he knows it.''
</P>
<P>
   Also intriguing is the fact that Shawn speaks English with a
slight Indian accent but has none when he speaks Spanish, Velez
said. He also uses articles like ``la'' and ``una'' that she hasn't
taught him yet.
</P>
<P>
   Both Velez and former Martin Downs Montessori School teacher
Sana Risedorph marvel at Shawn's ability to read and write long
words and sentences with no misspellings or mispronunciations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you say something, he wants to write it down, words like
automotive or northern hemisphere,'' Risedorph said. ``And he can
write in complete sentences.''
</P>
<P>
   Shawn even liked to spend his playground time writing, Risedorph
said. He would ask other children for words or their names and
write them with chalk on the concrete.
</P>
<P>
   As a baby, Shawn sat up, crawled and walked at the normal times,
but his parents knew his early curiosity with written words was
unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would demand paper and pen,'' Ravi Nigam said.
</P>
<P>
   While other parents toted around games and stuffed animals, the
Nigams carried colored pens and pads of paper to occupy their
toddler.
</P>
<P>
   He had an affinity for anything written and even lugged a heavy
dictionary to preschool to show his friends. He examined the words
on newspapers and books before he could read.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he even ate some newspaper once,'' Himani Nigam
laughed. ``I think that might have been where he got some of his
knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, while Shawn enjoys horseback riding, swimming and an
occasional Barney show, his favorite pasttimes are more cerebral.
</P>
<P>
   He became interested in the solar system _ facts about planets
and moons _ when his father found some pictures of planets in the
garage. More recently, his interest shifted to languages. But he
still sleeps with glow-in-the-dark star and moon pillows.
</P>
<P>
   Gage said in her report that ``his very superior abilities
warrant ... above age level placement and an accelerated
curriculum.''
</P>
<P>
   Himani Nigam agrees. She has visited about six schools and has
yet to make a decision about which would be best.
</P>
<P>
   School officials nationwide are cautious about placing children
who may not be socially ready for classroom settings into
kindergarten, even if they are mentally able. State law prohibits
children who are not 5 or older by Sept. 1 from entering
kindergarten in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``For parents of young children, the biggest problem is keeping
them interested,'' said Peter Rosenstein, executive director of the
National Association for Gifted Children. ``All the research and
studies on the brain show that one of the most crucial times is
from birth to 5. Parents have to make sure that they are
challenged.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the more challenged Shawn is, the more fun he
has.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying my best to do what I can at home, but if it's the
mother teaching, they don't want to learn,'' Himani Nigam said.
``Also, my husband and I haven't done school from this country. We
went to school in India. We want him to learn according to the
system over here.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that she and Ravi, an engineer at Pratt and Whitney,
aren't qualified to teach Shawn English and are concerned about him
picking up their accent.
</P>
<P>
   Gage has no doubt Shawn will be ready for a kindergarten
classroom in the fall when he's 4. By working with tutors, the
length of time he can focus on a task will gradually increase, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The day he was tested, Shawn looked into a box in Gage's office
filled with bracelets and rubber balls. He took out one of each and
said, ``If I put this ring around this ball, I can have Saturn.''
</P>
<P>
   Undeniably, Gage said, ``he is not your typical 3-year-old.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
