<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-PRICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUEL PRICES TO PEAK IN SUMMER BUT EVENTUALLY DROP, AGENCY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gasoline prices will continue to rise sharply,
hitting an average of $1.56 a gallon in the peak summer driving
season, but they will come down by this time next year, the Energy
Department predicted Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Because worldwide crude oil supplies are so low, a steep
increase in gasoline costs is unavoidable in the near future even
if oil-producing countries agree soon to significantly increase
production, the department's Energy Information Administration
said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said that the average price for a gallon of regular
unleaded gasoline, now about $1.35, would ``surge to unprecedented
levels before the spring is out'' and that motorists would pay an
average of 35 cents more a gallon from April through September than
they did in the period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But while the prices will probably set records in purely
numerical terms, they will still be 40 percent lower when adjusted
for inflation than they were at their all-time high, in March 1981,
the energy information office said. And they will be 16 percent
lower when adjusted for inflation than they were late in 1990,
during the Persian Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   As further consolation, an Energy Department analyst predicted
that there would be no long lines at gasoline stations, as there
were two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting the season with relatively low supplies,'' said
Dave Costello, an economist with the energy information agency.
``Meeting the demand _ which will happen _ will be attended by
relatively high prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the energy information office foresaw a return by this
time next year to today's gasoline prices as oil countries continue
to produce enough to bolster supplies once again.
</P>
<P>
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries is scheduled
to meet on March 27 to decide whether to increase production to
offset a shortage that now stands at more than 2 million barrels a
day. But even if OPEC decides to raise its production drastically,
and soon _ say, by 2 million barrels a day _ there is little chance
that enough crude oil can get to refiners in time to stave off
higher prices for summer vacationers in the United States, the
energy office said.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department report is full of caveats that are
intriguing to those who follow the economics and politics of oil.
In California, where clean-air rules make gasoline more expensive,
prices could approach $2 a gallon. Taxes also vary considerably
from state to state.
</P>
<P>
   The department said that heating oil prices, which hit $2 a
gallon or more in the oil-dependent Northeast this winter, were
already coming down as warm weather approaches and should be lower
next winter. So, presumably, will diesel fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson told Congress last week that he
thought oil production would go up, and that there was no need,
therefore, for the government to tap its 600-million-barrel
Strategic Petroleum Reserve in Louisiana and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But Richardson told some skeptical lawmakers that the option was
still ``on the table.'' With the price of crude oil at $32 a
barrel, three times what it was a year ago, the administration
could face renewed pressure to use the reserves. In New York, crude
oil rose 67 cents, or 2.1 percent, to $32.18 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving itself plenty of leeway, the energy information office
said it expected crude oil prices to be $22 to $28 a barrel by the
end of this year and $19 to $26 a barrel by the end of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   For now, analysts expect oil production to increase. Saudi
Arabia, Venezuela, Kuwait and Mexico, which is not an OPEC member,
have signaled a willingness to increase production.
</P>
<P>
   But there is good reason for caution in predicting oil trends.
OPEC has historically had trouble keeping discipline among its
members, partly because some members, like Iran, Iraq and Kuwait,
have been enemies on the battlefield. Another war in the Middle
East could dash all predictions.
</P>
<P>
   One prediction seems safe: American drivers will grumble over
higher gasoline prices, forgetting that not many months ago they
were extraordinarily low. The same amount of gasoline that cost $10
in 1984 cost only $10.19 in July 1999, according to the Consumer
Price Index, while the cost of most other goods and services went
up 60 percent over those 15 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
