<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8542 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SPOLETO-SCFLAG07-COX     03-06 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOLETO-SCFLAG07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dancer withdraws from Spoleto lineup over the S.C. flag issue
 &HT;    By Tom Sabulis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spoleto Festival USA in Charleston, S.C., the Southeast's
premier arts event, has suddenly lost one prominent artist to an
economic boycott directed by the NAACP. Festival leaders want the
exodus to stop there.
</P>
<P>
   They're hoping that Spoleto's multicultural tradition, and its
public support for the removal of the Confederate battle flag from
above the state Capitol, can keep arts lovers on track to this
year's $6.2 million event, running May 26-June 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be more than a bit unfortunate if audiences stayed
away in droves,'' said Eric Friberg of Atlanta, a Spoleto board
member who also leads the boards of the Atlanta Opera and the High
Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spoleto has done many things over the years to introduce
African-American art and culture into the festival,'' Friberg said.
``We do believe the festival has been tremendously responsible in
bringing together different cultures.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Spoleto's executive committee released a statement
supporting removal of the state's controversial flag. That still
didn't prevent dancer Bill T. Jones from withdrawing his company
from the festival's multidisciplinary lineup. ``It was the only
decision I could make,'' Jones told The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Spoleto's organizers are urging other artists and supporters to
make a statement of a different sort.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Festival strongly believes that the arts have a unique
ability to stimulate debate, draw people together and ultimately to
change them in ways that nothing else can,'' the Spoleto dispatch
read.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's a cause for great concern,'' said festival
director Nigel Redden from Paris on Monday. ``I strongly feel that
the best way for artists to deal with an issue is to speak out, by
performing, and not be silent.'' Because of the boycott, some
subscribers have written letters saying they cannot attend this
year's performances. Yet marketing director Marie Lawson
acknowledged Monday that ticket sales through January showed an
increase of 16 percent over last year, when 72,536 tickets were
dispensed.
</P>
<P>
   For many, attendance at this year's festival clearly involves a
moral decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the African-American community in Charleston feels
they can continue to support the festival as local people
supporting something local,'' Redden said. ``But they've all said
they would have a difficult time inviting friends to come to South
Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, no other arts groups have withdrawn from the lineup.
Dwight C. James, executive director of the NAACP branches in South
Carolina, said he plans to call all artists on the schedule, urging
them to back out. As of Monday, he had reached only
</P>
<P>
   ``20 percent'' of them.
</P>
<P>
   Redden wouldn't speculate on chances that the flag could be
removed from the Capitol by June 1, when the state legislative
session is expected to end.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Campbell, an African-American retiree who helps Spoleto
build audiences, said it's too soon to tell what will happen.
``There's still a chance this (boycott) could have a chilling
effect.''
</P>
<P>
   On the web: http://www.spoletousa.org
</P>
<P>
   Tom Sabulis writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
