<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8545 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BASS-OKEECHOBEE07-COX     03-06 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASS-OKEECHOBEE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bill seeks millions for lake cleanup
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ After a quarter-century of watching Lake
Okeechobee on television, Bruce Shupp finally got to visit the
fabled bass-fishing haven in January.
</P>
<P>
   His verdict: ``That's pretty ugly-looking water,'' said Shupp,
national conservation director of the Bass Anglers Sportsman
Society, the nation's largest bass fishing organization.
</P>
<P>
   He was astounded by the water's pollution-fed murk, and the loss
of the fish-nurturing grasses along the lake's shore. The fishing
was better than in your average lake, he said, ``but it's been a
lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   And by the looks of things, Shupp said, ``nobody was doing
anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   That will change this year, vow some state lawmakers, who want
to spend $38 million to begin a 15-year cleanup to stop fertilizer
and manure from flowing into the lake and scrape polluted muck from
its bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The cost eventually could exceed $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, sponsored by House Budget Chairman Ken Pruitt (R-Port
St. Lucie) is likely to be one of the most closely watched
environmental initiatives in the legislative session that begins
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators also will rule on Gov. Jeb Bush's $2.3 billion
proposal for financing the state's share of restoring the
Everglades, and battles over property rights, growth and ownership
of publicly owned streams and riverbeds.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists question whether the Lake Okeechobee bill
will share the fate of earlier legislative promises.
</P>
<P>
   They especially remember the Surface Water Improvement and
Management Act, or SWIM. That 1987 law never fulfilled hopes of
rescuing the lake, and legislators eventually lost interest in
spending money on it. In the past two years, they spurned South
Florida water managers' requests for money to keep the cleanup
rolling.
</P>
<P>
   Some environmentalists fear that Pruitt's bill may turn out to
be ``Son of SWIM'' _ undermined by a lack of money and lax
pollution limits.
</P>
<P>
   Pruitt vows that it won't. He said he aims to devote so much
money to the cleanup that future legislators will feel bound to
continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Action is contagious,'' said Pruitt, who is in his final year
in the House and faces a race for the state Senate this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The alternative is not good _ a dead lake.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides worries about the money, environmentalists want speedier
deadlines and stricter curbs on pollution from citrus groves, dairy
farms and cattle ranches.
</P>
<P>
   They also want to ban the practice of allowing landowners north
of the lake to import sewage sludge and chicken manure for
nourishing their fields. Pruitt's bill would merely limit those
practices.
</P>
<P>
   Some environmentalists also object to the continued role that
the bill would give to the state Department of Agriculture, which
would work with South Florida water managers and the state
Department of Environmental Protection in setting rules around the
lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Department of Agriculture should concern itself with
growing oranges,'' said West Palm Beach lake activist Wayne Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   But Okeechobee rancher Frank ``Sonny'' Williamson said farmers
want to save the lake as much as anyone does.
</P>
<P>
   ``A landowners' general response on this is, `I will do
everything I can short of committing economic suicide,''' said
Williamson, a former water manager.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the ranchers and farmers can't afford to meet the
pollution limits that some environmentalists are demanding.
</P>
<P>
   Pruitt's bill, largely following the advice of water managers
and other agencies, would pattern the lake's cleanup after the $763
million pollution removal under way just north of the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, engineers may plow 60 square miles of farms and
pasture into pollution-filtering marshes and reservoirs north of
the lake. Those structures would cleanse the algae-feeding runoff
from fertilizer and manure.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, water managers would test methods for vacuuming 300
square miles of manure-tainted muck from the lake's bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers and ranchers would reduce their own pollution, perhaps
by buying and selling the legal right to pollute.
</P>
<P>
   Pruitt's bill sets more modest goals for the next four years:
Water managers and the state would have four years to dig some
marshes, conduct some studies and devise a plan for finishing the
job.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Everglades cleanup, which relies mostly on special
taxes levied against property owners and sugar farmers, Pruitt's
bill would draw its money from the state's general tax revenue.
That would avoid any no-new-taxes battles _ but it also would deny
the lake cleanup a guaranteed, year-in-year-out source of money.
</P>
<P>
   Some money could come from the federal government, since the
lake cleanup would use some of the same reservoirs proposed in a
larger $7.8 billion Everglades restoration plan.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their differences, some environmentalists call Pruitt's
bill a start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a lot more than this, but you eat an elephant one bite
at a time,'' said David Guest, an attorney with the Earthjustice
Legal Defense Fund in Tallahassee. ``We can work with this.''
</P>
<P>
   State agencies already have most of the legal power they need to
fight the pollution, said Paul Gray of the group Audubon of
Florida. ``They mostly need the money to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
