   BOEING-STRIKE (Tukwila, Wash.) _ The chants and placards along
the picket lines outside the Boeing Co.'s huge aircraft plants are
a bit unusual. ``No Nerds, No Birds,'' proclaims one sign. And many
Boeing engineers, most on strike for the first time in their lives,
say they are still stunned at how unified their group has become in
the face of its protest against the jet manufacturer. The
increasingly bitter protest by the Society of Professional
Engineering Employees in Aerospace has mushroomed into one of the
largest strikes by white-collar workers against a private company
in years. For national labor leaders, who have rushed in to help
out the striking engineers, the strike is clearly seen as an
opportunity to make inroads in its hopes to organize a potentially
vast sector of the workforce. By Sam Howe Verhovek. 1,800 words.
