<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8560 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-06 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEDRO ASIDE, WHAT ABOUT JEFF FASSERO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Yeah, yeah, yeah, Pedro pitched Monday.
He wasn't anything special, what with the Luis Alicea home run and
the solid Royce Clayton double and the wild pitch and all. The
whole thing was pretty un-Pedrolike, not that it really mattered.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro is Pedro. He's going to be fine. He's going to win 20-plus
and he's going to win another Cy Young. It is time to move on to
more important matters, such as, what's up with Jeff Fassero?
</P>
<P>
   If the Red Sox really are going to challenge the Yankees, or at
least win a third straight wild card berth, it's the Ramon
Martinezes and Tim Wakefields and, yes, Jeff Fassero who will be
the difference. (Bret Saberhagen? When we see him on the mound,
we'll talk.)
</P>
<P>
   That's why innings three and four were a lot more important to
the Red Sox Monday at Charlotte County Stadium than innings one and
two were. For innings three and four belonged to Fassero, the
37-year-old lefthander who has a chance to be anything from one of
the great offseason pickups in all of baseball to a forgotten
spring training footnote.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is very simple. Was 1999 an aberration, or was it
Fassero's new reality? From 1992, when he broke through with an
8-7, 2.84 year in Montreal, through 1998 (13-12, 3.97), Fassero was
that most valued of baseball commodities, a quality lefthanded
pitcher. From '96 through '98 he averaged 229 innings of dependable
work, peaking with a 16-9, 3.30 1997 season while playing half his
games in the batter-friendly Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was a horror show. He was 4-14 with a horrifying 7.38
ERA in 139 innings. The Mariners happily unloaded him to Texas on
Aug. 27.
</P>
<P>
   He did pitch a little better for the Rangers, but not well
enough that anyone in the Rangers organization saw the need for
staff grievance counseling when he elected to accept a free agent
offer from the Red Sox, who have been searching for a solid lefty
starter to call their own since the departure of Bruce Hurst.
</P>
<P>
   It was a classic Dan Duquette maneuver, given that it involved
(a) a reclamation project and (b) a former Expo. Spicing the plot
was the presence of Red Sox pitching coach Joe Kerrigan, who, the
story goes, had something to do with Fassero's emergence as a good
major league pitcher in his ninth year as a professional.
</P>
<P>
   We got our first look at the 2000 model Fassero Monday. Let's
just say it was not Koufaxian. He went two innings, allowing two
runs (via a Rafael Palmeiro homer), while walking (ugh) three. On
the plus side: Unlike Pedro and Dan Smith, he did not give up a
home run to Alicea. And he deftly picked Gabe Kapler off first
base.
</P>
<P>
   He treated all this as any veteran pitcher would. He gave a
technical treatise. It was all about ``mechanics'' and ``location''
and a couple of pitches ``coming off,'' and ``not flying open,''
and one you don't hear all that often: ``being a little quick with
my head.''
</P>
<P>
   He says that the 1999 disaster really was about fouled-up
mechanics, and that he simply never felt comfortable. Now that he's
been reunited with Kerrigan, everything is going to be hunky-dory.
</P>
<P>
   He's got little choice but to believe that last year was the
athletic equivalent of a bad dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked and disappointed,'' he acknowledges. ``After
eight good years, it was a shock to have a year like that. But I
think I've learned something from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Such as?
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned how this game can jump up and get you,'' he says.
``The game wasn't as easy as I thought. And I learned that when
things go bad they can really snowball.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody in his situation would consider Boston. Fenway
Park still has the capacity to scare people _ particularly
lefthanded pitchers _ and then there's the pressure put on players
by both the intense fandom and the ravenous media. Fassero says he
has little worry about the ballpark, correctly reasoning that for
every cheapo home run there's a line drive single. And as for the
other business, Fassero assures us he's a big boy. ``There's
pressure everywhere,'' he shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   He likes what he's seen thus far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very glad to be a part of this team,'' he says. ``It's a
solid lineup, and it is very well prepared, which is a tribute to
the manager and the coaching staff.''
</P>
<P>
   A somewhat humbled Fassero worked out with more intensity this
winter in an effort to reconstruct his career. He has, he says, a
very reasonable goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to win 15 games,'' he says. ``In this game, that's a
good figure. Aside from that, I have no other personal goals. If I
win 15, everything else will fall into place.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff, baby, if you win 15 games, you'll be pitching in October.
That's a guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 1835EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0351 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8561 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-SHAQ07-COX     03-06 1531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SHAQ07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In Shaq's shadow
 &HT;    By Ethan J. Skolnick
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When you're the slamming, rapping genie
of the NBA, the Shaq Daddy, the only Notorious B.I.G. still living
large, the league becomes your traveling party. And as with most
parties, there is a guest list, those welcome to your bash.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Carter? You mean, the super-soarer Shaquille O'Neal
renamed ``Half Man, Half Amazing''? Of course, and if a strobe
lightbulb breaks, he can leap up and change it. Hakeem Olajuwon?
``The Dream,'' the center O'Neal reveres, and before the 1995 NBA
Finals called ``a class act, a soft-spoken, well-dressed, handsome
guy''? Certainly. Tim Duncan? A little quiet, sure, but didn't
O'Neal just say that ``you don't see too many guys who can go
inside and out. I admire him for that''? A guy with those skills
surely can come inside and snatch a party hat.
</P>
<P>
   Alonzo Mourning? Only as the hat rack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know and don't care,'' says the Miami Heat center, on
why O'Neal, a teammate on the 1994 Dream Team II, has never shown
him respect. ``I don't get involved in that, man. Everybody's
entitled to their own opinion, and he's entitled to his.''
</P>
<P>
   But he must have heard, even if O'Neal tends to speak in a
droning bass mumble.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's 1996 take on Mourning's contract: ``He must have had a
good agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Or this one: ``If you're going to pay 25 grand for a Beemer,
you've got to pay 40 for a Benz, bro, and I'm a Benz, bro.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he's a Shaq Diesel, and he's had more to say on
Mourning. As Mourning, in the past, has had more to say on O'Neal.
Once, when asked about the strength of the 305-pound behemoth,
Mourning said Joe Kleine was stronger.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday the two men faced each other in a regular-season game for
the first time since Jan. 17, 1998. O'Neal had 24 points in that
Lakers win, and Mourning just five, though most of their matchups
have been less lopsided. They were drafted first and second by
Orlando and Charlotte, respectively, in 1992, each the centerpiece
of expansion teams. Now they are separated by the mainland states,
playing in Los Angeles and Miami for the game's two cachet coaches,
Phil Jackson and Pat Riley, men who also are as dissimilar and
distant as men with like jobs and credentials might be.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal and Mourning play the same position. Differently. And
yet, that's all they share.
</P>
<P>
   One has spent many summers mugging on movie or commercial sets,
the other sweating in a Georgetown gym. One cuts rap albums, the
other is only seen crooning when the rare Motown record is played
on the arena speakers. One smiles for effect, the other is known
for his scowl.
</P>
<P>
   And although those characterizations are perhaps too simplistic
_ witness O'Neal's fight with Charles Barkley this year, or all the
grinning Mourning does when he's around children _ they have come
to define the two men in the eyes of the NBA public. One seeking
the spotlight, the other shunning it. One who often has played lazy
defense in the playoffs, the other who plays positional, relentless
defense in charity and All-Star Games.
</P>
<P>
   One clown, one frown.
</P>
<P>
   Simplistic, but it explains everything to the other NBA
superstar that O'Neal thinks of dimly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does Shaq have a good relationship with anybody?'' says San
Antonio Spurs center and noted good guy David Robinson. ``I don't
know. I played with Shaq in the Olympics, and we got along great.
Right after the Olympics, he said something negative about me
again. I think part of it is that it's just a big show for him.
It's like Hollywood. And I think he kind of likes some of that
tension in the media. I don't think there's much to it. I think you
go out and you win the game, and that's what it's all about. I
think Shaq does that a lot, probably, because it reads good in the
papers, it makes it interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   NO CRYING IN BASKETBALL
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there was some back-and-forth in 1995 when Robinson
noted the limitations of O'Neal's game. O'Neal, who was angry about
finishing second to Robinson in the regular-season MVP voting, used
the NBA Finals as a forum to question Robinson's fortitude, by
comparing it to Olajuwon's.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you guys are going to compare me to a great center, I want
to be compared to Hakeem,'' O'Neal said then. ``When I play him, he
doesn't complain. He doesn't cry. He just plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even Robinson acknowledges how far O'Neal has come on the
court, particularly in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really no comparison to playing Shaq,'' Robinson said,
when asked about defending Mourning and O'Neal. ``I don't know that
there's ever been anybody really like him. And I think he's getting
better and better. I think he's learning to use his body a little
bit better, I think he's learning how to manipulate his position in
the post a little bit better. I think Zo in this last two years has
really stepped up his game. His effort and intensity is fantastic,
I think defensively, he's blocking shots, doing a lot of tremendous
things. That's a credit to him. You only get that way by hard work.
But I still think it's not a comparison to Shaq.''
</P>
<P>
   And Mourning won't make one. ``I don't get into measuring
myself,'' he says. ``I let the critics do that.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not a criticism. Mourning's just ... smaller. Much smaller.
Four inches and 50 pounds smaller. He is one of the two best
centers in the game, but he's really an overachieving power
forward.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to keep from being overwhelmed by a man who crowds a
lane like a Hummer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zo will tell you, 'I can't do anything with this guy,''' says
Heat broadcaster and Hall of Fame coach Jack Ramsay. ``Imagine
hearing that from Zo? Zo might be the second strongest man in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Alonzo is not one of the big guys,'' NBC broadcaster and
former center Bill Walton said. ``He's one of the best guys. The
key is to find the way to make the big guy play your game. Dave
Cowens was the absolute master of that. He could take Kareem, he
could take Wilt, and make them play his game. That's what Alonzo
Mourning has to do. Alonzo's power game is not going to work
against Shaq. Pat Riley has done such a great job of diversifying
Alonzo's game. And getting him to play a cerebral game.''
</P>
<P>
   Walton notes Mourning's versatility, quickness and shooting
ability, calling the progress he has made ``fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of players, when they see Shaq, they just
say, 'I want no part of him,''' Walton says. ``They absolutely
disappear, and they come down with Shaqitis. If you are going to
beat the Lakers, you have to come out and make a major
contribution. It may not be the same type of game that you play
against others.''
</P>
<P>
   While Walton thought Mourning was the ``best center in
basketball'' last season, ``Shaq has taken it up this year to a new
level.''
</P>
<P>
   ONE STEP AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   That is how it always is, it seems. Mourning is going to the
Olympics in Sydney this summer ... because O'Neal didn't want to.
Mourning finished ahead of O'Neal in the MVP voting last season ...
but didn't win. O'Neal is a prohibitive favorite to win his first
this time. O'Neal has been to the Finals ... Mourning has not.
O'Neal is better positioned to go again and win.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Mourning is disrespected. He was a runaway choice to
start the All-Star Game against O'Neal. And opponents _ most of
them, anyway _applaud his intensity. ``Zo shows his emotions out
there on the floor,'' said Seattle's Horace Grant, who played with
O'Neal in Orlando but declined to comment on the relationship
between the centers. ``He wears it on his sleeve. You would love to
play with a guy like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still now O'Neal is being lauded for doing what Mourning always
has. The Heat center was the defensive player of the year last
season, and his blocks are up. Just this season, O'Neal decided
this aspect of his game was worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has stepped up his defense, to be a shot-blocker, an
intimidator, a rebounder,'' Ramsay said. ``He's changed his game,
and the result is that the Lakers are much better. They lead the
league in field-goal percentage allowed. That's the whole
difference. He and Kobe (Bryant) defensively, not scoring,
defensively. Because Kobe does it at the outside, and Shaq does it
in the basket area. Shaq denies that. Shaq says he hasn't been
healthy, had this stomach strain, and that's prevented him from
being as active. But I think Phil has put his defensive imprint on
this team.''
</P>
<P>
   SHAQ MAY USE MOVE NO. 299
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Jackson has put his imprint on the tattooed O'Neal, who
has generally spoken of his coaches _ Del Harris, Brian Hill _ in
mocking tones. Now he's the loyal warrior, just like Mourning.
</P>
<P>
   But he is not like Mourning. Nor does he like Mourning.
</P>
<P>
   He was kinder than usual when asked late Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miami's a good team, and Alonzo's a great player,'' O'Neal
says. ``Against a guy like that, you just have to take it to him.
They don't usually double-team me, and I've got 300 moves on each
block, so I'm just going to take it to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
