<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0355 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8568 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-JOHNSON-NYT &LR;      03-06 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-JOHNSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS THINK THE UNTHINKABLE: TRADING KEYSHAWN JOHNSON 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Jets have been talking to other teams
about trading their best player, Keyshawn Johnson _ one of the
National Football League's top wide receivers _ in a deal that, at
first glance, seems unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   But that is exactly what Jets' officials have been doing,
according to several NFL officials. The talks have occurred mainly
with the Baltimore Ravens; the Jets have offered Johnson to
Baltimore in exchange for the Ravens' fifth overall pick in the
April draft, the NFL executives say.
</P>
<P>
   A team executive said the Ravens were ``serious, very serious''
about a possible trade, as were the Jets. The Ravens are interested
in the deal only if they can create the salary cap room that would
be needed to sign Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Why would the Jets want to trade Johnson, who is one of the top
five wide receivers in the game? His six-year contract does not
expire until the end of next year, and Johnson believes he is no
longer being paid market value as a top-flight receiver. The Jets
are concerned that they may not be able to re-sign Johnson once his
contract ends, and trading him now would give the team more value
for Johnson than if the Jets simply lost him to free agency at the
end of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   If the Jets were able to trade for Baltimore's fifth pick, the
team would be in position to make several possible moves. The Jets
already own two first-round picks, and league executives speculated
that the Jets might combine either their 16th or 18th selection in
the first round with the No. 5 pick, and entice either Washington
or Cincinnati to switch with them. Washington has the second and
third picks and Cincinnati has the fourth slot.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Jets might have a shot at drafting Penn State pass
rusher Courtney Brown, who some personnel men believe could be the
next Bruce Smith. If Cleveland takes Brown with the first overall
pick, then the Jets could still be in position to snag Penn State
linebacker LeVar Arrington.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, with the Jets still holding their remaining
first-round selection, the team could draft a wide receiver to
replace Johnson. This draft is particularly deep at the position,
and one of the players the Jets like is Michigan State's Plaxico
Burress who, like Johnson, is a big, athletic player.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets might even use their second first-round selection, in
combination with other picks, to try to move into the top ten to
get Burress. Or they could remain at the 18th spot and still get a
good wide receiver. Other possibilities include Sylvester Morris
from Jackson State and Dez White from Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets and Ravens have been talking for at least a week, and
Johnson's name was not brought up in passing, the NFL executives
said. The Ravens consider the talks so serious that Baltimore owner
Art Modell is seeking ways to pay for what would be a pricey new
contract for Johnson, the executives said. When Johnson's current
deal expires in two years, he could become the highest paid
receiver in football.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a number of calls from teams about our fifth pick,
including the New York Jets,'' Modell said. ``Beyond that, I cannot
comment. All I can say is we are trying to improve our team.''
</P>
<P>
   The talks over Johnson could fall apart at any time, of course.
The Ravens may decide they want to keep the fifth pick, and the
Jets may determine that giving up Johnson is too steep a price. The
possibility exists _ though it is a tiny one _ that the Jets could
part from their longstanding policy of not renegotiating a contract
when it has more than one year remaining on it and redo their star
receiver's deal.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the chance, however remote, that the Jets
purposely initiated trade talks, hoping they would leak to the
public, and get to Johnson, thus rattling him. The Jets might be
hoping that Johnson, faced with the possibility of playing in
Baltimore or an even less desirable city, might be more patient
about renegotiating his current contract.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Parcells, the Jets' director of football operations, did
not return phone calls. Johnson could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   There are few players who have a better work ethic than Johnson
or who can put so much fear in a defense. At times throughout his
career, he has been unstoppable. Trading such a player is always
risky. There is the possibility that the Jets may not find a
receiver of his quality for years.
</P>
<P>
   But the team is apparently concerned about Johnson's contract
situation. He originally signed a six-year, $15 million contract
that included a $6.5 million signing bonus. His deal runs through
2001, with an average salary of $2.5 million a year, including the
bonus. That is way below market for a player of Johnson's caliber.
In fact, his $1.74 million base salary for 2000 ranks him 20th
among wide receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is irritated that wide receiver Joey Galloway recently
signed a seven-year, $42 million contract. Galloway's $12.5 million
signing bonus is more than Johnson has earned his entire career.
Galloway has 283 career catches for 4,457 yards and 37 touchdowns
and Johnson has 305 catches for 4,108 yards and 31 touchdowns. In
other words, the numbers are very close, and Johnson has been to
two Pro Bowls while Galloway has been to none.
</P>
<P>
   Thus Johnson, according to people close to him, feels he is not
earning his fair market value. He has said privately that he might
consider holding out next season.
</P>
<P>
   So the biggest reason the Jets have explored trading Johnson is
because the team expects a bitter, and possibly impassable,
contract fight. Especially considering that the team has a rocky
relationship with Johnson's agent, Jerome Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to talk about his contract situation, at all,''
said Stanley. ``As for any trade talks, I can't comment on
speculation or rumors.''
</P>
<P>
   The danger for the Jets is that if the trade does not go
through, they risk angering Johnson, leaving them with a bitter
star player on their roster for next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all speculation,'' Stanley said. ``No one knows what
Keyshawn would think if this were true.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
