<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8570 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-MISSROSE07-COX     03-06 1970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSROSE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Life after Robert: A millionairess and a maid recall a man they
both loved
 &HT;    By Michael Browning
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Robert Horne's life contained cashmere
and collard greens, diamonds and black-eyed peas.
</P>
<P>
   He was at home in one of the most sumptuous palaces of Palm
Beach, the Via Mizner, and he lived in a modest, foursquare house
with a screened porch on 11th Court, off Australian Avenue. He
drove a shiny Oldsmobile to work _ and an even shinier 1959
Rolls-Royce at work. He handled tens of thousands of dollars in
rent receipts from shops on Worth Avenue, and he was treasurer and
honorary deacon at the Friendship Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   He never lost his way, nor misplaced a penny, in either world.
People who knew him say Robert Horne did the impossible: He bridged
the enormous economic divide between Palm Beach and West Palm
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   When he died of lung cancer nearly two years ago, he bereaved
two women. He was faithful to both to the very end of his life.
</P>
<P>
   One woman was his wife, Missy Horne, who treasures his memory
still. She's in her 60s. ``I don't lie about my age, but I don't
advertise it either,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The other is Rose Sachs, 87, one of Palm Beach's best-known
socialites, whose 40-year relationship with ``my Robert'' bears an
uncanny resemblance to the 1989 movie ``Driving Miss Daisy,'' in
which a black man and a wealthy white woman gradually come to
discover a shared humanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true,'' said Missy Horne. ``Whenever they pulled up in
the Rolls-Royce at the Palm Beach Airport, all the porters would
shout, `Here comes Robert! Driving Miss Daisy!'''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right,'' giggled Rose Sachs. ``They called me `Miss
Daisy.' I would ride up in the front seat with Robert, because we
had so much to talk about. There were people who thought that was
improper, but I didn't care. I loved Robert.''
</P>
<P>
   The two women hug each other and smile, in the lush, flowery
garden of the $350-a-night Brazilian Court Hotel on Palm Beach.
Rose Sachs wears a glittering necklace of topazes and a massive,
glittering gold bracelet that was a gift from her husband,
Mortimer, over half a century ago. Missy Horne wears a simple,
silver letter `M' on a thin chain.
</P>
<P>
   They are two Southern farm girls, who grew up to lead lives as
far removed from each other as the wide leap of the Intracoastal
Waterway allows. Missy Horne is from Sylvester, Ga. Rose Sachs is
from Memphis, Tenn. Both were poor, both from big families. Neither
made it past grade school: Missy to the fifth-grade, Rose to the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   But today, Rose Sachs wears Tita Rossi evening gowns while Missy
Horne, until a week or two ago, wore a maid's apron to work.
</P>
<P>
   Rose married a man who became very rich: Mortimer Sachs of Long
Island, the king of Worth Avenue, Palm Beach's ``Mink Mile,'' where
he eventually owned 20 rental properties and another 30 scattered
over the island. She spends the season in Palm Beach and the rest
of the year in a pied-a-terre at the Sherry Netherlands Residential
Hotel on Fifth Avenue in New York. She sold her apartment in Monte
Carlo some years back.
</P>
<P>
   Missy married Robert Horne, the son of an Eufaula, Ala., farmer,
a man who was rich in spirit alone. She goes to Moultrie, Ga., each
year for family reunions. She has never been to Monte Carlo, but
she does remember being taken to dinner by Mortimer Sachs once,
``to some restaurant where we couldn't read the menu, it wasn't in
English.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had two cents when I was a little girl, I thought I was a
millionaire,'' said Rose, who is a millionairess many times over
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born in the country, the youngest of 10 children. I grew
up with chickens and cows. My father ran a little country store,
and my mother died when I was 13. After that all I knew was work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very poor. You won't believe this, but lunch was often
a can of creamed corn, mixed with cow's milk, and dinner might be a
can of peas, mixed with cow's milk.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose married, had a son, but left her husband within a year. She
doesn't go into details. ``I walked out of that house with a baby
in my arms and left everything behind,'' she says. She went to stay
with her brother in Teaneck, N.J., and met Mortimer Sachs at his
New York business, Paris Style Leather, which manufactured ladies'
purses. Sachs, a Columbia University graduate who taught political
economy before going into business with his father, was smitten
with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me if I liked to dance. Well, all Southern girls like
to dance. He asked me to marry him, and I said yes. We were married
50 years. The happiest day in my life was the day I met my husband,
and the saddest was the day he died. We not only loved each other,
we liked each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Missy Horne met her Robert in 1953 in church, one year after she
came to Palm Beach County from Georgia. She liked him the minute
she saw him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a young church man. He didn't drink, didn't gamble.''
They married in 1954, ``and he never let me buy so much as a loaf
of bread. He said: `Your money is your money.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mortimer and Rose Sachs first came to Palm Beach in 1941. ``Land
was cheap as dirt. We started buying up Worth Avenue. They were
just giving it away. We were the first young people to come in
here. We worked like mules.''
</P>
<P>
   Worth Avenue got its name in 1913 when the directors of the Palm
Beach Improvement Co. decided to memorialize Col. William Jenkins
Worth, a hero of the Second Seminole War. But the money to make it
the glittering shopping mecca it is today came out of Sachs'
handbag business in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secret of success is hard work, common sense _ and it
doesn't hurt to have a Southern accent, for charm,'' Rose Sachs
said.
</P>
<P>
   But she and Mortimer had one more hidden advantage. They had
Robert Horne.
</P>
<P>
   Unobtrusive, unassuming, yet indispensable, Robert Horne devoted
most of his life to Rose and Mortimer Sachs. He, more than money,
was their living link to Florida. His quiet competence freed them
to concentrate on business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We liked each other immediately because we were both from the
South,'' Rose said. ``He was such an elegant gentleman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He began to work for us in 1959, and he was with us nearly 40
years. I guess you would call him a major-domo. He ran our house,
the Via Mizner. He drove the Rolls-Royce. He could fix anything. He
made me coffee in the morning. There wasn't anything Robert
couldn't do.''
</P>
<P>
   Missy Horne nodded. ``Everybody was crazy about Robert,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert worked for us year 'round, even when we weren't here.
He was part of our family,'' Sachs recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took the responsibility. He was a good man,'' Missy Horne
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean! He was honest as the day is long,'' Sachs exclaimed.
``We would let him hold the rent receipts and checks for thousands
of dollars, and when we got down from New York, there they'd be,
not a penny short.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were married 44 good years,'' Missy Horne said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still can't get over how they called me `Miss Daisy'
whenever I was out with Robert,'' Rose Sachs said. ``It was the
funniest thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's true. They did,'' Missy Horne said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was a compliment. It meant we had a beautiful
relationship. He had a world of common sense, Robert did,'' Rose
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did,'' Missy agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will you stay for lunch?'' Rose asked Missy.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, ma'am. I'm sorry. I can't. I've got to be at work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, what a shame! Well, it was so nice to see you again!''
</P>
<P>
   ``You too.''
</P>
<P>
   Sachs orders lunch: a chicken breast sandwich, a glass of ice
water without ice and some decaffeinated coffee with NutraSweet.
Crotons and palms bloom beside the outdoor table at the Brazilian
Court Hotel, where she has a corner suite of rooms, and
white-uniformed waiters with soft Spanish accents hover and flutter
around her, expertly.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Mortimer died 18 years ago. I've tried to look after
Robert's family since then,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mortimer Sachs drew up a will in July 1982, three months before
he died of emphysema, in which he gave all his tangible property to
Rose. He gave $10,000 to St. Edward's Catholic Church, $5,000
apiece to two other servants, Elizabeth Dykes and Walter Span.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give and devise to Robert Horne, if he shall be employed by
me at the time of my death, the sum of twenty-five thousand
dollars,'' Sachs wrote. The $25,000 bequest was paid, Missy Horne
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mister Sachs was crazy about Robert,'' she said later, after
work, at her home on 11th Court. ``Not a holiday came, but he gave
him a big check: $3,000 for Christmas, $1,000 for Easter, $1,000
for Thanksgiving. He bought Robert two new cars, Oldsmobiles. New,
paid for, in the driveway. Brand new!
</P>
<P>
   ``He also gave us stock advice. He'd say: `Buy some of that,'
or, `No, don't put your money there, that's no good.'
</P>
<P>
   ``In return, Robert worked his heart out for them. A lot of
times he'd be over there at 8 o'clock in the morning and he
wouldn't get back until after midnight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to have them over here for dinner,'' Missy Horne said.
``Mr. Sachs loved stuffed cabbage, fried chicken, baked sweet
potatoes... Good Southern food. I even brought him some fried
chicken when he was in the hospital. Mr. Sachs was a nice man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Sachs died in 1982, and it was a funny thing, Robert's dog
died that day, too. Ate one of those big poisonous toads and
died.''
</P>
<P>
   After her husband's death, Rose Sachs sold his holdings on Worth
Avenue for large sums. The 1928 Via Mizner went for $11.9 million
in September 1985. Another property, 200 Worth Avenue, was sold to
Ferragamo for $7.75 million. Rose donated $1 million to Palm Beach
Atlantic College in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept the business up for three years after he died. Then I
asked myself, `Why are you doing this?' So I got rid of the
properties one by one and moved out of Via Mizner and got an
apartment in the Breakers II.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived there 14 years, and Robert stayed with me right along.
I could no more think of having anyone else than the man in the
moon. Then Robert said to me one day when he was bringing me my
breakfast on a tray, `I think I might be retiring.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `You are like family to me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And he said, `I know.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And so I kept him on another two years, even though he
couldn't do much. Then he retired and then he died, and I moved
here to the Brazilian Court two years ago. I'm having a lot of fun.
I go to parties every night. I entertain a lot. I don't go
backwards. I'm an optimist. What can you do about yesterday? I'm a
tomorrow person.''
</P>
<P>
   Missy Horne is a Sunday person. An old, well-thumbed Bible sits
on the sofa on the screened front porch of her green and white
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where I sit and read my Bible,'' she said. ``I'm a
quiet person. I don't watch much TV, just go to church every
Sunday. That's my highlight. Robert was the one who loved to watch
TV: football, baseball, basketball. He loved fishing, and he loved
to play checkers. He was a checker player.
</P>
<P>
   She worked for Rose and Mortimer Sachs, too, for 13 years, until
an illness compelled her to leave. Since Robert died, aged 69, on
Aug. 1, 1998, the two women have drifted apart, each to her side of
the Intracoastal. Missy Horne lays flowers on Robert's grave at
Royal Palm Cemetery and raises collards in her back yard, in his
memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert loved his greens. He could grow anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither widow plans to remarry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already had the best husband a woman could have,'' Rose
Sachs said. ``Why would I want another?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Marry again? No, sir. Not after Robert,'' Missy Horne said.
``Robert was one in a million.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
