<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SECRET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEX AND SPYING ALL OVER, NONE OF IT SPELLED OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes appear at end of review. Time and channel
are for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(DW) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Suppose someone took a fancy-shmancy pornographic
movie and edited out everything that cannot be shown on broadcast
television. Without the naughty bits, you'd be left with confusing
scenes of people looking vaguely hungry and speaking in monotones.
But what's the point? It would be like a car without the engine,
like a sundae without the ice cream. It would be like ``Secret
Agent Man.''
</P>
<P>
   This series with a familiar name, beginning Tuesday night on the
UPN network, is a heavy-breathing but lightweight spy tale with
only one thing on its mind. Which it cannot show. Like a
hormone-tortured teen-ager, it sublimates its frustration in
attempts at clever sex talk. The double-entendres are as thinly
veiled as some of the women on display. But there's no payoff.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of all the panting is a hunk named Monk, who works
for an unnamed international agency that somehow protects the
world. As played by Costas Mandylor, who used to be the droopy-eyed
cop on ``Picket Fences,'' Monk is no James Bond. Heck, he's no
Austin Powers.
</P>
<P>
   When first encountered, he is at some kind of mountain inn with
a tall, busty blonde in a small, slinky dress. He's teaching her to
play pool by the embrace-the-student method. ``Nice, long, smooth
stroke,'' he purrs.
</P>
<P>
   Monk's weekend is upended, however, by the arrival of Prima
(Musetta Vander), an operative for a rival spy agency and the love
of his life. He introduces her to the blonde as someone he ``works
with, or against sometimes.'' Prima amplifies, ``Against one
another in the biblical sense, if you know what I mean.''
</P>
<P>
   Prima's desire to defect to Monk's side puts her at odds with a
criminal mastermind called Vargas, played by Jesus Garcia in a
jumpy impersonation of Ricky Martin that is the only crumb of wit
in this hour. Vargas is holding the world hostage with a secret
weapon called an EMP. (That name, like most of what goes on here,
is never explained.)
</P>
<P>
   Monk is in grave danger, which causes anguish for his lovely
partner, Holiday (Dina Meyer), who of course is madly in love with
him. Holiday's seriousness is indicated by the folded-up eyeglasses
she hangs from her plunging necklines. She and another agent, Davis
(Dondre T. Whitfield), scurry around trying to save Monk's life. At
one point Monk and Holiday rendezvous in a dressing room at a kinky
lingerie shop where she is trying on something with feathers. Or is
that fur?
</P>
<P>
   About that familiar name: In the mid-'60s CBS ran a series
starring Patrick McGoohan called ``Secret Agent.'' It had a catchy
theme, ``Secret Agent Man'' by Phil Sloan and Steve Barri, which
this new series recycles.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's a tip-off that this is supposed to be ironic
nostalgia (or nostalgic irony). Otherwise why is this show being so
smarmily coy in an era when most viewers can switch to a cable
channel and find sex dealt with in a more frank (and occasionally
more mature) manner?
</P>
<P>
   Two of the executive producers of ``Secret Agent Man,'' Barry
Sonnenfeld and Barry Josephson, boast credits including the clever
film ``Men in Black.'' Maybe if you use a lot of imagination, you
can see the kind of clever television show they were aiming at. But
with just a little imagination you can find a better way to kill an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL; 
`SECRET AGENT MAN'  &QL; 
At 8p.m. ET Tuesday on UPN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barry Sonnenfeld, Barry Josephson and Michael Duggan, executive
producers; Richard Heus, co-executive producer; Flody Suarez, Brent
Friedman and Joel Fields, producers; written by Chris Dickie based
on a story by Alan Eisendtock and Larry Mintz; directed by Perry
Lang. A production of Sonnenfeld Josephson Worldwide Entertainment
in association with Columbia TriStar Television. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Costas Mandylor (Monk), Dina Meyer (Holiday), Dondre T.
Whitfield (Davis), Musetta Vander (Prima) and Jesus Garcia
(Vargas). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
