<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Julia Roberts No. 1 on Forbes celebrity list
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Movie producer Georgia Lucas (``Star Wars'') made the
most money last year and retired NBA star Michael Jordan attracted
the most Web hits on the Internet. But actress Julia Roberts, a
Smyrna, Ga., native, earned the top spot on Forbes' (March 20)
latest Celebrity 100 ranking, a list of the richest and most
powerful celebrities in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The ranking is based on the combination of income and media
coverage, including the number of cover stories in magazines, press
clips and TV/radio coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Roberts in the top 10 are Lucas, Oprah Winfrey, Tom
Hanks, Jordan, the Rolling Stones, Tiger Woods, Backstreet Boys,
Cher and Steven Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes devoted its cover to singer Britney Spears, whose debut
album sold 11 million copies last year in the United States, mostly
in the teen market.
</P>
<P>
   WAS GREENSPAN TOO LATE?
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan usually gets the highest
marks for his economic policy, but Business Week (March 13) detects
``growing murmurs of concern'' about his approach. Critics fear the
Fed waited too late to raise interest rates in its attempt to fight
inflation and now risks pushing the economy into recession.
</P>
<P>
   ``With gross domestic product rising at an astonishing annual
rate of 6.9 percent in the fourth quarter of 1999, the worry on
Wall Street _ and among a few anti-inflation hawks at the Fed _ is
that Greenspan allowed the unemployment rate to fall too low, the
stock market to rise too high and too much liquidity to slosh
around the system,'' the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   According to this argument, Greenspan will have to generate a
``growth recession'' _ a situation where the economy grows about 2
percent per year, but job growth slows enough to take the heat off
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   MILLIONAIRE IN THE MIRROR
</P>
<P>
   The next millionaire could be the person staring back at you
from the mirror, says Kiplinger's Personal Finance (March).
</P>
<P>
   ``A growing number of Americans are entering the winner's circle
the old-fashioned way: by working hard to develop, and possibly
sell, a business, or by investing steadily and astutely,'' the
magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   But would you know how to handle it? Lots of people don't.
Wealth brings new tax consequences, different implications for the
kids, and for some people an inability to stop worrying about money
once they've got it. At least you won't be alone: About 9 million
U.S. households have assets of $1 million or more.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Fast Company (March) says new companies are not built to last
these days, but ``built to flip,'' or to be sold or merged out of
existence as soon as the founders make a fortune. This phenomenon
threatens to ``kill the soul of the new economy.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Most people work, but the details of work _ or a career _ are
usually absent from most contemporary fiction, Fortune (March 13)
reports. The last time writers dealt with work in detail was the
industrial era between the 1880s and 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
