A8577 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-BLACK-FARMERS07-COX     03-06 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-FARMERS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BLACK FARMERS ARRESTED IN USDA PROTEST
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a spirited protest outside the U.S. Department
of Agriculture, 10 black farmers were arrested Monday while about
30 others waved signs and chanted ``no farmers, no food, no
justice, no peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The farmers, mostly from the South, are angry about the
department's handling of a racial discrimination lawsuit settled
out of court last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is getting paid but the farmers,'' said Eddie
Slaughter from Buena Vista, Ga. ``They settled out of court to deny
us access to the justice system.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, farmers do not get automatic compensation
for their claims Those with few records of their dealings with the
USDA can seek to qualify for $50,000 payments, along with tax and
debt relief. Farmers with more complete records and detailed damage
claims may go before an independent arbitrator.
</P>
<P>
   The protesting farmers said they had many grievances about the
process. They said USDA has not fired employees guilty of
discrimination and that it has denied debt relief to many
plaintiffs. They said they want the USDA to stop foreclosures until
all settlements are finished and to stop relying on local loan
officers for decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very people who discriminated against us control who gets
paid,'' said Tom Burrell of Covington, Tenn. ``Does that make
sense?''
</P>
<P>
   So far, 60 percent of the 10,540 reviewed cases have been
decided in favor of farmers, said Charles Rawls, USDA general
counsel. More than 4,000 have been denied.
</P>
<P>
   Rawls said the process is working, and that as part of the
settlement, USDA lowered the standard of evidence so that more
farmers would get compensation.
</P>
<P>
   The total case load _ about 20,000 cases _ should be reviewed by
late May, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, approved by a federal judge last April, ended a
class-action lawsuit that accused the USDA of regularly denying
black farmers loans for equipment and other necessary items to
yield crops.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's protest, the latest of several against the USDA, began
on the street outside the department with the farmers demanding to
speak to Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman, who was out of town.
They carried white signs with angry statements such as ``lawsuit
becomes death trap for black farmers.''
</P>
<P>
   They also waved three large American flags _ one upside down.
</P>
<P>
   As some of the protestors walked arm-in-arm to the entrance of
the building, about a dozen police officers moved in. After a brief
sit-in at the steps by the door, the men were arrested, several of
them chanting ``Dan Glickman'' very slowly and in a deep voice.
</P>
<P>
   Susan McAvoy, a USDA spokesperson, said the protesting farmers
were invited to speak with department officials but did not accept.
She declined to comment further about the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 men arrested at the protest were charged with
incommoding, which means they failed to obey a police order. The
charge carries a $50 fine, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Eunice Moscoso's e-mail address is eunicem(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
