<SLUG> BC-TV-SECRET-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `SECRET' UPN SHOULD HAVE KEPT TO ITSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the best thing about a new show is an old song, well, maybe
we're not talking instant Emmys.
</P>
<P>
   But here it is, the ancient theme song from ``Secret Agent'' in
1965. The Johnny Rivers version _ somehow I always heard it as
``Secret Asian Man'' _ leaped as high as No. 3 on the charts back
then.
</P>
<P>
   For UPN's new ``Secret Agent Man,'' which has no other
connection to ``Secret Agent,'' the song has been recovered from
karaoke heaven. It's been rerecorded by a group called the Supreme
Beings of Leisure, but that's probably more than most people care
to know.
</P>
<P>
   Costas Mandylor (``Picket Fences''), who seems more equal than
his co-stars Dina Meyer (``Starship Troopers'') and Dondre T.
Whitfield (``Between Brothers''), might have been found in Sly
Stallone heaven. Though he's shown a taste for comedic drama in the
past, Mandylor is burly and built to order for the heavy lifting of
an action show.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, Barry Sonnenfeld (``Men in Black'') and his
co-producers see Mandylor's character, Monk, as more than muscular
material. They think he can chuck the big, lovable lug stuff and
play debonair.
</P>
<P>
   He's first glimpsed in total James Bond guise _ suave man of the
world, mouthing puns as he entertains a blond playmate in a low-cut
gown. They're playing pool, but mostly just bending over the table
and amusing each other about what they'll be playing next.
</P>
<P>
   If you know your movie rules, the hero must now be interrupted
by business. ``Secret Agent Man'' hardly has the wherewithal to
make an exception. The cueballitus interruptus comes in the form of
another beauty, a brunette named Prima (guest star Musetta Vander).
</P>
<P>
   Prima has been working for an evil organization called Trinity,
which is threatening the world order with some kind of cheesy
pulse-bomb gizmo. She wants to defect to Monk's good-guy
organization, the Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Fine with him, because she's a pulse-bomb gizmo herself in
stringy black undies. And because Monk once spent a night with her,
or some damn thing.
</P>
<P>
   Before you can roll your eyes and yawn, Prima and Monk are on
the run from everyone. Odds are they won't live to see tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   But Monk's Agency pals Holiday (Meyer) and Davis (Whitfield)
want to save them, when they're not preoccupied modeling their
black outfits and those little ``M.I.B''-style sunglasses
Sonnenfeld adores so much.
</P>
<P>
   UPN viewers will be disappointed, but perhaps not crestfallen,
to learn that there's a shortage of big explosions in Tuesday
night's premiere. There are a few awkwardly staged fights, though,
with slo-mo and stop-action karate kicks.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers so desperate to avoid primary election results that
they'll watch this show will note that the escapade ends on a note
of utterly counterfeit emotion.
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, the show would be better with real-time karate
kicks and stop-action emotions. But that's only a suggestion for
our Men in Blechh.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
