<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8584 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-OKEEFFE-FAKES-NYT &LR;      03-06 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKEEFFE-FAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROVENANCE QUESTIONED OF `LOST' -- AND FOUND -- WATERCOLORS BY
GEORGIA O'KEEFE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mo., Texas, N.M.)   By GRETCHEN REYNOLDS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. _ Eleven years ago, the mysterious discovery of a
``lost'' series of 28 evocative watercolors by Georgia O'Keeffe
elicited almost swooning enthusiasm from art experts worldwide. J.
Carter Brown, then the director of the National Gallery of Art in
Washington, called the works ``a national treasure.''
</P>
<P>
   Called the ``Canyon Suite,'' the series became the focus of
elbowing interest from major collectors. In the end the suite sold
for $5 million to a Kansas City philanthropist, R. Crosby Kemper
Jr., who immediately donated it as a seedling gift to his new
Kemper Museum of Contemporary Art and Design in Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Times change. In December experts from the National Gallery,
including several who had sung the suite's praises, announced that
the 28 works could not have been painted by O'Keeffe, who died in
1986.
</P>
<P>
   Their provenance is now the subject of debate in the art world
and is under investigation by the FBI. One man came forward several
weeks ago to claim that the watercolors were partly his work. At
the same time, a man who is said by some to have forged the works
denied that charge. The dealer who sold the suite to Kemper has had
to refund the $5 million purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Keegan, director of the Kemper Museum, said the affair
had the makings of a significant scam.
</P>
<P>
   The story begins in the dusty vest pocket town of Canyon, Tex.,
where Georgia O'Keeffe lived from 1916 to 1918 and taught art at
West Texas Normal College (now Texas A&AMP;M University). It is also
where she embarked on her first truly mature paintings: majestic
studies of the sere, lunar canyonlands and surrounding desert. No
one disputes that some of the watercolors from that era are among
the foundation of all her later work. The question is the origin of
these watercolors.
</P>
<P>
   The Canyon watercolors were not even known to exist until 1988,
when Terry Reid Caballero of Amarillo, Tex., announced that she had
found the set in a package she had received as a gift from her
father-in-law, Emilio Caballero, a former director of the art
department at West Texas. He in turn said he had received the
package from Tim Reid, Terry Caballero's grandfather, who is said
to have been O'Keeffe's lover in Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Caballero said he had never opened the package and did not know
what it contained. Reid, who had died the previous year, left no
documentation concerning the works.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Keeffe experts immediately declared them to be authentic
and striking. With such Southwestern titles as ``Dark Mesa,''
``Purple Mountains'' and ``Dusk in the Canyon,'' they showed
sinuously abstracted buttes, slits, sunsets, and statuesque nudes,
the familiar physical and internal landscapes of the artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seemed so intimate to Georgia's thinking, it's still hard
for me to imagine they're not her work: they were and are
spectacular,''` said Gerald Peters, a Santa Fe art dealer who also
has galleries in New York and Dallas and who acquired ``Canyon
Suite'' from Terry Caballero for $1 million in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after ``Canyon Suite'' was discovered, Barbara Buhler
Lynes, a professor of art history at the Maryland Institute College
of Art, was commissioned by the National Gallery to begin work on a
catalog of OKeeffe's works that would serve as the final arbiter of
the authenticity of various works.
</P>
<P>
   Lynes, now the curator of the Georgia O'Keeffe Museum in Santa
Fe, began an intensive study of the paper used by O'Keeffe for her
watercolors. She discovered that the artist used a surprisingly
small range of different papers and that none of those were used in
the ``Canyon Suite'' series.
</P>
<P>
   More damaging, Lynes judged that some of the paper used for
``Canyon Suite'' was unavailable in the United States before 1930
and that some was not available until the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   If that were the case, the watercolors could not have been
produced during O'Keeffe's early stay in Canyon. It is unlikely
that she produced them later, Lynes reasoned, because O'Keeffe
usually painted landscapes when she lived in them. Last November
Lynes omitted the suite from her catalog along with 250 other
works, most of them on paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was certainly unwelcome news,'' Peters said of the
authenticity challenge. Although he recently sent out the drawings
for a separate independent analysis, he said, ``It seems clear at
least some of the works are not by O'Keeffe.''
</P>
<P>
   So whose work is it? Jacobo Suazo, a professed foster son of
O'Keeffe, says the work is his. He recently filed a copyright claim
asserting that he painted three of the disputed watercolors and
that he helped O'Keeffe finish 13 more.
</P>
<P>
   Suazo, 65, did indisputably live with O'Keeffe in Abiquiu, N.M.,
from the time he was 9 until he was 18; she taught him painting
techniques and relied on him to help alleviate her crushing
workload.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd work on dozens of paintings at a time,'' Suazo said.
``But I remember those perfectly.'' He said he saw a reproduction
of a work in the ``Canyon Suite'' series in a local newspaper,
recognized it (``It brought tears to my eyes'') and immediately
went to Kansas City to see the entire series. He rousted Keegan
from his home on a Sunday. ``I realized I did three of them and
some Mother O'Keeffe did,'' he said. ``Some I didn't recognize.''
</P>
<P>
   Suazo soon filed his claim, not to seek physical ownership but
to establish reproduction rights. He is reviewing the new catalog,
and his lawyer said he might file additional copyright claims.
O'Keeffe left Suazo $30,000 in her will.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Rose, a New York art historian and friend of O'Keeffe,
said: ``Georgia left Canyon quite suddenly to return to New York.
It's possible she left a few paintings and other materials
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that someone found the things left in her office and
realized they had a treasure trove,'' she said of O'Keeffe's office
at West Texas University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim Reid died in the spring of 1988, and suddenly in June 1988
Emilio Caballero deeds this unopened package to his
daughter-in-law,'' Rose said. ``Deeds it. Why do you deed something
whose contents you don't know?''
</P>
<P>
   Several other experts said they were suspicious about the
sequence of events surrounding the reappearance of ``Canyon
Suite.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, however, no one questioned it. ``Everyone was so
blinded by the drama and the big money,'' Rose said.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Beldon, a supervisory special agent for the FBI in
Albuquerque, confirmed that his office had opened an investigation
into the origins of ``Canyon Suite'' but said that the inquiry was
still ``very preliminary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 1901EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
