<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8593 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-KIDS-MOVIES-ART-(800)     03-06 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-MOVIES-ART-(800)2TAKES-TRIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT'LL BE 2 ADULTS AND 50 MILLION CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By RICK LYMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ It began early last November with a little yellow
creature named Pikachu, and it hasn't let up yet.
</P>
<P>
   Movie genres, like baseball seasons and presidential campaigns,
have their hot spells and their slumps. For the last four months
movies aimed at children and family audiences have been griddle
hot, one after the other, without a miss. Beginning in early
November with ``Pokemon: The Movie,'' continuing at Thanksgiving
with the huge box office success of ``Toy Story 2,'' then ``Stuart
Little'' right before Christmas and now ``Snow Day'' and ``The
Tigger Movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Children's films often do well, especially in the prime family
seasons of summer and the holidays. But this has been an
extraordinary string of successes without a single flop. One need
only go back to last summer to see that this is not always the
case. George Lucas' ``Star Wars: Episode 1 _ The Phantom Menace''
was a major success around Memorial Day, but several other movies
aimed at children, most notably the critically praised ``Iron
Giant,'' dropped with a thud.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get that momentum going, you can have a string of
hits,'' said Dick Cook, president of the Walt Disney Motion Picture
Group, which during this period released both ``Toy Story 2'' and
``The Tigger Movie,'' which features Winnie-the-Pooh and friends.
``Especially when people have gone to a movie and they loved it and
they realized what a great experience it was. They are much more
eager to go to the next one.''
</P>
<P>
   The trick, he said, is getting the streak started, as the
one-two punch of ``Pokemon'' and ``Toy Story 2'' did with this one.
``Any time the theatrical marketplace has gone into a slump, it's
always difficult to jump-start it,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   Few believe that the current family-movie streak points to any
permanent change in audience habits or to a tectonic shift in the
market, although the demographic of the moment, with baby boomers
raising the so-called echo boomers, would suggest flush times for
family movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe there's a major trend here that says anything,
except that families are always looking for movies as a family
activity, and if they feel there are movies out there they'd like
to take their kids to see, they take them to see them,'' said
Robert Levin, president for worldwide marketing at Sony Pictures
Entertainment, whose Columbia Pictures released ``Stuart Little.''
</P>
<P>
   Studio marketing and distribution executives credit the current
streak to a variety of factors. Besides the appetite for more
movies created by the enormous success of ``Pokemon'' and ``Toy
Story 2,'' they note that distribution was almost perfectly spaced
out. Each movie was released on a weekend when there were no other
new family films, and it then had a few weeks to run before the
next family movie came along, again without competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is about timing,'' said Robert G. Friedman, vice
chairman of the Paramount Motion Picture Group, which released
``Snow Day'' as part of a distribution deal with Nickelodeon Films.
``And you must make films that are not just kid-friendly, but
parent-friendly as well, so parents aren't sitting there clawing at
their eyes to get out of the theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Brad Ball, president for domestic marketing at Warner Brothers,
which released ``Pokemon'' and ``Iron Giant,'' agreed that timing
was vital. ``When you date your picture and its various components
has to be aligned equally as intelligently as the making of the
picture itself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By ``various components,'' he means the marketing tie-ins, like
trinkets at fast-food outlets. That was something ``Iron Giant''
did not have and may have played a significant role in keeping it
from reaching its audience in the summer competition before other
movies came along to replace it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not have a fast-food component,'' Ball said. ``If you
don't have that in this arena, you are behind the starting gate.
You're not only not in the pole position, you're seven or eight
rows back.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
