<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8594 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-06 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE BRADLEY BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Goodbye, Bill Bradley. We barely knew ye.
</P>
<P>
   Your quixotic adventure is over. You never won a primary and on
Tuesday elections across the country will reaffirm the polls that
show you badly trailing Vice President Al Gore in every primary
state voting that day.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley himself virtually conceded defeat in a Sunday television
appearance, claiming that he had not given up hope but sounding as
though he actually had.
</P>
<P>
   Next will come the armchair generals to second-guess the reasons
for the quick demolition of a challenge that had once seemed so
promising. But the Democratic presidential election was never
Bradley's to lose.
</P>
<P>
   It was Gore's to win. And he did. It was a rough but clean
fight, compared to the ruthless, dirty brawl on the Republican
side.
</P>
<P>
   The underestimation of Gore by pundits and politicians is the
Democratic story of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Gore went after Bradley's expensive health plan, mocked his
premature departure from the Senate and compared his relatively
passive support for women, racial minorities and labor to Gore's
own long record in the trenches for those causes. Bradley endlessly
complained that Gore was distorting his record, but Gore was
careful not to go too far. It was more a matter of spin. And that
is fair game in competitive politics.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has emerged as an aggressive, intelligent, engaging and
energetic politician, characteristics that were largely suppressed
in his role as veep. Forget wooden.
</P>
<P>
   The dull speaker in this campaign was Bradley; Gore has learned
how to shout, laugh and wave his arms around. It's a little
disconcerting but better than being put to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's early verbal gaffes and dramatic organizational shake-up
contributed to a mistaken impression that he could be easily
outwitted and outcampaigned by a liberal Democrat who merely
offered himself as the non-Gore. The fact that he is at the top of
his game came as quite a shock.
</P>
<P>
   In the Democratic primaries, Gore's eight-year service as
President Clinton's subservient sidekick was not the liability that
it might eventually become in a general election. Gore's
controversial role in the 1996 campaign finance controversies and
his praise for Clinton despite Clinton's dalliance with Monica
Lewinsky were never major issues with the Democrats. Those problems
are left for the Republicans to raise in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called Clinton fatigue did Bradley no good. On the
contrary, Gore's experience as second in command in the White House
and his resultant expertise in foreign and domestic policy were
assets. He simply knew more than his rival about the issues they
were discussing, and it showed.
</P>
<P>
   Where Bradley was fuzzy about what he might do in the White
House, Gore was relentlessly specific. He has a plan and a program
for everything, something for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was not helped by the excitement generated by Republican
Sen. John McCain, who attracted many independents who might
otherwise have gone to the Democrat. But it was not McCain who did
him in; it was Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Bradley did Gore a favor by doing so well initially.
Gore had been coasting to the nomination, untested and unfit for
battle. The possibility of defeat galvanized him into action.
</P>
<P>
   He got serious about his campaign, sharpened his attack mode and
came out fighting. He was ridiculed for moving his headquarters to
Tennessee and adopting informal earth-tone clothes, but they were
outward symbols of a transformation from a vice presidential
mentality to a campaign mode. It worked.
</P>
<P>
   It was never clear why Bradley ran in the first place. He didn't
seem to want the White House job all that badly. The campaign had
the aspect of an exercise conducted just to see what would happen
if a candidate took the high road.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, a road trod only by angels is not the path to a party's
presidential nomination. And as his campaign faltered, Bradley
strayed from his original abstract ideal to trash Gore for
legislative inconsistency and supposed character faults. But
Bradley's heart never seemed in it.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley reverted to a conciliatory attitude in his final debate
with Gore, suggesting that he means to exit the field with dignity.
He said that he would support Gore if Gore wins the Democratic
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Very civilized, really. And an outcome that positions Bradley
for an important role in a Gore administration, if there is one.
The vice presidential nomination, however, is likely to go to a
fresher face who is a proven vote-getter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
