<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8595 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-KIDS-MOVIES-ART-2NDTA     03-06 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-MOVIES-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: rows back.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The current streak began on Nov. 10, when ``Pokemon'' opened,
catching the craze for the Japanese animated phenomenon at its
crest and earning an astonishing $50.7 million before the end of
its first weekend and another $17 million the following weekend.
With interest in the film beginning to flag, ``Toy Story 2'' burst
into theaters nationwide on Nov. 22 and made $80 million before the
end of the subsequent Thanksgiving weekend and $140 million by Dec.
12. Just as that film was beginning to lose a bit of its box-office
steam (though it remained quite strong for weeks to come), ``Stuart
Little'' appeared on Dec. 17 and earned $15 million in its first
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Critical reaction to these films was all over the map. While
``Toy Story 2'' was almost universally praised and ``Stuart
Little'' received a number of favorable reviews, the others drew a
more mixed reaction and it was difficult to tell what difference,
if any, the reviews made. With ``Pokemon,'' certainly, the puzzled
reactions of critics seemed to have little impact on young
moviegoers.
</P>
<P>
   The success of ``Pokemon'' was not unexpected, though the size
of the numbers was startling to many. And everyone expected ``Toy
Story 2'' to dominate the Thanksgiving box office, which is why no
other family films opened anywhere near it. But ``Stuart Little''
was something of a mystery before its opening.
</P>
<P>
   Costing more than $100 million to produce, it boasted the latest
computer animation to bring E.B. White's mouse-boy to life but did
not have a franchise as foolproof as Pokemon or ``Toy Story.'' And
the movie's opening, to a much smaller audience than the previous
two films, attested to that. But ``Stuart Little'' had the
Christmas period pretty much to itself, young children loved it,
and family audiences embraced it. The film dropped only 21 percent
at the box office in its second week and then, in the week between
Christmas and New Year's, it actually increased its box office take
by 36 percent, earning $136 million by the middle of February.
</P>
<P>
   Many expected the family-movie streak to cool with the arrival
in force of films geared to attract Oscar nominations in the first
months of the year and with children back in school. But the tandem
releases of ``Snow Day'' and ``The Tigger Movie'' on Feb. 11, in
time for the President's Day weekend, proved that wrong. Both films
not only performed well, they also did much better than expected,
and both have reasons to brag, perhaps ``Snow Day'' most of all.
</P>
<P>
   The slapstick comedy about what happens when a snowstorm gives
children a day off from school was aimed at marginally older
audiences than some of the other releases but was propelled into
theaters on the strength of the Nickelodeon banner. The splotchy
orange Nickelodeon logo is almost as familiar and beloved to young
people as the Walt Disney fairy castle, and the power of the
various Nickelodeon-affiliated cable channels to reach young
eyeballs guaranteed that news of the movie's arrival would be known
among children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that there has been a dearth of family movies in
general,'' said Albie Hecht, president for film and television
entertainment at Nickelodeon. ``By that I mean movies that parents
really enjoy as well. You had very extreme action films and very
extreme teen films but very few attempting to do really broad-based
comedy for the whole family. It's something that Hollywood
abandoned for a long time, and we're trying to fill a void.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Nickelodeon logo alone cannot create a hit. ``Harriet
the Spy'' and ``Good Burger,'' two previous Nickelodeon efforts,
failed to catch fire at the box office. Hecht said the success of
``Snow Day'' came from its being aimed more clearly at family
audiences, rather than at children alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that brand is important to the initial success of
`Snow Day,''' Friedman said. ``But after that it comes down to word
of mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   What Nickelodeon marketing executives are seeing now, to their
great delight, is that young parents who watched Nickelodeon as
youngsters now are beginning to have children of their own, and
there is a second generation of brand loyalty, something that, in
the family arena, only Disney has had, going back to the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   When marketing executives try to explain the success of films
that were not necessarily expected to do so well, they often look
for time-proven hooks upon which to hang their reasoning. For the
current crop of family movies that has been easy. Pokemon, ``Toy
Story'' and Winnie-the-Pooh were reliable franchises with a proven
ability to attract young audiences. ``Stuart Little,'' while not
quite to their promotional level, was based on a beloved children's
book. But ``Snow Day'' came into the marketplace relatively
unheralded, with only the Nickelodeon brand behind it and a pitch
aimed a bit higher than the ``Pokemon'' or ``Tigger'' audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snow Day'' made $14 million in its first weekend, only
marginally less than ``Stuart Little'' had made during the
holidays, and like ``Stuart'' it held on at the box-office through
strong word of mouth, dropping only 20 percent in its second
weekend and 28 percent in its third, when it was still the No. 2
movie in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tigger'' also had a charmed life. Though it opened with only
minimal advertising and in very few of the large urban theaters, it
earned $9 million in its first weekend and $8 million in its
second.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have any advertising in the major city newspapers,''
Cook said. ``We went to the suburban papers. That's where we
believe the audience is, so we wasted no dollars on an audience
that wasn't going to be interested in seeing it.''
</P>
<P>
   The film had also been promoted during showings of ``Toy Story
2,'' which helped.
</P>
<P>
   How long the streak will last is anybody's guess. Perhaps the
first indication will come this week when ``My Dog Skip'' has its
first shot at wide, national distribution. The movie, based on
Willie Morris' memoir of his childhood pet, has played for several
weeks in limited release and earned some good reviews but
lackluster box office revenue. Now, however, Warner Brothers hopes
to capitalize on the current spate of family hits and on the recent
success of the film's young star, Frankie Muniz, who is featured in
the hit television series ``Malcolm in the Middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, on March 31, DreamWorks will release its next animated
feature, ``The Road to El Dorado,'' with Kevin Kline and Kenneth
Branagh providing the voices in a kind of Bob Hope and Bing Crosby
road movie set in 17th-century Central America.
</P>
<P>
   With luck, neither of them will meet the fate of ``Iron Giant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe in many respects, we're learning a little bit better
what we're doing,'' Ball said. ``Of course a lot of it may just be
coincidence and luck.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 1911EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
