<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0375 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8596 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-CAMPAIGN-HNS &LR;      03-06 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-CAMPAIGN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     McCAIN LOOKS BEYOND GOP IN BID FOR SUPER TUESDAY UPSET  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sen. John McCain on Monday wrapped up a
make-or-break bid to wrest the Republican presidential nomination
from Texas Gov. George Bush with a fiery ``call to duty'' for
Republicans and non-Republicans alike to help him repudiate the
influence of ``dirty money.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Republican barnstormed the length of California on
the eve of what amounts to a national GOP primary _ 613 convention
delegates at stake in 13 states stretching from California to New
England.
</P>
<P>
   McCain fought Bush's wide lead in polls in most of the states
with an impassioned appeal for voters to join his insurgency and
repudiate a $2.5-million advertising blitz in California, New York,
Ohio and Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   McCain accused two billionaire brothers _ Sam and Charles Wyly
of Texas _ of financing the ads that attack his environmental
record and demanded for the first time that Bush ask his supporters
to end the attack.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, claiming the integrity of the ``whole political
process'' is being threatened by violations of laws adopted after
the Watergate scandal, demanded immediate remedial action by the
Federal Communications Commission and the Federal Election
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   McCain told students on the Los Angeles campus of the University
of California that ``a couple of billionaires from Texas'' are
trying to ``steal this campaign; they're trying to hijack it.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain asked voters support his campaign on Tuesday and send a
message ``to Governor Bush and his cronies (to) take that dirty
money and give it back to the state of Texas, we don't want it.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain cautioned that with ``lots of billionaires'' in the
nation, ``we're going to see the disappearance of politics in
America'' if the Bush supporters are ``allowed to come into the
last few days of an American political campaign and spend millions
and millions and millions of dollars in attack ads.''
</P>
<P>
   At an earlier stop in Santa Cruz, McCain declared: ``We'll let
the people of California decide who they want to be the next
president of the United States _ not some people, some billionaires
from Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain campaign spokesman Howard Opinsky said that McCain hopes
to persuade non-Republican voters, particularly in California,
cross party lines and support his campaign rather than vote in
Democratic races to support former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Ten of Tuesday's 13 GOP contests are open to non-Republican
voters, including a largely symbolic contest for the popular vote
here in California. Polls show Bradley trailing Vice President Gore
in Tuesday's Democratic contests in 16 states.
</P>
<P>
   So far in the primary season, Bush has about 194 delegates to
McCain's 111, according to calculations by ABC News. The numbers
are approximations because not all delegates selected are committed
to candidates.
</P>
<P>
   McCain campaign aides said the best-case scenario for the
challenger on Tuesday would be sweeping five New England states and
New York and capturing the popular vote in California.
</P>
<P>
   While Democrats and independents can cross party lines, only
Republican votes count toward deciding who gets California's 162
delegates to the Republican nominating convention. Bush holds a
wide margin over McCain among Republicans, according to polls.
</P>
<P>
   McCain addressed rallies in Santa Clara, Los Angeles and San
Diego on the eve of Super Tuesday contests that will select 60
percent of the 1,034 delegates needed to win the GOP presidential
nomination at the national convention in Philadelphia in July.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks to more than 1,000 students crowded onto one of three
basketball courts in the gym at Santa Clara University, McCain
sought to bolster his anti-establishment credentials with attacks
on President Clinton and the Congress, as well as Bush and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our crusade is about saying come and serve and sacrifice and
be ennobled,'' said McCain, a former Navy pilot and Vietnam War
prisoner whose campaign ads cite his ``courage and character.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a call to duty. This a call of duty to awaken the
spirit of America that has been dormant for some period of time,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain spoke before a red, white and blue campaign banner,
``It's your country. Take it back from the special interests,''
that was designed to strengthen his populist appeal in an
independent-minded state where many voters turned their backs on
the Democratic and Republican nominees in 1992 to support
independent Ross Perot. Perot won 21 percent of the vote in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   McCain won a boost in his efforts to exploit Bush's Feb. 2
controversial appearance at Bob Jones University, an evangelical
Baptist institution in Greenville, S.C., that banned inter-racial
dating until last week and has promulgated anti-Catholic teachings.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Privett, a Jesuit priest and the provost leading the
7,700 students at Santa Clara University, contrasted McCain to
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had chosen to speak at an ``institution whose active
promotion of intolerance and divisiveness undercuts its claim to be
a university.'' McCain, he said, had chosen to address a
139-year-old ``Jesuit Catholic university that cherishes our
diverse community.''
</P>
<P>
   Privett hailed McCain's efforts to ``promote a more inclusive
political process that the promotes the common good of all rather
than pitting people against one another.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, McCain's allure to some Democrats is proving so
appealing that Chris Stampolis, a Democratic Party leader in the
Santa Clara state assembly district, made the rounds among
reporters covering McCain's rally to emphasize that many Democrats
would return to Gore in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that some moderate Democrats are excited
by McCain and drawn to his campaign,'' Stampolis said. ``But we
think these Democrats will vote for Gore in the end. Once they
learn about McCain's positions on the issues, they'll realize that
Gore will be the only candidate in the mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Opinsky said that once McCain emerges from Tuesday's contests,
he would gain additional benefits from Bradley's expected
withdrawal from the race against Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Opinsky said that Gore then would increasingly focus his
campaign attacks on Bush rather than Bradley, in a shift that
McCain hopes will enhance his claim that he would be a more
effective challenger to Gore in the race for the White House in
November.
</P>
