<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ETHIOPIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHIOPIA'S ROADBLOCK TO PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A nation where 8 million people are threatened by famine would
be wise to end a senseless war immediately. Ethiopia ought to
accept an African peace plan that calls for the peaceful settlement
of its border dispute with Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
   Yet late last month fighting broke out, as it has periodically
since heavy combat ended last June. Eritrea blames Ethiopia, but
whatever really happened, it is clear that Ethiopia is presenting
the biggest roadblock to peace.
</P>
<P>
   The Organization of African Unity devised a peace plan last
summer that provided for a withdrawal from contested areas and the
demarcation of the border by disinterested outsiders. This would be
a textbook example of how a regional organization settles a border
dispute if the Ethiopians would only agree to accept the plan in
full.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they are haggling over the precise nature of the
withdrawal and whether any weapons will be allowed in the disputed
zones. These issues could be resolved with a minimal amount of good
will. Ahmed Ouyahia, an OAU mediator, was in the region last week
in an effort to help out.
</P>
<P>
   So was Anthony Lake, former national security adviser to
President Clinton, who shuttled between the two capitals. Once the
peace plan is accepted, the United States would almost certainly
finance a peacekeeping operation in the disputed area.
</P>
<P>
   The war is fueled by more than boundary disputes. Since Eritrea
broke off from Ethiopia in 1991, the two countries have yet to
devise an economic relationship that combines interdependence with
independence. Eritrea controls the two ports through which most of
Ethiopia's seaborne commerce flows, while the 59 million Ethiopians
are prime customers for anything the 3.9 million Eritreans have to
sell.
</P>
<P>
   As it did 15 years ago, when it was fighting to prevent Eritrean
independence, Ethiopia today faces a famine that could kill
hundreds of thousands of people. Ethiopia was then ruled by
Mengistu Haile Mariam, a brutal dictator. The international
community needs to remind the present rulers, a more democratic
group, that it must end the war to avert another humanitarian
catastrophe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
