<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELIEVE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MAKE BELIEVE': IN THE FANCIFUL HEAD OF A SMALL BOY IN BIG
TROUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) (DW) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joanna Scott's characters have always been preoccupied by the
randomness of life, the uncertainty, even perversity of existence.
The men and women in ``Various Antidotes'' (1994) coped by
filtering their lives through a solitary obsession, be it the study
of bees or mice or the compulsive reliving of a traumatic event;
and in ``Arrogance'' (1990), the painter Egon Schiele used art to
try to control the world around him, remaking people and things to
conform to the lineaments of his own imagination.
</P>
<P>
   In Scott's uneven new novel, ``Make Believe,'' the hero is a
little boy named Bo who processes the tumultuous events that keep
overtaking his life through fantasy, stories and childish logic.
Bo's father was shot to death in a robbery attempt and died a month
before Bo's birth; his mother was killed in a car accident when he
was 3; and one of his grandmothers will die in a freak accident the
following year. Bo's custody will also be decided by seemingly
random events: the judge presiding over his case will allow his
decision to be affected by his own marital problems and a novel he
happens to be reading.
</P>
<P>
   The opening sections of ``Make Believe,'' which depict Bo's
experience of the car accident that killed his mother and his new
life with his paternal grandparents are as powerful as anything the
gifted Scott has written. They possess the unsettling intensity of
Benjy's interior monologue in Faulkner's ``Sound and the Fury,''
immersing the reader in the slip-sliding world of a child's
imagination, a world at once egocentric and rudderless, a world of
bright, shimmering sensations and fragmentary knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Bo experiences the accident as a strange succession of thuds,
like the thuds he ``made when he slid under his mama's bed and
kicked the mattress,'' with glass bursting into stars, and metal
bubbling ``with a noise that reminded him of secret laughter.''
Still, he realizes that what ``could happen was always worse than
what he could imagine,'' worries that the people in the hospital
who are poking and prodding him are capable of ``actions as awful
and mysterious as the sea creatures living at the bottom of the
ocean.'' It was his fault, he thinks, because ``everything was his
fault'' but at the same time, he imagines that ``everything that
happened to him now happened for a reason beyond his control.''
</P>
<P>
   From Bo's point of view, Scott shifts angles to sketch in the
lives of his family: his mother, Jenny, a rebellious young woman,
on the outs with her family for having a child with a black man;
his father, Kamon, who was shot outside a grocery store while
buying cigarettes for his cousin; Jenny's mother, Marge, a large,
complacent woman under the thumb of her self-righteous husband,
Eddie Gantz; and Kamon's parents, Erma and Sam Gilbert, who take Bo
in after Jenny dies.
</P>
<P>
   As a custody battle for Bo shapes up, however, Scott's
elliptical narrative inexplicably lapses into stark made-for-TV
melodrama: the Gilberts, who are black and who have been part of
Bo's life since he was born, pitted against the Gantzes, who are
white and who scorned Bo's mother, Jenny, when she became pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, we are told, that the Gantzes have taken a sudden
interest in Bo is that Eddie Gantz believes there is a lot of money
to be made by filing a malpractice suit against the doctors who
cared for Bo after the accident. Scott not only gives Eddie the
basest reasons for wanting custody of Bo, she later turns him into
a caricature of an abusive father, bullying the boy and beating him
and accusing him of being a devil who disrupted his perfect life.
</P>
<P>
   Though there has always been a gothic strain in Scott's writing
_ one of her novels depicted a grisly act of mutiny aboard a
19th-century slave ship; another portrayed an obsessive taxidermist
and the bizarre people around him _ this venture into family soap
opera does not mesh with the overall conception of ``Make
Believe.'' It stands in stark contrast to the carefully calibrated
depiction of the hazards of ordinary life that distinguished the
opening half of the book, and it turns the characters into hapless
puppets dancing spastically to their creator's whims.
</P>
<P>
   Although the penultimate chapter of ``Make Believe,'' which
sends Bo's life skidding off in yet another direction, contains a
dazzling set piece that showcases all of Scott's virtuosic skills,
it grows out of a willfully contrived situation, and so feels less
like an organic conclusion to this story than a showoff-y piece of
writerly legerdemain. In short, a disappointing and stage-managed
end to a novel that started off with such subtlety and promise.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MAKE BELIEVE' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Joanna Scott  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   246 pages. Little, Brown &AMP; Co. $23.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
