<SLUG> BC-FASTEST-CHIP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMD BEATS INTEL TO MARKET WITH 1-GIG MICROCHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first desktop computers to use ultrafast one-gigahertz
processors are coming to market months ahead of schedule, and with
no ``Intel Inside'' stickers on the box.
</P>
<P>
   In a public relations coup, rival chipmaker Advanced Micro
Devices Inc. has begun shipping the new one-gigahertz version of
its Athlon processor chip. That puts AMD out in front of industry
leader Intel Corp., which is expected to introduce its own
one-gigahertz chip later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Most PCs use chips that are compatible with the ``X86'' design
created by Intel. But AMD has snatched the speed lead from Intel
with the Athlon, a line of processors the company introduced last
year. The first Athlons ran at 500 megahertz, leading Intel to roll
out faster Pentium III chips to keep up. Last month, AMD took the
lead with an 850-megahertz chip, compared to Intel's 800-megahertz
Pentium III. Now AMD is offering Athlons at 900, 950, and 1,000
megahertz, or one gigahertz.
</P>
<P>
   Two leading computer makers, Compaq Computer Corp. of Houston
and Gateway 2000 Inc. of San Diego, say they're ready to begin
making computers armed with the new chip, the fastest
Intel-compatible processor on the market. Gateway is already taking
orders for the machines, with a base price of $2,999. Compaq will
start taking orders Thursday, with prices starting at $2,499.
</P>
<P>
   These are steep prices at a time when most personal computer
systems sell for $1,000 or less. That's partly because the Athlon
chip alone will cost $1,300. But then, Compaq and Gateway are
aiming their new systems at hard-core home users who want the best
of everything. The systems come with huge hard drives, high-end
stereo speakers, and advanced graphic accelerator cards. That makes
the systems well suited for high performance when playing
three-dimensional computer games.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Vena, Compaq's director of consumer desktop product
marketing, estimated Monday that about 20 percent of Compaq's
retail customers are likely customers for the new machines. ``These
are people who are well, well beyond PlayStations or Dreamcasts.
These are people who are looking for the ultimate entertainment
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The Compaq system also comes with video editing software and
FireWire data ports that will let users download digital camcorder
videos directly into the computer. Vena said the high-powered
Athlon processor will allow for quick and easy desktop video
editing.
</P>
<P>
   Both AMD and Intel had previously said they'd bring out
one-gigahertz chips later this year. But AMD is moving quickly to
capitalize on the success of the Athlon. It's the first AMD chip
considered equal in quality to Intel's top products. Meanwhile,
Intel has recently stumbled due to an inability to meet high demand
for its Pentium III chips. Gateway, for instance, had stopped using
AMD chips in its computers. But the company changed its mind and
started using Athlons, partly to make up for a shortage of Pentium
chips.
</P>
<P>
   Intel spokesman Michael Sullivan seemed unconcerned about AMD's
latest accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about having the first news release,'' Sullivan said.
``I don't think that the competitive environment has changed today
in any way. We fully plan to be the leader in this segment with the
fastest chips and the most of them.''
</P>
<P>
   It all sounds like pointless chest-thumping to chip industry
analyst Linley Gwennap, principal analyst of the Linley Group in
Mountain View, Calif. ``I think it's more of a race of testosterone
than technology,'' said Gwennap, adding that AMD can produce only
limited quantities of the Athlon and has therefore priced it high
enough to scare most customers away. ``Thirteen hundred dollars for
the chip? That's like slapping a big, red sign on them saying
`Don't buy me.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
