<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8607 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BRENNER-BIOTECH-2     03-06 1390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRENNER-BIOTECH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYDNEY BRENNER, A CEASELESS IDEA-GENERATOR IN MICROBIOLOGY'S GOLDEN
AGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: South Africa, Britain, France, Lithuania, Wis., Calif.,
Mass. ) (Science Times) (DW) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA JOLLA, Calif. _ Sydney Brenner's picture window apartment
overlooks a children's playground and a kelp-strewn beach where
surfers contest with the Pacific. The balmy California scene is a
far cry from the little South African town of Germiston where he
grew up, and the biting winds of Cambridge in England where he
worked for many years.
</P>
<P>
   That journey spans a scientific career of unusual versatility.
Brenner, who is now the inventor-guru of a new biotechnology
company after retiring from the British Medical Research Council,
has been a leading molecular biologist for nearly half a century.
In a career of unquenchable creativity, he has always kept moving,
searching for new and different problems to tackle, founding a new
field as soon as the old one seemed stale.
</P>
<P>
   Brenner played a starring role in the Golden Age of molecular
biology _ the years from 1953 to 1966 when the high mysteries of
the genetic code and protein synthesis were worked out. He is also
one of the architects of the present Genomic Era, brought about by
machines that can decode an organism's entire DNA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often you read these potted biographies of great scientists,
and when you meet them in real life they are not much different
from other people, but Sydney was very different,'' said Dr. John
White, a former graduate student of Brenner now at the University
of Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   A ceaseless flow of ideas, some successful, some less so, is one
of Brenner's traits. Another is his gift of spellbinding listeners
with his latest enthusiasm. He speaks with distinctive English
diction and in perfectly constructed sentences that often end with
a joke. In the humorless deserts of the scientific literature, a
consistent sparkle of wit is to be found in an iconoclastic column
he writes in the journal Current Biology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sydney Brenner is probably the cleverest and most articulate
of the founding fathers,'' said Dr. Norton Zinder of Rockefeller
University, referring to the creators of modern biology. ``He is
the most enjoyable company. He overflows with ideas, some of which
are occasionally even useful.''
</P>
<P>
   With the human genome expected to be substantially decoded
within the next few months, Brenner's deft handiwork can be seen at
both ends of the process. The decoding of an organism's whole DNA,
or genome, began as part of the array of studies on a tiny
translucent roundworm that Brenner selected in the mid-1960s as a
model organism.
</P>
<P>
   The little worm, known as C. elegans, is now studied in
laboratories around the world and has already yielded many insights
into the genetic design of animals. It has turned out to be
surprisingly relevant to humans _ by and large, people have a
worm-type genome repeated four times over _ and is expected to play
a major role in helping to interpret the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   That task, going from the raw sequence of the genome to the
knowledge of what each of its 100,000 genes may do, and how they
interact, is expected to be the work of decades.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Brenner announced a novel group of techniques for
analyzing very large sets of DNA. His invention, put into practice
by Lynx Therapeutics of Hayward, Calif., is based on anchoring DNA
fragments to microscopic beads by combinatorial chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   The beads can be processed so as to identify the handful of DNA
sequences that may differ between two large sets, like the
cancerous and noncancerous states of a human cell, or the genomes
of two people. If the system works as hoped, it could play a major
role in understanding the dynamics of the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney Brenner was born in 1927 to parents who had immigrated to
South Africa, his mother from Latvia and his father from Lithuania.
Though he studied medicine at the University of Witwatersrand,
biological research was his passion. But South Africa was then a
scientific backwater. When he wished to stain a cell, he had first
to synthesize the dye.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving in 1952 in Oxford, that ancient seat of learning, the
young provincial learned that his eminent adviser, the physical
chemist Sir Cyril Hinshelwood, was not a believer in mutation. His
first task was to persuade his professor of the reality of genetic
change. On a visit to Cambridge a year later, he met Dr. James D.
Watson and Dr. Francis Crick, who had just discovered the structure
of DNA, the hereditary material.
</P>
<P>
   Crick liked his quick wit and in 1956 brought him back from
South Africa to a job at the British Medical Research Council's
Cambridge laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Crick was then at the center of a nexus of biologists in
Cambridge, Paris and the United States who were working out the
first consequences of the discovery of DNA. Brenner, who shared an
office with Crick for 20 years, played a major role in many of
textbook discoveries made by Crick's circle.
</P>
<P>
   Several concerned the genetic code, the relationship through
which the order of units in DNA determines the structure of the
cell's various protein molecules.
</P>
<P>
   He and Crick proved the code must require three DNA units to
specify each amino acid, the building blocks of proteins, in an
ingenious experiment. By deleting DNA units from bacteria they
showed that only after three units had been deleted in close
proximity did the DNA message come back into correct phase, proving
the units must be translated three at a time.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, with Dr. Matthew Meselson of Harvard and Dr. Francois
Jacob of the Pasteur Institute in Paris, Brenner proved the
existence of messenger-RNA, the transcript that carries the genetic
message from DNA to the cell's protein-making factories.
</P>
<P>
   With these and several other discoveries, described in Horace
Judson's standard history ``The Eighth Day of Creation,'' the
essential nature of the relationship between gene and protein had
been resolved. Believing the details could be left to others,
Brenner and Crick cast around for new biological pinnacles to
conquer.
</P>
<P>
   The development of the organism and the working of the brain
being the two highest in sight, Brenner decided in 1964 to tackle
both through the medium of a brand new experimental organism, the
roundworm Caenorhabditis elegans.
</P>
<P>
   Decades of work had made the Drosophila fruit fly a standard
organism for geneticists, but the fly's brain was too complicated
for Brenner's purpose. He wanted an organism with a nervous system
so simple that he could compute its behavior from knowledge of the
interconnections between its nerve cells.
</P>
<P>
   Computing the worm's behavior, however, was one of Brenner's
less than fully successful ideas. After 14 years, his student White
succeeded in reconstructing the wiring diagram of the worm's brain,
but its 5,000 interconnections proved too complex a system for
further analysis.
</P>
<P>
   But the C. elegans project bore fruit in many other ways. Two
students, Dr. John E. Sulston and Dr. H. Robert Horvitz, worked out
the worm's fate map _ the precise lines of descent by which the 959
cells of the adult are generated from the single cell of the egg _
a pioneering feat that has been achieved with no other organism.
Sulston then began to sequence the worm's genome, the pilot project
that gave scientists confidence they could tackle the much larger
sequence of the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   After much hard work by Brenner and his students, many of them
Americans who came to work as postdoctoral researchers in his
Cambridge laboratory, the worm had developed into a gold mine for
solving outstanding problems in biology.
</P>
<P>
   But in the mid-1980s, Brenner, who did not entirely relish being
introduced everywhere as the `Father of the Worm,' decided to move
on to general problems of genome research.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still wanted to do the computing problem,'' he now says,
``but I thought it would require younger people than me. It's a
young man's problem. My problem is that I know too much to tackle
that. I'm a strong believer that ignorance is important in science.
If you know too much, you start seeing why things won't work.
That's why it's important to change your field to collect more
ignorance.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Having served as director of the Medical Research Council's
Laboratory of Molecular Biology from 1979 to 1986 and approaching
the council's mandatory retirement age, Brenner started working
part of the year in Southern California, where Crick and other
friends had already moved. A new project began to take shape: a
fish known as the fugu.
</P>
<P>
   As DNA sequencing progressed, it became clear that some 97
percent of the human genome is junk DNA, material that does not
code for genes and has no apparent function other than to make the
real genes very hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons yet to be fathomed, the fugu or puffer-fish genome
is end-to-end genes with almost no junk DNA. Brenner conceived the
idea of sequencing the fugu genome so as to find the genes more
quickly and develop a basis of comparison with the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   The idea has not found favor with the federal Human Genome
Project, which favors the zebra fish as a model organism for
studying animal development and the mouse genome for direct
comparison with that of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think they will do comparisons on the mouse,'' Brenner
said, ``but they won't succeed _ the mouse is too close. It hasn't
had enough time to randomize, so you are confused by the commonness
of origin.''
</P>
<P>
   He means that genes that have retained a similar DNA sequence in
puffer fish and people, species that separated 400 million years
ago, are likely to be of critical importance. Mice and men shared
an ancestor so recently that almost all their genes show signs of
relatedness.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists are more interested in theory, others in
experimental detail. Brenner has a cast of mind that pursues both
the tiniest cogs of a system and its overall design with equal
interest. ``He is a mixture of someone who likes to develop the
ultimate tool, but also to think of the concept behind it,'' White
said.
</P>
<P>
   For his DNA bead system, Brenner invented an artificial genetic
code that serves to tie each gene transcript a cell produces to a
different bead, creating a powerful system for DNA-based
computation and sequencing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in the end we are the people who will provide the
interface between the gene and the computer,'' Brenner said,
referring to his colleagues at Lynx. Part of the bead system was
published for the first time last month, but its full details are
not widely understood.
</P>
<P>
   After the beads? New projects are already lining up in Brenner's
mind. One is a new way of analyzing the human genome so as to
identify its most slowly evolving genes. Another is a speculation
about the kind of device the cell is.
</P>
<P>
   There are two kinds of machines, he pointed out. One, like a
computer, can calculate the answer to a problem. The other has a
set of tables with all the answers written out. Which kind are
cells?
</P>
<P>
   ``They are table machines, not program machines,'' Brenner said.
``So who calculates the tables? Evolution calculates them. It finds
the answer and stores it in the gene. So I envisage that the genome
is a library in which has been stored books with important numbers
which were generated by the process of evolution, a process which
is inelegant and opportunistic, but it works.''
</P>
<P>
   Where then is the cell's central computer that crunches all the
information in the tables? There isn't one. In Brenner's view, the
proteins are designed to interact with one another in a process
that produces the right answer.
</P>
<P>
   The origin of life is one outstanding biological problem that
Brenner has not yet tackled in depth. Perhaps a hint of his
thinking appears in one of his columns, where he relates how his
officemate Crick, trying to understand the embryonic organs from
which the fruit fly's wings develop, one day threw down his book
with the remark, ``God knows how these imaginal discs work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In a flash,'' Brenner wrote, ``I saw the whole story of
Francis arriving in heaven and Peter welcoming him.''
</P>
<P>
   Crick insisted on being introduced immediately to the deity and
after some persuasion was taken to a junkyard shack at the very
back of heaven, where there was ``a little man in overalls with a
large spanner in his back pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   ```God,' says the angel, `This is Dr. Crick; Dr. Crick, this is
God.' `I am so pleased to meet you,' says Francis. `I must ask you
this question. How do imaginal discs work?'
</P>
<P>
   ```Well,' comes the reply, `We took a little bit of this stuff
and we added some things to it and ... actually, we don't know, but
I can tell you that we've been building flies up here for 200
million years and we have had no complaints.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
