<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHALE-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP SUES US FOR FAILING TO PROTECT RIGHT WHALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Alarmed at the growing number of Northern right whales
being hurt or killed by fishing gear, one of New England's leading
environmental organizations plans to sue the federal government for
failing to protect the most endangered large whale species in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say the 300 remaining right whales, many of them in
Cape Cod Bay at this time of year, are slowly heading for
extinction, partly because they continue to become entangled in
fishing gear or are accidentally hit by ships. In all, rescue
workers tried to free six entangled right whales last year,
including one that died off the New Jersey coast from a deep cut
caused by fishing line.
</P>
<P>
   The Conservation Law Foundation of Boston charged Monday that
the National Marine Fisheries Service deserves at least part of the
blame for the gear entanglements because the agency has dragged its
feet in requiring the development of lobster traps, nets, and other
gear that allow whales to escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a crisis and it hasn't been treated like a crisis,'' said
Alan Wilson, vice president of the Conservation Law Foundation.
``The National Marine Fisheries Service really hasn't done as much
as it should to protect the whales.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the National Marine Fisheries Service declined to
comment on the planned lawsuit, but said that the agency expects to
require some type of breakaway nets and lines for lobster traps and
gillnets by the end of the year. They also said new federal funds
will allow more research into practical ways to make gear less
harmful to the whales.
</P>
<P>
   But conservationists and scientists alike say the service moves
too slowly. They hope that the lawsuit by the Conservation Law
Foundation, which in the past has successfully sued to force the
cleanup of Boston Harbor and restrict fishing on Georges Bank, will
give the right whale's decline far more urgency.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need to do is put this more on a war footing where we
really have a massive attempt to find solutions,'' said Scott
Kraus, director of the Edgerton Lab at the New England Aquarium.
``I think the agency treats us like orphans and they wish that we
would just go away, so maybe a lawsuit is just what is needed.''
</P>
<P>
   The right whale population has been declining since the early
1990s, due both to a plummeting birth rate and a steady stream of
human-induced deaths. Although fishing gear accounts for only 10
percent of whale deaths, 60 percent of the whales show signs of
fishing gear scars, including an entangled whale near Provincetown
that the Center for Coastal Studies is trying to free.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are well past the age of denial here. We've got so many
animals with scars and so many entanglements,'' said Peter
Borrelli, the Center's executive director. ``We have got to act
quickly with this few animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservation Law Foundation officials said their top goal is to
force more federal spending on ``whale-safe'' gear than the
$450,000 now available. Some scientists say at least $5 million is
needed to investigate products such as fishing line that dissolves
when imbedded in whale flesh, or lines that lie on the sea floor
until electronically ``called'' to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   However, both Kraus and others worry that the lawsuit could
reopen old wounds between fishermen and environmentalists just as
they are beginning to work cooperatively. An advisory team
including both fishermen and environmentalists are preparing a
report to the fisheries service on gear changes to help the whales.
</P>
<P>
   Just two years ago, activists and fishermen were deeply divided
over a National Marine Fisheries Service proposal, now shelved,
that would have cost fishermen $12,000 or more to make each boat
``whale-safe.'' Fishermen said the price was too high, considering
that most of the roughly 10,000 lobstermen and 100 or so gillnet
fishermen in federal waters will never snag a whale in their gear.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the division, activist Max Strahan, known as the
``Prince of Whales,'' sued the state of Massachusetts in an attempt
to ban lobstering and gillnet fishing in state-managed waters
altogether. The state ultimately agreed to close areas in Cape Cod
Bay during peak whale visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hell of a lot isn't getting done on fisheries management
because of all these lawsuits,'' warned Pat White, executive
director of the Maine Lobstermen's Association, who said the
National Marine Fisheries Service already faces 96 lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the six entangled whales last year, two right
whales have been reported entangled in fishing gear in 2000,
including one dead whale floating north of Rhode Island's Block
Island. However, researchers were unable to recover the carcass to
determine the cause of death.
</P>
<P>
   But Chris Mantzaris, chief of the protected resources branch of
the National Marine Fisheries Service in Gloucester, said the
increase in reported entanglements may actually reflect improved
efforts to protect the whales. He said scientists believe the
increase reflects better reporting of whale distress by everyone
from fishermen to the Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only in the last couple of years have we had such a massive
effort in looking for these animals,'' said Mantzaris.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
