<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8614 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-LONGEVITY-ETHICS-     03-06 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-LONGEVITY-ETHICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARGUMENTS OVER LIFE AND THE NEED FOR DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Ill., Calif.)  (The Science Times) 
(DW) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Advances in research in recent years have raised
the possibility of extending human life by decades. At a conference
held here to discuss the consequences of such a development,
scientists described the techniques of extending life, only to be
assailed for presenting a threat to human nature.
</P>
<P>
   Far from accepting greater longevity as a blessing, ethicists
and some theologians offered passionate praise of death. They
argued that life without death would be meaningless and that the
natural ambitions of career and family were satisfied within a life
span of 80 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't ban this research but we can make it socially
despicable,'' said Dr. Daniel Callahan, a biomedical ethicist at
the Hastings Center in Garrison, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Another ethicist, Dr. Leon R. Kass of the University of Chicago,
said, ``The finitude of human life is a blessing for every
individual whether he knows it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference, convened by Dr. Arthur L. Caplan of the
University of Pennsylvania's Center for Bioethics with support from
the John F. Templeton Foundation, brought together scientists and
theologians, but to a large degree the two groups talked past each
other and argued among themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists differed as to whether they would extend life
merely by curing its major diseases or would go beyond that to
tackle the underlying aging process. The theologians often split
along religious lines, with Christians saying that to delay death
was to delay union with God, and a Jew, Rabbi Neil Gilman of the
Jewish Theological Center, declaring that everything possible to
prolong life must be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can violate the Sabbath and Yom Kippur even if they are on
the same day in order to preserve life,'' Gilman said.
</P>
<P>
   In a wry philosophical joke, the conference was held in the
University of Pennsylvania's archaeological museum, under the nose
of a sphinx and in a room displaying artifacts of the Egyptian cult
of immortality.
</P>
<P>
   Enabling people to live 150 to 200 years or more is not an
immediate prospect but has become a matter of speculation after
discoveries about stem cells and other cellular mechanisms, and
success in prolonging the life of certain laboratory animals by
genetic manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have control of genes and gene expression, we can
control the things which are controlled by the genes, like aging
and mortality rates,'' said Dr. Michael R. Rose of the University
of California at Irvine. Rose has stretched the life of laboratory
fruit flies by breeding them in appropriate conditions, proving
that life span is under genetic control.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert P. Lanza of Advanced Cell Technology spoke of plans
to create a remedial patch for failing hearts by cloning an adult's
skin cells and inducing the embryonic cells so formed to develop
into heart cells. The company's work has been confined to cows.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists' projections of a greater human life span were not
universally welcomed. The Rev. Richard J. Neuhaus of the Institute
of Religion and Public Life criticized the search for immortality
as ``a pagan and sub-Christian quest'' and as an enterprise driven
by the ``essentially amoral and mindless dynamic of the
technological imperative joined to an ignoble fear of death.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do pursue this course of extended life, interminably
extended life,'' Neuhaus said, ``I would advise the most informed
and critical resistance at every point along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   After the drubbing from theologians, the researchers came under
assault from ethicists. Kass portrayed immortality as a state
altogether alien from that of being human.
</P>
<P>
   ``To argue that human life is better without death is to argue
human life would be better without being human,'' he said. He
praised the character of the Homeric hero Odysseus, who turned down
the nymph Calypso's offer of being her immortal consort in favor of
mortality and his human duty, that of continuing his hazardous
voyage back to his home and his aged wife, Penelope.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan said research on extending life was part of larger
pattern of misallocation of funds, a focus on fighting death and
lethal diseases rather than learning how to care for people at the
end of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who want medicine to increase life expectancy must show
us what the social and human benefit would be, and this case needs
to be laid out in advance, and we should assess it in the context
of enormous skepticism since no one has shown the present life
expectation is somehow a disaster,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another ethicist, Dr. Ronald Cole-Turner of the Pittsburgh
Theological Seminary, said that a longer life would be positive
because it would focus attention on the meaning of life and ``offer
an opportunity for the blossoming of our humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pure moonshine,'' Callahan retorted.
</P>
<P>
   Kass said he feared that public wisdom would not prevail against
the temptation of immortality. ``While the head might council
finitude, the blood likes to live,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
