u a BC-COLO-GUNS-ART-NYT &LR;      03-06 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-GUNS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORADO PROGRAM WILL PERMIT FEDERAL PROSECUTION IN GUN CRIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Texas, S.C., La., Pa., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT16 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER, Colo. _ It was a rare, almost surreal political moment:
the polar opposites of the enduring national gun debate sharing the
same stage, even applauding each other at introductions.
</P>
<P>
   James S. Brady, a board member of Handgun Control Inc., and
Wayne LaPierre, executive vice president of the National Rifle
Association, joined a dozen federal, state and local officials here
Monday at a news conference to announce that Colorado had become
the latest jurisdiction to inaugurate Project Exile, a program that
uses federal, rather than state courts, to prosecute gun crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a victim, I and many others can tell you it's no fun,''
said Brady, who was White House press secretary in 1981 when he was
shot and paralyzed during an assassination attempt on President
Ronald Reagan. The 1993 federal law that mandates waiting periods
and background checks of gun buyers bears Brady's name. ``Project
Exile is one of many initiatives needed to keep guns out of the
wrong hands,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre said, ``This is the most common-sense program of all.
It gets bad people off the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Project Exile began as a pilot program three years ago in
Richmond, Va., and now operates statewide in Virginia, Texas, South
Carolina and Louisiana, as well as in several cities, including
Rochester, N.Y., and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Its effectiveness relies on federal prosecution of crimes that
are generally left to state and local authorities, with the
expectation that the greater supply of federal prisons and stricter
sentencing guidelines will serve as a deterrent. Officials in
Richmond say crimes involving guns have dropped by 65 percent since
the program began.
</P>
<P>
   Project Exile is one of the few such efforts that has won
support from both gun rights groups like the NRA and from those
that favor tighter restrictions for gun ownership, like the
organization Brady leads with his wife, Sarah, who is president.
</P>
<P>
   To both sides, it is a vivid example of how prosecuting existing
laws can reduce gun violence even if gun control advocates would
favor additional legislation, like laws that would require
background checks for those buying guns from private dealers at gun
shows.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of Colorado's program took on added drama
through the presence of Brady, who has used a wheelchair since he
was shot and still has difficulty speaking. LaPierre said he had
appeared frequently with Mrs. Brady to debate and discuss gun
issues but rarely with her husband.
</P>
<P>
   While the two men sat at opposite sides of the stage and had no
opportunity to interact, LaPierre said he and Brady had chatted
briefly before the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre said several other states were considering programs
like Project Exile. But wherever such programs have begun, they
have achieved only limited support from the Department of Justice,
which has not made street crimes a priority. As a result, the
program largely depends upon community pressure to combat the
illegal use of guns, private donations to support an advertising
campaign that warns would-be criminals of the consequences of
getting caught and a local U.S. attorney who is willing to devote
more resources to street crime.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado has had no shortage of motivation, much of it stemming
from the shootings last April at Columbine High School, where two
students killed 12 other students and a teacher before turning
their guns on themselves. Last month, two more Columbine students
were shot and killed in a sandwich shop for reasons that are still
unclear to investigators. No one has been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Strickland, the U.S. attorney for Colorado, who took office
shortly after the shootings at the school, said he had decided
quickly that a Project Exile program would be worthwhile.
Strickland led efforts that raised more than $600,000 to pay for
billboards and radio and television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he was still uncertain how much more money might
become available from the Justice Department for new prosecutors or
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Strickland said, ``we'll just try to do more with
existing resources, and other things will move to a lower
priority.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
