<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8621 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-LEWIS-VICTIMS07-COX     03-06 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-VICTIMS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Using deceased victims' criminal history part of defense
strategy in Atlanta case
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin and Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ All Pro linebacker Ray Lewis and his two co-defendants
are slated to sit before a jury on murder charges in May. But they
probably won't be the only ones on trial. So, too, may be the dead
men.
</P>
<P>
   According to motions filed in the case, it appears the criminal
backgrounds of victims Jacinth Baker and Richard Lollar will be
scrutinized. Lawyers who follow the case predict Lewis
co-defendants Joseph Sweeting and Reginald Oakley will plead
self-defense and attempt to portray Baker and Lollar as the
aggressors.
</P>
<P>
   Painting a negative portrait of the deceased is a common defense
ploy in stranger-on-stranger killings involving street fights or
bar brawls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the `dude-needed-killing' defense,'' said criminal
defense attorney Dan Summer, who said the strategy allows the
introduction of ``specific bad acts by the deceased.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words, you're trashing the victim's character,'' he
said. ``Unfortunately for the state, that resonates with jurors.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Cook, district attorney in Newton and Walton counties,
agrees that such a defense is common when there is not ``an
innocent victim.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen it used before, and I've seen it sway juries,'' said
Cook.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most famous self-defense successes, recounted in the
best seller ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil,'' was
Savannah antiques dealer Jim Williams, who was acquitted in 1989 of
the fatal shooting of his 22-year-old housemate, Danny Lewis
Hansford.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, in his fourth trial, convinced jurors that he shot
Lewis because the young man was crazed with drugs and alcohol and
was trying to shoot him.
</P>
<P>
   And Sweeting's lawyer, Bruce Harvey, got client Jeff Henry freed
after a Douglas County jury could not reach a verdict on murder
charges in the 1991 shotgun killing of Henry's twin brother. The
shooting occurred during a drunken brawl, and the defense argued
that Greg habitually abused Jeff, who finally snapped.
</P>
<P>
   Making a self-defense claim in the recent stabbing case,
however, may be a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Some eyewitness accounts indicate Lollar and Baker were greatly
outnumbered in the deadly fracas outside Cobalt, a nightclub in
Atlanta's entertainment district, hours after the Super Bowl. At
least one witness said the two men were outnumbered 10 to two.
Another one described seeing six or more on one.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, 21, died of stab wounds to the heart and liver; Lollar,
24, perished from stab wounds to the chest, including one to the
heart, a Fulton County autopsy found.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeting's lawyers have petitioned the court asking to perform
tests on a gun they believe Lollar had at the scene. They claim it
was the gun fired at Lewis' rented limousine as it fled. Oakley's
father said his son told him he was hit over the head with a
champagne bottle. They've also asked to be given the results of
alcohol and drug testing of the victims, saying the tests ``will
tend to show that one or both of the decedents were aggressors.''
</P>
<P>
   And last weekend, an acquaintance of Lewis', Jessica Robertson,
told prosecutors that Lewis and some of his friends believed others
in his group thought they were about to be robbed by the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Baker's autopsy said he was carrying a large plastic bag and six
smaller bags containing what is suspected to be marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Both Lollar and Baker had drug arrest records. Baker was wanted
by police when he died, having violated probation on a gun offense
with a subsequent drug arrest.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1997, Baker fled on foot when the borrowed car he was
driving was stopped by police in his native Akron, Ohio. Police
said they found a loaded .22-caliber pistol and a baggie of
marijuana in the car, according to the Summit County prosecutor's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, who was listed as ``homeless'' in the police report,
pleaded guilty the following month to a lesser charge of improperly
handling a firearm and was given 18 months probation.
</P>
<P>
   Nine months later, Baker was again in a car stopped by Akron
police. This time, an officer said Baker, a passenger, was stuffing
something under the seat. Police say they found 25 grams of crack.
There was also an open container of brandy in the car.
</P>
<P>
   Baker and the driver were charged with possession of cocaine and
possession of an open container of alcohol but Baker missed a court
date 10 days later and a warrant was issued for his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Lollar also had three drug arrests. In June 1996, Akron police
arrested him and charged him with aggravated drug trafficking. The
grand jury did not find enough evidence for felony charges and
Lollar later pleaded guilty, agreeing to pay a $100 fine, according
to Summit County and Akron records. He was arrested again in
September 1996 on marijuana possession charges and got another $100
fine.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1997, he was arrested once more and charged with
marijuana possession and misrepresenting his identification. This
time, he was sentenced to serving 60 days in an Akron halfway
house.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Smith, who grew up in the same Akron neighborhood with the
two victims, was dismayed to hear their arrest records were being
brought up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense is just trying to slander two dead man,'' said
Smith, who finds it incredible that a football star and his cohorts
would feel threatened by the 5-foot-3 Baker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen Ray Lewis on TV, he's a linebacker; Jacinth's
nickname was Shorty,'' said Smith. ``You've got to remember, they
are the victims. They didn't jump on no people. That ain't going to
make it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said contentions that one of the victims had a gun makes no
sense. ``If that man had a gun, then why would he have got
stabbed?'' Smith asked.
</P>
<P>
   Putting victims on trial is risky and can sometimes backfire,
lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't willy nilly raise self-defense and attack the
victims,'' said Mike Mears, who represents indigent death penalty
defendants. ``Ideally, you want to be able to put some weapon of
equal or greater force in the victim's hands. If you're not
successful, you've not only hurt your case, you've alienated the
triers of fact _ the jurors. It can be a risky defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution's challenge will be to keep out any bad
character evidence of the victims, Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's appellate courts have allowed the introduction of a
victim's prior criminal history, if it's relevant. To be admitted
into evidence, the defense must show the judge that the victim was
the aggressor and that the prior offense is related to the claims
being made.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a victim had a prior shoplifting conviction, that wouldn't
be relevant in a murder case,'' Cook said. ``Prior drug convictions
wouldn't either, I believe, if drugs had nothing to do with the
killing.''
</P>
<P>
   Summer, who has tried a number of high-profile murder cases,
said prior histories are not limited to convictions and criminal
charges. ``You can be sure, they're going to find out any
aggressive acts committed by the victims, if there are any,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 1936EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0394 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8622 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LEWIS-VICTIMS07-COX     03-06 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-VICTIMS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Using deceased victims' criminal history part of defense
strategy in Atlanta case
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin and Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
