<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A PRIMARY PRIMER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some of you voters out there may be a tad disappointed about the
way this primary season has worked out. I know you thought that
when the campaign got to your state, the candidates would be up
close and personal, holding town meetings in the high school gym.
But hey, the schedule got crowded. And wasn't that pre-dawn rally
at the airport something?
</P>
<P>
   It's been a busy month since the New Hampshire primary, people.
Here's what's been happening.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 6: John McCain's TV ad says ``there's only one man running
for president who knows the military and understands the world.''
In an interview, McCain denies this is meant to suggest that George
W. Bush doesn't know the military or understand the world.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 11: In South Carolina, McCain comes under assault by
conservatives who call up talk radio, describing him as everything
from a communist spy to the father of multiple illegitimate
children.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 12: McCain begins comparing himself to Luke Skywalker.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 13: Bush, refusing to take a stand on South Carolina's
Confederate flag, warns voters not to ``judge my heart based on a
position on who ought to be flying a flag over what capital.'' Bush
also does not want his heart judged on his appearance at Bob Jones
University or anything Pat Robertson might have been saying over
the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 19: Bush thumps McCain in South Carolina, then McCain
thumps Bush in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 22, more or less: John and Charles Wyly, Texas businessmen
whose family hedge fund handles $96 million worth of investments
from the University of Texas, wake up and spontaneously decide
they're in the mood to spend $2.5 million on ads that unfavorably
compare John McCain's record on the environment with Bush's.
Luckily, their wacky impulse has no connection to the Bush campaign
and therefore is not regulated by campaign laws.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 23: Bill Bradley, attempting to restart his sputtering
campaign in Seattle, volunteers that his favorite grunge band is
Nirvana.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 25: The Bush campaign, which had $70 million a few months
ago, admits it is short of money. Bush asks voters not to judge his
head by the fact that he wasted $2 million buying TV ads for the
primary in McCain's home state.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 26, more or less: The Wyly brothers stumble on an ad
producer who has by coincidence done a lot of work for the state's
Republican Party. He whips them up a commercial that shows McCain,
looking quite a bit like Marley's ghost, floating over a belching
smokestack while Bush's smiling head soars across a pristine
prairie.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 28: Al Gore gives an analysis of American ethnic history to
the Seattle NAACP: ``The African-American experience is unique ...
the Irish-American experience is unique ... all the experiences are
unique ... the African-American experience is uniquely unique.''
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 29, more or less: The Wyly brothers impulsively decide to
target New York, fortuitously hitting on the place where Bush is in
a particularly tough race. In another remarkable coincidence, the
firm they choose to buy TV time turns out to have done work for New
York's governor, George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   March 1: McCain's social conservative allies recoil in horror
when he calls Pat Robertson ``evil.'' The candidate says it was
just part of his Luke Skywalker rap. ``I don't know what's going
on. I'm not a psychiatrist,'' says William Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   March 2: The Republicans debate in Los Angeles with McCain
appearing via satellite. The Arizona senator's chair is occupied by
a TV set, with McCain inside looking like Max Headroom.
</P>
<P>
   In a debate highlight, Bush suggests that requiring trigger
locks on guns might lead to ``trigger lock police knock(ing) on
people's doors saying show me your lock.''
</P>
<P>
   March 3: The Wyly brothers' ad starts running, causing a Sierra
Club spokesman to note that while McCain's record on the
environment is ``poor,'' Bush's is ``terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   March 4: &UR;  &LR;  Bush, currently running radio ads charging that
McCain ``opposes funding for vital breast cancer programs,'' says
he does not believe the senator is opposed to funding for breast
cancer programs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
