<HEADER>
A8626 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DELTA-ADS07-COX     03-06 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-ADS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Delta ads ready for takeoff
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines is about to launch the first ad
campaign by its new agency, Leo Burnett Co.
</P>
<P>
   Television spots for Atlanta-based Delta debut this weekend, and
will be accompanied by a print campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The airline plans to preview the campaign to the media
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a few tactical spots in recent months, it will be the
first fresh effort for Delta since 1997's ``On Top of the World''
campaign by Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi, based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's new management team, which arrived after that campaign
started, gradually curtailed it and moved the airline's account
last year to Chicago-based Leo Burnett.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Burnett created United Airlines' old ``Fly the Friendly
Skies'' theme _ one of the best-remembered taglines in airline
history _ but no longer has United's account.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Reid, Delta's executive vice president-marketing, said the
new Delta spots won't be built around a catchy tagline or a
signature song.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no song, no tagline, just Delta,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The spots ``are more passenger focused than airline focused,''
Reid said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most airlines talk about themselves,'' he said. ``Look at our
wine list, look at our seats, look at us, us, us. But when people
travel they have their own affairs on their minds. ... So the
centerpiece (of advertising) should be the passenger and not the
airline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to say the sky is blue and it's all
wonderful,'' Reid added.
</P>
<P>
   He said the campaign will be ``practical, realistic and maybe a
little humorous.''
</P>
<P>
   Delta advertising in the 1980s and early '90s was defined by
now-classic taglines such as ``Delta is Ready When You Are,'' and
``We Love to Fly and It Shows.'' But in recent years the airline's
advertising hit rough air.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 ``Delta Marathon'' campaign, timed to coincide with the
Atlanta Olympics, flopped. That prompted Delta to dump longtime
Atlanta agency BBDO South and hire Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi.
</P>
<P>
   Reid, who came to Delta in 1998 from Lufthansa, said Saatchi's
ethereal ``On Top of the World'' campaign, with its new age music
theme, was too oblique.
</P>
<P>
   It also came as Delta wrestled with service problems stemming
from mid-'90s financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to fix the deficiencies and then advertise, not the
other way around,'' Reid said. He said Delta's improved on-time
performance and efforts to improve passenger processing at
airports, coupled with more down-to-earth ads, will give the new
campaign more credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
