<HEADLINE>
STOCKS MOVE LOWER AFTER GREENSPAN'S COMMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices moved lower Monday after the three most
important guardians of the United States' financial system said
higher interest rates are needed to cool the economy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the cautionary comments, which were made by Alan
Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve Board, Lawrence Summers,
secretary of the Treasury, and Arthur Leavitt, chairman of the
Securities and Exchange Commission, last week's big run-up in stock
prices provided additional incentive to take some profits out of
equities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as if Greenspan wrote the speech for all of them,'' said
Arthur Hogan, chief market analyst at Jefferies &AMP; Co. ``As the day
wore on and the headlines of what they were saying hit the tape,
the market went down.'' The three officials addressed a conference
held at Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   By the close, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 196.70,
or 1.9 percent, to 10,170.50. IBM, Microsoft, American Express and
Wal-Mart led the decline.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday the Dow gained more than 200 points after February
employment data suggested the economy may be starting to cool.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index slipped 17.89, or 1.3
percent, to 1,391.28, pushed lower by big declines in Exxon-Mobil,
Bristol Myers Squibb and 3Com.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks bucked the trend for much of the session, but
late in the day the Nasdaq composite index began to sag and closed
lower. The Nasdaq finished at 4,904.85, down 9.94, or 0.2 percent.
At one point during the day it was up by as much as 65 points.
Trading was brisk.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, volume was 1.03 billion shares.
On the Nasdaq stock market, 1.9 billion shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   Stock investors have been worried that instead of cooling the
economy, a further series of interest-rate increases by the Fed
will cause the economy to lapse into recession.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the big question,'' said David L. Mead, chief
investment officer at Harris Bank in Chicago. ``I think they will
be able to avoid a hard landing, simply because they have done it
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Mead said the prospect of further increases in interest rates
has not caused him to change his investment strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were to make a change, we would shift money out of
large-cap sectors and into small- and mid-cap stocks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A number of bellwether technology companies had a tough day.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft was one of them. The stock fell 5{ to 90 5/8.
Meantime, Intel dropped 1 7/16 to 117 3/8. And Cisco Systems shed 1
5/16, to 136 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard was one of only three Dow stocks to gain ground.
</P>
<P>
   The stock gained 7 1/8, to 145 9/16, after Agilent Technologies,
which is 85 percent owned by Hewlett-Packard, announced a
switching-technology breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   Agilent closed at 161, up 53.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone-equipment manufacturers had a good day.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel gained 7, to 128. Lucent Technologies was up 2{, to 73
5/8. And Motorola gained 5 5/16, to 180 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   Biotechnology stocks, which have been among the market's leaders
so far this year, turned in a mixed performance.
</P>
<P>
   Amgen fell 1}, to 64 9/16. Genentech was off 19, to 215{. But
Immunex rose 3 11/16, to 248 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Williams Sonoma fell 12}, to 18 1/8, after the seller of kitchen
equipment said earnings for the quarter ended Jan. 30 may be below
Wall Street estimates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
