u p BC-CAMPAIGN-BUSH-BOS &LR;      03-06 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BUSH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH LIGHTS CANDLE AT HOLOCAUST MEMORIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Determined to convey a ``tolerant message of
inclusiveness'' on the eve of the March 7 primaries, Governor
George W. Bush addressed a gathering at a Los Angeles Holocaust
museum, then donned a yarmulke to light a memorial candle before
television cameras at a ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, indeed, tried on many hats throughout the day. Immediately
after touring an exhibit of Jewish death camps, he raced across Los
Angeles to appear on the ``Tonight Show'' with Jay Leno, hoping to
compensate for an awkward comedic appearance on David Letterman
last week. Earlier in the day, he shook hands with San Diego
Republicans over the sounds of a steel kettle drum band.
</P>
<P>
   But the main event was his trip to the Simon Wiesenthal Center,
purposely scheduled one week after his rival, Senator John S.
McCain, gave a speech lambasting Christian conservative leaders Pat
Robertson and Jerry Falwell as intolerant. Despite its intention,
that McCain speech has since brought the Arizona severe criticism
for being ``divisive,'' and has been widely blamed for the scope of
Virginia primary loss.
</P>
<P>
   Bush sought Monday to capitalize on that misstep. Communications
director Karen Hughes said the sudden outreach to the Jewish
community was ``designed to provide a stark contrast between the
message of divisiveness McCain delivered last week and our message
of unity.'' And as he wandered through the exhibit during a
40-minute tour, listening to historical accounts from the center's
founder, Rabbi Marvin Hier, Bush appeared moved.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, during a brief speech, Bush called the museum ``a
monument to the power of truth over falsehood.'' He also lauded the
museum for not allowing anti-Semitism to go unexposed, saying:
``Tolerance can never be assumed, and it must always be taught.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not respond to a member of the crowd who interjected:
``What about gay people?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his wife also signed a guest book signed in 1988 by his
father. The insciption by Vice President George Bush read: ``With
solemn appreciation for the spirit of remembrance.'' Monday his son
wrote: ``God bless this world!''
</P>
<P>
   With the Republican nomination in his sights, Bush and his
advisors also continued to map out a campaign fundraising plan to
raise an additional $5 to $10 million before the party convention
in late summer.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has spent some $60 million of the $70 million he
raised early on, once hoped to sail into the general election with
his war chest brimming. With most of it spent battling McCain, Bush
now faces a delicate dilemma if he becomes the nominee: Challenging
Vice President on campaign finance abuses while raising millions
more for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Because while Bush would automatically receive millions if he
were the nominee, he is leaving nothing to chance, scheduling
between 10 and 12 dozen fundraising events that he will personally
attend in upcoming months, advisors said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will appear at fundraisers in New York, New Jersey,
Maryland and Florida, among other places, his national finance
chairman, Don Evans, said. He is planning to raise money in
Illinois at an event next Thursday. And behind the scenes, Bush
fundraisers are already working aggressively to raise money through
direct mailings, Internet solicitations and surrogate fundraising
events.
</P>
<P>
   Evans insisted the campaign had always planned to continue
fundraising past March 7. ``We have yet to tap the vast number of
Americans that are starved for leadership. It takes a long time to
communicate with people all across America,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``It is safe to say we do have, and we will
continue to have, what we need through the convention.'' But, asked
how things would have been different without McCain's potent
challenge, Evans said, chuckling: ``Would we have spent less? We
probably would have spent less.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush planned to return late Monday night to his home in Austin,
where he hoped to hold a victory rally Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
