<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-RADIO07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cox Radio expands with $380 million deal in 2 markets
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cox Radio will sign on in two new markets under a $380
million cash deal announced Monday with Clear Channel
Communications. The price makes it the biggest acquisition to date
for Cox Radio, according to Robert Neil, president and chief
executive of the Atlanta-based broadcaster.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Radio agreed to buy three FM stations in Houston, and three
FM stations and one AM station in Richmond, Va. The former is the
eighth-largest radio revenue market, the latter the 47th, Cox Radio
said.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity to enter those markets came as part of Clear
Channel Communications' planned divestiture ahead of its takeover
of AMFM Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Clear Channel, based in San Antonio, announced agreements Monday
to sell a total of 72 stations in 27 markets. Infinity Broadcasting
and several other buyers were involved as well.
</P>
<P>
   The deal follows a familiar pattern for Cox Radio: Buy a mix of
stations, in terms of age and performance, with a preference for
the Sun Belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We prefer Sun Belt markets because they are growing faster
than the radio industry as a whole,'' said Neil.
</P>
<P>
   Neil said the purchase price works out to less than 18 times
broadcast cash flow for this year _ net revenue less station
operating expense _ for the established stations. ``It's on par
with what we've paid for good properties in the past,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, analyst Ed Hatch of SG Cowen Securities estimated
Infinity Broadcasting agreed to pay about 21 times cash flow for
the stations it bought, according to Dow Jones News Service.
</P>
<P>
   One of the stations Cox Radio will acquire in Houston is
KTBZ-FM, a new licensee. Cox Radio will buy the name and format of
KLDE-FM, also in Houston, and then switch KLDE-FM to the frequency
now used by KTBZ-FM, Neil said.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Radio, which counts itself the fifth-biggest radio company
in the United States in net revenue, said it expects to complete
the acquisition in the second half of the year, pending regulatory
approval. The company is controlled by Atlanta-based Cox
Enterprises Inc., which owns The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
