</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-STRIKE-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING ENGINEERS FIND UNITY AND DEFIANCE ON THE PICKET LINE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUKWILA, Wash. _ The chants and placards along the picket lines
outside the Boeing Co.'s jet plants are a bit unusual. ``No nerds,
no birds,'' proclaims one sign. And many Boeing engineers, most on
strike for the first time in their lives, say they are stunned at
how unified their group has become in the face of its dispute with
the giant aircraft manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, if you get six engineers in a room, you'll get 12
different opinions,'' explained Steve Love, a 45-year-old flight
test engineer who was warming his hands over a burning barrel on
the picket line here the other day. ``Well, Boeing has somehow
managed to get 19,000 of us together with one thought and one goal,
and that's a better contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Now nearing its fifth week, the increasingly bitter protest here
by the Society of Professional Engineering Employees in Aerospace
has mushroomed into one of the largest strikes by white-collar
workers against a private company in years. It is an unexpectedly
fierce action by a group long considered a union in name only,
whose sole act of defiance in its 56-year history was a one-day
walkout in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   For the company, which has clearly stirred up deep resentment
among the engineers by failing to offer 10 percent cash signing
bonuses and other terms of a contract it reached last summer with
its larger machinists' union, the strike is posing growing
problems. Boeing recently announced, for instance, that the strike
had already delayed 15 of 42 commercial jet deliveries planned for
February, and such delays will likely worsen if a settlement is not
reached soon, since many of the striking engineers are needed under
federal law to certify new airplanes as flightworthy.
</P>
<P>
   But for national labor leaders, who have rushed in to help the
strikers, the walkout is clearly seen as a major test of their
ability to organize a potentially large segment of the work force:
professional workers, like many of the engineers here, who complain
of both relentless pressure in the workplace and salaries that they
feel do not reflect their contributions to the booming national
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Labor has already scored once-unthinkable successes in
organizing doctors, especially in California and Florida, who are
especially angry at the intrusions of insurance companies on their
salaries and relationships with patients. It is making determined
efforts, with somewhat less success so far, to organize the
high-tech workers who are a huge part of the economy here in the
Seattle area and in Silicon Valley. And because the high-profile
battle the engineers are waging here is likely to resonate far
beyond the corridors of Boeing, organized labor is manning the
ramparts in a bid to help them win.
</P>
<P>
   John Sweeney, president of the AFL-CIO, with which the
engineers' union voted to affiliate a few months ago, visited the
picket lines this week, and the federation's secretary-treasurer,
Richard Trumka, the former head of the United Mine Workers, is due
in town Tuesday. Both have promised money and help to the striking
union, and Sweeney said the Boeing strike was an excellent example
of how disgruntled white-collar workers could rally to press for
better contracts and health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a whole area of the new economy that organized labor
would very much like to be involved in,'' said Harley Shaiken, a
labor specialist at the University of California at Berkeley. ``For
many white-collar workers, there's just a volatile combination of
feelings that they are underappreciated and not sharing fully in
the benefits of this supposedly booming economy. This strike
underscores what we've seen with doctors, teachers, now engineers _
there are many professionals who are feeling that they are the
proletariat of the information age.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the engineers prevail here and get a better contract, it
remains to be seen, of course, whether organized labor can ever
forge a truly broad-based coalition between many of these
professionals and the lower-wage workers it continues to try to
organize with major campaigns like the Justice for Janitors
movement.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, here in the Seattle area, there is no question
that the ``brains behind the planes,'' as the engineers are
sometimes called, are marching in the picket lines, and that
truckers and other union workers who drive by the Boeing plants
here constantly blow their horns in support. (Some drivers making
deliveries have declined to cross the picket lines; the machinists
and other Boeing unions are contractually prohibited from stopping
work in support of another union's strike at the company.)
</P>
<P>
   Many Boeing engineers, who typically hold advanced degrees and
whose salaries range from $37,000 to $128,000, express frustration
at having to haggle over contract terms in a region where it seems
like so many other smart, ambitious people are becoming dot-com
millionaires. Many also expressed bitterness over the huge bonuses
received by many corporate executives, including those at Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   But an even more immediate factor in this strike seems to be the
engineers' perception that the company is trying to play hardball
with them while, the engineers say, it basically gave in to the
machinists' union. The company reached a deal with the machinists
last summer as it was eager to achieve labor peace in the face of a
huge backlog of orders; many analysts described the pact as
extremely generous, and labor leaders described it as a major
victory.
</P>
<P>
   That pact, which headed off what would have been the third
walkout by the machinists in the last 10 years, was approved
overwhelmingly by the 44,000-member union. It raised hourly wages
by nearly 16 percent over three years, and contained a one-time
bonus averaging $4,400 per worker.
</P>
<P>
   It is undeniable that the engineers are incensed, and that
resentment is palpable in the analogies that the engineer union's
executive director, Charles Bofferding, uses to describe the
strike. He likened Boeing's management to the schoolyard bully who
declined to pick a fight with the class jock _ in this case, the
machinists, the largest union at Boeing _ ``and instead they see
the little kid in the corner with the glasses and they say, `Here,
let's slap him around a little bit.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, guess what?'' said Bofferding in an interview. ``What
they don't realize is, the kid with the glasses has been taking
kung fu. So watch out.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The union represents a broad array of engineers and technical
workers with varying levels of training, though those workers are
not required to join the union. The engineers' salaries average
about $63,000; technical workers pay ranges from $21,000 a year to
$81,000, with an average of $45,000.
</P>
<P>
   Since contract negotiations began in October, more than 3,000
eligible workers have joined the union; while less than half of
those eligible to join had done so last year, the figure now is
nearly two-thirds _ 13,329 out of 20,683 workers in the
``bargaining unit'' are represented by the union. And even some of
those who do not belong to the union are out on the picket lines.
The union says 19,000 of the workers in the bargaining unit are out
on strike; Boeing estimates that the number is about 17,000.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A Boeing spokesman, Peter Conte, said the company had made
several generous offers to the union. Last week, however, Boeing
formally declared an impasse, and this last weekend it announced it
would attempt to impose the terms of its last contract offer on the
engineers, a bid to force them back to work that the union insisted
would not shake its resolve.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the engineers say they have never supported unions, and
as one put it: ``All that brotherhood and sisterhood stuff kind of
made me sick. I mean, these are my co-workers, they're not my
brothers and sisters.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is changing. Jim Davis, a 64-year-old maintenance
programs engineer who spent 27 years in the Navy and has spent the
last 15 at Boeing, decided earlier this year to join the engineers'
union.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've really been pretty much an anti-union person,'' said
Davis, who holds advanced degrees in aeroengineering and systems
management. ``I never, ever thought I'd see the day that I went out
on strike. I still can't quite believe I'm out here on a picket
line. But Boeing pushed me over the edge. I think they've been
unreasonable and unresponsive to some truly unhappy engineers and
technical workers.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bill Sandell, a 34-year-old liaison engineer on the picket line,
said he thought unions were for other kinds of workers, not
engineers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognize their place for other people,'' he said. ``But
philosophically, I didn't want to be represented by a labor union.
I wanted to be represented by my training, my experience and my
abilities. I really thought that was my bargaining chip. But now, I
feel like joining a union was really the only effective way to make
my voice heard at this company.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Tom Claps, 37, a flight test engineer, said he was amazed to
watch his fellow engineers, holding signs, chanting and throwing
more wood in the blazing barrel to keep themselves warm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot for a bunch of engineers to get up and walk out
the door,'' he said. ``The rocket scientists are literally out on
the streets here. It's kind of incredible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 1950EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
