u i BC-JAPAN-POLICE-ART-2TAK     03-06 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-POLICE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISDEEDS BY ONCE-HONORED POLICE DISMAY THE JAPANESE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KYOTO, Japan _ In the playground of Hino Primary School here,
where a second-grader was stabbed to death in front of his
classmates in December, little evidence remains of the horrific
crime that traumatized the nation, even though Japan has slowly
been growing accustomed to more violence.
</P>
<P>
   But a botched police investigation into the slaying has made it
much harder for adults of this ancient capital city to recover. In
February, a 21-year-old man who was the prime suspect in the
stabbing escaped during questioning by six police investigators,
then plunged to his death from a nearby roof, an apparent suicide.
</P>
<P>
   TheKyoto blunder was the latest in a series of errors and
scandals involving police departments across the country that has
led many people to conclude that Japan's police, once celebrated as
a model of honesty and competence, may in fact be both corrupt and
inept.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't trust the police, and I don't think people can depend
on them for protection or to solve a crime when it happens,'' said
Toshiji Okada, a Kyoto food vendor. ``There have been so many
incidents of police wrongdoing that we don't know what or who to
believe anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Barely a day has passed in recent months on which newspaper
headlines have not reported another case of police corruption and
negligence, including drug abuse, extortion, bribery, sexual
assault, false reports, hazing of fellow officers and coverups.
</P>
<P>
   The scandals have prompted a political debate over what measures
are needed to increase oversight of the police and promote reform.
The police corruption cases have occurred as crime has risen,
apparently fueled by a decade of economic decline, in a society
with traditionally low crime rates.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent public opinion poll conducted by the newspaper
Yomiuri Shimbun, 60 percent of Japanese surveyed said that their
trust in the police had declined in recent years; 45 percent said
they did not trust the police at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was young, we had faith in the police and we could be
proud of them because they stood for something,'' said an elderly
Kyoto man, standing in front of the building where the stabbing
suspect perished. ``Today the police are a shame and an
embarrassment for all of Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the first scandals to focus nationwide attention on
police corruption occurred last year in Kanagawa prefecture, where
police officials were found to have concealed an investigator's
illegal drug use and to have obtained seminude photographs of a
female officer that they used to extort money from her. Kanagawa
police officials were also found to have abused younger colleagues
with beatings and gunplay.
</P>
<P>
   In a case in Hokkaido prefecture, a police sergeant was
sentenced to four and a half years in prison after being convicted
in February of repeatedly raping and molesting female convicts.
Investigators said the sergeant was able to pull off the sexual
abuse by sending his partner to patrol other areas of the police
station while he sneaked into the detention center unsupervised.
</P>
<P>
   In another widely publicized scandal in Niigata prefecture, 160
miles north of Tokyo, two senior police officials were forced to
resign in February over a series of blunders involving the case of
a 19-year-old woman who had been held captive for nine years.
</P>
<P>
   After being informed of the extraordinary case on the night the
teen-ager was rescued, the Niigata police chief left the
investigation to subordinates, while he wined and dined and played
board games with an investigator from the National Police Agency at
a hot spring inn until the early morning.
</P>
<P>
   The police chief later approved a plan to issue a false news
release that credited the Niigata police with finding the woman,
though she had in fact been discovered at the home of her
37-year-old abductor by health care officials, who had been drawn
there by his erratic behavior. The national police investigator had
been sent to Niigata to perform a routine department inspection
that was aimed at restoring public trust in the police.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Niigata police later admitted that when the woman was
reported missing in 1990, they had made no effort to contact the
man who turned out to have abducted her, even though he had
previously been arrested in an abduction case involving another
girl.
</P>
<P>
   Although both of the partying police officials were found to be
derelict in their duties and were forced to resign, they were
allowed to receive a pension, which caused widespread public
outrage. Police departments across Japan were inundated with
telephone calls and e-mail messages from people expressing anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their behavior lacked judgment and was inappropriate and
inexcusable,'' Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi said, referring to the
case at a parliamentary budget committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi's chief spokesman said that while the reprimand of the
two police officials was inadequate, there was little the
government could do because police supervision resides solely in
the hands of the National Public Safety Commission.
</P>
<P>
   But the commission is basically a rubber stamp for the
autonomous National Police Agency, which nominates its members and
is the main source of research and advice for them.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to public outrage over the Niigata case, the public
safety commission did reprimand the director of the National Police
Agency, Setsuo Tanaka, for failing to supervise its investigator
adequately. Tanaka, who is also the leader of the safety
commission, was penalized with a 5 percent pay cut.
</P>
<P>
   Tanaka was put in charge of the agency, which oversees Japan's
230,000 police officers, in January, after Yuko Sekiguchi resigned
in the wake of the scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few years ago, the police were Japan's pride and joy.
Revered around the world for their high morals and ethics and
devotion to duty, Japanese police were considered virtually
incorruptible and highly efficient in solving crimes. The Japanese
community-policing concept was widely emulated by New York and
other major cities.
</P>
<P>
   But the recent scandals, particularly the Kyoto and Niigata
cases, have severely damaged the reputation of the police and
raised questions about their ability to solve even basic crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials have said that as a result of the scandals,
officers are finding the public less cooperative in helping them
investigate crimes, and that some citizens have taken to scolding
officers about the corruption when they receive traffic violations
or other reprimands.
</P>
<P>
   Masamitsu Miura, planning officer for the national police
personnel division, said in an interview that it would not be easy
to regain the public's confidence. Miura said that his agency is
undertaking a series of reforms, including increased supervision
and better education, to avoid what he called ``mistakes in
judgment'' that led to many of the blunders.
</P>
<P>
   ``People expect us to solve crime incidents and remove the worry
from their lives,'' he said. ``These are our basic duties. By
pursuing these basic duties, we think that we can recover the
public's confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kyoto police said that they found evidence in the dead
suspect's home that proves that he killed the elementary school
student _ including a note saying he had committed the killing. He
left a note at the school saying that he had a grudge against it.
</P>
<P>
   But the school principal, Takeshi Shimokura, is taking no
chances. He has locked the school's gates and hired additional
teachers to monitor the students on the playground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very disappointed that police let the killer run away,''
Shimokura said. ``Not as the principal of the school but as a
father and an educator, I wanted to know why he did such a terrible
thing and what was troubling him. Hopefully we can use that
knowledge to prevent other children from growing up and doing the
same.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
