u f BC-COKE-REPORT07-COX     03-06 0335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-REPORT07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coca-Cola insists it's more than soft drinks in report
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For nearly three months, Coca-Cola Co. Chairman Doug
Daft has been saying that the company is in the beverage business _
not the soft drink business.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Coca-Cola's annual report hammers the point home.
</P>
<P>
   The company redefines its worldwide market, substituting
``non-alcoholic ready-to-drink-beverages'' for plain-old ``soft
drinks.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the annual report said, its global market share is
now 18 percent _ not 51 percent. And when you've had problems with
antitrust regulators _ as Coca-Cola did last year _ a smaller
market share can be a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Doug Daft and now the Coca-Cola Co. look at the
beverage industry as much more than carbonated soft drinks, and
they realize they are a smaller player in a bigger universe,'' said
John Sicher, editor and publisher of Beverage Digest.
</P>
<P>
   In the annual report, the company emphasizes the importance of
its wide range of brands. While Coke Classic, Diet Coke, Sprite and
Fanta are key brands, there are 228 others, including Dasani water,
Minute Maid juices and Georgia Coffee, which is sold in Japan, not
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company is seeking to become more active and competitive
in the liquid, nonalcoholic beverage market around the world,''
said Andrew Conway, an analyst for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``I
think it has everything to do with growth. Noncarbs are growing
faster than carbonated soft drinks.''
</P>
<P>
   The annual report also makes little mention of M. Douglas
Ivester, who retired as chairman and chief executive last month
after a troublesome two years at the helm and a total of 20 years
at the company.
</P>
<P>
   In Daft's four-page letter to shareholders, he mentions Ivester
in one sentence: ``I appreciate the counsel and friendship of my
predecessor, Doug Ivester.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
