<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN WARNS OF INFLATION THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The nation's economic boom could be halted by a burst
of inflation unless growth can be slowed to a more sustainable
level, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan warned that the United States can't keep up its
current pace of growth, with a surging stock market fueling
consumer spending and a tight labor market creating wage pressures.
He hinted the central bank, at its March 21 meeting, will again
raise interest rates to slow the galloping economy.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Fed is vigilant about fighting inflation, Greenspan
said, the benefits brought by increased productivity ``are at risk
of being undermined by financial and economic instability.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's latest warnings struck a sobering note at a
conference at Boston College on ``The New Economy,'' hosted by US
Representative Edward J. Markey, a Massachusetts Democrat. About
1,800 business leaders attended the conference, which explored the
impact of technology. Speakers included US Treasury Secretary
Lawrence H. Summers and founders of cutting-edge Internet
companies, such as Monster.com, Lycos, and Sycamore Networks.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan and other speakers, including the chairman of the
Securities and Exchange Commission, said this New Economy has
created new huge risks, as well as opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   After the audience rose to sing ``Happy Birthday, Mr. Chairman''
and Markey presented a 74th-birthday cake, Greenspan delivered an
analysis that contributed to a retreat on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, which gained 505 last week,
slid 196.70 Monday to close at 10,170.50, as 26 of the index's 30
stocks declined.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq, dominated by technology stocks, retreated from
Friday's record, dropping 9.94 to 4904.85.
</P>
<P>
   More than three stocks fell for every two that rose on the New
York Stock Exchange. The 500-stock Standard &AMP; Poor's index lost
9.94, closing at 1391.28.
</P>
<P>
   Although Greenspan repeated arguments first presented in
testimony last month in Congress, analysts interpreted his speech
as a signal rates would be raised, perhaps by a quarter point, at
the upcoming meeting. If the Fed acts, it would be the fifth rate
hike since last June.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed chairman cited two forces creating ``imbalances'' that
threaten the economy: wage pressures, due to a labor shortage, and
a soaring stock market, which drove a remarkable 6.9% annual growth
rate in the fourth quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Summers, speaking to The Boston Globe's
editorial board after leaving the conference Monday, said so-called
imbalances in the job market could be eased by bringing more
marginalized workers into the work &UR;  &LR; force, such as welfare-to-work
candidates or disabled workers.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage of workers is an ``imbalance that needs to be
addressed,'' by government policies, said Summers, who was a
professor of economics at Harvard University before joining the
Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Notable in Greenspan's speech was a suggestion there is a dark
side to rising worker productivity, which is typically seen as a
force keeping inflation at bay.
</P>
<P>
   The downside of high productivity gains, Greenspan said, is that
it adds to the scorching pace of growth and creates ``an even
greater increase in aggregate demand than in potential aggregate
supply.'' The result, he said, is ``higher expectations for
long-term corporate earnings,'' which drives the stock market even
higher and fuels consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation adds another dimension to the stock market. SEC
Chairman Arthur Levitt said there has been a sharp rise in recent
months of investing through the use of margin accounts _ basically,
borrowing money to invest in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of margin debt has surged even faster than the stock
market,'' Levitt said. ``I am very concerned about investors
borrowing on other assets, such as homes and real estate, to invest
in our markets.''
</P>
<P>
   A representative of the Internet economy, David Wetherall, chief
executive of CMGI, a holding company that invests in Internet
concerns, said that the New Economy has only begun to unfold.
</P>
<P>
   Within the decade, ``we're going to see an increase in Internet
viewing time of 150 to 300 times what it is today,'' Wetherall
said. ``We're only in the early innings.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Zarb, the chief executive of the National Association of
Securities Dealers Inc., an organization of traders, urged that
investors look beyond stories of high-priced stocks to the benefits
of technology.
</P>
<P>
   Zarb said that the Nasdaq's volume has risen to more than 2
billion trades per day from about 700 million just over a year ago.
The ``dot-com'' and Internet companies fueling this trading spree
``are reinventing the way you and I live,'' by changing the
economy's structure and adding jobs, Zarb said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
