<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0417 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8656 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-SEC-KENTUCKY07-CO     03-06 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SEC-KENTUCKY07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Smith, this Kentucky team `special'
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Ky. _ In December, Kentucky's record was 4-4. That
would be unacceptable at many major programs, but downright sinful
in these parts. And so, the clamoring resounded all over the Blue
Grass State, from the doubters' mouths to Tubby Smith's ears.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's March now, and Lexington is hearing a different kind
of uproar. For sure, they are wild about the Wildcats again, and
for good reason. The coach did not allow the criticism to
demoralize him or his team. Rather, he executed what he called his
``most satisfying'' season ever as coach, including Kentucky's
national championship in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have to say it is,'' Smith said about this season, which
brings his team to Atlanta for the SEC Tournament at 22-8 and
conference co-champions. ``We've gone through a lot. The death of
(touted recruit) John Stewart. The (three) transfers. We've got 10
guys and that's who we go with. So, to be where we are, we've
probably achieved more than any team I've ever had and certainly
more than any that's been through here in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 title team was laced with experienced holdovers from
the Rick Pitino era _ Wayne Turner, Scott Padgett, Nazr Muhammad,
Jeff Shepard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys on that ('98) team all knew; they had been there
before,'' Smith said. ``For this group to be here, to grow as it
has, is special. When we were 4-4, people were ready to give up on
us. But the kids battled back and achieved one of our goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Another goal is the SEC Tournament title, and the Wildcats come
to Atlanta with confidence. The Wildcats have won seven of the last
eight conference tournaments; Smith is 16-1 in March as Kentucky's
coach; and his team won five of its last six games, including the
convincing 85-70 defeat of Florida, to finish 12-4 in the
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``For this group to get where we are is a great statement,''
Smith said. ``Adversity makes you stronger, and this is as strong a
team as I've been around.''
</P>
<P>
   Guard Saul Smith, his son, said: ``Nothing feels better than
knowing you earned what you've gotten. No one has given us
anything. We've fought for what we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who knows Kentucky basketball knows that March has been
special.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like when the full moon is out and the werewolf changes
form,'' Saul Smith said. ``We're like that. March is here and we're
changing form, getting right.''
</P>
<P>
   Right from the start, Kentucky athletics director C.M. Newton
said the Wildcats could be formidable _ if they could find reliable
offense to go with their fierce defense, led by Smith and freshman
Keith Bogans on the perimeter and center Jamaal Magloire and
sophomore Jules Camara inside.
</P>
<P>
   On offense, Bogans and forward Tayshaun Prince can be deadly
from the perimeter, even if they aren't consistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said that if we start shooting, watch out,''
Newton said. ``It's hard to look pretty when you're missing. But
the job Tubby has done this year has been tremendous. For us to
keep winning when the team does not shoot well is just a great
coaching job. We've played one of the toughest schedules in the
nation. But we've continued to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The unconfirmed but persistent rumors of Tubby Smith to the NBA
continue to circulate. But last week, Smith said, ``I've got a team
to coach. That's where my interest is.''
</P>
<P>
   Other rumblings imply he has grown weary of the overreaction in
Kentucky to every loss and the criticism for relying on Saul Smith
to run the offense. ``Coming here, you never know what to expect as
the coach,'' he said. ``But this job is everything as advertised _
and more.''
</P>
<P>
   That statement could be taken as something other than positive.
But Smith does have strong reasons to stay: He's got one of the top
five college coaching jobs in the nation; and Saul is a junior and
Magloire is the only senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't pay attention to that stuff,'' Newton said about the
rumors. ``That's a bunch of Internet garbage. Tubby and I have a
great agreement, the same agreement I had with (Pitino): If there
is any other job out there of interest, I'm the first to know.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats, undefeated at the Georgia Dome in Smith's era, are
overflowing with optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is it about Atlanta for us?'' Tubby Smith asked. ``I
guess we're familiar with the place, for one. Our fans can easily
get there, so that helps. And we've just played well in domes.
We're comfortable there.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of it rides on the play of Saul Smith at the point.
Kentucky fans have been hard on him, some suggesting that his role
is increased because he is the coach's son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned from G.G. (Saul's brother, who played for his father
at Georgia) about playing for my dad,'' he said. ``The big thing he
told me was to be myself. Don't try to do too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great situation. If I could do it all over again, I'd
be right at Kentucky, playing for my dad with my mom and brothers
watching. And now we've got a chance to do something big. It's time
for us to play our best ball. What can be better than this?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
