<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8657 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-DEMOCRATS07-COX     03-06 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BRADLEY REMAINS HOPEFUL, BUT GORE LOOKING AHEAD
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD and KEN FOSKETT
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Vice President Al Gore, in the final day of
campaigning before Super Tuesday, aimed squarely at Republicans as
he vowed to make health care reform one of the main issues this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's sole challenger, Bill Bradley, pinned his presidential
hopes on come-from-behind wins in New England and his native
Missouri while urging New Yorkers to send a ``powerful message to
this country that we want a new politics and a new day.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's speech Monday to health care workers at a Brooklyn
medical center reflected his confidence that he is one the verge of
locking up the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to make health care one of the principal issues in
this election campaign,'' Gore said in criticizing the positions
taken by the Republican candidates, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
and Sen. John McCain of Arizona, on a host of health-related
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Gore singled out Bush for special criticism, charging that Texas
ranks 49th in providing health care for children and 50th in health
coverage for women. ``That's dead last,'' he said. ``You've got to
work at that.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that the Republicans oppose meaningful health care
reforms because they have sided with pharmaceutical and insurance
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he would advocate a patients' bill of rights that
would ``take medical decisions out of the hands of bureaucrats and
accountants,'' and that he would move toward universal health care
for all Americans, beginning with expanded federal programs
covering children.
</P>
<P>
   He said the patients' bill of rights measure proposed by Bush
and McCain was ``phony,'' failing to cover 100 million Americans.
He joked that it reminded him of the veterinarian and the
taxidermist who went into business together, advertising: ``Either
way you get your dog back.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore did not begin his campaign for the Democratic presidential
nomination advocating a bold approach to health care reforms. But
Bradley's push for universal access to coverage has forced the vice
president to make more dramatic proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Gore planned to visit St. Louis on Monday evening before
returning to Nashville on Tuesday to watch the election returns.
</P>
<P>
   Before his visit to the Brooklyn medical center, he addressed a
conference of Jewish leaders to reiterate his support for Israel
and to the peace process begun during the Clinton presidency.
</P>
<P>
   He also visited briefly with New York gay and lesbian leaders
before stopping to see his daughter, Karenna, and grandson, Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley campaigned in New York City and suburban Westchester
County before ending his day at a get-out-the-vote rally in a park
behind the New York City Library.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 800 curious onlookers and die-hard supporters turned
out for his last official campaign rally before Tuesday's balloting
in 15 states and American Samoa.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign chairman Doug Berman said the mood among staffers was
one of ``determined optimism that tomorrow we will surprise
people.''
</P>
<P>
   But the presence of so many of Bradley's top aides lent an air
finality to the event, as if staff members wanted to hear one last
time the candidate whom they have supported for more than 14
months.
</P>
<P>
   When Bradley arrived at the rally, he rushed to greet Tom
O'Donnell, vice president of the International Brotherhood of
Teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping for a miracle,'' O'Donnell said after Bradley moved
on. ``I hope this works out for him. Maybe he doesn't need a
miracle, but he needs a hell of a good showing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is everyone ready to do it on Tuesday?'' Bradley shouted from
the stage. Smiling broadly, he tossed some ``Bill Bradley''
baseball caps to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``This campaign is me running for Super Tuesday,'' Bradley
shouted. ``But it's also about you and your future. ... And after
tomorrow, we are going on to the next campaign and the next
campaign and the next campaign!''
</P>
<P>
   After the rally, Bradley lingered to sign more autographs and
shake more hands. He said he was hoping for victories in Vermont,
Maine, Connecticut, Rhode Island and Missouri. Despite yawning
polls, Bradley also said he was not prepared to ``write off'' New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett's e-mail address is kenf(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
