<SLUG> BC-BKC-CREMINS-NEXT07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cremins plugs Peterson for successor
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech basketball coach Bobby Cremins has
expressed a desire that Appalachian State's Buzz Peterson be
considered as his replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, who last year was among the finalists for the Georgia
job that went to Jim Harrick, captured the Southern Conference
Tournament title Sunday with an upset of the College of Charleston.
With the victory, Appalachian State secured its first NCAA
appearance since 1979, when Cremins was the coach.
</P>
<P>
   A former North Carolina player, Peterson was out of the office
Monday and could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Yellow Jackets athletics director Dave Braine will not comment
on the search until someone is hired. But Braine is thought to be
seeking a coach with a record of recruiting success at a school
with high academic standards, similar to Tech's.
</P>
<P>
   Being mentioned as possible choices are Tommy Amaker of Seton
Hall, Dayton's Oliver Purnell, Xavier's Skip Prosser and former
Tech assistant Perry Clark of Tulane.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Kent, head coach of surprising Oregon, who guided St.
Mary's (Calif.) to an NCAA Tournament appearance and was an
assistant at Stanford, is a hot candidate, as are Tulsa's Bill Self
and Miami's Leonard Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   No decision is expected until after the season ends for the
Jackets. They play Florida State on Thursday in the ACC Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cremins has said that first-year Tech assistant Mark
Price, who some speculated might be interested in pursuing the head
coaching job, would prefer an opportunity to stay on the staff of
the incoming coach.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Reese, another first-year assistant and former Tech
player, was a successful high school coach at Landmark Christian
Academy. The Atlanta native is highly regarded in state high school
circles and could be an asset to the next coach.
</P>
<P>
   But Kevin Cantwell, Tech's associate head coach, who assisted
and then succeeded Cremins at Appalachian State, will move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get a head coaching job,'' Cantwell said. ``I'll
just keep an eye out on what might become available.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
