<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CHILE: PINOCHET IMMUNITY CHALLENGED
</P>
<P>
   Judge Juan Guzman Tapia requested that the Appeals Court revoke
Gen. Augusto Pinochet's immunity so that he can proceed with
indictments against the former dictator involving charges of
torture, kidnappings and executions. Should the Appeals Court
agree, Pinochet's lawyers can be expected to appeal the decision to
the Supreme Court. Pinochet has been a senator for life, a position
that grants him broad immunity from prosecution, since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: TAKEOVER AT UNIVERSITY
</P>
<P>
   About 60 hooded protesters carrying clubs and rocks took over
the building that houses the offices of the president of the
National Autonomous University of Mexico in Mexico City. The
demonstrators, who broke windows and cut through steel bars to
enter the building, demanded the release of dozens of students
jailed after the police ended a 10-month strike at the university
on Feb. 6.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: BLAIR TO VISIT
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain will on Friday become the
first Western leader to visit Russia since Acting President
Vladimir Putin took office. A spokesman for 10 Downing Street said
the agenda includes Russia's military campaign in Chechnya.
``Nobody is pretending we like what is going on there,'' he said,
adding that Blair will argue that ``these problems cannot be solved
by force without a political process.''
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: `RED KEN' BREAKS PLEDGE
</P>
<P>
   Ken Livingstone, a Labor left-winger known as ``Red Ken,''
defied Prime Minister Tony Blair by declaring himself an
independent candidate for mayor of London. He acknowledged that he
was breaking a pledge not to break ranks with his party but said he
was justified because the choice of the official Labor candidate in
the May 4 election, former Health Secretary Frank Dobson, was
``rigged.'' Blair said Livingstone as mayor would be a ``a disaster
in terms of crime and police and business.''
</P>
<P>
   SWITZERLAND: VOTE ON U.N.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of joining the United Nations have collected enough
signatures _ more than 125,000 _ to force a popular vote on
membership. The last effort, in 1986, was resoundingly defeated
even though Geneva is the U.N.'s European headquarters. A
nationwide vote will be held within three years.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: REBELS SUSPECTED IN BOMBING
</P>
<P>
   A car bomb exploded in the northern Basque city of San
Sebastian, injuring two Civil Guard officers and three other
people, Spanish news media reported. The blast, six days before the
general elections on Sunday, was blamed on the separatist roup ETA,
which is blamed for two car bombings since January that have killed
three people.
</P>
<P>
   GREECE: PROSTITUTES PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   Some 200 prostitutes demonstrated in Athens, demanding that the
socialist government repeal a law barring renewal of their licenses
that was designed to clear the city of brothels ahead of the 2004
Olympics. The prostitutes vowed to march to the prime minister's
office on Tuesday to press their demands.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: CLINTON'S ITINERARY
</P>
<P>
   Ambassador Richard Celeste said President Clinton would visit
New Delhi, Agra _ site of the Taj Mahal _ Jaipur, Hyderabad and
Bombay on his visit to India from March 21 to 25. He will land in
New Delhi on the evening of March 19, then fly to Dhaka,
Bangladesh, the next day. The envoy said it was not clear yet
whether the president would visit Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: COPING WITH TB
</P>
<P>
   In India, where 2 million people develop tuberculosis each year
and nearly 500,000 die from it, an intensive treatment program has
saved more than 40,000 lives and achieved cure rates of more than
80 percent, according to a review by a team of 25 national and
international experts.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: DEATH ON THE ROADS
</P>
<P>
   About 70,000 Indians die and more than 1 million are seriously
hurt each year in road accidents caused by faulty vehicles, bad
roads, improper traffic controls, and other problems, according to
Dinesh Mohan, secretary-general of an Asian conference on injury
prevention in New Delhi sponsored by the World Health Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ARICA
</P>
<P>
   RWANDA: AIDE AMBUSHED
</P>
<P>
   An adviser to President Pasteur Bizimungu was killed in his car
outside his home in the capital, Kigali. The adviser, Assiel
Kabera, had been a a prominent figure among survivors of the 1994
genocide _ in which at least 500,000 ethnic Tutsi and moderate Hutu
were killed by Hutu extremists _ in western Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   SUDAN: U.S. ENVOY VISITS
</P>
<P>
   It was a ``mistake'' that Sudanese warplanes bombed a school
last month, killing 14 children and a teacher in the
rebel-controlled Nuba mountains, the nation's justice minister,
Mustafa Osman Ismail, told the U.S. envoy to Sudan, Harry Johnston.
Sudan is under criticism for the bombing of a hospital on March 1,
which killed at least two people. Government planes on Monday
dropped two bombs on the compound of the Irish aid group, Concern
Worldwide, in southern Sudan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
