<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Tuesday, March 7, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Bob Schenet on the national-foreign desk at (206) 448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-TANKERS (Seattle) In a decision of wide import for
environmental protection and states' rights, the Supreme Court
sides with oil shipping interests and the Clinton administration
against Washington state, invalidating tough state oil-spill
prevention rules enacted after the 1989 Exxon Valdez disaster in
Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Barber. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   HERDING-ELKS (Richland, Wash.) _ The largest relocation of elk
in Washington history was supposed to get under way with 50 head
being herded by helicopter into a holding pen and then trailered
four hours east to the Blue and Selkirk mountains. But in the crisp
dawn hours, amidst the dry, shrubby steppes just across the street
from the world's largest nuclear cleanup site, unpredictable,
untamed nature took over.
</P>
<P>
   By Kriston Dizon. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   AIRBUS-JUMBO (Seattle) _ Executives of Boeing rival Airbus
Industrie insist they will go ahead with development of their A3XX
superjumbo by the end of this year, but a new independent market
analysis questions the need for such a behemoth jetliner anytime
soon.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
