<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8669 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-PAROLE-NYT &LR;      03-06 0274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PAROLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL PAROLES SETTLER WHO KILLED AN ARAB 
</HEADLINE>
   (Shorted)  
(jt) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ A Jewish settler sentenced to life imprisonment for
the execution-style killing of a Palestinian in the West Bank was
given parole Monday, after seven years in jail.
</P>
<P>
   The settler, Yoram Skolnik, 31, is to be freed next month.
</P>
<P>
   The decision continues a pattern of leniency for Jews convicted
of killing Arabs. Skolnik's life sentence was cut on two earlier
occasions.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Palestinians sentenced to life terms for killing
Israelis have not had their sentences commuted. But as part of the
interim accords with the Palestinians, Israel has released dozens
of Arab prisoners convicted of killing Arabs suspected of being
informers for Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The release of Skolnik ``sends a negative message to Israeli
society,'' said Ahmad Tibi, an Israeli Arab legislator and a former
adviser to Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader. ``We demand equal
treatment for Jewish and Arab security prisoners.''
</P>
<P>
   Moshe Negbi, a legal commentator for the Israeli radio said:
``The sense is that that the legal system is lenient toward Jews
who kill Arabs out of nationalist motives. Reducing the penalty
grants legitimacy to such acts.''
</P>
<P>
   On March 23, 1993, Skolnik fired several shots from his Uzi
submachine gun at Musa Abu Sabha, a Palestinian who lay face down,
his hands tied behind him. Abu Sabha had been caught near the
settlement of Susia, south of Hebron, carrying a knife and a
grenade, and had stabbed and slightly injured a settler before he
was subdued.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
