<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8670 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-1STLD-W     03-06 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH HOPES SUPER TUESDAY WINS WILL ENERGIZE FUNDRAISING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: DELETES extraneous line in 2ndgraf; SUBS 20thgraf, In New
York, to add latest poll numbers; FIXES quote marks thruout)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush is counting on a strong
showing in the 13 Republican ``Super Tuesday'' primaries to goose
his fundraising campaign, aides said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush declared Monday that he's on ``a long march to victory.''
</P>
<P>
   A good showing for Bush on Tuesday would help fuel his legendary
fundraising machine, which raised nearly $70 million last year but
now has less than $20 million left.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is planning fundraisers in New York, Newark, N.J.,
Chicago, Michigan and Palm Beach, Fla. and Miami. According to Bush
finance chairman Don Evans, the goal is to raise between $5
million-to-$10 million.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush does well on Tuesday and McCain's challenge evaporates,
that should be enough to tide the campaign over until after the GOP
convention this summer in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   After that, if Bush wins the nomination, the campaign can expect
up to $70 million in federal matching funds, and up to $15 million
from the Republican Party, Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's unexpectedly stiff challenge has had an unanticipated
draining effect on Bush's coffers, Evans acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got one plan that says it's over in February and
another that says it's competitive through the spring,'' he said.
``That's the one we're on.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's results here in California and in New York, Ohio,
Georgia, Missouri and eight other states ``could indicate who the
nominee's going to be, but we're fully prepared to keep on going,''
Bush told reporters. ``I'm looking forward to the contests down the
road as well as the results tomorrow night.''
</P>
<P>
   A total of 613 delegates are at stake on Tuesday, with 1,034
needed to win the Republican nomination. So far, Bush has about 194
delegates to McCain's 111, according to calculations by ABC News.
The numbers are approximations because not all delegates selected
are committed to candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaigned through Southern California with polls showing
him in the lead in several of the most important ``Super Tuesday''
contests.
</P>
<P>
   Bush toured the Museum of Tolerance at the Simon Wiesenthal
Center in an effort to attract the region's sizable Jewish vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every American must know they are equally American _ no matter
their culture, race or religion, Bush said. ``And those who
practice intimidation and violence will have a determined enemy in
the president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, according to the Zogby/Reuters/MSNBC poll, Bush
leads McCain 59.3 percent to 25.6 percent among Republicans whose
votes are the only ones that count toward selection of the state's
162 delegates _ the major prize of Tuesday's primary balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone can vote in the non-binding preference ballot or the
``beauty contest,'' as it's called in political circles. Although
this doesn't affect each party's delegate-selection process, it
stands as an important measure of each candidate's popular appeal
and capacity to attract independent and cross-over votes.
</P>
<P>
   The Zogby poll Monday showed Vice President Al Gore in the
overall lead with 30.5 percent, followed by Bush with 26.4 percent;
McCain with 19.9 percent and former Sen. Bill Bradley with 9.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
   This was good news and bad news for Bush. It was good for Bush
because if he beats McCain in the ``beauty contest,'' he dents
McCain's claim to be the GOP candidate most likely to attract
non-Republican votes and win in November.
</P>
<P>
   And it's bad news because it shows Bush slipping to Gore. The
same poll Sunday showed Gore with 27.5 percent in a virtual tie
with Bush at 27.4 percent. McCain had 20.9 percent, and Bradley had
10.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Other polls showed Bush solidly ahead of McCain in Georgia with
54 delegates, Ohio with 69 delegates and Missouri with 35
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Tuesday's second Republican prize with 101
delegates, the Zogby poll showed a tightening race with Bush
leading McCain by 45.9 percent to 41.1 percent in a primary
restricted to party members.
</P>
<P>
   The New York delegates are apportioned by congressional
district.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show McCain ahead in the New England states.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &LR;  &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Confident in their chances to sew up their parties' respective
contests, Bush and Gore started sniping at each other over the
weekend. Campaigning in Cranston, R.I. Sunday, Gore said an
independently financed television ad praising Bush's environmental
record while criticizing McCain's showed that Bush was in the
pocket of special interests.
</P>
<P>
   Wealthy Dallas investor Sam Wyly, a Bush acquaintance, came
forward to say he had bankrolled the ad. Both Wyly and Bush denied
there was any coordination between them, which would be illegal
under federal election law.
</P>
<P>
   Bush lashed back at Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was somewhat pleased that the vice president took time out
of his schedule to talk about my candidacy,'' Bush playfully joked
to reporters. ``The man must have amnesia when he's talking about
campaign funding reform.''
</P>
<P>
   He condemned Gore for his controversial appearance at a Buddhist
temple in Southern California during the 1996 campaign. At that
events, monks and nuns who had taken ``a vow (of) poverty,'' as
Bush phrased it, contributed money to the Clinton re-election
campaign and were reimbursed. Federal election law prohibits
contributions by ``straw donors.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Maria Hsia, a friend of Gore who helped organize the
event, was convicted of violations of election law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to debate with VP gore at the appropriate
time,'' Bush said. ``Right now I'm trying to earn my party's
nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the McCain campaign filed a complaint with the
Federal Election Commission alleging that the Bush campaign
illegally coordinated with Wyly on the TV ads.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes responded that the Bush campaign
didn't know the ad was planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sen. McCain should be ashamed for himself and his campaign for
making allegations that our campaign did something that would be
illegal,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
