<HEADLINE>
CHINESE ARREST PAIR WANTED IN MURDER OF 5 IN BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a major breakthrough in one of Boston's most
coldblooded homicides, two Vietnamese nationals believed to be
responsible for the 1991 execution-style slayings of five men in a
Chinatown social club have been arrested in China and may face
extradition to, law enforcement officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Police from several countries had been searching for the men,
Siny Van Tran and Nam The Tham, since warrants charging them with
the early-morning massacre were issued nearly a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Both defendants allegedly have ties to Asian organized crime,
and a third suspect, Hung Tien Pham, remains at large.
</P>
<P>
   Because the United States has no extradition treaty with China,
efforts to return the men to Boston to face trial will depend on
the success of discussions between the US State Department and
Department of Justice officials and Chinese government authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Tran, who was arrested in the city of Dongxing by the Guangxi
Provincial and District Police, also faces prosecution in China for
possessing illegal drugs and fraudulent Chinese identification
documents. Tham, who was arrested in the city of Shenzhen by the
Guangdong Provincial and District Police, also faces prosecution by
Chinese authorities.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Boston attended by top law enforcement
officials, US Attorney Donald K. Stern said the arrests came after
years of teamwork by overseas authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``For nine years, local, state, federal and international
officers, agents, and prosecutors worked together, without regard
to borders or boundaries, to track down two men charged with
participating in one of Boston's most heinous and vicious crimes,''
Stern said. ``Criminals who believe they can run from the United
States and seek sanctuary from justice on foreign shores are
mistaken.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jan. 12, 1991, shootings occurred during a violent period in
Boston _ in 1990 the city experienced its highest-ever homicide
rate _ and the nature of the attack shocked Chinatown residents and
even veteran police officials.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the victims was forced to lie face-down and was shot at
least twice in the back of the head at point-blank range, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings took place during a low-stakes game of cards at a
Chinese and Vietnamese social club. A dispute precipitated the
killings, according to Suffolk County District Attorney Ralph C.
Martin II. Several of the victims knew the shooters, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A sixth victim survived the shooting and ``has been helpful'' to
investigators, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have long believed that the three suspects, who
were on the Boston Police Department's ``Ten Most Wanted'' list and
are suspected members of the Los Angeles-based Viet Ching gang,
fled to Vietnam or China.
</P>
<P>
   American law enforcement officials waited to announce the
arrests, which were made about a month ago, until fingerprint tests
were confirmed, Stern said. He declined to comment on whether
investigators have any leads on the third suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Also aiding in the investigation are the Federal Bureau of
Investigation and the US Drug Enforcement Administration, as well
as Interpol, the Hong Kong Police, and the Ministry of Public
Security of the People's Republic of China and its Guangxi and
Guangdong components.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
