<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8675 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-PLANETARIUM-ART-NY     03-06 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PLANETARIUM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE NEW PLANETARIUM: EXPLAINING THE STUFF THAT STARS ARE MADE
OF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Tenn.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Turns out, it really is rocket science.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Rose Center for Earth and Space opened last month amid
praise for its architecture and multidimensional tour of the
universe, visitors have lined up with enthusiasm. Sometimes, they
have left in confusion. As one woman complained, ``My brain hurt
when I was done.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the exhibits seem to require, if not a degree in
astrophysics, at least a passing acquaintance with light years,
astronomical units and orders of magnitude.
</P>
<P>
   Karin Miller-Lewis of Manhattan brought her 8-year-old son,
Joshua, to the center, and they loved it. In particular, she liked
the way it showed how small humans are on a universal scale. But
something was nagging at her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The red shift,'' she said. ``I'm still stuck on the red shift.
There are some completely new terms to me as a nonscientist.''
(Light emitted from an object traveling away from us in space, like
a galaxy, shifts toward the red end of the spectrum and, according
to a sign at the center, that ``tells us how much the universe
expanded during the time the galaxy's light has traveled to us.'')
</P>
<P>
   At a cost of $210 million, the center, which opened Feb. 19,
replaced the Hayden Planetarium, at the 81st Street end of the
American Museum of Natural History. It includes installations worth
$30 million by Ralph Appelbaum, an exhibition designer known for
his modern storyteller style. His work can be seen at the
U.S.Holocaust Memorial Museum in Washington and the Country Music
Hall of Fame in Nashville, and in many other popular attractions.
</P>
<P>
   While visitors do rave about the spectacle of the Rose Center,
some also find its subject matter a bit over their heads, literally
and figuratively.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a challenge for an adult to concentrate on so many
exhibits,'' said Hilda Koch of Manhattan, who was visiting the Hall
of the Universe with her granddaughter and great-grandson from
California. ``Actually, the material seems condensed in a
complicated manner, to me.''
</P>
<P>
   On one topic, Donald Harris of Greenwich, Conn., called himself
lost in space. ``I can understand everything that's been explained
so far, except for the ramp,'' he said, referring to the exhibit
about time. ``The pictures on the ramp aren't really clear to me,
what points they're trying to get across.''
</P>
<P>
   The center's creators had an inkling such perplexity might be a
problem. ``We knew in advance that everybody was not going to get
everything,'' said Neil deGrasse Tyson, director of the Hayden
Planetarium. ``If everybody got everything, then the level of the
exhibits would be so low that we would be a different kind of
museum.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why six months ago the center hired a small museum in
Connecticut to help with a solution. The Eli Whitney Museum in
Hamden is developing carts equipped with computer screens and
powered by 200-pound batteries. Human ``explainers'' will push the
carts around the center and clarify topics like the speed of light
and how radio telescopes and X-ray telescopes work.
</P>
<P>
   A prototype of the first cart, which explains the speed of
light, arrived at the Hall of the Universe Thursday. Each cart
costs $35,000 to $50,000 to develop and build; at least two or
three more are planned. They can be rolled where they are most
needed and are expected to be useful in entertaining crowds waiting
in line.
</P>
<P>
   The explainers, with the carts, will talk to the public using
the Socratic method, asking how much visitors know and what more
they need to understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to go back to the fundamental language of
astronomy and astrophysics and remind people that they are more in
touch with it than they realize,'' said Bill Brown, director of the
Eli Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, most people can explain why they count the seconds
between lightning and thunder to gauge the distance of a storm.
Through questions, they discover they knew more about the speed of
sound and light than they thought. (Think of it as nurturing your
inner quantum mechanic.)
</P>
<P>
   Brown stopped short of saying the carts would make the exhibits
more intelligible. He drew other parallels instead. ``We wanted to
kind of create a glossary,'' he said. ``Like when you're reading
James Joyce, it takes a day before you catch the language of it,
before you say, `I got this.'''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the language of astrophysics. ``They know the language
of their presentation needs a little bit of warming up,'' he said
of the center's leaders. ``We're kind of the comedians who warm the
audience up before the show begins.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eli Whitney has never annotated ``Finnegans Wake,'' but it
did help bring Leonardo da Vinci's Codex Leicester to the common
man, when the manuscript visited the Museum of Natural History in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The universe is a slightly thornier project. For museum visitors
used to seeing objects and asking questions about them,
astrophysics poses a problem. The artifacts involved are pictures
or computer printouts, on a scale larger than a trillion blue
whales or Barosauruses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really more `minds-on' than `hands-on,''' said James
Sweitzer, director of special projects for the Rose Center.
</P>
<P>
   The trick, curators say, is to find ways to connect such
concepts directly to people. Supernovas, for example. At the
mention of them, Sweitzer throws his hands up, as if in a papal
blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``For astronomers, they're the main event. They're the Sammy
Sosas of astronomy,'' he said, referring to the Chicago Cubs
slugger. ``Yet where's the connection to people?''
</P>
<P>
   As the exhibit explains, it is right within us. Sweitzer
described how all the elements in the human body originated first
in the Big Bang, which formed hydrogen and helium, and later in the
explosions of stars. Oxygen was formed in the explosions of the
first generation of stars, and all the iron in human blood came
later from supernovas. Myles Gordon, vice president for education
for the museum, said, ``It's the most powerful idea I've ever seen,
that we are star stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweitzer agreed. ``It's a big, big idea,'' he said. ``And when
you get it across to other people, you've hit a home run.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 2021EST &QL; 
