<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NY-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: PATAKI MAY HAVE MORE RIDING ON N.Y. PRIMARY THAN BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
 (See also REPUBS-NYT) 
(nk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When George Pataki marched the New York Republican Party behind
George W. Bush's candidacy last year, at a news conference staged
with much fanfare in Manhattan, there seemed little question about
how the primary nomination contest would go: fast, smooth and right
to Bush. As far as Pataki was concerned, Bush was the ideal
candidate: smart, moderate and vibrant, an accomplished governor
and, more important, a prodigious fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   The perception of Bush is very different today, as Republicans
prepare for their first contested presidential primary in New York
since 1976. The candidate's star is not as polished as it once was.
If fairly confident that Bush will defeat Sen. John McCain on
Tuesday, the same Republicans who enthusiastically signed on to the
Texas governor's candidacy last year are tense about his prospects
in a general election, particularly in New York, a state where
Republicans once thought they might have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   But for all that, there is not the slightest sign of Pataki or
his supporters backing away from their candidate. Even Monday
night, they were still making telephone calls, distributing
literature, and attacking McCain's record and campaign tactics. No
matter how Bush's bid for the presidency turns out, the New York
Republican Party, and Pataki, will clearly be remembered as one of
his more steadfast and energetic supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for that, though, has less to do with Bush than might
be imagined. The primary in New York has in recent days become less
about Bush's campaign for the presidency, and more about Pataki and
the state Republican Party, particularly as Bush has essentially
handed off control of his campaign to Pataki and the Republican
machine.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Pataki has a lot riding on the outcome of Tuesday's
primary. It can fairly be viewed as a test of a governor who has
tried to present himself as a national figure, as well as of the
state Republican machine. Its outcome could well shape Pataki's
future, especially if Bush wins the White House next year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is no evidence that Bush has stirred any passion or
deep-seated loyally among the Republicans who are now working so
feverishly on his behalf in New York. When Republicans talk about
why they support him, they do not tend to talk about the vision
Bush has offered during his long campaign, or his personal skills
or abilities as a campaigner.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they talk in the cold currency of politics: That he
alone has the ability to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this race is about is putting a Republican out there who
can end the Clinton-Gore era,'' said Zenia Mucha, who is Pataki's
chief political adviser and has largely directed the Bush campaign
effort here in recent days. ``He is the stronger, by far, more
principled candidate in the race.''
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to forget, in a campaign that has been both elongated
and quick-paced, how different the scene is today than it was last
May, when Pataki assembled most of the state's Republican leaders
on a stage in Manhattan and announced he was delivering the party
to Bush, whose face was beamed into the event via Austin, Texas.
McCain was a sideshow then; it would have been hard to find anyone
in the Republican party _ or for that matter, any journalist among
those covering the race _ who did not believe that Bush was certain
to be the Republican nominee, if not the nation's next president.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was that even if Pataki, Mucha and the state
Republican chairman, William D. Powers, had wanted to distance
themselves from Bush as they grew worried about his campaign skills
in the ensuing months, they could not. They had made too much of a
ceremony of the endorsement. More than that, they then had
orchestrated a very public _ and very unsuccessful _ effort to use
New York state election laws to keep McCain off the ballot and
assure Bush the state's delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, there is a personal element as well. This senator
from Arizona clearly succeeded in sticking the New York Republican
Party in the eye, whether it was by forcing it to let him on the
ballot, or by his gleeful references to ``Comrade Pataki'' and
``Comrade Powers,'' as he uses the party as a foil in presenting
himself as the reformer. This might have accounted for the extra
shot of vinegar that seems to have found its way into the party's
attempts to assure Bush's victory this week _ or, more precisely to
assure McCain's loss.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, for example, Bush's campaign learned that state
Sen. John Marchi, a McCain supporter, had put out a letter
criticizing McCain for distributing a piece of literature that
mentioned Bush's visit to Bob Jones University in South Carolina,
whose leaders have espoused anti-Catholic sentiments. Bush's New
York campaign aides were instantly on the telephone to the
reporters, faxing out a copy of the letter to anyone who needed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sincerely hope that you will see to it that attacks on
Governor Bush, painting him as one of anti-Catholic views, will
stop immediately,'' Marchi wrote, overstating the actual content of
McCain's flier.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Molinari, the Staten Island borough president and head of
McCain's New York campaign, responded by saying that the New York
campaign had very explicitly avoided making any such attacks.
``They made a lot of mistakes and they blame us for their
mistakes,'' Molinari said. ``Thanks but no thanks. We've run a
positive campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Against this backdrop, the only question now is what will
constitute a win in the balloting Tuesday. For Bush, who has a
fairly straightforward agenda here, it's mostly a matter of winning
as many delegates as possible. But for Pataki and his cohorts, it
may not be that simple, after this difficult year for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe when all is said and done, the rocky road they traveled
to get here won't be remembered,'' one Republican consultant who is
not sympathetic to Pataki said Monday. ``The antidote to all of
this is that he carries this race big. You might say that the most
interested election-watcher in the state of New York tomorrow will
be the governor of New York.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
