<SLUG> BC-COURT-NAVY-YARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.H. SEEKS SUPREME COURT DECISION IN NAVY YARD DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOIS R. SHEA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTSMOUTH, N.H. _ Firing a salvo over the Piscataqua River that
reverberated all the way to Augusta, N.H. officials have asked the
US Supreme Court to try to settle their long-standing border
dispute with Maine.
</P>
<P>
   N.H. Governor Jeanne Shaheen and Attorney General Philip
McLaughlin hope the high court will hear the case and rule in their
favor, saying that New Hampshire's border runs along the Maine
river shore and not in the middle of the river's main navigable
channel, as Maine contends.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is the Portsmouth Naval Shipyard, which sits on
Seavey's Island in the Piscataqua River. If the court decides the
New Hampshire-Maine border is on the Maine shore, New Hampshire
gets the shipyard. If it decides the border runs on a watery line
in the middle of the Piscataqua, Maine gets it.
</P>
<P>
   Also at stake are millions in tax revenues for shipyard workers.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire bolsters its argument with 129 pages of maps and
hundreds of other documents _ some dating to colonial times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historical records of colonial America, of New England, the
state of New Hampshire and, to a large extent, the state of Maine
show that for most of the last three centuries, there was little
doubt that Portsmouth Harbor was part of New Hampshire,'' Shaheen
said. ``New Hampshire should not cede its claim on Portsmouth
Harbor to the state of Maine.''
</P>
<P>
   Maine is ready for fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're massing troops on the southern border,'' joked Maine
Governor Angus King Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a frivilous matter,'' he added, adopting a
more serious tone, ``but I don't think they're likely to prevail,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   King said the strongest evidence for Maine's case ``is there was
practical recognition that it was part of Maine for as long as
anybody can remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen disagrees. ``During the colonial period it was New
Hampshire officials who administered the Port of
Piscataqua...during the Revolutionary War and the War of 1812, it
was New Hampshire that manned Fort Sullivan on Seavey's Island
where the Shipyard is now located and defended the harbor,'' said
Shaheen. ``And for the past 200 years it was New Hampshire and the
City of Portsmouth that provided services to the Naval Shipyard.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen pointed out that New Hampshire has long overseen and
funded maintenance and repairs to Portsmouth Harbor _ including a
$5 million turning basin in 1991 that extended to the Maine shore.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear when the Supreme Court will decide whether to hear
the case. But there is precedence for the high court weighing in on
similar state-to-state boundary feuds. It ruled in 1998 that most
of Ellis Island _ the historic immigrant entry point _ was part of
New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire contends this case is just as important.
</P>
<P>
   ``The harbor is part of our state's identity,'' Shaheen said.
``It has played a large role in our economy throughout history, and
it is destined to play an important role in our economy in the
future. That is why we must protect our historic right to
Portsmouth Harbor.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half of the shipyard's workers live in New Hampshire,
which has no state income tax. But those workers are levied an
income tax by Maine _ a tax that also takes into account the
incomes of the workers' spouses.
</P>
<P>
   Some N.H. shipyard workers have refused to pay Maine's income
tax, and lost a class-action lawsuit in 1988 in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Should the Navy decide to close the base, the state that is
found to have jurisdiction over the islands will be the big winner
in terms of revenues generated from economic development on that
land.
</P>
<P>
   The N.H. Attorney General's office, led in this case by
Associate Attorney General Leslie Ludtke, has assembled a team of
lawyers and academics to make its case.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Bourre, a former shipyard worker who for years has
championed the case that the shipyard is in New Hampshire, cheered
the state's filing Monday. Bourre has devoted himself full-time to
researching the boundary dispute, and some of his discoveries
helped to make New Hampshire's case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful day for me,'' Bourre said. ``It's like trying
to climb a mountain and getting to the top.''
</P>
<P>
   In its filing, New Hampshire argues that ``the Shipyard has
always been culturally, economically, and politically connected to
New Hampshire. Since the colonial period, New Hampshire and the
city of Portsmouth have exercised authority and responsibility over
nautical regulation, quarantine and harbor improvements in
Portsmouth Harbor and have provided municipal and other services to
the Shipyard and naval personnel with little or no protest from
Maine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The five islands that now form the Portsmouth Naval Shipyard
are situated in Portsmouth Harbor, New Hampshire,'' the filing
states, and says the Navy and federal government long considered
them as such.
</P>
<P>
   King said the dispute is fueled by taxes. ``The issue only
became a cause after Maine imposed the income tax in the late
sixties.'' King said that through the ``19th and virtually all of
20th centuries, all of the actions of people in that area confirmed
that it was part of Maine.''
</P>
<P>
   But Maine has long argued that it was that state that ceded
Seavey and Dennett's Islands to the federal government in the
1800s.
</P>
<P>
   Maine Attorney General Drew Ketterer said Monday that his state
had agreed in the 1800s to retain parallel jurisdiction over the
property with the federal government . ``New Hampshire took no such
correlary action, because the property is not located in New
Hampshire,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ketterer, who said he expects the high court to hear the case,
also thinks a 1969 opinion by then-New Hampshire Attorney General
George Pappagianis bolsters Maine's argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Hampshire Attorney General wrote a written opinion
saying the property's in Maine,'' Ketterer said. ``We think he was
right. It is in Maine.''
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire hopes the Supreme Court will decide Pappagianis
was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, in a settlement over the so-called ``lobster war''
between Maine and New Hampshire, the U.S. Supreme Court set the
ocean boundary between the states at a point in the mouth of the
Piscataqua River. New Hampshire contends that this line sets the
maritime boundary only, and does not extend upriver, as Maine
argues it does.
</P>
<P>
   King said the case will not have ``any particular negative
consequence for the relationship,'' between Maine and New
Hampshire. ``I consider Governor Shaheen a friend and we'll
continue to collaborate and work together on a number of matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Maine has 60 days to respond.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
