<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP candidates ply California voters for support
 &HT;    By Ken Herman and Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Arizona Sen.
John McCain barnstormed California on Monday as they sought support
in the biggest state on the biggest day of the battle for the GOP
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, counting on an unbeatable combination of wins, wants to
make today the final day of the battle.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in 13 states participate in contests today that
offer a total of 613 delegates, more than half the 1,034 needed for
nomination. Bush wins in California, New York and Ohio could end
the McCain campaign.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, Monday looked like the last lap by a candidate
convinced he is about to go into a victory trot in Western
primaries scheduled for Saturday, and Southern contests that
include Texas next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My attitude is this is a long march to victory and (Tuesday)
night could indicate who the nominee is going to be, but we are
fully prepared to keep going,'' Bush said after a San Diego rally.
</P>
<P>
   McCain believes momentum is on his side, but time may not be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, Is it going to be enough? I don't think
there's a question of a momentum shift. We have got him (Bush) on
the defensive across the board,'' McCain said aboard the Straight
Talk Express on his way to a rally and Internet chat at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's day included San Diego and Long Beach rallies, a solemn
speech at the Simon Wiesenthal Center in Los Angeles and an
appearance on ``The Tonight Show with Jay Leno.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain traveled from the Bay Area to San Diego on Monday,
accompanied by his wife, Cindy, four of his seven children and most
of his senior campaign staff.
</P>
<P>
   The entourage is planning to rest Wednesday at McCain's weekend
retreat in northern Arizona, where he and his aides will figure out
what to do next based on today's results.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is also hoping to get final results from last week's
Washington state primary. As hundreds of thousands of absentee
ballots are counted, McCain is narrowing Bush's lead in the overall
vote. He trailed Bush by fewer than 7,000 votes with more than
175,000 ballots yet to be counted.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, McCain filed complaints with federal agencies about
$2 million pro-Bush ads bankrolled by Bush backer Sam Wyly of
Dallas. Bush has denied any connection to the ads.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has allowed McCain to return to his core message,
particularly his call for campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   At Santa Clara University, McCain told supporters, ``Tell his
sleazy Texas buddies to stop these negative ads ... Don't try to
corrupt American politics with your money.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, the speech and tour at the Wiesenthal Center's Museum
of Tolerance also resurrected what has been a theme Bush has
reluctantly had to deal with throughout the campaign, as well as
earlier in his career: his attitude toward Jews.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1998 letter to the Anti-Defamation League, Bush addressed
fallout from 1993 comments in which he said his Christian faith
tells him that heaven is open only to those who accept Jesus Christ
their as personal savior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret the concern caused by my statement and I reassure you
and the Jewish community that you have my deepest respect,'' he
said in the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Bush told Catholic leaders he had ``regrets'' about
not speaking out against Bob Jones University's anti-Catholic views
when he spoke at the South Carolina school.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, at the Wiesenthal Center, Bush praised the center's
work on behalf of Jews and others who face oppression.
</P>
<P>
   ``A leader must do more than hold this conviction. He must give
it voice. And he must give it force. That is my commitment to the
people of this country,'' he said. ``And those who practice
intimidation and violence will have a determined enemy in the
president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice during his speech, a spectator tried to ask Bush about
tolerance toward another group.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about gay people?'' the man yelled, getting no response.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush spent Monday working toward the short-term goal of
wrapping up the nomination, his campaign staff was gearing up for
the longer term.
</P>
<P>
   In coming weeks, Bush will attend 10 to 12 fund-raising events
nationwide, including in Chicago, South Florida, Little Rock, Ark.,
Newark, N.J., New York and Baltimore, according to Don Evans,
chairman of the money-raising side of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Bush has spent almost $60 million of the $70 million he
has raised. He hopes to raise as much as $10 million through the
upcoming events, as well as Internet and direct-mail efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot more people to really contact that would like to
support the governor and just haven't heard from us and we need to
talk to them, we need to get to them,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   That money would take Bush through the period after he
presumably clinches the nomination until federal funds for the
general election _ estimated at $70 million _ begin flowing
following the Republican National Convention in August.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
