<HEADER>
A8687 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-TRIALS-NYT &LR;      03-06 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-TRIALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULES ON WARNINGS TO JURIES ABOUT DEFENDANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court ruled Monday that prosecutors may
try to undermine a defendant's credibility by warning the jury that
the defendant might have tailored his testimony to match that of
witnesses who took the stand first.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-2 decision overturned a ruling by the federal appeals
court in New York that drawing an adverse inference for the jury
from the fact that a defendant attended his own trial violated his
constitutional rights to be present at trial and to confront his
accusers. In New York, in fact, defendants are required by law to
attend their trials.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses are typically not allowed to be present in a courtroom
when they are not needed for their own testimony. In that sense,
defendants who testify in their own defense have the advantage of
having heard the prosecution's witnesses by the time they take the
stand themselves. Lower courts have disputed for some years what
the prosecution should be permitted to make of that fact.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1991 trial of a New York man accused of sodomy and
weapons possession, the prosecutor summed up the state's case by
telling the jury that the defendant, a ``smooth, slick character,''
was able to ``sit here and listen to the testimony of all the other
witnesses'' before he testified. ``That gives you a big advantage,
doesn't it?'' the prosecutor said.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Ray Agard, was convicted. The New York state courts
rejected his appeals. But in 1997 the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals granted his petition for a writ of habeas corpus, ordering
a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court said the prosecutor's comments violated
Agard's Fifth Amendment right to be present at his trial, his Sixth
Amendment right to confront his accusers and his 14th Amendment
right to due process of law. The Queens district attorney's office
in New York City appealed the case, Portuondo vs. Agard, No.
98-1170, to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court had based its analysis largely on a 1965
Supreme Court decision, Griffin vs. California, which held that a
defendant's Fifth Amendment right against compelled
self-incrimination was violated by the prosecution's comment on his
failure to take the stand at his trial.
</P>
<P>
   But that decision was ``a poor analogue'' to the current
situation, Justice Antonin Scalia wrote for the majority on Monday.
Scalia said the fact that a defendant does not testify, as in the
Griffin case, should not be permitted to relieve the prosecution of
the burden of proving its case. Guilt should not be inferred from
silence, he added, because a defendant might have many reasons,
including fear, not to testify.
</P>
<P>
   However, Scalia said, a jury was ``perfectly entitled'' to
evaluate the credibility of a defendant who did testify. ``It is
natural and irresistible for a jury, in evaluating the relative
credibility of a defendant who testifies last, to have in mind and
weigh in the balance the fact that he heard the testimony of all
those who preceded him,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He added that ``allowing comment upon the fact that a
defendant's presence in the courtroom provides him a unique
opportunity to tailor his testimony'' might sometimes be
``essential to the central function of the trial, which is to
discover the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   In a dissenting opinion, Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg said that a
prosecutor's comment on a defendant's presence at trial did not
advance a search for truth, because it ``tarnishes the innocent no
less than the guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that under the 2nd Circuit's decision, prosecutors
could still point out specific flaws or inconsistencies in the
defendant's testimony, but were simply barred from making
``generic'' adverse comments that were not tied to anything
specific.
</P>
<P>
   As a general matter, Ginsburg said, a defendant's testimony
might conform to that of earlier witnesses because the defendant
was telling the truth. ``The court today transforms a defendant's
presence at trial from a Sixth Amendment right into an automatic
burden on his credibility,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said it was unfair for the prosecutor to make these comments
at the summation stage, when the defense has no further chance at
rebuttal. Justice David Souter signed the dissenting opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia's opinion was joined by Chief Justice William Rehnquist
and by Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Anthony M. Kennedy and
Clarence Thomas. Justice John Paul Stevens filed a separate
concurring opinion, which Justice Stephen G. Breyer signed. They
said they agreed ``with much of what Justice Ginsburg has written''
but said that the prosecutor's remarks, while troubling, did not
rise to the level of constitutional error.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
