u p BC-DEMS-ART-NYT &LR;      03-06 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY AND GORE MAKE FINAL APPEAL TO VOTERS ON DAY BEFORE `SUPER
TUESDAY'
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos _ NYT5, 7 _ are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the eve of climactic primaries in 16 states, the
two Democratic presidential candidates seemed to look past each
other as they stumped through New York City on Monday: Vice
President Al Gore toward the general election and former Sen. Bill
Bradley toward his place in history.
</P>
<P>
   As he dived into boisterous crowds throughout the city and gave
interview after interview on Monday, there was a valedictory
quality to Bradley's events. In a morning television interview and
then at an afternoon rally, Bradley and his wife, Ernestine, spoke
of the candidate's contributions to the campaign in the past tense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I'm most proud of is we put some issues on the
agenda that weren't there before, in terms of health care, in terms
of gun control, in terms of making sure people understand how
important campaign finance reform is in this country,'' Bradley
said on CBS' ``Early Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Democratic Party has moved in the direction that
I've pushed it over the last year,'' he continued. ``I'm pleased
about that. But, of course, having the party move in the direction
is not the same as leading the party as the candidate and president
of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore made a quick tour of key Democratic constituency groups,
speaking before Jewish voters, a gay and lesbian group and hospital
workers in Manhattan. Looking confident and relaxed, the vice
president spoke as much of the general election as the primary but
insisted he was not ``taking a single vote for granted'' in today's
contests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am working hard,'' Gore said at the offices of United Jewish
Appeal. ``I am focused. I would like to ask for your help.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen states, including New York, California, Ohio, Georgia
and most of New England hold Democratic primaries or caucuses on
Tuesday that will select nearly a third of the delegates to this
summer's Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Bradley trailing by wide margins in almost all those
states. Bradley said on Monday that he must win ``several''
contests on Tuesday to justify continuing his insurgent campaign, a
feat most Democrats, including many of Bradley's senior aides, say
is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Even in trying to give the impression that their campaign was
gaining momentum, Bradley's aides managed to underscore the
difficulty of their situation. Eric Hauser, Bradley's press
secretary, called a news conference on Monday morning to say that
Bradley had finished a close second in Sunday's Democratic caucuses
in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The caucuses picked delegates. The number of delegates each
candidate will get will be determined by the primary on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a piece of good news,'' Hauser told the assembled corps
of reporters. ``In Maine, we almost beat the vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   At events in the Bronx, Westchester County and Manhattan,
Bradley preached his message of expanding health care, ending
poverty and regulating guns, then invoked the comeback image of a
fellow Missourian, President Harry S. Truman, who stormed back to
victory in 1948 after being declared a loser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say to you in the same spirit of Harry Truman, don't listen
to the polls and pundits,'' Bradley said under cloudless skies to
more than 400 supporters in White Plains. ``Vote your convictions,
vote your heart, vote for the future of this country. If you share
my dream, make it your dream and help me make it our dream.''
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates' schedules on Monday suggested the stark
differences in their campaign styles. Gore gave sharp political
speeches targeted to important Democratic constituency groups. And
Bradley, on possibly his last full day of campaigning, delivered
general, inspirational sermons, the kind he clearly would have
liked to have given all year had the campaign not turned nasty
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, Bradley told parables about the importance of
discipline and respect to 200 students at the High School for Law,
Government and Justice in the South Bronx. Almost none of the
students were old enough to vote, so Bradley concluded by urging
them to ask their parents to cast ballots for him.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley seemed to strike a chord with his audience when he
mentioned the shooting of Amadou Diallo, the West African immigrant
mistakenly killed in a barrage of 41 police bullets, and spoke
about the need to end racial profiling by police. ``I would
challenge white America to stop denying the indignities that
African Americans experience every day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But his talk was so devoid of political points that he seemed
almost relieved when one student asked him what he would do about
health care. ``I'm so glad you asked that question, since that is
the main aim of my campaign,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In White Plains, Bradley called for universal health care,
tougher gun regulations, better schools and a ``new politics'' that
would ``honor our past but see the future clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the one thing that can prevent us from doing all these
things?'' Bradley asked the crowd. ``George Bush,'' a man yelled
back. To which Bradley replied, ``There's only one thing. And
that's politics as usual. As well as George Bush. And John McCain,
for that matter.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bradley was speaking, a large blue banner emblazoned with his
campaign motto, ``It will happen, March 7,'' collapsed behind the
podium after flapping in the chill wind. Bradley's aides quietly
rolled it up and stuck it under a park bench, where it remained
after Bradley left.
</P>
<P>
   Gore waded into comfortable territory on Monday morning,
speaking in Manhattan to about 200 of the country's most prominent
Jewish leaders assembled at the offices of United Jewish Appeal.
Gore has long been popular in the Jewish community, given his
pro-Israel voting record while in Congress, as well as his
relatively consistent defense of Israeli interests during his seven
years as vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you entrust me with the presidency, in the Gore
administration there will be one constant during any negotiations
that we may facilitate,'' the vice president said. ``The United
States must have an absolute and uncompromising commitment to
Israel's security and an absolute conviction that Israel alone must
decide the steps necessary to ensure that security. Whatever Israel
decides can never, not ever, alter our fundamental commitment to
her security.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Lesbian and Gay Community Services Center in Greenwich
Village, the vice president toned down his speaking style and in
hushed tones told more than 200 supporters that he understood the
discrimination that many homosexual citizens faced and vowed that
this was the year to begin ending discrimination against gays and
lesbians. ``We have the duty in our time to create that kind of
future,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
