<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Applewhite keeps busy with rehab, coaching
 &HT;    By Mark Wangrin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ There is the tendency to do too much and try to
go too fast, and Major Applewhite, almost nine weeks after knee
surgery to repair a torn anterior cruciate ligament in his knee, is
finding this out.
</P>
<P>
   As he diligently rehabs for what he hopes will be his job in
upcoming falls, the junior Texas Longhorns quarterback has learned
the value of patience.
</P>
<P>
   With the other, younger, quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite, his left leg still only about 60 percent as strong
as the healthy one, wants to someday be a college football coach,
and is using his forced stint as a bystander to coach the
quarterbacks pushing for his job, sophomore Chris Simms and
redshirt freshman Adam Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I've learned is you can't do too much coaching on
the field, because their heads are swimming,'' he said. ``When they
get some water, have a little time, you give it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the same with Applewhite's surgically repaired knee. As can
be expected, he has turned the rehab process since his Jan. 14
surgery into a competition. As a player, Applewhite has always
tried to know more and understand more than his opponents to get
the edge.
</P>
<P>
   He has taken the same approach with his rehab. He knows where
the graft came from to repair his torn ligament (the middle third
of his patellar tendon) and he knows why (it's the strongest part,
and the two outside sections will eventually grow together, making
it whole again). He knew what to hope for during his surgery _ no
other cartilage or ligament damage, because he saw what a near
total knee reconstruction cost linebacker Anthony Hicks last year.
He describes the surgery as if he were an active participant or as
if he has at least watched a videotape (he hasn't).
</P>
<P>
   And most important, Applewhite says, is that he knows not to do
any more or any less than what physical therapist Allen Hardin
tells him to do. Applewhite's father, Larry, had the same surgery
about seven years ago, 21 years after he tore his ACL in a church
softball game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me that if they want you to do three sets of 50, don't
cut it short and don't do any more,'' Major said. ``Just make it
the best set you can do. If you work too hard, tendinitis can set
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite is careful to elevate the leg when he's supposed to
elevate it, ice it when he's supposed to ice it. He's already
taking a three-step drop and throwing, though he's not planting
hard, and he's been doing some jumping and cutting and movement
drills, all while Hardin pulls on him with a bungee cord to improve
his balance and build the supporting muscles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a test,'' Applewhite said. ``The reward might come this
summer, or next summer, or the summer after that. The Lord puts
certain circumstances in your life to prepare you.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that he should be healthy by the time the
Longhorns begin fall camp in August. He'll need to be, because
he'll get no special treatment as the incumbent starter, just as
Richard Walton didn't draw any favors when he returned from a
broken finger, four weeks after Applewhite took his job.
Applewhite, elected to University of Texas student government as an
at-large representative last month, takes a politician's approach
when asked how it affects him that there's a faction of Longhorns
fans who fully expect Simms to take over the starting spot in the
fall, even though Applewhite set school single-season records for
passing yards, touchdowns and total offense and was named the Big
12 offensive player of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure I put on myself is the greatest that can be put
on me,'' Applewhite said. ``Sure, you'd like everybody to be a
Major Applewhite fan _ if you're Major Applewhite. But if you're
mature, not worry about it, you can just deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
