<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves' first for catcher tandem
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUNEDIN, Fla. _ From the cozy quarters of one position, a most
unlikely friendship has blossomed between Javy Lopez and Eddie
Perez.
</P>
<P>
   From the time they met in spring training with the Braves in
1988, became minor-league teammates for the first time in Durham,
N.C., in 1991 and then reunited in Atlanta in 1995, the two
catchers not only have stayed close but have become best friends in
a climate that easily could have driven them apart.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez was the can't-miss prospect who became a star. He entered
the system a year later than Perez and moved to the majors three
years earlier. Perez was the often underappreciated defensive
specialist. But his value to the team as a backup catcher became
evident last season when Lopez was lost to a season-ending knee
injury. And Lopez knew it better than anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say to myself, `If there's somebody who's going to take my
job, I'd rather it be him,''' Lopez said.
</P>
<P>
   With encouragement from Lopez, who talked to Perez before and
after every game, whether in person or by cellular phone, Perez
went from catching Greg Maddux every fifth day to catching every
day.
</P>
<P>
   Perez wasn't expected to provide the offense that Lopez would
have, but he did his best Lopez imitation by winning the National
League Championship Series MVP award.
</P>
<P>
   Perez started all six games against the Mets and hit .500. He
hit game-winning home runs in Games 1 and 2, inspiring Braves fans
to chant ``Ed-die, Ed-die,'' which sounded an awful lot like
``Ja-vee, Ja-vee'' of three years before when Lopez led the Braves
to the World Series by pounding the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed every moment of it,'' Lopez said about watching
Perez in last year's NLCS. ``Besides his wife, I was the happiest
person.''
</P>
<P>
   And the feeling has been mutual for Perez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never get jealous of anybody playing in front of me,'' said
Perez, who played behind top draft pick Tyler Houston and Lopez in
the minors. ``I worry about my chances. It wasn't their fault. I
just waited for my chance.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of attitude makes it easy on manager Bobby Cox.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie's such a quality person,'' Cox said. ``He knows Javy's
the guy.... Eddie could be catching for somebody else. We certainly
didn't want to lose Eddie in the expansion draft (in December
1997). I don't think we've ever talked about trading Eddie.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez, a 31-year-old Venezuelan, and Lopez, a 29-year-old Puerto
Rican, got to know each other well in Durham. And now, they are
connected by so much more.
</P>
<P>
   Following Lopez's lead, Perez kept his family in Atlanta in the
offseason this year for the first time. The families live a five
minute walk apart. At least once a week their families eat dinner
together and pray together.
</P>
<P>
   The two worked out together in the offseason while
rehabilitating from surgery _ Lopez from his knee injury and Perez
from shoulder and knee surgery. And they goof around together, too.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody gave Perez more grief for the beating he took behind the
plate last year from foul balls and stray pitches than Lopez. Perez
also got grief for being locked out of the Braves' clubhouse
following an ESPN interview on the field after a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's too big; he's too wide. He's like a wall,'' Lopez said
when describing why he thought Perez was so good at blocking
pitches. And what made Perez a good friend?
</P>
<P>
   ``He lies too much,'' Lopez said. ``Other than that, he's the
best you can find out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez, a deadpan kidder who keeps his teammates in stitches,
will give Lopez that. And he came back with a ``wider is better.''
</P>
<P>
   But he quickly turned serious in explaining how he and Lopez
have remained so close.
</P>
<P>
   ``We care about the team,'' Perez said. ``We care about
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
