<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8697 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     03-06 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: YANKS BEGIN TO NOTICE TOUCH OF GRAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINTER HAVEN, Fla. _ Wherever they go, the fans push as close as
they can and they call out to them by their first names. David Cone
says he has been struck by this more than ever, here in the
intimacy of spring training, 2000. The Yankees go by Derek and
David, Paulie and Bernie, as if they were more rock band than ball
club, as if they were Michael and Scottie's Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   The explanation, obviously, is a continuity of core players,
with reinforcements picked up at stations along the express track
to three World Series titles and five straight playoff runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become a rarity in sports to see teams stay together five
years,'' Cone said. ``This must have been the way it was years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone wasn't campaigning to turn back the clock, good union man
that he is. In no particular order, he was just thanking his
resourceful arm and George Steinbrenner's redoubtable wallet for
another shot, another year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it's just one more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, Cone began his sixth season with the Yankees
here Monday, pitching two and two-thirds innings against the
Cleveland Indians. He pitched ``free and easy'' but surrendered a
two-run homer to Roberto Alomar and the Yankees rewarded
Steinbrenner for making the drive from Tampa with their fifth
straight defeat, a 15-1 horror show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the numbers we're losing by,'' Steinbrenner
huffed, referring to the composite Florida score of Their Guys 48,
Our Guys 16.
</P>
<P>
   These are the symptoms of a young spring and an aging staff. At
37, Cone has looked stiffer, puffier, than ever before. He said he
didn't pick a ball up all winter, cognizant of the need to let his
arm retool for the long haul to October. More than anyone, though,
Cone characterizes a starting rotation that is watching the
hourglass and a team that is graying at the temples.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens is also 37, and Orlando Hernandez, at last report,
34. Paul O'Neill is 37 and Tino Martinez is possibly in his last
go-round as the Yankees groom Nick Johnson to move in at first
base.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some age,'' Cone agreed. ``I look at Paul O'Neill and
I can identify with him. We're kind of going at it year to year.''
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing to enter the age of higher risk and quite
another to suffer cardiac arrest, which is what happened to the
Bulls' dynasty the day Michael Jordan quit. Baseball is a more
complex game with a radically different financial structure. The
only true, indispensable Yankees are Derek Jeter at shortstop,
Bernie Williams in center field and Mariano Rivera coming out of
the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more of a mixture of age and youth, and the Yankees do
have prospects coming, so it's hard to see this as a Chicago Bulls'
situation, a last hurrah,'' Cone said. ``But when you're part of a
nucleus like this one, when you've done what we've done, that's
incentive enough to come back and keep doing it again.''
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, the Yankees are not unlike Jordan's Bulls in
their final years, the old gang having to justify the enormous
expenditure of its ownership by, more or less, winning it all.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner reminded the Yankees of that as he made his exit
during the seventh inning Monday, the score 13-1. ``It's too
early,'' he said; but as Yogi once said, it gets late around here
early.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll let you know,'' Steinbrenner said, on when not too early
might be. ``I'll let the whole club know, believe me.''
</P>
<P>
   It is, of course, an insufferable exercise, always has been,
gauging the quality of the Yankees by Steinbrenner's preseason
standards. Yet this spring marks the first since their mid-1990s
rise that the Yankees came South without one significant addition,
no expensive new toy.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as Joe Torre tells me he's happy with this team, there
probably won't be anything,'' Steinbrenner had said the other day,
in a better mood and forgetting for the moment the need for a lefty
designated hitter. ``When a team that's done what this one has, it
deserves the benefit of the doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   In the next breath, he admitted that some benefits run out much
faster than others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the year we made the trade for Bucky Dent on the
last day of spring training,'' he said. ``So nothing is guaranteed,
except death and taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   And one other thing: these Yankees are being judged by their own
degree of dominance, just as Jordan's Bulls were at the end.
Anything less means the end of the old gang, or at least the core
gang and perhaps the classiest gang of championship Yankees there
has been.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
