<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8712 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MARDIGRAS07-COX     03-06 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARDIGRAS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mardi Gras revels build toward blowout
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ A few things seen around the city this Mardi Gras
season:
</P>
<P>
   A cow playing golf. A besotted Grim Reaper. A cross-dressing
cheerleader.
</P>
<P>
   Today is Fat Tuesday, the final and wildest day of a Carnival
season that, for residents, began in January, on the 12th night
after Christmas. It's not just the tourists and college kids who
whoop it up in the last week before Lent, the Christian season of
prayer and self-denial that begins Wednesday. With parades rolling
every day and every evening, followed by society balls and backyard
crawfish boils every night, New Orleanians are claiming their
annual right to leave inhibitions at home and party hearty.
</P>
<P>
   Mardi Gras does to New Orleans what a snowstorm does to New
York: It makes residents cheerful and friendlier, except for the
few grumps who are undone by traffic problems.
</P>
<P>
   And everyone wants to be in costume. All the time. Residents
have entire closets dedicated to jester suits, superhero capes,
wigs, hats and masks.
</P>
<P>
   The man in the cow suit was a member of the Krewe of Tucks, one
of the clubs that host Mardi Gras parades. He was squeezing in a
few holes of golf Saturday before climbing on a parade float.
</P>
<P>
   The Grim Reaper weaved and bobbed his way through the Krewe of
Hermes parade Friday night. A seriously intoxicated krewe member
dressed in a creepy death costume that rose at least 10 feet above
his head, he needed several friends to hold him as he stumbled down
St. Charles Avenue. The crowd nicknamed him the ``Gin Reaper.''
</P>
<P>
   The cross-dressing cheerleader is a member of the Booker T.
Washington High School squad. Last week, during the Ancient Druids
parade, the young man, dressed in the same tights and sequined
outfit as the girls, strutted and wiggled and kicked with the best
of the girls, and attracted a lot of attention along the way.
Parade watchers shouted and cheered him on. This is Mardi Gras.
Pretending to be something you're not is normal.
</P>
<P>
   I called the high school to find out who the student is, but
they were tight-lipped on the subject. An official would only say
he is a ``super senior,'' which means he has finished all his
classes but needs to take a final state test to graduate. Last week
was his last parade, because he can no longer participate in
extra-curricular activities.
</P>
<P>
   `THE REAL WORLD'?
</P>
<P>
   American ingenuity at work: Some revelers from the New Orleans
suburbs created a homemade john in the bed of their pickup. It
consisted of a bucket surrounded by a stall made of blue plastic
sheets tacked to a flimsy frame. Better in the bucket than the
street.
</P>
<P>
   I won't have to wash glasses for days: I caught about 20 plastic
cups from a Krewe d'Etat float Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just got yourself a whole set of Cajun china,'' said Sean
Arrillaga, a parade watcher and New Orleans resident.
</P>
<P>
   One of the hottest spots in New Orleans this Mardi Gras has got
to be the intersection of St. Charles Avenue and Third Street in
the Garden District. On one corner, Anne Rice's house. On another,
the house where Rex, the king of Carnival, stops his float and
makes a toast today. And across the street is the Belfort Mansion,
home of the moment to the cast of MTV's ``The Real World.'' The
seven handsome twenty-somethings who live there and are filmed 24
hours a day have been the talk of Mardi Gras. ``Real World''
sightings are as cherished as a good set of beads.
</P>
<P>
   But be careful if you want to take pictures of the television
stars-to-be. I took out my camera and started snapping as the
entourage left the mansion Friday night, camera crews trailing. A
bleached blond producer put his hand in front of the lens and said
I should respect their ``privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me, but aren't you on a public street in the middle of
the biggest party in the country?'' I asked, ever so politely.
Click. Click. Flash. Flash. The ``Real World'' New Orleans episodes
will air in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   100 MARCHING ELVISES
</P>
<P>
   A bit of advice to potential Romeos: Don't try to shimmy up a
pole to reach a balcony whilst in the French Quarter during Mardi
Gras. They have been slicked down with petroleum jelly to prevent
climbing. No Juliet is worth a bad fall to the pavement.
</P>
<P>
   A little Mardi Gras trivia from Carnival guru Arthur Hardy,
publisher of the ``Mardi Gras Guide'': The first krewe was Comus, a
secret society formed in 1857. Comus began the tradition of themed
parades. Rex, the king of Carnival, first appeared in 1872. The
Krewe of Rex came up with the three colors that symbolize the
season: Purple for justice, green for faith and gold for power. Who
thought these colors looked good together is a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   There are lesser-known, ``underground'' krewes as well, like the
Krewe of the Box of Wine, the Krewe of Nutria, Le Gran Cru De
Mentia, and the Krewe of Bra. A personal favorite is the Krewe of
Elvis, started by a man from Conway, Ark. The Krewe has grown to
more than 100 people from around the country, who will be marching
today through the French Quarter. They'll be easy to spot: 100
Elvises, throwing donut necklaces to the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
