<HEADER>
A8715 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GEORGIA-VOTERS-2TAKES     03-06 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGIA-VOTERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ELECTORATE: AS A REGION'S ECONOMY BOOMS, SO DOES INTEREST IN
THE RACE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COVINGTON, Ga. _ In the old orange cotton fields of Newton
County's past, bright automated factories now turn out an unending
stream of Honey Nut Cheerios and flawless polyester sheeting. And
with each truck that heads out from here on Interstate 20, the
transformed local economy also produces what might be called the
opposite of complacency, an engagement with the world of prosperity
and politics that has surprised even those who planned for this
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Here in north central Georgia, Newton County and its neighbors
are practically reverberating with the economic success that has
enveloped the once rural region. With the unemployment rate below 3
percent, good jobs are piling up in the classified ads. There are
no longer any vacant stores facing the historic town square, which
served for years as the backdrop to the television series ``In the
Heat of the Night.''
</P>
<P>
   And suddenly, national politics does not seem to be so distant
an exercise. People with health benefits and retirement portfolios
talk about the presidential race as if they were company
shareholders examining a slate of directors, thoughtfully
dissecting the candidates and their inner lives. When talk at
restaurants around the square turns to the presidential primary on
Tuesday, there is a sense of absorption in people's voices, as if
they know these candidates well, and as if that knowledge matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been listening to Bush during this campaign, and it's
like he's becoming stronger because he had to figure out McCain,''
said Dan Corder, a builder of subdivision homes, who was sitting in
Smiley's Restaurant on the square. ``I think he's learned something
about the country from this campaign. Maybe he's figured out that
we don't want the old party politics anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Crystal Butler, who works at Bell's Discount Groceries west of
town, is delighted with the county's growth and the number of her
friends who are no longer unemployed, and plans to thank Vice
President Al Gore with her vote on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the way he tells people what he's going to do on
education and the economy,'' she said. ``He comes across like he
really means it. And he doesn't spend all his time chopping on
people, like the Republicans do.''
</P>
<P>
   If previous election campaigns seemed to people here a blur of
headlines and angry demands, this year's is more like an
interesting but leisurely novel. The plot, played out by wildly
contrasting characters, is one of national prosperity, and the
people of Newton County have a big stake in its outcome. Like many
voters in earlier primary states, those here say economic growth is
a chief issue driving them to the polls on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hinkle, a mechanical maintenance supervisor at the huge
new Korean-owned SKC factory, which makes enormous rolls of
high-quality plastic film, said he, too, was planning to vote for
Gov. George W. Bush, but was enjoying the competition from Sen.
John McCain, which has produced high turnouts in several primary
states.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Bush person, but I'm sure curious about McCain,'' said
Hinkle, who moved here from central Alabama to take his high-tech
job. ``I want to do some research and find out what he stands for
and why people are attracted to him.''
</P>
<P>
   There is not much doubt who will win in Georgia on Tuesday. Both
Bush and Gore are enormously popular here, and none of the four
major candidates have even bothered to campaign regularly in the
state. But inevitability does not seem to have dimmed Newton
County's interest in this election. No one here has seen a single
political advertisement or shaken a candidate's hand, and yet
voters are planning to show up at the polls, without making
decisions in last-minute frustration. Republican officials are
predicting a record turnout for the state, and the Democratic
primary may draw large crowds as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are spending more time looking at the intangible things
that they never got to before,'' said Denny Dobbs, an environmental
engineer and former state legislator whose family has lived in the
county for four generations. ``They want truth, they want
sincerity, but mostly they want to take the time to find someone
who can give them a normal presidency. Someone who will do what
they say and not disappoint them.''
</P>
<P>
   Newton County, in fact, is full of people who are in no mind to
be disappointed. The county spent years at a comfortable distance
from Atlanta's chaotic boom, hoping to nibble at growth while
avoiding the strip malls and tract homes. The invasion could not be
held off, but now the benefits of good times have also arrived here
with full force.
</P>
<P>
   Every week seems to bring another announcement of a new employer
or subdivision taking advantage of the 45-minute drive to Atlanta's
airport, Hartsfield International. When the SKC plant, where
machine operators are paid between $14 and $22 an hour, expands to
full size in seven or eight years, it will employ more than 1,000
people and, at $1.5 billion, amount to the largest industrial
investment in the state's history.
</P>
<P>
   Now that they have begun to taste the good life, many of the
county's 59,000 people want to hear precisely what each candidate
would do to keep it going. They want to know details of education
planks and economic blueprints. People who work at SKC, or
Michelin's tread-pressing factory, or Nisshinbo Automotive's
brake-pad assembly plant, are far more interested in trade policy
than they would have been a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really broadened people's horizons, and I don't think any
of us fully anticipated that,'' said Samuel B. Hay III, chief
executive of Main Street Bank, one of the largest retail banks
here. ``We've got a large Asian contingent here now, a French glass
maker, people moving here from all over the world. There might be
some political friction, but I think over all it's better for the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Like most rural Southern counties, Newton retains a large number
of ardent Democrats, many of them the blacks who make up about 26
percent of the population and descendants of the liberal Methodists
who founded the original Emory College, in the town of Oxford, just
north of Covington. Many well-educated natives of the county who
once assumed that they would have to leave to find a good job, like
Michael Davis, the plant scheduler at SKC, now say they are
thrilled to be able to work where they grew up.
</P>
<P>
   But Newton's location about 50 miles east of downtown Atlanta
has made it increasingly attractive too for a growing number of
newcomers, many of them commuters who tend to settle in suburban
developments on the western edge of the county and vote Republican.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Newton is fairly evenly split between Republicans
and Democrats, and has been a swing county for several elections.
In 1992, Bill Clinton won the county by just 7 votes, of 13,613
cast; he lost it to Bob Dole by 515 votes four years later. In
1998, Roy Barnes, a Democrat elected governor that year, lost the
county to Guy Millner by just 73 votes. Many people suspect that
the tiny but detectable trend toward a Republican majority may
deepen as county incomes rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new people coming in are more conservative, more
Republican, pushing things to the right,'' said one Democrat, Don
Ballard, a lawyer who has long been politically active in the area
and whose son, Tommy, is running as a Republican for chairman of
the county commission. ``I suspect that the county will go for
Bush'' in the general election, the elder Ballard said, ``although
we've got the economy as our ace in the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   It is clear, though, that fervent partisanship of either stripe
does not appeal to most residents here, new or old. Considerable
interest in McCain is expressed by many of the county's voters,
including Democrats, who expect him to do well in a region where
personality and policy now often outweigh party affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   Covington's mayor, Sam Ramsey, who owns a large furniture store
just off the square, is a longtime Democrat who occasionally finds
himself voting Republican and has seen the tendency in others. The
movement away from party loyalty, he says, is inevitable as income
and education rise, but in no way reflects a disengagement from the
political process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people enjoy making up their own minds, forming their
own opinions about the candidates,'' he said amid the clutter of
his busy store. ``You might think that in a good economy people
might not be as concerned, but in a smaller community like this, we
don't see that. It's not the big city, where people think they're
not important. Here they know they've got a role to play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
