u w BC-ELDERLY-DRUGS-NYT &LR;      03-06 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDERLY-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDIES DOUBT EFFECTIVENESS OF DRUG PLAN BY PRESIDENT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Half of all Medicare beneficiaries already have
prescription drug coverage at least as generous as the benefits
proposed by President Clinton, the Congressional Budget Office said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these beneficiaries are retirees who get drug coverage
through former employers, and ``retiree plans usually provide much
more generous coverage'' than Clinton has proposed, the budget
office said.
</P>
<P>
   The finding helped explain why many members of Congress have
expressed reservations about Clinton's proposal to expand Medicare
to offer drug coverage to all beneficiaries. The president's plan
would offer federal subsidies to employers to encourage them to
continue providing drug benefits to retirees.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has repeatedly said that under Clinton's
proposal, the government would pay half of the drug costs incurred
by a Medicare beneficiary, with the maximum federal payment
starting at $1,000 a year in 2003 and rising to $2,500 in 2009.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts at the budget office said that when premiums and
co-payments required under the Clinton plan are included, Medicare
beneficiaries would actually pay at least 75 percent of the cost of
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The study, by Sandra Christensen and Judith Wagner of the budget
office, is one of many on prescription drugs published Monday in
the journal Health Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the studies suggested that Clinton was right to
identify prescription drug costs as a major burden for the elderly,
but that his proposal was not necessarily the most effective way to
deliver those benefits and control costs.
</P>
<P>
   In seeking the Democratic presidential nomination, Vice
President Al Gore often praises the Clinton administration proposal
and says the Republican candidates have offered no real
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate study, Dr. Earl P. Steinberg, a health policy
consultant, found that a small number of Medicare beneficiaries
accounted for a large amount of drug spending. Overall, he said,
spending on drugs for an elderly person averaged $1,100 a year. But
18 percent of the elderly did not buy any prescription drugs in
1998, and among those who filled at least one prescription, 5
percent used more than $4,100 in drugs, and 1 percent used more
than $6,600.
</P>
<P>
   A third study, by the Health Care Financing Administration,
which runs Medicare, said Medicare beneficiaries who do not have
drug coverage filled fewer prescriptions and spent more of their
own money on medications than people who have such insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare beneficiaries with drug coverage filled an average of
21 prescriptions a year compared with only 16 for those without
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hash, deputy administrator of the Health Care Financing
Administration, said: ``This study shows that insurance makes a
difference. The absence of drug coverage results in fewer
prescriptions and higher costs to beneficiaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Another study in Health Affairs said that while drug spending
had soared, drug prices accounted for only a small share of the
increase. Most of the increase in spending, it said, resulted from
rapid growth in the number of prescriptions written, the number of
patients receiving drugs and the number of days of therapy for each
prescription.
</P>
<P>
   For example, spending on hormone replacement therapy more than
tripled from 1995 to 1998, mainly because of a big increase in the
number of women who received such drugs to relieve symptoms of
menopause or to reduce the risk of osteoporosis or heart disease.
Spending on drugs to treat asthma and diabetes nearly doubled in
the same period.
</P>
<P>
   The author of the study, Dr. Robert W. Dubois, chief executive
of Protocare Sciences, a consulting concern in Santa Monica,
Calif., said the greater use of prescription drugs _ getting people
into treatment or providing more intensive treatment _ often
benefited patients with high cholesterol, diabetes, asthma and
depression.
</P>
<P>
   Under Clinton's proposal, the government would hire companies to
manage drug benefits for the elderly. When such companies arrange
benefits for large employers and health maintenance organizations,
they typically get discounts of 14 percent to 30 percent, Steinberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the budget office said the discounts under Clinton's plan
would be smaller _ 12.5 percent off the retail price charged to
uninsured retail customers _ because the private companies would
not have as much freedom or incentive to use cost-cutting
techniques.
</P>
<P>
   John K. Iglehart, the editor of Health Affairs, said the studies
suggested that the government should focus its assistance on
Medicare beneficiaries with the greatest need for drug coverage,
those who are poor and those who have chronic illnesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
