<SLUG> BC-MGM-MIRAGE-ART-735&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MGM GRAND TO ACQUIRE MIRAGE RESORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mirage Resorts Inc. agreed Monday to be acquired by MGM Grand
Inc. for $4.4 billion in cash, creating a casino industry
powerhouse but probably ending the reign of Stephen A. Wynn, the
founder and chairman of Mirage, as the unofficial king of Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of the deal made no mention of what role, if
any, Wynn would play in the combined company. But people close to
MGM said Wynn, while he might have a seat on the board of
directors, is not expected to have a day-to-day role in operations.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Baron, chairman of Baron Funds, which is a major Mirage
shareholder, said that Wynn told him Monday that he intended to
quit and ``start over.'' A person close to the acquisition talks
also said that Wynn had ``other plans.'' A Mirage spokesman said
Wynn would not be commenting.
</P>
<P>
   MGM Grand, which is controlled by billionaire Kirk Kerkorian,
will pay $21 a share in cash. That is $4 a share, or about $1
billion, higher than the $17 a share that MGM Grand offered for
Mirage two weeks ago and nearly double the $10.875 price of Mirage
stock before the offer was made. MGM Grand will also assume about
$2 billion of Mirage debt.
</P>
<P>
   Mirage had rejected the initial offer last Tuesday but had left
the door open to a higher price. Talks began almost immediately
after that, continued through the weekend and concluded about 6
a.m. Monday, executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Industry executives and analysts said the deal could presage
further consolidation in the casino industry. With few new states
opening to gambling, casino companies will increasingly try to grow
through acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   J. Terrence Lanni, the chairman of MGM Grand, called the
transaction ``a dream combination of assets and people.''
</P>
<P>
   The combined company is expected to be the second-largest casino
company in revenue after Park Place Entertainment, which itself
recently completed its acquisition of the Caesars World casinos.
</P>
<P>
   MGM Grand will own 14 casinos, including five of the splashiest
resorts on the Las Vegas Strip _ its own 5,000-room MGM Grand,
which is the largest hotel in the nation, and New York-New York as
well as Mirage's Mirage, Treasure Island and the $1.6 billion
Bellagio.
</P>
<P>
   It will also have a half-interest in the Monte Carlo on the Las
Vegas Strip and own casinos elsewhere in Nevada as well as in
Mississippi, Detroit and Australia. The company is expected to
control about half the market for gambling by high rollers.
</P>
<P>
   MGM and Mirage each plan to develop a casino in Atlantic City,
N.J., so it is now possible that only one of those projects will go
forward or that one will be delayed, dealing a blow to the city's
development plans but helping some existing competitors. ``You had
two major companies building two major facilities. Now you have one
very major company building one facility,'' said Donald Trump, who
fought Wynn's plans in Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   But a person close to MGM said it had not been decided how many
projects would go ahead in Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   The swiftness with which the Mirage deal was consummated
surprised analysts. They thought that Wynn, who parlayed a Maryland
bingo parlor that he inherited from his father into a chain of the
world's splashiest theme hotels, would fight to escape Kerkorian,
who is also a self-made man and every bit as powerful as Wynn,
though he tends to remain behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A week ago I was on record as saying it was over Stephen
Wynn's dead body he would sell his company,'' said Harry Curtis, an
analyst with Robertson, Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   But Wynn was under pressure from investors because Mirage shares
had fallen so far from the recent peak of $26 a share last May as
earnings fell short. Mirage's new Beau Rivage casino in Mississippi
proved too fancy for the market there, and the Bellagio in Las
Vegas, with an impressionist art collection worth several hundred
million dollars, stole customers from the Mirage. And there seemed
to be little prospect that the shares would recover on their own in
the near term.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a fair price for the current environment,'' said
Baron, whose funds own about 6 percent of Mirage shares. Wynn,
meanwhile, said in a statement that the transaction ``fully
embraces the value of the franchise created by each of the Mirage
properties.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Mirage rose $3.125, to $19, while MGM Grand shares
rose 50 cents, to $19.50.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   People close to the matter say that Wynn, 58, was growing tired
of dealing with Wall Street. And Wynn, whose eyesight is gradually
failing from a hereditary disease, might believe that now is the
time to take the money _ his 11.8 percent stake in Mirage will net
him about $500 million in the sale _ and pursue other ventures or
devote more time to his passion of collecting art.
</P>
<P>
   But some people who know him say Wynn has not shown any loss of
enthusiasm for the casino business and might plunge back in,
perhaps by buying the Desert Inn in Las Vegas, which is for sale by
Starwood Hotels &AMP; Resorts Worldwide Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he feels everything he built is not the ultimate
building,'' Baron said. He also said it is possible that Kerkorian,
who is 82 and might be looking for a successor, will yet find a
role for Wynn.
</P>
<P>
   Some say that the industry and the state of Nevada would suffer
if Wynn left gambling. He is credited with creating the boom in Las
Vegas over the last decade by pushing to offer entertainment other
than gambling.
</P>
<P>
   MGM Grand officials said the acquisition, expected to be
completed by the end of the year, would immediately add to its
earnings per share. The company anticipates significant cost
savings, some of which could come from having to pay less to lure
the high rollers.
</P>
<P>
   MGM Grand is also likely to sell assets, such as Mirage's
airplanes and some homes or apartments used by Wynn or other
executives. It is not clear yet what will happen to the art
collection, one person close to the situation said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
