<SLUG> BC-AMOCO-GASOLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BP AMOCO TO CUT SULFUR LEVELS IN GASOLINE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ BP Amoco, the world's second-largest oil company,
announced on Monday that it planned to reduce sharply by the end of
2002 the level of sulfur contamination in virtually all of the
premium gasoline that it sells in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford Motor Co. said the step would cut air pollution by up
to half for cars burning the fuel, and said those models needing
premium gasoline would receive a tankful of the new fuel before
leaving the assembly plant.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton announced new rules in December to require oil
companies to reduce sulfur in all types of gasoline from 2004 to
2006. Most oil companies strongly opposed the rules during the
drafting process, contending that they would impose a considerable
and unnecessary expense that they would have to pass on to
consumers by raising gasoline prices by six cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   But BP Amoco did not fight the regulations, and has been trying
to market itself as more environmentally responsible than other oil
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The company said that while it would need to make some changes
at its refineries, it would not charge extra for its premium
brands, Crystal Clear Amoco Ultimate and BP Super 93.
</P>
<P>
   The two premium brands, which will have less than a third of the
sulfur of other premium brands and a tenth of the sulfur of regular
gasoline, account for nearly 3 percent of the gasoline sold in the
United States each year.
</P>
<P>
   Sulfur, which occurs naturally in crude oil, clogs cars'
catalytic converters, making them less effective in cleaning
exhaust.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
