<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Greenspan Warns Again On Rates, and Stocks Fall
</P>
<P>
   Just in case investors had chosen not to heed his previous
warnings, Alan Greenspan gave them a reminder that the Federal
Reserve intends to raise interest rates until it is sure it has
squeezed any inflationary imbalances out of the economy. In a
speech at at Boston College, Greenspan, the Fed chairman, repeated
his message that the wealth being created in the stock market is
creating more demand than the economy can satisfy.
</P>
<P>
   Investors took notice. The Dow Jones industrial average fell
196.70 points, or 1.9 percent, to 10,170.50; the Nasdaq composite
index declined 9.94 points, to 4,904.85; and the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index slipped 17.89 points, or 1.3 percent, to 1,391.28.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers Seek Tax Shelter Inquiry
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress from both parties called for an
investigation into a tax shelter that makes it possible for
American insurance companies to stop paying income taxes by moving
their headquarters to Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   Qwest Is Daunted by Its Own Deal
</P>
<P>
   If Qwest Communications International had not agreed to acquire
U S West, Qwest probably would have announced a deal to be acquired
by Deutsche Telekom of Germany by now, and at a healthy premium to
its stock price of $57.25 a share. For Qwest's top executives, that
has to hurt. Not only have they failed so far to grasp a highly
lucrative opportunity, but more important, the hurdles standing in
their way are strictly of their own making.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin Making $15 Million a Year
</P>
<P>
   Former Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin will be paid more than
$15 million _ not including options for 1.5 million shares of stock
_ this year as an executive at Citigroup, according to a filing
with the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Music Industry Sees a New Threat
</P>
<P>
   The music industry was already disturbed about how easy it is to
copy music online without paying for it. But in recent months an
online service called Napster has greatly magnified the threat by
making it easier to find and copy music. Last month, the Recording
Industry Association of America sued Napster, seeking damages and
an injunction that would effectively end the service.
</P>
<P>
   Labor Faces a Test in Boeing Strike
</P>
<P>
   The strike against Boeing by the union that represents engineers
and technical workers has mushroomed into one of the largest
strikes by white-collar workers against a private company in years.
For national labor leaders, the walkout is clearly seen as a major
test of their ability to organize a potentially large segment of
the work force: professional workers.
</P>
<P>
   Hip Forefather Backs Dollar Coin
</P>
<P>
   A wry, sly version of George Washington _ portrayed in
contemporary pursuits from dining on Chinese takeout to surfing to
riding the subway _ is the focus of an atypically offbeat campaign
from the federal government, promoting use of the new dollar coin.
The goal is to help prevent the new coin from suffering the same
fate as its predecessor, the Susan B. Anthony dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Hain to Buy Celestial Seasonings
</P>
<P>
   Hain Food Group, which has been acquiring companies in the
natural food business over the last several years, agreed to buy
Celestial Seasonings, the maker of herbal teas, in a stock deal
valued at $390 million.
</P>
<P>
   Genzyme Plan to Acquire Biomatrix
</P>
<P>
   The biotechnology company Genzyme agreed to acquire Biomatrix
for about $738.5 million in cash and stock. Genzyme plans to
combine Biomatrix with two of its units and create a company called
Genzyme Biosurgery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
