u i BC-CHINA-RIGHTS-NYT &LR;      03-06 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA TRIES TO DEFLECT CRITICISM ON RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ With the Clinton administration determined to
have China's record on human rights condemned by the U.N. Human
Rights Commission in Geneva, the Chinese are relying on intensive
diplomacy and procedural ploys to escape criticism.
</P>
<P>
   It is a system that has worked well in the past for would-be
targets of condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the U.S. administration decides to sponsor the anti-China
resolution, we believe, like in previous situations, the majority
of the commission will be on China's side,'' Shen Guofang, China's
deputy representative at the United Nations said in an interview.
``They don't want to see a confrontation in the commission.''
</P>
<P>
   Shen predicted that the United States would not get the solid
support of Europe. Some Western diplomats here say the Chinese have
been able to play American and European commercial interests
against one other with considerable success.
</P>
<P>
   China has had ``dialogues'' with European countries to explain
its record, Shen said, adding that there should be more talks with
the United States, whose main irritant may really be China's
socialist system, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course we have some room for improvement,'' Shen said. But
since the 1970s, when China began to open its economy and begin
other reforms, there have been big changes, he said. ``China now
has the best human rights situation in its history.''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats and human rights officials, who point to steps China
has begun taking to cooperate with rights monitors, say that public
criticism is anathema to Beijing. When the U.N. high commissioner
for human rights, Mary Robinson, said in China that the rights
situation had declined, officials warned her not to raise the issue
of Falun Gong, the banned religious sect, or other problems that
she has highlighted.
</P>
<P>
   For a powerful and determined country like China _ or Russia,
when Chechnya is at issue, or at times the United States _ the U.N.
system can offer many ways to avoid public scrutiny and
embarrassing moments, from the Security Council all the way down to
subcommittees meeting in basement rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Official functions are not the only focus. Film screenings, art
exhibitions, journalists' briefings and even ecumenical religious
services can be blocked by pressure from various nations. China is
considered one of the most active in denying a platform for
critics, including the Dalai Lama, who is effectively barred from
U.N. events.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead of the annual commission meeting in Geneva, which this
year runs from March 20 until the end of April, China has been
running a two-track defense, diplomats and human rights advocates
say.
</P>
<P>
   In Geneva, the Chinese are expected to try to keep an
American-sponsored resolution on its human rights record off the
full commission's agenda by using a pre-emptive parliamentary
technique, a ``no action'' motion. With support of other Asian,
African and some Latin American countries, China has managed to
have the resolution struck in advance nearly every year; once it
was discussed and defeated.
</P>
<P>
   India, whose rights record the State Department last week
characterized as rife with ``significant abuses,'' backs China, as
does Iran.
</P>
<P>
   On a second track, China works to bar organizations of Chinese
or Tibetan exiles from getting a hearing there. This year it has
already succeeded in excluding Human Rights in China, a New
York-based group led by prominent exiles.
</P>
<P>
   Fang Lizhi, an astrophysicist now teaching in the United States,
is co-chairman with Robert Bernstein of Human Rights in China; Xiao
Qiang, another scientist in exile who has worked closely with
Chinese grass-roots groups, particularly the mothers of victims at
Tiananmen Square in 1989, is executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups and U.N. officials say that in the past the
commission meeting in Geneva had been unique within the U.N. system
in its openness to nongovernmental organizations. But they say that
may be changing.
</P>
<P>
   Joanna Weschler, Human Rights Watch's representative at the
United Nations, said that tolerance for nongovernmental
organizations, known as NGO's, has generally been shrinking under
the current composition of a 19-member committee that is able to
grant or deny ``consultative status'' to independent groups.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Huang, Asia program director for the Robert F. Kennedy
Memorial Center for Human Rights in Washington, said the committee
was ``not very NGO-friendly now.'' Some Western diplomats agree.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy Center made Xiao a member of its delegation last
year, and was criticized for giving back-door access. ``This year I
feel for the first time I may not be able to speak,'' Xiao said.
``If we're not going and don't speak, Chinese issues are gone from
the commission.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 2105EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0454 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8731 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     03-06 1403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>

(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By JIM REEVES c.2000 Fort
Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Jerry Narron carried the first lineup card of
the spring to the plate at Hammond Stadium, where the Rangers
opened the exhibition season against the Twins last week, just as
he has for each of his six springs as manager Johnny Oates'
right-hand man. This time, there was one significant difference:
Narron's mom went with him.
</P>
<P>
   He carried her close to his heart, where she will have a special
place for the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Narron kissed his mother goodbye for the last time on Nov. 30 as
she lay in a coma in a hospital bed at Duke University Medical
Center in Durham, N.C. Vileigh Narron died a few moments later, the
lowest point of a tragic off-season for the stoic and very private
Rangers third-base coach.
</P>
<P>
   Narron's marriage of 16 years was in its final, painful months
after a long two years of trying desperately to hold it together
for his five children when the phone rang late on the night of Oct.
30. By then, Jerry and wife Linda had been separated for almost a
year, a prerequisite to divorce in the state of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   As difficult as things had been since January of 1997, when
Linda, out of the blue, told him she wanted to end their marriage,
nothing had prepared Narron for what was to come.
</P>
<P>
   His brother was calling to tell him that their parents, driving
home to Goldsboro, N.C., after attending a 50th-wedding-anniversary
party in Raleigh, had been hit head-on by a drunk driver. They were
both in bad shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impact knocked them into an 18-wheeler, and the 18-wheeler
flipped them over into the median,'' Narron said. ``It took about
45 minutes to cut them out of their Suburban. If they'd been in a
regular-size car, they'd have been killed on impact.''
</P>
<P>
   It was John Narron's injuries that most concerned paramedics
initially. His right leg was almost completely severed in the
crash. His left foot was crushed. He had fractures of the wrist and
collarbone. As soon as he'd been cut out of the vehicle, he was
airlifted to Duke Medical Center, where doctors tried
unsuccessfully to save his right leg.
</P>
<P>
   Vileigh Narron, diagnosed with broken ribs and a fractured
pelvis, was taken to the little hospital in Smithfield. That's
where Jerry Narron went first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to her, and she seemed like she was going to be OK,''
he said. ``On the day after the accident, if you'd told me I was
going to lose one of them, I'd have thought it would be my dad.''
</P>
<P>
   What doctors didn't know was that 80-year-old Vileigh Narron had
suffered internal injuries that would prove fatal. Five days after
the accident her stomach began to swell and emergency surgery was
performed. Her intestines ruptured, essentially poisoning her
system. She died exactly one month after the accident, having never
regained consciousness after the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   By then, she, too, had been transferred to Duke Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``They rolled my dad into her room in a wheelchair on the day
she died,'' Narron said. ``He held her hand and prayed with her.
But he can't remember anything that happened now between the night
of the accident and Dec. 15.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers general manager Doug Melvin, who has been close friends
with Narron since the two played minor-league ball together,
vividly remembers the phone call he received from the Rangers'
coach informing him of the accident. It came on Nov. 2, half an
hour before Melvin was due at a news conference to announce the
trade of two-time American League MVP Juan Gonzalez to Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in my office, and there were several people there, Jim
Lites and Dan O'Brien and Chuck McMichael, and when I hung up from
talking to Jerry, I was emotional and I was crying,'' Melvin
recalled. ``I just broke up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Hey guys, I'm not crying because I just traded Juan
Gonzalez.' I told them I just needed a few minutes by myself.''
</P>
<P>
   It was almost, Melvin said, as if his own parents had been in
the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``His parents always came to visit us in the summers,'' Melvin
said. ``I can still see his father _ we called him `Big Daddy'
because he was a huge man _ sitting up in the stands with Jerry's
mom, watching batting practice.''
</P>
<P>
   The Narrons were a fixture in Baltimore, always driving in to
catch the games whenever the Rangers were in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just great people,'' Melvin said. ``When I went to
his mom's funeral and saw his father with his leg amputated, it was
tough. They were a part of me, too. We've known each other's family
for such a long time. At our parents' ages, we know they're
eventually going to leave us, but the way it happened was so
sudden.''
</P>
<P>
   John and Vileigh Narron were still vibrant, active people. She
was a retired high school math teacher who had played college
soccer and basketball at East Carolina, a great cook who still
baked biscuits from scratch twice a day. John, 72, had retired from
the retail-furniture business 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The week before the accident, they'd gone out with friends
doing something almost every night, and I'd asked my mom if they
were ever going to slow down,'' Narron said. ``She said, `Well,
we're going to go as long as we can because at some point we might
not be able to.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The tragic consequences of that fateful night haven't ended yet.
Although John Narron made a remarkable turnaround from mid-December
to mid-January, the injuries to his left foot were horrendous and
went virtually ignored while doctors fought to save his life and
his right leg, which had become infected. Now his left foot is also
infected and it is increasingly likely that he will lose it, too.
</P>
<P>
   And the intoxicated driver of the other car? Also seriously
injured, he was airlifted to a medical center in Chapel Hill.
Police theorize that he entered the divided, four-lane highway by
driving up an offramp the wrong way. His blood-alcohol content was
almost twice the legal limit.
</P>
<P>
   On the day he was released from the hospital in mid-December, he
was arrested and jailed, but Jerry Narron hasn't even bothered to
find out what charges have been filed against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't really thought a lot about him,'' Narron admitted.
``He has a family that loves him, and it must be very, very
difficult on him, but as far as them throwing him in jail, I
haven't thought about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hate for him to do this to someone else, but this
might have been the first time he's ever been drinking and driving.
I do know that no matter what the DWI laws are, they're not
stringent enough. It only takes one time.''
</P>
<P>
   His parents' accident, coming on top of the painful divorce, has
been devastating, but Narron remains incredibly upbeat and
positive. refusing to give in to the loneliness and pain that haunt
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been easy, but I have been blessed all through my
life with outstanding parents,'' Narron said. ``I was given an
outstanding advantage with the parents I've had. I don't know why
it happened. One day, I think we'll know, but it's just that right
now, things happen in life that we just don't understand why they
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do know that through times of suffering it gives us a chance
to grow closer in our relationship with God, and I believe if I do
anything other than that, my mom and dad's accident will have been
in vain. I just won't allow that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   To do anything less, Narron feels, would dishonor his mom's
memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at it that I had 44 years with as good a mom as anybody
could ever have. I just try to focus on the 44 years of blessing
that I had instead of dwelling on the tragedy of it in losing her
in an accident like that. I just feel so fortunate that I had her
as long as I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going through my personal problems with my wife strengthened
my faith, and I think that helped me get through this. God graces
us, and it is sufficient. Just through what has happened with my
mom and dad, I've grown stronger by it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning of the Rangers' exhibition opener, rookie
sensation Ruben Mateo hooked a low line drive that Narron, standing
in the third-base coaching box, could not avoid. It smacked hard
into his right ankle and caromed away.
</P>
<P>
   Narron looked down and kicked the dirt. He didn't rub it. He
didn't limp. Whatever pain he must have felt, he kept it locked
inside.
</P>
<P>
   Close to his heart.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
