<HEADLINE>
OUTFIELDER COMES FULL CIRCLE AFTER SEVERE INJURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ David Hulse could have, perhaps should
have, quit baseball a long time ago. Perhaps after the first
surgery on his shoulder. Or the second. Certainly the third.
Perhaps after the first surgery on his elbow. Or the second.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps in 1998, when the only job he could get was with
Nashua of the independent Atlantic League.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Hulse stills plays baseball. The Rangers' 1993 rookie
of the year is back with the team, in camp trying to win a job as
an extra outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just shows you how wonderful this profession is that people
will do so much to stay in it,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said.
``You go through a lot pain and frustration and disappointment to
stay alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Hulse loves the game, to be sure. But that's not his only
purpose for being here instead of back home in Colleyville.
</P>
<P>
   ``My reason for being here is to be in the big leagues, but also
to prove that there is divine healing,'' Hulse said. ``I want to
prove to everyone that with God, all things are possible.''
</P>
<P>
   In strictly a baseball sense, it might take a miracle for Hulse
to make the team. He hasn't played in the majors since Sept. 7,
1996, with the Milwaukee Brewers, when he mangled his left shoulder
sliding into home against the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have one outfield job open behind Rusty Greer, Ruben
Mateo, Gabe Kapler and Chad Curtis. Hulse, who flied out to left in
his only at-bat in a 13-6 victory against the Boston Red Sox
yesterday, is 0-for-4 this spring. He is currently behind Mike
Simms, Jason McDonald and Scarborough Green in the pecking order
for the fifth outfielder's spot.
</P>
<P>
   But in a spiritual sense, Hulse is convinced it's a miracle that
he's still playing baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``After my injury in '96, I saw four or five team doctors that
weren't giving me a chance,'' Hulse said. ``Then I went to see Dr.
\RJames\S Andrews, and he said I'm going to do all I can, but I
just want you to be able to throw with your son one day.''
</P>
<P>
   Hulse had carved out a decent career until that injury, using
his speed to make himself a useful player. He batted .290 and stole
29 bases in 114 games with the Rangers in '93, his first full
season in the majors. He hit .255 with 18 steals in the
strike-shortened '94 season and was traded to the Brewers in '95
</P>
<P>
   The next season, his career almost came to an end when he messed
up his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew when I tried to get up that something was wrong,'' he
said. ``I got this burning feeling like I was going to pass out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hulse had severely dislocated his shoulder, and completely
crushed a nerve. The round of surgeries started, as did constant
pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I either slept in the bathtub, because the water made it feel
better, or in a recliner,'' he said. ``I couldn't lay down. And I
was throwing up at night because of the medicine. It felt like it
was dislocating again every time I threw up. Not playing in all of
'97, and averaging a surgery every two months, the pain factor
alone was enough to make me want to hang it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Hulse persevered, though. He signed with Nashua in '98 and hit
.352 in 62 games. That led to a job with Pawtucket, the Boston Red
Sox' Triple-A club, where he hit .329 in 21 games.
</P>
<P>
   He landed a job in the St. Louis Cardinals' organization last
season and batted .335 in 74 games at Triple-A Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best I've hit my whole career,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, he doesn't throw as well as he used to, and he didn't
have a strong arm to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   The odds of making the team are long. Hulse, though, figures he
has beaten longer ones just to get this far.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
