<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAMB SAYS HE'S IN GOOD SHAPE AT THIRD BASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Mike Lamb is not concerned that he might
be falling behind Tom Evans in the third-base battle. Lamb went
1-for-7 in the first three exhibition games, while Evans went
4-for-6 with three home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't put too much emphasis on at-bats right now,'' Lamb
said. ``The timing's not there for anyone, except for Tom.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamb said he got off to poor start in the Arizona Fall League
last year, batting under .250 after the first couple of weeks. By
the end of the season, however, he was up to .343.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a slow starter,'' Lamb said. ``This is
nothing new to me. I'm sure by next week I'll be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamb dropped to 1-for-8 after flying out to shallow left field
in his first at-bat yesterday, but then singled on a sharp liner to
right field. However, he also made an error on a slow one-hopper.
</P>
<P>
   Evans continued to swing a hot bat, lining an opposite-field
single to right and also drawing a walk.
Mateo keeps playing Players assured of regular playing time usually
get plenty of time off this early in the spring, but not center
fielder Ruben Mateo. He started his fourth consecutive exhibition
game yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Mateo, though, is not complaining. Two stints on the disabled
list last year limited him to 122 at-bats in the majors, and he
only got 88 at-bats in winter ball because of a stomach ulcer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play a lot in winter ball, so I need a lot of
at-bats,'' said Mateo, who went 0-for-3 yesterday and is batting
.182 this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates said he wants to get all the young players,
including right fielder Gabe Kapler and third basemen Mike Lamb and
Tom Evans, plenty of at-bats in exhibition games, as well as Mike
Simms, who was out almost all of last year because of a torn left
Achilles' tendon.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want the young hitters to learn,'' Oates said. ``They play
a lot in spring training. That's the way it is. When you've been
around for a while, you get to play your four innings and go to the
beach.''
Well-armed Gabe Kapler showed off his strong right arm in the third
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Speedy Red Sox shortstop Donnie Sadler was at first when Jose
Offerman singled to right. Sadler tried to go to third, but Kapler
threw a bullet to the base to get him by about 20 feet.
</P>
<P>
   With Kapler in right and Ruben Mateo, who has one of the best
arms in baseball, in center, opposing teams might think twice about
taking the extra base this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both throw pretty good,'' Johnny Oates said. ``They've
got a chance to throw some people out. In the past against us,
runners just kept going.''
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Justin Thompson increased his throwing program from 25 pitches
to 35, still all fastballs at about 60 percent velocity. ``He
looked good,'' pitching coach Dick Bosman said. ``He looked crisp.
He put something on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Luis Alicea had a two-home-run game. First
baseman Rafael Palmeiro had his first of the spring, a two-run shot
off former Ranger Jeff Fassero.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Darren Oliver took some ribbing from his teammates for
being identified as ``Diaz'' during highlights on ESPN's
``SportsCenter'' on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   One day after being accused by Johnny Oates of being a
front-runner for jumping on the Cincinnati Reds' bandwagon,
basketball analyst Dick Vitale showed up in camp yesterday wearing
a Rangers cap. ``I shamed him into it,'' Oates said. / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
