<SLUG> BC-GLF-CENTENARIAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT MANY PEOPLE CAN CALL HOGAN AN EX-CADDIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ As a charter member of Colonial Country Club
and a lifelong golf lover, Marie Goodfellow could not think of a
more appropriate place than ``Hogan's Alley'' to celebrate her
100th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly what she'll do Sunday during a birthday tea at
the club made famous by one of her former caddies. Goodfellow, who
turns 100 on Thursday, began playing golf in 1923 as a member of
Glen Garden Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   A competitive amateur golfer during that era, Goodfellow said
her game began improving after she turned to a teen-ager at Glen
Garden for some advice: a caddie named Ben Hogan, who went on to
win nine major championships and five Colonial titles during a
legendary PGA Tour career. Hogan died in 1997 at age 84.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben was a good caddie,'' she said. ``He always helped us. When
I started playing, I didn't know much. I'd shoot around 80. Ben
taught me how to play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Once in a while, another future Hall of Famer carried
Goodfellow's clubs. Byron Nelson also caddied at Glen Garden during
the 1920s. But Goodfellow said Nelson, now an 88-year-old Roanoke
resident, spent most of his time in the pro shop during the years
she was a course regular.
</P>
<P>
   ``Byron caddied for me once in a while, if my regular caddie was
off,'' she said. ``But he mostly ran the pro shop. He was selling
clubs and checking in players. Byron was an awfully fine fellow ...
very loyal. Both he and Ben really made something of themselves. It
makes me proud to say that I knew them. To this day, if Byron sees
me at Colonial \Rduring tournament week\S, he always makes it a
point to come and speak to me.''
</P>
<P>
   When Goodfellow began playing golf, Colonial was not an option.
The course did not open until 1936. But she and her husband, Jack,
were among the first to pay the $50 initiation fee to join Marvin
Leonard's creation when Colonial opened its doors.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow members will be among Sunday's guests. So will former
co-workers from Cook Children's Hospital, where Goodfellow served
as a volunteer for 37 years.
</P>
<P>
   Her playing days are over, but Goodfellow remains connected to
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still her passion,'' said Mae Ryon, a cousin who is
organizing the birthday tea. ``She loves to talk about golf and she
watches it every Saturday and Sunday. It puts her age into
perspective when you think about the fact that Ben Hogan and Byron
Nelson caddied for her. Not many people can say that.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
