<HEADLINE>
NIEUWENDYK'S RETURN AWAITED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ When center Joe Nieuwendyk's return from a
separated right shoulder came up yesterday, Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock was cautious in his selection of a date.
</P>
<P>
   Definitely not tomorrow, maybe Friday and more likely Sunday.
But Hitchcock is rarely cautious, which probably says as much about
the importance of Nieuwendyk's return as anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to be effective, we have to have a second line, which
he's always been responsible for, that can score, that is a threat
to score every shift,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars haven't had that since Jan. 19, when Nieuwendyk went
down against Anaheim. He said he was sitting there driving himself
crazy as he watched the Stars' 5-3 loss to Detroit. He's ready to
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not naive either,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``I know what is
ahead. I know there is going to be some high-emotion times down the
road. I can't get too worked up.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will be on Nieuwendyk's line?
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, on the right wing will be \RJamie\S Langenbrunner
or \RBrett\S Hull,'' Hitchcock said. ``The left side is still a
gray area.''
</P>
<P>
   The choices are more plentiful than before Nieuwendyk got
injured. There's Brenden Morrow, Kirk Muller, Aaron Gavey, Scott
Thornton and Jere Lehtinen, when he returns from his ankle injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know since I've been here they've kind of played musical
wingers, and now I think you have two really solid guys up there,''
Nieuwendyk said. Nieuwendyk played with Morrow before he got hurt.
Now, the rookie has been playing on the top line with Mike Modano.
</P>
<P>
   So have Nieuwendyk and Modano been bartering about who gets to
play with him?
</P>
<P>
   Not really, Nieuwendyk says.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the consolation prize? Lehtinen,'' Nieuwendyk said.
``That's a nice luxury to have.''
Carbonneau update
</P>
<P>
   Coach Ken Hitchcock said the Stars wouldn't know the extent of
center Guy Carbonneau's right wrist injury until they get results
from his magnetic-resonance-imaging examination this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll kind of know then the kind of situation we have to deal
with,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau exited midway through Sunday's loss to Detroit. He
didn't return.
</P>
<P>
   If Carbonneau isn't able to play against Vancouver tomorrow,
Kirk Muller will take Carbonneau's spot on the checking line,
Hitchcock said. The line already was missing winger Blake Sloan,
who has been out since Feb. 21 with a hairline fracture of his left
fibula. Hitchcock said he expects Sloan to begin skating sometime
this week.
About last week
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hitchcock still had trouble evaluating the Stars' past week,
in which they went 2-1-1 against Colorado, Philadelphia, Phoenix
and Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think looking at the week I'd say that we're right there
with all of the top teams,'' Hitchcock said. ``But we aren't any
better than any of those teams. ... I think it just shows you there
is a lot of teams in this battle right now, a lot of teams that
obviously think the same way we do, that they've got as good of
teams as we do or better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars didn't lose any of their seven-point lead in the
Pacific Division with Sunday's loss because Phoenix lost, too. And
the Stars are set to get back Joe Nieuwendyk, Jere Lehtinen and
Blake Sloan.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, we have to be pleased where we are at right
now considering the number of injuries this year,'' Nieuwendyk
said. ``If we go on all of our cylinders, we'll be a tough team to
beat. I think our game is pretty solid all the way through right
now.'' / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
