<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRBUS-JUMBO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS QUESTIONS NEED FOR SUPERJUMBO JET ANYTIME SOON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Airbus executives insist they will go ahead with development of
their A3XX superjumbo by the end of this year, but a new
independent market analysis questions the need for such a behemoth
jetliner anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   A commercial plane the size of the doubledecker, 550-seat
A3XX-100 will eventually be needed by airlines, but not until 2009,
according to the forecast by the Teal Group, a market research firm
in Fairfax, Va., whose reports are closely watched by the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The A3XX is utterly irrelevant in today's market
environment,'' said Richard Aboulafia, the Teal Group's aviation
analyst and author of the report.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than launching the A3XX this year, Airbus should wait
until 2004 or 2005, which would push back the jet's service entry
until 2009, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to take a much more realistic view of the timing of
a launch,'' he said of Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   If the A3XX is launched by the end of this year, Airbus has said
the first deliveries to customers would begin in 2005. But there
will not be a market for the A3XX by then, Aboulafia said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of deregulation and more ``open skies'' agreements
between nations, airlines today have more flexibility to haul
passengers directly from one city to another, bypassing the big
airport hubs.
</P>
<P>
   Known as point-to-point service, this fragmentation of routes
has resulted in airlines wanting smaller jets to provide passengers
with more frequency of travel.
</P>
<P>
   David Venz, chief spokesman for Airbus in the United States,
said Airbus is well aware of the trend toward route fragmentation.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also high-density hub routes _ such as Hong Kong
to London _ where bigger planes are needed, Venz said. And as
passenger volume at hub airports continues to increase, so will the
demand for bigger planes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an either or situation,'' he said of the hub vs.
fragmentation debate.
</P>
<P>
   The Teal Group report sees the market differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very simply, here and now, route fragmentation and airline
right-sizing are clear realities,'' Aboulafia wrote in his report.
``Denying these trends looks silly.''
</P>
<P>
   British Airways is an example of an airline that is trying to
``right-size'' its fleet. The carrier announced last year it will
replace its 747s with 777s that carry fewer passengers but will
make the airline more money. And British Airways is also replacing
its Boeing 757s with the new 100-seat Airbus A318 now in
development.
</P>
<P>
   The move to the small A318 will allow the airline to focus on
better-paying customers on shorter routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airlines today want to concentrate on high-value passengers,''
Aboulafia said in an interview. ``They are trying to get the
backpackers off their planes. A lot of airlines will be doing
this.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a trend that spells doom for the A3XX should it be launched
now, he said.
</P>
<P>
   There are few issues in the industry that have generated more
debate than the A3XX.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Airbus must develop the A3XX if it expects to be
Boeing's commercial airplane equal. Without competition from the
A3XX, Boeing will continue to enjoy its 30-year monopoly with the
747, the only plane today that can carry more than 400 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is watching what Airbus does with great interest. It
plans to build a stretch version of its 420-passenger 747-400 that
would carry as many as 100 more passengers and be much more
efficient to operate.
</P>
<P>
   A derivative jumbo jet would cost far less to develop than an
entirely new plane, and, Boeing believes, effectively counter the
threat from an Airbus superjumbo.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing executives have said they will develop their ``growth''
jumbo regardless of what Airbus does, but they also acknowledge
there has been little interest from customers so far.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus and Boeing have extensively examined and re-examined the
market for big airplanes and reached much different conclusions.
Boeing's latest market forecast puts demand for a superjumbo at
only 360 planes over the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus, though, has forecast that market at about 1,500
aircraft, including about 300 freighters.
</P>
<P>
   In recent interviews, top Airbus executives have said they see
no reason why the Airbus supervisory board will not give the go
ahead for development of the A3XX by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not the first time Airbus has said it would launch
the A3XX, Aboulafia said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a huge file on this,'' he said. ``I can show you
similar statements from previous years. If they go ahead, I can't
think of more than one or two airlines that would be at all
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   The Airbus consortium has said it needs 30 to 40 total orders
from three to five carriers before going ahead.
</P>
<P>
   In December, however, the Airbus supervisory board put off until
later in 2000 giving the green light to start trying to sell the
plane to customers. The board said it was still working to confirm
financing for the development costs. Those development costs,
according to Airbus, are expected to around $12 billion, a figure
that many analysts believe is several billion dollars too low.
Airbus reportedly has spent about $600 million so far on A3XX
design work.
</P>
<P>
   But in his report, Aboulafia said Airbus has also kept money in
reserve for a possible launch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airbus has already inflicted a few wounds on itself by
constantly keeping money in reserve for the A3XX,'' he wrote. ``The
A318, A340-500/600, and other projects should have gone ahead
before they actually did. And unless Airbus resigns itself to
waiting for a 2004/2005 launch date for the A3XX, other projects,
such as the A330-100, will remain starved for cash while waiting
for the big one.''
</P>
<P>
   The A340-500/600, now is development, are ultra-long-range
planes for Asian airlines. Boeing late last month announced it
would develop two long-range derivatives of its 777 that will
compete against the A340-500/600.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus has not yet launched the A330-100. It would replace older
A300s and A310s and would help Airbus tap into what is seen as an
emerging market _ for new medium-range jets that seat about 250
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, which is looking at possibly shrinking its 777 should
this market develop, has benefited from the Airbus ``fixation'' on
the A3XX, Aboulafia said in the interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``The A3XX has yet to attract customers, but it has occupied
Airbus' attention and a lot of its money for the last four or five
years,'' he said. ``I can't think of anything better for Boeing.''
</P>
<P>
   But the A3XX will eventually be needed, and that will hurt
Boeing long term, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that happens, the good old days for the 747 may be over,
though by no means done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors points toward success of the A3XX by 2009, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the thick routes are fragmenting today, requiring
smaller planes, they will eventually thicken and things will be as
flexible as they can get,'' he said. ``And then the equipment will
start getting bigger again because of growth.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition he said, right-sizing will have run its course.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airlines will have gotten rid of as many cheapskate
backpacking passengers as they can and will see growth again with
bigger planes.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, airlines by 2009 will be retiring their older 747-400s.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing will have to move fast with its new stretch 747 once the
A3XX is launched, Aboulafia said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boeing should wait for now, but be ready to hit the ground
running,'' he said. ``They should be ready to go from a standing
start. Boeing needs to get out there and say they can be just as
good for a whole lost less.''
</P>
<P>
   The 550-seat A3XX-100 is projected to cost about $208 million; a
stretch version that could carry 650 passengers would cost upwards
of $240 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing 747-400 goes for around $165 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were Boeing,'' Aboulafia said, ``I'd have a fairly witty
ad campaign to make the A3XX look truly unaffordable. I'd be
flippant about it: `For the price of an A3XX we will be sell you a
growth 747 and throw in for free a new 757.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
