u f BC-QWEST-MARKETPLACE-NYT     03-06 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QWEST-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: ENGAGED TO U S WEST, QWEST FALLS FOR DEUTSCHE
TELEKOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (Budgeted earlier as QWEST-USWEST) 
(mk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Qwest Communications International Inc. had not agreed to
acquire U S West Inc., Qwest probably would have announced a deal
to be acquired by Deutsche Telekom of Germany by now, and at a
healthy premium to Qwest's stock market value.
</P>
<P>
   For Qwest's top executives, that has to hurt. Not only have they
failed so far to grasp a highly lucrative opportunity with the
German company, but more important, the hurdles standing in their
way are strictly of their own making.
</P>
<P>
   It would almost surely take at least a week, but Denver-based
Qwest, the fast-growing long-distance communications carrier, could
still end up striking a deal with Deutsche Telekom. Such a deal
would allow Joseph P. Nacchio, Qwest's chairman, to walk away with
hundreds of millions of dollars and Philip P. Anschutz, the
reclusive tycoon who is Qwest's largest shareholder, to expand his
bankroll by billions.
</P>
<P>
   But it will not be easy, and other high-technology companies
whose stock valuations are growing as fast as their dreams will be
left with a lesson in how taking a proverbial bird in the hand can
make it difficult to go after a greater prize later.
</P>
<P>
   For a week or more, executives at Qwest tried to figure out how
they could sell their company to Deutsche Telekom, Europe's biggest
communications carrier, while minimizing any entanglement from U S
West, one of the regional Bell phone companies. That is why they
did not even tell U S West's chairman that they were speaking with
the Germans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here they were, locked into this merger with U S West, so the
Qwest people, those at the top anyway, thought they could make a
lot more money selling out alone, rather than go through the
still-cumbersome merger process with U S West,'' said Steven
Lehman, manager of the Federated Utility Fund in Pittsburgh, which
owns more than $50 million of Qwest and U S West shares.
</P>
<P>
   But on Sunday night, Qwest gave up that hope. It had become
clear that U S West would not go away quietly. Much more important,
it became clear that U S West would have at least a decent case
that it would be owed billions of dollars in damages, perhaps from
Deutsche Telekom, were Qwest to repudiate U S West in favor of a
deal with the German company. So Qwest announced that any agreement
would have to include offers for both Qwest and U S West.
</P>
<P>
   There is hardly any chance that Deutsche Telekom would be
interested in acquiring U S West on its own. In fact, some analysts
said Monday that institutional investors in Europe were expressing
doubts about the sense of the German company's acquiring U S West
at all. So now Deutsche Telekom must decide whether acquiring U S
West, with all of the regulatory difficulties that is sure to
entail, is worth the price of admission to acquiring Qwest.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it is worth asking why or how Qwest ended up in a
deal with U S West that now carries such significant baggage.
</P>
<P>
   It smacks of Monday-morning quarterbacking to point out that the
deep strategic rationale underlying Qwest's bid for U S West was
not crystal clear when it was announced last summer. But it is
true. The conventional wisdom at the time was that the deal was
more about Qwest using its high-flying stock to go after an
undervalued company with concrete assets and customers that had
already put itself on the block_ by agreeing to be acquired by
Global Crossing Ltd. of Bermuda _ rather than about far-reaching
strategic synergies.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the U S West deal stood up on its own merits and
there was little way for Qwest's senior management to know just how
it would constrain them in the future. And most relevant, there was
little way for them to foresee the explosive increase in value of
shares in European communications companies, which allowed Deutsche
Telekom to consider acquiring a company of Qwest's market value,
about $45 billion. Still ensnared in the imploding Global One
venture last summer, Deutsche Telekom may not have even been on
Qwest's radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``In hindsight does Qwest wish that it didn't have the U S West
issue to deal with? Yeah,'' said Eric Strumingher, a
telecommunications analyst for Paine Webber. ``But it's pretty easy
to second-guess the decision today, now that Deutsche Telekom's
stock has more than doubled. At the time it looked like a great
decision and personally, if I were Joe Nacchio and Phil Anschutz, I
would have done that deal again.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Anschutz in particular is faced with that deal's
consequences. Deutsche Telekom may have already been spooked by the
circus that Nacchio started last week when he publicly suggested
that Qwest was exploring ways out of the U S West deal. If not,
Anschutz now needs to figure out just what it will take to get U S
West on board with a German offer.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, there could still be a way for Qwest to extricate
itself from U S West, if Anschutz wants to strike a solo deal with
Deutsche Telekom badly enough. After all, everything has its price.
But any check that would persuade U S West to walk away would have
to bear 10 or even 11 digits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
