<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPER-GEORGIA07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia has local issues on the line for Super Tuesday
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Georgia voters go to the polls today, they'll
have plenty of company.
</P>
<P>
   Super Tuesday presidential primaries and caucuses in 16 states
and one U.S. territory could virtually decide the nominees in this
year's Democratic and Republican presidential contests.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia's Republican primary, the main battle is between
Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Arizona Sen. John McCain, with
conservative radio commentator Alan Keyes also vying for Republican
votes.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Vice President Al Gore faces former New
Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore held sizable leads over their opponents heading
into today's Georgia's primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia elections officials expect about 38 percent of the
state's 3.4 million registered voters to cast ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Polls across the state are open from 7 a.m. until 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much harder to predict'' this year, said Chris Riggall a
spokesman for the secretary of state's office. ``The candidates
haven't been here. We've not seen any TV (advertising). We aren't
in the game as we have been in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   But a handful of local ballot questions will be decided today
that could help energize voters. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   _ Cherokee County _ Continuing a 1 percent sales tax to fund
parks and green space, a new jail and improvements to the old one,
a new animal shelter, three new fire stations, libraries, road and
bridge improvements, and projects in the county's cities. The
special sales tax could bring in up to $125 million over five
years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Newton County _ A proposed five-year sales tax that is
expected to generate $40 million to $42 million. The money would be
used for expanding the jail, enlarging the county's landfill,
renovating the courthouse and constructing a building for the
county's mental health and physical health departments.
</P>
<P>
   _ Henry County _ A 10-year, $32.7 million bond issue that would
pay for school construction, including a proposed $25 million high
school, probably in the Luella community. The rest of the funds
would pay for renovations and additions at several elementary
campuses.
</P>
<P>
   _ Roswell _ A $34.04 million bond issue to pay for parks in the
city, with the remainder allocated for a combined fire and police
station, firefighting equipment, and sidewalk and drainage
improvements.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
