<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-OHIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN AMBASSADORS FOR BUSH BLANKET OHIO 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ This is what it means for Gov. George W. Bush
to have the state's entire Republican organization behind him in
Ohio, the third-largest state with a primary on Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
   For the last three days, Gov. Bob Taft has been barnstorming for
Bush, flying back and forth, in a private plane rented by the
party, to Cleveland, Cincinnati, Dayton, Toledo and Columbus,
campaigning with all the intensity he would devote to one of his
own races.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. George V. Voinovich was on the stump this weekend for Bush
too. So were three prominent congressmen _ Rob Portman, John R.
Kasich and John A. Boehner _ as well as Lt. Gov. Maureen O'Connor,
Attorney General Betty Montgomery and dozens of other elected
officials and party leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's Ohio campaign manager, Robert Paduchik, on leave from his
regular job as Taft's political director, said on Monday that the
Bush campaign had made 100,000 telephone calls, dropped 250,000
pieces of literature and planted 15,000 yard signs across the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Indications are that all this work is paying off. The
organization is especially important because Bush himself has
campaigned in Ohio for only one day this year, and 69 delegates are
at stake here on Tuesday, third only to California's 162 and New
York's 101.
</P>
<P>
   A new poll released on Monday by the University of Cincinnati's
Institute for Policy Research showed Bush ahead of Sen. John
McCain, 61 percent to 36 percent. The survey, which was conducted
Wednesday through Sunday and involved 407 probable voters in the
Republican primary, has a margin of error of plus or minus 4.9
percentage points. A poll taken earlier last week for The Cleveland
Plain Dealer by Zogby International of Utica, N.Y., showed Bush
ahead by a similar margin.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain, whose own organization in Ohio consists basically of
a loose-knit band of volunteers, has hardly given up in a state
that could be critical to his survival in his race for the
presidency. He drew large and enthusiastic crowds to rallies on
Sunday in a high school gymnasium outside of Cleveland and at an
airport hangar in Wilmington in southwestern Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mike DeWine, the only Ohio politician of any note who is
backing McCain, said in an interview on Monday that he had his own
pollster, the Tarrance Group of Alexandria, Va., test the
presidential race in this state last week, and it found Bush ahead
by only 5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   DeWine said he had spent the weekend knocking on doors in
blue-collar neighborhoods in Northeastern Ohio and had found
considerable support for McCain among independents and conservative
Democrats who, under the rules here, are free to vote in the
Republican primary. DeWine said he figured these voters had been
undercounted by the pollsters showing a large Bush lead.
</P>
<P>
   Similar rules allowing crossover voting led to a surprising
victory by McCain in the Michigan primary two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have been advertising heavily. The Akron Beacon
Journal reported on Sunday that Bush was spending about $800,000
and McCain about $650,000 on television commercials in Ohio,
amounts comparable to what is spent here in competitive races for
governor or the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Both camps have steered clear of negative advertisements. Bush's
commercials mostly promote his record as governor of Texas.
McCain's emphasize his conservative credentials as senator of
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   John Green, director of the Ray C. Bliss Institute of Applied
Politics at the University of Akron, said he believed that Bush was
ahead but not by anything like the comfortable margin reported on
Monday in the Cincinnati poll.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Taft and the other Bush supporters here, Green said,
``I suspect they're not 25 points ahead in their own polls, or they
wouldn't be working so hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
