<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPER-LEDE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Presidential contests today could settle nominations
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Today the cold hand of certainty is scheduled to reach
down and take hold of a race that up to now has had its share of
surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Until today's primaries and caucuses, spanning a swath of the
globe from Maine to American Samoa, the twists and turns of the
campaign have been recorded in those imprecise measurements known
as bounce and spin.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday morning, the race to the nomination will be
measured in delegates, and for each of the five contestants left in
the running for the Democratic and Republican nominations, the
campaign will have taken a fateful turn.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate with the least to lose is the one who cares least
about how many delegates he wins: Alan Keyes, the stem-winding
conservative orator making his second run for the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   With tenacity, and respectable showings in Iowa and New
Hampshire, Keyes has won a spot on the podium for the final
Republican debates. He can continue a low-budget campaign whether
he wins delegates today or not.
</P>
<P>
   For Keyes, the question may be how long he can expect the kind
of exposure he has had up to now, with the race for the Republican
nomination headed toward a speedy conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   After riding so high, the candidate with the most to lose is
Sen. John McCain of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   With losses last week in Virginia, North Dakota and Washington
state, McCain now trails Texas Gov. George W. Bush in the delegate
race by 208 to 104. With 613 of the 1,034 delegates needed to win
the nomination up for grabs, the former Navy pilot has to pull off
a tough combination to keep his insurgency campaign afloat.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is expected to run strongest in the five New England
states voting today. If he could sweep those states, win in New
York where polls show the Republicans in a very close race, capture
a respectable number of delegates in Ohio and top Tuesday's
``beauty contest'' in California, McCain would have bounced back
handsomely after last week's defeats.
</P>
<P>
   That still cedes Bush the delegate race in California as well as
other delegate-rich states such as Georgia and Maryland. But if
McCain shows good results in the three biggest states, he would at
least force Republicans to take another long look at Bush's
viability as a national candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Skipping to the Democrats, the candidate who has already lost
the most is former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   If McCain has to pull off a long shot to stay in the Republican
race, Bradley needs huge upsets all across the electoral map to
climb back into the Democratic competition with Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley began his campaign in better shape financially than
McCain, with whom he has been compared so often. But his narrow
loss in New Hampshire and the media's gallop to cover McCain's
livelier campaign left him in poor position to compete for the
bounty of Democratic delegates in play today.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's best hope may be that a respectable showing today
gives him a way to make a graceful exit.
</P>
<P>
   But for Bush and Gore _ who, it's presumed, can't really lose
today _ a lot is still at stake.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush wins Georgia, Ohio and the California delegates, he
moves to a virtual lock on the nomination, especially with his home
state of Texas and Florida, where his brother Jeb is governor,
among the states voting the next week.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Democratic race nearing an end, every day the
Republican race goes on costs Bush. He'd like to wrap it up
decisively with solid victories in every region of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Already on Monday, Bush was talking about reuniting the
fractured party after the tense competition with McCain. Bush has
repeatedly insisted he was spending so much money because he's
running a national campaign. He wants a national victory today to
spring him into the general election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Very soon _ maybe Wednesday _ Gore has to begin an effort to win
over independents, who have been cool to him.
</P>
<P>
   But just as Bush wants the GOP primaries decided by true-blue
Republicans, Gore would have no problem with a 100 percent
Democratic electorate at the polls today.
</P>
<P>
   With his nomination nearly secure, Gore also will be looking at
the results today with an eye to the general election. He wants a
good turnout of union members and African-American voters as a dry
run for the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Another big primary looms next week, but the front-runners in
both parties hope by then they will have no contest.
</P>
<P>
   The challengers are hoping in the complex chemistry of this
cross-country primary day, there is some combination that can keep
their hopes alive.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
