<HEADLINE>
FLYING WITH JETBLUE, THE NEW KID IN THE AIR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 12) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a promise of stylish economy and attentive service, JetBlue
has started flying out of Terminal 6 at Kennedy International
Airport to Fort Lauderdale and Buffalo, the first of 30 cities it
plans to serve within three years.
</P>
<P>
   Since airline deregulation in 1979, more than 40 new carriers
have come and, mostly, gone. In JetBlue's favor, it is backed by
the deep pockets of the financier George Soros, who is one of three
primary investors, and it is being led by a management team with
solid experience in the tricky business of scheduling, reservations
and quick turnarounds.
</P>
<P>
   JetBlue flies new Airbus A320s, a single-aisle aircraft, and
offers one class of service. The airline was scheduled to take
delivery of its third plane last week. As a new one arrives, about
every five weeks for the next few years, a new destination will be
added, said Gareth Edmondson-Jones, the airline spokesman. Tampa
service is set to begin Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The strengths, and a few weaknesses, of the new carrier were
evident one recent morning on Flight 1 from Buffalo to JFK.
</P>
<P>
   At check-in an agent issued a paper boarding coupon, the first
sign of cost-cutting. The two-week advance fare is $49 each way;
$69 on Friday and Sunday. The walk-up fare is $99, compared to a
$245 walk-up fare on US Airways, which flies to Buffalo from La
Guardia Airport.
</P>
<P>
   At 8 a.m. the only indication of JetBlue at Gate 10, which is
owned by United Airlines, was a small metal sign, slung over the
gate door. At 8:27, two minutes late, the plane pulled up, its blue
and white fuselage matching the cloudless sky and mantle of snow
outside.
</P>
<P>
   Just seven minutes later all 67 passengers were off, and the
gate agent called for families with small children to start
boarding, along with those in rows 20 through 27.
</P>
<P>
   Three minutes later, when an elderly woman with a walker
appeared, so did the first sign that JetBlue may not be different
from other airlines. While one gate agent accompanied the woman to
her seat, the other stood at the gate desk, never making eye
contact with the tightening semicircle of passengers.
</P>
<P>
   When a passenger came rushing down the concourse and pushed
through the crowd, this gate agent let him board, as well as two
more passengers who followed moments later, without acknowledging
those waiting their turn.
</P>
<P>
   On board, the cabin crew worked every moment. When one man's
struggle to close a packed bin held up the boarding, the lead
flight attendant, in a friendly voice, called out: ``Sir, if you
will just leave that for now I'll get it. That way we won't hold up
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   The overhead bins, while large, are not deep enough to allow
roll-aboard luggage to slide in wheels down. Future aircraft will
have deeper bins.
</P>
<P>
   The last passenger stepped through the door at 8:53, but because
the passenger count came up one short at 121 the departure,
scheduled for 8:55, was delayed two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the JetBlue plane looked spacious and spare. The gray
leather seats are designed so that when the back is reclined the
bottom comfortably slides forward.
</P>
<P>
   Later this month, a television set with direct feeds from
satellites should be on the back of each seat. A credit-card swipe
to turn on the TV will cost $5, a fee that may be waived on delayed
flights.
</P>
<P>
   The plane also features unusual bulkheads at the first row that
create a sense of spaciousness. One is only five feet high,
allowing passengers to catch a glimpse of the cabin crew in the
galley. On the A-B-C side (seating is six across), there is a
trapezoidal bulkhead window that allows passengers to see two
flight attendants in their jump seats.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers were served robust coffee, orange juice and a package
of color-coordinated blue food. The ``blueberry toast'' baked bread
chips contained 5 grams of fat.
</P>
<P>
   When the plane landed at JFK, two minutes late at 10:07, another
problem arose: getting out of the airport.
</P>
<P>
   By summer, Edmondson-Jones said, JetBlue plans to run a shuttle
bus to and from Jamaica Station so people can catch a train into
the city or out to Long Island. But on this morning there were so
few taxis that some people waited in line to get one for as long as
the flight took.
</P>
<P>
   And one passenger paid $40 with tip and toll, more than the fare
of $30.50, including tax, that JetBlue charged in a promotion in
February.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
