<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; HACKER  &LR; _ In the wake of last month's much-publicized hacker attack
against a slew of prominent Internet Web sites, customers of online
brokerage firms suddenly are feeling vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Among the sites temporarily disabled by the so-called
denial-of-service attack was the one maintained by Palo Alto-based
E-Trade Group. The site, at www.etrade.com, was swamped by phony
log-in calls, making it difficult or impossible for E-Trade's real
customers to gain access during a 90-minute period. So, what's a
brokerage customer to do? One preventative measure would be to open
more than one online brokerage account, so if one Web site is down
you can (hopefully) use the other. It also is a good idea to have
at least one account with an online broker that makes it easy for
you to trade securities offline as well _ by telephone, direct
modem hookup or even by visiting a branch. By Arthur M. Louis
</P>
