<HEADER>
A8762 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-AMD-STOCK07-COX     03-06 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMD-STOCK07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fast chip appeals to high-end buyers
 &HT;    By Kirk Ladendorf
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Investors sent Advanced Micro Devices Inc.'s
stock to a 52-week high Monday, following the chipmaker's
announcement that it is shipping Athlon microprocessors running at
1 gigahertz, or 1,000 megahertz.
</P>
<P>
   Sunnyvale, Calif.-based AMD's stock rose $6.50, or 15 percent,
in New York Stock Exchange trading Monday, to close at $48, based
on news of the fast, new Austin-designed-and-manufactured chip.
AMD's previous fastest chip ran at 850 megahertz.
</P>
<P>
   Rival Intel Corp., of Santa Clara, Calif., is expected to make
its own announcement Wednesday that it has begun shipping 1
gigahertz versions of its Pentium III processor.
</P>
<P>
   Dell Computer Corp. of Round Rock is expected to begin shipping
high-end Pentium III-based gigahertz systems toward the end of the
month. Dell, however, declined Monday to set a firm date,
cautioning that it won't begin offering a consumer desktop computer
until it has the necessary components.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that AMD has kept up easily with Intel's fastest chips
has impressed industry analysts, some of whom had written off AMD
as a strong competitor after a series of production mishaps in the
late 1990s kept the company consistently in the red.
</P>
<P>
   ``AMD's products look the best since I've followed this damned
company,'' said analyst David Wu of ABN AMRO in San Francisco.
``They have finally gotten their act together on manufacturing.''
</P>
<P>
   Intense competition between AMD and Intel is influencing both
companies to make early announcements when they ship
high-performance chips, even if they can only produce limited
quantities. That's because each company wants desperately to be
considered the performance leader in Windows-compatible computing,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are shipping thousands of units rather than hundreds of
thousands of units,'' said Dean McCarron of Mercury Research, a
Scottsdale, Ariz., high-tech market research company.
</P>
<P>
   But as both companies steadily improve their manufacturing
processes, their shipment volumes should increase within a month or
two, McCarron said.
</P>
<P>
   ``By mid-summer a gigahertz computer will be an ordinary system
that people will buy,'' McCarron said.
</P>
<P>
   AMD's gigahertz chips are pricey, costing $1,299. Compaq
Computer Corp. said it would begin taking orders for PCs using the
chip with a starting price of $2,499. Gateway Corp. said it has
already begun taking orders for Athlon-based gigahertz computers
with a starting price of $2,999.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the high prices, analysts said three groups of computer
users will snap up the fast new machines: technical workers,
including engineers who work with graphics-oriented design programs
that demand heavy computer horsepower; high-end computer gamers who
crave cutting-edge performance to give them an edge on the
competition; and ``prestige buyers'' who want to have the fastest
machines available on their desktops, whether or not they need the
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The high end of the market, PC enthusiasts, is where most of
the interest will be,'' said Dell spokesman Andy Prince, who
declined to discuss expected prices for the company's 1-gigaherz
machines.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
