<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-ART-2TAKES(820)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE EVE OF A BIG DAY, 2 CANDIDATES DIVERGE
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT4, 26 are being sent to NYT photo clients. A
poll graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM and ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The leading Republican contenders crisscrossed the
biggest state Monday, with Gov. George W. Bush offering a set
speech on racial and religious tolerance and a quiet olive branch
to gay Republicans, and Sen. John McCain keeping up a stiff attack
on the campaign advertising tactics of Bush and his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 24-hours before coast-to-coast contests in 13 states,
including New York, Ohio, Georgia and most of New England, Bush and
McCain both spent a full day in California, whose winner-take-all
primary will account for 162 of the 613 Republican delegates at
stake on Tuesday, the biggest voting day of the presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In rallies and speeches from Santa Clara to San Diego and from
Los Angeles to Long Beach, Bush sounded an upbeat appeal to
moderates, while McCain sought to stoke a backlash against Bush and
``his sleazy Texas buddies,'' over campaign ads attacking McCain on
environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all its flaws, I believe our nation is chosen by God and
commissioned by history to be the model to the world of justice and
inclusion and diversity without division,'' Bush said in brief
remarks at the Simon Wiesenthal Center and the Museum of Tolerance
here. ``These are American convictions. Defending them is America's
calling, and they must be passed intact to America's children.''
</P>
<P>
   In his latest apparent effort to address the firestorm of
criticism that grew out of his visit to Bob Jones University in
South Carolina, Bush added: ``A leader must do more than hold this
conviction. He must give it voice, and he must give it force.
That's my commitment to the people of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   A heckler twice interrupted Bush's speech by calling, ``What
about gay people?'' and Bush made no response. But in an interview
published in The San Francisco Chronicle on Monday, Bush softened
his previous opposition to a meeting with the Log Cabin
Republicans, a national gay group. Last fall, Bush said he would
probably not meet with the group because, ``I don't believe in
group thought, pitting one group of people against another, and all
that does is create kind of a huge political, you know, nightmare
for people.''
</P>
<P>
   After the group ran a weekend of radio advertisements attacking
Bush in New York, where he is in a close contest with McCain, the
Texas governor told The Chronicle, ``Yes, I would consider meeting
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, McCain filed a formal complaint with the Federal
Elections Commission on Monday alleging improper campaign
contributions by two of Bush's biggest financial backers in Texas,
Charles and Sam Wyly, who spent $2.5 million for television
advertising in New York, Ohio and California, attacking McCain
under the name ``Republicans for Clean Air.'' Bush has said he had
no knowledge that the Wylys planned to run the ads, but the McCain
campaign took the position that as a major Bush fund-raiser,
Charles Wyly held an official position in the campaign and had
already contributed the maximum amount allowed by law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ask Governor Bush to do what he refused to do,'' McCain
said at a student rally at Santa Clara University, a Jesuit school
south of San Francisco, ``tell his sleazy Texas buddies to stop
these negative ads and take their money back to Texas where it
belongs and don't try to corrupt American politics with your
money.'' He added: ``Let the people of California decide who will
be the next president of the United States not some billionaires
from Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The McCain camp also filed an emergency complaint with the
Federal Communications Commission, which McCain oversees as
chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee, asserting that the ads
had violated the Communications Act by failing to properly identify
the true sponsor. But Monday evening, the commission declined to
intervene after its officials concluded that they could do little
more than notify the broadcasters that a potential violation had
been raised, and that television stations had an obligation to
assure that the sponsor of the ad was properly identified. The
agency made no judgment about what that identification should be.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who plans to spend election night here on Tuesday,
acknowledged that even if the ads were taken off the air, it would
be a Pyrrhic victory, since the election is Tuesday. ``We'll at
least feel better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After Bush, wearing a Jewish skullcap, lit a memorial torch in
the garden of the Museum of Tolerance, his chief spokeswoman, Karen
Hughes, reacted bitingly to McCain's charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's irresponsible and it's shameful,'' Hughes said. ``He
should be ashamed. He has not one shred of evidence. The governor
has personally said our campaign did not coordinate, our campaign
knew nothing about the ad until a member of the media asked us
about the ad, and Senator McCain should be ashamed of tossing
around scurrilous accusations like that.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
