<SLUG> BC-ALZA-ALZA </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 FDA Approves Alza's Tiny Drug Dispenser  &HT;     By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Alza Corp., the company best known for developing the nicotine
patch, has won government approval to sell a matchstick-size pump
that would be implanted under the skin and deliver a year's worth
of prostate cancer medicine.
<P>
   Alza of said U.S. Food and Drug Administration approval will let
it begin selling its time-release drug, Viadur, late this year or
early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Viadur will be dispensed by a pump , &LR; implanted under the inner
arm. It will drip out a steady supply of a drug that suppresses the
production of testosterone.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors know testosterone fuels prostate cancer growth, and
currently  &LR; prescribe the drugs Leupron or Zoladex to inhibit its
production. Viadur will be a new entry into what financial analysts
fix as a U.S. market for testosterone inhibitors worth more than
$700 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   Alza Vice President Sam Saks said current testosterone
inhibitors are given by injection. Each shot lasts last three or
four months, and a year's treatment costs $2,000 to $3,000. He said
Viadur would offer a convenient yearlong treatment. Alza has not
yet set a price.
</P>
<P>
   Financial analyst Sena P. Lund with Mehta Partner in New York
said Alza must now decide whether to sell Viadur itself, or partner
with a larger drug firm, giving up a share of the revenues for a
larger sales effort.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street was unimpressed. Alza lost 19 cents yesterday to
close at $37.81. Lund said the company's stock has been depressed
for months, after its unsuccessful bid to merge with Abbott
Laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   With the launch of Viadur, Alza will compete with Abbott, which
sells Leupron in a joint venture with the Japanese drug firm
Takeda. Astra Zeneca sells Zoladex.
</P>
<P>
   Alza's first challenge will be convincing patients and
physicians that a yearly dose of testosterone suppressor is worth
the main side effect, the almost complete loss of sexual drive and
erectile function.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard Szabo, a urologist with Kaiser-Permanente in San
Francisco, said most patients on testosterone suppressors lose
their sex drive. He said older patients may not mind, but young men
find the loss so demoralizing that physicians are experimenting
with intermittent hormone control _ keeping the men on the drugs
for six to nine months, then giving them free spells, so sexual
drive can return.
</P>
<P>
   Alza's Saks noted that the intermittent therapy is still
experimental. He said even if doctors and patients move toward this
therapy, the pump can still be easily removed if need be.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, Alza's development of the pump _ which it
called the Duros technology _ could be more significant than its
first use for prostate cancer. Saks said the company is testing
other potential drugs for delivery through the pump, which is made
of the nonreactive metal titanium.
</P>
<P>
   The Duros pump is 44 millimeters long and 4 four  &LR; millimeters in
diameter. Most of its volume will contain the drug. Bodily water
will flow into one end of the pump, swelling a tiny engine and
driving a piston that will push minute amounts of drug out the
other end.
</P>
<P>
   Alza says the pump will dispense 1/100th of a drop of drug per
day, in a continuous, almost infinitesimal flow.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to developing new uses for the pump itself, Alza has
licensed the Duros technology to a privately - &LR; held startup, Durect
Corp. of Cupertino, which will develop ways to use it to deliver
drugs to specific locations in the body.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Tom Abate at abate &LR; sfgate.com
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
