u p BC-REPUBS-ART-2NDTAKE-NY     03-06 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES: like that.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the rally at Santa Clara, and another here at the University
of California Los Angeles, McCain seemed to draw strength from his
enthusiastic student audiences. The senator, who often says he
wants Republicans, Democrats ``libertarians and vegetarians'' to
vote for him, delighted in one sign at Santa Clara proclaiming,
``Carnivores for McCain.'' His aides insisted they were picking up
momentum with the latest barrage on their opponent, and announced
that they had bought $200,000 in new television advertising in
Colorado, which votes on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But the consensus among both Republican and Democratic
professionals here Monday was that McCain had lost energy in the
last week, and now appeared to be trailing Bush not only among
Republican voters, who will select all of the state's delegates,
but among the overall electorate, too. In California's unusual
``blanket'' primary, the names of all candidates will appear on the
same ballot regardless of party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all sort of rushing to a fizzle,'' said Bill Carrick, a
leading Democratic consultant. ``The latest private polling is
certainly showing that unless we get some skewed turnout, or an
unusual number of Democrats decide to cross over, most of the
pollsters in both parties are predicting a 6 to 7 point edge for
Bush overall.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's latest appeals to tolerance seemed clearly aimed at
re-establishing the moderate, inclusive image with which he began
his campaign last year. Touring the Museum of Tolerance on Monday,
he signed ``God Bless This World,'' on the same page of the
Wiesenthal Center's guestbook that his father had signed in 1988,
when the museum was still only a scale-model. And earlier, at a
rally in San Diego, he said his struggle with McCain had been good
for him as a candidate, and had not deeply divided his party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the fracture is much of a fracture,'' Bush, who
will await returns Tuesday in Austin, Texas, said. ``I really
don't. Our party is enthused and excited.'' He added: ``John
deserves credit for bringing people into the party and I deserve a
lot of credit for exciting the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, the Bush spokeswoman, insisted that the governor had
been reluctant to meet with the Log Cabin Republicans because some
of the group's national leaders had helped raise money for McCain.
But Kevin Ivers, a spokesman for the group, said that happened only
after Bush said in an interview in November that he would
``probably not'' meet with the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd been hearing through a number of channels that the
governor had changed his mind concerning a meeting, and now for the
first time he has made his opinion public,'' Rich Tafel, the
group's executive director said in a statement Monday. ``There are
too many divisions in the Republican Party now. A meeting between
the governor and our national board would mark an important step in
healing our party's divisions.''
</P>
<P>
   After his appearance at the Wiesenthal Center, Bush went to
Burbank to appear as a guest on NBC's ``The Tonight Show with Jay
Leno.'' But unlike an appearance last week on CBS's ``Late Show
with David Letterman'', when in the judgment of most wits, the
governor bombed trying to match Letterman joke for joke, Bush made
no effort to go head to head with Leno.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he gave relaxed, straightforward answers about such
things as his family and how he felt the campaign was going.
</P>
</TEXT>
