<HEADER>
A8768 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG_SFC     03-06 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 MONEYBAG/ARTHUR M. LOUIS  &HT;     Figuring Stock Costs Is Taxing Business 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: How can I determine the current cost basis per share of my stock
for tax purposes, taking into account mergers and splits, and sales
of fractional shares resulting from these actions?
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: Let's take a simple example first.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you purchased 100 shares of America Online in 1996. The
stock has since undergone four 2-for-1 splits, so you now have
1,600 shares, assuming that you didn't buy or sell any after the
original purchase. Simply divide the cost per share of the original
shares by 16 and you have the current cost per share.
</P>
<P>
   You can trace any stock's history of splits on the Yahoo
Internet Web site. Go to http://finance.yahoo.com. Enter the ticker
symbol for your stock to the left of the ``Get Quotes'' prompt bar,
then choose ``Charts'' from the list to the right of the bar. Click
on the bar and you will find not only a chart, but also a list of
splits _ if there have been any.
</P>
<P>
   Things become more complicated when you are awarded fractional
shares.
</P>
<P>
   This can happen, for example, if you own an odd number of shares
_ say, 251 _ and your stock is split 3- &LR;  for- &LR;  2. You would be
entitled to receive 125.5 additional shares, but your company will
liquidate the half-share and send you cash instead.
</P>
<P>
   It also will enclose a letter explaining how to account for the
sale of the half-share for tax purposes, and how it will affect the
cost basis of your remaining shares. If you didn't save the letter,
call or write headquarters and direct your query to the
investor-relations department.
</P>
<P>
   A similar situation can arise in a merger.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the company that buys yours might exchange 1.073332
shares of its common stock and $3.27 in cash for each share you
own. I'm picking those numbers out of thin air, but mergers often
seem to involve that sort of decimal-laden exchange. Here, too, you
will have to rely on the company for information about the tax
treatment of the fractional share (and the cash).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I need money for a down payment on a house. I can raise it by
selling stock, but someone suggested that I ought to borrow the
money from my broker on margin, using the stock as collateral. I
don't have any experience with margin accounts, but the idea
appeals to me, because I don't really want to sell the stock, a
solid networking company. And if I did sell it, I would have to pay
a substantial capital-gains tax. Are there any risks I should be
aware of in margin accounts?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: The biggest risk is that the stock price might plummet after you
borrow money against your shares. In that case, you could be hit
with a margin call _ a demand to deposit more cash or securities in
your brokerage account. If you can't meet the demand, your broker
would be authorized to sell part or all of your stock to get back
the money you borrowed.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose, for example, that your stock is worth $100,000, and you
borrow the limit against it _ 50 percent of your equity, or $50,000
_ as a down payment on the house.
</P>
<P>
   Margin rules vary from broker to broker, but at Charles Schwab,
to take a notable example, your margin maintenance rate would be
pegged at 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   What that means is that if the value of the equity in your
account, minus the amount of your margin debt, falls to less than
35 percent of the value of the equity, you will have to add assets
to the account.
</P>
<P>
   So, for example, if the value of your $100,000 worth of stock
drops below $76,920, you will get a not-so-friendly call from your
broker. ($76,920 minus $50,000 equals $26,920, which is just under
35 percent of $76,920.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I'm a contract programmer, working for consulting firms at
client sites. I get straight hourly pay, no benefits, and my income
is reported to me at the end of each year on W-2 forms. I pay my
own premium for individual health coverage from Kaiser. Can I
deduct any part of this on my income tax form?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; A: If you are legally classed as an employee, rather than
self-employed, you can deduct your medical expenses _ including
health insurance _ to the extent that they exceed 7.5 percent of
your adjusted gross income, notes Internal Revenue Service
spokesman Jesse Weller.
</P>
<P>
   If you are self-employed, you can deduct 60 percent of your
health-insurance premiums directly, without regard to the 7.5
percent cutoff.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag &LR; sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
