<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8770 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-HACKER-HACKER_SFCHRON     03-06 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HACKER-HACKER_ </SLUG>
 SF CHRON  
 When Online Brokers Go Off  
 By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
In the wake of last month's much-publicized hacker attack against a
slew of prominent Internet Web sites, customers of online brokerage
firms suddenly are feeling vulnerable.
<P>
   Among the sites temporarily disabled by the so-called
denial-of-service attack was the one maintained by Palo Alto-based
E-Trade Group.
</P>
<P>
   The site, at www.etrade.com, was swamped by phony log-in calls,
making it difficult or impossible for E-Trade's real customers to
gain access during a 90-minute period.
</P>
<P>
   Active traders who wanted to use the site to buy or sell
securities found themselves sitting on their hands, hoping the
market wouldn't move against them.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade spokesman Patrick DiChiro says the company was able to
steer some customers _ who called to complain _ to an alternate Web
address so they could trade online. He insists that the number of
people inconvenienced by the hacker attack was ``very small.''
</P>
<P>
   While E-Trade and its customers were the victims that time, the
same sort of thing could happen any time to any online broker.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it doesn't necessarily take a hacker to shut down a
broker's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade, Charles Schwab and just about every other online broker
have been hit from time to time by server problems or other
technical difficulties that have made their sites inaccessible _
sometimes for several hours.
</P>
<P>
   So, what's a brokerage customer to do?
</P>
<P>
   One preventative measure would be to open more than one online
brokerage account, so if one Web site is down you can (hopefully)
use the other.
</P>
<P>
   It also is a good idea to have at least one account with an
online broker that makes it easy for you to trade securities
offline as well _ by telephone, direct modem hookup or even by
visiting a branch.
</P>
<P>
   John Payne, an analyst with Cerulli Associates, in Boston, says
that multiple accounts are becoming increasingly common among
online investors. There now are 2.4 accounts per online
account-holder _ up from 1.7 a year ago. ``Many people are hedging
their bets,'' he observes.
</P>
<P>
   However, that solution has practical limitations.
</P>
<P>
   If you open a second account, you will have to put funds or
securities in it before you can use it. Some brokers require you to
deposit thousands of dollars in cash or securities up front before
they will activate an account.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential limitation: Even if you have two accounts, it
may be that a stock you want to sell is in the wrong account _ the
one that can't be accessed, because of trouble on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Or, you may want to buy a stock, but don't have enough cash on
deposit with the broker whose Web site is functioning.
</P>
<P>
   To get around this, you might divide your holdings down the
middle, putting half your cash and half your shares of each stock
into each of the two accounts. That way, each account will be
equally useful.
</P>
<P>
   But this can prove awkward _ and expensive.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you decide to dump all your shares in a
particular stock, you will have to place orders with two different
brokers, incurring two separate commissions.
</P>
<P>
   If you decide to buy stock using all your available funds, again
you must place two orders.
</P>
<P>
   And that's assuming both Web sites are functioning.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Stein, executive vice president of Gomez Advisors, a
Massachusetts firm that tracks the performance of online financial
institutions, points out that if you open a brokerage account that
allows you to sell stock short, then you won't have to bother
dividing your share holdings in half.
</P>
<P>
   Selling short is a technique normally practiced by sophisticated
speculators who think a security is about to decline in value.
</P>
<P>
   It involves borrowing stock through a broker, selling it,
collecting the proceeds, then buying the stock back after it has
tumbled. It then is returned to the rightful owner.
</P>
<P>
   But short-selling, Stein says, can be used as a nonspeculative
maneuver in a pinch _ when the shares you want to sell are held in
an account with an online broker whose Web site is inaccessible.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you own 100 shares of XYZ Co., and they all are
deposited with Broker A, whose Web site is down, you can sell 100
shares short through another broker _ Broker B.
</P>
<P>
   You can later instruct Broker A to transfer the shares you own
to your account with Broker B. That will cover the short sale and
complete the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   There should be time enough to pull this off, because trades do
not have to be settled until three working days after they are
placed.
</P>
<P>
   While Internet trading is normally fast and convenient, you
should also have the means to trade offline as well. That means
holding an account with at least one broker that provides telephone
or direct-modem trading _ which circumvents the Internet _ or even
trading in person at branches.
</P>
<P>
   In the cyber age, it may be difficult to imagine people actually
walking into a branch to place orders.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of such prominent online brokers as E-Trade,
Ameritrade, DLJ Direct, Suretrade and Datek Online, it is not only
difficult to imagine, but impossible. None of them has any
branches.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Schwab, Fidelity, Quick &AMP; Reilly and
Waterhouse _ to name a few _ do have branches. Schwab has 345
nationwide _ approximately one for every 700,000 Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, customers placed all their trades over the
telephone by speaking with real, live brokers.
</P>
<P>
   You still can do that with so-called multiple-access online
brokers such as Schwab and Fidelity Investments. Both started as
conventional brokers, and they still are staffed to handle
telephone transactions.
</P>
<P>
   However, Schwab spokesman Greg Gable concedes that his firm's
telephone lines tend to get impenetrably jammed when there is
trouble on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't get through on the phones, Gable says, you can go
to the nearest Schwab branch and place your orders. If you do that,
the company will rebate up to $500 in commissions on the trades you
place there.
</P>
<P>
   Getting through on the telephone to many of the smaller online
brokers is theoretically possible. But don't hold your breath _
particularly during an Internet outage, when just about every
active trader will be calling in.
</P>
<P>
   Stein, of Gomez Advisors, thinks that online brokers that don't
provide their customers with viable telephone access could
eventually fall by the wayside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Multiple access will increasingly be a minimum standard of
service,'' he observes. ``Yes, every broker has a telephone, but
making people hang onto the phone for a long time is not adequate.
A firm that hasn't staffed for substantial telephone trading
doesn't have a true backup.''
</P>
<P>
   Some online brokers let you use the telephone to place trades
automatically, using the touch-tone keypad. Schwab's Telebroker
system and E-Trade's Telemaster are examples.
</P>
<P>
   Both these brokers normally charge more for such trades than for
trades placed over the Internet, but E-Trade will refund the
difference during an Internet crisis. Schwab will not.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade also lets you place trades through your computer via a
direct modem hookup, which bypasses the Internet. E-Trade's
customers have to request proprietary software that makes this
possible, and load it onto their computers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
