A8776 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TAX-SHELTERS-NYT &LR;      03-06 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-SHELTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGISLATORS DENOUNCE TAX SHELTER USED BY INSURERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, Fla., Texas, Del.)  (mk) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON with JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Members of Congress from both parties called Monday
for an inquiry into a tax shelter that makes it possible for
American insurance companies to stop paying income taxes by moving
their headquarters to Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any tax policy that provides incentives for companies to move
offshore and at the same time creates competitive advantage against
American companies needs to be re-examined,'' said Sen. Charles E.
Grassley of Iowa, the second-most senior Republican on the Senate
Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Two Florida Republicans on the House Ways and Means Committee
went further, saying the tax shelter must be shut down, in part
because it will encourage other companies to move offshore or to
ask for similar big tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Rep. Mark Foley, said the Bermuda tax shelter ``is
startling because it allows companies to completely avoid all
income taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   A Democrat on the House Ways and Means Committee who has been
attacking a variety of other tax shelters, Rep. Lloyd Doggett of
Texas, said: ``It's legal, but it shouldn't be. It's a new type of
Bermuda Triangle where revenues disappear, and we need to do
something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislators were reacting to a report in The New York Times
on Monday that a half-dozen American insurers have begun exploiting
a loophole in federal tax law simply by moving their headquarters
to Bermuda or by being acquired by a Bermuda insurer. By doing so,
the companies avoid income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   If all American property and casualty insurers similarly moved
to Bermuda, they could shelter $40 billion a year based on recent
profits, avoiding $7 billion in taxes annually, the Treasury
Department estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of taking advantage of the loophole, four of the biggest
American insurers are trying to demolish the tax shelter. The
insurers are Chubb, Hartford, Kemper and Liberty Mutual. The four
big insurers contend that, while legal, the arrangement threatens
to reduce drastically the government's revenues. They also say it
discriminates against any property and casualty insurer that
continues to maintain its headquarters in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the biggest Bermuda insurers, ACE Group of Cos. and X.L.
Capital Ltd., a unit of Exel Insurance, have recently bought
American insurance companies, which are now in a position not to
pay income taxes. They say they are involved in no improprieties.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement that X.L. Capital said reflected its own
position, ACE said it was abiding by ``longstanding,
well-established international tax rules.''
</P>
<P>
   The Washington legislators said the existence of the loophole
had caught them by surprise. ``This is an unintentional consequence
of the tax code,'' said Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., R-Fla., a member of
the House Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has stirred up a hornets' nest,'' said Foley, who along
with Shaw has sponsored legislation that would make American
companies more competitive with their Bermuda counterparts that pay
no corporate income tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about the effect of this issue on the U.S.
domestic tax base,'' said Sen. William V. Roth Jr., R-Del., the
chairman of the Senate Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Doggett and other Democrats said they hoped to get bipartisan
agreement on legislation to shut down the Bermuda tax shelter.
</P>
<P>
   The Bermuda tax shelter differs from those that Treasury
Secretary Lawrence Summers denounced last week. Summers' attack was
focused on the rapid spread of sham transactions by corporations to
evade taxes, while the Bermuda tax shelter is a legal loophole that
had been unused until last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
