<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8778 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     03-06 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Maybe Jerry Lewis will volunteer to do a
charity telethon. And in these sad cases, shouldn't the United Way
be notified? Hopefully, the Salvation Army is also prepared to
scramble the canteen wagons.
</P>
<P>
   Our state's richest and largest university is now facing
financial disaster in its athletic department. Brace yourself for
those grim minicam shots of starving young jocks in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, however, there's an emergency plan in place. As of yet,
all hope is not lost. University of Texas athletic director DeLoss
Dodds is a master at working the backroom, or as some will say,
working the backstab. Right, Tom Penders? Right, Steve Hatchell?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, thank goodness for DeLoss. Along with football coach
Mack Brown, a scheme was devised that could provide a financial
rescue for UT's $41 million athletic department budget _ the
largest in the Big 12 Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Cancel the long-scheduled football season opener in Hawaii on
Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's a desperate measure for desperate times, but ...
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's environment we cannot afford to do something that
is fiscally irresponsible,'' Dodds said.
</P>
<P>
   It's a heartwarming story. The football team willing to dump the
trip to Hawaii in order to save the entire jock kingdom at the
University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, however, there are doubters. I know. I know. In
today's jaded world, even this tremendous show of compassion can be
publicly trashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do not want to play us, period,'' said June Jones, the
University of Hawaii football coach.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones didn't simply leave his displeasure there. He also
delivered this personal insult:
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived in Texas for four or five years, and I've never
known a Texan to back down from a fight before. I guess their coach
isn't from Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   How catty. DeLoss and Mack are worried sick about where Chris
Simms' next meal comes from, and then they are subjected to this
kind of attack.
</P>
<P>
   OK, under Jones, the Hawaii football program did make a giant
leap last season, finishing 8-4 and winning a bowl game against
Oregon State. And when UT was doing its advance scheduling four
years ago, opening the 2000 season against the Rainbows was
probably considered no more than a pleasure trip for players and
fans. Plus, an easy W.
</P>
<P>
   But what coach Jones can't seem to understand is that a $41
million athletic department budget just doesn't have the same
spending power as four years ago. And since Hawaii was the first of
12 games for 2000, the more games the players are asked to play,
the more they will want to eat. It's a nutritional thing.
</P>
<P>
   If there's no money at Texas to pay for that additional food,
does Jones want to be held responsible for starvation in Austin?
</P>
<P>
   The skeptical will also look at the UT 2000 schedule and see 11
consecutive games without a week off, starting with the Hawaii
trip. The grind of that long plane ride, combined with playing the
next week against Louisiana-Lafayette, could mean Brown simply
doesn't want to start the season with an exhausting trip. Then
there's the fact Hawaii is much more dangerous than originally
thought.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of worrying about starving jocks, or the shrinking
value of $41 million, do you think Brown is simply applying
football sense here?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there's also one other thing. If it's really about budget,
and feeding the young jocks in Austin, why did Texas say it would
come to Hawaii if the game was moved to a Thursday night? Hawaii
nixed that. Apparently the Rainbows sponsor a daylong flea market
at the stadium leading up to the Saturday night kickoff, and
there's nothing worse on the islands than a disrupted flea market.
</P>
<P>
   A neutral observer in all this would be Dennis Franchione, the
TCU football coach. One of those four losses for the Rainbows last
season was to the Frogs. In Hawaii, too. And afterward, there was
some whining by coaches on Jones' staff about dirty play from the
TCUs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say that guy \RJones\S spends too much time worrying about
what other coaches are doing,'' Franchione said. ``That trip is a
terrible drain, particularly when you are playing the next week. I
don't think Mack is worried about how tough the game will be, but,
instead, about how that kind of trip can impact your players.''
</P>
<P>
   If it will make a June Jones feel any better, TCU voices say the
school wants to play both Texas and Texas A&AMP;M. The answers have
been ``no'' and ``no.'' Under Franchione, the Frogs are now more a
nonconference threat, both on the field and in recruiting, than
either wants to chance.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is hard to believe the Hawaii trip could cause
financial wreckage at a place like UT. But with all those hungry
mouths to feed, DeLoss and Mack have their story and they're
sticking to it.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
