<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAIN-CELESTIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAIN FOOD TO BUY CELESTIAL SEASONINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hain Food Group, which has been rapidly acquiring companies in
the natural-food business over the last several years, said Monday
that it had agreed to buy Celestial Seasonings Inc., a well-known
maker of herbal teas like Sleepytime and Lemon Zinger.
</P>
<P>
   The value of the deal was about $390 million, with Celestial
Seasonings shareholders receiving 1.265 shares of Hain stock for
every share of their stock. Wall Street greeted the news with
dismay, driving Hain's share price down $4.75, to $27.625.
</P>
<P>
   The merger came about after four months of negotiations, said
Irwin D. Simon, president and chief executive of Hain, who will
become chairman, chief executive and president of the new company,
to be called Hain Celestial Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celestial has a fantastic name and it enhances our brand
portfolio,'' Simon said, adding that he expected the combined
companies to save at least $10 million in manufacturing and sales.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Siegel, the chairman of Celestial Seasonings, which sold $100
million worth of tea last year, will become vice chairman of the
merged companies.
</P>
<P>
   H.J. Heinz Co. owns 19.5 percent of Hain, which bought the
Earth's Best brand of baby food from Heinz last fall in exchange
for the ownership stake.
</P>
<P>
   Hain has acquired companies that make natural foods like Health
Valley cereals, Terra Chips snacks and Westsoy soy milk, sometimes
for prices that analysts felt were too high. ``My objective is to
get us to be a billion-dollar company by 2002,'' Simon said of his
strategy.
</P>
</TEXT>
