<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-MARINO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINO CONSIDERS VIKINGS' OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dan Marino is considering three alternatives: joining the
Minnesota Vikings as a likely starter, returning to the Dolphins as
a likely backup or retiring.
</P>
<P>
   His agent, Marvin Demoff, said Monday that the Vikings have
assured the 38-year-old Marino that he would be the team's starter
for the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's interest is twofold _ to gain a star and a proven
starter and to give Daunte Culpepper one more season of grooming.
Culpepper was Minnesota's first-round draft pick last season but in
1999 he did not throw a regular-season pass.
</P>
<P>
   When the Dolphins learned that Marino was being courted by the
Vikings to sign a one-year contract, the Miami president Eddie
Jones said Marino would be welcomed back if he decided to play this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny has been told he can come back,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Marino is expected to talk with the Dolphins' owner, H. Wayne
Huizenga, and to the Dolphins' coaches and then make a decision
later this week.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 10 Marino voided the final two years of his Miami
contract, which allowed him to become an unrestricted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Vikings Coach Dennis Green has decided against sticking with
Jeff George, who was 9-3 as the team's starter last season, mainly
because of contract and salary cap reasons. Green is undecided on
the status of Randall Cunningham, who has been both a starter and
backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have talked to Dan Marino since he is an unrestricted free
agent, and we have had good success in getting those type of
players,'' Green said. ``We think Dan Marino still has some gas in
the tank. He's had a lot of teams contact him but we have a very
quarterback-friendly system. It comes down to does Dan want the
opportunity to climb that hill one more time? It's an opportunity
to get one of the top two or three quarterbacks to have ever played
the game. Our mind is made up. It's up to him.''
</P>
<P>
   If Marino says no to the Vikings, Culpepper would start this
season, Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Marino has completed 4,967 passes for 61,361 yards and 420
touchdowns, all National Football League career records.
</P>
<P>
   But last season was his worst as a pro. For the first time as a
Dolphin he threw more interceptions (17) than touchdown passes
(12). He ranked 30th leaguewide in quarterback rating (67.4). He
missed five starts last year because of a pinched nerve, spasms and
weakness in his right, throwing shoulder and because of a bulging
disk in his back. Once he returned, the Dolphins finished 2-5. They
won a playoff game at Seattle but then ended their season in
Jacksonville in humiliating fashion, a 62-7 thumping, in which
Marino looked worn and frazzled.
</P>
<P>
   The lasting memories of that game hinted that Marino's career
was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said that about Randall, but he came here and
produced,'' Green said. ``They said that about Jeff George, and he
came here and proved them wrong. We're doing what we always do;
we're going after players who can contribute and play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings have juggled their coaching staff and lost three
stars to free agency: receiver Jake Reed to New Orleans and
offensive linemen Randall McDaniel and Jeff Christy to Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``This system is part of the National Football League and
whether you are the champion St. Louis Rams or any other team, you
are going to lose players in free agency,'' Green said. ``The key
is what players do you have in the pipeline? We've got young,
developing players that we love. We think they can fill in and make
good on their chance due to the players we have lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we drafted Daunte so high, it was apparent even before he
stepped on the football field for us that he was our quarterback of
the future. We never said that he was the starter for this year,
his second year, but I believe he could be. Dan Marino for us would
be need specific. One year.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
