<HEADLINE>
THE DOLMENS OF ANTEQUERA  
 TOURS WITH A JEWISH FOCUS 
RUINS OF CENTRAL SICILY 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 12)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
By SUZANNE MacNEILLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am planning a trip to Antequera in Spain, and would like
some information on visiting the dolmens there. Tips on
accommodations would also be helpful. _ Sandy Williams, Pittsburgh
</P>
<P>
   A. The ancient dolmens you are referring to are about a
20-minute walk from the center of Antequera, a market town about 30
miles north of Malaga. The dolmens _ or rock tombs _ predate the
Moors, who built a fortress in Antequera before losing it to the
Christians in 1410.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest dolmen, called Menga, was built around 2500 B.C.,
with a gallery covered with earth and stone. Nearby is a somewhat
smaller dolmen, Viera, dating back to 2000 B.C. The site is open
Sunday and Tuesday from 9 a.m. to 3:30 p.m. and Wednesday to
Saturday from 9 a.m. to 6 p.m., and closed Monday. Free admission.
The Romeral dolmen, a mile away on the N-334 highway, dates from
1800 B.C. and is considered the most refined of the group, with a
long gallery and two circular chambers. It is open Wednesday to
Sunday 9 a.m. to 3:30 p.m., closed Monday and Tuesday. Free
admission.
</P>
<P>
   You'll probably want to see some of the other sites of
Antequera, which is famous for its religious buildings. Two
churches have been declared national monuments: the Renaissance
Real Colegiata de Santa Maria La Mayor, built from 1530 to 1550,
and the 17th-century Los Remedios Church, which contains the town's
patron saint, Our Lady of the Remedios. Another important site is
the San Sebastian parish church, on the plaza of the same name,
built from 1540 and 1549, with a handsome brick tower, the tallest
in town, erected from 1701 to 1706.
</P>
<P>
   The Muslim Castle, or Alcazaba, on the eastern edge of town, is
also a national monument, and was largely built in the first half
of the 14th century. The site is open Tuesday to Sunday from 10:30
a.m. to 2 p.m. and 4:30 to 6 p.m.; closed Monday. Free admission.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular lodging in town is the three-star Parador
Nacional de Turismo, on the Paseo Garcia del Olmo, telephone (34)
95-284-0261, fax (34) 284-1312. A double costs $79, at the rate of
171 pesetas to the dollar. The two-star Hotel Castilla opened late
last year at 40 Calle Infante D. Fernando, telephone and fax, (34)
95-284-3090. A double costs $32.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, contact the Tourist Office, at 7 Plaza San
Sebastian, which is open daily. The phone and fax is (34)
95-270-2505. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can you give me the names of companies that offer tours
especially for Jewish travelers? There seem to be plenty that go to
Europe or Israel, but we're interested in traveling to Asia or
South America. _ Sam L. Kleiner, Tampa, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A. Here are two itineraries worth looking into:
</P>
<P>
   Lotus Tours, based in New York, is offering an 18-day kosher
tour to Japan, China and Hong Kong that departs July 2. The trip
includes a four-day cruise down the Yangtze River in China and
visits Kyoto, Kobe, Beijing, Shanghai and Hong Kong. The trip will
be led by Rabbi Marvin Tokayer, who was formerly a rabbi in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Besides visiting well-known sites like the Imperial Palace in
Kobe, and the Forbidden City and the Great Wall in Beijing, the
group will also meet with members of Asian-Jewish organizations
like the Jewish Club of Hong Kong and the Center for Jewish Studies
in Shanghai. In Shanghai, a destination in World War II for Jews
who had no visas, there will also be a tour of the Jewish ghetto
and visits to the former homes of the Kadoories and the Sassoons.
The cost, including round-trip air fare from New York, starts at
$6,390 a person, double occupancy. Information: (212) 267-5415, fax
(212) 608-6007.
</P>
<P>
   Isram World of Travel has several Jewish heritage tours,
including a new 12-day itinerary to Argentina and Brazil.
Departures are on March 22, April 5, May 3, Oct. 25, Nov. 8 and
Dec. 6.
</P>
<P>
   The group will visit Buenos Aires, where it will go to the
Teatro Colon Opera House, Casa Rosada (the president's residence),
the cathedral and tomb of General Jose de San Martin, as well as
attend Sabbath services at the Temple Beth El in the Belgrano
district. In Rio Janeiro, the group will see major sights, like
Sugar Loaf, Copacabana, Ipanema and the Grand Synagogue. Other
stops include Sao Paulo and Iguacu Falls. The cost, based on double
occupancy, is $4,389, including air fare. Information: (800)
223-7460, fax (212) 370-1477. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm going to Palermo, Sicily, this spring and I'm trying to
decide if it would be worthwhile to visit Morgantina and the ruins
near Piazza Armerina. What are the major sites there? _ Rusty
Schraeder, Norfolk, Va.
</P>
<P>
   A. Many visitors to Sicily bypass the town of Piazza Armerina
and the ancient ruins of nearby Morgantina, about 100 miles
southeast of Palermo. But the impressive remains of their rich
Roman heritage certainly make the area worth visiting.
</P>
<P>
   While Piazza Armerina has numerous Arab-Norman buildings and
Baroque palaces and churches, visitors who don't have a lot of time
might want to head directly for the Roman Villa of Casale, about
four miles southwest of Piazza Armerina. The 37,000-square-foot
villa, which dates from the third or fourth century, has beautiful
mosaic pavements covering most of the building's galleries,
peristyles, courtyards and thermal baths. The tilework _ including
the mosaics of the Labors of Hercules in the banquet hall and the
mosaics illustrating the Roman circus in the baths _ are of the
Roman-African school and date from the fourth century.
</P>
<P>
   Morgantina is about nine miles northeast of Piazza Armerina,
near the village of Aidone. The site, which is still undergoing
excavation, has been identified as an early Sikel settlement from
the ninth-century B.C. that was at one point colonized by the
Greeks. The principal excavations have been conducted in the third
century B.C. agora, or marketplace, and in the residential
buildings on the hillsides.
</P>
<P>
   The agora is a vast rectangle built on two levels and joined by
a trapezoidal staircase with a covered market at the center and the
sanctuary of Demeter and Kore as well as a fourth-century theater
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Admission to the Villa Romana del Casale, which is open daily
from 8:30 a.m. to about one hour before sunset, is $4 (at 1,991
lire to the dollar). Information: (39-0935) 680036. Admission to
Morgantina, open daily from 8 a.m. to 5 p.m, is $3. Information:
(39-0935) 87955. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
