<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8797 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-REVIEW-FASHION-ART-NY     03-06 1345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEETING THE ENEMY: OVERSTIMULATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT31 and NYT32 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By CATHY HORYN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The night before his show, Karl Lagerfeld was up in the
kitchen at Chanel working his way through a plate of cheese and
talking, talking, talking, as only he can, about the current state
of fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are scared a little,'' he was saying. ``Always they
think that life was better before, so they go back to the past. But
this is not the problem, because, after all, revivalism has always
been part of fashion. Dior's New Look was a revival of the 1916-War
crinoline. No, it is that everything is moving very quickly. Life
was changed by computers, TV and video. And, in a way, it's very
scary. Life became a special effect.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the thought, more than any other, that kept coming up
as the French fall 2000 collections banged to a close. There was
Nicolas Ghesquiere's highly focused show for Balenciaga, with its
blade-thin shoulders and singular silhouette, all played out in
sleek tapestry trousers, raw-edged blouses and jersey tops piled
ingeniously with mop fringe and fabric curls. Ghesquiere is now one
of the bona fide stars of Paris: his influence is everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   There was Martin Margiela, who, after herding his guests into
railway boxcars laid out with spindly gold chairs and disco balls,
proceeded to show flagrantly oversize clothes _ think men's size
48. Yet, as disturbing as the boxcar scenario was for some guests,
Margiela is onto something with his voluminous clothes. They are
not only highly personal, with adjustable hooks in the waistbands,
but they are also, if one actually puts on one of the coats,
strangely evocative of the solemn glamour of designers like
Cristobal Balenciaga himself.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was John Galliano's show on Thursday night. One
could have easily hated its childish antics _ the models'
paint-splattered faces, the girlish cotton underpants they wore as
they came staggering out under crazy cardboard animal
superstructures, the purposely oversize shoes and dresses, in size
16. And in fact, a lot of people did seem horrified by Galliano's
schoolyard romp, with only a handful bothering to troop backstage
to congratulate him.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, something in this collection struck a rare nerve, a joy
completely absent from his sour Dior show. ``It's about
innocence,'' Galliano said. Up close, in the showroom, the clothes
conveyed all that. So why not play it straight on the runway?
Because Galliano knows, as Karl Lagerfeld had said only an hour
before, that you can't hope to appeal to people's overstimulated
nerve endings unless you show something that looks radically, even
hatefully, different. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Lagerfeld is an expert at bringing things back to
earth while keeping you slightly suspended with exhilaration. To
say that his Chanel show on Friday was about coats is a little like
saying the New Look was about a corset. He added volume to the
clothes, mostly in quilted or pleated skirts, but the brilliance
was all in the controlled mix as the models came stomping out in
tweed coats swinging over loosely belted blouses and skinny
trousers. They wore wigs that playfully evoked Lagerfeld's new
fringed hairdo, and they also had on things like scarves and
strands of pearls the size of Ping-Pong balls. More than 1980's eye
candy, they were reminders that fashion's back in fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Few designers of Ann Demeulemeester's 30's generation have her
capacity to resist the changes around them so serenely. She is like
a tortoise, taking her home, her self-informed ideals, with her
wherever she goes in whatever season. For fall, she, too, makes
women look chic, but with a rawness that is unfailingly connected
to modern life.
</P>
<P>
   Her show last Wednesday night in Montmartre opened with
distressed motorcycle leather wrapped closely around the body and
falling in asymmetrical points. There were wrap skirts in
lightweight wool pinstripes, and denim and burnt-orange suede
jackets whose crusty texture resembled the surface of a cake right
after it's been turned out of a pan. To these rough effects, she
applied her frosting: sweaters of pink and white yarn spun with
silver and long vests of vanilla hand-sheared fur that were shown
bare-armed and tied twice around the waist with plain cloth tape.
Delicious.
</P>
<P>
   Those who saw Jean Paul Gaultier's haute couture show in January
hoped he would transfer some of that je-ne-sais-quoi French
elegance to his ready-to-wear collection. On Wednesday, he did, and
then some. Before the show, in a musty old theater, white-gloved
hostesses scattered cigarette butts on a wet black runway, thus
signaling that this was Gaultier's street version of that
indefinable something.
</P>
<P>
   That something turned out to be fetching jersey tops and
halter-neck tunics worn with womanly skirts or mannish pinstripe
trousers, and shown with black fishnet leggings and those
spiked-heel shoes that never fail to excite the customers at a
Pigalle bust-and-leg revue. For pure ooh-la-la, there were fluid
jersey pants and cute sweaters knitted in grosgrain ribbon. The
show was strong on separates, reflecting Gaultier's ability not
only to manipulate French chic, but to merchandise it, too.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the speed of change and the effect it has on the
overstimulated brain, it might be a good idea if designers who do
subtle clothes started confining their presentations to showrooms.
Peter Speliopoulos' collection of ladylike tweeds for Cerruti was
pretty, but visually, to use a phrase from Henry Allen of The
Washington Post, it was as irrelevant as a daytime moon. Narciso
Rodriguez also would have been better served if his leather shifts
and separates for Loewe, in the cocoa-and-meringue hues of a Paris
pastry shop, weren't put on the runway, where the hungry eye can
brutally dismiss them as ``nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Scott's show, among those closing out French fashion week
on Friday, felt thin on ideas. Scott kept alive his logo theme from
last season, and cotton leotards printed with bow ties and other
ritzy cliches were fun. But, as Scott should know by now, the Paris
stage is too demanding for white Hollywood goddess gowns. The
collection needed more work, and more of himself.
</P>
<P>
   Then, today, the early-morning sound of taxi doors slamming:
suddenly everyone was gone, and Paris seemed marvelously deserted.
At the flea market, there were vintage Chanels waiting. On the Left
Bank, women were bounding into Yves Saint Laurent's men's store to
look at Hedi Slimane's spring clothes; although for men, they have
a cult status among women.
</P>
<P>
   And in the Marais, Azzedine Alaia was working on his latest
collection. Twenty years ago, when some French editors turned up at
other designers' shows in his curvaceous clothes, the photographer
Bill Cunningham, now on the staff of The New York Times, , whom
Alaia credits with discovering him, wrote that they would influence
the look of fashion for the next decade. He was right. Alaia, who
still stays up most of the night sewing, literally imposed his look
on the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Alaia, who hasn't shown his clothes, in any formal way, since
1992, said, without bitterness: ``The editors used to spend two or
three evenings here during the collections. But now they don't have
time.''
</P>
<P>
   His art, his technique, may be more relevant than ever, and not
because the '80s are being revived. As four workers calmly sewed
clothes, including a coat for Naomi Campbell and a suede tango
skirt embroidered with flowers for the couture patron Mouna Ayoub,
Alaia brought out an outfit in progress: a black taffeta ball
skirt, enormous in its silk folds, and a fitted black wool jacket,
on whose back Alaia was now expertly pinning the complete hide,
tail and all, of a baby crocodile.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't say when it would be finished, but few questions are
more beside the point.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
