u p BC-CAMPAIGN-MEDIA-NYT     03-06 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS PLAN SWEEPING COVERAGE OF SUPER TUESDAY PRIMARIES
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the three broadcast networks and their cable cousins and
competitors, Tuesday's coverage of the most sweeping presidential
primary ever will resemble the coverage of a general election, with
ABC, CBS and NBC updating their evening news broadcasts and
breaking into regular programming with the latest news as polls
close in 16 states across four time zones.
</P>
<P>
   But it will again be the cable news channels that offer nonstop
election news starting at 5 p.m. (CNN) and 6 p.m. (Fox News Channel
and MSNBC), as seen through the eyes of their reporting staff as
well as political barons past and present like former House Speaker
Newt Gingrich, who will appear on Fox, and Mike McCurry, the former
spokesman for the Clinton White House, who will appear on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're committed to cover this night all the way through _
we're not going to change,'' said Brit Hume, Fox's Washington
managing editor and senior political correspondent. If the
contest's underdogs, former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey and
Sen. John McCain of Arizona, falter early, ``some of the suspense
will be lost,'' Hume added. But, he said, in most of the five
Tuesday evening primary marathons to date, Fox's audience has not
diminished throughout the evening, even, as in South Carolina, when
the end result was evident before the polls closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the enviable position of journalists who like
politics appealing to people who also like politics,'' Hume said.
``Not only do people want to know who won and who lost, they want
to hear what the candidate said about the other guy, they want to
hear their least favorite guy eat crow.''
</P>
<P>
   During election evenings this year, Hume said, ``the audience
was up or consistent throughout,'' except during the coverage of
the Michigan primary on Feb. 22. On average, Fox's election-night
coverage this year has been watched in 410,000 households, up about
84 percent over the channel's February prime time average of
223,000 households. The cable channel is received in 45 million
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Those figures, provided by Nielsen Media Research, show that
even though MSNBC is received in 54 million homes, 9 million more
than Fox News Channel, its political coverage has drawn smaller
audiences. But MSNBC's Tuesday evening audiences grew steadily,
from 217,000 households the night of the New Hampshire primary, to
378,000 households for last week's Virginia, Washington State and
North Dakota primaries.
</P>
<P>
   CNN, which has a 20-year franchise in election coverage and is
carried in 76 million households, has seen its prime-time audiences
grow noticeably on primary election evenings, up from about 611,000
households on an average February evening to 826,000 the night of
the New Hampshire primary, more than its two cable news rivals
combined.
</P>
<P>
   The combined audience for network news broadcasts is about 23
million households, but the broadcast networks have tended to leave
prime-time election coverage to cable. Tuesday night, spokesmen
said, the networks will break in with updates all evening. ``We're
going to call the races as the polls close if we can,'' said Bob
Murphy, ABC's senior vice president for news.
</P>
<P>
   Key information that is used to call the elections comes from
the Voter News Service, a survey organization administered by a
consortium of six news organizations: ABC, NBC, CBS, CNN, Fox and
The Associated Press. Other news organizations, including The New
York Times, subscribe to the data service.
</P>
<P>
   As the votes were still being cast in New Hampshire and South
Carolina, Slate, the online magazine, posted the overall results of
the news service poll. Sponsoring news organizations, which had
pledged to Congress that the information would remain confidential
until the polls closed, were furious.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Shafer, a Slate columnist, said Monday that after the
service's legal warnings, the magazine's editors had decided to
abandon the exit-poll postings. ``Essentially, we've declared
victory and are leaving the battlefield,'' Shafer said.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy of ABC believes that ``Web sites that steal information''
are ``doing a disservice to the process. And they are in violation
of the VNS contract.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web site of the conservative magazine National Review last
Tuesday picked up where Slate left off and posted exit-polling data
for Virginia in midafternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Richard Lowry, the magazine's editor, said he
received a letter from lawyers for the Voter News Service, saying
that such actions ``constitute an unlawful misappropriation of
VNS's intellectual property.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowry, who had been ``inclined'' to post exit-polling data
Tuesday afternoon, said he would consult his lawyers before doing
so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
