<SLUG> BC-SCI-ATOM-SCIENTISTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTIFIC GROUPS COMPLAIN ABOUT TREATMENT OF WEAPONS SCIENTIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES GLANZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two major American scientific organizations have written to
Attorney General Janet Reno to protest the conditions under which
Wen Ho Lee, the former Los Alamos scientist charged with improperly
handling nuclear secrets, is being held before trial.
</P>
<P>
   One letter, signed by Dr. James S. Langer, the president of the
American Physical Society, the nation's leading organization of
physicists, says in referring to Lee that group members ``are
deeply disturbed by the inhumane treatment that he has received in
his pretrial incarceration.'' It is dated Feb. 28.
</P>
<P>
   A second letter from the committee on scientific freedom and
responsibility of the American Association for the Advancement of
Science, a large and influential group, is dated the next day and
signed by the committee's chairman, Dr. Irving Lerch.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our perspective, Dr. Lee's pretrial treatment appears to
be exceedingly cruel,'' Lerch wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The second letter stated, and a lawyer for Lee confirmed, that
he is held in a cell in a New Mexico jail for 23 hours a day; his
ankles and wrists are shackled when he is moved about the jail,
including during a weekly meeting with his family. The lawyer said
Lee was kept separate from other prisoners during his hourlong
exercise period.
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court last week denied Lee's effort to be
released on bail, citing the danger that he might pass information
about nuclear weapons designs to foreign powers. Lee is accused of
illegally copying secret information about the designs onto
unsecure computers at Los Alamos National Laboratory and onto
portable computer tapes. Some of the tapes have not been accounted
for; Lee's lawyers said he destroyed them. He has not been charged
with espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, federal officials defended Lee's continued
incarceration. ``This is a case that involves missing computer
tapes containing some of the nation's most sensitive nuclear
secrets,'' said Myron Marlin, a Justice Department spokesman, in
response to the letters. ``The conditions imposed upon him are
either those that would be imposed upon any prisoner placed in
administrative segregation or they are those that are intended to
ensure that he does not communicate the location of any of the
missing tapes.''
</P>
<P>
   Plato Cacheris, a Washington lawyer who represented Aldrich
Ames, the CIA agent convicted of spying for Moscow, said that those
conditions sounded more restrictive than the ones under which Ames
was held before trial. For example, Ames was routinely ``in the
company of other prisoners'' until his conviction, said Cacheris,
who has no firsthand knowledge of the Lee case.
</P>
<P>
   Lerch said that some scientists feared that Lee was ``being
intimidated in order to force him into a plea bargain.''
</P>
<P>
   Both groups of scientists emphasized that their letters made no
presumption about Lee's guilt or innocence. But members of the
groups, and of two other scientific organizations that composed
protest letters _ the Committee of Concerned Scientists and a human
rights committee at the New York Academy of Sciences _ said that
Lee's case resembled those of dissident Chinese and Russian
scientists, particularly during the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we would get a letter or somebody would inform us that a
refusenik was blamed for something _ still did not stand trial,
still not convicted _ and was treated like this, we would have
raised hell,'' said Dr. Zafra Lerman, a chemist and a member of the
American Association for the Advancement of Science committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 2211EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0503 </DOCNO>
