<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-McCAIN-AD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 GOVERNOR RELEASES LETTER FROM CRITIC OF McCAIN  
(lb) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a Long Island advocate for breast-cancer
research was quoted as saying she was sorry she made a commercial
criticizing Sen. John McCain's votes on research programs, Gov.
George Pataki's office released a letter Monday night from the
woman defending her involvement in electoral politics.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Newsday reported that the advocate, Geri Barish of
Nassau County, had said of the commercial, for Gov. George W. Bush,
``With all the controversy, I am sorry I did the radio spot and
it's come out the way it did.''
</P>
<P>
   Barish did not answer calls seeking comment. But on Monday
night, the office of Pataki, who is leading the Bush campaign in
New York, released a letter in which Barish says, ``Breast-cancer
activism and politics are joined at the hip.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``Advocating for breast cancer on Long Island is like
being in the hottest kitchen on earth. You have to able to take the
heat _ and I can.''
</P>
<P>
   In the commercial, which the Bush campaign paid for, Barish
criticized McCain for voting against financing for some
breast-cancer programs.
</P>
<P>
   After the commercial began running, some other advocates for
breast-cancer research criticized Barish, saying it was
inappropriate to make the topic an issue in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   McCain says he opposed the programs because they were part of a
spending bill that underwent little scrutiny.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
