<HEADER>
A8801 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BOURQUE-TIMELINE-     03-06 1442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BOURQUE-TIMELINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOURQUE THROUGH THE YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   1979-80 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Boston's first pick (eighth overall) in June amateur draft . . . In
his first game, a 4-0 win Oct. 11 vs. Winnipeg, the 18-year-old had
an assist 40 seconds into his first shift and later scored his
first goal . . . Set a record (since broken) for points by a rookie
defenseman with 65 . . . Became first non-goaltender in NHL history
to win Calder Trophy as Rookie of the Year and be a first-team
All-Star in same season. &QL; 
 &QL; 
1980-81 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Had played in 94 consecutive games, dating back to previous season,
before a broken jaw sidelined him for 13 games . . . Came back to
score 20 of his 27 goals in the second half of the season . . .
Named second-team All-Star . . . Had 12 points in 13 playoff games
. . . Played for Team Canada in 1981 Canada Cup . . . In July '81,
signed a four-year, $1 million deal. &QL; 
 &QL; 
1981-82 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Again earned first-team All-Star honors . . . Of his 66 points, 13
came in the final eight games . . . His goal with 55 seconds left
gave Bruins a 4-3 win over Quebec in second-round playoff opener .
. . Broke his wrist in Game 5 of that series and did not return, as
team lost in seven games. . . Runner-up for Norris Trophy as
league's best defenseman (won by Doug Wilson). &QL; 
 &QL; 
1982-83 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Scored his only career hat trick March 8 in an 11-5 win at Quebec,
the first Bruins defenseman to get three goals in a game since
Bobby Orr in 1975 . . . Finished with a plus-49, fourth best in the
league . . . Had his best scoring season thus far (73 points)
despite missing 15 games with a broken sinus bone . . After he
returned from injury early in season, team went 31-4-5 over the
next 40 games . . . Named second-team All-Star . . . Had 23 points
in 17 playoff games before Bruins bowed to Islanders in conference
finals. &QL; 
 &QL; 
1983-84 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Statistically his best season, with career highs in points (96),
goals (31), and plus-minus (plus-51) . . . Named first-team
All-Star for the third time . . . Played for champion Team Canada
in '84 Canada Cup. &QL; 
 &QL; 
1984-85 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Took 333 shots, second most in the league, with at least one in all
but two of his 73 games . . . Led Bruins in scoring with 86 points
and finished a plus-30 . . . Was at his best down the stretch,
scoring seven goals and 21 points in the final 13 games before
Bruins got bumped in first round by Montreal . . . Named a first
team All-Star and was runner-up for Norris Trophy (won by Paul
Coffey). &QL; 
 &QL; 
1985-86 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Named 15th captain of the Bruins (sharing the honor with Rick
Middleton the first three seasons) . . . Scored 11 of his 19 goals
on the power play . . . Missed four games with a sprained ankle and
two with bruised ribs . . . Named a second-team All-Star. &QL; 
 &QL; 
1986-87 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Took his place among the NHL's greatest defensemen with a 95-point,
plus-44 season that earned him his first Norris Trophy . . . Also
was runner-up to Wayne Gretzky for the Hart Trophy as MVP and
earned first-team All-Star honors . . . On Dec. 4, he beat Quebec
with his second goal of the night with one second left . . . Lead
team in scoring, was 10th in the league. &QL; 
 &QL; 
1987-88 &QL; 
 &QL; 
On Dec. 3, switched to No. 77 after handing over his No. 7 jersey
to Phil Esposito in an emotional ceremony . . . Led team in scoring
for the third time with 81 points . . . In playoff run to Stanley
Cup finals against Edmonton, had 21 points in 23 games . . . Won
his second straight Norris Trophy and was again a first-team
All-Star. &QL; 
 &QL; 
1988-89 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Missed 20 games with knee injury, the most time he ever missed in
one season . . . Still earned second-team All-Star honors with 61
points in 60 games . . . Became seventh defenseman in NHL history
to get 200 goals when he scored against Chicago Nov. 26. &QL; 
 &QL; 
1989-90 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Had career-best 6 points (one goal, five assists) in a 7-2 win at
Vancouver Feb. 18 . . . Won his third Norris Trophy and was
runner-up for Hart Trophy (won by Mark Messier) . . . Again named a
first-team All-Star . . . At All-Star skills competition, won
shooting accuracy competition, a title he would come to own with
seven victories (including three shared) over 10 seasons . . .
After injuring his hip in Game 2 of opening-round playoff series
with Hartford, dramatically charged onto the ice for Game 7 to lead
the Bruins to a 3-1 victory; they reached the Cup finals, where
they lost to Edmonton . . . Finished third in playoff scoring with
17 points in 17 games. &QL; 
 &QL; 
1990-91 &QL; 
 &QL; 
After signing a four-year, $5 million deal just before training
camp, he went out and led the Bruins in scoring for the fourth time
with 94 points . . . With an assist vs. Hartford Jan. 24, passed
Orr's 888 points to become the team's leading scorer among
defensemen . . . Had 25 points in 19 playoff games, sixth best in
the league, including an assist April 21 against Montreal in the
Adams Division finals that made him the Bruins' all-time leading
playoff scorer . . . Won fourth Norris Trophy and was named
first-team All-Star for the eighth time. &QL; 
 &QL; 
1991-92 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Became third defenseman in NHL history to reach 1,000 points with
an assist Feb. 29 in a 5-5 tie vs. Washington . . . Moved past Orr
as leading goal scorer among Bruins defensemen with his 265th on
Jan. 22 in Toronto . . . Led team in scoring with 81 points . . .
Named first-team All-Star and was runner-up for Norris Trophy (won
by Brian Leetch) . . . Won King Clancy Trophy for leadership on the
ice and humanitarian contributions off the ice. &QL; 
 &QL; 
1992-93 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Became Bruins' all-time assist leader when he notched his 795th
March 20 vs. Detroit, surpassing John Bucyk . . . Finished a
plus-38 in a season in which he earned another first-team All-Star
selection and again was runner-up for the Norris Trophy (won by
Chris Chelios). &QL; 
 &QL; 
1993-94 &QL; 
 &QL; 
One month into the season, signed a five-year, $12.5 million deal .
. . Matched career high with five assists in an 8-2 win against
Washington Jan. 2 . . . Before missing final 11 games with a knee
injury, had been on the ice for more than 70 percent of Boston's
goals . . . Won his last Norris Trophy, becoming just the third
player to win five (Orr eight, Doug Harvey seven) . . . 11th
first-team All-Star selection gave him the most of any defenseman
in NHL history. &QL; 
 &QL; 
1994-95 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Led league in shots and was second in power-play points . . .
Second among defensemen in scoring with 43 points in
lockout-shortened season . . . Named second-team All-Star for the
fifth time. &QL; 
 &QL; 
1995-96 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Named All-Star Game MVP after scoring winning goal with 37 seconds
left at FleetCenter Jan. 20 . . . Named first-team All-Star for
12th time, equaling Gordie Howe's mark . . . Hit 20-goal mark for
the ninth time and was runner-up for Norris Trophy (won by
Chelios). &QL; 
 &QL; 
1996-97 &QL; 
 &QL; 
His game-winning goal Feb. 1 against Tampa Bay made him the Bruins'
all-time leading scorer with 1,340 points, surpassing Bucyk . . .
His 1,000th assist March 27 vs. the Islanders made him just the
fifth player in history to reach that mark . . . Missed 20 games
with an assortment of injuries (shoulder, ankle, oblique muscle) .
. . For the first time, he is not named a first- or second-team
All-Star, breaking a record string of 17 years. &QL; 
 &QL; 
1997-98 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Earned first game misconduct of his career Jan. 29 vs. Pittsburgh
when he cross-checked Jaromir Jagr from behind . . . For the fourth
time in his career, played every regular-season game . . . Finished
with 48 points, lowest output of his career in a full season . . .
Played on Canadian Olympic team at Nagano that lost in semifinals
to eventual champion Czech Republic. &QL; 
 &QL; 
1998-99 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Signed two-year, $10 million contract extension Sept. 9 . . . Moved
up to third on the all-time list, passing Howe, with his 1,050th
career assist, part of a three-assist night vs. Detroit Dec. 19 . .
. Became Bruins' all-time leader in games played with his 1,437th
March 13 in Buffalo . . . Made NHL-record 12th straight start in
the All-Star Game, representing the North American squad . . .
Played a remarkable 53 minutes 26 seconds in double-OT playoff
victory over Carolina April 30 . . . Named postseason second-team
All-Star, giving him 18 first- or second-team selections, second
only to Howe . . . Finalist for Norris Trophy (won by Al
MacInnis). &QL; 
 &QL; 
1999-2000 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Moved ahead of Coffey, still playing for Carolina, to rank No. 1
all-time for goals by a defensemen with 395 and counting . . .
Scored his last goal as a Bruin Feb. 25 at Washington, firing a
shot from inside his own blue line into an empty net, securing a
3-0 victory . . . Last home goal came Dec. 4 in the first period of
a 9-3 loss to Chicago.
</P>
</TEXT>
