<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-LEWIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WBA ARGUES TO A DRAW OVER LEWIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The World Boxing Association convened after a six-hour hearing
in Philadelphia Monday without determining whether to strip Lennox
Lewis of its share of the undisputed heavyweight championship of
the world for refusing to fight John Ruiz, the WBA's newly declared
No. 1 contender.
</P>
<P>
   A decision is expected within a few days, said James Binns, the
WBA's legal counsel, who presided over the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing brought together lawyers for Lewis, Evander
Holyfield and Ruiz as well as Don King, the promoter for Holyfield,
to argue the issue. Ruiz was the only boxer present.
</P>
<P>
   The WBA's president, Gilbert Mendoza, was not present at the
hearing, but listened by telephone from time to time from
Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a foregone conclusion, but I'm not very
optimistic,'' Lewis' lawyer in the United States, Milton Chwasky,
said on the prospect of the WBA continuing to recognize the British
heavyweight as champion.
</P>
<P>
   If Lewis (35-1-1) is stripped of the WBA title, that means he
will hold only the World Boxing Council and the International
Boxing Federation versions of the title when he meets Michael Grant
(31-0) on April 29 at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   If the WBA strips him of the title, the organization could make
a bout on June 3 between Ruiz (36-3) and Holyfield (36-4-1), the
WBA's No. 2 contender, a match for the vacant championship.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has been the undisputed heavyweight champion for almost
four months. He defeated Holyfield in Las Vegas on Nov. 13 for the
IBF and WBA titles, adding them to his WBC championship. That fight
was the rematch of a bout March 13, 1999, between the two fighters
that ended in a controversial draw, although it appeared Lewis had
beaten Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   After that match, all three organizations called for an
immediate rematch and all three sanctioned it.
</P>
<P>
   But the WBA stipulated that Lewis' first title defense was to be
against its No. 1 contender, who at the time was Henry Akinwande, a
Nigerian heavyweight who fights out of Pensacola, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   King said that Lewis agreed to the WBA stipulation before he
fought Holyfield in the rematch.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis wants his match against Grant to be sanctioned by the WBA.
Ruiz, who has been the WBA's No. 1 heavyweight contender for two
weeks, wants Lewis stripped of the title. And King wants Ruiz and
Holyfield to fight for the vacant WBA title in Las Vegas on June 3.
</P>
<P>
   Akinwande was to have fought Holyfield for the title in June
1998. But that fight was canceled when Akinwande tested positive
for hepatitis B. The effects of that disease lingered, but
Akinwande remained the WBA's No. 1 contender until a few weeks ago
when it was discovered that he had developed a liver ailment and
was taking drugs to combat it. That forced the WBA to find another
No. 1 contender and Ruiz was elevated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems odd that there was a rush for a mandatory for a guy
who has been the No. 1 contender for just 13 days,'' Patrick
English, the lawyer for Main Events, Lewis' promoters in the United
States, said regarding Ruiz.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' first defense of his undisputed championship was supposed
to be against Akinwande, the WBA mandatory challenger, but when
Akinwande was not available Lewis moved on to Grant.
</P>
<P>
   ``In November we approached the WBA to resolve this matter,''
English said. ``In December we wrote them a letter with a proposal
for a box-off to get this matter resolved. We got nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   English said that after going to court in Philadelphia and
determining that Akinwande was not healthy enough to challenge for
the title, the WBA offered no solution to the matter. So, Main
Events and Lewis made a fight with Grant, who is No. 2 in the IBF
and the WBC rankings and No. 5 in the WBA.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
