<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRUINS-REBUILD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS' REBUILDING TO BEGIN ANEW _ WITHOUT BOURQUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins today face much the same thing they faced in
the spring of 1997 when that dreadful campaign came to a close.
</P>
<P>
   They will miss the playoffs again.
</P>
<P>
   They will have to rebuild again, as they did three years ago
when they tabbed the No. 1 and No. 8 picks overall (Joe Thornton
and Sergei Samsonov) as stars of the future.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a decidedly different atmosphere surrounding the
team this time, because now they face a future without Ray Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   Many around the club also expect coach Pat Burns, who was
brought in to lead the youngsters to the promised land, to be fired
at the conclusion of the year despite the players' strenuous
objections.
</P>
<P>
   The '97 team was not expected to do anything, but this season
has been an abject disaster for the Bruins, who were picked by
Sports Illustrated to win the Eastern Conference championship.
</P>
<P>
   The march to the basement started in the summer when the Bruins
let center Tim Taylor walk away without even making him an offer.
It continued when they walked away from Dmitri Khristich's
arbitration award and got only a second-round pick for him. It
continued with the holdouts of several players, the most pivotal of
which was goalie Byron Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries to Jason Allison continued the derailment of the
offense. Add to that the bizarre criticism of Burns by owner Jeremy
Jacobs, followed by the subtraction of Joe Murphy, who was kicked
off the team for insubordination and wound up in Washington. The
Bruins added defenseman Marty McSorley, who was suspended by the
league for the season after hitting Vancouver forward Donald
Brashear in the head with his stick last month. Whatever morale was
left in the already-stressful environment evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   It became clear after that Feb. 21 contest that the Bruins would
be lucky to win another game all year. Forget the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The awful deterioration, which led to Bourque asking out after
21 years in Boston, has come as a huge shock to those who believed
this club was building something positive at the start of the
1997-98 season. Right wing Rob DiMaio, for one, signed up for a
long-term deal after assurances by management that the talent would
be kept together. Instead, over time, it's been torn asunder.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the young guys three years ago and we were going to
build from there, and each year seemed to develop a little more,
now it's like `OK, let's start all over again,' '' said a
distraught DiMaio. ``When's it going to really get to a point where
it's `Let's take a run at this'?
</P>
<P>
   ``For Ray, that's what is unfortunate. He wanted that so bad
here and it didn't happen. I don't know if loyalty is gone in this
game now. Sometimes you learn the hard way by thinking and pretty
much being told one thing and that not happening. I was very
disappointed at the start of the year when certain guys weren't
coming back. I couldn't understand it. I just couldn't understand
it. So, I guess it's more of a business than you want to realize
and that's what sucks about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Count DiMaio as one in a huge group who wish Bourque nothing but
happiness and a Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said if this team was competitive and he felt we had a shot
at winning, there is no way he'd go anywhere else,'' said DiMaio.
``He'd love to finish here but the situation is what it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think it will be a tarnished Stanley Cup if he were to
win it. There's no guarantee he'd win it, but I don't think it
would be because if you've never got to the end point, you don't
know how exciting that can be. To have a shot at it, that's all he
wants, and all the power to him because he deserves it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 2219EST &QL; 
