<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8805 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-RYAN-ON-BOURQUE-B     03-06 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RYAN-ON-BOURQUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SAINT IS TRADED, AN OWNERSHIP IS BLEMISHED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Somewhere out there is a female correspondent who
always maintained in her letters that Ray Bourque was a living
saint.
</P>
<P>
   She really meant it. She honestly believed that Raymond Bourque
was more than just an exemplary hockey player. She believed he was
so personally virtuous that he was nothing less than a saint.
</P>
<P>
   Well, if part of being a saint is the capacity to avoid saying
you-know-what if stuffed with a mouthful, then perhaps Ray Bourque
really is a living saint. He has been the good soldier's good
soldier, the teammate's teammate, the company man's company man. He
has borne witness to 20 years of ups, downs, and all sorts of
in-betweens during his distinguished Bruins career, and at no time
has he publicly aired so much as a doily of the organization's
soiled laundry. Whatever Ray thought or believed, if it was
negative, or if it would have reflected poorly on the party of the
second part, it stayed inside his head and heart.
</P>
<P>
   It long ago reached the point where we really did begin to
wonder whether, if pricked, he perhaps wouldn't bleed, at least in
that Shakespearean sense. It seemed that Ray Bourque would simply
accept what the Fates had dealt him, that his record total of 1,518
regular-season games played without winning a Stanley Cup would
casually escalate, game by game and year by year, until he played
his final contest with the Boston Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   But Bourque has had enough. He has decided that there must be
something better out there for him. He wants a shot at the Cup he
was never going to win in Boston. It has been 10 years since he had
a viable opportunity to win it all in Boston. He certainly doesn't
owe anyone in the Bruins organization anything. He has remained
perennially optimistic, and he had always fulfilled his end of the
bargain. The decision to leave rightfully belonged to Ray Bourque,
and Ray Bourque alone.
</P>
<P>
   If Bourque winds up playing on the 2000 Stanley Cup champions,
how satisfying will that really be? He more than likely will have
been a contributor, but he will still be an appendage to a core
group, and it will not be the same as if he had done it with a team
he had bonded with from the first day of training camp in a sport
where mutual body sacrifice is the norm. Other than, say, basking
in the glow of having just scored the winning goal in Game 7 of the
finals, just how satisfying will it be for Ray Bourque to be
skating around whatever arena, hoisting the Cup in some funny
uniform?
</P>
<P>
   That assumes he finds himself on the winning team. There are no
guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   We, of course, cannot crawl inside Bourque's head. We don't know
how much seeing his name engraved on that Cup will mean to him. We
don't know how much it hurt to be on the losing side in 1988 and
1990, nor do we know what goes through his mind each spring when he
turns on his TV and sees the annual revelry. He may be looking
enviously at former teammates, or perhaps even contemptuously _ can
a saint be contemptuous and keep his standing? _ at foes for whom
he has no respect, perhaps some cheap-shot guys who have loosened a
tooth or two in the Bourque mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Nor can we underestimate the sheer gravitational pull of the
Stanley Cup to a Canadian-bred hockey maven like Raymond Bourque.
There are professional athletic championships and there is the
Stanley Cup, a vessel that has a cachet not present in the other
major sports. No American has the proper appreciation of the
Stanley Cup mystique. Bourque may have decided that, however
limited his contribution, however tangential his involvement, it is
worth it to him just to be a part of the most hallowed ritual North
American sport has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   All this is Bourque's prerogative. But he should understand that
our growing mania with championships as the validation of the
individual player is nonsense. The inherent nature of his chosen
sport dictates that victory will be very much the result of
collaborative activity, and that if any one man will wield
disproportionate influence, it will be the goaltender, not a
defenseman, and not even one as skilled and dedicated as Bourque.
Wayne Gretzky did not win in a vacuum; neither, for that matter,
did Bobby Orr.
</P>
<P>
   So let it be known that no one with any remote degree of
sensitivity to the matter will think anything less of Bourque if he
does not win a championship. When you are the single most
personally admirable star to have performed in your town for more
than 20 years, which Ray Bourque happens to be, the presence or
absence of a championship ring on your finger is an utter
irrelevancy.
</P>
<P>
   Playing an entire career with one team is an increasingly rare
superstar phenomenon, and it can be argued that for someone in
Bourque's position it has as much to recommend it as does winning a
championship ring. But Bourque has chosen a different path, and
that truly speaks ill of the Bruins as an organization.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone who knows him wishes Ray Bourque the most conceivable
happiness. And everyone who cares about the Bruins should now
understand how morally bankrupt its ownership really is when an
athletic saint is so demoralized that he chooses to leave.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
