<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, MARCH 7
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-INDEPENDENT-ADS-NYT (moved on Friday, March 3)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, March 3,
about Sam Wyly, the Texas businessman who paid for advertising
critical of Senator John McCain, referred imprecisely to a
provision of campaign finance law dealing with independent ads that
appeal directly for or against a candidate. While political parties
using unregulated ``soft money'' donations and corporations and
unions cannot make such direct appeals, individuals operating
independently of a campaign are permitted to do so.
</P>
<P>
   BC-REPUBS-NEW-ENGLAND-NYT (moved on Friday, March 3)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, March 3,
about the primary campaigns in New England referred incorrectly in
some copies to the Maine voting rules. Party members may vote only
in their own primaries, not in another party's. Nonaffiliated
voters may enroll in a party at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   BC-POLICE-CRIME-RATES-NYT (moved on Friday, March 3)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, March 3,
about several cities that have reduced crime without the aggressive
police tactics used in New York misstated the origin of the New
York Police Department's Street Crime Unit. It was created in the
1970's by Police Commissioner Patrick Murphy and greatly enlarged
in the late 1990's under Howard Safir, Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani's
second police commissioner. It was not created during the tenure of
Mayor Giuliani's first commissioner, William J. Bratton.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ESSENCE-MAG-MEDIA-NYT (moved on Sunday, March 5)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, March 5,
about Essence magazine misstated the new title of Susan L. Taylor,
its former editor in chief, at the magazine's parent, Essence
Communications. She is publications director, not editorial
director. The article also misstated the name of the
bed-and-breakfast in Brooklyn owned by Monique Greenwood, Taylor's
successor. It is Akwaaba Mansion, not Akwaaba House.
</P>
<P>
   The article also misstated the frequency of B. Smith Style, a
competiting magazine published by American Express Publishing. It
appears every two months, not monthly.
</P>
</TEXT>
