<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8807 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-MARTIN-NYT &LR;      03-06 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MARTIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT RULES IN MARTIN'S FAVOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Casey Martin won another court decision Monday, and he will
continue to ride his cart on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld a federal
magistrate's 1998 ruling that allows Martin to use a cart in Tour
competition. This could be the last legal obstacle for Martin. The
PGA Tour could choose, however, to continue the legal battle,
either by appealing to the U.S. Supreme Court within 90 days or by
asking the 9th Circuit, which sits in San Francisco, to rehear the
case with a full panel of 11 judges rather than the 3 who issued
Monday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Martin has Klippel-Trenaunay-Weber Syndrome, a rare circulatory
disorder that causes severe pain and swelling in his right leg.
Martin won his original case against the Tour on Feb. 11, 1998,
when U.S. Magistrate Thomas Coffin granted Martin an injunction
that required the Tour to furnish him with a cart.
</P>
<P>
   In Coffin's view, Martin established that he was legally
disabled, and that his use of a cart in competition was a
reasonable accommodation under the Americans with Disabilities Act.
Coffin accepted the Tour's argument that walking is a substantive
part of Tour golf, but he rejected the notion that riding in a cart
would give Martin an advantage over his peers.
</P>
<P>
   That opinion was upheld Monday by the 9th Circuit in a 3-0
ruling. The appeals court ruled that golf tournaments were covered
by the Americans with Disabilities Act and that Martin's cart was a
reasonable accommodation that would not change the ``fundamental
nature'' of a tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``The central competition in shot-making would be unaffected by
Martin's accommodation,'' Judge William Canby wrote. He said there
was ample evidence to support Coffin's finding that fatigue _ the
element in which Martin would presumably have an advantage by
having a cart _ was not a significant factor in golf, compared to
factors like stress and motivation.
</P>
<P>
   Martin was en route to Florida for this week's Honda Classic and
was unavailable for comment, but his representatives expressed
their delight with the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thrilled,'' said Mark Freeland, one of Martin's agents
with Imani Sports in Minneapolis. ``It just reaffirms the original
decision. We felt that Thomas Coffin made a sound decision, and the
fact that it was 3-0 reaffirms that feeling. All this does is
permit Casey to engage in professional golf with his disability.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Tour released a statement Monday saying it has not
decided its next course of action, but that the Tour would announce
its plans sometime after the next policy board meeting March 15.
Even if the Tour asks for a Supreme Court review, there is no
guarantee it would agree to hear the case.
</P>
<P>
   The Tour must also decide if the case is worth pursuing from
both a legal and public-relations perspective. Many sympathize with
Martin, who made it onto the PGA Tour by finishing in the top 15 on
last year's Nike Tour money list.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tour is currently reviewing the 9th Circuit's opinion,''
the Tour said in statement released Monday. ``Additionally, we will
also review the opinion with the PGA Tour policy board at the
regularly scheduled policy board meeting on March 15. We will have
further comment, if appropriate, following next week's policy board
meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, a 27-year-old native of Eugene, Ore., has played in five
PGA tournaments this year, making the cut in three. He is coming
off his best finish _ last month's Touchstone Energy Tucson Open,
where he tied for 17th place. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
