<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BOURQUE-PARK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOURQUE TRADE BRINGS BACK MEMORIES FOR BRAD PARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was his first game at the FleetCenter this year.
Brad Park came to see for himself a Bruins franchise on which, in
Park's words, Mother Nature has dumped buckets and buckets of rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You keep thinking the rain has stopped, and it's just cloudy
out,'' said Park, ``but then Mother Nature dumps some more rain.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ray Bourque Watch was on for yet another day, yet another
game. Park, of course, is another superlative defenseman who never
had the joy of playing on a Stanley Cup-winning team in his 16
years with New York, Boston, and Detroit. And Park shrugged when
talking about Bourque's rationale, that Bourque wants a chance to
win a Cup, a chance obviously not to be had in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me when people bring that up,'' said Park. ``I know
a whole lot of guys who won the Stanley Cup who couldn't carry my
skates.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning the Cup is a joy, Park went on, but a player knowing he
gave his all on every shift in his career is perhaps just as much
so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the reasons why everything is happening,'' said
Park. ``It's a shame Ray has to leave the team to accomplish his
goal of trying to win everything. But Ray and guys like Steve
Yzerman are two of the few guys who've spent their entire career in
once city. It's a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   Park was as much the identity of the Rangers as Bourque was of
the Bruins _ even if Park had played with the Rangers for only
seven seasons _ at the time of his trade to Boston. The last thing,
the very last think Park envisioned was that his Rangers would
trade him.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, nearly 25 years later, each detail of the sudden,
unexpected and truly shocking trade is fresh in Park's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still can't forget mine,'' said Park. ``It really bothered
me.''
</P>
<P>
   For all concerned _ fans, players, coaches, and general managers
_ what happened on Nov. 7, 1975, when the Bruins sent Phil Esposito
and Carol Vadnais to the Rangers for Park, Jean Ratelle, and Joe
Zanussi was the jolt of all jolts.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long did it take me to get over the Rangers' trading me?''
Park said. ``Put it this way: I think it was for three years after
that trade that the Rangers didn't beat us. Jean and I wouldn't let
it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque's departure to the Avalanche was less of a surprise
Monday night after the week of speculation. The same cannot be said
of the trade that Bruins general manager Harry Sinden and his New
York counterpart, Emile Francis, pulled off just months after the
Bruins lost a crushing Stanley Cup final series to the Philadelphia
Flyers. None of the players had a clue; neither did fans or media.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was captain of the Rangers and I loved the city and I loved
the fans,'' said Park. ``I was very happy there. It was a wonderful
life I had in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Esposito's reaction when the word of the trade reached the team
in Vancouver is part of Bruins lore. Bobby Orr and coach Don Cherry
went up to Esposito's hotel room to tell him that he was traded and
Esposito, standing by a window, said, ``Just don't tell me it's to
the Rangers or I'll jump out this window.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Cashman trashed his hotel room in anger, and many of the
Bruins players cried. But the reaction of Park and Ratelle, the New
Yorkers, was emotional, too. The classy Ratelle, who was
comfortable in New York and worked on Wall Street during the
offseason, was so upset that he didn't report to Boston for three
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very, very hard,'' recalled Park. He and his wife Gerri
``had established ourselves in New York,'' and Boston, as is in
every sport, was a bitter rival to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil was very emotional when he got to New York, saying he
didn't like the city or the fans,'' Park recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Park, if not as vocal, was just as upset, but soon enough, he
got to like Boston and became an indispensable cog in good Bruins
teams the next eight seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't realize I played longer in Boston than New
York,'' said Park. ``Eight years to seven.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1983, Park left for Detroit as a free agent, it is here that
Park offered advice to Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it would be better if we kept the family in Boston
when I went out to Detroit,'' recalled Park. ``But after only a few
months . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Ray is going to find out the same, that it might be OK
for a few months but it would be very hard after that. After only a
few months, we had built ourselves a home in Detroit.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque, said Park, most likely will learn the same lesson ``if
he stays in another city next season,'' said Park. ``It'll be hard
for Ray being away from his family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
