<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DERBY JINX CLAIMS GREENWOOD LAKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALLANDALE, Fla. _ The Florida Derby and the Kentucky Derby lost
one of their stars Monday when Greenwood Lake limped home from a
morning workout at Hialeah and was immediately booked for a flight
to Kentucky for surgery on a hairline fracture of his left front
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-year-old colt seemed likely to make a full recovery, but
no one could say when that might be, nor could anyone predict
whether he would come back with the same performance level that won
the Champagne and the Remsen last fall and that made him the early
choice to win the Kentucky Derby on May 6 at Churchill Downs in
Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   ``The early prognosis is for a full recovery,'' said Nick Zito,
who trains the colt. ``But we'll cross that bridge when we come to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   He meant that the unexpected accident would remove his best
horse from the only Kentucky Derby he could ever enter, and that
the injury might prevent Greenwood Lake from ever returning with
the same brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   Zito noticed that Greenwood Lake was laboring when he came back
from a five-furlong breeze, which he ran in 1:00 3/5 at Hialeah,
where he is stabled and where many horsemen keep their racing stars
because of its superior surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came back off,'' the trainer reported. ``He is definitely
out of the Florida Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury was the most dramatic to strike this year's
contenders, many of whom were gathered here at Gulfstream Park for
Saturday's Florida Derby, the defining race in Florida on the road
to Kentucky. It also continued a relentless streak of misadventures
to befall Derby candidates in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Derby ``jinx'' struck Wondertross, the favorite
in the Blue Grass Stakes at Keeneland, who suffered an intestinal
blockage the day after he finished sixth in the Blue Grass. The
year before, Lil's Lad, the early favorite for the Kentucky Derby,
was eliminated with a chipped left front ankle. It was detected
three weeks before the Kentucky Derby. Also, Coronado's Quest was
withdrawn from the Derby because of behavioral problems, and Grand
Slam, winner of the Champagne Stakes, was removed with deep cuts on
his flank sustained during the Breeders' Cup Juvenile.
</P>
<P>
   Six years earlier, in one of the more dramatic accidents to
befall a star horse, A.P. Indy was withdrawn on the morning of the
Kentucky Derby when he was found to have a fractured bone. And,
hanging over Derby contenders every year was the fact that no
2-year-old champion since Spectacular Bid in 1979 had gone on to
win the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwood Lake joined this casualty list at a time when his
fortunes seemed to be improving. The colt, a son of Meadowlake and
the mare Au Printemps, ran second in the Belmont Futurity last
September in his third start. Then he came back to win the
Champagne in October and the Remsen in November, and closed his
rookie season with three victories in five starts.
</P>
<P>
   Zito chose not to run him in the Breeders' Cup Juvenile, which
was won by Anees, the 2-year-old champion who has since strained a
tendon in his leg and has yet to start a race at 3. Then Greenwood
Lake unaccountably ran sixth in the Holy Bull at Gulfstream Park in
January and fourth in the Fountain of Youth in February.
</P>
<P>
   But he closed threateningly in the Fountain, racing from deep in
the pack to finish fourth and making up 30 lengths in the
homestretch. He reminded people of the Zito style of training
speedy closers like Strike the Gold, who won the 1991 Kentucky
Derby. And Joe Cornacchia, one of the owners of Strike the Gold,
was also one of the owners of Greenwood Lake, reviving memories of
Derby glory for the barn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
