<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BOURQUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOURQUE GOES TO AVALANCHE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Ray Bourque Watch reached a stunning conclusion
Monday night when Bruins president/general manager Harry Sinden
announced after Boston's 4-1 loss to Ottawa at the FleetCenter that
the team's longtime captain had been traded to the Colorado
Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque, a Bruin for 21 seasons, was traded along with winger
Dave Andreychuk to Colorado for forward Brian Rolston, defenseman
Martin Grenier, center Sami Pahlsson, and Boston's choice of
Colorado's first-round pick in either 2000 or 2001.
</P>
<P>
   What made the deal so surprising was that the Avalanche, despite
an abundance of talent such as Patrick Roy, Joe Sakic, and Peter
Forsberg, are barely hanging on to a Western Conference playoff
spot and are by no means considered a favorite to win the Stanley
Cup. Bourque had said he wanted to be traded to a viable contender,
and Bruins management had expressed a desire to accommodate him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our attitude right now is we will report,'' said Bourque's
agent, Steve Freyer. ``(The Avalanche) have a game in Calgary
(Tuesday). His first game will probably be in Edmonton on Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   As of 9:30 p.m. Freyer had not talked to Colorado general
manager Pierre Lacroix about the trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be talking to Pierre later,'' said Freyer. ``For the
short term, Ray will report. Then we will see what comes of a new
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Freyer said Bourque would not comment. ``He's home, and he's
tucked in for the night,'' Freyer said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Sinden said the Avalanche were chartering a plane to
get Bourque to Calgary on time for Tuesday's game (9 o'clock
Eastern time).
</P>
<P>
   Early in the night, it appeared a deal had been consummated with
Bourque's first choice, the Philadelphia Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   But around 8:15, word came from the Flyers' practice rink in
Voorhees, N.J., that an angry Philadelphia general manager Bob
Clarke emerged from his office after more than an hour and said the
deal had fallen apart.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bruins coach Pat Burns was forced to go with only 19
players against the Senators because Andreychuk had been scratched
in anticipation of a deal. Around the same time Clark was getting
hot under the collar, Andreychuk left the FleetCenter upset that he
hadn't been clued in as to what was happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm heading home now,'' said Andreychuk. ``I can't wait around
here anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night was the weirdest in a very bizarre year for the
Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was particularly painful for the players, who watched
Bourque collect the puck at the end of a 3-0 loss to the Flyers and
then accompanied him to the dressing room for the very last time.
That was the point at which it really hit them that an era was
over.
</P>
<P>
   Goalie Rob Tallas said, ``The rumors were just kind of there in
the air before. Then all of a sudden he grabs the puck and then the
silence in this room. People realized that, `Wow, it really could
be happening.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque didn't give any speech or formal farewell. It was more
subtle, more emotional.
</P>
<P>
   ``You came in here tired and you put your head down and thought
about the loss but then, all of a sudden, you realized there was
more to the loss,'' said Tallas. ``Everybody just sat back and had
their breath taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray had a lot of emotion. He's an emotional guy. You could see
it. He clinched his eyes with his fingers. You knew something was
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray's the type of guy that if he tried to start speaking, he
would've lost all that emotion and at that point, I don't think he
wanted to. You could look around at the guys who have been here and
see the sadness in their eyes. You could see it, it was a shock, it
really was. A huge shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gretzky was traded, but it's different because he's been here
for so long and he's been so loyal to the city and the team. It's
sad.''
</P>
<P>
   In a year full of disastrous turns for the Bruins, one more
dramatic and gut-wrenching than the next, Bourque's departure is
the most devastating of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had so many huge knocks,'' said Tallas. ``It's been
headline news what's happened to this team this year. Normally, a
team might get one headline a year and we seem to have five, six,
or seven and it just continues.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kevin Paul Dupont of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 2228EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
