u p BC-CARVILLE-POLITICS-ART     03-06 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARVILLE-POLITICS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOYAL, OATHFUL D.O.B. _ DEFENDER OF BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT26 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Attention all furniture within striking distance: The bald man
has a point to pound home, and he's darn likely to use his fist to
do it.
</P>
<P>
   The subject is loyalty in a disloyal town, and James Carville's
diabolical face, one that could be the prototype for every
jack-o'-lantern ever carved, looms large in his dog-dominated
basement office in a quaint Colonial on Alexandria's main drag.
(Somehow Virginia is big enough to hold Carville, the
self-described ``loudmouth'' political consultant and Clinton
defender, and his nemeses, the Rev. Jerry Falwell and Kenneth
Starr.)
</P>
<P>
   Now Carville's down-home voice, one that assaults the average
eardrum like an overtwanged banjo string, traipses the decibels,
loud, louder, loudest. Don't even try extracting the bayou from
this good ole Louisiana boy, oldest and boldest of a brood of eight
born to Lucille Carville, a tough-talking lady better known as
Nippy.
</P>
<P>
   Is Carville, a Machiavelli enthusiast whose Republican enemies
accuse him of exhibiting qualities more cobralike than human,
incensed about anything special? Nope. He's just ranting about the
spirit that moved him to write his latest book, ``Stickin''' (Simon
&AMP; Schuster), in which he plays Boswell to the theme of loyalty,
mainly to President Clinton who, for better and for worse, put him
on the map.
</P>
<P>
   What Carville, 55 and fit but for a little case of runner's
arthritis, is bellowing about now, a tad ahead of schedule he
hopes, is his obituary. And the clause that popped into it the
minute he began defending Clinton and denigrating Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what I call my comma: James Carville, comma, Clinton's
sex defender, comma,'' he explains, his hands testing the
horseshoe-shaped bristle of graying hair (``My wife made me shave
it'') behind his ears. ``Ask people who's that guy, and he's not
the guy who wrote four best sellers, not the guy that ran the
successful presidential campaign here or in Israel or wherever,''
says Carville, whose international client list includes presidents
and prime ministers in Israel, Mexico, Brazil and Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the guy who defended the guy who got in trouble. I wish
it never happened. But wish in one hand and spit in the other, and
see which one fills up fastest,'' says Carville, whose pithy
colloquialisms don't tend to be G-rated.
</P>
<P>
   Sex _ and lying about sex, he adds _ is not enough of a crime to
provoke him to bail out on Clinton. After all, without him, ``I
wouldn't have an obit! I wouldn't have a comma! I wouldn't have had
anything!'' The observation makes him giddy.
</P>
<P>
   One fist is hammering the coffee table. The other hand is
picking white dog hair from his dark pants leg; the shed hairs are
souvenirs from two Cavalier King Charles spaniels deep in slumber
beside him on the sofa. (His very Republican spouse, the political
analyst Mary Matalin, correctly surmised that a jolly lapdog or two
would help cure the doldrums of her 1994 miscarriage.)
</P>
<P>
   Not that Carville and Matalin's political polemics make for a
family-feud atmosphere at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go home, it's a little bit like if you were a plumber
and the rule of the house was you couldn't fix the toilet'' is
Carville's analogy. ``We sleep with six living things in the bed:
the two of us, two kids, two dogs, so even if we wanted to have a
big fight about capital-gains tax cuts, most nights we're too
exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   In Carville, La., where his father ran a general store, Carville
grew up poor and proud of it. He also grew up intoxicated by
politics, especially once ``To Kill a Mockingbird'' convinced him
that the South was ``all wrong on the race thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He spent summers running errands from a Baton Rouge bank to the
Capitol, where the politicians ``were these hefty characters who
wore cologne and drove black Cadillacs,'' recalls Carville who,
surprise, has a couple of Cadillacs.
</P>
<P>
   After a stint in the Marines, he got his law degree from
Louisiana State University, less because he wanted to be a lawyer
than because people said he talked like one. ``Everybody said,
`You've got a silver tongue.'''
</P>
<P>
   At 38, realizing that if he needed a lawyer he wouldn't hire
himself, he quit to be a political consultant. He says it was the
first thing he had ever done that he was actually good at, says he
took an uncle's advice about training chihuahuas (``You have to
think like the dog'') and applied it to politics. ``It has nothing
to do with IQ. You just have to put yourself to thinking like the
voter would, got to have this sort of razor edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Carville thinks he's lost a bit of the old edge. Sure, he still
does some barking, but he rarely bites anymore. Here it is an
election year, and he's not frothing at the mouth. He's providing
advice, gratis, to Clinton (``Let's just say he seeks it
periodically, but I don't know how much of it he takes''), Hillary
Rodham Clinton (``Giuliani would be a senator that would speak for
the powerful, those who have it made, and she would be a senator
for people trying to make it''), and Al Gore (``This was not good
vs. evil, this was good vs. better,'' he says of his preference for
Gore over Bill Bradley). Still, Carville is having ``a quiet
year.'' ``The wars are all kind of over,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Would he ever enlist again?
</P>
<P>
   ``At my age you don't predict your future. You just want a
future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 2231EST &QL; 
