<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0515 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8819 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     03-06 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STRANGE ENDING TO A WORTHY CAREER WITH THE BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Twenty-one years after he first suited up for the
Boston Bruins, defenseman Ray Bourque was traded to the Colorado
Avalanche. The man who came to town in the Old Garden the same year
Larry Bird arrived will seek his Stanley Cup in the Rocky
Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Such a strange day. Such a strange night.
</P>
<P>
   It's never easy and rarely tidy when we say goodbye to a local
sports legend as he goes off to play for a new team. We could go
back to that cold January day in 1920 when Red Sox owner Harry
Frazee said the New York Yankees were ``taking quite a gamble'' by
paying $100,000 for Boston lefty Babe Ruth. Remember the furious
fan fallout when Bobby Orr signed with the Chicago Black Hawks? And
again when Carlton Fisk blew town after Haywood Sullivan neglected
to mail him a contract in time?
</P>
<P>
   Now beloved Ray Bourque has played his last game for the Black
and Gold and there's a giant crack in the Vault on Causeway Street.
</P>
<P>
   Bruin Black Monday was a study in rumor and speculation. Morning
papers reported that Ray had said farewell to his coaches and
teammates in the locker room after Saturday's matinee loss to the
Flyers. Boston radio stations competed to be first with the news
that Bourque had been traded to . . . Colorado. Or was it Detroit?
Or was it Philadelphia? Or New Jersey? Ray didn't come to the
morning skate, and then it was reported that he cleaned out his
locker at the New Garden in mid-afternoon. The report was
incorrect.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the goofiness of this sorry day, the infamous Marty
McSorley showed up in midafternoon to see the Bruins trainers.
Maybe he picked up some fan mail.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the afternoon, reporters flocked to the New Garden,
hungry for a pregame press conference. There was none. But when
veteran winger Dave Andreychuk was scratched from the lineup,
everybody deduced that a Bourque deal had been struck and
Andreychuk was part of it. Defenseman Brandon Smith was called up
from Providence to skate in Bourque's place.
</P>
<P>
   There were a lot of emtpy creamsicle seats as the Bruins and
Senators skated their first shifts. There wasn't much noise in the
hollow New Garden. Fans brought signs that said, ``We Love You,
Ray'' (everybody loves Raymond) and ``Trade Harry.'' Many wore No.
77 Bourque sweaters.
</P>
<P>
   A number of reporters never left the press room to watch the
game. It was as if the Red Sox and Twins were playing another one
of those endless Lee County exhibition games. The news was not on
the ice. The news was in the back rooms and on the phone lines
between Boston and Philly. Or was it Detroit? Or Colorado? Or New
Jersey?
</P>
<P>
   Don Sweeney and Rob DiMaio skated with the ``A'' on their
sweaters, signifying their status as alternate captains. Nobody
wore a ``C.'' Captain Ray was gone and the Bruins were playing like
a team of headless gunners.
</P>
<P>
   At 8:15, Andreychuk left the building, saying, ``I'm heading
home now. I can't wait around anymore.'' Minutes later, word came
from Philly that the Flyers were out of the hunt for Bourque.
Philly GM Bobby Clarke was said to be steaming. Speculation moved
toward New Jersey. Or Detroit. On the ice, the Bruins trailed, 1-0,
midway through the second period.
</P>
<P>
   After two periods, Bruins officials were saying that an
announcement would be made after the game. In the third period, no
one's mind was on playing hockey as the Senators scored three goals
in 1:40. Boos rained down on the head of coach Pat Burns and his
sad soldiers. Fans chanted, ``We want Ray.''
</P>
<P>
   No debris on the ice. Only Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   It was ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors flew throughout the third period as the sorry game played
on. Detroit. No, Colorado. A Bruins publicist announced that there
would be a press conference after the game. Harry Sinden and Mike
O'Connell would ``provide an update on the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   At 9:40 p.m., Sinden, O'Connell, and Burns took the stage in a
makeshift press area on the third floor of the building and
announced that the Bruins had traded ``our captain'' Ray Bourque
and Andreychuk to Colorado for Brian Rolston, Martin Grenier, Sami
Pahlsson, and a first-round pick. Sinden said he had just spoken
with Bourque and that ``he was a bit stunned at the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, standing next to Bourque's locker, veteran
Sweeney said, ``I learned from him every day. Despite the fact that
he was the best player in this locker room every night, he treated
everybody the same.''
</P>
<P>
   That's it. After 1,518 games, Ray Bourque is no longer a Bruin.
The unthinkable has become reality. Ray Bourque has been traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great trip for me with Raymond Bourque and a great
trip for everyone in this town,'' said Sinden. ``And I think it's
been a great trip for Raymond Bourque even without the Stanley Cup.
We have our memories.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
