<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8821 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-GRAVANO-DRUGS-NYT &LR;      03-06 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAVANO-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAVANO INDICTED ON ARIZONA DRUG CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ State prosecutors here unveiled a 201-count indictment
against Salvatore Gravano, the former Gambino crime family member
and turncoat; his wife and children, and dozens of others on
Monday, charging them with a wide-ranging racketeering conspiracy
to sell the designer drug Ecstasy throughout Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   In two separate court appearances on Monday _ Gravano in the
first, and his son and Michael Papa, accused of being a leader of
the racketeering ring, in the second _ the defendants sought to
have their bail reduced and be released from jail. They cited what
defense lawyers called warrantless arrests and complained that
their repeated requests to speak to their lawyers were denied.
</P>
<P>
   But Judge Ronald S. Reinstein of Superior Court rejected the
requests by Papa and Gravano's son, Gerard Gravano, and postponed a
ruling on the elder Gravano's request. All three, who were arrested
on Feb. 24, appeared in black-and-white-striped inmate clothing on
Monday, with ``sheriff's inmate'' emblazoned across the clothing in
capital letters.
</P>
<P>
   A grand jury on Friday returned a 47-page list of charges
against Gravano; his wife, Debra; his son and his daughter, Karen,
mostly dealing with possession and attempted distribution of
dangerous narcotics, but also charging the Gravanos with money
laundering and use of telephones in relation to drug crimes. In a
series of raids last month, investigators served search warrants on
an Italian restaurant run by Gravano and a swimming pool
construction business run by Gravano.
</P>
<P>
   In rejecting assertions by defense lawyers that there was not
enough judicial oversight of the investigation, government lawyers
revealed Monday afternoon that at least part of the evidence in the
case rests on recordings from 11 wiretaps, conversations heard on a
bugging device planted in a business and material gathered as 14
search warrants were executed during raids last month.
</P>
<P>
   The Gravanos were among 36 people arrested on Feb. 24, after a
months-long investigation by local, state and federal authorities.
The authorities allege that Gravano helped Papa turn his fledgling
operation dealing Ecstasy into one that brought in millions of
dollars a week, growing from selling 1,000 pills a week to up to
25,000. They assert that Gravano, whose son was friendly with Papa,
provided money and expertise to Papa.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, Gravano's turncoat testimony helped bring down
John J. Gotti, the boss of the Gambino crime family. An admitted
killer of 19 men whose ferocity gave him the nickname Sammy the
Bull, Gravano went on to testify at nine trials and has been
credited with being the force behind the convictions of 39
organized crime figures and their associates. He moved to Arizona
after entering the federal Witness Protection Program, which he
later quit.
</P>
<P>
   In another case Monday involving the Gambino family, a federal
indictment handed down in Brooklyn charged that Gotti's son-in-law,
Carmine Agnello, and three associates were part of a group that
threatened or used ``force, violence and fear'' through extortion
and arson in a scheme to take over a rival auto wrecking yard in
Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Agnello, who already faces state charges of arson, extortion and
other crimes in connection with the case, was charged in federal
court with racketeering, extortion, arson and income tax fraud.
</P>
</TEXT>
