<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0517 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8823 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-TEXASA&AMP;M-BROWN-HN     03-06 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXASA&AMP;M-BROWN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEIL HOHLFELD  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
Brown
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION _ This week at the Big 12 Tournament in Kansas
City, Jerald Brown will play his final game for Texas A&AMP;M,
concluding a puzzling career that began with boundless potential
and will end in melancholy.
</P>
<P>
   When Brown was recruited in 1996 by then-coach Tony Barone, he
was one of the hottest properties in the nation. He was a member of
the McDonald's and Parade All-America teams and was named Mr.
Basketball in Texas after his playing days at Aldine High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bar none, I think I was one of the best players in the
country,'' Brown said last week without a trace of braggadocio,
merely recalling the glory days.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody who was anybody in college basketball was beating down
Brown's door. The 6-7 forward was recruited by, among others, North
Carolina, Michigan, Temple, Arkansas and Massachusetts. When he
chose to go to Texas A&AMP;M, mainly because he wanted to remain close
to home, the Aggies had their most prized recruit ever.
</P>
<P>
   Brown did not disappoint during his freshman season, averaging
10.1 points and 3.9 rebounds. He started 24 games, scored in double
figures 14 times and was named Big 12 Freshman of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Against Nebraska, Brown scored what proved to be his career high
with 24 points, going 8-of-10 from 3-point range. The Aggies
finished 9-18, but Brown seemed poised to become a big-time player.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, the only question seemed to be whether he would stay
four years at A&AMP;M or leave early to go to the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   In high school, he could play point guard. He could hit
3-pointers or slash to the basket. He could play the post. He could
rebound. As a senior, he averaged 23.9 points and 11.5 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   But somewhere along the way, Brown lost his shot and, with it,
his confidence. He went into a dismal shooting slump during his
sophomore season, hitting only 29 percent from the field. In one
four-game stretch, he was 3-for-23.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies went 7-20. Barone was fired.
</P>
<P>
   When Brown's average dropped to 7.4 points per game as a
sophomore, even opponents were surprised. Texas' Gabe Muoneke, who
played at Cypress Falls when Brown was at Aldine, was
flabbergasted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows how good Jerald Brown is,'' said Muoneke. ``He
wasn't a McDonald's All-American for nothing. In high school there
was nobody that could handle him. Inside out, he had the most
complete game of any high school player in the state when we were
seniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened last year, but I know he can still
play.''
</P>
<P>
   During Brown's sophomore slump, Barone said publicly that Brown
was putting too much pressure on himself and hinted that Brown
couldn't handle that pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tremendous amount of pressure on Jerald Brown,''
Barone said in January 1998. ``You don't have any choice but to
accept the pressure. He's trying to work himself into a situation
where he is not worrying about what other people think
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Brown, who is good-natured and polite, is hesitant
to relive a two-year disagreement with a man who is no longer
coaching. Instead, Brown merely says, ``The coaching change was
great for me.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he catches himself daydreaming about what it would have
been like to play his entire career under Melvin Watkins, who
replaced Barone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the young guys now come to me and talk about, `Coach
did this, coach did that,''' said Brown. ``I tell them this guy is
great compared to what we had. It's a totally different atmosphere.
Coach Watkins is a terrific guy, the right guy for this program.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't push the young guys too hard. You don't want to push
them away, and coach Watkins knows that. He doesn't come in with
the scalpel not knowing where he's going with it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a more restricted role last season, Brown averaged only 5.9
points. This year, Watkins was counting on Brown for veteran
leadership on a team that often started three or four freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown suffered a broken orbital bone near his right eye in
preseason practice, starting an injury-slowed season in which he
played only 21 games and averaged 21 minutes a game. He averaged
5.5 points and was just 7-of-28 from 3-point range. As a freshman,
he was 54-of-154 on shots from beyond the arc.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew of Jerald before I came here because every coach knew
of him,'' said Watkins, who was at North Carolina Charlotte before
coming to Texas A&AMP;M. ``I don't know what happened, but I found him
to be as hard a worker as I've been around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever we asked him to do, he did. He was a great guy to
have with all of our young kids. He played with a broken hand for
most of the last part of the season, and that says a lot about a
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown missed the first three games with the eye injury, suffered
the hand injury in late January and later suffered cuts on his
forehead and inside his mouth that needed stitches.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy for Brown to mope about ending a career that
wasn't supposed to end this way. However, he chooses to look on the
bright side, pointing to the fact that he intends to receive a
degree in agricultural development in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tend to look back and wonder what if I would have done
that or what if I had gone to that school,'' said Brown. ``That's
human nature. I've done it. But I came to the conclusion that if
you spend too much time worrying about it, you're just going to get
caught up in it and never move forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to look back and learn. I don't regret anything I
did, or anything I went through. I mean, it was a tough road. The
injuries, the on-the-court things I went through after my freshman
year. The off-the-court things, being away from home.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Brown can't put his finger on exactly what happened from
his glorious high school career to his mundane career at A&AMP;M, he
isn't ready to give up on trying to attract attention from an NBA
team.
</P>
<P>
   He knows he won't be drafted, but he wants to see if there is
any interest in a player who once was one of the hottest things
going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look back and know that something good is going to come out
of all this,'' said Brown. ``Not only am I going to get a degree
from Texas A&AMP;M, but I believe basketball isn't over for me. I'm 23
years old, and I feel like I've got a lot of basketball left in me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be one of those guys who has a rough, tough
four years (in college) and gives up. When I'm 55 years old, I
don't want to look back and wish I would have at least given it a
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Jerald Brown's future seemed to have NBA written
all over it. After his star-crossed career at Texas A&AMP;M, that shot
now is a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
