<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8824 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-PLANETARIUM-EXPLAI     03-06 0330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PLANETARIUM-EXPLAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU CAN SAY THAT AGAIN. PLEASE. 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-PLANETARIUM) (DW) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Visitors to the new Rose Center for Earth and Space
may have to brush up on their astrophysics. At the start of a
spiral ramp that tracks the 13-billion-year history of the
universe, for example, is a plaque with several scientific
notations under the title ``Pathway Cosmological Parameters Based
on Observational Data and Theoretical Models, 1 January 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from notations for the Hubble parameter, the matter
density parameter and the vacuum energy parameter, there is no
further explanation. Dr. James Sweitzer, director of special
projects for the center, said the plaque sums up the state of human
knowledge, on Jan. 1, about the age of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, the Hubble parameter (expressed on the
plaque as H(EQ)70km/s/Mpc), is the expansion rate of the universe:
70 kilometers per second, over a distance of one megaparsec. A
megaparsec is 3.26 million light-years (a light-year is the
distance light can travel in one year, about 5.88 trillion miles.)
</P>
<P>
   Farther down the ramp, pictures of distant galaxies are
accompanied by captions that mention ``red shift.'' Some visitors
have been confused by an explanatory wall panel that says: ``What
is Red Shift? The red shift of a galaxy tells us how much the
universe expanded during the time the galaxy's light has traveled
to us. Red shift is therefore a measure of a galaxy's distance and
of the epoch at which we observe it. The ongoing expansion of space
stretches the galaxy's light and shifts features in its spectrum to
longer and longer wavelengths. For visible light, those features
shift toward the red.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Sweitzer said, light emitted by an object in
space that is traveling away from us shifts toward the red end of
the spectrum. This shift can be measured and used to calculate the
distance to the light source.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 2239EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0519 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8825 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-LOUIMA-TRIAL-2NDLD-WR     03-06 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUIMA-TRIAL-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-920(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 OFFICERS CONVICTED OF COVER-UP PLOT IN LOUIMA TORTURE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS throughout to recast, add background, quotes; no
pickup.) 
 (nk) 
 By EDWARD WONG and ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two New York City policemen and one former officer
were convicted Monday of covering up the brutal assault on Abner
Louima, a Haitian immigrant, in an emotional verdict that the
defendants' families vowed through tears to fight.
</P>
<P>
   The three defendants _ Charles Schwarz, Thomas Wiese and Thomas
Bruder _ each were found guilty in federal District Court in
Brooklyn of conspiring in dozens of phone calls to obstruct justice
by making up a story for authorities that Schwarz was not involved
in the attack on Louima in the bathroom of a Brooklyn station house
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   After Monday's verdict, lawyers for the three defendants
continued to say that Justin Volpe, who pleaded guilty at the first
trial in the case last May, had attacked Louima alone. The lawyers
said they would appeal the verdicts.
</P>
<P>
   The horrible details of the assault, in which Volpe beat and
sodomized Louima with a broken broomstick, had been fully aired at
a trial last year. Monday's verdicts spoke to the systemic problem
of whether police officers and officials of the policeman's union
lied to protect their brethren rather than the citizens they were
sworn to serve.
</P>
<P>
   At the first trial, which ended in June, Schwarz was found
guilty of helping Volpe torture Louima and then fired from the
force, while Bruder and Wiese were acquitted of beating the
prisoner in a squad car.
</P>
<P>
   What emerged as a central element in both trials was Schwarz's
role. After the first trial, Volpe said Schwarz had not been in the
bathroom during the attack. And in the second trial, Volpe
testified that the second officer in the bathroom was Wiese, not
Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
   The trial that ended Monday in federal District Court in
Brooklyn concerned what prosecutors said was a plot to lie about
Schwarz's involvement. The government argued that Schwarz pinned
Louima to the bathroom floor while he was tortured and then, with
the help of Bruder and Wiese, lied about his role. The defense
maintained that there was no conspiracy to free Schwarz from blame
because, from the start, Schwarz was not involved.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict came almost two weeks after a jury in Albany
acquitted four police officers in the shooting death of Amadou
Diallo, a 21-year-old Guinean immigrant, a year ago. While the
details of the cases were different, they have become linked in the
public's mind. Since the victims in both cases were black and the
officers white, there has been an angry debate about police conduct
and officers' treatment of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz, Bruder and Wiese can be sentenced to a maximum of 5
years in prison on the charge of conspiracy to obstruct justice. No
sentencing date has been scheduled. The jury comprised six white
and six nonwhite panelists, who were granted anonymity by the court
and did not speak to reporters after the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   From the Feb. 7 outset of the second trial, Alan Vinegrad, the
chief prosecutor, based his arguments on two categories of
evidence: phone records showing that the defendants spoke with each
other in a series of calls after the attack _ sometimes only
moments apart _ and testimony that they held a closed meeting in
the basement of the 70th Precinct station house with a trustee of
the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association.
</P>
<P>
   It was during those calls and at that meeting, Vinegrad charged,
that the defendants prepared their stories. He argued that, in the
early days of the inquiry, Wiese lied to the Brooklyn district
attorney's office by saying that, when he walked into the bathroom
moments after the attack, he saw only Volpe and Louima inside, and
not Schwarz. Months later, Vinegrad said, Bruder lied to federal
agents by backing up Wiese's account.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz never gave a statement to the authorities, but he was
charged in the case because the government believed he recruited
his co-defendants and others to construct and then perfect his own
cover story as the investigation pressed on.
</P>
<P>
   The defense was severely disheartened when the judge in the
case, Eugene Nickerson, instructed the jurors that they could
convict the defendants of conspiring to lie about Schwarz even if
the jurors were not sure that he had played the role described by
prosecutors. Federal law holds that a conspiracy may exist even if
the underlying crime never occurred.
</P>
<P>
   After a parade of 23 witnesses and the introduction of more than
100 pieces of evidence, the three officers seemed stunned to the
point of hysteria Monday each time the jury forewoman pronounced
the word ``guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruder, the first to be convicted, grabbed his neck, squinting
in disbelief, before laying his head on the shoulder of his lawyer,
Stuart London, and bursting into tears.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz sat back in shock when his verdict was read, then
glanced angrily around the courtroom, from his lawyers to his
family to the jury.
</P>
<P>
   After Wiese heard his verdict, he and Bruder met in a tearful
embrace, gripping each other's heads. Moments later, outside the
courtroom, Wiese's mother collapsed to the floor and Wiese dropped
to his knees to cradle her in his arms. ``Get a nurse!'' someone
shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Bruder paced the hallway amid a crowd of family and friends,
crying openly and calling out: ``You tell the truth and this is
what happens!''
</P>
<P>
   Andra Schwarz, Schwarz's wife, who has been working to appeal
her husband's earlier conviction, promised to fight Monday's
verdict as well. ``The prosecutors were not seeking the truth,''
she said, in a voice stony with fatigue and disbelief. ``They just
want a conviction. I'm fed up. We're not going to let them get away
with this.''
</P>
<P>
   As he was led out of the courtroom, Schwarz cursed and yelled,
``Why did they do this!'' His lawyer, Ronald Fischetti, said the
ex-officer was ``absolutely devastated.'' He added that he had
asked the authorities to place Schwarz on a 24-hour suicide watch.
</P>
<P>
   Louima was not in the courtroom when the verdict was read, but
hours later, his lawyer, Sanford Rubenstein, said: ``Today's
verdict was a further vindication for Abner Louima. I hope this
sends a message to police all over that they will be held
accountable if they obstruct justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubenstein also said he would press forward with Louima's $155
million civil lawsuit against the three defendants, Volpe, the
city, the police department and the police union. The suit is
expected to be heard sometime later this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference outside the courthouse, Loretta E. Lynch,
the U.S. Attorney in Brooklyn, praised the jury's decision, saying
it would help close a traumatic chapter in the city's history.
``There's no greater betrayal of the badge and the brotherhood than
to ensnare a fellow officer in a web of lies and deceit.''
</P>
<P>
   But John Puglissi, first vice president of the Patrolmen's
Benevolent Association, called the case ``a witch-hunt by federal
prosecutors'' and said Schwarz was an innocent man and that Bruder
and Wiese had been wrongly convicted.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Countless times in tones of bereavement and contempt, the union
officials and the defendants' relatives said Monday that in five
weeks of arguments the prosecution never introduced tapes of the
phone conversations or produced a witness who testified that a
cover-up plot was actually discussed at the station house meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of such concrete evidence, the jury was left with
a case of inferences: Were the defendants discussing ways of
getting their stories straight? Or were they seeking moral support
from each other and discussing his hospitalization and the chance
that they might face repercussions for having injured their
prisoner during the arrest, as the they maintained?
</P>
<P>
   After the verdict, Vinegrad said the jury's decision proved that
the officers were liars. He said the testimony of Schwarz, in
particular _ the only defendant to take the witness stand _ was
``incredible on its face'' and ``essentially a lie.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Louima, one officer _ the prosecution said it was
Schwarz _ held him down as Volpe rammed the 2-foot-long segment of
the broomstick into his rectum.
</P>
<P>
   But Volpe, who is now serving 30 years in prison for the
assault, testified in the second trial in plaintive, emotional
tones that Schwarz was never in the bathroom and that he alone
tortured Louima as Wiese stood by but did nothing to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   For his own part, Schwarz said he had absolutely no knowledge of
the attack while it occurred because he was outside the station
house searching his patrol car.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 2245EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000306.0521 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8827 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-WETLANDS-NYT &LR;      03-06 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-WETLANDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PROTECTION FOR THE WETLANDS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, March 7:
</P>
<P>
   Two successive presidents, George Bush and Bill Clinton, have
promised to stop the steady erosion of the nation's wetlands _ the
100 million or so acres of swamps, marshes and fens that help
prevent floods, filter harmful pollutants, provide habitat for
endangered species and nourish tiny organisms essential to the food
chain. They have succeeded in beating back the big threats,
including efforts by former Vice President Dan Quayle and, later,
the Contract With America Republicans to transfer millions of these
valuable acres to private interests almost overnight. But they have
been less successful in persuading the Army Corps of Engineers,
which actually regulates wetlands, to take a harder line on
developers and others who covet wetlands for commercial purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, however, the Corps announced new and stricter
regulations that will make it much harder for developers to keep
chewing up the country's wetlands in small bites. The rules would
require developers to secure a permit from the Corps for all
projects affecting a half-acre of wetlands or more, down from the
current minimum of three acres. This change could make a big
difference. Though precise figures are elusive, wetlands are
disappearing at a rate of about 70,000 to 100,000 acres a year,
many of them lost to development on small parcels. Regionally, the
rules should benefit New York City's watershed, where thousands of
acres essential to the purity of the city's water supply are
threatened by small-scale development.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules reflect steady pressure from the Clinton
administration and from the Natural Resources Defense Council, an
environmental group that took the Corps to court. The rules also
represent the Corps' second effort to soften the impact of an
arcane but ecologically destructive rule known as Nationwide Permit
26. Until three years ago, in the interests of administrative
efficiency, Permit 26 had allowed the Corps to grant automatic
permits to construction projects that affected less than 10 acres
of wetlands. In December 1996 the Corps dropped that limit to three
acres. But even these stricter standards have allowed the
disappearance of 20,000 or more acres a year.
</P>
<P>
   Several important steps remain. Developers and contractors have
denounced the new rules, and the administration must be ready to
resist legislative attempts to overturn them.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the Corps itself is under a heavy obligation to enforce
the new rules in a fair-minded but hard-nosed way. This will
require careful scrutiny of thousands of individual development
proposals that the Corps could ignore under the old rules. The
administration should make sure the Corps gets the money it needs
for these additional enforcement responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, anyone who worries about wetlands has reason to
cheer. The Corps of Engineers, which is not known for environmental
stewardship, has acted responsibly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
