<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8828 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-FRONT-ROW-NYT &LR;      03-06 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRONT-ROW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRONT ROW: THE DRIVING GLOVE RIDES AGAIN; SWAG FROM EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By GINIA BELLAFANTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arnold Nerenberg, a clinical psychologist, declares on his Web
site, Roadrage.com, that 28,000 Americans died in 1996 from
``aggressive driving.'' Nerenberg offers no support for this
statistic, but the fact that there is a therapist who has carved a
specialty out of the unkind things people do on an Interstate
indicates the distance Americans have come from an era when driving
was considered a leisurely good time, like playing croquet.
</P>
<P>
   To judge from the traffic in Paris last week, or any week for
that matter, navigating a Renault around the Place de la Concorde
is no less stressful than navigating a Dodge Caravan around New
York or Silicon Valley. Still, designers in Europe seemed to be
paying tribute to the genteel era of the automobile, resurrecting
the driving glove in countless variations.
</P>
<P>
   Driving gloves _ wrist-high and made of crocheted string or,
more often these days, leather _ turned up on runways in New York,
London and Milan but peaked at the collections in Paris, which
ended on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Lacroix showed orange ones for his fall 2000 show.
Alexander McQueen did variations in olive, black and white at
Givenchy. Alber Elbaz used them to toughen the more feminine looks
at his show for Yves Saint Laurent. At Louis Vuitton, Marc Jacobs
showed them with square, rather than traditional circular, cutouts
for the knuckles.
</P>
<P>
   Driving gloves ``remind you of people going out for a Sunday
drive, of a time when you drove for fun, not because you were going
somewhere,'' Michelle Kessler, Vogue's accessories director,
observed. ``You see someone with driving gloves and you think, `How
luxurious.'''
</P>
<P>
   Just as aviator glasses and tank watches crossed over as status
symbols from the world of flying, said Caroline Rennolds Millbank,
a fashion historian, so did driving gloves become symbols of the
good life soon after the advent of the automobile. Their original
purpose was to keep the hands clean, because the first cars
generated so much dust.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion's renewed interest in driving gloves is simply an
extension of its obsession with status symbols. Luella Bartley, the
young British designer of the moment, was among the first to show
them for fall in London a few weeks ago. She said she did so
because she wanted to ``pile luxury upon luxury.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not certain, however, that driving gloves will be filling
store shelves this fall. At least one major retailer, who did not
wish to be named, said they have never sold well, because they
don't keep hands warm, which for most people remains the sole
purpose of gloves. Driving gloves, the retailer said, are a
``guaranteed markdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Swag From Europe
</P>
<P>
   Twice a year, as the European collections wind down in Paris,
Americans who've been on the international fashion circuit for
three weeks engage in a communal fret. In Milan, they've bought
Sergio Rossi pumps, Gucci python sandals, certainly Prada bags. In
Paris, perhaps they've bought a Jeremy Scott logoed something or
other. All in all, many have spent far more on foreign merchandise
than their $400 tax-free allowance.
</P>
<P>
   Most editors have tricks to avoid getting into the kind of
trouble that befell Columba Bush, the wife of Gov. Jeb Bush of
Florida, when she returned from Europe last year and was fined
$4,100 for failing to declare $19,000 in new clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Some editors mail home the hard evidence of their sprees, the
receipts. Others ask assistants or friends to help carry the loot
through. Most remove the tags so that, in a pinch, they can tell a
customs officer they've had those Jil Sander sweaters for years.
One editor admitted to rubbing the soles of new shoes against a
rough surface to make them look abraded and old.
</P>
<P>
   For failing to declare goods, they are all risking fines as much
as eight times the normal duty. Christine Pitz, a public affairs
officer at the Customs Service in New York, said that last year 637
people were fined for bringing in undeclared merchandise worth $4
million at Kennedy International Airport alone. They paid $418,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gerard Schiebel, a deputy chief inspector of customs at Kennedy,
said that no one on his staff was trained to distinguish a $5,000
Hermes bag from a $200 imitation, but that they watch for travelers
on ``high profile'' flights like the Concorde or first class on Air
France and Alitalia.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can spot these people,'' he said, alluding to possible
luxury-goods smugglers. ``They're not in dungarees. They've got
their Louis Vuitton bags.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
