<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8830 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FL-MINORITY-ADMIT07-C     03-06 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FL-MINORITY-ADMIT07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida universities' minority enrollment booms
 &HT;    By Stephen Kiehl
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ More blacks and Hispanics applied to the
state's top colleges this year than last year, calming fears among
some educators that Gov. Jeb Bush's One Florida plan would hurt
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Florida and Florida State University used
different methods to attract minority applicants. But admissions
officials said the effect will likely be the same: more minorities
on state university campuses this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears we've been successful in attracting more
minorities,'' said a cautiously optimistic John Barnhill,
admissions director at Florida State. ``But it's a lot harder than
it ever was before.''
</P>
<P>
   As thousands of people descend on the Capitol today to protest
One Florida _ the Bush plan that ends racial preferences in college
admissions _ college officials say FSU has already proven that
race-neutral admissions can work.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, FSU saw a 41 percent increase in minority applications
this year, including a third more applications from blacks. And as
of last week's March 1 application deadline, the school had
admitted 1,034 black students, 140 more than last year. (White
applications were up 18 percent this year. And through last week,
9,142 whites had been accepted, 310 more than last year.)
</P>
<P>
   The FSU admissions numbers are important because the Tallahassee
school has been doing for the past year what One Florida requires
all other universities to do _ give up race as an admissions factor
and reach out to rural and urban students who have long been
neglected.
</P>
<P>
   FSU did this by aggressively wooing minority students with mass
mailings, phone calls and school visits and by looking at the
hometowns and family income of applicants to craft a diverse class.
FSU also increased its admissions and recruiting budget from
$200,000 to $1.2 million in five years.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Daryl Jones (D-Miami) said FSU's positive numbers
should be attributed to hard work from people like Barnhill, not to
any provisions in the Bush plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it means is that a well-meaning person can get the job
done with or without One Florida,'' said Jones, head of the
legislative black caucus. ``But for other people, there will be no
obligation'' to maintain diversity.
</P>
<P>
   The FSU method has been watched closely by other Florida
universities that will soon try to increase minority enrollment
without using affirmative action policies that have been in place
since 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida State is fast out of the chute in proving that you can
build a diverse class without considering race,'' said Keith
Goldschmidt, spokesman for the Board of Regents.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at UF hope that's true. The school saw a 15 percent
increase in applications from blacks this year _ encouraging news
but still not enough, officials say, for a university with 6.5
percent black enrollment. By contrast, 12 percent of the students
at FSU are black.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to step up recruiting and take a more
holistic approach to applications,'' said UF admissions director
Bill Kolb. By holistic, he means UF will look at students' essays
and other factors to help identify disadvantaged students.
</P>
<P>
   UF has formed a committee to figure out how to maintain minority
enrollment, and the school has brought in educators from other
states that have already ended affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   FSU's success offers some direction, Kolb said, but he doesn't
have the resources to duplicate FSU's personnel-intensive efforts.
FSU has a phone bank that's staffed five days a week. Admissions
officers visit every major high school in the state and keep track
of every contact they have with potential applicants.
</P>
<P>
   At Florida Atlantic University in Boca Raton, minority
applications are up just slightly this year. And FAU has admitted
only 199 of the 549 black students who applied. But admissions
director Dick Griffin said many more should be admitted before the
fall. The applications of 309 blacks were deferred because they
were incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the numbers will come up by the first of May,''
Griffin said.
</P>
<P>
   For this year, at least, Florida's colleges seem to have avoided
the drop in minority enrollment that has accompanied affirmative
action debates in other states. At the University of Virginia, for
example, the number of black applicants fell 25 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Florida admissions officials are desperate to avoid such a drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think we were quite ready to do away with race this
year,'' FSU's Barnhill said. ``But if we had to do it without
recruiting, it would have been impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
