school-choice program was born of necessity. Ninth grader Kelly
Marrone, left, receives individual after school help from math
teacher Barb West at the Long Trail School in Dorset, Vt. (Tom
Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) AMHERST, Mass. -- March 6, 2000 -- LORD-AMHERST-BOS -- A
small but vocal group of citizens from Massachusetts is questioning
the propriety of naming places such as Amherst, Mass., after a man,
in this case Lord Jeffrey Amherst, who ordered killing Native
Americans by deliberately issuing them blankets infected with small
pox. Jack Dunphy at the Sunderland-Amherst town line is leading the
charge against Lord Jeff. ``I don't know where political
correctness ends, but I know where it starts,'' says Dunphy. (John
Blanding/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- March 6, 2000 -- MCCAIN-2 -- Sen. John
McCain, center, running for the Republican presidential nomination,
speaks with Ken Kachigian, right, who is in charge of McCain's
campaign in California, as they fly to Los Angeles, Monday.
McCain's son Doug leans on a seat in the background. McCain,
struggling to keep his Republican presidential campaign alive,
planned a heavy day of campaigning across California Monday on the
eve of the crucial Super Tuesday primaries. (Ruth Fremson/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) LAGOS, Nigeria -- March 6, 2000 -- NIGERIA-STRIFE-3-COX
-- Abdul Hamid, with beard, is among the Muslims who argue that it
is appropriate for Nigeria to be subjected to Sharia P or Islamic
law. A roiling conflict between Muslims and Christians over the
push for Sharia in four Nigerian states threatens the country's
tenuous unity and is disrupting the nation's slow march to
democracy. (Seamus Conlan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) LAGOS, Nigeria -- March 6, 2000 -- NIGERIA-STRIFE-2-COX
-- Ferdinand Obi Abbas in a tiny electronics shop where he works
near the sprawling Okoko market. Abbas, a Christian, fears Muslims
want to subject members of his faith to Islamic law. Over the last
two weeks an estimated 500 people have been killed in clashes
between Christians and Muslims in Nigeria's north, where Muslims
are the majority. (Seamus Conlan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LAGOS, Nigeria -- March 6, 2000 -- NIGERIA-STRIFE-COX --
Workers at a market in central Lagos last week near one of the
city's mosques. Over the last two weeks an estimated 500 people
have been killed in clashes between Christians and Muslims in
Nigeria's north, where Muslims are the majority. (Seamus Conlan/Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- March 6, 2000 -- EROS-PHOTO-B&AMP;W-- The NEAR
spacecraft, which has been orbiting the asteorid Eros since
Valentine's Day, sent back this photograph of Eros's puckered
surface from about 180 miles on Feb. 29. The asteroid, about 20
miles long, has numerous grooves as small as 100 feet across,
perhaps related to fractures below the surface. (NASA/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) CHESTNUT HILL, Mass. -- March 6, 2000 -- GREENSPAN --
Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve, blows out birthday
candles after an address to a conference titled ``New Economy,''
Monday. Holding the cake is Karen F. Colannino, right, of the
school's Carroll School of Management and at left is Rep. Edward J.
Markey, (D-Mass.). Greenspan, who turns 74 today, was surprised by
the cake which was presented to him after his speech. The nation's
remarkable prosperity will be put at risk unless supply and demand
are brought into balance, Greenspan said. (Tom Lansders/The Boston
Globe) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- March 6, 2000 -- GORE -- Vice President Al
Gore, left, talks with Maria Lubrano during a visit to a physical
therapy facility at Lutheran Medical Center in Brooklyn, Monday.
Lubrano is recovering from a car accident. Gore campaigned in these
final days before the potentially decisive Super Tuesday
presidential primaries with new confidence and conviviality. (Paul
Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- March 6, 2000 -- SCI-CIRCUS-CLASSES -- With
Big Top music in the background, and revived child hood fantasies
in the forefront, circus-inspired workouts at Crunch Fitness in
Manhattan include trapeze, juggling and gymnastics. Short, sturdy
or slight, there is a place for everyone in circus sports, an
instructor assures the participants. All shapes and sizes are
needed for tumbling, flying, juggling or simply holding up the
human pyramid. The only requirement is confidence. (Thomas
Dallal/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- March 6, 2000 -- BRADLEY -- Bill Bradley,
second from right, running for the Democratic presidential
nomination, greets commuters leaving the Staten Island ferry docks
in lower Manhattan, Monday. Bradley continued campaigning on his
reformist message while admitting he needed good results in
Tuesday's round of primaries to stay in the presidential race.
(Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) SANTA CLARA, Calif. -- March 6, 2000 -- MCCAIN -- Sen.
John McCain, running for the Republican presidential nomination,
greets supporters during a rally at Santa Clara University, Monday.
McCain, struggling to keep his Republican presidential campaign
alive, planned a heavy day of campaigning across California Monday
on the eve of the crucial Super Tuesday primaries. (Ruth
Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) GAITHERSBURG, Md. -- March 6, 2000 -- SCI-FIRES-COMPUTERS
-- Mathematician Kevin McGrattan in his office at the National
Institute of Standards and Technology during a demonstration of a
computer program that simulates the effects of fires. The software
helps to reconstruct fatal fires and to perform other complex
fire-related problems including predicting the performance of
ceiling sprinklers. (Marty Katz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- March 6, 2000 -- SCI-GAMMA-RAYS -- An artist's
rendering of the Gamma Ray Large Area Space Telescope, better known
by the acronym GLAST, being developed by Standord University. NASA
selected Stanford to develop and build the main instrument to
ensure the continued study of the powerful and mysterious
radiations that appear to signal the most violent phenomena in the
distant universe. (NASA/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- March 6, 2000 -- SCI-HERBAL-SUPPLEMENTS --
Assorted herbal remedies available over-the-counter at local
stores. Experts on herbal supplements attending a conference last
week called for stronger government regulation of their manufacture
and sale. Americans spend $4 billion dollars a year on herbal
remedies, which are not regulated by the Food and Drug
Administration. (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
