<P>
   (NYT34) NEW YORK -- March 6, 2000 -- BRADLEY-2 -- Bill Bradley,
running for the Democratic presidential nomination, campaigns along
Flatbush Ave in Brooklyn, Monday. Bradley continued campaigning on
his reformist message while admitting he needed good results in
Tuesday's round of primaries to stay in the presidential race.
(Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEW YORK -- March 6, 2000 -- NY-PLANETARIUM -- At the
Rose Center for Earth and Space, Art Ellis, a designer, explains
the prototype of an exhibit to a family from Nashua, N.H. Since the
center's opening, the exhibits have been baffling to some, who find
them to complex. Some of the exhibits seem to require, if not a
degree in astrophysics, at least a passing acquaintance with light
years, astronomical units and orders of magnitude. (Keith
Meyers/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) PARIS -- March 6, 2000 -- REVIEW-FASHION-2 -- Jean Paul
Gaultier's tunic and full-cut trousers, left, is a street-wise
spin-off of his January couture show. Gaultier's jersey dress,
right, was part of a classic French chic theme. (Corina Lecca/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) PARIS -- March 6, 2000 -- REVIEW-FASHION-1 -- From
Chanel, left, a taupe corduroy coat dress with pleats from Karl
Lagerfeld's collection. Right, John Galliano returns to playschool
with oversized skirts and the look of children playing in adult
clothes. (Jean-Luce Hure/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) ALEXANDRIA, Va. -- March 6, 2000 -- CARVILLE-POLITICS --
Loyalty is the theme of political consultant James Carville's
latest book, ``Stickin.'' Carville, 55, with his two Cavalier King
Charles spaniels, is a good ole Louisiana boy and a staunch
defender of President Bill Clinton, who he says put him on the
political map. Furthermore, sex, and lying about sex, he says, is
not enough of a crime to provoke him to ``bail out'' on Clinton.
(Justin Lane/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) ATLANTA -- March 6, 2000 -- CARDIOLOGIST-COX -- Dr.
Elizabeth Ofili, 44, president of the Association of Black
Cardiologists and Chief of Cardiology at Morehouse School of
Medicine. Ofili was born in Nigeria, to a father who was a U.S.
Information Service librarian and a mother who worked as a nurse
and raised seven children. Ofili received her medical degree in
Nigeria and a master's of public health in the United States, then
completed medical residencies in internal medicine and cardiology.
(Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) MECK ISLAND, Marshall Islands-- March 6, 2000 --
MISSILE-DEFENSE-2 -- Lift off of a rocket carrying TRW's
antimissile during a test, June 23, 1997. Employees with TRW, who
manufactured the antimissile, claim the company manipulated test
results to get favorable results. In a recent statement TRW said it
``categorically denies that it misrepresented or improperly
manipulated any flight test data.'' (Department of Defense/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) REDONDO BEACH, Calif. -- March 6, 2000 --
MISSILE-DEFENSE-1 -- Dr. Nira Schwartz, a former senior engineer at
TRW, outside the main campus of the company last month. Schwartz,
has charged the company with faking tests and evaluations of a key
component for the proposed $27 billion antimissile system and then
firing her when she protested. TRW has vigorously denied Schwartz's
charges. (William J. Broad/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) LOS ANGELES -- March 6, 2000 -- REPUBS -- Texas governor
George W. Bush speaking at the Simon Wiesenthal Center in Los
Angeles, Monday. With one day to go before 13 states hold
Republican primaries or caucuses, Bush holds a commanding position
over the McCain in most contests, though the battle in New York
remained very close. (Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) ATLANTA -- March 6, 2000 -- HOSPITAL-INFECTIONS-2-COX --
The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention has organized an
international scientific meeting, to examine the problem of
infections acquired by patients called ``nosocomial.'' Up to 2
million Americans each year, one in 20 of all those admitted to
hospitals, contract such infections, according to the CDC. The
infections kill almost 90,000 patients and cost an additional $5
billion each year to treat. Proper procedure for preventing
infection in the hospital environment, includes scrubbing and
syringe disposal. (William Berry/Cox News Service Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) ATLANTA -- March 6, 2000 -- HOSPITAL-INFECTIONS-1-COX --
The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention has organized an
international scientific meeting, to examine the problem of
infections acquired by patients called ``nosocomial.'' Up to 2
million Americans each year contract such infections. The
infections kill almost 90,000 patients and cost billions each year
to treat. Betsy Hackman, director of infection control for Crawford
Long and Emory University hospitals demonstrates proper glove use
at Crawford Long Hospital. (William Berry/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) ONJUNGRI, North Korea -- March 6, 2000 --
NKOREA-INVEST-3 -- The tourist center at the near Mount Kumgang,
built by the South Korean firm Hyundai Group, a few miles north of
the demilitarized zone that has divided the Korean peninsula for
half a century. The investment in building the center, along with
with several other developments, is more than just a bet on tourism
by Hyundai. It is the biggest business risk taken so far in the
hopes that the two Koreas, which are technically are still at war,
will someday peacefully reunify. (Calvin Sims/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) ONJUNGRI, North Korea -- March 6, 2000 --
NKOREA-INVEST-2 -- The cultural center at the base of Mt. Kumgang,
built by the South Korean firm Hyundai Group, a few miles north of
the demilitarized zone that has divided the Korean peninsula for
half a century. The investment in building the center, along with
with several other developments, is more than just a bet on tourism
by Hyundai. It is the biggest business risk taken so far in the
hopes that the two Koreas, which are technically are still at war,
will someday peacefully reunify. (Calvin Sims/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) ONJUNGRI, North Korea -- March 6, 2000 --
NKOREA-INVEST-1 -- The Mt. Kumgang Spa, built by the South Korean
firm Hyundai Group, at the foot of the mountain a few miles north
of the demilitarized zone that has divided the Korean peninsula for
half a century. The investment in building the spa, along with with
several other developments, is more than just a bet on tourism by
Hyundai. It is the biggest business risk taken so far in the hopes
that the two Koreas, which are technically are still at war, will
someday peacefully reunify. (Calvin Sims/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) RAMALLAH, West Bank -- March 6, 2000 --
PALESTINIANS-POET -- Mahmoud Darwish, 58, the poet whose lyrical
writings have long been a touchstone of Palestinian national
passions, was banned from Israel and the occupied territories for
nearly 30 years. Darwish has written poems that range from dreamy
reflections on love to bitter longing for the Palestine that was
lost when Israel was created in 1948. He writes of the pain of
exile, a state he says he now realizes he may never leave. (Rina
Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- March 6, 2000 -- LOUIMA-TRIAL -- Thomas
Bruder, center, leaves Brooklyn Federal court after being convicted
of consiracy in the assault on Adner Louima, Monday. A federal
court jury convicted Bruder and two other white New York City
police officers of conspiring to cover-up the 1997 sexual torture
of Louima, a Haitian immigrant, in a Brooklyn police precinct
bathroom. (Richard Perry/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- March 6, 2000 -- KIDS-MOVIES -- For the last
four months movies aimed at children and family audiences have been
griddle hot, one after the other, without a miss. Children's films
often do well, especially in the prime family seasons of summer and
the holidays. But this has been an extraordinary string of
successes without a single flop. Children and parents getting
tickets for ``Pokemon: The Movie.'' (Marilyn K. Yee/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- March 6, 2000 -- ALTRUISTS-THEATER-REVIEW --
Sam Robards as Swallow and Veanne Cox as Sydney in ``The
Altruists'' by Nicky Silver at the Vineyard Theater. Directed by
David Warren, Silver's longtime collaborator, the playwright
presents a group of solipsists who can't see past the ends of their
neuroses. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) DENVER -- March 6, 2000 -- COLO-GUNS -- Wayne LaPierre,
executive vice president of the National Rifle Association, speaks
at a news conference endorsing Project Exile, a set of enforcement
measures designed to put criminals with guns behind bars, Monday.
Listening at left is James Brady, former press secretary for
President Reagan, injured during an assassination attempt on the
president in 1981. In a rare moment of solidarity, Brady and
LaPierre, the two sides in the nation's gun control debate,
together pushed for the program that would provide toughter
enforcement of current gun laws. (Kevin Moloney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) DORSET,Vt. -- March 6, 2000 -- SCHOOL-CHOICE-BOS --
Unlike the politically driven, experimental voucher systems that
have sparked debate in cities such as Milwaukee, Vermont's
school-choice program was born of necessity. Ninth grader Kelly
Marrone, left, receives individual after school help from math
teacher Barb West at the Long Trail School in Dorset, Vt. (Tom
Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) AMHERST, Mass. -- March 6, 2000 -- LORD-AMHERST-BOS -- A
small but vocal group of citizens from Massachusetts is questioning
the propriety of naming places such as Amherst, Mass., after a man,
in this case Lord Jeffrey Amherst, who ordered killing Native
Americans by deliberately issuing them blankets infected with small
pox. Jack Dunphy at the Sunderland-Amherst town line is leading the
charge against Lord Jeff. ``I don't know where political
correctness ends, but I know where it starts,'' says Dunphy. (John
Blanding/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- March 6, 2000 -- MCCAIN-2 -- Sen. John
