<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8836 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-NY-BALLOT-NYT     03-06 0358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-BALLOT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: VOTERS, READ THE BALLOT CAREFULLY
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, March 7,
2000:
</P>
<P>
   For all the excitement about how New Yorkers finally have a
chance to help pick this year's presidential nominees, the act of
voting in Tuesday's primary may prove confusing to many citizens.
The names in big print on the Republican ballot will be candidates
to be delegates to the party's national convention. Voters will
have to look hard to see that tucked under each delegate's name is
the name of the presidential candidate the delegate is pledged to
support at this summer's nominating convention. To know whether
they are voting for Gov. George W. Bush or Sen. John McCain, New
Yorkers, like anybody else worried about being sold a bill of
goods, will have to read the fine print.
</P>
<P>
   This ballot arrangement favors Bush, the candidate of the state
Republican establishment, because his delegate candidates are
better known than McCain's. The ballots, which are slightly
different in each county, are far easier for Democrats who simply
want to vote for either former Sen. Bill Bradley or Vice President
Al Gore. Their names come first, and the votes they receive
determine the number of convention delegates pledged to them.
</P>
<P>
   Voters interested in a simpler ballot or other reforms should
voice their sentiments to Gov. George Pataki and the state
Legislature, including the Senate majority leader, Joseph Bruno,
and Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver. The Legislature should change
more than the format of the ballot. It must also rewrite the ballot
access laws, not merely for presidential candidates but for other
elections as well. In a few months the byzantine petitioning
process that makes it unreasonably difficult for candidates like
Steve Forbes or McCain will begin again, this time for candidates
in state races.
</P>
<P>
   New York has gained the reputation as a state that works hard to
make voting difficult. Future New Yorkers should have plenty of
choices, and they should not need a magnifying glass to choose
their favorite candidate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 2253EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
