A8837 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CT-MYSTIC-FIRE-NYT &LR;      03-06 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-MYSTIC-FIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRE DESTROYS SHOPS IN HISTORIC MYSTIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MYSTIC, Conn. _ A fire destroyed a half-block stretch of shops
early Monday morning in this historic maritime center, leaving a
charred wreck in the center of Connecticut's most popular tourist
destination. It was the fourth time since 1863 that fire has struck
the same building on West Main Street, just steps from Mystic's
famous drawbridge.
</P>
<P>
   The building's eight storefront businesses were destroyed in the
blaze, which began shortly after 12:30 a.m. and smoldered almost
until dawn. The structural damage to the wood-frame building is so
severe, officials said, that it will have to be condemned, which
will leave a wide vacant lot at the core of a downtown commercial
district that draws some 2 million visitors a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hole right in the heart of downtown Mystic,'' said
Linnea Lindstrom, executive director of the Mystic Chamber of
Commerce, which has called an emergency meeting on Wednesday night
to help relocate the ruined businesses. ``It's had quite an
emotional impact. These stores have a lot of memories for a lot of
people. The store owners are our neighbors and our friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The building, built on pylons over the Mystic River, has always
been at the center of town life. For much of the 19th century, it
was filled with stores, offices and a large public meeting space
where traveling performers like Tom Thumb and speakers like
Frederick Douglass and William Lloyd Garrison came to find an
audience.
</P>
<P>
   The rear of the wrecked building overlooks historic Mystic
Seaport and its collection of tall ships, schooners and whaling
boats. The building is three blocks east of Mystic Pizza, which
became famous by lending its name to the 1988 movie featuring Julia
Roberts. Firefighters were able to stop the fire from spreading to
adjacent buildings, and no one was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The ruined stores, at 10-22 W. Main St., were exactly the type
of quirky, independent shops that tourists enjoy poking around on
summer afternoons, including Trade Winds, a gallery of antique maps
and nautical prints; Dexter's handcrafted jewelry and pewterware;
Radio Waves vintage music, and Pepper Grass &AMP; Tulip, which sold
crafts and antiques.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm unemployed for the first time in my life,'' said Tom
Dexter, whose jewelry shop had been in the building for 22 years.
``It's a disheartening feeling,'' he said, adding that he hoped to
find temporary space and rebuild within six months.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the business owners were away on vacation, residents
said, taking a last break before spring and the onset of the heavy
tourist season. Gov. John G. Rowland toured the fire scene Monday
afternoon and promised that the state would assist in rebuilding.
The owners of the building, Rufus Allyn and Roy N. Bohlander, did
not have casualty insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Allyn, whose family has owned the building for generations, said
he could not estimate its worth. But Celeste and Judi Caracausa,
sisters who run a real estate agency specializing in commercial
properties, said the building could have sold for $1.2 million to
$1.5 million. ``This part of downtown is like a little jewel,''
Judi Caracausa said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also said it was too soon to calculate the loss to
each of the eight businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Few people in town were optimistic that a new building could be
constructed in time for this year's high season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mystic fire chief, Fitz Hilbert, said an alarm was first
received at 12:38 a.m. By the time firefighters reached the scene
minutes later, he said, flames had already raced through a loft
that ran the length of the wood-frame building, above all eight
stores. Firefighters immediately set about breaking through the
roof to let the flames escape, he said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 firefighters from at least a half-dozen
surrounding towns joined in helping to suppress the blaze, Hilbert
said, and it was extinguished about 5 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Hilbert said that officials had not pinpointed a precise cause,
but that the fire did not appear to be suspicious.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
