<SLUG> BC-TRIBE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS LOSES LAWSUIT TO PREVENT CASINO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge in Topeka has dismissed a lawsuit filed by
Kansas that sought to block the Wyandotte Tribe of Oklahoma from
building a casino in Wyandotte County.
</P>
<P>
   Don Brown, a spokesman for Gov. Bill Graves, said Monday that
Kansas would appeal the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our initial legal action was based on a desire to get some
clarity on these issues,'' Brown said. ``This decision leaves a lot
of questions unanswered.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Leaford Bearskin was buoyed by the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won the case,'' he said in a telephone interview from
tribal offices near Wyandotte, Okla. ``I don't think there's any
doubt about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we're not held up any longer. We've been waiting a long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   In the ruling made public Monday, Judge Richard D. Rogers
exposed a Catch-22 facing Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said he was forced to dismiss the case because the tribe
was not a party to the legal action and the tribe did not waive its
sovereign immunity to be brought into the suit as a defendant.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Kansas and its four indigenous tribes that operate
casinos sued the U.S. Department of the Interior and other federal
agencies over Interior's decision that year that set the stage for
tribal gambling in Wyandotte County.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt agreed to hold in trust for the
tribe the Shriner building in downtown Kansas City, Kan. It sits
adjacent to the tribe's historic Huron Indian Cemetery, which is
across the street from City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Trust status for the Shriner building could enable the tribe to
conduct legalized gambling activities at the site under terms of a
1988 federal law that governs reservation casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas sued to obtain a judicial determination whether Interior
was correct in designating the ``reservation'' cemetery and its
adjacent Shriner site as legal trust land eligible for gambling
activities.
</P>
<P>
   But Rogers found that the tribe and its economic interests were
essential parties to the action, but because the tribe will not
consent to be sued, the case must be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   The judge admitted that his decision resolves nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court acknowledges that this holding leaves undecided the
Huron Cemetery issue, which could be critical to the underlying
dispute ... whether there is casino-style gambling on the Shriner
(land),'' Rogers concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the tribe is barred by a 1997 federal law that
prohibits it from using the cemetery grounds for gambling. That law
was passed in response to the tribe's plans at the time for a
casino on pillars that would occupy air space over the half-acre
cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Another bill is pending before Congress that would allow the
tribe to buy land anywhere else in Wyandotte County for a casino,
as compensation for taking the cemetery land rights away from the
tribe.
</P>
<P>
   That measure, sponsored by Johnson County Democrat Rep. Dennis
Moore, was approved by a House committee last summer and awaits
floor debate. It instructs Babbitt to take into trust for gambling
purposes whatever land the tribe buys in Wyandotte County.
</P>
<P>
   Bearskin said Monday that the tribe's preference was to strike a
deal with The Woodlands to add a casino to the greyhound and horse
racing complex in western Wyandotte County.
</P>
<P>
   Woodlands owners have said they are willing to sell the track to
the tribe and then lease back parts of it to continue racing while
the tribe developed its casino elsewhere on the property.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
