<HEADLINE>
KC'S ZOO AIDS IN FIRST BIRTH OF AFRICAN ELEPHANT FROM ARTIFICIAL
INSEMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
 -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT CAMPBELL   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kansas City shares partnership in the world's
first successful birth of an African elephant from artificial
insemination.
</P>
<P>
   A healthy 201-pound female calf was born Monday to a 24-year-old
elephant at the Indianapolis Zoo that had been impregnated with
sperm collected from a bull elephant at the Kansas City Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Staff at both zoos were elated by the pioneering success with
the endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now know that we can do it,'' said Conrad Schmitt, Kansas
City Zoo curator. ``Hopefully, in the long term this will help with
genetic management, not only in the United States but globally.''
</P>
<P>
   The birth follows the first from artificial insemination of an
Asian elephant at the Springfield zoo in November. Monday's birth
was the result of efforts by zoo staffs at Springfield, Kansas
City, Omaha, Neb., and Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City has been collecting semen from Dale, a 22-year-old
bull, since 1996. Chilled samples were flown to Indianapolis and
implanted in the female, named Kubwa. It was her first baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is a wonderful mom, and so calm,'' said Judy Gagen,
spokeswoman for the Indianapolis Zoo. ``We're so pleased. It's a
wonderful day to have a baby elephant. She is just delightful.''
</P>
<P>
   The baby, as yet unnamed, will remain at the Indianapolis Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Officials knew from ultrasound tests as early as July 1998 that
Kubwa was pregnant. Elephant gestation takes 22 months. The mother
was in hard labor for about an hour before giving birth at 4:30
a.m. Monday. They baby was on her feet within 20 minutes and was
nursing by 1:40 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Zoo is among relatively few that have facilities
to handle bull elephants.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are hoping to mate Dale with the six females here, but
programs with other zoos also are important to keep the gene pool
healthy. Artificial insemination makes that simpler because it is
easier to move a bull elephant's sperm around the country than the
actual elephant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the things this zoo is striving for, to conserve
species and to be at the top of the game,'' said Kansas City Zoo
veterinarian Kirk Suedmeyer.
</P>
<P>
   Veterinary staff at the Omaha Zoo are working on ways to freeze
elephant semen for longer storage. That could prove useful in the
wild, by enabling genetic diversity among isolated elephant groups
across Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both African and Asian elephants have seen huge drops in their
populations in the wild and reproduction in captivity has been
very, very difficult,'' said Kansas City Zoo Director Mark Wourms.
</P>
<P>
   ``So every time we develop a new technique or solve another
piece of the puzzle, it may mean we're going to be able to keep
this species on Earth that much longer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
