<HEADER>
A8966 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ROCK-HALL-OF-FAME-NYT     03-06 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCK-HALL-OF-FAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONORED ROCKERS FIND COMFORT IN THE BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rock's softer side was celebrated at the 15th annual
Rock and Roll Hall of Fame ceremony Monday night at the Grand
Ballroom of the Waldorf-Astoria, as the hall this year recognized
performers whose music is comforting, not confrontational.
</P>
<P>
   The hall's new additions included Eric Clapton, who has already
been named twice to the hall as a member of the Yardbirds and
Cream, and Bonnie Raitt. Both apprenticed in the blues, then moved
toward rock and pop. Also inducted were the positive-thinking 1970s
soul group Earth Wind and Fire; the Lovin' Spoonful, who brought an
amiable, jug-band sensibility to 1960s pop; the mild-voiced
songwriter James Taylor, and the Moonglows, who whispered their
doo-wop harmonies in songs including ``Ten Commandments of Love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The cool thing about getting this award,'' Raitt said in an
interview, ``is that you could go tomorrow and you've done
everything you have to do. It's from my peers, and I'm getting
respect from them, so in a way I don't have to prove myself
anymore. But actually, at every show on tour I feel like I have to
prove myself, to make sure that I'm even badder than I was last
year. If anything I feel more and more like a pit bull, grabbing
somebody's leg and not letting go.''
</P>
<P>
   Highlights from the ceremony are to be shown on the cable
network VH1 on Wednesday at 9 p.m. and simulcast on the Westwood
One radio network, including Q104 in New York City. The event, with
performances by the hall members and a closing jam session, has
grown more controlled than it was in its early years, with
teleprompters now being used. But the induction has resisted
becoming a standard awards show, as presenters write or improvise
their own speeches. The hall even turned down VH1's suggestion to
use a celebrity host.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the hall added a new category to recognize the backup
musicians who were the backbone of many indelible hits. The first
group of sidemen to join the hall, selected by a committee of 50
producers, includes King Curtis, the archetypal soul-music
saxophonist; Scotty Moore, who put the guitar twang behind Elvis
Presley; Hal Blaine, the drummer on hundreds of hits recorded in
Los Angeles, including ``Be My Baby,'' ``Mr.Tambourine Man,''
``Good Vibrations'' and ``California Dreamin''; Earl Palmer, the
New Orleans drummer behind Fats Domino and Little Richard, and
James Jamerson, the bassist throughout Motown's glory years in the
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``With James, you did not have to know music,'' said Harvey
Fuqua of the Moonglows, who went on to groom younger stars as
Motown's director of artist development during the 1960s. ``You
could say, hmm, hmm, hmm, and he got it going. And if you came in
with something funny, James Jamerson would make it right.''
</P>
<P>
   As always, musicians paid tribute to their elders. ``I may be
young, but I grooved to Earth Wind and Fire,'' said the rapper Lil'
Kim, adding that the band's greatest-hits album was ``the
soundtrack to more good parties than any one of us can ever
remember.'' The band's nine original members were on stage together
for the first time in 20 years. Maurice White, the band's founder,
stopped touring with the band in 1995; he recently revealed that he
has been suffering from Parkinson's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Simon praised the Moonglows' 1954 hit ``Sincerely'' as
``perfect,'' adding that it included ``a riff I've stolen on many
occasions.'' The Moonglows' hits came from rock's primordial era
when, Fuqua recalled, singers and musicians performed with a single
microphone. ``If you were too loud, back up,'' he said. ``If you
were too soft, come closer. When you were finished, you had what
you had.'' He said that for ``Sincerely,'' the drummer was tapping
a telephone book to play quietly enough.
</P>
<P>
   A voting body of 1,000 musicians, executives and history-minded
observers chooses the hall's members, who become eligible 25 years
after the release of their first recording. Clive Davis, the
president of Arista Records, followed up his Grammy award this year
for producing Santana's album ``Supernatural'' by joining the hall
in its nonperformer category. The crooner Nat King Cole and the
jazz singer Billie Holiday were inducted as early influences.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame and Museum is in
Cleveland, most of the annual induction ceremonies have been held
in New York City, the home of music-business executives whose
companies can pay $1,500 to $2,500 per seat. The induction has also
been held in Los Angeles, another music-business capital, and once
in Cleveland. A future ceremony may be held in London in a year
when British rockers are inducted, said Suzan Evans, the hall's
executive director.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the hall of fame followed the lead of the
Rhythm-and-Blues Foundation and the National Academy of Recording
Arts and Sciences, which gives the Grammy Awards, by starting a
program for needy musicians. It has earmarked $100,000 for members
of the hall who need help with medical bills or living expenses,
and it hopes to expand the program in future years.
</P>
<P>
   In Cleveland, the museum is working on plans to expand its
scholarly side by building a library and research archive, and is
also considering adding a restaurant. It has been drawing about
500,000 visitors a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
