<SLUG> BC-HERDING-ELKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELK HERD DODGES RELOCATION _ FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KRISTIN DIZON  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANFORD, Wash. _ A battle of wills unfolded between a herd of
animals and a cowboy in a whirlybird Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The moral of the story: Herding elk is like trying to lasso the
wind.
</P>
<P>
   The largest relocation of elk in Washington history was supposed
to get underway with 50 head herded by helicopter into a holding
pen here. The elk were then to be moved by trailer four hours east
to the Blue and Selkirk mountains.
</P>
<P>
   It sounded simple, but in the crisp dawn hours on the dry,
shrubby steppes just across the road from the nation's largest
nuclear cleanup site, untamed nature took over.
</P>
<P>
   The elk, you see, failed to read the relocation plan.
</P>
<P>
   Chopper pilot Gary Brennan started the round-up in the
Rattlesnake hills, where crescent-shaped fingers of snow nestle in
the crevasses of the taupe and dun-colored mounds. Brennan pushed
several groups of animals together in a moving column of nearly 100
elk.
</P>
<P>
   He drove them three miles, then turned them toward a V-shaped
fence _ a funnel to ease them into a corral. But just when it
looked like the wildlife would run into the snare, they turned tail
and the cat-and-mouse pursuit started over again.
</P>
<P>
   Back and forth they went, with Brennan giving chase and
directing them back toward the trap. A few jumped right through the
burlap-covered wire fence; others dashed into the hills.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the whirring roar of helicopter blades at their hind
quarters did the trick. At one point Brennan, who skillfully zipped
and dove and looped toward the herd during the three-house chase,
came so close that he said he had to pull up to avoid grazing them
with the helicopter's landing skids.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like putting a cat in a bucket of water _ they just don't
want to go,'' said Brennan, of Grey Bull, Wyo. ``I know how to push
these animals and when to give them a break and get their heart
rates down.''
</P>
<P>
   A second, shorter attempt in the afternoon with another group of
elk yielded even worse results. One cow was trampled in the frenzy
and had to be destroyed. The carcass was taken to the Yakama
Indians, who skinned and cleaned it immediately, said Dale
Bambrick, regional director of the Washington Department of Fish
and Wildlife. Officials had expected a mortality rate of as high as
five percent, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The combined effort of the federal and state Fish and Wildlife
departments, along with volunteer help and tribal input, was
designed to move about 200 Rocky Mountain elk from the Hanford
site's 77,000-acre Arid Lands Ecology reserve. The
trap-and-transfer project is expected to cost about $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the week, wildlife officials hope to move the
animals from their windswept, sagebrush habitat to thickly
forested, snowy mountains. About 100 are headed to the Selkirk
mountains in Pend Oreille County; another 100 will go to the
southeastern corner of the state.
</P>
<P>
   A total of about 500 elk will be relocated in coming years.
</P>
<P>
   The herd was first established in 1975, when eight elk began
frequenting the unpolluted buffer area of the Hanford nuclear
complex. Today the herd, which cannot be hunted on the preserve,
numbers more than 800, and experts fear that such a continued
growth rate will overtax the ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers and ranchers in the area have long complained about
grazing damage to crops, grassland and fences, resulting in a
number of financial claims that the state is processing.
</P>
<P>
   ``As it grows, if we did nothing, this site could be on the
verge of ecological collapse,'' said Bambrick. ``Look how much
trouble we had with them today. Imagine we're three years down the
road and there are 2,200 of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten percent of the relocated elk will be fitted with radio
collars and tracked to see if they're adapting well to their new
locales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both places are good locations to put elk, but, frankly, it's
an experiment,'' said Madonna Luers, a spokesperson at state Fish
and Wildlife's Spokane office.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty elk were relocated in a test run last week. They appear
to be doing fine and are mingling with the local elk population,
Luers said. But those elk were more easily rounded up with net
guns, which is more expensive, labor-intensive and dangerous than
herding with helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Two elk died last week when their necks snapped while struggling
in the nets. The carcasses were picked up by the nearby Wanapum
Indians, who fed a crowd of 150 at a feast last weekend, said
Clayton Buck, a cultural resources specialist with the tribe.
</P>
<P>
   Those 20 elk were tested for radioactive compounds and found to
have lower concentrations of radiation then elk at higher
altitudes, said Kathy Criddle with the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service. They also were disease-free.
</P>
<P>
   No one was sure why Monday's roundup went wrong. One theory was
that the elk smelled humans and were spooked, another held that the
elk didn't like the 12-foot high fence or thought the entryway into
a walled corral was too small.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, everyone agreed that elk are a sharp bunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah. They're pretty smart. You better believe it,'' said
Spike Norton, who volunteered his stock trailer to move the elk to
an area near Usk, where he has a ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Norton, who drove 11 of the test elk to their new home last
week, said people in Pend Oreille County are excited about the
transplants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demand for elk to view up there is pretty heavy,'' he
said. ``We hope that when those hunters get through with them,
there's something left for us to look at.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, about 50 Fish and Wildlife employees,
volunteers and media made up a herd of its own on a ridge
overlooking the round-up site.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the crowd bet on who would run out of gas first _ the
pilot or the herd. One man remarked, ``We've got the best pilot on
Earth, by God. If he can't get them ... ''
</P>
<P>
   But officials are counseling patience. They widened the corral
gateway late in the afternoon and made other adjustments to the
trap. They'll try again Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not everything happens the minute you want it to,'' Bambrick
said. ``We're going to re-group and come back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
