A8971 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-BUSYKC-KAN &LR;      03-06 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSYKC-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS TO CONVERGE ON KC FOR AUTO SHOW, BIG 12 BASKETBALL
TOURNEYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Downtown is going to be a wee bit crowded this week.
</P>
<P>
   Big 12 college basketball fans, auto lovers and thousands of
others will converge in the downtown loop from morning till night
in what has become Kansas City's version of March Madness _ filling
every hotel room and parking spot in sight.
</P>
<P>
   To ease the gridlock, networks of shuttle buses _ some free _
will be plying city streets moving masses at the Country Club
Plaza, the River Market and points between.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great week,'' said Rob Sight, president of the Greater
Kansas City Auto Show. On Wednesday, the auto show at Bartle Hall
kicks off its third consecutive year as a concurrent event with the
Big 12 men's and women's basketball tournaments, with women's games
next door at Municipal Auditorium and men's games at Kemper Arena.
</P>
<P>
   More than 225,000 visitors are expected to troop through Bartle
Hall through Sunday during the auto show's annual five-day run that
features 500 vehicles under one roof.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them will be among the nearly 30,000 fans, locals and
out-of-towners alike with tickets for the Big 12 games that start
at noon today and run through Sunday afternoon. Almost half of them
are from out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Music Hall will hold performances by the Kansas
City Symphony on Friday and Saturday; the Quality Hill Playhouse
has daily performances of its new musical, ``Hi Hat Hattie,''
through Sunday; and tonight's Fat Tuesday ``Mardi Gras Blues Club
Crawl'' is expected to draw its own crowd of revelers.
</P>
<P>
   If all of that isn't enough, more than 1,000 conventioneers
begin arriving at downtown hotels starting today through early next
week for annual meetings of the American Concrete Paving
Association and the Salvation Army.
</P>
<P>
   The Greater Kansas City Convention and Visitors Bureau estimates
that the basketball crowd alone will leave $20 million behind when
the last of the fans leaves town late Sunday afternoon, said bureau
spokeswoman Maxine Odell.
</P>
<P>
   While most auto show attendees are local residents or basketball
fans killing time between games, Sight said the event also
attracted day trippers from around the Midwest plus hundreds of
manufacturer's representatives and other behind-the-scenes workers
who fill hotel rooms during the run of the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really brings a lot of people into the city,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them will have trouble finding a place to park anywhere
close to the action.
</P>
<P>
   To ease the crunch, the Downtown Council will run free shuttle
bus service about every five minutes along a route linking several
downtown parking lots to Bartle Hall and Municipal Auditorium on
Thursday afternoon from 3:30 p.m. to 11 p.m. and Saturday from 11
a.m. to 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   There are no women's games Friday. Sight says the Auto Show
attracts the bulk of its visitors Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the downtown loop and beyond, specially marked
``Shuttle'' Metro buses will pick up riders at many regular city
bus stops for $1 one-way fares to both game sites.
</P>
<P>
   The buses will run from approximately one hour before the day's
first games to the final buzzer of the day's last game. Shuttles
will also be marked with windshield placards that declare either a
``Municipal'' or ``Kemper'' destination.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about Metro shuttle bus routes and other
tournament week schedules and special events, visit
www.big12tournament.com or call (816) 221-0660.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
