<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8974 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MIGRANT-LABOR-805&AMP;ADD     03-06 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIGRANT-LABOR-805&AMP;ADD-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWERS AND WORKER ADVOCATES CLASH OVER MIGRANT LABOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ore.)  (lb) 
 By CARL HULSE   NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Facing new high-tech scrutiny from government
authorities, the United States' agricultural employers are
clamoring for changes in federal law governing how they hire
workers to harvest fruit and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Growers say stepped-up electronic verification of the Social
Security numbers provided by migrants has revealed the extent of
the illegal work force, put farmers at risk of fines and criminal
charges, and sent workers packing during the picking season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go to your workers and tell them there is a problem with
their numbers, and the next day you have no workers,'' said Sharon
Hughes, executive vice president of the National Council of
Agricultural Employers. ``We want to have a secure, stable, legal
work force.''
</P>
<P>
   Employers across the country have received letters from the
Social Security Administration informing them of a high percentage
of mismatches between the names and the numbers they provided.
Financial penalties can be imposed for such irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, employers fear that an employment eligibility
verification system being tested by the Immigration and
Naturalization Service will eventually be put in place nationwide,
requiring them to quickly check worker documents against an
electronic database. Illegal workers would have to be rejected or
growers could face charges for knowingly hiring them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that a very large number of illegal
people are picking fruits and vegetables in the United States, and
an aggressive, higher-technology enforcement regime is going to
find them out,'' said Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla. He is the chief
sponsor of a controversial measure to revamp the migrant-worker
program.
</P>
<P>
   Graham and Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., proposed an approach that
would enable current undocumented farm workers to earn U.S.
residency in exchange for allowing farmers to more easily tap
foreign labor sources if they cannot find enough legal workers. The
measure would also institute wage and housing guarantees and create
a job registry to match workers with openings.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and farm-worker advocates, however,
say the bill is not needed and is simply a maneuver to provide
agricultural employers with a new crop of easily exploited foreign
workers. More than 180 interest and advocacy groups have sent a
letter opposing it to every member of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The growers want this because it would give them tremendous
power and control over guest workers,'' said Bruce Goldstein of the
Farmworker Justice Fund.
</P>
<P>
   He and others say farmers' claims of a labor shortage are
unfounded. They point to the fact that demand for workers is not
forcing wages and benefits to rise. Unemployment in some large
agricultural areas is up. In Florida a group of farm workers
recently marched across part of the state to protest working
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am in the middle of the Florida harvest and there are
certainly lots of unemployed farm workers,'' said Greg Schell,
managing attorney for the Migrant Justice Project in the
agricultural community of Belle Glade, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Congressional Research Service report also disputes the
notion of a labor shortage. ``At the present time, trends in the
farm labor market generally do not suggest the existence of a
nationwide shortage of domestically available farm workers in part
because the government's databases cover legal and illegal
employment,'' said the study issued in December.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agree that the prevalence of illegal workers gives a
skewed picture of the farm labor market. An ongoing U.S. Department
of Agriculture survey found that more than 50 percent of migrants
interviewed identified themselves as undocumented. Social Security
audits have found farms where 80 percent of the numbers given are
invalid.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that illegal migrants willing to take less in
wages force legal workers to the unemployment line and put farmers
at risk of getting in trouble with the federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier version of Graham's measure twice passed the Senate
but never made it to the White House, where it was threatened with
a veto. To broaden support this year, backers added an opportunity
for illegal workers to become legal.
</P>
<P>
   First, they must show they worked in agriculture 150 days in the
past year. Then if they work at least 180 days annually in
agriculture in five of the next seven years, they could become
permanent residents. In the interim, they could only remain in the
United States for 10 months of each year.
</P>
<P>
   A House version is expected to be introduced soon, and Graham
said a hearing is being scheduled on the proposal in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Farm-worker advocates expect few people to have the evidence to
qualify. ``We don't view it as a realistic amnesty for most
folks,'' Schell said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rick Swartz, an immigration-policy expert who helped craft the
amnesty proposal, said the farm-worker advocacy community is being
shortsighted in fighting the plan. He attributed the opposition to
historic, deep-seated animosity toward growers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you talk to the farm workers about it, they think it is a
ticket to freedom,'' said Swartz.
</P>
<P>
   Graham said he is willing to adjust his proposal to answer
critics. But he is frustrated by continued opposition to a measure
that he believes would improve conditions for both legal and
illegal migrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill gives higher wages, better benefits, and it gives to
this large group some legal status and position of respect in our
society,'' he said. ``I am just kind of bewildered as to what the
concerns are.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief of the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 2320EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
