<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8976 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-SCOTUS-TANKERS-SPI &LR;      03-06 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-TANKERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT STRIKES DOWN STATE'S TANKER RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE BARBER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Supreme Court on Monday struck down the tough oil-spill
prevention rules enacted by Washington state after the 1989 Exxon
Valdez disaster in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous decision has wide import for environmental
protection and states' rights.
</P>
<P>
   The justices said federal laws pre-empt states from setting
their own standards to prevent oil spills from tankers _ except to
address ``peculiar'' conditions in local waterways, the justices
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state of Washington has enacted legislation in an area
where the federal interest has been manifest since the beginning of
our republic and is now well established,'' Justice Anthony Kennedy
wrote for the court.
</P>
<P>
   The decision reversed a unanimous 1998 Ninth U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals ruling that said states can enforce their own laws. That
ruling upheld an earlier U.S. District Court decision.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's rules, designed to prevent an Exxon Valdez-type
disaster in the state, required additional crew training, a higher
standard of English-language proficiency for crewmembers, increased
navigation-watch requirements and accident reporting.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, siding with the Clinton administration and the oil
shipping industry, said such state rules venture into the field of
foreign affairs, affecting operations outside state waters.
</P>
<P>
   Shipping industry lawyers argued that state rules would upset
international treaties, which require uniform national standards.
</P>
<P>
   In light of ``considerable federal interest at stake,'' the
justices Monday ordered a lower court to decide whether other
federal law pre-empts state rules.
</P>
<P>
   The decision drew immediate fire from Washington Gov. Gary Locke
and state Attorney General Christine Gregoire.
</P>
<P>
   Locke called the ruling ``a major set-back for states that want
to take prudent steps to prevent oil-spill catastrophes. ...
Oil-spill protection for the entire nation will be set at the
lowest-common-denominator, with no recognition that some marine
habitats deserve a higher level of protection.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor also promised to ``press Congress and the (Clinton)
administration to move quickly to compensate for the greater safety
protections state regulation would have offered by substantially
increasing Coast Guard funding and efforts to ensure safe
shipping.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregoire called the decision a ``terrible blow to Washington's
Puget Sound protection efforts,'' and requested the Coast Guard
immediately strengthen tanker regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court's decision has tied the state's hands from ensuring
tankers will safely transit Washington waters and that there will
be full and adequate protection for Puget Sound,'' Gregoire said.
``We know better than those in Washington, D.C., how to protect
this natural resource gem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this exposes our coastline to more danger,'' added
Bill Collins, a state assistant attorney general who handled the
case since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one states and territories, seven Washington counties,
several fishing groups and environmental organizations nationwide,
as well as a citizens' group from Alaska's Prince William Sound,
filed legal briefs supporting Washington's case.
</P>
<P>
   The tanker industry and the federal government were supported by
15 foreign governments and a variety of shipping and business
groups. Those groups are largely concerned with preventing their
members from having to comply with different regulations in
different states, which they said would be confusing and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed, deeply,'' said Fred Felleman, whose
environmental organization, Ocean Advocates, long has supported
permanently stationing a rescue tug for tankers in the Strait of
Juan de Fuca. ``Our waterway is both one of the most traffic laden
and one of the most biologically rich, which the Coast Guard alone
is not equipped to take account of.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the International Association of Independent
Tanker Owners, known as Intertanko, could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said the state's 1991 regulations were aimed at
minimizing human error in the relatively narrow Straits of Juan de
Fuca and Puget Sound. Human error is accountable for 60 percent to
80 percent of all oil spills, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A 20-year-old court state case that the Supreme Court justices
spent a good deal of time analyzing, Ray v. Atlantic Richfield, was
aimed at minimizing mechanical and technical hazards in tankers
that could lead to oil spills. It led to double-hulled tankers and
tug escorts for them in Washington waters. Washington's late U.S.
Sen. Warren Magnusson, meanwhile, succeeded in getting Congress to
ban supertankers from the Sound.
</P>
<P>
   Tanker industry lawyers argued that the state's rules are
already covered under the 1990 Oil Pollution Act, enacted by
Congress a year after the Exxon Valdez drove onto a charted reef
and dumped 11 million gallons of oil into Prince William Sound.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Washington state adopted additional standards for
training, language, staffing and drug-testing of oil tanker crews.
</P>
<P>
   The state's rules require tanker operators to file
spill-prevention plans and to have three licensed officers on the
bridge _ one more than usual.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Intertanko complained in federal court that state's
rules were inconsistent with uniform industry standards that took
20 years to create.
</P>
<P>
   Intertanko, a Norway-based organization representing 75 percent
of the world's tanker companies, lost in U.S. District Court. The
Clinton administration intervened on the organization's behalf in
the Ninth U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   During arguments before the Supreme Court in December, some
justices expressed consternation at the appeals court's reasoning.
Others, particularly Justice Sandra Day O'Connor and Chief Justice
William Rehnquist, expressed concern about whether federal
regulators could adequately address the peculiarities of local
waters.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist referred to a ``very strong local interest'' in a
requirement such as ``in heavy fog in Seattle harbor, you have to
have a tug. I, for one, would be loath to read some general federal
statute as pre-empting something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the state's legal brief, the waters of Washington
state are more difficult to navigate than those in Prince William
Sound because of persistent fog, heavy fishing traffic and narrow
waterways. State officials argue that an oil spill could be
devastating to fish and wildlife and to the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court on Monday noted that issue and left the state
with some wiggle room.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said states can regulate their own ports and waterways
so long as the rules are based on ``the peculiarities of local
waters'' and do not conflict with federal rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``On remand, Washington may argue that certain of its
regulations, such as its watch requirement in times of restricted
visibility ... are necessary to address the peculiarities of Puget
Sound,'' Kennedy wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The state also has a role in setting regulations where they do
not conflict with the Coast Guard, which is responsible for design,
maintenance, staffing and operation of tankers, Kennedy noted.
</P>
<P>
   And federal law allows states to set their own liability rules
for oil-spill pollution, Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   For Locke, that at least left open some state control over its
own environmental health.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court admitted that the federal standards may not
provide the necessary level of protection _ and we absolutely
agree,'' Locke said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-00 2326EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
