<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-06 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8983 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-TEXAS-MUONEKE-HNS     03-06 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS-MUONEKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
AUSTIN _ No regrets.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That's how Nnadubem Gabe Muoneke feels about his college
basketball career.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, there would appear to be plenty for the Texas
senior to lament, what with well-chronicled incidents involving
opponents and referees that are highlights, or maybe lowlights, in
the soap opera that Muoneke's four-year stay with the Longhorns has
been.
</P>
<P>
   But Muoneke is not that type of person.
</P>
<P>
   While he would surely not make the same mistakes if given a
chance to rewind history, Muoneke stops short of wishing he could
exclude the distasteful dishes from his full plate of life's
experiences. Even the ones that may have tarnished his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's one (incident) that I would really
choose to erase,'' Muoneke said. ``I'm not a person of regret.
Everything that happens to me happens for a reason, and I'm
thankful. I always thank God for every experience that I go
through.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been an interesting ride for the 6-7, 250-pound forward,
from run-ins with officials that led to his being a target even
when on his best behavior to a couple of punches delivered to
opponents who got under his skin.
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke was also among the group of Longhorns who ignited the
Tom Penders fiasco with a visit to the home of athletic director
DeLoss Dodds following the 1997-98 season.
</P>
<P>
   But with all of that behind him, Muoneke now prepares to play in
his final Big 12 Tournament in Kansas City, Mo., this week as a
respected teammate on the country's No. 13 team. It's a team he
believes can make it to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Just being here for his fourth and final season is something of
which Muoneke says he is proud.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not many players have been through all I've been through and
hung around for four years,'' said Muoneke, a petroleum engineering
major. ``Under the same circumstances, the number of players that
would have transferred or quit by now would be pretty high.''
</P>
<P>
   Numbers tell almost as much of the Muoneke story during his
first three years at Texas as do words.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman year: 5.9 points, 3.8 rebounds and 15.2 minutes per
game. It took some time for him to contribute to a Sweet 16 team,
but he had his best game in the season finale, scoring 19 points
and grabbing 12 rebounds against Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore year: 10.4 points and 5.7 rebounds per game; 43.1
percent shooting; fouled out six times; ejected once. With
officials watching his every move, Muoneke's anger got the best of
him at times, and he struggled to improve under Penders' wild
offensive system.
</P>
<P>
   Junior year: 16.5 points and 6.6 rebounds per game; 49.5 percent
shooting. He may have been the best player in the Big 12,
flourishing under Rick Barnes' inside-dominated system and leading
the Longhorns to the conference title.
</P>
<P>
   But despite all the ups and downs of his first three UT seasons,
Muoneke said the experience he learned from most was an incident at
practice a few weeks ago that resulted in Barnes' pulling him from
the starting lineup for a game.
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke's ``bad day to be in a bad mood'' at practice turned
into six games of reserve duty, an experiment Barnes had been
considering anyway because Muoneke would bring him something he
needed off the bench _ consistency.
</P>
<P>
   But Barnes might never have pulled the trigger on his experiment
if not for the practice incident. Muoneke said he turned to his
Christian faith to handle the demotion, and that is what helped him
learn from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord teaches you that you have to be humbled to learn the
real meaning of being exalted,'' Muoneke said. ``Being humbled the
way I was this year was definitely a huge thing I learned.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sophomore year, I knew I shouldn't have been talking to
referees. I knew better than that. (Last year) I knew I shouldn't
have hit anybody. Nobody needs to teach me that. I knew that (was
wrong) when I did it. But this one, I have to deal with real
adversity _ adversity that really can affect you mentally. The
other things didn't affect me mentally that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he expects more from himself than any of his coaches
have ever asked him to deliver and he is a tougher reviewer of his
actions than his harshest critics could ever be, it seems no
outside pressure could have much effect on Muoneke.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the thinker and analyst, he is too hard on himself,
according to Barnes, who only echoes the sentiments of Penders, now
the coach at George Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is tougher on Gabe than Gabe,'' Barnes said. ``Gabe
really wants to win. He has a lot of pride and a lot of drive. I
mean he really wants to win. People don't understand that he is a
student of the game. He watches everything and breaks it all down.
But I have to tell him not to put so much pressure on himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke understands that, but he thinks that is one way for him
to reach his full potential. And he appreciates the difference
Barnes has made in his game, especially his on-court demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge difference; it's not even close,'' Muoneke said.
``He took the potential I had, and he honed it. He molded it. He
made me understand that it wasn't all about physical talent. You
have to separate yourself somehow. He (helped me do) that by
teaching me how to mentally understand the game, and I'm hoping
that separates me in some way.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that separation means an NBA career remains to be seen,
but Muoneke's drive to achieve is too intense to expect anything
less than success on the next level.
</P>
<P>
   Obstacles? No problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a survivor,'' Muoneke said. ``God made me that way. He's
pulled me through. In situations that I think I'm pretty much dead
in the water, he's always given me a boat to paddle out with. He's
done it more than once, and he'll do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
