<SLUG> BC-ALTRUISTS-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE ALTRUISTS': BUT ENOUGH ABOUT YOU _ LET'S TALK ABOUT ME 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 17 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Sydney, the hyperemotional soap opera star in
Nicky Silver's new play, ``The Altruists,'' Veanne Cox gives the
kind of performance that you feel you should watch wearing
sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   Everything about Sydney is bright to the point of blinding, from
her electric pink pantsuit to the feverish glow of her face as she
swings between pharmaceutically enhanced extremes. Her trim, sharp
body punctures the air with its angularity; her voice lances the
eardrums. And her self-obsession makes the original Narcissus look
like a shrinking violet.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when someone this vital crosses your line of vision, how
can you look away? Too thin, too rich, too selfish to live, Sydney
is nonetheless a life force of sorts, at least as presented by the
invaluable Cox. And as empty as Sydney may be, she is the only
fulfilling element in this surprisingly simple-minded satire from
the author of ``Raised in Captivity'' and ``The Food Chain.''
</P>
<P>
   After bursting with great eclat onto the Off Broadway scene in
the mid-1990s, the prolific Silver has recently been plying his
considerable talent in ways that often feel perfunctory. He always
manages to come up with some sparkling epigrams, suggesting
cyanide-laced Champagne, and he usually provides one juicy female
role that the right actress can run with. But there has been an
increasingly recycled feeling in his work, no matter how much he
varies the surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Altruists,'' directed by David Warren, Silver's
longtime collaborator, the playwright again presents a group of
solipsists who can't see past the ends of their neuroses. Though
three of the work's six characters present themselves as selfless
social benefactors, the altruists of the title, they are as
unlikely as any of Silver's people to utter the phrase ``but enough
about me'' and mean it.
</P>
<P>
   This leads to easy scores off easy targets: the social worker
who can't shut up long enough to find out what anyone else is
thinking; the political agitators who can't remember just what the
rally they're headed for is in support of; the woman who, in the
year 2000, reflexively yells, ``Free Nelson Mandela!'' The
liberalism portrayed here may be knee-jerk, but so is the parody of
it.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney, who plays the title heroine of the popular soap
``Montana Beach,'' is the one professed materialist onstage, which
gives her an edge in self-awareness. Her lover, Swallow (Sam
Robards), a womanizing political activist, and her brother, Ronald
(Joey Slotnick), the social worker, are different types of deluded
romantics.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Cybil (Kali Rocha), a self-described lesbian who
tends to forget not only what she is protesting but also her avowed
sexual preference, and Lance (Eddie Cahill), a beautiful, stupid
street hustler who is _ wouldn't you know it? _ the only character
who approaches moral goodness.
</P>
<P>
   Presented in alternating scenes in three Manhattan apartments
(the polished triptych of a set is by Neil Patel), ``The
Altruists'' has the fuguelike structure that is a specialty of
Silver. As usual, his characters speak in monologues even when they
are ostensibly engaged in dialogue. It seems appropriate that much
of the evening's ranting is directed at an anonymous, sheet-covered
and totally unresponsive person in Sydney's bed.
</P>
<P>
   The performers are a likable, energetic lot, and Warren keeps
them moving at a sprightly pace. But except for Cox and Cahill, who
has the advantage of playing a character who has not been written
with contempt, the ensemble members are defeated by their status as
dartboards.
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of charming moments of self-conscious
theatricality in which the characters deliver (or try to)
autobiographical soliloquies and several funny coital and
postcoital exchanges. (Slotnick, playing the archetypal Silver
schlemiel, says to Lance the hustler the morning after: ``You're
beautiful. What do you weigh? Do you know?'')
</P>
<P>
   Only Cox, an expert in neurotic intensity (as she demonstrated
in ``The Waiting Room'' and the revival of ``Company''),
consistently breaks through the rote quality that pervades the
evening. It's not that she gets better lines, it's that she
delivers them with such spectacular vehemence.
</P>
<P>
   Silver has written, and no doubt will write, far better works
than ``The Altruists.'' In the meantime, there is the blaze of
energy that is Cox, resourcefully turning theatrical cardboard into
fuel for a one-woman bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `THE ALTRUISTS'
</P>
<P>
   By Nicky Silver; directed by David Warren; sets by Neil Patel;
lighting by Kenneth Posner; costumes by Teresa Snider-Stein; sound
by John Gromada; production manager, Kai Brothers; production stage
manager, Nancy Elizabeth Vest. Presented by the Vineyard Theater,
Douglas Aibel, artistic director; Barbara Zinn Krieger, executive
director and founder; Jeffrey Solis, managing director. At 108 E.
15th St.
</P>
<P>
   With: Joey Slotnick (Ronald), Veanne Cox (Sydney), Eddie Cahill
(Lance), Kali Rocha (Cybil), Sam Robards (Swallow) and Monica Plank
(Audrey).
</P>
</TEXT>
